<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 17)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GOD'S PERFECT CHILD: Living and Dying in the Christian Science
Church &LR;  By Caroline Fraser. (Owl/Holt, $16.) A former Christian
Scientist traces the history of the religion founded by Mary Baker
Eddy, which in its heyday drew many followers with its spiritual
approach to healing. Fraser ``does a splendid job of explaining the
reasons for Christian Science's rise and fall,'' Philip Zaleski
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WELDING WITH CHILDREN &LR;  By Tim Gautreaux. (Picador USA, $12.)
These Cajun-flavored stories are set in a place where rusted car
engines dangle from trees and kids have names like Nu-Nu and
Tammynette. ``The author proves himself an able cartographer as
well as a nimble writer, mapping with affectionate but unflinching
accuracy both the back roads of Louisiana ... and the distance
between parents and children,'' Liam Callanan wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN PRIDE STILL MATTERED: A Life of Vince Lombardi &LR;  By David
Maraniss. (Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16.) According to this
biography, the legendary Green Bay Packers coach was a complex
figure who was both a world-class motivator and a small-minded
bully. ``Maraniss has a superb eye for detail'' and he ``shows not
only that winning isn't everything, it's not even what it's cracked
up to be,'' Allen St. John wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DANGEROUS HUSBAND &LR;  By Jane Shapiro. (Back Bay/Little,
Brown, $12.95.) The heroine of this humorous novel is a 40-ish New
York photographer who is driven to distraction by her pathological
_ if well-meaning _ klutz of a husband. ``Shapiro's most subtle
accomplishment ... is her creation of a loony-beyond-belief
marriage that nevertheless bears a resemblance to every marriage,''
Karen Karbo said in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HUNGRY YEARS: A Narrative History of the Great Depression
in America &LR;  By T.H. Watkins. (Owl/Holt, $16.) This chronicle of the
1930s draws on the experiences of ordinary Americans in both urban
and rural areas. ``Watkins' prose often has the intensity and
warmth of a photo by Dorothea Lange or a novel by John Steinbeck,''
Michael Kazin wrote last year. ``He refreshes old accounts about
the misery and insurgencies of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST DAYS OF LOUISIANA RED &LR;  By Ishmael Reed. (Dalkey
Archive, $11.95.) This 1974 novel, nominally a detective story
featuring a hoodoo sleuth named Papa LaBas, is mainly a
free-wheeling satirical attack on 1960s racial politics and
culture, exemplified by a militant movement known as the Moochers.
``Reed has a shrewd eye, a mean ear, a nasty tongue,'' Robert
Scholes said in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued another of Reed's novels,
 &UR; YELLOW BACK RADIO BROKE-DOWN &LR;  ($11.95), a loopy allegory about a
black cowboy in a surreal Wild West that lampoons organized
religion and white myths about American history. ``Reed's
topsy-turvy vision says something meaningful _ certainly in a
unique way,'' one critic said in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORDS FAIL ME: What Everyone Who Writes Should Know About
Writing &LR;  By Patricia T. O'Conner. (Harvest/Harcourt, $12.) A former
copy editor at The New York Times Book Review offers advice on how
to draft, write, revise, unsnarl and rescue prose. ``The practical
and tough-minded O'Conner uses her playful sense of humor to help
us swallow with a laugh the rules that schoolmarms once forced down
students' throats,'' Diane Cole wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RIVER SOUND: Poems &LR;  By W.S. Merwin. (Knopf, $15.) Now in
his 70s, the poet continues to explore the grieving that
accompanies daily life, but his work here is infused with a desire
to settle old debts and bequeath particular moments. ``He's
performing what James Merrill knew was the most important task of
all, taking care of the `need to make some kind of house / Out of
the life lived, out of the love spent,''' Melanie Rehak wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PARROT'S LAMENT: And Other True Tales of Animal Intrigue,
Intelligence, and Ingenuity &LR;  By Eugene Linden. (Plume, $12.95.)
These accounts of wildlife behavior, drawn from interviews with
zookeepers, researchers and trainers, feature con artists,
scoundrels, jesters and even an orangutan escape artist. ``Linden's
respect and love for all creatures in the animal kingdom is
infectious,'' Sara Ivry wrote earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AARON COPLAND: The Life and Work of an Uncommon Man &LR;  By Howard
Pollack. (University of Illinois, $24.95.) This open-minded,
respectful biography portrays the great composer (1900-90) as an
indefatigable promoter of American music whose national convictions
were central to his art. The result is ``the definitive study of
Aaron Copland's life and work,'' John Rockwell wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
