<SLUG> BC-ONE-A-DAY-MED-BRIEF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEPING A HOSPITAL PROBLEM UNDER THE MATTRESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This premium feature from The New York Times Syndicate is
available for a limited time without charge to clients of this news
wire.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By SAM URETSKY  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Hospitals go to great lengths to avoid infections. That's why
they use disposable needles and syringes, and single-dose drug
packages. Items that can't be thrown away after use are carefully
cleaned before the next patient gets to them.
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Universidade de Sao Paulo, in Brazil, studied
the cleanliness of hospital beds. As reported in the April issue of
the Portuguese-language journal Reviste Dr Saude Publica, they
checked 52 hospital mattresses.
</P>
<P>
   Before cleaning, they found 259 bacterial colonies that might
have led to infection. After the mattresses were cleaned, a second
test revealed 255 bacterial colonies.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers conclude that the cleaning process doesn't get
rid of bacteria, it just moves the colonies to other places on the
mattress.
</P>
<P>
   So when the insurance companies make a fuss about getting
patients out of the hospital faster, maybe they know what they're
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT HEALTHSCOUT:
</P>
<P>
   HealthScout (http://www.healthscout.com) is a service of Rx
Remedy, Inc., a leader in the field of health information and
publisher of REMEDY Magazine, a prize-winning health publication
read in 2.2 American homes.
</P>
<P>
   -- All of HealthScout's original stories are based on primary
sources: reports in refereed medical journals and interviews with
the medical researchers who authored them. Fact-checkers
independently confirm reporters' work on sensitive stories.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's medical writers and editors have previously
worked at many of the nation's most respected newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's Scientific Advisory Board includes leading
authorities in more than a dozen disciplines.
</P>
