<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-STOKES-2TAKES-BOS     09-11 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-STOKES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAILBLAZER LOUISE STOKES WENT NOWHERE FAST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALDEN, Mass. _ Her Olympic metal is black iron. It stands
starkly atop a granite slab, elegant and dignified in its
simplicity, the centerpiece of the courtyard named in her honor _
the Louise Stokes Fraser Memorial _ at her alma mater, Malden High
School.
</P>
<P>
   It is a striking silhouette of a runner crouched in the starting
blocks, and beneath it, the inscription encapsulates both her
signal achievement and eternal frustration: ``Erected in honor of
the Malden High School track star and member of the Onteora Girls
Club, who, in the 1930's, was selected to the U.S. Olympic team as
an official entry . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   That is as close as Louise Stokes ever got to the starting
blocks in the 1932 and 1936 Olympic Games at Los Angeles and
Berlin, respectively. She was never given the chance for a harvest
of a more glorious cast: gold, silver, or bronze. With her death in
1978 at the age of 64, the wife of Wilfred Fraser carried the
definitive account of her heartache to her grave, as if it were the
baton she was not allowed to touch more than six decades ago in the
4x100-meter relay event of the world's greatest competition.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the 2000 Games at Sydney looming as a showcase for
Marion Jones and her quest for an unprecedented five track gold
medals, the efforts and plight of Louise Stokes _ the groundbreaker
for Jones and all future African-American women Olympians _ are
lost amid the conjecture and innuendo of history. Stokes is an
Olympic obscurity, save for the 1987 Malden tribute and a handful
of history books and magazine articles noble in intent and
ultimately inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   All postulate to at least some degree, but cannot unequivocally
prove, that Stokes and her fellow trailblazer on the '32 and '36
Olympic relay quartets, Tidye Pickett of Chicago, were victims of
racism and, to a lesser extent, sexism and political factionism.
The three surviving members of the '32 US world-record foursome _
Annette Rogers Kelly, Evelyn Furtsch Ojeda, and, most adamantly,
Stokes's archrival from neighboring Medford, Mary Carew Armstrong _
contend through hazy recollection that the four fastest American
women were selected and that Stokes and Pickett were not among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the shreds of circumstantial evidence, only two facts are
indisputable: In 1932, Louise Stokes and Tidye Pickett became the
first two black American women chosen to run in the Olympics. And
did not run in them.
</P>
<P>
   While he was playing ball with the other kids, Bill Mini would
see her in the dusk, running, never stopping, through Malden's
Ferryway Green. He also watched her do roadwork along the Boston &AMP;
Maine Railroad tracks from Malden to Saugus and back, regular as a
train schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The particulars are misty, but Mini, who later would become a
teacher at Malden High and spearhead the courtyard tribute, knew
one thing as gospel: Louise Stokes was the fastest girl in town.
</P>
<P>
   That was no secret. Stokes had been Malden's preeminent speed
merchant since 1929, when one of her teammates on the Beebe Junior
High girls' basketball team, impressed with the way she gobbled up
the court whenever she ran, persuaded her to try out for the
Onteora Club. It was the local girls' track team, overseen by
William Quain, a legendary Malden athlete in the 1890s and now the
city's parks commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Quain knew little about the girl when she came to audition.
She'd been born in 1913, the great granddaughter of slaves and the
oldest of William and Mary Stokes's six surviving children. Louise
had first lived at 542 Ferry Street in Everett, exactly two houses
from Malden's border. But by the time Quain discovered her, or vice
versa, upheaval had entered Stokes's world. The family had moved to
55 Faulkner Street, a brown duplex in Malden. There William
supported his dependents as a gardener in the summer and a stoker
of the furnaces of the well-to-do in the winter. Mary worked as a
housekeeper, often outfitting her children in the castoffs of her
wealthy clients. They were borderline poor, but this was Depression
America, and they considered themselves fortunate to be employed.
</P>
<P>
   They also had become targets of tragedy. In 1922, Louise's
4-year-old sister, Alice, set her nightgown ablaze while playing
with a match and died several days later. As the oldest child,
Louise bore a sense of guilt for not having kept a closer watch on
her sister.
</P>
<P>
   But as Quain and her Onteora teammates discovered, running set
her free from the burdens of the outside world. She immediately
established herself as the club's prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was Mr. Quain's No. 1 on the track,'' says Genevieve
Ferrick, who as Genevieve O'Mara was a teammate and playmate of
Stokes. ``It was obvious right away that she was our best runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet O'Mara and the other girls didn't consider Stokes anything
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took her for granted; she was just another kid,'' says
O'Mara.
</P>
<P>
   Also like most of her contemporaries, O'Mara regarded Stokes as
``a very nice kid, kind of quiet.'' She sang in the choir at the
Eastern Avenue Baptist Church. When not involved with schoolwork or
attending to her four sisters and brother, she would run from
Faulkner over to O'Mara's house in Salem Place and call for her to
come out and play _ ``Hiii, Jen'' _ without bothering to knock on
the door. And off they'd go to Amerige Park, a couple of kids
running carefree.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes also seemed blessedly untouched by the degradations of
color-coded America where, almost seven decades after the
Emancipation Proclamation, lynchings were still so commonplace that
they rarely rated headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no such thing as black and white'' in Malden, says
O'Mara. ``It didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Malden's 58,000 citizens would help underwrite
Stokes's Olympic quests with contributions for her expenses, and in
the meantime, they celebrated her increasingly impressive
achievements. In September 1931 at Fenway Park, Stokes won the
James M. Curley Cup, awarded in the name of Boston's roguish mayor
for the year's outstanding women's track showing. Stokes's
credentials were a victory in the 100 meters, second in the 50
meters, and third in the high jump. Runner-up for the Cup was the
local rival with whom Stokes often traded victories, Mary Carew of
the Medford Girls Club.
</P>
<P>
   During her career, Stokes later would add regional and/or
national titles in the 50 meters, 100 yards, 100 meters, and high
jump, setting a US record for the 50 with a time of 6.6 seconds in
1933. She also was a consistent contender at 40 and 200 yards. Her
crowning achievement occurred at the Boston YMHA in Roxbury Dec.
30, 1931, when she shattered the US record of Boston's Katherine
Mearls and tied the world mark with a leap of 8 feet 5 1/2 inches
in the standing broad jump. For this she was dubbed the
``sensational daughter of Mercury'' in the Boston Post, a lustrous
companion to her prevailing nickname, ``the Malden Meteor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Olympics _ opened to women only four years earlier in
the 1928 Amsterdam Games _ became a logical target rather than
simply a lofty one.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very dedicated runner,'' says O'Mara. ``She worked
so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Quain began pointing Stokes in earnest toward the 1932 US track
and field trials in Evanston, Ill. He focused in particular on her
tendency to jump the gun, which in those days warranted a penalty
of stepping 1 foot farther behind the line for the restart.
</P>
<P>
   It all paid off on July 16, a sultry day at Northwestern's Dyche
Stadium. Stokes finished tied with Carew for fourth in the
100-meter finals and Pickett came in right behind them; as a
result, the two black 18-year-olds earned relay berths for the Los
Angeles Games two weeks hence.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than a milepost to glory, the trials served as a
warning signal of the roadblock that lay ahead. The murky
proceedings of LA were foreshadowed at Evanston.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rules, all six finals participants qualified
for the Olympic team _ the top three gained the individual
100-meter spots, the fourth through sixth finishers qualified for
the relay, and the final member of the quartet would be selected
later. In one of the preliminary heats at the trials, race leader
Ethel Harrington misjudged the finish line and pulled up short.
Sympathetic judges allowed her to compete in the finals, which
would have dropped Pickett from the field. Because of the asterisk
attached to Harrington's victory, George Donoghue, a white trials
judge, decreed that Pickett should be included as a seventh runner
in the finals field. Harrington then won the race ahead of
second-place Wilhelmina von Bremen of San Francisco and No. 3
Elizabeth Wilde of Kansas City. Pickett finished in the No. 6 spot
ahead of Furtsch.
</P>
<P>
   But the largesse _ and the muddle _ didn't end there. The
Chicago-based Rogers, who had qualified in the high jump but had
lost one of her new shoes and failed to finish her preliminary in
the 100, was allowed in the mix. And Furtsch, who ran for Tustin,
Calif., and is now 86, says, ``I had fallen at the tape during the
finals but I had won my preliminary heat, so they let me in.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, at least one competitor still disputes the order of
finish in the trials. Sitting in a Framingham nursing home and
caressing her cherished gold medal, Carew, 87, points to a tattered
newspaper photograph of the runners at the Northwestern finish
line. In it, she appears at least a stride ahead of Stokes. ``I
beat Stokesy,'' she says, ``pure and simple.'' But times weren't
factored beyond tenths of a second, and other accounts, including
the official report of the Olympic Committee, list Carew and Stokes
in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-STOKES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     09-11 1865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-STOKES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MALDEN, Mass.: ... in a dead heat.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At any rate, the women's team proceeded directly from the trials
onto a Pullman train bound for LA. Carew emphasizes that when the
competitors boarded, ``Stokesy knew she was going as an alternate.
She knew she wasn't going to run in the Olympics.'' Again, other
accounts indicate just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no such discord existed among the overflowing field
of relay candidates as they traveled west.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all very close, very friendly,'' says Furtsch.
``Everybody got along real well.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rogers, 86, recalls Stokes as ``a wonderful person, a
wonderful teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   That solidarity was most poignantly evident during the team's
stopover in Denver, where Stokes and Pickett experienced their only
confrontation with racism _ at least of an overt nature. At the
Brown Palace Hotel, the two African-American women were ordered to
enter from the rear door. Rogers recalls that as a gesture of
support, the entire team joined them.
</P>
<P>
   The segregation did not end there, but the team's unified stance
did. Stokes and Pickett were consigned to a single attic room while
their fellow Olympians stayed individually in regular rooms. In
addition, the two teens did not partake of the team banquet because
blacks were denied access to the hotel dining facilities; their
meals were served on trays delivered to their room. And when the
Olympians took a celebrity turn on a Denver radio program, Stokes
and Pickett remained isolated in their room.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, almost every member of the team was left in a large
shadow _ that of headliner Mildred ``Babe'' Didrikson, the
all-around sensation who in 1950 would be named the top woman
athlete of the half-century. A native of aggressively
segregationist Texas, Didrikson was no friend of the black
sprinters. But she was not discriminatory in her hostility. As far
as she was concerned, the Olympics existed solely as a vehicle for
her, and anyone or anything that interfered with that mission was
the enemy. Rogers remembers Didrikson drowning out her teammates
during the Denver radio broadcast if the interviewing strayed too
far from her favorite subject: Babe. She was almost unanimously
reviled as a prima donna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody liked her,'' says Carew, Didrikson's roommate in LA.
``I became friendly with her, but she was always brag, brag,
brag.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no further incidents in Los Angeles. Pickett and
Stokes were excluded from the Athletes' Village, but that was
because of their gender, not their race; all the women were barred
from those special quarters and were housed at the Chapman Park
Hotel. There Pickett and Stokes shared the same accommodations as
their teammates and participated in all team functions.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one. The race they had come to run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With eight candidates _ Carew, Furtsch, Harrington, Stokes,
Pickett, Rogers, von Bremen, and Wilde _ for four relay slots,
coach George Vreeland conducted informal tryouts. He had one
objective, say the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach picked whoever he thought the best runners were,''
says Carew, ``and didn't concern himself with status. He just
worked as good as he could and picked the best people he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers agrees, though she can't remember the specifics: ``I was
under the impression he picked the four fastest runners.''
</P>
<P>
   Furtsch recalls one other consideration _ dexterity in passing
the baton, which Vreeland regarded as pivotal to success: ``He
tried to pick the girls who had the best interchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his criteria, Vreeland's word was law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 18 years old,'' says Furtsch. ``We never questioned
the authority of the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   How the coaches determined the fastest and most adroit quartet
is open to speculation. Extensive documentation of the women's
audition times is nonexistent, and there has been speculation that
rather than clocking the runners, the coach and his staff relied on
observation and memory. In truth, any of the women was capable of
beating the others in a given race; you could throw a blanket over
them. Instead, a shroud was thrown over Pickett and Stokes. Von
Bremen and Rogers were judged to be the two fastest, Carew the
quickest out of the blocks, and Furtsch the handiest with the
baton.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, those four women won the gold in a world-record time
of 46.9 seconds. Meanwhile, Pickett and Stokes watched from the
sidelines, devastated but apparently silent as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember anybody being difficult,'' says Furtsch.
``There was no resentment on anyone's part. There was no racism I
was aware of. Not until years later did the racism charges come
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The only official disclaimer was implicit. Fred Steers concluded
his report as track team manager by stating, ``I further recommend
that all matters pertaining to the team be transacted through the
Manager only. This was not done in many cases and as a result,
considerable confusion was caused which might otherwise have been
avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was a racial injustice that Steers wanted to prevent,
but like the formation of the gold-medal relay squad, the intent is
vague.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it was not in Stokes's nature to protest on her
behalf. Carew described her as ``shy, naive'' in her pre-Olympic
days. And that evidently didn't change upon her return to Malden,
where she was accorded a warm reception, medal or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never talked about why she didn't run,'' says O'Mara,
adding that ``everybody had been very excited and felt really bad
for her. She had trained so hard in the winter and summer.''
</P>
<P>
   That pattern continued as Stokes focused on the next
opportunity, the 1936 Olympics in Berlin. Even as she gained
grander success and prominence with her national championships, she
made a precipitous decision that created grave distress on the home
front. With track her consuming interest, Stokes failed several
courses during her senior year of high school. And while her
parents were distraught, Louise decided not to return to make up
the work for her diploma, instead banking all her fortunes on
running. This was in contrast to Pickett, who while continuing to
compete also attended college at Northern Illinois and was an
esteemed school principal before she died in 1986 at age 72.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes left herself with no alternative except track, and she
risked disaster in the 1936 trials at Brown University in
Providence when she failed to qualify in the 100 finals. However,
she had won her preliminary heat, and several days after the
trials, she received a reprieve when Olympic officials added her to
the relay pool _ perhaps because they felt guilty about the
treatment of the black women four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the tensions attending these Games were of a far
greater scale, for they were the notorious Nazi Olympics of Adolf
Hitler, who promised that his blond, blue-eyed Aryan nation would
prove superior to all other competitors, especially blacks and
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk of the United States boycotting the Games, and
while that never materialized, fund-raising was shot. There were
none of the Olympic megasponsors who form a corporate parade of
jingoism today, and the competitors were required to subsidize at
least $500 of their Berlin trip, an enormous sum in the dying days
of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   But Malden came through for Stokes. At the last second, just
before the US team's ship, the SS President Roosevelt, was
scheduled to depart from New York, a waiver for the required amount
arrived. It came courtesy of Malden Mayor John Devir and Onteora's
Quain, who had collected donations by soliciting the townspeople.
In addition, Stokes received $75 in expense money and $105 was set
aside for a homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the celebration would be enthusiastic but
bittersweet. Pickett finally got to compete _ in the 80-meter
hurdles, where she broke her foot in the semifinals. That meant she
was out of consideration for the relay, and so, ultimately, was
Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   One factor may have been cold cash, given the US Olympic
movement's shaky financial status. The Western establishment was
far more powerful, and better funded, than the Eastern. And
Hitler's virulent anti-Semitism may have trickled down to
indirectly block Stokes. These were the Games in which Jesse Owens
dominated _ and was repeatedly snubbed by Hitler, who refused to
shake any black athlete's hand. Owens won three gold medals, and
the coaches believed his presence would enhance the chances for a
fourth in the 4x100 relay. He and fellow African-American medalist
Ralph Metcalfe were added to the quartet _ at the expense of the
only two American Jewish competitors, Marty Glickman and Sam
Stoller.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently enough, where an opening had developed for blacks
on the men's relay, it vanished for them on the women's. Pickett
was hors de combat, and Stokes was excluded from the team in favor
of ``veteran'' Western runners _ three of whom she'd beaten in
Berlin tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Stephens, Betty Robinson, Harriet Bland, and Rogers
retained the relay gold for the United States, while once again a
spot was reserved for Stokes on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time she was more outspoken when she returned, but only a
bit. During a reception at the Ferryway following a welcoming
parade, she alluded to the superior organization of the Westerners.
There was no mention of race, nor would there be, it seems, until
late in her life.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Pete Kearin of the Malden Evening News on
Aug. 29, 1972, Stokes referred to the Olympic oversights. By then,
she had married a noted cricket player, Fraser; raised a son,
Wilfred Jr.; found work as a clerk in the state Department of
Corporations and Taxation; and transferred her athletic skills to
the alleys, becoming a proficient bowler.
</P>
<P>
   She indeed had been twice snubbed in her Olympic efforts, Stokes
told Kearin, ``and the worst part of it all is that they've never
said a word about it, not to this day.'' She described herself as
``just a cute little girl that hardly didn't know anything.'' Of
her Olympic shunning, she said, ``When we (Stokes and Pickett) went
out to run, we found other runners in our places. We just had to
stand there, and I felt terrible. I really should have said
something. But after it was done, what could you do?''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. No blistering diatribe. No self-congratulatory
reference to pioneering efforts, though they couldn't be
overlooked, as Pickett once told the Chicago Sun-Times: ``The girls
who came on later didn't have to face the same things. We took a
lot for them. We really opened the door for them, but I'm glad it
was opened.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Stokes passed quietly from the scene. But she was
not completely forgotten. In 1974, the New England AAU declared a
day in her honor, and several trophies were awarded in her name.
Posthumously, she was inducted into the Hall of Black Achievement
at Bridgewater State College last year.
</P>
<P>
   And there is her high school courtyard, where she is frozen
forever, poised and ready to take her place in posterity, though
never her rightful place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1019EDT &QL; 
