<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-FREEDMAN-2TAKES-B     09-11 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FREEDMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDMAN CYCLES TO HER OWN RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ She was weak. She bought a pair of sandals
today, $200 black leather beauties. They feel so good and she feels
so guilty; even as she luxuriates in them, Nicole Freedman ponders
the hedonistic implications. Two hundred dollars? That's a month's
rent. Literally. For some footwear. How utterly decadent. How
positively _ ugh! _ Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but maybe she can balance the moral ledger. She already has
observed that there are too many athletic shoes on her closet
shelf. Closet? Shelf? The uninitiated would more readily identify
it as the dashboard of a psychedelic 1978 Ford Econoline van that
reposes like a junkyard dog in the driveway and has served as
Freedman's bedroom the past four years, the antithesis of the
upper-middle-class entitlements she enjoyed while growing up in
Wellesley, Mass. Anyway, some of these ratty running relics will
have to go, just on general principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like having stuff,'' says Freedman. ``It's too much
stuff. I'm an antimaterialist. You can get too chained to things.''
</P>
<P>
   And that just doesn't fit with a lifestyle that the most ascetic
monk probably would reject as too heavy on self-denial. One sinful
indulgence cannot erase the no-frills equation that is Freedman's
core: Right now, at age 28, with a degree in urban planning from
Stanford and two undergraduate years of engineering at MIT on her
resume, she exists solely to cycle, to pursue the endeavor to its
sacred essence _ the Olympic Games, where she'll be riding at
Sydney Sept. 26 in the 100-kilometer road race. The van, an
heirloom from her earliest days of hard-core riding for the
now-defunct Odwalla team, is a handy metaphor for the regimen of
humbling sacrifice, the purist's reward of competition for
competition's sake, that once was the Olympic ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's the way it is,'' says Freedman. ``It's no big
deal. To the outside world, it's a symbol of what it takes in a
non-mainstream sport.''
</P>
<P>
   It also takes this:
</P>
<P>
   Sally Jean Alexander remembers the girl, no more than 9 or 10
years old, who used to run for the Wayfarers junior track club.
Alexander, a Wayland High School teacher, had organized a travel
team to help showcase the talents of a 16-year-old up-and-coming
star runner, John Mann. Little Nicole Freedman had been recommended
to her after winning a Patriots Day run for 9-year-olds at
Wellesley High with a 6-minute-49-second mile; the time was
indelibly precise because one of the men standing with Nicole's
father, Boston University mathematics professor Marvin Freedman,
had clocked her with a stopwatch and, duly impressed, had suggested
that the girl join Alexander's troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet, innocent Nicole. Almost two decades later, Alexander is
hazy on many particulars but vividly recalls one race. It was at a
meet put on by a New England track group, and Freedman was doing
very well. As she entered the finish chute, she had fourth place
locked up. But after the winner broke the tape, the would-be
runner-up took a spill. Flat on the ground, she blocked the path to
the finish line. Instinctively, the No. 3 runner stopped to assist
her fallen comrade. Instinctively, the No. 4 runner assessd the
fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a chance to move up two places,'' says Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   So she jumped over the prone runner _ make that rival _ and
finished second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was going to deter her,'' says Alexander. ``I'm sure
if she saw the girl was hurt, she would have stopped, too. But she
did just what the high school runners would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Competition for competition's sake. With a little
cutthroat thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is an incongruous mix, an apparent clash of mutually
exclusive elements, but genuine nonetheless. Calling Freedman an
idealistic pragmatist _ or a pragmatic idealist, take your pick _
does no disservice to either term. The evidence is as strong as it
is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   There was her Spanish experience. At 16, she raised the money to
participate in a volunteer health services organization, Amigos de
las Americas, which provides assistance for Latin countries. For
six weeks, she built latrines in Oaxaca, Mexico, and her only
regret was that she had been too young to qualify for duty the
previous year, when she originally tried to get into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she'd never done another thing in her life,'' says
Freedman's mother, Corey, a Realtor, ``that alone would have been
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   But this same civic benefactor was savvy enough to exploit her
Spanish studies for the greatest gain. Nicole was an academic
standout, as her college pedigree would indicate, but Corey
believed she never did more than what was necessary to excel.
Except in Spanish. Her essays were extensive, elaborate exercises
in the language, far more comprehensive than any of her other
schoolwork. Corey always wondered why. Then she found out. At the
Wellesley High 1990 commencement, Freedman earned a Spanish
scholarship _ ``I think it was worth something like $7,000,'' says
Marvin _ that was annually awarded to the top senior. Aha, thought
Corey, ``in all the other languages, they only got books (for
academic distinction), and Nicole must have realized as a freshman
that there was this financial award. That's why she put so much
work into the Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole is horrified that her mother would think she calculatedly
pursued the payoff for three years. ``I was a junior when I found
out about the money,'' she says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   It's no different in her athletic endeavors. That Patriots Day
race that stamped her as a track prodigy was a fun run. But she'd
had her father take her to the track several weeks beforehand so
she could acclimate herself to the conditions because she wanted to
have the fastest fun.
</P>
<P>
   And until she transferred to Stanford, cycling never had been
more than an activity, probably her favorite one. She'd fallen in
love with it when she was 8 and Marvin and Corey would take their
daughters _ Nicole and Emily, two years older _ to Concord to
participate in American Youth Hostel rides. Rides, not races. But
Nicole _ aboard a miniature 10-speed bike Corey had scoured the
area to find _ only briefly would accompany her parents. ``She'd
wave to us and take off right to the head of the group,'' says
Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed except the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freedman is a 5-foot-2-inch, 115-pound laugh track for whom
conventional conviviality would be reclusive. Lisa Raskin, a
Stanford cycling colleague, was drawn to her like so many others _
``because she has such a strong, dynamic personality.'' Freedman
is, in fact, a Roman candle of enthusiasm who writes irreverent
diaries in the cycling publication Velo News and on the Internet
for CNN/SI, musings that have established her as a maverick on the
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the establishment considered her a comedian,'' says
her mentor, Steve Miller. ``She has what is considered an
overwhelming and unstoppable sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   The iconoclastic message doesn't necessarily enchant the
traditionalists. ``Her writing style can be a little sarcastic,''
says Julie Schwab, niece of investment guru Charles and overseer of
Freedman's current team, the first to pay her a stipend for riding.
``A lot of people take it way too seriously to have her come in and
say, `Hey, nobody is making a million dollars, so let's have fun.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Serious fun; that's what the skeptics don't get. Freedman's
philosophy is unwavering: ``If you're going to do something and
really enjoy it, you might as well have a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycling is her vehicle of expression. She isn't committed to it;
she is consumed by it. And as indicated by her startling Olympic
trials victory at Jackson, Miss., May 20 on the eve of her 28th
birthday _ a clinical masterpiece ``that brought tears to your
eyes,'' says Miller, a witness who was so moved _ the old guard had
better get used to her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
