<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IONICS? NATURALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They've built an electronic tennis racket.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous, yes. But even as the weekend player with no serve
rejects the latest madness from a gadget-centric world, a sick
curiousity begins to work on the brain. Maybe, just maybe it can
end years of mediocrity on the court. Maybe, just maybe, it can
blow a doubles match wide open in Weymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Smartest racket in the world, they say. Probably the most
expensive racket in the world, too, says a spokesman for Continuum
Control Corp. in Billerica, Mass., which engineered the guts of the
beast, available from Head in February.
</P>
<P>
   Something about ``piezoelectric power,'' transforming mechanical
motion into energy when the ball hits the strings. Something about
a circuit board in the handle sending messages to the racket head.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. A death ray in a zippered case is what we're after,
and for a crazy minute or two the player with no serve starts to
believe it exists. For an even crazier minute that person thinks
about ordering it online.
</P>
<P>
   This is America, ladies and gentlemen. This is human nature.
Hard-charging capitalism meets the soaring ego, and a whole lot of
money changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, we can do a self-righteous dance blaming the excesses
of a materialistic society on Mephistophelean inventors, but nobody
is taking the plastic out of our pockets at The Sharper Image.
Nobody is forcing us into the shower with a water-resistant compact
disc player so we can think we sing like Sinatra through the
shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   Big item at the gadget emporium, the CD player. Goes for about
$190. Comes with an AM-FM radio, plays TV audio, picks up European
stations overseas, and sports two time zones. Another model has a
tape to record a 20-second message, should someone want to save a
great thought, or leave one for the next person in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   But why would a sane person want to do that? For the same reason
a weekend player with no serve wants robo-racket. Because the
technology is there. Because we feel we are owed nice toys in
payment for stressful days. Because we are the most sophisticated
people ever to walk the planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Romans have ionic air dryers? No way, and Rome was damn
good. ``Ionics'' _ the word is edging out ``natural'' and ``clear''
as the most over-used advertising adjective. Something about
positive and negative charges. Bathes the hair shafts. Also comes
as an air purifier. Deodorizes the house, the car, the dog, and
beats all heck out of those little cardboard pine trees hanging on
rearview mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   The most sophisticated people ever to walk the planet Earth
demand perfection from the cosmos. That's why Brookstone is selling
a clock radio with its own sun. When the clock goes off in the dead
of a winter morning, a bulb comes up out of the works to light the
bedroom. Hit the snooze button and the sun sets.
</P>
<P>
   The most sophisticated people ever to walk the planet Earth
leave nothing to chance. They buy the corkscrew with the degree
from MIT and a ``computerized probe'' indicating if a wine needs
chilling, or warming, or is ready to drink. It's part of a family
of ``smart tools'' that can tell when chickens have been barbecued,
if steaks are rare, and if pasta is al dente.
</P>
<P>
   Cooks used to be able to tell this simply by looking at the
food, or tasting it, but that's so 20th century. People are busy.
Too much going on. Too many decisions to make about equipment. And
choices create tension, which could explain the proliferation of
products designed to help people relax.
</P>
<P>
   There are foot baths, back massagers, ergonomic porch chairs,
pillows that untangle neck knots, interactive mood lights, and
``heart and sound soothers'' that claim to slow the pulse with
recordings of ocean waves, rain forests, and chirping crickets _
but not all at once, unless something goes terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Do we need therapy? Will the human behavior experts of a future
age stare at the artifacts of the most sophisticated people ever to
walk the planet Earth and figure that ionized air must have been a
hallucinogen?
</P>
<P>
   What a racket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
