<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-ONLINE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ONLINE SITES STILL OFFER FREE LISTENING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Napster, then MP3.com. The uninitiated might be forgiven
for assuming that the entire digital-music world is made up of
pirates fighting a pitched battle against the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   But that's hardly the case.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to the mall to pay $13 for your next CD, take a
few minutes to peruse the online music offerings. Net-savvy music
lovers will find a variety of sites that allow them to download
tunes quickly, cheaply, and perfectly legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record labels aren't going after all digital-music
sites,'' said Eric Scheirer, an analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass. ``There are important legal differences between
what (most music sites) do and what MP3.com does.''
</P>
<P>
   Before using any of the sites, you'll need to download a free
MP3 player, which is also completely aboveboard. On that count you
have dozens of choices, but RealPlayer (www.real.com) and Winamp
(www.winamp.com) are the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, while the Napster and MP3.com cases wend their way
through the appeals process, drop by the sites below to preview the
next Wynton Marsalis album, find a rare or out-of-stock tune,
compare prices with the mall stores, or just see what all the
digital-music fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   If none strikes the right tone for you, there are more than 150
other music sites available on the Web. Not all, though, are as
scrupulous about avoiding ``objectionable material'' (translation:
illegal MP3s).
</P>
<P>
   --www.EMusic.com is designed for people who want to pay for
their digital music, a prospect that might shock (or at least
amuse) some Web users. But it does have plenty of tunes to choose
from, featuring 125,000 tracks in a variety of genres, including
blues, classical, country, jazz, reggae, rock, and hip hop.
</P>
<P>
   Buying individual songs from EMusic.com costs 99 cents, albums
$8.99. Or you can download as much music as you like for a $9.99 to
$19.99 monthly subscription, depending on the length of the
contract you agree to. Before buying anything, shoppers are allowed
to sample 30-second song clips.
</P>
<P>
   EMusic also offers a free-download area, with a smattering of
individual tunes that change regularly. The day I checked, gratis
MP3 tracks from Elvis Costello, Tom Waits, Buddy Guy, and Phish
were there for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   --www.epitonic.com started out as a pay-per-download site along
the lines of EMusic.com, but it threw in the towel pretty quickly.
These days, it features free downloads and pays the bills by
selling banner ads. (Record labels don't object to sites such as
Epitonic, because, unlike Napster and MP3.com, they don't allow
users to digitally store or swap songs.)
</P>
<P>
   As with EMusic, you're not likely to find the biggest stars and
their latest hits at this site. Playing down that weakness,
Epitonic focuses on niches, such as folk rock, techno music, and
20th Century classical composers.
</P>
<P>
   Within each genre, you can sample or download a few songs from
each album. If you like what you hear, you can also click through
and buy the entire CD from Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   --www.GetMusic.com not only has the major record labels on
board, it is the major record labels. The site is a joint venture
of powerhouses BMG Entertainment and Universal Music Group, and it
has sales agreements with others on the A List.
</P>
<P>
   That means it is more likely to have the latest hot tracks you
want. It also means the site is geared not only to selling CDs, but
also to giving fans ample opportunity to chat about, send postcards
of, and generally obsess about entertainers that the labels want to
promote. It seems especially geared to preteens and their millions
in annual music spending.
</P>
<P>
   The site does have a page of free downloads that change
regularly, but not in MP3 format. You're allowed to download the
songs only in Liquid Audio format (available from
www.liquidaudio.com), which assures the labels that you can listen
for only 30 days. If you want more after that, you have to buy the
CD.
</P>
<P>
   --www.launch.com, in a different twist, lets you design your own
Web-cast radio-television station. For starters, you're asked to
enter your music preferences, so that Launch.com can create a
profile. Then you're given a list of other users with similar
tastes, so you can combine your playlists and video watchlists with
theirs if you like.
</P>
<P>
   When you look up music, you are given the option of adding it to
your virtual station or buying the CD. You can also refine your
profile by rating songs as they play.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the way Launch.com stays on the good side of the
record studios limits its usefulness. For example, I wanted to add
``Louis Armstrong: An American Icon'' to my cyber station, so I
could listen to the three-CD set and decide whether it was worth
$50. But the site won't play more than four songs by the same
artist in a three-hour period, making the effort too time-consuming
and cumbersome to bother with.
</P>
<P>
   --www.musicmaker.com issued a statement the day the MP3.com
decision was announced last week, making sure everyone knew its
content is ``fully licensed.'' The predictable downside: Nothing is
free. But the site still offers an interesting and low-cost option
for CD shoppers, especially fuddy duddies without the technology to
rip or burn their own albums at home.
</P>
<P>
   What Musicmaker.com does is allow you to make a custom CD,
picking and choosing individual tracks from among 160,000 stored at
the site. Essentially, you pay $10 for any five songs you want,
plus $1 for each additional song, then place your order. Within a
few days, a customized CD arrives at your doorstep with the songs
you want in the order you want.
</P>
<P>
   Before selecting your tunes, you can sample the offerings at the
site. You'll need RealPlayer to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
