<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIO GROWTH AND TAXES COMPLICATE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I am a teacher and plan to retire at about age 60. Am I
diversified enough? I don't contribute regularly to the taxable
mutual fund accounts, but I do when I can. Should I get out of
some? Which should I be adding to?
</P>
<P>
   L.A., Long Beach, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are some uncertainties that make a precise answer
difficult. How is your annuity account invested? What should you
expect in the way of growth from the state retirement system? What
is the level of your irregular contributions to the taxable mutual
funds?
</P>
<P>
   If the answers to the first two questions are that the growth
can be tied to stock-market performance, you should probably be
able to expect overall portfolio growth of about 10 percent.
Without factoring in any contributions to the taxable fund
accounts, the pool would grow to $1,976,139 over 14 years with 10
percent growth and total contributions of $20,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   If growth in the annuity and retirement system savings is likely
to be more modest, say 8 percent, that would take the pool to
$1,552,160.
</P>
<P>
   Both projections assume that you use other funds to pay the
taxes generated by the fund portfolio. That may become quite a
burden toward the end of your working years. For example, if you
project the growth of just the fund portfolio over 14 years, 10
percent returns would take it to $604,718 by the time you are 60.
In the last year before retirement, the internal growth of those
accounts would be $57,320, at least on paper. That could generate
considerable tax liability. One way to forestall that problem, to a
degree, would be to add an index fund to the mix, since index funds
tend to be quite efficient. They are, by definition, buy-and-hold
investments. Another alternative would be to try tax-managed funds.
If you take the first course, you could consider Fidelity Spartan
500 Index fund. In the latter case, consider either Vanguard
Tax-Managed Capital Appreciation fund or Vanguard Tax-Managed
Growth and Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I do not like your selection of a fund for the Roth IRA
account. Since this is the single holding from which you will be
able to withdraw funds in retirement without any taxes due, it
should be your most aggressive investment. The Fidelity Freedom
funds are fine vehicles for saving for retirement, but not within a
Roth IRA that is part of a diversified portfolio. Right now the
Freedom 2020 fund holds 71 percent of its assets in stocks and the
rest in bonds, cash, and other instruments. But by the time it
reaches its target year of 2020, it will resemble the current
portfolio of Fidelity Freedom 2000 fund, which is 39.7 percent
stocks and the balance in bonds and cash. It's only a bit more
aggressive than Fidelity Asset Manager Growth, although it does
have a better performance record.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say I am against either Freedom 2020 or Asset
Manager Growth to give your portfolio some conservative balance,
but both should be among your taxable accounts. If you have faith
in American Century Vista, a high-risk, feast-or-famine mid-cap
growth fund, that would be a better investment for a Roth IRA. (I
don't have particular faith in that fund; if it were my portfolio,
I'd swap that position for shares in Fidelity Select Health Care,
and use the IRA as the vehicle for those shares.)
</P>
<P>
   If my thoughts on American Century Vista scare you off that
fund, I would seek out some other fund in the mid-cap universe to
balance your concentration in large-caps. I use Alger Mid-Cap
Growth, Class B. Vanguard Mid-Cap Index is also a solid fund in
that peer group.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. After 32 years of teaching, I will retire in 2001 with a
fixed annual pension. At a 3 percent average inflation rate in the
following 22 years of my retirement, the added income I would need
to maintain the same $50,000 purchasing power is quite substantial.
Is there a formula to compute how much money I would need with a 7
percent annual return at the beginning of my retirement?
</P>
<P>
   H.P., Chelmsford, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I knew I didn't know the answer to your specific question _
the formula behind the answer. But I thought it would be easy
enough to find. Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   I went online, and the Google search engine came up with 80,500
hits for retirement calculator. After about three hours of
wallowing through them _ well, since this is a family newspaper, I
won't say what I think most of them are worth. But eventually I
came upon the site of New England Financial, a unit of MetLife, and
got to the page at
www.nefn.com/Content/Needs/retirement/calculator.cfm and, Eureka!
There it was.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that if you now have about $168,750 earning 7
percent annually, you could die perfectly broke at age 87. (But
this calculation does not take into effect the tax liability on
your supplemental savings.)
</P>
<P>
   A simpler bit of work was to track how much you would be
spending to maintain that target lifestyle, beginning with $50,000
in the first year of your retirement and escalating to $93,614 in
the 22nd. That, of course, leads to the further question of what
would happen if you lived beyond age 87, with your pension income
representing only 52.2 percent of what you would need in the 23rd
year of retirement. So it certainly would be a more comfortable
situation if you have a bit more than that target $168,750.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to those online retirement calculators, after working
through several dozen of them, I thought the best overall was the
Vanguard Retirement Planner _ with a single problem that was
critical, in the case of your question. It simply could not be
shaken out of the assumption of 4.5 percent annual inflation. A
locked-in assumption of 4.5 percent for annual inflation seems
pretty silly, since other calculators said for the 25 years ending
in 1999 that the average US inflation rate was 3.8 percent _ and
those years included the horrible inflation of the 1980s, to which
we all earnestly hope not to return.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest flaw in most of the calculators was either that they
don't provide for adjustments for inflation, or that they don't
make provisions for people who have both fixed pensions and other
investments.
</P>
<P>
   For investors with similar questions but without the complexity
of a fixed pension, I did find a nice program called Retirement
Calculator, from American River Software. This allows a person to
include an inflation rate on calculations relating to a retirement
pool _ very much worth the 10-minute download and something I've
been searching for for several years. Go to www.americanriver.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can I get a list of low-interest credit cards?
</P>
<P>
   A.L., Lakewood, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have a computer, you can go to
www.asque.com/creditcards and click on ``rates and fees'' and then
on ``interest rate'' and you will find a list of credit-card
interest rates, the issuers, their phone numbers, the annual fees,
grace days allowed, introductory rates and their duration, and any
other benefits offered.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can just type in www.asque.com/creditcards/ccir1.htm to
go directly to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the list begins with the American Express card, with
no interest (but with the requirement that the bill be paid in full
monthly) and with a $55 annual fee. It is followed by First
National Bank of Atlanta, with an 8.5 percent interest rate and an
$88 annual fee. You'll have to consider your particular situation
to decide if your typical balance makes the interest rate or the
annual fee the more important criterion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
