<HEADLINE>
BIDDING ON GAS CAN SAVE MONEY, MAYBE NOT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Priceline.com's new gasoline card gets a thumbs up from me, but
not for the reasons you might think.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the card is relatively easy to use and saves you several
bucks a month. But what I really like is the psychological boost
the card provides _ the feeling that you have a tiny bit of control
over what you pay at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Readers who responded to my recent query about Priceline were
divided, with fans of the gas card slightly outnumbering critics.
The critics either encountered glitches or said the savings weren't
worth the extra hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, including Kevin Stock of Boston, who has saved as much as
15 cents a gallon filling up his Ford Explorer, offered cautious
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's been successful for me, I'm not sure it's
worth the time,'' he said. ``But I guess with gas prices as high as
they are, there's some psychological benefit to not paying full
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com is the Connecticut company that has revolutionized
the sale of everything from airline tickets to groceries by letting
customers bid the prices they want to pay.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds great, but there is always a drawback.
</P>
<P>
   With airline tickets, it's flexibility. If your bid is
successful, you have to accept the flight times and routes
Priceline offers.
</P>
<P>
   With groceries, it's the extra time. You in effect have to shop
twice (once on the Internet and once in the store) and check out
twice (once for your Priceline items and once for anything you buy
on impulse).
</P>
<P>
   The drawbacks of the gas card, which hit the market in June, are
far less onerous. Once you've obtained your card, given Priceline
your credit card information, and selected which stations you want
to use, the bidding for gas takes only a few minutes. Other than
that, the gas-buying and pumping are the same.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline's participating gas stations are arranged by Zip code,
and you have to select at least three. The stations tend to be the
more expensive brand names, such as Mobil, Shell, Sunoco, and
Texaco. The stations that already sell gas at cheaper prices don't
appear to participate.
</P>
<P>
   To save time, Robert Sedell of Berkley, Mass. suggests selecting
stations that let you use your credit card at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding is simple: Priceline's Web site tells you the
average price per gallon at the stations you've selected ($1.62 for
my five stations last Tuesday) and then gives you four price
options and the chances of acceptance (e.g., $1.57 great, $1.53
good, $1.50 fair, and $1.47 low). You can also pick your own price.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of weeks, I successfully bid twice on the
price that had a fair chance of being accepted, at $1.50 and $1.47
a gallon. My own bid for $1.42 was rejected, but not rejected
outright. Priceline told me I could purchase the gas at the price I
had bid, if I was willing to go to a station not included among the
five I had selected, or by buying a service or gift certificate
from one of Priceline's sponsors. They included Essential.com,
Net2Phone, Cattoys.com, Movie Cash, Red Lobster, and the Olive
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   To pump the gas, you use your Priceline card instead of a credit
card and punch in the access code. You have already prepaid for the
gas, so all you need to keep track of is how many gallons you pump.
If you lose track, you may be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: Let's say you purchase 20 gallons at $1.50 a gallon
and pump 14 gallons on one visit to the gas station. On your next
visit, you have six gallons left on your order, and Priceline will
let you pump an extra five gallons at the same price. If you exceed
11 gallons (the six left on your order plus the five-gallon
buffer), you will be charged the pump price for the extra gas you
pumped, plus a $1.50 surcharge _ which would wipe out any savings.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald C. Wiedemann of Amesbury, Mass. said that trying to pump
only as much gas as you ordered is a pain in the neck. On his order
for 20 gallons at $1.55 a gallon, Wiedemann pumped 17.469 gallons,
leaving him with 2.531 gallons. He took the time to go back and
pump the 2.531 gallons, but he suspects many customers wouldn't
bother.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't gone back, I would have paid $31 for 17.469
gallons, for a unit price of $1.77 per gallon. Where are my savings
then?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you slice it, Priceline's savings aren't huge. If
you pump 50 gallons during a month at what Priceline says is the
average discount of 12 cents a gallon, that's a savings of just $6.
And those savings are based on prices at brand-name stations that
tend to charge more.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, using the Priceline gas card gave me a good
feeling. It was fun (visually, the bid process is a bit like a slot
machine), easy, and I saved some money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds up over time,'' said Priceline spokesman Robert
Padgett. ``It's amazing what people will do to save 5 or 6 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   Priceline had been preparing to charge its 250,000 cardholders
$3 for every month they use the card, which would have made using
it a waste of time. Priceline wisely did away with the fee two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   I still wonder how Priceline turns a profit. The company pays
the gas stations their full pump prices, and makes its money not by
selling gas but by selling its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Padgett said that 5,000 of the 30,000 stations listed on the Web
site have agreed to pay Priceline between 25 cents and $2 for every
customer delivered to them. The 5,000 stations, apparently hoping
to boost their sales volume and sell other items to gas customers,
are given preference in referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors also pays Priceline an undisclosed fee for every
referred customer.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce D. Weinberg, associate professor of marketing and
e-commerce at the Bentley College graduate school of business, has
been impressed with the Priceline gas card. But he thinks the
company is using its gas card as a loss leader, to pull customers
to other parts of its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really getting customers for other parts of their
business that will yield better returns,'' Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom price hike
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Customer service seems to be an alien concept at long-distance
phone companies these days, with MCI Worldcom the latest offender.
</P>
<P>
   Alfie Kohn of Belmont, Mass. was on an MCI Worldcom calling plan
that charged him 7 cents peak and 5 cents off-peak, with a monthly
fee. Without any notice, the company recently hiked the peak fee to
9 cents (an increase of 29 percent) and boosted the monthly fee by
a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ABellTolls.com, a consumer comparison site of long-distance
plans, says thousands of MCI Worldcom customers were affected by
the backdoor changes. Those on the company's 5-cent Everyday Plus
plan saw their monthly fee go up 20 percent and their peak rate
rise 28 percent. Internet billing discounts were also cut 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ABellTolls was also critical of MCI Worldcom for misleading
customers about the cost of in-state calls and calling-card calls,
as well as sales pitches that were either misleading or out-and-out
false.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom did not return my phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Gasolineprotest.com _ This site is for people who want to
gripe about the price of gasoline, help others find cheap gas, or
place gas prices in perspective. My favorite was the site's
GasGripe software. Gasoline may cost $1.62 a gallon, but the
software showed me that's still a bargain when compared to
Gatorade, which costs $10.17 a gallon, Pepto Bismol, at $123.20 a
gallon, or Vick's Nyquil, which is $178.13 a gallon. I feel better
already.
</P>
<P>
   --Paper or plastic? Vicki Lansky, author of ``The Bag Book,''
says it requires 40 percent less energy to make a plastic bag as
opposed to a paper one. She says plastic bags also generate 80
percent less solid waste and and produce 70 percent fewer
atmospheric emissions. But whatever bag you choose, Lansky advises
reusing it until it's used up or worn out. Her book, just published
by Book Peddlers of Minnetonka, Mn., offers 500 possible reuses for
bags.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
