<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both software, hardware can help keep interlopers from getting
your stuff
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Readers: Broadband connections, hackers and home firewall
solutions all make for one big, raging debate out there. You've
e-mailed us tons of comments and responses to recent columns and,
frankly, they're too good to keep to ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Rich Wilson of Atlanta, a system administrator, worries
that broadbanders may get a false sense of security if they think
unplugging their network connection when not in use is the ultimate
way to ward off hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Users are creatures of habit, he says, and they access
their computers in fairly regular patterns. Hackers can predict
when you are online and can bore through any security hole in your
system in no time. Plus, intruders have this nasty way of slipping
out a ``back door'' sight unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Rich is pretty hip on firewalls, though, as is Bob
Ventimiglia of Mableton, Ga. Bob offers up one of his favorite
options for the PC. Thanks, Bob. He gave high marks to ZoneAlarm
software from Zone Labs (www.zonelabs.com).
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: It's free for personal and nonprofit use. Not to be
confused with ZoneAlarm Pro, which is more customizable and
beefier. It's cool but not free. Zone Labs has it for $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Mike Butcher of Lawrenceville is a ZoneAlarm fan, too. He
said he learned a lot about intrusion attempts on his computer from
the firewall software's pop-up alerts. Mike was full of good info
about finding out how vulnerable you are. He suggests putting
Shields Up to work. Surf to www.grc
</P>
<P>
   .com and click the Shields Up link to find out how Windows users
can get a free Internet connection security analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: George Notel of Cumming, Ga., prefers the muscle of a
hardware solution. He's been using a cable/DSL router with his
cable modem setup for three months and believes the router is the
best deterrent to a hacker. The router sits between the broadband
modem and your computer, like a fortress against attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: George likes the router built by Linksys at Netgear
(www.linksys.com/). It provides firewall protection, plus allows
users to share their connections with other computers in the house.
To anyone looking for openings, the only thing they see would be
that router. It masquerades as your computer while your system
remains hidden from the prying eyes of the Internet. Users can
leave file sharing up and running because the router blocks
incoming connections. You can expect to pay $120 to $175.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Another hardware option is the DI-701 Internet
gateway/firewall. It's made by D-Link and costs $99. Have a
look-see at www.dlink.com/. It bonds with any operating system that
can connect to the Internet, including Windows, the Mac OS and
Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
