A8713 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY0912-COX     09-11 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadband users need firewall to prevent hackers from prying
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If I were an explorer, I would just be getting around
to discovering America. Despite a love of technology _ and a
glimmer of understanding _ I stumble along way behind the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   I'm just now getting around to installing a firewall in my home
computer. Despite my own backward ways, I figure some of you are
also two steps behind. Think of this as remedial education on
computer security.
</P>
<P>
   A firewall, according to its original meaning, is a fireproof
bulkhead used in building construction to delay the spread of fire.
When the Internet and computer networks came along, the name was
applied to software designed to keep hackers out. Like in the
original meaning, it can't stand up to an intense attack but it
does nicely for ordinary purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, firewalls were of more use to business and
government networks. For most home users, who used a dial-up modem
to connect to the Internet for just a few hours or minutes, a
firewall was overkill. In those days, since firewall programs were
written for the sophisticated audience of users, configuring them
was way beyond the skills of most people with home PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the advent of fast and constant broadband
connections to the Internet, the landscape has changed, and it
makes sense to have a firewall on a home computer. The notion of an
``always on'' high-speed connection is no longer exotic, and that
has made the need for computer security more intense.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been the case that each computer on a network
needs an address. Just like on a postal route, the address is used
so packets of information can be delivered to the right place. If
you log on with a dial-up modem, it is likely your address changes
each time you connect. That's called a dynamic address.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when you log on with DSL or a cable modem _
like the one I have at home _ it is likely your address stays
constant. That's called a static address.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of those rare times in the computer world where
common sense will help you understand the two reasons why there's
an increased danger of hackers. The first reason is that the longer
you stay online, the more opportunities a hacker has of finding and
invading your computer. The second reason is that if you have a
static address, you are no longer a moving target for the hackers.
Instead, your computer just sits there hooked up to the Internet,
making it easier to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, as the market has changed, so have the firewall
programs. What once was a complicated mess of settings has become
easy. There are plenty of firewall programs designed for the home
(and small-business) user. Norton has one, there's one called Black
Ice that's very popular, and the one I use and prefer, called Zone
Alarm. It is available free to home users and nonprofit
organizations as a download at www.zonelabs.com.
</P>
<P>
   The download is almost instantaneous using a cable modem or DSL.
</P>
<P>
   The real joy of this program is the setup. There really isn't
any. It installs in the most logical configuration for your
computer and should work great without tweaking with settings on
your part. You won't be faced _ as is true with some other
firewalls _ with answering esoteric questions about your IP address
and system settings. Instead, it automatically fills in all the
information for you.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as time goes on, and you get more familiar with how it
works, you may want to make some changes so that the firewall suits
the risks you face and your own preferences for security. You can
do that at any time, using the manual settings. And, if you have
questions, the ZoneLab Web site is a good source for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone who uses a firewall program is shocked at the
number of alerts you'll get when another computer comes knocking on
the door. Many are false alarms (generated by Web sites you've
visited that are too stupid to know you've disconnected and are
still trying to send data). But a good number are not. Many are
attempts to get into your machine that might have succeeded without
a firewall. If a hacker gets into your machine, he can do anything
you can do, including deleting files or looking at personal or
financial information.
</P>
<P>
   I recommend installing a firewall if you use a high-speed
connection. You can figure that _ as slow as I move in deciding
things like this _ that is a conservative opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
