A8715 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GAMEREVIEW0912-C     09-11 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMEREVIEW0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online play, price cut ensure Sega's survival
 &HT;    By Troy Oxford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This time last year, consumers were excited about the
launch of the Sega Dreamcast video game console. The graphics and
animation of the Dreamcast were considerably more advanced and
visually impressive than the Sony PlayStation and the Nintendo 64
game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast also came equipped with a 56k bps modem, enticing
gamers with the thought of playing games online _ a feature never
before experienced with a home video game console.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement was mixed with some skepticism, however. Sega's
previous video game console, the Saturn, had a short lifespan in
the United States due to the small number of popular games and a
$399 price tag. With only 18 games available at launch, it was
uncertain whether the Dreamcast would follow the same path.
</P>
<P>
   The Sega system was also in the approaching shadow of Sony's
PlayStation 2, and many consumers were considering holding out for
the successor of the reputable PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   These factors left the Dreamcast on shaky ground. One year
later, with a robust selection of games, online capabilities and a
new pricing strategy, Sega's game console has found stability.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of games for the system has blossomed from 18 to
more than 100 and is expected to grow to 200 by the holiday season.
Notable developers such as Namco, Capcom, Infogrames, Midway and
Ubi Soft have created games for the system and are continuing
future developments.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a typical Dreamcast game is between $39.99 and
$49.99. However, Sega has reduced the price of some of its
best-selling titles to $19.99 for the All Star series. Other
first-generation games have been reduced to less than $30.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Robison, group director of third-party licensing at Sega of
America, feels this is a good factor for consumers. ``When a family
goes in to buy a video game console, they don't just look at the
price of the hardware; they look at the price of the software as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial cost of $199 for the Dreamcast console has also been
reduced to $149 _ $50 higher than the current PlayStation but half
the price of the upcoming $299 PlayStation 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sega has also given Dreamcast owners some clarity about online
gaming with its dedicated gaming network, SegaNet. The service not
only allows PC and Dreamcast users to surf the Web and send e-mail
like an ISP, it also lets gamers play certain titles online.
</P>
<P>
   Before the release of ``NFL2K1,'' the only title playable online
was ``Chu Chu Rocket.'' Although the puzzle game finally delivered
network playability, the title didn't represent the intense online
gaming experience consumers were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Robison feels ``Chu Chu Rocket'' was integral to delivering
Sega's promise of online gaming. He describes the title as an
``experiment that allowed us to really test out game servers,
online connectivity and look at behavior of playing online games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega's advanced network is expected to run without the lagging
witnessed in typical online games via the PC. With a dedicated
network for the Dreamcast, gamers won't be subject to the numerous
hops and rerouting of ISPs. Games like ``NFL2K1'' can be played by
two players coast-to-coast as if they were playing in the same
room.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``NFL2K1'' and ``Chu Chu Rocket'' are currently the
only Dreamcast games online, Sega and other developers have such
games in the works. Some online titles that will be available
before the holidays are ``Quake 3,'' ``Speed Devils 2'' and ``POD
2'' by Ubi Soft; and ``Unreal Tournament'' by Infogrames.
</P>
<P>
   With the purchase of the $149 Dreamcast, owners can try SegaNet
free for 50 hours. The full, unlimited service is $21.95 a month.
Customers who sign up for 18 months of the SegaNet service get a
Dreamcast keyboard and a $150 rebate _ in essence, a free Dreamcast
console.
</P>
<P>
   After a year, Sega is showing that its system will subsist and
grow. With original games, competitive pricing and, most notably,
advanced online gaming, the Dreamcast is looking like a solid game
console.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
