<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KID0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Role-playing title features plenty of options in odd location _
space
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like many PC role-playing games, ``Terminus'' has a
detailed and intricate story line, complete with multiple
characters, missions and scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other role-playing games, ``Terminus'' serves up a
virtual smorgasbord of role-playing options for players to explore,
including multiplayer modes and career options.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a ``scenario web'' that changes the story line based
on the success, or failure, of the missions and career choices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Terminus'' has taken many elements commonly found
in the traditional role-playing game and fused them with space
combat. The result is a story line that can be played again and
again from different perspectives and with varying outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good game, so far,'' said Randy Rogers, 16, who
reviewed the game. ``I haven't tried a lot of the options yet, but
I like to have a lot of flexibility. This game is kind of like a
cross between `Mantis' and `Wing Commander.' I liked both of those
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the options is a player's choice of a career path
to follow. Gamers can choose to be on either side of the law,
choosing among military service, trading, engineering, hijacking or
other criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   One of the game's five modes is ``multiplayer,'' an option not
usually found in RPGs. In multiplayer, gamers can play
cooperatively with a friend in the same career or competitively
against friends in different careers.
</P>
<P>
   Randy, who's been playing PC games since he was 10, said most of
the time he chooses to be a fighter pilot, flying among the 18
space stations throughout the solar system where players can trade,
organize and re-arm. He said it took him a while to tweak the
adjustable flight controls until he got them to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the easiest game to get into,'' he said. ``If I
hadn't done this before, I would have given up after the first
couple of tries.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the game's setting is the 22nd century, Randy said the
program's graphics are nearly archaic by today's standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really surprises me,'' the Stockbridge resident said. ``I
would have thought the graphics would be better, but they are way
behind the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The characters don't look that good, and the explosions aren't
that great. I think they could have done a better job with that
part of the game. The sound wasn't that great, either, but it was
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   `TERMINUS'
</P>
<P>
   Format: PC
</P>
<P>
   Developer: Vatical Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Price: $42.99
</P>
<P>
   Randy's grade: B-plus
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
