<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke it out with mutants in Activision's X-Men Mutant Academy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   X-Men Mutant Academy ($40; www.activision.com; for the
PlayStation), is a game simpatico with the recent summer
blockbuster, which in turn is based on an immensely popular comic
and cartoon franchise. Unfortunately, the game is merely another
means to brand name us with X-Men; it has little to do with the
film. In fact, it only vaguely resembles a modern video game.
Mutant Academy is a well-drawn, well-animated 2-D fighting game _
and that's it. There's no adventure akin to a movie plot, just the
various super-antiheroes duking it out in a face-to-face,
side-scrolling romp. Even on the aging PlayStation console, most
fighting games are known to contain so much more than flat-action
eye-candy, such as three dimensions. Nevertheless, X-Men Mutant
Academy is a good 2-D fighting game complete with trademark
super-moves and painful powers of mutant punishment. But it's the
weakest member in the grand amalgamation scheme of console,
cartoon, comic and cinematic extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   SquareSoft is pushing the bounds of electronic entertainment
into artistic interactive storytelling on game consoles like nobody
else. Besides being the most graphically bright and beautiful game
the PlayStation has seen, Chrono Cross ($40; www .squaresoft.com;
for the PlayStation) is the closest we have yet to come to fully
interactive storytelling. Players move through an engaging world
full of interesting characters, all the while feeling like their
decisions have consequence. The rare computer-generated cut-scenes
are astounding and further draw one emotionally into the adventure.
An elemental rock-paper-scissors combat system is interesting and
effective, yet nonintrusive. Gamers who like turn-based combat can
battle to their hearts' content, while those more interested in
following the storyline are able to mostly avoid conflict, though
not the important battles with boss creatures that they wouldn't
want to miss anyway _ that is until the last third of the game: a
fifteen hour repetitive battle sequence in which the otherwise
remarkable combat system of Chrono Cross loses all entertainment
value. The weak ending, however, isn't enough to drown the memory
of the game's brilliant beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about this PlayStation version of Worms Armageddon:
($30; www.hasbro-interactive .com; for the PlayStation) Sony
initially nixed the idea of a 2-D,
cuter-than-dimples/funnier-than-Looney Tunes action/strategy game
starring squeaky-voiced invertebrate simply for the fact that the
idea of a 2-D, cuter-than-dimples/funnier-than Looney Tunes
action/strategy game starring squeaky-voiced invertebrate didn't
seem like a viable PlayStation game a few years back when Sony was
marketing a hardcore gamer's machine. Now, of course, Sony will
license everything just to saturate the market, which is usually a
bad thing in the watered-down library sense of things, but a very
good thing in this specific case as Worms Armageddon is a
surprisingly great 2-D, cuter-than-dimples/
</P>
<P>
   funnier-than-Looney Tunes action/strategy game starring
squeaky-voiced invertebrate. Excellent even.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Just another racing game? Perhaps, but Breakneck ($40; www
.southpeak.com; for Windows) delivers some of the finest-looking,
smoothest-moving, most engaging racing ever found in the otherwise
saturated genre. Some 40-odd vehicles screaming around eight
variations of a couple dozen tracks promise more bang-for-the-buck
than most. Playable as both a tetchy racing simulation or a
balls-out, crash-bang-smash-`em-up arcade motor-romp, Breakout even
includes an optional combat mode where vehicles are armed with
delightfully effective James Bond-type weapons. Lord knows there's
nothing like dropping a sack of nails behind you to thwart that
aggressive tailgater, and hey, who hasn't wished for a heat-seeking
missile on that dolt who always manages to take the lead despite
one's best efforts?
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   In a world of clones, you've got to admire innovation, even when
it succeeds modestly. Case in point: Evolva ($50,
www.interplay.com, for Windows), a refreshingly unusual squad-based
third-person-shooter set in a vastly distant future in which humans
_ or what humans have become _ must devour the DNA of their enemies
and evolve on the fly to survive. You control a customizeable
four-person squad of genohunters who must defeat a planetary
infestation of evil space spore. It sounds strange, and it is _
almost too strange. An undefinable coolness creeps into the
gameplay, with its lack of verbal communication or music, its
muted, pastel environments and its reptilian kill-or-be-killed
gameplay. Multiplayer fighting becomes a race to evolve fastest,
and the single-player levels border on the mundane. That said,
Evolva gets extra credit for going out on a limb with its weird
premise, smooth controls, multiple camera screens, creepy monsters
and uncanny alien feel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Stafford
</P>
<P>
   , but don't expect anything akin to the summer motion picture
blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
