<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The thinking tot's puzzle
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A simple, durable puzzle game geared more toward
conceptual thinking than basic motor skills, the Changing Places
Puzzle ($10; www .allaboardkids.com offers animal picture pieces on
transparencies that overlay onto corresponding scenery; the owl
goes in the tree, the octopus in the ocean, the spaceman in space,
that sort of thing. And while even the hardiest cardboard puzzle
games don't seem to withstand the chewing, stomping and throwing
tests most toddlers manage to put toys through, Changing Places
Puzzle pieces are made of smoothly polished wood. And, the puzzle
comes with a lifetime guarantee should any part be damaged or lost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   A GENTLE BOUNCE FOR BABY
</P>
<P>
   Fisher Price really seems to shine when it doesn't they don't
try too hard. The Deluxe Soothing Bouncer Seat ($30;
www.fisher-price.com) is a marvel of simple technology,
well-implemented. A cute and colorful cloth hammock in a stalwart
but springy wire frame, complete with retractable sun-screen
canopy, is further enhanced by a single-battery motor that will set
the unit to vibrating like a gentle martini maker. This comforting
movement is reportedly ``similar to a ride in the car,'' albeit one
in which case your car is in desperate need of on an alignment.
Regardless, the Deluxe Soothing Baby Seat is wonderfully efficient,
cost effective and a must-have for any parent wishing the
second-best thing to an old-fashioned, hands-on, comforting cuddle
for their soothable wee one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
