<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animation on the Web takes two steps forward and one back
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.icebox.com _ Animation on the Web has matured in
sophistication but much of it has severely regressed in taste.
Icebox.com is at the center of a storm of controversy over its
``Mr. Wong'' cartoon, deemed offensive by some Asian-American
groups. While you may want to skip that show, others, such as
``Superhero Roommate'' and a new show by ``Ren and Stimpy'' creator
John Kricfalusi are funny and entertaining, if a bit dirty.
</P>
<P>
   209.35.112.207/buddies/frisbee/ _ It will take up, maybe, three
minutes of your day, but for those three minutes, you will be
pleasantly amused by this animated game of ``Frisbee dog.'' Just be
careful _ very bad things can happen if your dog catches something
other than a frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   www.emotioneric.com _ Eric Wu can be pretty emotional. In fact,
his site is not much more than a collection of pictures showing
Eric displaying various emotional states. While the first few were
predictable, later requests submitted by readers (``Hardcore
Gangsta Eric,'' ``Being Born'') have brought out some true
creativity in Eric.
</P>
<P>
   www.theforce.net/theater/trailers/episodeii/directorepisodeii.shtml
_ Star Wars fans, this one's for you. Cut together by an anonymous
director, this fan trailer for ``Star Wars: Episode II'' looks so
real, it's hard to imagine George Lucas will be able to top it.
Splicing in footage of actors scheduled to appear in the new film,
it may turn out the amateur trailer bests the real thing when it
</P>
<P>
   finally appears.
</P>
<P>
   _ Omar L. Gallaga
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
