<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Official site gets you in mood for Olympic Games to begin
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Caught the Olympic fever yet?
</P>
<P>
   Already program the Palm, the pager and the phone to deliver
track and field results and soccer scores? That's OK. You still
have some time before the torch lights up in Sydney to work up some
enthusiasm and national pride for the good old US of A.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you could care less about platform diving,
world-class cycling or even basketball, one visit to the official
Olympic site (www.olympics.com/eng) is something you absolutely
must do if you do nothing else Olympics-related for the entire
month of September.
</P>
<P>
   Built for the nations of the world by the good folk at IBM who
know a thing or two about sports sites _ they do the Web handiwork
for the Masters golf tournament, Wimbledon and the U.S. Open, after
all _ the Sydney 2000 site is really something to see.
</P>
<P>
   This official Olympics site is exactly what the Olympic Games _
or any major sporting event _ of the modern era are all about: the
merger of sports, commerce and high-tech entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Equally entertaining are the well-designed sponsor boxes in the
top right-hand corner. Is it just irony that the Games devoted to
discipline, endurance and self-sacrifice are sponsored by Cadbury
chocolates and Olestra, the fake-fat product found in products like
Lay's Wow potato chips?
</P>
<P>
   Log on to the Olympics site, and you can look at a breathtaking
view of Sydney's harbor from the Goodyear ``blimpcam'' while music
plays in the background from the CD ``Olympic Record.'' The CD is
for sale in the Olympic shop, in case you were wondering, along
with a variety of unique and un-touristy objects ranging from fine
jewelry to works of art and one-of-a-kind quilts on sale to support
the Paralympics. There are, of course, the ever-popular Olympic
pins _ think of them as Pokemon cards for the over-40 set. Prices
are in Australian dollars, but there is a currency converter that
pops up in a separate screen so you can see how many American
dollars it'll cost you to get the goods from Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   But shopping and technological fireworks aside, the Sydney 2000
Web site gets down to some fundamentals clueless North Americans
might need. For example, where is Australia anyway? Let's answer
that puzzler before we move on to tougher topics _ like when will
Americans get to see the gymnastics on TV?
</P>
<P>
   Click on the words ``What time is it in Sydney?'' and you'll get
another pop-up screen with a world map, a time and temperature
check, a three-day forecast and the time difference between Sydney
and every time zone in the world. We discovered, for example, that
11 p.m. on the East Coast of the United States is 2 in the
afternoon the next day in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Compare the official Olympics site with NBCOlympics.com. NBC has
exclusive U.S. broadcast rights to the Olympics, and its site is a
frenzy of pro-American news. And it's brought to you not by a candy
bar company but by those pushing good old-fashioned red-blooded
American products like Budweiser, adidas and Ameritrade. Beer,
running shoes and stocks _ the hot dogs and apple pie of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC site was designed by Quokka Sports, the extreme-sports
Internet company that's much admired by Web designers for its
ability to make nearly any sport jump off the computer monitor and
into your home. (Check out the Mountainzone.com site for a
combination of great photos and climbers' diaries to get a sense of
what Quokka is all about).
</P>
<P>
   So between the official site and the NBC site, there's an
international and a country-specific look at the Olympic Games,
which is fine. But neither site can answer one very fundamental
question: When will we get to see the actual Olympics on TV?
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Olympics site lists events in local time. The NBC
site offers two schedules: an ``Olympic schedule'' and a
``broadcast schedule.'' NBC will also be using all three of its
broadcast properties (including CNBC and MSNBC) to round out
coverage of the Games. But unless you want to bust open another
browser and toggle back and forth between the American broadcast
schedule and the timing of the actual events, it's easy to become
very confused.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Web and our good neighbors to the north come
in. The Canadian Broadcasting Corp. (www.cbc.ca) is going to show
the events live. That means the opening ceremonies will begin at
3:45 a.m. Friday on the East Coast (that's 6:45 p.m. in Sydney).
But NBC won't be airing the ceremonies until 7:30 that evening.
Sports junkies can also check out a number of international Web
sites in the wee hours of the morning to get scores and results
even if they have to wait to see the action stateside.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in the broader issues surrounding the Olympics
will enjoy the CBC's detailed coverage of athletes bounced from the
Games for failing drug tests. Or check out a BBC report
(news.bbc.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   /sport/hi/english/olympics2000/default.stm) on the questionable
manufacturing practices of Nike sneakers. There's a lot more than
sports going on in Sydney, and the Web is a window to a
multicultural perspective on a multinational event.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
