<HEADER>
A8736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-LEARN-ONLINE0912     09-11 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LEARN-ONLINE0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting an education online
 &HT;    By Anne Meyers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The computer has become the classroom for an
increasing number of college students, in a transformation that
eliminates the boundaries of geography and scheduled class times.
</P>
<P>
   Computers provide virtual classrooms, cyberlibraries and online
chat areas where students can plug in to their college classes from
any location. The ability to enroll in full-fledged undergraduate
and graduate programs has opened the possibility of college
instruction for time-pressed professionals as well as those
shackled to home by family responsibilities or physical
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience of course work, combined with greater access to
computers, has fueled the growth of Internet offerings at Georgia
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   At Southern Polytechnic State University in Marietta, the
Internet was first used in the fall of 1997 for the master's of
science in quality assurance program. That semester, 69 students
were taking classes on campus and 29 were taking courses online. In
the fall of 2000, 19 students are taking on-campus classes and 76
are taking the courses using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see more courses and degrees offered in the
Internet distance-learning format,'' said Larry Aft, a professor
who helped develop the pilot degree program for Southern Tech.
``The convenience and flexibility of this format make it very
attractive to students.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet offerings made up approximately 31,560 credit hours in
fiscal year 2000 for the 34 public colleges and universities of the
University System of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is becoming much more of a tool in our everyday
lives,'' says Kris Biesinger, assistant vice chancellor of advanced
learning technologies for the Board of Regents of the University
System of Georgia. ``Using this same tool to access education is
becoming more mainstream. It is converging in a one-stop approach
to education, and it's becoming more user-friendly. Technology
affords us to really match learning environment with learning
need.''
</P>
<P>
   An August report by media measurement firm Media Metrix shows
overall growth in Internet use plus a significant increase in
Internet accessibility for families with a household income under
$25,000 a year. ``Among the reasons for the gradual closing of the
`digital divide' are the continued fall in computer prices,
increased technological ease-of-use, and improved access to the
Internet in professional, academic and community environments,''
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Green is vice president for communication for Georgia
GLOBE, a University System of Georgia program designed to increase
access to courses and degree programs offered by the public
colleges and universities. Green is pursuing her education
doctorate through an online degree program.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an online student, I have a much greater flexibility as to
how and when I study,'' Green said. ``There was no way I could do
my job and go through a doctoral program. But because I've been
able to do a large portion of it online, I now can.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said many Georgians share in her enthusiasm. ``In a
statewide survey of over 500 respondents, over 60 percent indicated
they would use either the Internet or Georgia Public Broadcasting
to take courses,'' Green said. ``The numbers of people taking
online and/or distance-learning courses is increasing rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Distance learning isn't new. But technology has changed the
delivery of the old-fashioned correspondence course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distance education has been around since a reliable post
office,'' says Lynne Schrum, associate professor at the University
of Georgia's department of instructional technology. ``We now have
the whole gamut from totally online to still sending out
videotapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, one of the world's leading engineering schools,
offers graduate level degrees through distance learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students want courses anytime, anyplace,'' says Joe Boland,
director of Georgia Tech's Center for Distance Learning.
``Engineers realize that a master's degree in a technical field is
important, and some cannot interrupt their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Boland, Georgia Tech's distance-learning program
reaches a wide range of students. The program has admitted students
who range from fresh-out-of-college 22-year-olds seeking master's
degrees to a 70-year-old student wanting to brush up on his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Distance-learning programs often attract working professionals.
Some may live far from the teaching institution; others may work
late hours or travel in their careers. For these students,
on-campus classes are not a viable option. Distance learning allows
these professionals to pursue their desired degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got people in north Atlanta that take courses and attain
the degree by distance learning,'' Boland said. ``They choose to do
them this way because of the convenience. ... We deliver the
courses anywhere in the world where we can ship videotapes or they
can have access to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 34 public colleges and universities in the
University System of Georgia participates in distance education.
Some may use distance learning to only enhance traditional courses,
while others may only receive courses that originate from other
campuses through GSAMS (Georgia Statewide Academic and Medical
System), an interactive videoconferencing system.
</P>
<P>
   The number of distance offerings and types of courses varies by
institution. Degree programs are offered through six of these
institutions, and an online MBA is offered by a consortium of five
others. More institutions will be offering degrees through distance
learning in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Distance-education delivery formats vary by course, with some
courses using several technologies. Options include GSAMS,
Internet, CD-ROM, satellite, cable and video-based instruction.
</P>
<P>
   GSAMS allows an instructor to teach students in multiple
locations simultaneously. It links approximately 400 sites in
Georgia for primarily academic programs. The students reduce travel
time by selecting a site near them. This technology could be
likened to a visual group phone call where students and instructor
communicate in real time.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is used in several ways. Students can access course
notes and assignments on the World Wide Web. Some online courses
are supplemented with CD-ROMs and videotapes. Classmates can
communicate with each other and the instructor using e-mail, online
chat, electronic bulletin boards or a combination of methods,
sometimes including face-to-face meetings.
</P>
<P>
   A popular method of delivery is the telecourse. Telecourses use
television or videotapes as well as printed materials. Access to
telecourses is through satellite, cable television, public
television and wireless cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely degrees that people get almost entirely
without seeing each other,'' Schrum said.
</P>
<P>
   There are also combinations where some classes meet at select
times during the semester but the majority of course work is
completed at a distance. A distance-learning course, by definition,
requires at least 51 percent of the course to be conducted through
distance-learning formats.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary statistics that cover the past year in
distance learning within the University System of Georgia,
Internet-based courses hosted approximately 11,000 course seats.
This number compares to GSAMS' 5,300 course seats over the same
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear a great deal about Internet-based courses because it
is the new thing and very appealing in theory,'' Schrum said.
</P>
<P>
   Grading systems vary by course and instructor, just like those
in a traditional environment.
</P>
<P>
   There are distance courses that grade by class participation,
research papers and essay exams.
</P>
<P>
   Some courses weigh heavier on midterm and final exams, which may
even be offered at a student's workplace with a proctor.
</P>
<P>
   The distance-learning courses are as difficult and
time-consuming as traditional courses. ``When I speak with
potential students, I tell them that it requires every bit of
effort that it takes you if you come to campus,'' Boland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be motivated, self-disciplined, and you have to
see the need for the program and how it will benefit you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
