<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel camera a good intro to digital
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A little device called the Intel Pocket PC Camera has
given me my first taste of digital photography, and it's been a
very good introduction.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel camera is designed to work both as one of those
cameras tethered to a PC or as a free-range camera like its big
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tiny thing, about 4 inches by 2 1/2, all plastic, and it
looks like a toy. However, the Intel camera is surprisingly
capable.
</P>
<P>
   When connected by a long cable to your computer's USB port, it
draws its power from the computer.
</P>
<P>
   It is somewhat awkward to use as a proper camera in this mode,
because you're supposed to use the image presented through the
accompanying software on your computer monitor instead of the
viewfinder.
</P>
<P>
   This means that regardless of how long the cable may be, you
have to be positioned behind the PC monitor.
</P>
<P>
   In this mode, you can adjust the focus by turning the little
blue lens housing, and every press of the snapshot button produces
an image in the software.
</P>
<P>
   Unhooked from the computer and powered by four AAA batteries,
the operator uses the viewfinder and the little display window on
the top of the camera. This indicates whether the presumed subject
is in focus, how many photos are in memory and whether the camera
is set to make high-quality images (640x480 pixels) or normal
quality (320x240).
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable thing about this camera, perhaps, is its 8
megabytes of memory. That's as much as provided with some digital
cameras costing five times as much.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Intel camera can hold up to 128 high-quality
images. There is no way, of course, to view and selectively delete
images from memory when the camera isn't connected to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The camera has a 10-second self-timer; it can take 10-second
movies and run off a string of five sequence shots. The mode is
selected by a button beside the display window, and the window, in
addition to noting the mode, also indicates battery life and the
timer's progression.
</P>
<P>
   Images from the camera are, it seems to me, better than they
ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   The camera comes with MGI Photosuite, which allows considerable
manipulation of the images and a program that downloads the images
and affords basic manipulation, plus help in making e-mail
postcards and other productions. It's quite easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with a little wrist strap, a base on which the
camera can be placed while tethered to the computer, and a carrying
case.
</P>
<P>
   The only real downside is the documentation, which is entirely
online. There is, however, a little basic guide that will fit in
the carrying case with the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The Pocket PC Camera lists for $149. For more information, see
www.intel.com/PCcamera.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
