<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8741 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0912-COX     09-11 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to say about (at)$&AMP;?
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Reporters can be a pain in the posterior.
But describing them as more particular parts of a posterior is
going too far.
</P>
<P>
   So when George W. Bush described a New York Times reporter last
week as ``major league'' in a vividly uncomplimentary manner while
a microphone broadcast it, a certified issue was created.
</P>
<P>
   And editors had to decide how to impart this tastefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press report described the word only as ``a
profanity.'' This is tasteful but vague. You didn't know if the
offending word was something very bad, something pungently
Texas-sounding in the tradition of fellow-Texan Lyndon Johnson, or
merely something a little too naughty to say around the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Did Bush evoke one of the mild expletives deleted from a Richard
Nixon recording or one of the stronger expletives not deleted from
an Eminem recording? If you didn't hear it, you wouldn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``THAT GUY'S AN (at)$&AMP;!'' The New York Daily News blared. I like
this approach. Yet it, too, can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``(at)$&AMP;'' suggests a string of curses not one, lonely noun. Any
comic page reader will confirm this. It is always in the next panel
after you see Dagwood carrying a hammer and picture frame.
</P>
<P>
   No such niceties were observed by editors of National Public
Radio's ``Morning Edition.'' They rolled the tape and let it speak
for itself. No beeps.
</P>
<P>
   There is something to be said for this. When I hear a beep over
a word, I assume the worse. If I heard a tape of Bush calling the
reporter ``a major-league beeeeeep,'' I would have reached into the
further reaches of my vocabulary to fill the blank.
</P>
<P>
   And I would have been wrong and excessively creative. NPR
editors said, reasonably enough, they included the offending
reference to human anatomy because after all the yucky Starr Report
stuff, it didn't seem that bad.
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But I suspect a post-Monica backlash is brewing
among news consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The printed word has a certain power and lastingness that
amplifies any offhand remark, any biting sound bite, any snippet
overheard by a microphone's indifferent circuitry. Which is why
newspapers handle matters of popular vocabulary rather
conservatively.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone wanting the exact language may look it up on the
Internet, a medium in which you may seek out a word without a word
seeking out you.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, I have learned firsthand about reader
sensitivities. I received complaints for using the phrase ``old
f_t'' in a self-depreciating way. Several people contacted me to
depreciate me themselves, feeling I had done an inadequate job.
</P>
<P>
   I have been more careful since.
</P>
<P>
   Bush apologized for his statement. Sort of. Mostly he said was
sorry other people heard. He wasn't sorry he dissed someone for
doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a certain amount of tsk-tsking, the result is a wash.
Bush may have been embarrassed _ though probably not _ but nobody
ever lost an election by insulting the press. The key to
press-bashing is to seem like a person righteously provoked and not
a (at)$&AMP; whiner.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, meanwhile, gained street credibility his
colleagues can only envy.
</P>
<P>
   In most occupations, being insulted by a potential president of
the United States so that's it's heard everywhere on the planet
would considered A Bad Thing. For a reporter, it could go on a
resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``That major-league (at)$&AMP;! Why wasn't it me?'' his colleagues
on the bus are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
