<HEADER>
A8742 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0912-CO     09-11 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The mysterious Aunt Rob
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Aunt Rob lived just around the corner from
the Parkers on Herschel Street. She was Granddaddy Parker's sister,
but as I recall, there wasn't a whole lot of visiting back and
forth. I don't ever remember seeing Aunt Rob at Grandmother's table
for Sunday dinner or sitting on the front porch drinking tea and
talking with visitors. I never knew if she'd been married or had
any children. Guess no one thought to mention it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a short walk to Aunt Rob's and if I really concentrated,
and if I was lucky enough to be wearing my canvas beach shoes, the
ones with the soft soles, I could walk all the way over and back
without slipping off the half-round, six-inch curb stones that
separated Riverside lawns from the octagonal stone sidewalks that
were okay for hopscotch but impossible for roller skating.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Rob's house, like Mrs. Parker's and so many other places in
Jacksonville, had a cane break in the yard for shade and privacy.
Summer nights I remember lying in my bed beside the sleeping porch
window and listening to the sough of the cane as the river breeze
stirred it into a loosely conducted symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Fat columns lined the porch that surrounded Aunt Rob's house,
and I remember hugging one each time I went there to see if I'd
grown enough to reach around it. I never had.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Rob didn't answer her own door. That was Nelson's job. He
lived on the place and took care of things like phones and doors,
and emptying the drip pan under the icebox that Aunt Rob had kept
even though there was a Norge refrigerator in the pantry, because
she had to have chipped ice, not cubes, in her tea and Co'Cola.
</P>
<P>
   It was always quiet and shady in Aunt Rob's parlor because
Nelson had learned the finely tuned southern art of climate control
long before anyone had air-conditioning. As the sun moved across
the house, he'd adjust the wooden-louvered shutters that covered
the downstairs windows, four and six to a room, running from the
floor almost to the 12-foot ceilings, to take advantage of any
breezes that might stray in across the St. John's River.
</P>
<P>
   Once I asked Nelson if he had any children I could play with and
he looked sad. Said his babies had all grown up and gone away.
``Moved to Georgia,'' I remember him saying with such a sour look
coming across his face that for years I was wary of stepping off
the train with my parents for a walk around the platform in places
like Waycross or Valdosta, for fear something awful would happen
and I too would have to leave home and move to Georgia. A couple of
decades later, I did just that, but nothing too awful came of it.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to Aunt Rob's were always kind of formal, but I was
fascinated by what I couldn't see there. I often wondered what life
was like in the other rooms _ the ones I'd never seen and never
would see. I tried to imagine what Aunt Rob might be like when no
one else was around.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, early, I sneaked out of Grandmother Parker's house
and padded barefoot around the curbstones and into Aunt Rob's side
yard. I knew better than to peek through the dining room shutters,
but I did it anyway and saw Aunt Rob sitting at the little table by
the windows, picking toast from a rack that I guessed Nelson had
put there with her breakfast. Her hair was loose from the wispy bun
she usually wore and she looked so pretty and so young that I
wanted to run back and tell someone, but of course, I couldn't
because I'd been snooping. Aunt Rob remained my mystery.
</P>
<P>
   I was seven the summer I walked the curb to Aunt Rob's for the
last time. I rang the bell and hugged a column while I waited for
Nelson to answer. He never did. Aunt Rob was gone too.
</P>
<P>
   I walked the same curb back to Grandmother's and asked where
Aunt Rob was. I was told, ``Away.'' That's all I ever knew.
Finally, I stopped asking.
</P>
<P>
   And now there's no one left who knows.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
