<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A MiniDisc Walkman to get you groovin'
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The MiniDisc format, which allows
digital-quality recording and re-recording on a tiny, flat disc,
may never reach its full potential now that recordable CDs are all
the rage and portable MP3 players make the idea of any kind of disc
seem almost quaint. But Sony is proving there's still life in the
format with its array of MiniDisc Walkman models, including the
MZ-R70PC ($300; www.sel.sony.com), which includes a USB connector
for hooking up to a computer and recording audio right off the
desktop. The player/recorder looks and sounds fantastic, and the
sparse packaging is packed with stuff _ an AC adapter, a
headphones/wired-controller combo that allows you to edit tracks,
an optical digital cable for hooking up to your sound system and
even a rechargeable battery. Setup and installation is a breeze. If
there's any complaint it's that the MZ-R70PC isn't Mac-friendly and
doesn't seem to record at very loud volumes off a PC, even with the
volume in Windows cranked up all the way.
</P>
<P>
   _ Omar L. Gallaga
</P>
<P>
   GOLF SCOPE'S GOT A LINK TO DISTANCE
</P>
<P>
   There was quite a frenzy around Radio Shack's Golf Scope ($20;
www.radioshack.com) last Christmas. After all, everybody knows at
least one golfer, and the friendly price tag pretty much made this
distance-to-pin elucidator a no-brainer gift idea. Hence, it sold
out at every store. I finally had the chance to evaluate a Golf
Scope only to find, first off, that a lot of golfers were looking
at me funny. But regardless of how nerdy the technogeek device made
me look, it really did exactly what it's supposed to do. You merely
peek through the telescope and line up the pin on an inset grid
pattern that effectively gives you the distance. No matter, I
continued to slice right regardless of the apparently appropriate
club the scope helped me to select . . . Good golfers may find it
more useful _ the technogeek golfers at any rate.
</P>
<P>
   GLADIAC'S GOT A LEG UP ON THE COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   While the next generation of ``next generation'' 3-D accelerator
cards seem to appear about as fast as they collectively push
polygons, Elsa's Gladiac ($330; www.elsa.com) not only uses
nVidia's current iteration of its fast graphics chip, the GeForce2
GTS, it was the first out of the gate and onto retail shelves,
which gave it a huge head start on all the other manufactures using
nVidia chips. More importantly, the Gladiac's Winman Suite utility
includes, among other things, an overclocking tool, which allows
one to tweak performance beyond its stock specs. That means
blindingly fast graphics in first-person-shooter games like Quake
III. A bold addition further enhanced by a crash utility that will
perceive a system lock, notify you at reboot and automatically
reset your tweaks back to the default settings. Regardless, Elsa's
Gladiac GeForce2 GTS is remarkably stable and frightfully fast; it
promises to remain faithfully powerful and stinky speedy in spite
of the fact that a GeForce2 GTS ``Ultra'' chip is due to appear on
the market shortly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
