<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One quick mouse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While Apple ``reinvents'' the mouse a year after
Microsoft does the same thing with an optical sensor _ or
``IntelliEye'' _ replacing the underbelly trackball, it's worth
visiting the sci-fi-sexy Razer Boomslang 2000 ($99;
www.razerzone.com), a frightfully fast precision mouse that
reinvents, instead, how that underbelly trackball is read. With a
pinpoint accurate laser light reader, the Boomslang's refined
encoder accurately tracks mouse-ball movement at 2000 dpi, far more
than the typical rodent reading at 400 dpi. This means, of course,
you get fast and accurate cursor movement with very little throw of
the actual device. Essentially the quintessential gamer's mouse
(it's particularly malicious with first-person-shooting games), the
USB Boomslang can also replace your MAC or PC mouse for everyday
usage at work.NO MORE NOTEBOOK CRAMP
</P>
<P>
   3M, ever the innovator of unglorified office products, scores
again with the Adjustable Notebook Platform ($70; www.3m.com) from
its Office Ergonomics line. Mindful of the fact that the compact
design of laptop computers can put a strain on the user's body,
particularly when it is placed on a support surface that isn't
height and tilt adjustable, the Adjustable Notebook Platform has an
``adjustable wedge'' design that angles a notebook toward the user
to improve wrist angle and viewing posture. It also features a
built-in mousing area with a gel-filled wrist rest that
accommodates standard-sized mouse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Conlin
</P>
