<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0912     09-11 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So what if Olympics are tape-delayed? Get over it
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Here's a bulletin for all you folks whining
about NBC's forthcoming tape-delayed coverage of the Summer
Olympics:
</P>
<P>
   There are three alternatives to taped coverage of the Games in
Sydney and none is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   First, NBC could telecast the Games live as they are taking
place in prime time in Australia. That means American viewers would
get to watch premiere events such as gymnastics, diving and track
at about 3 a.m. We could set our alarms, gather around the tube and
squeeze in all our family viewing before work and school. We'd be
exhausted and grumpy by lunch, but we'd get to watch the Olympics
live.
</P>
<P>
   Second, we could somehow convince organizers of the Olympics
that no matter where the Games take place, athletes must perform at
times that coincide with prime time in America. That means hundreds
of athletes who have spent their entire lives training for that
moment of glory would have to perform at unnatural times. Marathon
at high noon? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Third, we could insist that all Olympic Games take place in the
United States, so this ugly problem with time zones would
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of ugly . . . it is the height of Ugly Americanism
(theme song: ``Jingo Bells'') to assume that the world should
revolve around our prime-time TV schedule. It is our privilege to
watch Olympic athletes perform. They should do so at their
convenience, and they should be seen at the convenience of the host
country.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a teensy bit unsettling that results of the competition
will be all over the media before prime-time TV coverage begins?
Well, maybe for some people, especially obsessive sports fans like
Austin American-Statesman executive sports editor David Humphrey,
who was ``appalled'' to learn that all of NBC's coverage will be
tape-delayed, and KTBC sports anchor Dave Cody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say tape-delay ruins the Games, but it does take away
some of the immediacy,'' Cody says. ``As a viewer, I wish they'd
carry them live because I like live TV. I'd tune in in the middle
of the night to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody says he'll probably watch some of the Olympics, but he'll
check news sources, including the Internet, to find the results of
events he's particularly interested in before they're on TV.
Viewers who don't want to know ahead of time will need to steer
clear of news reports during the day.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, though, it's a thrill to see the international
spectacle of the Olympics. Who wins or loses _ the thrill of
victory and the agony of defeat _ is only part of the story. The
human drama, the journey to the result, are equally compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the complaints have been louder this time around because
NBC is being up-front about the tape-delay issue, instead of using
those ``plausible'' and ``virtual live'' tags from the past.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not like this is the first time we've had taped
Olympics. The '96 Games in Atlanta were 60 percent tape-delayed and
turned out to be the most-watched Olympics ever. The '92 Games in
Barcelona were all tape, and the '94 Winter Games in Lillehammer,
with that spectacularly high-rated women's ice skating contest,
were on tape. Obviously people can stomach tape-delayed Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol, vice president of NBC Sports and executive
producer of the Olympics, has wrestled with time zone problems for
years and said in a recent teleconference that he thought briefly
about asking the Australians to change the times of the events. But
after less than a day Down Under, he changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 19 1/2 million people who live there, and they
deserve to come home, turn on the Olympics at the end of the day
and watch all of the key events in their prime time,'' Ebersol
said. ``We have to learn to get along, and we have to accept the
fact that we cannot walk into somebody's country and say, `This
would be more convenient for people in America to watch in the
evening, while they're having their chips and Cokes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I'm pumped. We've been watching reruns for months, and this week
we get the Parade of Nations, followed later by platform diving,
profiles of obscure but fascinating jocks from Belarus and the
fastest men and women alive. When Michael Johnson slips on his gold
track shoes, I'll be there. And I won't have to set an alarm to do
it. So what if he's on tape? He's going for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
