<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumer Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Greigc. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I am desperately, desperately in search of a
3- or 4-foot-tall Statue of Liberty (inflatable?) for a display. It
has to be somewhat affordable.
</P>
<P>
   _ C.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Is $390 somewhat affordable? That is the going rate for a
30.5-inch-high resin replica of this 151'1'' tall lady, who
celebrated her 100th birthday in 1986. Contact the small book shop
on the statue's pedestal at (212) 363-3180 for details. Short gig?
Dress up like the statue in a costume from Any Kind-A Costume, 2700
W. Anderson Lane, where a $30 rental fee gets you the torch, crown,
sash and dress. Q: How can the famous Olsen twins, Mary-Kate and
Ashley, be fraternal twins if they look exactly alike? How can they
not be identical twins? I am a triplet and one of my sisters looks
like me and the other doesn't. I have always thought that meant I
have an identical twin and a fraternal twin, but now I am not too
sure.
</P>
<P>
   _ K.O.
</P>
<P>
   A: Similar appearance is no guarantee that twins are identical _
only strong evidence, says University of Texas genetics lecturer
Nan Hampton. Triplets may be all single zygotes (three different
eggs fertilized by three different sperm), in which case no pair is
genetically identical. Triplets may also be a pair of identical
(monozygotic, a single egg fertilized by a single sperm split into
two embryos) twins with the other triplet being a single zygote.
</P>
<P>
   How to tell? Differences in traits such as blood groups and
plasma protein types indicate twins are not identical, reports
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Famous triplet? Dr. Elisabeth Kubler-Ross, author and expert on
death and dying, was the first born in her set. And Texas' own Todd
triplets, Joseph, Michael and Daniel, played the sons of Katie and
Robbie Douglas on ``My Three Sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: On Trinity Broadcasting Network is a performer named Carman
(no last name). He is a singer, actor, dancer, Bible teacher and
very, very handsome. Could you please tell me how old he is, his
nationality, marital status and how tall he is? Oh yes, could you
give me his address?
</P>
<P>
   _ Donna B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Carman does have a last name _ Licciardello. Born in New
Jersey on Jan. 19, 1956, he is of Italian heritage. I could not get
his exact height from the folks at Carman Ministries, but they
estimate about 6 feet. Good news? Carman is not married, and
autographed photos are free. Write to him at Carman Ministries,
Inc., P.O. Box 5093, Brentwood, Tenn. 37024 or visit
www.carman.org. Q: I remember a cartoon that featured superheroes
like Strong Man, Rope Man, Baby Man, Tornado Man and Cuckoo Man.
Unfortunately, no one else does! Can you dig up any information on
these guys?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jason Kutac
</P>
<P>
   A: You are right. ``Mighty Heroes'' was a short lived
(1966-1967) half-hour series that replaced the popular, albeit
dated, ``Mighty Mouse Playhouse'' on Saturday morning. Directed by
Ralph Bakshi (``Lord of the Rings'') this CBS series had a lock on
odd characters. Diaper Man as a leader? For more on this wacky set
of villain chasers, pick up copy of Alex McNeil's ``Total
Television.'' Q: I've been trying to remember the old adage that
dictated the daily routines of our grandmothers and
great-grandmothers. Part of it goes like this: ``Wash on Monday;
iron on Tuesday; clean on Friday; bake on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   What did these busy women do on Wednesday and Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosemary W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Close. Wash on Monday, iron on Tuesday, mend on Wednesday,
clean on Thursday, shop on Friday, cook on Saturday and rest on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   Need more information on the Synthroid class action litigation?
(Synthroid is a prescription medication for a thyroid condition.)
Deadline for filing claims or objecting to the settlement was this
past March. Call (800) 853-4853, write to Synthroid Marketing
Litigation, P.O. Box 7090, San Rafael, Calif. 94912-7090 or visit
www.synthroidclaims.com.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
