<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     09-11 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS AND PATIENTS WIN OVER DRUG CZAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds, use brackets sted parens in 4thgraf) 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His email address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government lost what may be a key battle in the drug
war last week over doctor-recommended use of marijuana for medical
purposes. The federal government deserved to lose.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, U.S. District Court Judge William Alsup for the
Northern District of California issued a permanent injunction
forbidding the government from threatening California doctors for
recommending medical marijuana to their patients (Dr. Marcus Conant
v. Barry R. McCaffrey).
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, California voters passed Proposition 215, the
Compassionate Use Act or Medical Marijuana Initiative. The law
states, in part, that ``seriously ill Californians have the right
to obtain and use marijuana for medical purposes where that medical
use is deemed appropriate and has been recommended by a physician
who has determined that the person's health would benefit from the
use of marijuana in the treatment of cancer, anorexias, AIDS,
chronic pain, spasticity, glaucoma, arthritis, migraine, or any
other illness for which marijuana provides relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 215 specifically protects physicians who recommend
marijuana: ``(No) physician in this state shall be punished, or
denied any right or privilege for having recommended marijuana to a
patient for medical purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Drug Czar Barry R. McCaffrey's claims to the contrary,
doctors across the nation have found that marijuana is a very
effective anti-nausea drug, stimulates appetite and takes the
cutting edge off cancer and other pain _ with few side effects.
</P>
<P>
   A mere two months after Proposition 215 was passed, the Office
of National Drug Control Policy issued the Clinton administration's
official response: ``a practitioner's action of recommending or
prescribing Schedule I controlled substances is not consistent with
the `public interest' and will lead to administrative action by the
Drug Enforcement Administration to revoke the practitioner's
registration.'' The response also stated that the U.S. Department
of Justice would review cases for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana is classified as a Schedule I drug, like peyote and
heroin. Schedule I drugs do not have established medical value.
Therefore, the Drug Enforcement Agency, the Department of Justice
and McCaffrey began threatening to take away doctors' ability to
dispense medical drugs if those same doctors recommended medical
marijuana to their patients _ despite California's law.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is ample evidence that the Clinton administration
fashioned its punitive response after California and Arizona had
each passed medical marijuana initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after California's Proposition 215 took effect, a
DEA agent began investigating Robert Mastroianni, a physician in
Pollock Pines, because he had allegedly written a marijuana
recommendation for one of his patients. This action by the DEA
stopped most doctors from talking freely to their patients about
the use of medical marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors filed a class action lawsuit in a federal district
court against McCaffrey and federal government drug agencies. The
point of the doctors' original lawsuit is that drug agencies were
interfering in the doctor-patient relationship and keeping doctors
from giving patients their best medical advice. The lawsuit asked
for a temporary injunction against the government _ to halt the
unwarranted harassment of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors won that lawsuit on April 30, 1997, but the terms
laid out by U.S. District Court Judge Fern M. Smith weren't clear
enough to protect the doctors from further harassment.
</P>
<P>
   So the doctors went to court again and asked that the temporary
injunction be made permanent and urged the court to define the
terms of allowable communication more clearly. The doctors sought a
clear demarcation line that says a doctor can recommend medical
marijuana to a patient without being in jeopardy of retaliatory
action by the DEA.
</P>
<P>
   However, doctors cannot dispense or prescribe marijuana for the
patient without falling outside the law. The doctors did not seek
the authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The new ruling does just what the doctors hoped it would. It
permits California doctors to recommend the use of medical
marijuana and enter it on the patient's charts without worrying
about being penalized.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union's attorneys, representing
doctors and patients, crafted their brief carefully so that it
raised a First Amendment issue only. Can doctors speak freely to
their patients without drug agents interfering?
</P>
<P>
   Alsup analyzed the legislative history and language of the bill
that created the drug laws. He notes: ``Congress did not address
whether the government may revoke a physician's registration based
on the physician recommending a Schedule I drug to a patient. The
term `recommend' does not appear in Section 824 of the statute. The
legislative history is silent as to whether Congress intended that
such conduct could constitute a ground for revocation. As stated,
no case law addresses the point. No regulations have been issued.
All that exist are statements by the government, including the
administration's Response, giving its current view of the
statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress did not address the issue and the drug agencies
had not issued rules regarding doctor recommendations, the judge
decided that the First Amendment must take precedence. He wrote:
``The government itself would allow physicians to `discuss' the
pros and cons of marijuana therapy with their patients. In some
cases, however, it will be the professional opinion of doctors that
marijuana is the best therapy or at least should be tried. If such
recommendations could not be communicated, then the
physician-patient relationship would be seriously impaired.
Patients need to know their doctors' recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also noted that a patient armed with such knowledge
may enter the public debate about the medical use of marijuana.
``In the marketplace of ideas, few questions are more deserving of
free-speech protection than whether regulations affecting health
and welfare are sound public policy. ... To hold that physicians
are barred from communicating to patients sincere medical judgments
would disable patients from understanding their own situations well
enough to participate in the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge permanently enjoined the government from revoking a
doctor's DEA registration ``merely because the doctor recommends
medical marijuana to a patient based on a sincere medical
judgment'' and prohibits the government from initiating any
investigation solely on those grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Will the government appeal? Gretchen Michael, press officer for
the U.S. Department of Justice, would not say. She said that she
can't discuss strategy of ongoing cases.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is narrowly written to protect the doctor-patient
relationship in regard to medical advice _ based upon the rights
guaranteed under the First Amendment. There seems little room to
overturn the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the eight states that have passed medical marijuana
laws fall under the jurisdiction of the U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeals: Alaska, Arizona, California, Hawaii, Nevada, Oregon and
Washington. An appeal from the federal district court in northern
California would go directly to the U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeals _ known to be a liberal court.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling from the federal appeals court that affirms the lower
court would force the government to toe the line in all those
states.
</P>
<P>
   One almost hopes that the Department of Justice decides to
appeal Judge Alsup's well-argued decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
