<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-BOBBY-KNIGHT-C     09-11 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-BOBBY-KNIGHT-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, KNIGHT WAS HIS OWN WORST ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Sept. 12, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``ROEPER!''
</P>
<P>
   It was my first week on the job at a warehouse in an industrial
park in the south suburbs. Financial need had necessitated a break
between my sophomore and junior years in college, and I was
thrilled when a buddy hooked me up with a full-time gig that paid
$6.50 an hour, plus overtime.
</P>
<P>
   My job was to roam the cavernous warehouse on foot or driving a
forklift, plucking various machine parts and supplies listed on an
order sheet, and then delivering the orders to area steel mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``HEY ROEPER,'' the boss yelled again. I ignored him.
</P>
<P>
   ``ROEPER!'' the boss screamed one more time, but I didn't turn
around until he amended it to: ``RICH!'' Then I hustled right over
and asked what I could do for him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he wanted to know why I had ignored him three times.
I said that after far too many afternoons on football practice
fields with husky, embittered men grabbing my face mask and
screaming ``ROEPER!'' at me, I hated to be addressed by last name.
He looked at me like I was nuts but promised to keep that in mind.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen years later, I was walking through the Sun-Times
newsroom on my first day as a city reporter, and the editor had an
assignment for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir Richard of Dolton!'' he said in his erudite way. ``May I
present to you an assignment which I believe is perfectly tailored
to your muse?''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. What he really hollered out, of course, was:
``ROEPER!''
</P>
<P>
   Since then I've been addressed by last-name-only on dozens of
occasions, as I'm sure you have. Strangers on the street,
colleagues, a jock-type woman I briefly dated _ all have called me
``Roeper,'' sometimes with great affection, but I'm still not a fan
of that pseudo-tough guy greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it comes from somebody younger. I don't want to
be called ``Mr. Roeper'' because it makes me feel like either my
dad or Norman Fell on ``Three's Company,'' but even that is
preferable to a stand-alone ``Roeper.''
</P>
<P>
   So I can see why Bob Knight blanched last Thursday when a
19-year-old student at Indiana University said: ``Hey, what's up,
Knight?''
</P>
<P>
   Knight turns 60 next month. Some smirky dweeb a third his age
has no right calling him ``Knight.'' (I know I just called him
Knight. But that's the accepted journalistic style.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Knight isn't just any 60ish man; he's a famously
short-tempered bully who was on double-secret probation. Given his
situation, Knight should have ignored the smart aleck. He should
have kept walking, but he is a man without grace or restraint _ so
he grabbed the kid by the arm and scolded him. It was a lesson in
manners, Knight claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. Bob Knight has insulted women to their faces. He has made
a joke about rape. He has grabbed, choked, pushed and cursed at
players. He has thrown a chair across a basketball court, deposited
a human being in a trash can and has peppered reporters with
obscenities and verbal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   This man giving a lesson in manners makes about as much sense as
Eminem doing a private concert at a Barney Frank house party. The
kid who charges that Knight hurt him and cursed at him is the
stepson of a former talk show host who has ripped the coach over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or conspiracy? Knight thought it was the latter, as
his press conference last Friday included a session at a blackboard
where Knight outlined the incident like Kevin Costner's Jim
Garrison ridiculing the magic bullet theory in ``JFK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to be an absolute moron, an absolute moron, with
the things that have been laid down on me, to grab a kid in public
and curse at a kid in public,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Because you've been such a restrained genius over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   According to CBS SportsLine, Indiana University President Myles
Brand contacted Knight on Sunday morning and asked Knight if he
wanted to recant anything from the press conference. When Knight
declined to do so, Brand fired him. If it hadn't happened this
time, it would have gone down after the next embarrassment. Or the
one after that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Knight is not a moron. He's a smart man who
consistently makes the mistake of thinking he's smarter, and of
superior moral quality, than everyone else in the room, and that's
the sword he finally fell on. That chair didn't fly across the
court ``Bewitched'' style on its own; that guy didn't jump into the
trash can; his players haven't pushed their throats and jerseys
into Knight's hands.
</P>
<P>
   You can call him Bob, or you can call him Bobby, or you can call
him Mr. Knight or Coach Knight or ``Knight.'' He's a sad man by any
name, and he's the one who slayed his own legacy.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper and the
Movies.'')
</P>
