<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-AMERICANS (San Francisco) _ Once called the
``unassimilable race,'' Japanese Americans are the very symbol of
assimilation _ upwardly mobile, marrying outside their ethnic group
at high rates and dispersing throughout suburban America. By ANNIE
NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   DIABLOS (Kerrville, Texas) _ Gerardo Ureste, a firefighter from
Mexico, has been working here for $9.75 an hour, many more times
what he could earn in his village across the Rio Grande from Texas'
Big Bend National Park. He was among 23 Mexican villagers recruited
in 1990 and trained by the National Park Service to fight fires.
His squad, known as the Diablos, has since expanded to 43 members,
and with hundreds of U.S. blazes the Diablos have seen action this
year in Arizona and Colorado as well as Texas. By ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   FROG (San Francisco) _ The threatened red-legged frog, which is
believed to be the inspiration for Mark Twain's short story ``The
Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County,'' is on the verge of
getting extra protection from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BLUM-LAWSUIT (Los Angeles) _ Richard Blum, a wealthy financier
and husband of U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.), wants $20
million in punitive damages from a retired carpenter who accused
him on an Internet Web site of looting a union pension fund, for
which Blum is the investment adviser. In an unusual claim filed in
U.S. District Court, Blum contends he has been defamed by Horacio
Grana, a disabled retiree who draws a $570-per-month union pension.
By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   EAGLETS (San Francisco) _In the high sandstone desert of
northeastern Arizona, two Hopi men traveled to a sacred ancestral
spot last year in search of nests of golden eagle chicks to be
killed in Hopi rites. But National Park Service managers turned
they away, saying their permit to capture 40 golden eaglets in
three Arizona counties was invalid in national parks. Claiming a
loss of religious freedom, the Hopi tribe complained to Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt, and his department may resolve the issue
this fall. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLD-NAVY (San Francisco) _ When everyone wants to be in vests,
as many did last year, it looks great on Gap Inc.'s bottom line.
But when everyone doesn't, it can get ugly. In recent months, Gap's
sales have tumbled, and its stock has tumbled. Last month's sales
drop at Gap's Old Navy store was especially disturbing since the
chain has been Gap's main growth vehicle and is now responsible for
35 percent of the San Francisco-based retailer's sales of $11.6
billion last year. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-JONES-GAYS (San Francisco) _ Talk about an ironic sight: a
room packed with gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender
journalists, leaping to their feet to applaud an organization not
noted for its sexual radicalism _ Dow Jones &AMP; Co. The firm,
publisher of the conservative Wall Street Journal, will award
domestic partner benefits to its employees regardless of sexual
orientation, the newspaper's managing editor said in a speech to
the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association meeting last
weekend. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOUND-OF-MUSIC (San Francisco) _ Celebrating the 35th
anniversary of its release of ``The Sound of Music,'' 20th Century
Fox is re-issuing a special VHS version of the movie, as well as a
new DVD version. And RCA Records, which has sold 7 million
soundtrack albums, has put together a digitally remastered version,
including a two-CD ``collectors edition,'' with unreleased musical
material, including preludes and interludes. It's the musical that
just won't die. By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOS-FLY (San Francisco) _ Fox Home Entertainment has released
three extraordinary, double-feature DVDs for $35 each. These
selections are especially fitting for Halloween and include ``The
Fly,'' ``Return of the Fly'' and ``The Fly 2.'' They deal with a
scientist who, while working on teleportation experiments,
accidentally merges with one of the tiny insects on a molecular
level. The mishap leaves the man with a head of a fly, and the fly
with the head of a man. By BOB STEPHENS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY (Sydney, Australia) _ The Sydney Olympic Games are just
the thing to whet the appetite of travelers. While the city will
look good when the cameras are rolling for the Olympians, the
sparkle won't stop when the athletes and news media go home. By
JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY-DINING (Sydney, Australia) _ Great places to eat in
Sydney with an eclectic fare. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY-SHOPPING (Sydney, Australia) _ Sydney's neighborhood
bazaars and arcades are wonderful places to shop and explore. By
JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-OLYMPICS-MAGAZINE (San Francisco) _ The U.S. Olympic
Committee, which carefully guards its rights to the words and
symbols associated with the Olympic Games, has a new complaint: an
``Olympics USA'' magazine sold by the publisher of the National
Enquirer, and filled with references to Olympic events, athletes
and medals. The publication violates a federal law granting the
USOC ``the exclusive right to use Olympic terminology and
symbols,'' the committee says in a lawsuit filed here. By BOB
EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOCCER (San Francisco) _ Jerry Smith is used to being
introduced as ``Mr. Brandi Chastain,'' which doesn't bother him
because he knows his wife is not only a world-class soccer player
but also owns the world's most famous sports bra. Smith, however,
deserves a moment or two in the spotlight on his own, heading into
the 2000 Olympics. Two of his Santa Clara University women's soccer
players, Nikki Serlenga and Danielle Slaton, have joined Chastain,
an assistant coach with the Broncos, on the U.S. national team that
will play in Sydney. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
</TEXT>
