<HEADLINE>
GREAT STUFF FOR WORK AND FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Illustrations showing the wireless temperature station,
the pressure washer, the golf pushcart, Motorola's Talkabout, the
Exide Select battery, the Hypersaucer, the Old Car Hobby book and
the fence watering system are available on Newscom or by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By CLIFF GROMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From home improvement to outdoor sports, automotive to
electronics, here's the newest gear you'll want to own.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S FEATURED PRODUCT
</P>
<P>
   HOT 'N' COLD
</P>
<P>
   What's the temperature outside? This wireless temperature
station uses remote sensors to transmit the temperature to the
indoor display unit from as many as five different locations. The
sensors can be placed up to 80 feet away and will even transmit
through walls. Sensors with probes are available for pool and
garden-soil temperatures. The display also gives you the time and
indoor temperature. The unit stores the minimum and maximum
temperatures together with the time the reading was taken.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless weather station with one sensor (No. 303536) costs
$39.95 plus $5.95 shipping and handling. Each additional sensor
(No. 303538) costs $19.95 and each additional sensor with probe
(No. 303537) costs $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   To order call 800-223-3073. Specify Department Code PM901.
</P>
<P>
   CLEANUP TIME
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman's multitank pressure washers now have Honda engines
and a side-mounted hose reel. The hose reel makes it easier to work
with the machine, since the 25-foot hose can be quickly and neatly
coiled. The engines have overhead valves and an overhead cam. Honda
says the design is cool running, quiet and durable. Several models
are available. The 5.5-horsepower model produces an adjustable
spray at 2400 psi. It has four dispenser tanks, three of which hold
different cleaners. The fourth tank holds water for rinsing. Turn
the dial on the machine's side to whichever tank you want. The
machine costs $550 at Sears. Contact Sears, Department 703, 3333
Beverly Rd., BC 112B-A, Hoffman Estates, IL 60179; 800-377-7414.
</P>
<P>
   PUSH CART
</P>
<P>
   Tired of pulling your clubs on the links? Try pushing them. The
three-wheel Speed Cart is the first collapsible golf push cart, and
it eliminates shoulder pressure caused by pull carts. Features
include off-road tires for easy maneuverability and straight
tracking. It quickly folds to fit in your trunk and weighs only 14
pounds, thanks to an aircraft-aluminum frame. The ergonomic handle
decreases muscle strain, giving you more muscles to strain with
your swing. The cart includes a drink holder. You'll find Speed
Cart at golf shops for $199. Contact Sun Mountain, 301 N. First
St., Missoula, MT 59802; 800-227-9224.
</P>
<P>
   TALK BOTH WAYS
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's new Talkabout T900 personal interactive communicator
offers low-cost two-way wireless messaging capabilities for those
of you who need information in the palm of your hand. Along with
the ability to send and receive text messages and e-mail, you can
also request up-to-date information from the World Wide Web. A
small, but full, QWERTY keyboard lets you send your text messages
fairly easily, while a built-in address book can store up to 250
phone numbers, e-mail addresses, and pager and mobile numbers. For
privacy junkies, there's a Private-Time feature that automatically
turns off all alerts during preselected times. Retails for under
$200. Visit the Motorola Web site at www.motorola.com.
</P>
<P>
   FEELING CRANKY
</P>
<P>
   More NASCAR Winston Cup teams race with Exide's NASCAR Select
Battery than any other battery. Built tougher than conventional
batteries with 28 percent thicker grids and added plate strength,
the battery is designed to withstand vibration and high underhood
temperatures while providing more reliable starts and rebounding
from more discharges. The battery comes with a two-year free
replacement and an 84-month warranty. Prices start at $69 at auto
parts and mass-merchandiser outlets. Contact Exide Corp. at
800-START-IT; www.exideworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   SMOOTH SAILING
</P>
<P>
   Fear of sailing? Relax. Hypersaucer makes the sport easy and
intuitive to learn. The solid polystyrene twin-hull craft is
exceptionally stable and maneuverable, and assembles in under 30
seconds. Hypersaucer uses a foot-activated rudder, seats two and
can sail backward as well as forward _ just the ticket for parallel
parking in tight docking spots. And there's no boom to come about
and whack your head. The craft costs $2500 from Future Beach Corp.,
340 Marie Curie, Vaudreull-Dorion, Quebec, Canada J7V 5V5;
800-357-7837; www.futurebeach.com.
</P>
<P>
   CAR FARE
</P>
<P>
   Remember when cars were cars and had fenders so solid that you
bruised your knuckles when you rapped on them? If you'd like to
relive those halcyon days of chrome bumpers and rumble seats, ''How
To Get Started In The Old Car Hobby,'' a 32-page booklet from
Hemmings Motor News, can, well, get you started. Covering
everything from choosing the right car to researching your
potential purchase to the ins and outs of restoration, the book
gives you the basics of car collecting. The book costs $3 from
Hemmings Motor News, P.O. Box 100, Bennington, VT 05201;
800-227-4373.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE APPEAL
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like a faster Internet connection with an external
modem, try 3Com's new HomeConnect Cable Modem External. Just a
two-way-over-cable modem, the HomeConnect has capabilities of up to
10 megabites per second (Mbps) downstream throughput and up to
3Mbps upstream. Interoperability is guaranteed and it also includes
built-in security and protocol filtering to protect the privacy of
your data. The standard 10BASE-T Ethernet interface makes the
HomeConnect compatible with almost any network-ready computer.
Prices vary. Contact 3Com, 5400 Bayfront Plaza, P.O. Box 58145,
Santa Clara, CA 95052; 800-638-3266.
</P>
<P>
   RAINMAN
</P>
<P>
   Storms and lightning strikes are real threats to everyone from
pilots to boaters to hikers. The handheld Thunderbolt Storm
Detector senses air-to-ground lightning strikes to give 100 percent
accurate storm detection. The LCD readout shows estimates of storm
speed, storm range and intensity level from a range of 60 miles.
The 14.5-ounce unit detects squall lines and severe cells and is
powered by a 9-volt battery or the included 120-volt AC adapter.
The cost is $399 from Speedtech Instruments, 10413 Deerfoot Dr.,
Great Falls, VA 22066; 800-760-0004; www.speedtech.com.
</P>
<P>
   WATER THE PLANTS, NOT THE FENCE
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to water plants around a fence because often the
fence gets more water than the plants do. This kit may offer a
solution. It consists of 50 feet of flexible plastic hose, a garden
hose connector, seven spray heads, a puncturing tool and goof plugs
(in case you puncture the hose in the wrong place or if you want to
change the location of a spray head). The spray heads are
adjustable, so you can put the water just where it needs to go.
It's a well-designed and inexpensive watering system. It costs
$23.95 postpaid from Lee Valley Tools Ltd., 12 E. River St.,
Ogdensburg, NY 13669.
</P>
