<SLUG> BC-PICKUP-AND-SUV-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK FOR NEW 2001 PICKUP AND SUV 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Illustrations showing the Nissan Frontier pickup and the
Hyundai Santa Fe SUV available on Newscom or by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By JIM DUNNE AND BEN STEWART 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   2001 NISSAN FRONTIER
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a year ago Nissan restyled its compact pickup
truck, Frontier. New styling, new cabin, and a new four-door cab
were among the highlights of the revamped 2000 model. With those
changes, the popularity of Frontier rose dramatically. Sales zoomed
50 percent. And to many, it seemed that Frontier's new styling was
set for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But the folks at Nissan weren't satisfied. They wanted more, and
in a hurry. So now we have a new Frontier for 2001, a four-door
pickup with a new, more aggressive appearance from the cowl forward
and a powerful supercharged V6 engine to back up that in-your-face
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the truck face that'll get your attention first,
starting with the assertive shape of the front end. Hood, fascia,
grille, fenders, headlamps and foglamps have all been changed. The
aggressive image is carried to the rear with the oversize lips on
the rear fenders and a new, more sculptured shape for the tailgate.
Not everything has changed, however. The cab and cargo box have
been taken directly from the 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   For the less demanding drivers, Frontier offers a tame
143-horsepower 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine and a 3.3-liter
naturally aspirated V6 as lesser-cost choices. Four-wheel drive is
an extra-cost option with both V6s, but is not available with the
four-cylinder. And that's just the beginning of the mix-and-match
menu of the Frontier's order sheet. You have the choice of models,
base XE, upscale SE, the SC (supercharged) and the Desert Runner.
All are available with two- and four-wheel drive except the Desert
Runner, which is 2-wheel-drive only. Listed under cab choices are
Regular, King and four-door Crew Cab. The length of each affects
the length of the cargo box _ 56.3 inches with the Crew Cab, 77.4
inches with the Regular and 74.6 inches for the King Cab.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the 2001 models will be much in line with the '00
models, except for the supercharged option, which adds about an
extra $1500.
</P>
<P>
   2001 HYUNDAI SANTA FE
</P>
<P>
   What the market needs is another SUV. Well, maybe not, but
Hyundai and its dealers felt that they needed one. So the Korean
maker has jumped into the already crowded pool with its own
car-based compact sport utility, the Santa Fe. And to help it stand
out, the folks at Hyundai sent the Santa Fe into the world with its
own, distinctive styling.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Sonata midsize car platform, Hyundai's new Santa Fe
sport utility was designed in California, and is the Korean
manufacturer's first foray into SUVdom in this country. Besides its
rather unusual look, Santa Fe offers an optional V6. And, since it
is a Hyundai, it's priced in the low 20s _ fully optioned. There it
will compete with the smaller four-cylinder Honda CR-V and Toyota
RAV4, as well as the new Ford Escape and Mazda Tribute.
Dimensionally, the Santa Fe is closer to the Escape and Tribute
with a 103.1-inch wheelbase, an overall length of 177.2 inch and an
overall width of 71.7 inches.
</P>
<P>
   A 150-horsepower 2.4-liter DOHC four-cylinder engine powers the
base models with either a five-speed manual or four-speed
automatic. The optional 185-horsepower 2.7-liter dual overhead cam
aluminum V6 is coupled solely to Hyundai's Shiftronic four-speed
auto with manual override shifting. The Santa Fe is available with
either front- or all-wheel drive, the latter providing traction
through a viscous-coupled transfer case without low range.
</P>
<P>
   Though not the hot setup for serious boulder hopping, the 60/40
torque split of the all-wheel-drive system will get you down the
rutted dirt road or up to the ski lodge _ more agility than 99.9
percent of the populace needs. Opting for the front-wheel-drive V6
model not only saves some green and some 400 pounds of weight, but
also provides noticeably quicker acceleration, lighter-effort
steering and more nimble handling.
</P>
<P>
   Though car-based, the all-wheel-drive Santa Fe drives like a
real SUV. Command-style seating and a Weight Watchers-like
3700-pound bulk combined with the relatively slow and heavy
steering make drivers think they're in a truck. But the soft
independent MacPherson struts up front and multilink rear
suspension provide a close-to-carlike ride when the dirt is covered
with macadam.
</P>
<P>
   When pushed through corners, the Santa Fe remains fairly neutral
with the front tires losing adhesion before the suspension gets too
unsettled, resulting in predictable understeer. Aside from the
SUVesque seating and steering wheel position, the Santa Fe is as
comfy as many cars. This is especially true in the rear where a
raked seatback and plentiful legroom make the Santa Fe legitimate
transport for four sufficiently plump passengers. And all models
get a 60/40-split rear seat that, when folded, can hold 78 cubic
feet of mountain bikes, camping gear or plain old groceries. Santa
Fe offers standard air conditioning, power windows, CD player and
16-inch wheels. Rear disc brakes come on GLS and uplevel LX models.
Options include leather seating and four-wheel, four-channel
antilock braking system.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
