<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     09-11 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ''separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A photo of a scientist and a plasma engine, a photo of
the DeepWorker 2000, a photo of a man shoveling olives, photos of
radioactive debris covered and uncovered, a photo of a woman with a
space mirror, and a photo of ceiling decor are available on Newscom
or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKET RECOVERY SUBMERSIBLE
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the risky task of recovering a space shuttle
booster from the Atlantic Ocean has been done with the aid of a
mini-submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the job is done by divers, who must insert a car-size
plug into the spent rockets that parachute into the Atlantic about
140 miles off the Florida coast, after every launch. They are
brought to shore, refurbished and reused.
</P>
<P>
   The DeepWorker 2000, built by Nuytco Research of North
Vancouver, British Columbia, fits the plug in half the time, and
reduces risk to divers. NASA will conduct more tests before using
the sub on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   PLASMA SATELLITE THRUSTERS
</P>
<P>
   France will equip the Stentor satellite it launches in 2001 with
four plasma engines.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny engines, which make orbital corrections, use
electricity to create jets of plasma, making them lighter than
chemical rockets. Two engines will be made by Fakel, a Russian
company, two by Snecma of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this launch, more companies will start to use plasma
engines to reduce mass and lengthen satellite lifetimes,'' predicts
a Snecma spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRICITY FROM OLIVES
</P>
<P>
   Electric power companies in Spain are dipping into olive oil for
fuel. A plant in the southern city of Benameji is burning crushed
olive pulp and skins to produce 12 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the world's olive oil comes from Spain. With that
comes the sticky problem of getting rid of more than 5 million tons
of waste. For centuries, Spanish farmers have been burning dried
olive pulp to warm their houses. By using the same principle on an
industrial scale, engineers have found a way to turn the
environmental concern posed by agricultural waste into a relatively
cheap fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year project has been so successful that Spain's
biggest utility company is now ready to begin construction on two
16-megawatt plants. Spain's annual olive harvest could fuel eight
plants.
</P>
<P>
   FOAM SEALS CHERNOBYL RADIATION
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years, Chernobyl Unit 4, the site of the world's worst
nuclear accident, continues to stress the ability of cleanup crews.
One difficulty is stabilizing odd-shaped debris piles in
hard-to-reach areas. A recent successful test should make this task
easier. Workers applied a radiation-resistant material known as
Ekor over a fuel-containing mass that had collected underneath the
reactor.
</P>
<P>
   The foam is said to withstand intense radiation fields, without
loss of its physical properties. It differs from most other
containment coatings in that it does not itself become radioactive,
says its supplier, Eurotech of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that Ekor will provide the first practical
solution for safe, long-term containment of radioactive waste and
debris, not just at Chernobyl, but at nuclear facilities around the
world,'' says Eurotech president Don Hahnfeldt.
</P>
<P>
   SELF-FABRICATING SPACE MIRROR
</P>
<P>
   Glass won't cut it when it comes to making mirrors for future
space telescopes. Glass is heavy and grinding it costs too much
money.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Sandia National Laboratories in Albuquerque,
N.M., and the University of Kentucky say the solution could be to
switch to smart materials.
</P>
<P>
   Made of thin, lightweight films of piezoelectric material, their
shape changes in response to the flow of electric current. Mirrors
would fold for flight, unraveling in space, then be smoothed out
with electron guns built into the telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Smart mirrors could be standard on space telescopes by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   A CEILING WORTH LOOKING AT
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to spend hours flat on your back to decorate the
ceiling. The marriage of computers and plastic has created a new
way to pretty up cracked or stained ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Send a photo or drawing to the Newmat Web site (www.
cattoire-rp.fr). In two weeks, the company will ship you an
enlarged image printed on a PVC sheet. Corner fittings stretch the
material, forming a ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ULTRASOUND HELPS BRAIN DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   Precisely placed bursts of ultrasound could make it possible for
drugs to cross the protective barricade that obstructs the passage
of material between blood and brain tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The blood-brain barrier consists of specialized cells that line
the capillaries within the brain. At a recent meeting of the
Acoustical Society of America held in Atlanta, University of
Washington researchers described a hairnet covered with transducers
that would apply high-frequency sound to any portion of the brain.
According to lead researcher Pierre Mouran, the sound disrupts the
barrier, allowing drugs to pass.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea needs further development, it may lay the
groundwork for at last providing a safe and effective way to
deliver medicine to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
