<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-BUSH,2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS' MISS ON MEDICAID SCRUTINIZED &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ As the presidential campaigns continue to fight over
Texas' record of providing health care to the poor, Democrats and
health-care advocates here say Gov. George W. Bush missed a chance
in the mid-1990s to expand medical coverage to more than a half
million low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush administration blames the failure on the federal
government and, by implication, Bush's Democratic opponent, Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But a Democratic legislator and several health-care advocates
and government-policy experts said foot-dragging by the governor's
office was at least partly responsible for the state's failure to
broaden its Medicaid program a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The critics include both Democrats and Republicans, but, mindful
of Bush's power either as the next president or as a governor with
two more years in office, most didn't want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the debate is a health-care initiative drafted
by the Legislature in 1995 that failed to win federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Bush's office) did everything they could to keep it
from getting approved in the manner in which the Legislature had
envisioned,'' said a member of then-Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock's staff
who did not want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, a Democrat who died last year, had endorsed Bush for
president and helped him push some of his own measures through the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Medicaid study ordered by Bullock in 1994, several
months before Bush was elected, that led to the health-care
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics also question the Bush administration's belated
decision in the federal approval process to change the state's
original plan and remove adults from the proposed coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal could have made as many as 570,000 poor Texas
children eligible for health coverage two or three years earlier
than the new children's health-insurance program, or CHIP, which
started enrolling applicants in the spring. CHIP was established by
the Legislature in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Left uncovered by Medicaid, children of lower-income parents
often don't get preventive or routine medical care. The result is
that they may not see a doctor until they are seriously ill and
taken to an emergency room _ care that ultimately costs more in tax
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature's 1995 proposal also would have offered Medicaid
coverage, including prescription drugs, to 255,000 of the state's
poorest adults. Then and now, relatively few adults are eligible
for Medicaid coverage in Texas. Those who are covered are mainly
welfare recipients or are elderly, blind or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, as authorized by the Legislature and submitted by
Bush to the federal Health Care Financing Administration in August
1995, was a request for a waiver changing eligibility requirements
for Medicaid. It would have eased income requirements to make
Medicaid more widely available.
</P>
<P>
   For most age groups, the previous income cutoff was much lower
then than it is now. The original waiver proposal would have
expanded Medicaid coverage to all children from families with
incomes as high as 133 percent of the federal poverty level, or
$20,748 a year for a family of four in 1995. The adult portion of
the proposal would have covered individuals earning $3,360 a year
or less.
</P>
<P>
   The HCFA never rejected the waiver outright. But Texas let its
application die two years later after the federal agency demanded
that Texas provide two sources of health-care providers for new
Medicaid recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Texas proposed only one provider network through county hospital
districts. The districts also would have provided the state's share
of matching funds through their local tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McKinney, a Bush appointee who then was Texas' health and
human services commissioner, said Texas didn't add private
insurance companies and HMOs as a second provider network because
the hospital districts opposed that alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital districts feared that private HMOs would have taken
the less expensive cases to treat and left local taxpayers holding
the bag for the most costly Medicaid care, other sources said.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, a physician and former state legislator who now is
president of a managed-care company based in Indianapolis, said
Bush aggressively tried to get the waiver approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great deal for Texas,'' McKinney said. ``He was on
this program big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards blamed the federal government for
the failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government's insistence to dictate from Washington
with bureaucrats and mandates instead of letting Texas decide how
best to expand health-care coverage resulted in the people going
without health-care coverage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, who co-sponsored the
1995 law authorizing the waiver proposal, said the Bush
administration didn't try hard enough to negotiate a compromise
with federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want something, you push. If not, you let it
passively go away. They (the Bush administration) didn't push,''
said Coleman, who criticized Bush's budgetary priorities earlier
this summer and has assisted the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another person involved in the waiver process, who didn't want
to be identified, added, ``It was foot-dragging and no concerted
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist with a Republican background who also was familiar
with the waiver application said that if there was foot-dragging,
some legislators were to blame as well. He said that negotiations
with the federal government were affected by a reluctance by the
governor's office and a number of lawmakers to do anything that
could be perceived as expanding welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, 1995 was the `Contract with America' era, when
welfare reform was a big issue,'' he said, asking not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   The same source said Coleman and other legislative sponsors, not
Bush, were the driving force behind the waiver application. ``The
governor was not involved in the details of the legislation that
HCFA objected to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The HCFA first responded to Texas' initial waiver request in
early November 1995, about two months after the waiver application
was filed.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
