<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MEDICAID-BUSH     09-11 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-BUSH,2ND </SLUG>
 TAKE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
AUSTIN: was filed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a letter to McKinney, the HCFA said it had several
``significant'' concerns, including whether the county hospitals'
role as health-care providers would constitute a conflict of
interest because they also would monitor the treatment plans and
set payment rates.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 18, 1995, the HCFA sent a follow-up letter to McKinney,
listing 18 pages of detailed questions for the state to answer
about the proposed Medicaid expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Records indicate the state never answered those questions, at
least not in writing. But almost a year later, Texas submitted a
revised waiver application that removed adults from the expanded
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The state later answered another detailed set of questions from
the HCFA about the revised waiver request. But Texas officials
never satisfactorily addressed the federal agency's requirement
that a second system of providers be established.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said primary-care physicians, outside of an HMO, could
have been recruited by the state to screen the health-care needs of
new Medicaid recipients. He said that arrangement, which already is
used for some Medicaid cases, may have met the HCFA's requirement
for a system of providers outside hospital districts.
</P>
<P>
   But McKinney said that alternative would have been too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman and others who were either directly involved in
negotiations over the waiver or closely monitored them said they
were surprised when the Bush administration removed adults from the
waiver application.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just sort of pulled the rug out from everybody when the
governor came up and said, `We're just doing kids,''' said Lisa
McGiffert, a senior policy analyst for Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   McGiffert said that change probably slowed the application
process because ``any time you change the plan, HCFA has to go back
and look at it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the Bush administration excluded adults from the
revised waiver request believing that the move would make it easier
to win federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   She said the federal government required programs for adults to
be ``budget-neutral.'' In other words, they couldn't cost
additional federal money. The adult proposal in Texas' original
application, Edwards said, didn't meet that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman questioned her explanation because, he said, nine other
states operate similar waiver programs that cover adults.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized Bush over both children's health care and
prescription drugs for the elderly. Last week, the governor
addressed the prescription issue by offering a plan to help pay
Medicare insurance premiums for coverage that also provides drug
benefits for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gore's running mate came to Bush's home turf, making
an appearance in Houston. Sen. Joseph Lieberman said Texas ranks
second to last in the number of children nationwide with health
insurance. ``That says to me that Governor Bush has just not made
children's health coverage and care a priority here in his home
state,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bush was blindsided when U.S. District Judge William
Wayne Justice ruled that Texas had failed to honor an agreement to
provide adequate health care to children eligible for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked the federal government several times for waivers to
make it easier to sign up people. Those waivers were denied,'' Bush
said upon learning of Justice's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said Bush wasn't referring to the 1995 waiver request
but to a later attempt to consolidate and privatize a system for
screening Texas applicants for welfare, Medicaid and other social
services.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized the federal government in 1997 for failing ``to
give us a clear answer for almost a year'' on the &UR;  &LR; screening
proposal. That same year, however, the Legislature killed the plan,
which drew opposition from both Republican and Democratic
lawmakers, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
