<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LONDON, AN AGONIZING DECISION OVER JOINED TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Under his powdered wig, behind his big black glasses,
Lord Justice Alan Ward's weary eyes looked very red.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting behind the grand bench at the Court of Appeal in the
Royal Courts of Justice last week, Ward acknowledged he had not
been getting much sleep lately. He and two other judges must decide
whether to authorize an operation to separate Siamese twins,
knowing that to do so may save the life of one and will certainly
kill the other, while not doing so will guarantee that both
5-week-old girls die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we murder Mary to save Jodie?'' a sleep-deprived Ward
asked, summarizing in one stark, chilling question the harsh choice
facing him, Lord Justice Clive Brooke, and Lord Justice Robert
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   It is a question that torments the judges, who are being asked
to play God for the first time in their long legal careers, and
will no doubt torment many more before this legal, ethical, and
moral quandary is resolved. The night before the hearing was
adjourned last week, Ward was up until 3 a.m., restless and unable
to sleep, he said. Sitting next to Ward in the courtroom, Brooke
nodded in sleepy agreement, saying he had been reading briefs on
the case at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which resumes Wednesday, is unprecedented in English
law. Medical officials said there have been previous cases in which
Siamese twins shared vital organs, forcing doctors to doom one to
save the other. But this case is different because the parents have
adamantly rejected the medical advice. A heart-rending decision
that is normally taken in the privacy of hushed hospital corridors
has been thrust into the august chambers of the Royal Courts of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Medical ethicist George J. Annas of Boston University said the
case is unprecedented not just in England, but anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, this is the first case in which anyone
has tried to force a separation where the parents don't want one,''
said Annas, chairman of BU's health law department. ``Ethically,
the general practice has always been that the parents have a right
to make medical decisions for their kids unless there is evidence
that they are abusing their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Annas said that, from an ethical standpoint, parents and doctors
are on equally solid ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an impossible decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he had to decide, Annas said, he would side with saving
Jodie's life, but quickly added, ``Neither choice is preferable.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 25, a High Court judge, Justice Robert Johnson, made
just that decision, ruling that the twins should be surgically
separated over the objections of the parents, who are described
only as devout Roman Catholics from a country somewhere along the
Mediterranean. Johnson acknowledged that he made his ruling with a
heavy heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Jodie, separation means the expectation of a normal
life,'' he intoned solemnly from the bench. ``For Mary, it means
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents, who came to Britain because the treatment their
daughters needed was unavailable in their own country, appealed
Johnson's ruling. Whatever the three-member appeals court rules,
the case seems destined to end up before the Law Lords in the House
of Lords, the highest court in England and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   The parents could also take the case to the European Court of
Human Rights in Strasbourg, France. But if the case drags on until
Oct. 2, which appears likely, that will not be necessary. On that
day the European Convention on Human Rights becomes enshrined in
English law, allowing the parents to cite the convention before
English courts, and that could lead to a whole new round of legal
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching a decision has been agonizingly slow for the appeals
court judges, who had initially hoped to resolve the case quickly.
Once they asked for additional medical opinions and expert advice,
an already complicated case grew even murkier.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at St. Mary's Hospital in Manchester, where the twins
were born joined at the abdomen Aug. 8, say that because the girls
share a heart and lungs, neither will survive longer than three to
six months if they remain attached. If the twins are separated, the
doctors believe that Jodie, whose body contains the heart and
lungs, will survive and have a normal life span. Separation,
however, will mean instantaneous death for Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The judges sought a second medical opinion from doctors at Great
Ormond Street Hospital in London, who agreed with the Manchester
team.
</P>
<P>
   But while there appears to be a consensus on the medical
prognosis, there is nothing approaching a legal and moral consensus
among the myriad lawyers representing the twins, the parents, the
doctors, and the British government.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read to the court by their lawyer, Simon Taylor,
the parents said they want God, not doctors, to decide how long
their daughters live.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot kill one of our daughters to allow the other to
survive,'' they wrote. ``We believe nature should take its course.
If it's God's will that both of our children should not survive,
then so be it. It's not something we believe we have the right to
interfere with.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that in their homeland, his clients live four hours
from the nearest hospital, and that even if Jodie survives the
hardship on the family will be extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have been at pains to keep secret the identities not
just of the parents and children _ Jodie and Mary are pseudonyms
adopted by the court _ but of medical personnel, too. St. Mary's
has received many calls, some of them threatening, from people
opposed to the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The parents have powerful allies, including the leader of the
Catholic Church in Britain, Archbishop Cormac Murphy-O'Connor. The
archbishop said a legal ruling authorizing the killing of one child
to save the other would set a dangerous, Orwellian precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents in this case have made clear that they love both
their children equally and cannot consent to one of them being
killed to help the other. I believe this moral instinct is right,''
the archbishop said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when Taylor suggested it would be illegal for the
court to authorize the killing of Mary, Lord Justice Ward showed
his frustration at being forced into the role of a King Solomon who
might have to do more than threaten to slice a baby in half. The
judge agreed with Taylor that, legally, it would be a crime for
surgeons to use a scalpel to separate the twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment the knife goes into that united body,'' the judge
said, ``it touches the body of unhappy little Mary. It is in that
second an assault. . . . You cannot pretend that is not actively
engaged in assaulting her integrity. For what justification? None
of hers.''
</P>
<P>
   But, underscoring the legal Catch-22 they face, the judges mused
that one could argue that Mary is assaulting Jodie, slowly killing
her by relying on and weakening her organs.
</P>
<P>
   While the judges appear determined to keep the arguments secular
and away from the realm of the spiritual, Ward found himself
pondering the religious dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not God's will that this baby should live because it
was not born with the capacity to live,'' he said of Mary. ``Nobody
in their right mind would hook this child on to a life support
system, given the utter deformity of her heart and lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Parker, the lawyer appointed to represent Jodie, said she
has a 95 percent chance of surviving if the operation is carried
out soon. She said if doctors wait until Mary dies while attached
to Jodie, Jodie's chances of surviving the operation will be less
than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary's lawyer, David Harris, argued that Mary is entitled to
full protection under the law. He said it would be illegal to
purposely kill her, even if the intention was to prolong Jodie's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Parker argued that Mary's rights are irrelevant because she
cannot live without the organs in Jodie's body. That argument,
suggesting that Mary was never able to live on her own, seemed to
find some intellectual sympathy with Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is kicking,'' he said of Mary. ``Whether she is alive and
kicking, I don't yet know.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke agreed that Mary's legal status as a viable human being
was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this creature in the eyes of the law?'' Brooke asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
