</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (i and s coding)  
 AUSTRALIA HOPING OLYMPIC EXPOSURE CLARIFIES ITS IMAGE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ NBC president Dick Ebersol had a sly warning: The
Olympics are prom night for Australia, and the prettiest girl in
school has a blemish big enough to compete with her corsage.
</P>
<P>
   What Ebersol called a ``pimple'' was a web of power lines
criss-crossing Olympic Park at Homebush Bay, obscuring his dream of
a ``beauty shot'' of central Sydney 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still beautiful, but she would be even more beautiful
without it,'' Ebersol said, playing on a weakness of
image-conscious Australians.
</P>
<P>
   And so, displaying an eager-to-please Aussie nature as well as a
national fear of being exposed as imposters, government officials
spent $25 million to demolish 47 huge electric towers, and to bury
the lines they carried. Cynics said it was a good thing Ebersol
hadn't asked to relocate the Sydney Opera House, which remains
stubbornly just outside camera range.
</P>
<P>
   When the 2000 Summer Olympics open on Friday, Australia will
command the world's attention as never before. And as the power
line story illustrates, it is a country desperate to make a good
impression, to be seen in the best possible light.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it is eager to shed its persistent image as a
pleasant but remote nation, strangely rooted in its penal colony
past, filled with bush-hat-wearing, crocodile-wrestling,
shrimp-barbecuing, Foster's-Lager-drinking yobbos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're all living under gum trees and slaughtering
kangaroos, if they know anything about us at all,'' said Mel
MacPherson of Canberra, a retired transportation worker riding a
Sydney Harbor ferry. Some foreigners, he said, even confuse
Australia with a landlocked European republic. To prove his point,
he nodded toward a beer-bellied man wearing a T-shirt with the
words: ``There are no kangaroos in Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, revealing a curiously Australian habit of self-blame,
McPherson added: ``In fairness, we might be at fault for not trying
to explain ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics, then, offer an unprecedented opportunity for
Australians to explain themselves, or at least to expose the other
six continents to this iconoclastic yet icon-loving island that in
almost every way is far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are the basics: They're called prawns here, not
shrimp. And Foster's isn't ``Australian for beer,'' despite the ad
slogan; the brew commands just 1 percent of the market. As for the
Outback hero Crocodile Dundee, actor Paul Hogan is considered
something of a has-been, the subject of facelift rumors as he films
another sequel south of Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, Australians hope to show the world the smart,
peaceful, prosperous face of a laid-back, ``no-worries'' society,
complete with cocky grin and ready ``G'day.'' It is a heartwarming
picture, not wholly inaccurate, but simplified to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australians like to think of themselves, justified or not, as
friendly, outgoing, hospitable, egalitarian, and this is the image
we will be trying to project,'' said Clive Kessler, a sociologist
at the University of New South Wales in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, Australians want the world to be
clear about what they are not. That is, British or American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always think of ourselves in opposition to England, a cold,
nasty country versus our warm, pleasant one,'' Kessler said. As for
America, ``We spend much of our time here at the end of the world
trying not to succumb to the onslaught of Americanism under the
label of globalism.''
</P>
<P>
   That impulse can be seen in countless small ways, such as
letters to the editor complaining that a new restaurant advertises
``carry-out.'' (Aussies prefer ``take-away,'' despite it's being
the British term). It also comes in regular doses from David Dale,
who writes a popular culture column in the Sydney Morning Herald
that seems to be based largely on how much Australians are
knuckling under to American influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past week,'' he wrote triumphantly this year, ``we
have been more different from the Americans than any time this
millennium.'' He then reported breathlessly that an Australian band
had the top-selling album, an Australian television show had the
highest rating, and an Australian movie ``has beaten a bunch of
Hollywood's most commercial products.''
</P>
<P>
   One result of all this effort, of course, is that Yank
(American) visitors here tend to view Australia as vaguely British
_ left-side drivers, fealty to the queen _ while Pommy (British)
visitors hear an American echo, with bronze surfer dudes, a disdain
for social class, and designer coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Distinctions between Australia and the United States seem
particularly important here because of similarities at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Both started as British colonies on the far frontier, blessed
with endless horizons and confronted by often-unwelcoming natives _
aborigines in Australia, Native Americans in North America. In the
1830s, Charles Darwin noticed the similarities and thought
Australia might eventually rival the United States for power and
grandeur, though he later recanted.
</P>
<P>
   The key differences were in both the people and the places.
</P>
<P>
   The American colonies were founded by intense religious freedom
seekers, while Australia was originally home to hooligans, the
refuse of overcrowded British prisons. And while Australia is
roughly the same size as the lower 48 states, it has a barren
heartland, as dry and inhospitable as North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Historians cite those differences to help explain the divergence
of psyches. Americans fell in love with the self-image of the
rugged individual, going it alone to tame a rich, wild land.
Australians embraced an ideal of ``mateship,'' of pulling together
to survive an unforgiving place with egalitarianism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to a golf club, you'll find employees playing
against their bosses, and if the worker is a better player, he'll
win,'' said Kessler, the sociologist. ``And far from being upset by
this, both sides feel rewarded by it because it proves this is
still Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side of that coin is what's known as the ``tall-poppy
syndrome.'' Achievers who poke up their heads risk having them cut
off, figuratively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   But that has been changing. ``You used to be ashamed in this
country about being rich. That has stopped being the case,''
Kessler said. Still, a recent poll found that 70 percent of
Australians cling to old sensibilities, saying they would prefer a
narrower gap between rich and poor to a faster growth rate for
national wealth.
</P>
<P>
   There is also hand-wringing about the end of the mythically
class-free, ``fair-go society.'' The blame _ or credit, as the case
may be _ is often placed on 15 years of overhaul and deregulation,
during which the government has sought to heighten productivity,
bolster the service and high-tech sectors, and make the country a
global player. Successes include low unemployment, low inflation,
and a yearly growth rate of about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some of the complaining is attributed to a
fundamentally Australian belief that no matter how good things
might seem, they're really much worse. It is an impulse that seems
at odds with the easygoing Aussie style, but there is much about
Australia that seems in conflict with itself.
</P>
<P>
   For all the swooning about mateship, for instance, it never
included the native Aborigines, who continue to struggle for a
place in society. And despite an anti-British streak, Australians
voted last year to retain Queen Elizabeth II as the figurehead head
of state for their parliamentary democracy. The majority apparently
considered it the lesser of two evils; as the nation approaches its
first centennial next year, mistrust for native politicians is a
pastime second only to cricket.
</P>
<P>
   Some contradictions might be explained by the fact that in many
ways this is two countries, one urban and relatively rich, the
other rural and relatively poor.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three-quarters of the 19 million Australians are on 10
percent of the land, most on the southeastern coastline from
Adelaide to Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is in the middle of that congregation and is home to
nearly one in five Australians, seemingly all of them talking on
cell phones or in chat rooms. Despite a reputation for insularity,
a recent survey found that more than 36 percent of Australians use
the Internet, a higher rate than the United States and most other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the population is spread throughout the mostly
empty expanse of the vast interior, the bush, which 19th-century
poet Henry Lawson called ``the nurse and tutor of eccentric minds,
the home of the weird, and of much that is different from things in
other lands.'' Few city folks visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bush? Never been,'' said Shana Mills, a waitress at a
restaurant near Sydney's Manly Beach. ``I want to go to the States,
though. I've made friends there on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   For rural and urban Australians alike, a notable part of the
native psyche is devotion to a fairly inexplicable list of national
icons. There is a horse (Phar Lap), a hat and coat (the Akubra and
the Drizabone), a cricket player (Donald Bradman), a car (the
Holden), a boat (the aluminum dinghy), a food (meat pies), a
marsupial (the kangaroo), a macho cartoon pitchman (Chesty Bond),
and a yeast spread (Vegemite), among others.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, it is a nation that still stokes the memory of
the 1915 invasion at Gallipoli, a disastrous bid to knock the
Ottoman Empire, Germany's Turkish ally, out of World War I.
Thousands of Australians died, and the battle remains a defining
moment for a country that was just 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Those pillars of old Australia might be losing their hold,
though, as immigrants come ashore in huge numbers. The proportion
of the population born overseas rose from 10 percent in 1947 to 23
percent in 1998, with notable recent increases coming from Vietnam,
China, and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   One result has been occasional uprisings of racist and
xenophobic sentiment, although most observers consider race
relations cordial and perhaps even exemplary compared with
elsewhere. One exception is the historic mistreatment of
aborigines, who until 1967 weren't even counted in the census _
they were on a par with native fauna.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had his misgivings, Darwin in 1836 offered an
assessment that Australians consider relevant still: ``As a means
of making men outwardly honest, of converting vagabonds, most
useless in one hemisphere, into active citizens of another, and
thus giving birth to a new and splendid country _ a grand centre of
civilization _ it has succeeded to a degree perhaps unparalleled in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the impression Australians hope will remain long after
the Olympics have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everybody to like us,'' said MacPherson, the retired
transport worker. ``The minute someone arrives at the airport, we
ask, `So, what do you think of the place?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he added, when the visitor says it's wonderful, ``The
Aussie isn't quite sure whether to believe him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
