<HEADLINE>
THE `NAKED GUN' TRILOGY ALL DRESSED UP FOR DVD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ON DVD: ``The Naked Gun,'' ``The Naked Gun 2 1/2,'' and
``The Naked Gun 33 1/3'' _ The folks behind ``Airplane'' give the
same zany comic treatment to the cop picture with this trio of
hilarious hits. One of the most interesting elements in the DVD
home-video format is that filmmakers are more likely to tell the
truth about casting and production. When a film is released
theatrically, there's a tendency for the creators to become
pitchmen. They tend to forget that the star who's perfect for the
role was his or her third choice. The true story is much more
likely to come out after most of the major revenue streams are
running dry and the filmmakers need new revelations to reinvigorate
their films.
</P>
<P>
   Director and screenwriter David Zucker, reached in his Los
Angeles office, was forthcoming about the casting in these films.
``We didn't want to hire comedians,'' he said. ``I think the key to
the success of these films is that we were ruthless in cutting
material and we hired all noncomic actors. It was like in
`Airplane,' we wanted Jack Webb for the Robert Stack role and he
turned us down. We wanted Pete Rose for the part played by Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, but he was playing ball at the time we were
shooting.'' Did he always want O. J. Simpson, who plays a strong
supporting role in all three of the ``Naked Gun'' movies? ``Yes,''
he said, without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braveheart'' _ Mel Gibson's Oscar-winning spectacle looks and
sounds terrific on DVD. There isn't as much insightful commentary
as fans of the film might like, but it does make a magnificent
transfer from film to DVD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sound of Music'' _ The 35th anniversary edition of the
movie that made Julie Andrews a film star crackles with a
remastered soundtrack. The Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein
III score fills the Austrian Alps with uplifting anthems about
faith and love. Fans of the Oscar-winning musical will love this
version. Unfortunately, they didn't revise the story. It still
needs a solid shot of scotch-bonnet pepper sauce instead of all the
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: Tuesday: ``Tweety's High Flying Adventure.''
Sept. 19: ``A Map of the World'' (DVD), ``Ready to Rumble'' (DVD),
``Tales of the Kama Sutra'' (DVD). Sept. 26: ``Molokai,'' ``Final
Destination,'' ``Black and White'' (DVD). Oct. 24: ``American
Beauty'' (DVD), ``The Patriot'' (DVD), ``U-571'' (DVD). Oct. 31:
``Touch of Evil'' (DVD). Nov. 7: ``The Bridge on the River Kwai''
(DVD).
</P>
</TEXT>
