<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-COLLEGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES SEEK TO REIN IN NETWORK-CLOGGING NAPSTER ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The routine at Amherst College generally went this way: Students
like Chris Fargis woke up, logged on to Napster.com's Internet
library of recorded music, entered a search for a few tunes _ a
little indie rock, a little hip-hop _ and then went off to class.
</P>
<P>
   The Napster activity by Fargis and dozens of other students
burned up the campus computer system through the day, often taking
a stunning 50 percent of Amherst's network capabilities. Some
professors, like biologist Stephen George, became so frustrated
that they gave up using the Internet in class, or started coming in
at 7 a.m. to do research online.
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon, meanwhile, students were itching for their Napster
finds. ``It's just really nice to leave for class and come back and
have them there,'' said Fargis, a senior, of the songs he
automatically received on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   But no more. Starting this fall, Amherst is blocking all access
to the well-known Napster site. Smith and Hampshire colleges are
doing the same, citing rampant overuse of the popular, and
controversial, site. Other schools are trying less direct, and more
unusual, solutions: Mount Holyoke College, for one, has begun
monitoring Internet usage of each student _ and will question those
who are taking up too much bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   While the courts have become the chief battleground over the
legality of Napster _ which accommodates the electronic copying and
distribution of copyright music _ a secondary skirmish is taking
place exactly where the controversial software was invented and
thrived: college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawyers for recording artists asked Harvard, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and nine other schools to
join in a nationwide campus ban on Napster.
</P>
<P>
   With countless students downloading music from the Internet site
for free, arguably violating copyrights, colleges have ``a moral,
ethical, and legal obligation'' to block access, according to a
letter the lawyers sent the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is already facing a federal appeals court hearing,
expected in October, over whether its sampling service is
infringing on the rights of artists and record companies. The
outcome could well determine how involved colleges need to become
in the debate _ and for now, they want to avoid it as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and MIT officials said Friday that they would consider
the request to block Napster, but added that they were reluctant to
filter the Internet on campus.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent national survey of 50 colleges, about one-third
reported that they blocked access to Napster's site. For schools
that ban, questions about academic freedom and the free use of the
Internet have inevitably surfaced. Yet, those issues have
ultimately been sidestepped in most cases, as administrators
imposed bans as a way to relieve computing systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't taken a stand on the legal issues,'' said Philip
Fitz, Amherst's director of information technology. ``If the courts
are having trouble deciding that, it doesn't seem we would be able
to make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The costs Napster posed to Amherst exceeded the $25,000 in
estimated bandwidth use, Fitz said. Students paying tuition were
losing out because they couldn't zip around the Web quickly for
research projects or other uses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Smith College, complaints among professors began to mount as
well. ``We weren't thrilled about blocking, but there was great
concern that academic scholarship was being interrupted because of
the congestion,'' said Herbert Nickles, who oversees information
technology at Smith. ``It would take an hour to download the data,
rather than five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mount Holyoke officials also grew irritated about Napster's use
this year, but were loath to adopt a ban. Instead, they are handing
out a memo to students this month saying that activity on the site
``must be curtailed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a computer security official will analyze
online activity _ though not the content of it _ for each student.
Those found using much more bandwidth than others, in turn, will
get a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they work with us, there's not a big deal,'' said Susan
Perry, the college's director of library, information, and
technology services. ``And if they don't, we'll just cut them off
the network.''
</P>
<P>
   But some computer specialists at other colleges took a dim view
of both strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you block Napster, you'll just encourage it to take on a
different form that's harder to block,'' said Scott Conti, the
network operations manager at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst. ``And at public institutions, there's a whole freedom of
speech issue. We don't want to be inspecting traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Conti, among others, predicted that Web-savvy students would
hack their way through colleges' blocking technology and back into
Napster. It was a former Northeastern University student, Shawn
Fanning, who wrote the Napster program; some other undergraduates
are already trading safecracker tips in Internet chat rooms,
recommending using the off-campus computers of friends as Web
portals with which to access Napster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't found a way around the block yet, but I wouldn't be
surprised if there was a hack out there,'' said Fargis, who buys
music regularly but uses Napster to find live, unreleased, or
especially rare tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Chau, another Amherst senior, said she thinks the ban
will hurt Napster because many won't inconvenience themselves with
trying to break onto the site. The average student, she said, uses
Napster to procrastinate _ searching for songs to pump them up as
their homework sits on another screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole reason people used Napster was because it was
easy,'' Chau said. ``Everyone felt kind of guilty about using it. .
. . But now, they're annoyed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
