<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Sept. 14, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boot-scooting out of the Sundance-alternative Slamdance Film
Festival, ``Dill Scallion'' makes its TV debut on VH1 at 8. It's a
sort of mock ``Behind the Music'' about small-town bus driver Dill
Scallion, who becomes a country music star almost by accident and
whose injured foot gives rise to a dance phenomenon. (Billy Ray
Cyrus, call your agent.) Billy Burke stars in the title role;
Lauren Graham, Kathy Griffin and Henry Winkler co-star, and there
are appearances by Jason Priestley, Robert Wagner, Peter Berg,
Willie Nelson, LeAnn Rimes and Travis Tritt. Sheryl Crow provided
original music.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer Olympics, local cable provider channels, 6:30 p.m.: U.S.
Women's Soccer. The opening ceremony isn't until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: G is for the Gruesome ``challenges''
inflicted on the housemates by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sole Survivor,'' Fox at 8: Part two. Billy Zane stars in this
adaptation of a Dean Koontz thriller, as a reporter who has lost
his wife and child in a plane crash. But then he meets a woman who
was on the plane, even though there were supposedly no survivors.
Gloria Reuben of ``ER'' co-stars. Conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends,'' NBC at 8: Chandler's shopping for rings, and Bruce
Willis is still hanging around as Ross' girlfriend's father _ and
Rachel's new love interest. Life is so complicated. Rerun.
</P>
