<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-COLTER-BOS &LR;      09-11 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN, A SPECIAL DOG, AND HOW THEY THRIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
COLTER 
By Rick Bass. Houghton Mifflin. 160 pp. $22. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in ``Colter,'' Rick Bass's heartfelt book about his German
shorthaired pointer, Colter mysteriously disappears one winter
evening. Bass feels grief closing in on him like the night itself,
having lost a dog that has been at his side for years, bird hunting
on the vast Montana prairie east of the Continental Divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dog like Colter sharpens your joy of all the seasons, and
for a while, sometimes a long while, such a dog seems capable, by
himself alone, of holding time in place _ of pinning it, and
holding it taut,'' Bass writes, drawing to a close his 16th book in
nearly as many years. ``And then when he is gone, it is as if the
world is taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Colter is indeed gone. Bass finds his remains about a year later
on a logging road near his Yaak Valley home with a bullet hole
through his spine. Bass buries him near his writing cabin, ``in
that sunken, blissful spot where he had napped, always waiting for
the next hunt.'' And to this day, ``even after burying his bones, I
have the feeling, every day, that I'm going to see him again _ am
going to hunt with him again, at least once more.''
</P>
<P>
   A poignant end to an eloquent book, one oriented about the
relationship between a man and his dog, through which Bass explores
such deeper themes as the transformation of the American West, the
imperative of environmentalism, the wonders of hunting, even man's
fate. Much is set against Montana's glorious grasslands and
mountains in autumn, making for the most impressive work from Bass
in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun's slant, early into September, still had enough bite
to burn off frost quickly the next day,'' Bass writes at the start
of an especially difficult hunt, occurring one month after one of
his other dogs, Ann, was accidentally killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove out into the country, found the vast ranch, parked on
the side of the road, and I waited for a few minutes, savoring the
blue sky, and freedom, and the health and vigor of my dog, and the
scent of sage. A distant line of willows snaked through the distant
prairie, beyond which lay the foothills. Colter was raring to go,
but I wanted to sit a moment longer, soaking in the autumn, and
this new place, new pursuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass should thank Colter for this book. Hunting with a dog, he
writes, takes one ``into new country, new territory: some
unexplored land, still in this life, but so sensate and crisp as to
seem beyond this life; everything is felt more sharply, more
intimately, and at a smoother, more supple pace. Even when things
are happening fast in the field there is a slowed down, or
timeless, quality.''
</P>
<P>
   That quality is just what Bass, who turned 40 while writing
``Colter,'' has needed. His relentless productivity, and aching
ambivalence over art versus activism, have taken their toll on his
recent work. Besides his books, he has written seemingly countless
pieces for publications as diverse as The Paris Review and Sports
Afield. After dazzling early work, much of what followed was
disappointing, including ``The Book of Yaak'' (1996), ``The New
Wolves'' (1999), and his first novel, ``Where the Sea Used to Be''
(1998).
</P>
<P>
   But with ``Colter,'' Bass seems to have indeed slowed down,
taking the time to draw upon his considerable talent, especially in
describing the natural landscape and its influence on those who
live on and with it. In so doing, he has crafted a narrative as
artful as it is activist, a weave he has sought as furiously as
Colter once stalked grouse.
</P>
<P>
   Through anecdotal chapters, Bass recalls when he got Colter as a
pup, when he sent him to a friend in Texas to be trained as a
pointer, how years earlier he had found two of his other dogs,
Homer and Ann, as pups on a Mississippi road, how as a child he had
an unwavering affinity with the natural world, especially turtles
and, oddly, dirt. There are early moments when Bass has not yet
established Colter as a character and his exultation over the dog
seems excessive. ``Oh, the wretched excess of the heart!'' he
writes, when missing Colter in Texas. At one point, Bass actually
apologizes for this excess.
</P>
<P>
   But as time passes and the hunts begin, Colter comes alive,
taking on qualities that are endearing, revealing as much about
Bass as about the dog because of the oneness between them that Bass
stresses throughout the book. Bass makes his societal critiques _
about true hunters versus road hunters, the loss of wilderness, the
false dichotomy between environmentalists and hunters, among
others. But he never leaves the story of man and dog, enabling him
to offer such commentary without artistic sacrifice; indeed,
enhancing that commentary by having it emanate from the story,
rather than become the story.
</P>
<P>
   Bass grieves. ``Colter was probably the greatest pointer who
ever ran,'' he writes. ``There will always be a hollow spot in me,
a burnt circle in the bottom of my stomach, whenever I think of
him: as if I am carrying a bucket of hot, hot ashes in the bottom
of my stomach _ the memory of how he ran, the memory of how he
was.'' But Bass should take heart in this simple, elegant book, one
as clean and clear as the human and natural landscapes it explores,
one that suggests an emerging return to form for an environmental
writer who has been among America's most important.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-VALLEY-BOS &LR;      09-11 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-VALLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORN OF THE CIVIL WAR AND BRED ON A WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
VALLEY OF THE SHADOW 
Two Communities in the American Civil War: The Eve of War 
By Edward L. Ayers and Anne S. Rubin 
Norton, 130 pp., accompanied by CD-ROM, $49.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considering the inexhaustible (if exhausting) stream of books
about the Civil War that appear in a year's time, it is not
surprising that numerous Web sites have sprung up to cover the same
territory. Now, with ``Valley of the Shadow,'' we have a book and
CD-ROM that have grown out of a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The valley in question is the ``Great Valley,'' lying between
the Allegheny Mountains and the Blue Ridge, running roughly
northeast-southwest from Pennsylvania through a corner of Maryland
and into western Virginia and thus down to Georgia _ thus crossing
the Mason-Dixon line, the traditional dividing line between North
and South. It was the scene of some of the major events and some of
the fiercest fighting of the Civil War. Harpers Ferry lies in the
valley, where the Shenandoah meets the Potomac; Stonewall Jackson
campaigned up and down the Shenandoah section of the valley in the
spring of 1862, and Philip Sheridan in 1864; Gettysburg lies some
25 miles east of the Pennsylvania section.
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, two communities in the valley _
Chambersburg, in Franklin County, Pa., and Staunton, in Augusta
County, Va. _ have been the focus of a digital history project at
the University of Virginia headed by historian Edward L. Ayers.
Co-author Anne S. Rubin is project manager of the Valley Project.
</P>
<P>
   The project's Web site, on-line since 1995, has been
well-received. The present package of book and CD-ROM, ``The Eve of
War,'' is to be the first of three covering the impact of the Civil
War on the two communities, which, the authors write, occupied
``strategic locations in the war'' as recruiting posts, hospital
bases, and supply depots.
</P>
<P>
   The package consists of a pleasantly written book (which could
stand as an introduction to the Civil War for the general reader)
and the CD-ROM. The latter contains hundreds of articles from
newspapers in the two communities, excerpts from diaries and
letters, census data, tax records, photographs of sites in the
communities, maps, and even four tunes played in period style by a
regionally based string band.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the assembled material is impressive (though
the reader/user will have to go to an atlas to figure out how far
it is from Chambersburg to Staunton, or from either to Harpers
Ferry, because there is no scale of miles on the map provided in
both the book and on the CD-ROM). But after the initial impression
of documentary riches, the question arises of just how useful all
this material is. Much of it could, of course, have been
incorporated into a traditional book _ and probably will be, in the
book Ayers is reported to be writing. But unless reader/users are
planning books of their own, knowing how many slaves were owned by
a particular Staunton resident _ as opposed to knowing what part
slavery played in the community as a whole, say _ is a superfluous
detail. (And not all that easy to decipher: A random search of the
slaveowning data for one of the leaders of the Confederate infantry
regiment formed in Augusta County turned up somewhat confusing
data.)
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ayers and Rubin write that with the material
assembled on the CD-ROM, ``you can find your own answers to the
questions about the Civil War that have haunted Americans since
1861.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But a bit further on they rephrase that promise,
suggesting that by using the material assembled in the Valley
Project ``you can test the consensus view'' of the causes of the
Civil War ``and accept, reject, or modify it.'' That ``consensus
view,'' as they describe it, ``is that serious conflict between
North and South was bound to occur because the two societies were
organized on different principles, that the North gradually
awakened to the inhumanity of slavery over the course of the war,
and that Abraham Lincoln both embodied and led the moral growth of
the Union.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for ``Valley of the Shadow'' is that the data does
not clearly uphold this consensus view, nor does it entirely
discredit it. It is most likely to leave the would-be historian
confused.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta County, the southern one, ``had been a stronghold of
Unionism'' and was home to some 500 free blacks as well as 4,000
slaves. In the presidential election of 1860, it voted for John
Bell, the candidate of the compromise-seeking Constitutional Union
Party. In Franklin County, the northern one, a leading newspaper
was the southern-leaning Valley Spirit. The county went for Lincoln
in 1860, but John Breckinridge, who carried the solid South, was a
strong second. Franklin County, which sits on the Mason-Dixon line,
is no more a typical northern community than Augusta County is a
typical southern one. And in any case, the matter needs more
interpretation than is given here.
</P>
<P>
   But qualifications aside, there is no question that it is an
enjoyable experience to surf through the data on the CD-ROM,
clicking back and forth between tax records and city street maps _
and then indulge in the ``Daughter of the Stars'' waltz, a
period-sounding piece composed for the Valley Project. And at the
very least, the exercise might inspire a young reader/user into
some archival research of his or her own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
