$ADV15 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Sept. 15, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally!
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of hype, the 2000 Summer Olympics kick off in
Sydney, on NBC at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually they kicked off hours and hours ago, because
depending on where you live, it's, like, breakfast time on Saturday
over there. And that huge tape delay is going to be NBC's big
challenge in getting people to tune in for 441.5 hours of coverage
on NBC, CNBC, MSNBC and any other cable channels the peacock picks
up this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Costas and Katie Couric host tonight's celebration, which
features Australian stars such as ... Olivia Newton-John. (You were
expecting Midnight Oil, maybe?)
</P>
<P>
   Costas has the challenge of hosting the other nights of the
Games, through Oct. 1. He'll have to sell the competition via NBC's
patented storytelling techniques _ when we already know who's won
thanks to every other media outlet and the Internet. NBC has sold
millions and millions of dollars of ads betting they can pull it
off.
</P>
<P>
   But all those issues will fade away tonight, temporarily, with
the grandeur of the parade of nations and the excitement of the
Olympic torch coming into the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you're not an Olympics fan, and you're wondering where
all the new shows are on the other networks, we have some bad news
for you. The start of the fall TV season has been delayed till the
first week of October, so those new shows don't have to compete
with track and field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: The second B is for the boredom from
which we're all suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Line Is It, Anyway?'' marathon, ABC at 8: Four episodes
of the improv comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Blues,'' WB at 8: A night out for Daddy and Zoey. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' CBS at 9: The network has scheduled two weeks of
reruns opposite NBC's ``Olympics.'' The tape delay is only slightly
longer. This was the most-watched summer series since Nielsen has
been keeping the statistic, and CBS is betting you'd rather watch
it again than, say, pole-vaulting when you already know the winner.
It may turn out to be a brilliant strategy, or it may be that we've
all had our fill of the castaways due to their relentless media
appearances since the show's finale on Aug. 23. But in any case,
the rats are paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ''20/20,'' ABC at 10: Part two of Peter Jennings' examination of
the early lives of George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Music Mania 2000,'' Fox at 8: Jacksonville concert features 'N
Sync, 98 Degrees, Sisqo, Jessica Simpson, Mandy Moore, Destiny's
Child and several other people who are not Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie Brown,'' FX at 7:30: Quentin Tarantino's 1997
adaptation of Elmore Leonard's thriller stars Pam Grier, Samuel L.
Jackson and Robert Forster. Grier's the flight attendant who's
tangled up in crime. And check out the supporting cast: Bridget
Fonda, Michael Keaton, Robert DeNiro, Michael Bowen and Chris
Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley Varrick,'' AMC at 8: The late Walter Matthau stars as
a guy who robs a bank and finds out it holds a bunch of Mob money.
This is gonna be tricky. Don Siegel directed the 1973 film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix,'' HBO at 9:30: Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne,
the crazy concept and some wild special effects. And no Olivia
Newton-John!
</P>
<P>
   ``Invisible Man,'' Sci-Fi at 8: Vincent Ventresca stars as the
subject of a government experiment with the Quicksilver gland.
Tonight, the Chinese government tries to steal him. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
Mo'Nique, Coolio and someone named E-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Rock Show,'' HBO at midnight: Spike Lee and D'Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 12:35: Penelope Cruz.
Note time after Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: Juliette
Lewis and Eugene Levy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 1:35: Queen Latifah
and Fastball. Note time after Olympics.
</P>
