<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINING OUR CRAVINGS FOR FATTY FOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Item: Women who watch ``Oprah Winfrey'' are seven times less
likely to crave fattening foods than women who watch other daytime
talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   This amazing factoid comes to us courtesy of DietSmart, an
online nutrition and fitness service (www.dietsmart.com) that
recently conducted a survey of Americans' food cravings in which
562 men and women were interviewed about which emotions,
situations, and types of entertainment make them crave certain
foods.
</P>
<P>
   The survey came about because, according to CEO Tamara Totah,
``we wanted to highlight some of the everyday life situations that
effect people's food cravings so we can help individuals recognize
the way emotions impact unhealthy food and diet choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the doughnuts, please. Which reminds me, the survey also
found that 77 percent of Americans crave doughnuts most between 10
p.m. and midnight. That seems a little odd, even to one who craves
them at every waking moment. But so much about this survey seems
odd.
</P>
<P>
   Grateful as I am to know that women who watch Oprah are less
likely to crave fattening foods than those who watch Montel or
Rikki or Sally, I can't help but wonder about the researchers'
methods. What was their line of questioning? And how do they manage
to find the sort of person who comes up with these responses? It
can't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello. Do you have time to answer a few questions about your
fattening food cravings and how they relate to your entertainment
choices?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. I'm just sitting here watching `Jerry Springer' and
eating a six-pack of Mounds bars.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd also like to know if the women they interviewed were less
likely to crave merely for the duration of Oprah's show? Or is
there something about watching Oprah that made them less likely to
want to pig out all the time?
</P>
<P>
   Could we solve the nation's obesity nightmare if we all sat down
to watch Oprah once a day? Is it possible? It seems too much to
hope, but Oprah is, after all, an amazing cultural force.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the DietSmart survey's other findings are a tad hard to
fathom too. For instance, ``Men who wear briefs were seven times
more likely to crave vegetables than men who wear boxers.''
</P>
<P>
   And this: ``71 percent of Republicans said that their craving
for fattening foods increased the week following the announcement
that Joe Lieberman would be Al Gore's running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Other results are easier to understand, for example, ``84
percent of women surveyed who have children said that they crave
fattening foods.'' (And the other 16 percent were lying.)
</P>
<P>
   And this: ``88 percent of men craved fattening foods when their
in-laws visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly stress is a threat to the best of diet intentions. No
wonder we're a nation with so much to lose.
</P>
<P>
   But what are we to make of the fact that 62 percent of women
said they crave fattening foods after sex, as compared with only 6
percent of men? Maybe it has to be seen in relation to another
finding, that the emotion that most drove men to crave fattening
foods was feeling randy, while for women it was feeling sad.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that in the interest of fitness, women should watch
more Oprah and have less sex, while men should see less of their
in-laws and have more sex. Maybe DietSmart's next survey will be
about diet and divorce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
