<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FALL-CDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSIC AND OLD, FROM DION TO THE BACKSTREET BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you're a troubled soul who swoons to the dark musings of
PJ Harvey or the good-natured type who prefers your ear candy light
as air a la Barenaked Ladies, it's going to be a blockbuster fall
for pop and rock CDs. Hotly anticipated new releases from such
titans as U2 and Madonna will arrive in the coming months, as will
fare for hungry devotees of cult icons Bjork and J Mascis. Major
collections from the archives of Jimi Hendrix and the Beatles will
also be in store racks in time for the giving season. Remember to
include yourself on the list of deserving recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The sweetest music to our ears is news that on Oct. 3 Brit
rockers Radiohead will release ``Kid A,'' their first album since
1997's brilliant ``OK Computer.'' Early word is that the album is
all about atmosphere, losing hooks and choruses in the wake of
dreamy moods and a soaring, prog-rock feel.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities, however, begin immediately. It's been five long
years waiting for the follow-up to Joan Osborne's delicious
``Relish,'' but ``Righteous Love'' will finally arrive Tuesday, a
massive release day that includes teen star Christina Aguilera's
Spanish-language album ``Mi Reflejo'' (featuring new songs and
translated versions of five tracks from last year's eponymous
debut), Barenaked Ladies' ``Maroon,'' Rickie Lee Jones's ``It's
Like This,'' Tom Tom Club's ``The Good, the Bad, and the Funky''
(ex-Talking Heads Chris Frantz and Tina Weymouth's first new album
in eight years), Irish quartet the Corrs's ``In Blue,'' Boyz II
Men's ``Nathan Michael Shawn Wanya,'' Underworld's ``Live,'' and
Emmylou Harris's ``Red Dirt Girl.'' Also in stores Tuesday is ``The
Jimi Hendrix Experience'' _ a four-CD boxed set of 56 rare and
previously unreleased songs packaged (of course) in purple velvet
with an 80-page booklet _ and remastered and repackaged editions of
the late, great Nick Drake's three full-length albums.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna continues mining electronic pop on ``Music,'' her eighth
album of new material, due out Sept. 19. Recorded in London, the
album trains a spotlight on French house/dance pioneer Mirwais
Ahmadzai, who co-wrote 6 of 10 tracks and co-produced the album.
(Madonna is also recording English-language versions of some of the
best-known Brazilian soccer songs for ``The Passion for Football,''
an upcoming movie about the sport.) Also out that week: Icelandic
art-pop goddess Bjork's ``Selma Songs,'' frat-boy-rap-rocker Limp
Bizkit's ``Chocolate Starfish and Hot Dog Flavored Water,'' and
Fastball's ``Harsh Light of Day.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
And that's not all &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Dire Straits frontman Mark Knopfler returns Sept. 26 with
``Sailing to Philadelphia,'' his first album of new solo material
since 1996's ``Golden Heart,'' with guest vocalists James Taylor,
Van Morrison, and members of Squeeze. Also that day: Paul Simon's
``You're the One,'' the bard's first non-world-music-oriented album
since 1983's ``Hearts and Bones,'' and Morphine's ``Bootleg:
Detroit,'' recorded by a fan on March 7, 1994 at St. Andrew's Hall
in the Motor City and edited and mixed under the supervision of the
late Mark Sandman; collectors have been shelling out big time for
promotional-only copies of Sting's ``Brand New Day Tour: Live From
the Universal Amphitheatre,'' which is finally being released
commercially. The soundtrack to ``Girlfight'' features the first
new track from Santana since last year's smash album ``Smooth,''
and ``Bowie at the Beeb,'' a limited edition three-CD set features
live BBC radio show performances. Two discs are culled from shows
taped between 1968 and 1972, and the third is a live album of his
recent performances this past summer.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 3: punk rockers Green Day return with ``Warning.'' Oct. 10:
the Wallflowers finally issue their third CD, ``Breach,'' after a
four-year wait (which reportedly involved a bad case of
sudden-fame-induced writer's block for frontman Jakob Dylan)
following the breakthrough album ``Bringing Down the Horse.'' On
that day, the ever-unpredictable Van Morrison releases ``You Win
Again,'' a collection of duets with Linda Gail Lewis, sister of
Jerry Lee Lewis. They sing rockabilly, blues, and country covers
including three Hank Williams tunes.
</P>
<P>
   South African vocal group Ladysmith Black Mambazo's body of work
is condensed into a 17-track compilation, ``Ladysmith Black
Mambazo: The Warner Brothers Collection,'' with liner notes by Paul
Simon (whose album ``Graceland'' introduced the group to a world of
listeners), out Oct. 17. Also that day, alt-rapper Everlast
releases ``Eat at Whitey's,'' a followup to 1998's triple-platinum
``Whitey Ford Sings the Blues,'' with guest performances from
Santana and N'Dea Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   The following week (Oct. 24) sees the release of British fringe
icon Polly Jean Harvey's sixth album, ``Stories From the City,
Stories From the Sea.'' Word is that the disc merges the punk
aesthetic of her early albums with the melancholy air of her recent
work. Also on Oct. 24: former Dinosaur Jr. frontman and influential
indie hero J. Mascis and his new band the Fog issue ``More Light,''
Southern rappers Outkast release ``Stankonia,'' and
folk/rock/doo-wop legend Dion is immortalized in the three-disc
collection ``Dion: King of the Streets,'' which spans his 40-year
career. The set features liner notes by Dave Marsh, and written
tributes from Bruce Springsteen, Bob Dylan, Lou Reed, Paul Simon,
and Waylon Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   On Halloween, U2 releases its 10th studio album, ``All That You
Can't Leave Behind,'' produced by longtime associates Brian Eno and
Daniel Lanois. In the works for two years, the album reportedly
still plays with technology but also revives the elemental surge of
early U2. Marilyn Manson returns to his Goth roots on an
as-yet-untitled album, newly minted Boston rock stars Godsmack
release ``Awake,'' notorious rap-rockers Insane Clown Posse release
the well-titled double CD ``Bizzar Bazaar,'' and Erykah Badu
releases ``Mama's Gun,'' all on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   November 7: The Dave Matthews Band and Ricky Martin release
studio efforts (no titles for either yet), and Jennifer Lopez
wisely goes for the fast follow-up to ``On the Six'' with
``Passionate Journey.'' The Beatles legacy continues to bloat with
the Nov. 14 release of ``Beatles Ones,'' a 27-track CD containing
all of the band's singles that reached No. 1 in the States or in
the UK. And finally, teenage girls will want to start lining up for
the Nov. 21 release date of the next Backstreet Boys disc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
