<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON OF DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Between now and the end of the year, something like 150 new
movies will open. That's too many. We wouldn't dream of avalanching
them all down on your head. Instead, we've compiled a list of the
golden dozen. Well, OK, make that the 30 or so new movies we're
most curious to see. (If I could count, I'd have been a banker.)
Don't look for any unifying theme or concept to cover these films
like an umbrella. They're all over the place, the way a movie
season's offerings should be _ adaptations, remakes, sequels, even
a handful of original works. If nothing else, they'll at least
raise the moviegoing year above its far from stratospheric current
level. If, if, if. As my father used to say, if we had some ham, we
could have ham and eggs, if we had some eggs. At any rate, here are
most of the films we'll be clucking about.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington probably won't be Oscar-nominated for it, but
``Remember the Titans,'' in which he plays an unpopular choice as
the football &UR;  &LR; coach of a reluctantly desegregated Virginia high
school in 1971, promises to put new spin on the pigskin genre.
``Almost Famous,'' Cameron Crowe's look back at his
peach-fuzz-cheeked beginnings as a rock journalist, smells like a
winner, boosted by heads-up performances from Billy Crudup's
mixed-up rocker and Kate Hudson's even more mixed-up groupie.
``Nurse Betty,'' Neil LaBute's carnival of criminality starring
Renee Zellweger as a traumatized innocent who emigrates to the
world of her favorite soap opera, is already showing strong legs.
Bjork, Iceland's gift to the A-list, and Danish director Lars von
Trier break new ground in their musical that wowed Cannes, ``Dancer
in the Dark.'' And who'd want to miss Christopher Guest? He's back
in ``Spinal Tap,'' and surfaces again with his ``Waiting for
Guffman'' follow-up, ``Best in Show,'' taking on the world of dog
shows.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be seeing a lot of Helen Hunt between now and Christmas.
She'll star opposite Richard Gere in Robert Altman's new ``Dr. T
and the Women.'' She'll be seen briefly as Tom Hanks's girlfriend,
waiting for him to be rescued from a desert island in Robert
Zemeckis's ``Cast Away'' _ the big holiday buzz movie, partly
because Hanks interrupted filming for a year so he could lose 50
pounds to look right in the enforced slimming mode. She'll be the
other half of Mel Gibson's first romantic comedy, ``What Women
Want.'' First, though, Hunt stars opposite Kevin Spacey and Haley
Joel Osment in ``Pay It Forward,'' as the alcoholic mom of Osment's
kid bent on improving the world, starting with her.
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro is another luminary who won't restrict himself to
one film next month. First he plays a guy who's unreceptive to the
idea of getting Ben Stiller as a son-in-law, in ``Meet the
Parents.'' Then he plays the hard-nosed Navy instructor of Cuba
Gooding Jr.'s first black master diver, in ``Men of Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Damon carves out a nice chunk of multiplex turf in two
films that promise quality. He plays the role Robert Redford once
eyed in ``The Legend of Bagger Vance,'' combining golf and
mysticism, aided by a gifted caddy played by Will Smith. Redford
directs. Damon also will be seen opposite Henry Thomas in Billy Bob
Thornton's long-gestating film of Cormac McCarthy's novel ``All the
Pretty Horses,'' about young bucks chasing adventure in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ben Affleck and Gwyneth Paltrow arrive in ``Bounce,''
about a man who gives up his air ticket to another man, then falls
in love with the guy's widow after the plane crashes. Paltrow's out
there with a second film, ``Duets,'' about the world of karaoke;
it's directed by her father, Bruce Paltrow. Most prominent among
the seasonal teamings are Jim Carrey and Dr. Seuss, in Ron Howard's
``Dr. Seuss's How the Grinch Stole Christmas.'' This one looks
huge, what with Carrey's green makeup and the season's
never-to-be-underestimated Bah, humbug! factor. Then there's Bruce
Willis and his ``Sixth Sense'' director, M. Night Shamalayan, back
with another supernatural thriller, ``Unbreakable,'' in which
Willis inexplicably survives a train crash. Perhaps co-star Samuel
L. Jackson has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Having no connection at all to ``The Sixth Sense'' is ``The 6th
Day,'' in which Arnold Schwarzenegger plays a helicopter pilot who
gets cloned. Michael Douglas and his fiance, Catherine Zeta-Jones,
appear not, as you might expect, in a ``Honeymooners'' remake, but
in ``Traffic,'' refashioning a British TV series about the drug
trade. Another high-impact teaming figures to be that of Cameron
Diaz, Drew Barrymore, and Lucy Liu in ``Charlie's Angels.'' Their
mission: to stop an evil plot to poison Charlie, no matter how many
explosions it takes or how many wet suits they have to go through.
</P>
<P>
   Among the remakes is ``Get Carter,'' with Sylvester Stallone
top-cast in a Seattle-based version of the 1971 British gangland
revenge drama that starred Michael Caine, who gives his imprimatur
to the new version via a bartender's role. Also joining the remake
parade is the Dudley Moore-Peter Cook ``Bedazzled,'' with Elizabeth
Hurley climbing into the devil suit this time. Speaking of the
devil, Adam Sandler stars as his good son, going up against his
hellraising brothers Rhys Ifans and ex-wrestler Tiny Lister Jr. in
``Little Nicky.'' Don't confuse ``Bedazzled'' with ``Bamboozled,''
the new Spike Lee movie in which Damon Wayans's writer rubs the
white media establishment's nose in its racism by penning a
contemporary minstrel show.
</P>
<P>
   And the sequels: Glenn Close once again teases her hair
outrageously and climbs into any number of politically incorrect
costumes as Cruella De Vil in ``102 Dalmatians,'' in which reminds
anyone who needs reminding that she just can't leave those spotted
dogs alone. The big noise among the sequels, either smashing or
crashing, will come from ``Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2,'' filmed
in what will seem like lavish color compared to the original.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the witch hunters will be asked to provide all the
year-end creepy panache. In Philip Kaufman's ``Quills,'' Geoffrey
Rush's Marquis de Sade finds his style cramped by Michael Caine's
serious asylum keeper. Then there's ``Shadow of the Vampire,''
which attempts to do for F.W. Murnau's 1922 silent ``Nosferatu''
what ``Gods and Monsters'' did for ``Frankenstein.'' Expect kiddie
vampires, too _ specifically Jonathan Lipnicki in ``The Little
Vampire,'' based on the popular children's book.
</P>
<P>
   History, the gift that keeps on giving, steps up to the plate
resonantly with ``Thirteen Days,'' in which Bruce Greenwood's JFK,
Steven Culp's RFK, and Kevin Costner's Kenny O'Donnell sweat out
the 1962 Cuban missile crisis. The Merchant-Ivory team offers
another of Henry James's opulent upper-crust soap operas, ``The
Golden Bowl,'' in which an American father and daughter (Nick Nolte
and Kate Beckinsale) are faced with the fact that the daughter's
husband (Jeremy Northam) is having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Film buffs will recognize the historical echo in the new Coen
brothers comedy, ``O, Brother, Where Art Thou?'' That's the title
of the overblown social-consciousness drama Preston Sturges
satirized in ``Sullivan's Travels.'' In the Coen brothers' take,
three convicts _ George Clooney, John Turturro, Tim Blake Nelson _
escape into the Depression-era South. Sturges also seems to be a
guardian angel of David Mamet's showbiz comedy ``State and Main,''
about a movie company on location _ loose morals, cell phones, and
all _ in a Vermont town.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is a handful of films with nothing in common but
the fact that they look irresistible. How, for instance, can you
not want to see a film starring Cate Blanchett and Hilary Swank? In
this case, it's the spooky-sounding ``The Gift,'' in which
Blanchett plays a young Savannah widow who tunes into her
neighbors' secrets, including Swank's abuse at the hands of her
husband, played by Keanu Reeves. Jack Nicholson and Sean Penn,
building on their ``Crossing Guard'' collaboration, team up again
in ``The Pledge,'' with Penn behind the camera as director and
Nicholson up front as a retired cop bulldogging an unsolved
homicide. Then there's Ang Lee, promising Hong Kong Yuletide action
with ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon.'' Chow Yun-Fat and Michelle
Yeoh provide the acrobatics. How many films is that? More than 30,
maybe. But who's counting?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
