<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HOOKER-STATUE-ART-BOS     09-11 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-STATUE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 GENERAL HOOKER'S ROUGH RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What is a gigantic statue of Joseph Hooker doing in
front of the State House next to the likes of Daniel Webster,
Horace Mann, and John F. Kennedy?
</P>
<P>
   Hooker, after all, is best remembered by Civil War buffs as the
Union general who led 138,000 troops to bloody defeat by Robert E.
Lee, who had a mere 62,000 men, at Chancellorsville, Va., in the
first week of May 1863.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Hooker was ``a most objectionable fellow in all
kinds of ways,'' says Shelby Foote, the eminent Civil War
historian.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker is commonly thought to be the eponym for a prostitute.
Hooker biographer Walter H. Hebert quotes one observer who examined
Hooker's headquarters at the Army of the Potomac and called it ``a
combination of bar-room and brothel.'' Few doubt the gamy
connection between the man and the red light district in
Washington, known during the war as ``Hooker's Division.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is believed now that the origin of the term predates
him, Hooker's dissolute behavior in uniform has forever tethered
him to the oldest profession.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Francis Adams Jr., brevetted as a brigadier general in
the Civil War, could abide neither man nor monument. ``Never since
it has been placed there have I passed by the front of the State
House without feeling a sense of wrong and insult at the presence,
opposite the head of Park Street, of the equestrian statue of
Hooker,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That statue,'' he continued, ``I look upon as an opprobrium
cast on every genuine Massachusetts man who served in the Civil
War. Hooker in no way and in no degree represents the typical
soldiership of the Commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, few passers-by know the colorful history of General
Hooker, or the origin of the looming bronze statue in his honor.
But the monument, like the man, has been controversial from the
opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after its dedication on June 25, 1903, Massachusetts
veterans were fuming over a bronze tablet on it listing the man's
military accomplishments because, incredibly, they considered it
not laudatory enough.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some 3,000 veterans in the state signed a petition
demanding its removal because they found the inscription, ``A
Soldier In The Army That Kept The Nation Whole,'' demeaning to
Hooker. Unmoved by its simple humility, they were convinced that
the major general warranted grander distinction than a mere
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   To make the case, an organization called the Hooker Brigade
Committee published a pamphlet entered at State House hearings on
the subject titled: ``The Hooker Veterans Are Only Asking For What
Is Right.''
</P>
<P>
   The veterans prevailed. The offending tablet was removed and
over 500 copies of the commemorative book about the Hooker statue
and its dedication were ceremoniously burned in Furnace (NU)3
beneath the State House. But no new tablet replaced the old one.
Wiser heads concluded what was good enough for Webster was also
good enough for Hooker; just the name would do.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of the controversy, termed ``a long and bitter
fight'' by The Boston Journal, speaks to the strength of the
nascent veterans' movement in Massachusetts after the Civil War. It
coalesced in The Grand Army of the Republic, the powerful group
formed in 1866 to represent Northern veterans. (Confederate states
had their own veterans organizations.) It served as a model for the
American Legion, founded in 1919 by American soldiers in France.
</P>
<P>
   That the statue was built with taxpayers' dollars speaks to the
muscle of the veterans lobby. The Legislature approved $50,000 for
the memorial _ large money in those days. This was one of the early
cases in which public, rather than private, money was used for such
memorials.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Massachusetts veterans adored Hooker, who was popular
with his troops if not with President Lincoln, who fired him as
commander of the Army of the Potomac less than two months after
Chancellorsville. Their feelings were shared by thousands of others
who had served under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soldiers were delighted with Hooker,'' concedes Foote.
``He fed them well and gave them decent clothes and shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker materialized in bronze from the gifted hands of sculptor
Daniel Chester French, who crafted the Lincoln Memorial. A Hooker
veteran concluded, ``The verdict of the art-loving public of
Massachusetts is that the Hooker statue is the finest equestrian
statue in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker was also memorialized as a vehicle to honor all
Massachusetts men who fought for the Union. The veterans needed a
symbol, and the pickings were slim.
</P>
<P>
   Augustus St. Gaudens had already completed the exquisite bas
relief across Beacon Street dedicated to the 54th Massachusetts
Regiment _ the first ``colored'' unit raised in the North _ led by
the young Boston patrician Robert Gould Shaw. The memorial was
dedicated on May 31, 1897.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bay State commanders had not bathed themselves in
glory. ``With Butler, Banks, and Hooker, Massachusetts had quite a
remarkable trio,'' drily notes Peter Drummey, librarian of the
Massachusetts Historical Society, which houses a rich trove of
material on Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Butler, the Union general known as ``Spoons'' while
commanding the Union occupation of New Orleans, lasted one year as
Massachusetts governor before resigning in 1883 amid withering
animosity. Nathaniel Banks, another Bay State general, was known as
``Stonewall Jackson's quartermaster'' because of the amount of
materiel and ordnance captured from his command by the
Confederates, according to Drummey.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker's connections to Massachusetts were thin. While born in
Hadley, the grandson of a veteran of the American Revolution, he
spent the rest of his life outside of the state after graduating
from West Point in 1837. He resigned from the army in 1853 and
bought a farm in Sonoma, Calif., where he lived until the outbreak
of the war. Today, his papers are housed at the Huntington Library
in San Marino, near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a century of harsh judgment, Hooker is enjoying a
comeback among some historians. Author Stephen Sears argued in a
recent book that a head injury Hooker sustained at Chancellorsville
clouded his judgment during much of the three-day battle. James
McPherson, author of the Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Battle Cry of
Freedom,'' agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``All evidence points to a severe concussion,'' says McPherson.
``He was really not himself, but the medical director of the Army
of the Potomac refused to certify him as unfit for command.'' But
that allowance, he says, is not enough to rescue Hooker's overall
military reputation as ``one of the failures'' of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says McPherson, ``Lesser men than Hooker have statues
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   True. Dotting our landscape are monuments that made sense when
they were commissioned but look bizarre today. The Hooker statue,
in contrast, struck some as weird from the start. But then they
misread the growing voice of American veterans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
