<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-POWER-BOS &LR;      09-11 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-POWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL KICKING NIXON AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ARROGANCE OF POWER 
The Secret World of Richard Nixon. 
By Anthony Summers. Viking. 544 pp. Illustrated. $29.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great defining question of Watergate (the great defining
scandal of Richard Nixon's career) was ``What did the president
know and when did he know it?'' Anthony Summers's much-publicized
new book about Nixon has a great defining question, too: What
didn't the president do, and when didn't he do it?
</P>
<P>
   Summers, a British investigative reporter who has published
books on the Kennedy assassination, Marilyn Monroe, and J. Edgar
Hoover, presents a Nixon of nearly unrelieved venality, ambition,
and pettiness. Summers's Nixon could as well have been labeled Sick
Dick as Tricky Dick. Summers says he drank too much, abused pills,
secretly relied on psychotherapy, was emotionally unstable, and
beat his wife. Not that there wasn't also trickiness: He took money
from organized crime (he took money from pretty much anyone) and
even stooped to betraying his country (by encouraging South
Vietnam, on the eve of the 1968 election, to refuse to join the
United States in peace talks with North Vietnam).
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing thing about Summers's book is how little it
enlarges _ or, for that matter, diminishes _ the conventional
portrait of Nixon. He was the only president to resign from office,
after all; and despite the two decades he spent assiduously
cultivating his image, no real historical revision of his career
has yet taken hold. More important, almost all Summers's
revelations elaborate on things previously known about Nixon rather
than break new ground. There are relatively few names in his index
that do not appear in that of, say, Stephen Ambrose's three-volume
biography.
</P>
<P>
   It's not news Nixon took sleeping pills, for example, or
occasionally saw a pyschotherapist, Dr. Arnold Hutschnecker. What
is news is Summers's assertion that one of the drugs may have been
the anti-epileptic medication Dilantin and his having spoken at
length with Hutschnecker. And the one thing that hasn't seen print
before, the accusation that Nixon struck his wife on at least one
occasion (and possibly more), is based on a single third-hand
account. Furthermore, it ignores the larger, and arguably more
damning, truth that Pat Nixon was clearly a battered wife
emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, are Summers's many allegations plausible?
Certainly, based on what we know about Nixon and the extensiveness
of Summers's research. He and his wife conducted more than a
thousand interviews for ``The Arrogance of Power''; he is clearly
conversant with the archival record; and the book boasts a copious
bibliography.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in history, as in a court of law, plausibility is not good
enough. Almost all Summers's allegations lie in what one might call
the shadow of the subjunctive. ``May,'' ``might,'' and ``could''
appear far more often than such Nixon standbys as ``lied,''
``bugged,'' and ``resigned.'' Indeed, Summers writes as a
prosecuting attorney under the Napoleonic Code: The accused is
guilty until proven innocent. Whenever there are conflicting
statements about culpability, whenever the evidence is wholly
circumstantial or inferential, the judgment invariably goes against
Nixon. After a while, one begins to wonder. What Summers writes
about a purported attempt by Howard Hughes to bribe Nixon applies
across the board here: ``Yet the question remains: In this gallery
of corrupters and corrupted, men who suffered convenient memory
lapses or simply lied, whose account can be deemed reliable?''
</P>
<P>
   Consider two examples. The man who claims to have introduced
Nixon to Dilantin, Jack Dreyfuss Jr., the founder of Wall Street's
Dreyfuss Fund, was well known as both a proselytizer for the drug
and as a generous contributor to the Republican Party. It is
easier, perhaps, to imagine Nixon placating Dreyfuss by accepting a
bottle of pills and later telling him how helpful they had been,
without ever having used them, than is his having acted as his own
pharmacist. Conversely, Hutschnecker's comments are nearly all
self-serving in the extreme (of the ``Then I told the president . .
.'' and ``If only he'd listened to me . . .'' variety). Nor does
their having come from a 97-year-old increase the reader's faith in
them.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, a certain numbness sets in, so unrelenting is
Summers's litany of illegality, immorality, and irrationality. The
obvious literary parallel is with Seymour Hersh's ``The Dark Side
of Camelot,'' about John F. Kennedy. Summers's book is the more
impressive of the two, but also the less alive. Maybe it's owing to
the fundamentally differing characters of Nixon and Kennedy, but
Hersh's book at least had an occasional juice and excitement to it
that ``The Arrogance of Power'' utterly lacks. Tabloid readers are
even less likely to be reading Summers's book than historians are.
</P>
<P>
   Massive as his research is, Summers's imaginativeness is almost
nonexistent: ``imaginativeness'' not in any Edmund Morris sense of
making things up but rather that of reaching out to another human
being and trying to imagine how he or she lived and thought and
felt. The enduring fascination of Richard Nixon has as much to do
with who and why as with what and how. The what and how of
Summers's book can, and will, be argued over for some time to come.
The who and why are hardly there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
