</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-DIAGNOSIS (Undated) _ ``The Diagnosis'' is neither so
eloquent nor as open-ended as ``Einstein's Dreams''; it is instead
a darkly allegorical novel about the human costs of a meaningless,
high-tech work world run amok. By Gail Caldwell. 1160 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-POWER (Undated) _ The great defining question of Watergate
was ``What did the president know and when did he know it?''
Anthony Summers's book about Richard Nixon has a great defining
question, too: What didn't the president do, and when didn't he do
it? By Mark Feeney. 960 words.
