NYT-09-11-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TX-COURTHOUSE-HNS &LR;      09-11 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-COURTHOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
2 Takes By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL _ It has all the makings of a messy urban-suburban
brouhaha, the kind that splits mammoth cities such as Houston and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown boosters propose an expensive project to ignite lagging
revitalization efforts. But those plans attract opposition from the
hinterlands, where penny-pinching taxpayers balk at forking out
more money.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston and Dallas, referendums for downtown sports
facilities have broken down over regional lines in recent years,
with those living far from the central business district opposing
them.
</P>
<P>
   But a similar rift in Harrison County, a sleepy East Texas
community of about 60,000?
</P>
<P>
   You bet your Santa Claus boots.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, county residents narrowly defeated a $5 million
referendum to repair the courthouse, which has hit hard times since
county offices left it in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   On one side _ rural residents wary of government spending. On
the other _ city dwellers who benefit from 750,000 visitors
flocking here between Thanksgiving and New Year's Eve for a
Christmas light show anchored by the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, local business leaders are trying to reassure the region's
tourism industry that the annual Wonderland of Lights will continue
this Christmas despite rumors to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opponents who led the taxpayer revolt are scrambling
to raise private funds to pay for what they don't think taxpayers
should.
</P>
<P>
   And stuck in the middle is the courthouse, boarded-up and closed
a week after the referendum failed by the narrowest of margins _ 47
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe the people here would let this happen to the
courthouse,'' said Jim Nash, who owns a golf store just off the
courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to take care of one of the few precious things
you have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Each Christmas since 1987, Marshall has decorated itself for
Christmas, the brainchild of a local newspaperman who claimed a
revelation about the courthouse bathed in lights. Other cities in
the region now emulate the Marshall celebration, which has become
one of the largest lighting displays in the country. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the festival's early years, volunteers adorned the
Renaissance Revival courthouse's pediments, porticos and &UR;  &LR; giant
columns with lights.
</P>
<P>
   Lights were later bolted to the courthouse, remaining there
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   As the festival attracted more observers, the Chamber of
Commerce hired a small staff to assist the volunteer effort. The
lights spread to other buildings and houses throughout town.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there were roughly 9 million lights, strung along
1,000 miles of wiring around town. Locals estimate that 750,000
people visited the event last year, with most coming from outside
the county of 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up the morning after the referendum and saw that
it lost, I cried,'' said chamber president Connie Ware. ``I was sad
not just because it is such a wonderful building that should be
preserved but because the Wonderland of Lights is so important to
our community.''
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse, built on one of the seven hills around Marshall,
was completed in 1901 to replace the one destroyed in an 1888 fire
that killed the courthouse cat that could not be persuaded to
abandon her home.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Marshall had become a booming railroad city after
New York railroad tycoon Jay Gould abandoned nearby Jefferson when
city fathers said they preferred being a port for steam engines.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with money, county officials hired architect James Riely
Gordon, who helped build 15 other courthouses from 1889 to 1902,
including 12 that still stand.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an imposing yellow-brick and limestone courthouse
that include pink limestone from the Hill Country quarry that
supplied the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon went on to design the Arizona Capitol before moving to
New York City, where he was president of the New York Society of
Architects.
</P>
<P>
   What he left in Texas _ stellar designs in Harrison, Bexar,
Ellis and McLennan counties _ are considered the best of the
state's courthouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``His courthouses capture the essence of the spirit of the
golden age of architecture,'' said museum consultant Conover Hunt.
``They speak to the high aspirations of the people who tamed the
frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   But preserving beauty was not a major concern in the early
1960s, when county officials needed space. So in 1964, they opened
a bland-but-functional courthouse across the street. Over time, the
old courthouse, as it is called, came to hold a historical society,
a local museum and a genealogy library.
</P>
<P>
   But the building deteriorated from negligence and lack of use as
Marshall's boom days were over.
</P>
<P>
   No one thought about tearing the building down, largely because
it meant so much to the small city of about 30,000. It is a piece
of their history and lore.
</P>
<P>
   One can still see where the granddaughter of Judge Sam Hall, the
daughter of former Congressman Sam Hall Jr., carved her
grandfather's name into the black enamel lining the cast iron
staircase outside his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s, a hobo once lived in the crawl space where the
clock was kept. To reach his home, the hobo had to crawl up two
steel ladders outside the dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a courthouse. It has been the center of this
town for 100 years,'' said County Judge Rodney Gilstrap.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TX-COURTHOUSE-HNS &LR;      09-11 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-COURTHOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   2nd Take COURTHOUSE: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, local government and business leaders agreed
that the courthouse needed attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They hired Hunt, who helped prepare the Sixth Floor Exhibit at
Dallas' Texas School Book Depository.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the various problems _ a leaky dome,
moisture-soaked bricks, decaying walls and floors _ the cost to
update the building was at least $6.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the estimate was removing ancillary walls and floors
added to a two-story courtroomthat Gilstrap said once resembled the
one in the movie To Kill a Mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing need was the roof. So using $1.5 million in
local, city and county funds, the roof was restored to its full
golden glory. The other $5 million has been hard to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Gilstrap said the county approached the Texas Historic
Commission for a portion of the $50 million the 1999 Legislature
appropriated for courthouse repairs throughout Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But facing a high demand for that money, the historic commission
decided to allocate for courthouses built before 1900, a near miss
for the Harrison County building, Gilstrap said.
</P>
<P>
   That left the county looking within for the money, ultimately
deciding to ask voter approval for a 1-cent property tax hike to
pay for the $5 million project.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tax increase meant just $5 extra for owners of a
$50,000 house, an anti-tax group in Harrison County used the
proposal to generate steam for its organization.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Citizens for Better Government, is headed by local
real estate agent Fuzzy Harmon, who was overwhelmingly defeated by
Gilstrap for the judge's position in 1998. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Using a campaign based on the idea that repairing the
courthouse was a waste of taxpayers' money, Harmon was able to
appeal to rural voters who don't benefit as much from the annual
Christmas tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad business, you know what I mean?'' Harmon said. ``I
mean, you can build a house for $70 a square foot, and it would
have cost $338 a square foot to repair the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Marshall, the referendum passed in all but one precinct.
</P>
<P>
   But in rural Harrison County, where more than half the voters
live, the referendum failed in 17 of 19 rural voting precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant was the 5-1 margin of defeat on the county's
western edge, where neighboring Longview has spilled over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The residents there work in Longview, and they are tied to
Longview,'' Gilstrap said. ``They don't really care what happens to
Marshall, or the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the election, Gilstrap persuaded the
county commissioners to close the courthouse, kicking out the
library, museum and historic society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't argue all over the county that the courthouse
wasn't safe, and it's not, and keep it open,'' Gilstrap said.
</P>
<P>
   The closing caused alarm from those in the tourism industry, who
began calling with worries that it would mean no Christmas tour. As
a result, the chamber is spending extra dollars in advertising to
counter those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still can't believe he (Harmon) did this,'' Ware said.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that most business leaders are rankled with him, Harmon,
who intends to run for judge again, has pledged to work with
Gilstrap and other courthouse supporters to find additional private
money.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon has proposed charity golf tournaments, an Internet Web
site and taping a documentary about the courthouse that could be
used like an informercial soliciting donations. Or perhaps, the
courthouse could be sold to a private developer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite being cast as a pariah after the referendum _ having
a rock thrown through his business window and being threatened _
Harmon said he will not give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I knew how to do events that raised money when I was in
the Jaycees,'' Harmon said. ``You have to make these things fun,
you know what I mean? I know we can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilstrap isn't so sure there is enough private money available
for such a mammoth project. ``He hasn't proposed a bake sale but
maybe that's next,'' Gilstrap said sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   So the judge intends to seek additional state funds if the
Legislature allocates more courthouse restoration money.
</P>
<P>
   And he will examine other ways to finance the building with
local tax dollars, though he doesn't intend to seek another bond
referendum such as the one that failed.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the courthouse will be renovated, he said. Time is
on their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This courthouse has been here a long time, and it will be here
a long time to come,'' Gilstrap said while climbing a ladder that
led to the room where the hobo once lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not get to it this year, or next,'' he said. ``But in
time, we will find ways to return this courthouse to its glory.
That's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
