<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ In Florida George W. Bush launches
a five-state swing touting his proposals on health care,
conservation, and education and courting senior citizens and women.
Al Gore opens an eight-state drive trying to cement his gains with
women voters in an appearance on Oprah Winfrey's TV show. He
attacks Bush's plans for Social Security and prescription drug
coverage. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Entertainment companies
still target children in their ads for sexually-explicit movies,
violent video games and raunchy music, the Federal Trade Commission
reports. It threatens government sanctions against the companies if
the industry ``is unable to clean up its act.'' We get reaction
from the presidential candidates and President Clinton. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COINS (Washington) _ Just as Congress is about to consider new
designs of U.S. coins, a poll of 1,940 collectors shows they favor
adding Martin Luther King Jr., Ronald Reagan and Harry Truman to
the face of America's pocket change. Some of those polled say John
Wayne, Elvis Presley, Bill Gates and Tiger Woods should also be on
coins. By JENNIFER DLOUHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ There's something missing from the
presidential campaign. Neither Al Gore nor George Bush pays much
attention to the GOP-controlled Congress. Their silence may vanish,
however, now that Congress and the White House are locked in
legislative battles once again. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
