<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8922 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     09-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Texas' progress on clean air undeniable; serious
work lies ahead
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Houston, Dallas and El Paso, dog days have come to mean smog
days.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Houston again chased down and passed Los Angeles as
the nation's ozone alert capital, with soaring temperatures and
stagnant air patterns contributing.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's two years running. Houston air quality has never
been worse, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. In fact, Houston's ozone levels at their present-day
worst are only half as bad as they were in the early 1970s. That's
when the United States started doing something about its air and
created the Environmental Protection Agency to do it.
</P>
<P>
   So if the air is cleaner, why is the EPA dogging Texas?
</P>
<P>
   It's because ozone readings in key areas of the state are sorely
out of attainment. Under EPA standards, Houston's status is ranked
``severe.'' Dallas got bumped up from ``moderate'' to ``serious''
under the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Several other cities including San Antonio, Austin, Longview,
Tyler, and Marshall are targeted for air cleanups by the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission. However, the TNRCC has
given them an ``unclassifiable'' status, meaning there's not enough
data yet to justify an EPA crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   As for Houston falling behind Los Angeles on air quality, though
Texas has taken some key steps to improve air quality in the last
20 years, California has been more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say that Texas is victimized by its wealth _ of
refineries and petrochemical industries _ and the heat, which cooks
nitrogen oxides to ozone.
</P>
<P>
   But observers like Lone Star Sierra Club air expert Neal Carman
point out that Southern California has the same ingredients.
California has bitten the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   He points out, for instance, that refineries in the Houston area
put out far more ozone-producing emissions than similar-sized
plants in the Los Angeles basin.
</P>
<P>
   With refineries and petrochemical plants, said Carman, Texas'
major problem is grandfathered operations _ in place or in
construction before the Texas Clean Air Act of 1971 and therefore
not subject to the same pollution controls as those built
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Texas took an important step in the last session of the
Legislature when it incorporated a major cleanup of nitrogen oxides
from grandfathered power plants as a part of electric deregulation.
But that leaves all other grandfathered industrial sites largely
untouched, with only a voluntary cleanup plan promoted by Gov.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the EPA steps in _ at least for Houston and
Dallas-Fort Worth. It's not that Texas had not been warned over and
over. In fact the state has been receiving warnings from the EPA
for five years over non-attainment in Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the EPA threatened Texas with the loss of highway
dollars if it didn't come up with air plans for the two metro
areas. The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Committee responded
with plans that would dramatically curb emissions at power plants
and grandfathered industries. Also included are lower speed limits
and curbs on the use of some heavy equipment in mornings.
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC, Texas' environmental watchdog, is in the middle of all
this. On one hand, critics assert that it is a snoozing agent of
lassitude under the George W. Bush administration. On the other
hand it is assailed by critics who see the proposals now on the
table for the Houston and D-FW areas as overly draconian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something,'' said TNRCC executive director
Jeff Saitas. ``To not do something would not have been a
responsible discharge of our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In an Austin interview, Saitas disputed the notion that the Bush
administration has influenced his agency to go easy on industry.
</P>
<P>
   The message from the governor has been ``very clear,'' said
Saitas: ``We want clean air, clean water'' and a balance struck
between environmental protection and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Foster, state air implementation coordinator for the
agency, said that except in comparison to California, Texas has
taken a back seat to no one in addressing EPA requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 20 years Texas has made major strides in curbing
ozone and other air pollution, he said. But Texas' growth _ all
those automobiles, all that power generated _ has caused gains to
level off.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, Texas' record on air pollution is decidedly
mixed.
</P>
<P>
   With grandfathered plants doing too little to clean up their
acts; with the state's auto emissions testing program having
started, stopped and started again; with alarming levels of mercury
unchecked in exhaust from coal-fired plants; with pollution getting
shared between regions (a problem compounded by snoot-fulls of bad
air from Mexico), Texas has incredible challenges.
</P>
<P>
   It will not meet those challenges in a prone position.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald . E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
