<P>
   George W. Bush is the first governor in state history to have
been elected to two consecutive four-year terms, and Rick Perry,
the lieutenant-governor, is the first Republican to hold that
position since Reconstruction in the 1860s, after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Although the lower house of the Texas legislature and most of
the state's congressional districts remain in Democratic hands,
this is largely thanks to a crafty redistricting scheme devised by
Democrats in the legislature after the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republicans now holding the reins of power in Austin,
it is unlikely that the state's electoral map will be so friendly
to Democrats after the next redistricting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other states of the old Confederacy, Texas began
turning towards the Republicans as a reaction against the
civil-rights movement of the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Southern Democrats, alienated by the growing
influence in their party of minorities and Northern liberals, began
to cast ballots for Republicans throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Johnson, as the vice-presidential nominee, just managed
to deliver the state to John F. Kennedy; but after he himself
signed civil-rights legislation into law in 1964 and 1965, the fate
of Lone Star Democrats was sealed.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the South the Democrats, by dint of alliances
between blacks and moderate whites, began to recover a little
ground in the 1990s, electing governors in Alabama, Georgia and the
Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, with a relatively small black population of 12 percent,
could not follow that lead. And Texas Democrats have been less
successful than their California counterparts at turning the
state's Latino population (nearly 30 percent) into a solid
Democratic voting block.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won roughly 40 percent of the Latino vote when he was
reelected in 1998, and he and other Republicans are careful to
pander to Latinos by speaking Spanish, enjoying Tejano culture and
being friendly to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As a Democratic political consultant, George Christian, puts it,
``Republicans in Texas knew that if they didn't develop long-term
appeal to Latinos, they would have a short life in Texas
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Another unhelpful trend for the Democrats has been the drift
from the rural counties, LBJ's heartland, to the more Republican
big cities and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the votes in Texas are cast in the Dallas and
Houston metropolitan areas, and Republican presidential candidates
carried these regions easily all through the 1990s. But nowadays
even the rural parts of Texas are wavering.
</P>
<P>
   These failures have started to affect the sort of people the
Democrats put forward for statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   Although a throng of young, ambitious Republicans currently hold
statewide offices, the Democratic Party has tended to field
politically inexperienced trial lawyers _ a breed not much loved in
Texas, or indeed, anywhere (save possibly New York). In fact, the
Democrats seem to be concentrating most of their puny firepower on
local races, especially the Texas Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, the Democrats are biding their time until
Bush leaves the stage.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats in the state, the ultimate humiliation came when
the last great Democratic power broker, the former
lieutenant-governor Bob Bullock, who had dominated Texas politics
for four decades, threw his support behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bush visited him on his deathbed and Bullock wished
the presidential candidate good luck in the coming fight. He died
the next day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
