<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Details on the Mideast peace talks
between the United States and the Palestinians. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ Protests against high fuel costs spread
to Britain and Ireland on Monday. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-POLIO (Undated) _ Developments at a conference in
Britain on the theory that AIDS was spread by contaminated polio
vaccine. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Clearwater, Fla.) _ The conventional wisdom is that George
W. Bush shouldn't be talking about issues, particularly when his
positions make for a harder sell than the Democrats'. But that's
what he's doing today, talking about health care. His week will
continue in that vein. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum) _ Al Gore starts his campaing day with
Oprah, then talks about education in Illinois. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT8.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE (Albuquerque) _ Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos
scientist accused of stealing a library of nuclear weapons secrets,
is expected to be released on Monday after pleading guilty to a
single felony count of improperly downloading classified material
onto an unsecure computer. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   LEE-SPY-CHARGES (Washington) _ On what has happened to the
espionage case against Wen Ho Lee. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-SELL (Washington) _ Producers of movies, video
games and music aggressively try to attract children and teen-agers
to entertainment that contains violent themes, the Federal Trade
Commission said in a report released Monday. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FREE-TUITION (Los Angeles) _ All needy high school
students in California with a B average will get free tuition at
state college under law to be signed by Gov. Gray Davis on Monday.
By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINNCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Crude oil prices rose above $34 a barrel
in early New York trading Monday despite Sunday's agreement by OPEC
to increase production by 3 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) _ On the prospects for regulatory or
legislative action in Washington in the wake of the
Bridgeston/Firestone tire recall. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-CONSULT (Undated) _ Looking at why Hewlett-Packard may
make a big push into consulting services. The company confirmed
Monday that it is in talks to acquire to buy
PricewaterhouseCoopers's management and information-technology
consulting business for as much as $18 billion in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   REAL-LIFE-MARKETING (Benton Harbor, Mich.) _ A small group of
new employees at Whirlpool is essentially sentenced to live in a
large house, where they prepare more than 900 plates of food, wash
no fewer than 120 bags of laundry and perform countless hours of
loading and reloading of the company's refrigerators, dish washers
and dryers. Company executives say the reality-based training
program is a more pragmatic and effective way of preparing its
youthful marketing representatives than the lectures and slide
shows that make up so many corporate initiations. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undted) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-SPEAR (Undated) _ Goldman Sachs Group has agreed to pay
$6.5 billion in stock and cash for Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, the
biggest specialist firm on the NYSE. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSE-MERGERS (London) _ The Frankfurt exchange on
Monday put off its vote on its merger with the London Stock
Exchange, while the operator of the Stockholm exchange made an
official bid for the London exchange. By Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-MERGE (London) _ Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline
Beecham said they have delayed their merger a second time as U.S.
antitrust regulators scrutinize their quit-smoking products. By
Suzanne Kapner.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan's economy expanded by an annual rate
of 4.2 percent in the second quarter, more than what economists had
expected, but most of the growth came from public investment rather
than private sector demand. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Collins is on vacation.
</P>
