<P>
   But the real point of the exercise is to raise doubts about
Bush's capacity for hard work.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore is the Energizer Bunny of this campaign, Bush is the
napster, taking his favorite feather pillow wherever he goes _ an
aide carries it in a special bag _ and pining if he has to spend
too many nights away from home.
</P>
<P>
   For all its symbolic virtues, however, Gore should hesitate
before organizing another workathon, if only to keep the press from
staging a revolt. Listening to one speech by Gore is hardly a
rousing experience. Listening to several speeches in a row,
including one just before dawn, verges on torture.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started the week with yet another faux pas: calling a New
York Times journalist a ``major-league (vulgarity)'' in the range
of a live microphone. (A hint: it's an anatomical part in the human
southern hemisphere; site of hemorrhoids.)
</P>
<P>
   That word was mild compared with the ones being bandied around
by some members of the press as they completed their 28th
consecutive hour of following the vice president. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
