<HEADER>
A8942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-SELL-44     09-11 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-SELL-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY CRITICIZED FOR USING VIOLENCE TO ATTRACT
CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Producers of movies, video games and music
aggressively try to attract children and teen-agers to
entertainment that contains violent themes, federal regulators said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said people in the entertainment
industries use advertising to promote products that they themselves
acknowledge warrant parental caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``And are these advertisements intended to attract children and
teen-agers?'' the trade commission asked in a statement issued on
Monday. The report found that ``for all three segments of the
entertainment industry, the answers are plainly `yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The report was undertaken in response to a request made by
President Clinton on June 1, 1999, barely five weeks after the
school massacre in Littleton, Colo. Several members of Congress
made similar requests.
</P>
<P>
   The agency does not recommend legislation on the violence in
marketing to children issue. ``Self-regulation is especially
critical in this area, given the First Amendment protections that
prohibit government regulation of these products' content,'' the
trade commission said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, endorsed in a 5-0 commission vote, drew its
conclusions in part from marketing plans and other material
submitted by the industry itself. The agency found evidence of
marketing and media strategies that expressly focus on children
under 17 and promote and advertise goods in outlets most likely to
reach young children.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders, anticipating the conclusions in the report,
questioned the validity of the findings. ``If we are causing moral
decay in this country, we ought to have an explosion of crime,''
Jack Valenti, the head of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said on Sunday. ``The exact opposite is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti went on to praise Hollywood's self-rating system. ``For
almost 32 years, this industry has been the only segment of our
national marketplace that voluntarily turns away revenues at the
box office to redeem the pledge that we have made to parents,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the report is available on the agency's web site,
www.ftc.gov. A more complete response from Valenti's organization
may been seen at www.mpaa.org.
</P>
<P>
   While the 104-page report reached some harsh conclusions, it did
acknowledge that the entertainment industry has made efforts to
identify content that may be inappropriate for children. But the
commission chairman, Robert Pitofsky, said: ``Companies in the
entertainment industry routinely undercut their own rating
restrictions by target-marketing violent films, records and video
games to young audiences. These industries can and should do better
than this report illustrates.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is a perennial debate over whether violent material that
is marketed to children spawns violence by children, and what can
be done about it without violating the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, have said they would propose legislation or regulatory
authority against the entertainment industry if it does not stop
marketing violent material to children.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, Gore's Republican opponent in the
presidential race, said through a spokesman that the entertainment
industry and parents must play stronger roles in protecting
children. ``We're all in this together,'' said Ari Fleischer, a
spokesman for the governor's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Commerce Committee plans to hold a hearing Wednesday
on the commission's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wisc., said on Monday that one of his aides
accompanied two seventh-grade boys to several retail stores in the
Washington area over the weekend, where the boys were able to buy
``ultra-violent video games'' despite ratings that labeled the
games as suitable for adults only.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has long focused on what can be done about violent video
games. On Monday, he accused retailers of deliberately skirting
their own ratings for profit. ``The video and computer game
industry failed to act in good faith,'' he said, ``and shouldn't be
surprised that Congress is ready to step in if it does not do
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
