r a BC-NECK'N'NECK-GOREBUSH-     09-11 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NECK'N'NECK-GOREBUSH-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD TO HEAD, NECK AND NECK: MOUTH-TO-MOUTH REVIVES RACE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 3 trims, total 325; 1,450 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: THREE OPTIONAL TRIMS _ TOTALING 325 WORDS. TOTAL
UNCUT IS 1,450 WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's presidential election has been
transformed. For much of the past year, it had seemed George W.
Bush's to lose. Streets ahead in most polls, he had been able to
set the policy agenda and stamp his authority on his party.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, meanwhile, written off by many as the president's
apologist-in-chief, lurched from one public persona to another
while his fractious party squabbled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an inspired choice of running mate, a lingering
uxorial kiss and a policy-laden speech at his party's nominating
convention, it is Gore who is surging ahead in the polls, with an
average lead of three percentage points in most and ten points in
one.
</P>
<P>
   On some measures Bush, whose troubles began with his own
lacklustre choice of running mate and were compounded by a
convention speech that, in retrospect, looks vacuous on policy, is
scoring lower than the generic Republican vote _ a remarkable
setback for someone who has built his campaign on not being one of
those awful partisan congressional Republicans whom voters loathe.
</P>
<P>
   So now it is an animated and forceful Gore who is setting the
agenda, forcing Bush into spelling out his prescription-drug plan
last week by challenging him to ``put up or shut up'' about the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   And it is Bush who is stumbling on the hustings, getting his
billions and his trillions muddled up (twice) and blurting unsavory
things into open microphones.
</P>
<P>
   The event mainly responsible for this turnaround was Gore's
acceptance speech at the Democratic Convention. Criticized at the
time as a catalogue of pandering to special-interest groups, his
policy promises are now seen to have cemented his reputation as the
candidate talking most about the bread-and-butter concerns of
America's middle class: i.e., most voters.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Joe Lieberman's harping on religion and morality,
this has given the Gore ticket a double appeal to the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   It has also revealed the weak points of Bush's appeal. When he
was ahead in the polls, he tended to stress his policy proposals:
partial privatization of Social Security, tax cuts, school vouchers
and the like.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention he changed tack, stressing instead the
failures of leadership and character of Clinton and Gore and
promising to ``change the tone in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   This seemed like a good idea at the time. Gore looked vulnerable
to some kinds of personal attack, especially for the fund-raising
scandals that bedevilled his and Clinton's re-election campaign in
1996. Conversely, the policy debate seems less promising for the
unwonkish Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the shift in strategy ran two hidden risks. First, the
character thrusts were made in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Before the convention, voter ignorance about Gore had been
profound, even though he had been in the public eye for years. As
it turned out, they liked what they saw in Los Angeles, and the
``leadership gap'' (in which Bush was deemed by poll respondents to
be the more decisive leader) disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   That undermined the force of Bush's first big anti-Gore
televised advertising campaign. He ended up attacking
pre-convention views about Gore while the candidate and voters had
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Second, by attacking at all, he was not doing much to change the
tone in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these travails, some of Gore's more enthusiastic
supporters now think the vice president has done more than merely
erase the early Republican lead. They think he has put himself in a
position to romp home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 625) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There are two bits of evidence to support this. First, it is
possible that voters may be making up their minds a little earlier
than usual. Historically, around two-thirds of voters have made
their decision by this point in the campaign cycle, a share that
has fallen slightly over the years (to 55 percent in 1992).
</P>
<P>
   This time, some pollsters have found that as many as nine-tenths
of voters say they have made up their minds, which, if true, makes
Gore's current poll lead the more significant. (Since 1960, the man
ahead at this point has gone on to win in November.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, some of Gore's backers think that the state of the
economy is the most reliable guide to any presidential race, and
that this should be enough to see their man home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A rule of thumb says that assuming there is peace abroad and
neither candidate is affected by personal scandal (the outgoing
president's disrepute does not count), the incumbent will win if
the economy is growing by more than 4 percent at an annual rate in
the first half of the election year.
</P>
<P>
   It has been growing by far more than that (rising 5.8 percent in
the first six months of 2000 compared with the second half of
1999).
</P>
<P>
   It is true that voters split the credit for this, giving some to
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, some to the
Republican Congress, and some to America's entrepreneurial spirit.
But, argues Tom Mann of the Brookings Institution, that has always
been true. And if this election is like any other, then Gore should
benefit from the growth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the final years of the Reagan boom helped George W.
Bush's father erase a 17-point gap in the summer and destroy
Michael Dukakis. The 2000 election has started to follow that
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it would be foolish to think it is all over. For one thing,
around a fifth of voters have changed their minds in the past
month. That suggests considerable volatility.
</P>
<P>
   For another, if you take the polling evidence state by state,
rather than nationally, the race looks like a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is ahead in three polls, Gore in three others. Based on the
most recent state polls, Bush has 223 Electoral College votes to
Gore's 228, which means neither has the 270 needed to win. Since
America chooses its president through the Electoral College, not by
direct popular vote, this is the relevant measure.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the character of the policy debate points to a
close contest. The race is turning into a debate about how to react
to growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,075) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Partly, that means it is about how much of the forecast budget
surplus to hand back in tax cuts and how much to spend in
government programs or for paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, it is a debate over the virtues of consolidation
versus radicalism.
</P>
<P>
   Gore essentially says that after eight years of growth, America
should now concentrate on consolidating its gains. That means
paying down the national debt by 2012, shoring up the finances of
Social Security and Medicare (rather than changing the programs
fundamentally), and spending more money on education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore unveiled a plan to set aside $300 billion as a
contingency fund in case the forecast budget surpluses do not
materialize, and grouped all his various economic programs into a
prototype budget document, which he describes as ``specific,
detailed and _ above all _ prudent.''
</P>
<P>
   If the campaign were a military one, Gore would be the general
ringing conquered territory with solid defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush essentially argues that the eight years of growth provide a
chance for America to expand market mechanisms into new areas,
notably the big government entitlement programs.
</P>
<P>
   In Social Security he proposes to allow workers to set aside a
share of their payroll taxes for private retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In Medicare he has proposed letting private companies offer a
range of competing services, rather than the single,
government-financed one. He proposes education vouchers for failing
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a military operation, he would be the admiral
saying ``Damn the torpedoes, full steam ahead!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,350) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Looked at this way, the race seems too close to call. On the one
hand, America is friendlier to market solutions than almost any
other country; and this election is taking place at a time when
half of all households own shares, which may mean that people are
more willing to take risks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, consolidating your gains is a natural
reaction, especially among older people who vote in larger
numbers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF THIRD TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,450) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the race is no longer Bush's to lose. Equally, it would
be too much to say it has become Gore's to lose. But the changes
mean it is now up to Bush to shift the momentum back in his favor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
