<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's presidential election has been
transformed. For much of the past year, it had seemed George W.
Bush's to lose. Streets ahead in most polls, he had been able to
set the policy agenda and stamp his authority on his party.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, meanwhile, written off by many as the president's
apologist-in-chief, lurched from one public persona to another
while his fractious party squabbled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an inspired choice of running mate, a lingering
uxorial kiss and a policy-laden speech at his party's nominating
convention, it is Gore who is surging ahead in the polls, with an
average lead of three percentage points in most and ten points in
one.
</P>
<P>
   On some measures Bush, whose troubles began with his own
lacklustre choice of running mate and were compounded by a
