<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8964 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ZEDILLO-LEGACY-ECONOM     09-11 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-LEGACY-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX INHERITS A BETTER MEXICO, BUT PROBLEMS STILL LURK  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: 300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,150
WORDS.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Last Friday, when President Ernesto Zedillo gave
his final state-of-the-union address to Mexico's Congress, he had
much to be proud of. Back in 1994, he took over a country teetering
on the brink of economic crisis, and scarred by political violence
and guerrilla rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, he will hand over to Vicente Fox a country that
differs for the better, in two fundamental ways.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Zedillo overseen Mexico's peaceful transition to
democracy, with power passing to the opposition in the form of Fox
after seven decades of rule by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo also passes on a booming economy: this year GDP is
set to grow by 7 percent, its highest rate since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Zedillo, a dry, bookish man devoid of charisma, will
bow out on a wave of popular esteem: his popularity rating stands
close to 70 percent, compared with just 30 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, too, that his speech was largely uninterrupted by the
angry protests that have punctuated these occasions over the past
decade, nor that it was cheered by the opposition, while the PRI's
congressmen sat stony-faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no applause, because he didn't deserve it,'' said
Senator Manuel Bartlett, a leader of the PRI's diehard faction.
That is a backhanded compliment to Zedillo's statesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   He has done much to smooth what might have been a bumpy
transition to Fox. In particular, Zedillo has sought with almost
obsessive zeal to break the cycle of economic crises that have
accompanied the past four presidential handovers.
</P>
<P>
   In this, he appears likely to succeed: such is the confidence of
the financial markets that Mexico last week felt able to pay back
its outstanding loans to the IMF, totalling $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Zedillo is also bequeathing some problems to Fox.
One is that the economy looks too strong for its own good, yet
growth is only just starting to benefit the poor majority of
Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   Another set of difficulties has been dramatized by the
corruption scandals that are marring Zedillo's final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Take the economy first. After plunging in Zedillo's first year,
in the wake of a bungled devaluation, Mexico's GDP has grown at an
annual average rate of 5 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Behind that growth lie Mexico's close economic links with the
booming United States through NAFTA, free-market reforms enacted by
Zedillo's predecessors, and sound economic management: Zedillo has
often acted as if he were finance minister, rather than president.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that growth is underpinned by increased
investment, the current-account deficit is manageable at around 3
percent of GDP this year, and a floating exchange rate has worked
well as a shock-absorber.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately for Fox, who has promised still-higher growth,
the economy needs to be cooled. Recorded unemployment has fallen to
just 2 percent; skilled labor is in especially short supply, and
some of the export growth reflects high but volatile oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The (independent) central bank has nudged up interest rates; but
relying on a monetary squeeze alone risks strengthening the
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   As Alfredo Thorne of J.P. Morgan, an American bank, notes, to
sustain growth, Fox will have to tighten fiscal policy while
pushing through structural reforms to boost productivity. In doing
so, Fox will be handicapped by his legacy, and by his own seeming
reluctance to take unpopular stands.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wants to increase public spending, while needing to cut the
fiscal deficit. Under Zedillo, Mexico's tax revenues have amounted
to no more than 11 percent of GDP; to attack poverty and improve
education, Fox has said he wants the figure to rise to 17 percent.
But he has also backed away from specific tax reforms, such as
introducing VAT on food.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo failed to persuade his own party to accept structural
reforms; lacking a congressional majority, Fox may struggle to gain
approval for his modest proposals to allow private investment in
electricity and oil.
</P>
<P>
   A second set of tasks for Fox is the reform of Mexico's
institutions. The depth of the rot under the PRI has been
highlighted by a string of setbacks and embarrassments that have
hit Zedillo's government since the presidential election in July. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 725) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   First, Oscar Espinosa, Zedillo's treasurer in the 1994
presidential campaign, resigned as tourism minister and disappeared
_ seemingly to escape prosecution on charges of embezzling $45
million while mayor of Mexico City from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a drama at Cancun airport, when police boarded an
aircraft to arrest Ricardo Cavallo, the head of Mexico's national
car registry, as a suspected Argentine war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Five former prisoners have identified him as Miguel Angel
Cavallo, a naval officer and torturer during Argentina's ``dirty
war'' of the 1970s. In Mexico, he had abused his position to
traffic in stolen cars.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case, two army generals were last week arrested on
suspicion of helping drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Mexico's Supreme Court ruled last month that
Zedillo should hand over to congressional investigators documents
relating to Banco Union, a failed bank formerly run by Carlos Cabal
Peniche, a fugitive financier.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal lost an appeal on Aug. 30 against extradition from
Australia to face charges of fraudulently pocketing $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   He claims that he was pressed by aides, including Espinosa, to
make an illegal donation of $4 million from Banco Union's funds to
Zedillo's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the cost of that alleged donation would
have been passed on to taxpayers, since Banco Union was one of
several banks that later collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the government's flawed bailout of the financial system
after the 1994 devaluation is costing $100 billion. It was the
first time that the normally supine court had ruled against a
Mexican president.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, too, the PRI has blocked attempts in Congress to
investigate Cabal's claims, citing banking secrecy laws. But now
the courts and the new Congress may dig more deeply into the bank
bailout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 300-WORD TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,150) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The end of the PRI's rule, and the emergence of a plural
democracy in Mexico, were always likely to prompt an outpouring of
revelations of corruption and other wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   That process, if well-directed by Fox, should lead to a salutary
cleansing of public institutions. But it could yet prove to be
politically explosive.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that such scandals will damage Zedillo's personal
reputation for scrupulous honesty, though they may blight his
administration's record.
</P>
<P>
   With more pesos in their pockets, many Mexicans will no doubt
forgive Zedillo, if not some of his officials, regardless of what
the investigators turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his government's shortcomings, Mexicans will have
grounds for satisfaction if their new president turns out to be as
successful as his predecessor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
