<P>
   TWINS-DEBATE (London) _ A case of Siamese twins who share a
heart and lungs spawns a huge ethical and religious debate in
England after court rules that surgeons can perform surgery that
would save one while dooming the other. By Kevin Cullen. 1450
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CHENEY (Wayne, Pa.) _ When Dick Cheney was picked as
George W. Bush's running mate, the campaign said he wouldn't be
relegated to minor markets, but that is where he often appears. By
Michael Kranish. 1880 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CLAIMS (Carbondale, Pa.) _ Exaggeration is a fact of
life on the campaign trail. Candidates always present their
proposals in the best possible light and their opponent's in the
most unfavorable terms. By Glen Johnson. 1090 words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-EDUCATION (Undated) _ The 2000 political campaign
calculus for students and their parents works out this way: The
Republican nominee is embracing a $5 billion new federal subsidy
for the poor; the Democrat is touting tax cuts, primarily for the
middle class. By Patrick Healy. 1257 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DRAFT (Undated) _ Dick Cheney and Joe Lieberman have
something in common beyond their hope to become vice president:
draft deferments. By Walter V. Robinson. 340 words. &QL; 
