<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATION PITS PARK SERVICE AGAINST INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the high sandstone desert of northeastern
Arizona, two Hopi men traveled to a sacred ancestral spot last year
in search of nests of golden eagle chicks.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of years, young men in initiation ceremonies have
scaled mesas near the Little Colorado River and the Painted Desert
to capture the eaglets. The birds are later killed in holy rites
for the very existence of the Hopi and the world.
</P>
<P>
   But on that day in May 1999, the National Park Service turned
away the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Park managers for the 35,000-acre Wupatki National Monument near
Flagstaff told them their permit to capture 40 golden eaglets in
three Arizona counties might be valid on private property or land
owned by the U.S. Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management. But
not Park Service land.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming a loss of religious freedom, the Hopi tribe complained
to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, a former governor of Arizona.
They wanted a change in the Organic Act of 1916, which created the
National Park Service and protects for future generations the
scenery, natural and historic objects, and wildlife. Babbitt has
directed his agency's Solicitor's Office to decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is expected to reverberate throughout the country _
perhaps opening parks to hunting of caribou in Alaska, desert
bighorn sheep in Arizona and elk in California, Washington and New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' said Sam Henderson, superintendent of
the Wupatki, Walnut Canyon and Sunset Crater monuments in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at Hopi who were friends were suddenly pointing the
fingers at us, the bad guys, and we pride ourselves in our
relationships with Native American groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these monuments are islands of wildness in America saved
for future generations. In another 200 years, maybe these islands
will be there in their original shape as primitive as they are
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other park superintendents await the decision. The Hualapai have
talked about hunting bighorn sheep and deer in the Grand Canyon
National Park. Shoshone and other groups have wanted to open
buffalo hunting in Yellowstone National Park. In California's
Redwood National Park, the Yurok have asked about hunting elk and
deer, and the Quinault wish to hunt in the Olympic National Park in
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past years, the National Park Service has interpreted
the Organic Act to mean prohibiting hunting, killing, wounding,
frightening, capturing or attempting to capture animals in national
parks. There are few exceptions, one of them Grand Teton National
Park in Wyoming. When it expanded by two-thirds to 305,000 acres in
1950, park advocates had to compromise by allowing cattle grazing,
private property and an airport in the park, and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Department spokeswoman Stephanie Hanna said the
decision from the Solicitor's Office could come in weeks and
certainly before the end of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The decision might involve only the Wupatki case. But Interior
Department officials indicate that they may recommend broader
regulations, driven by Babbitt, affecting many other parks and
monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough issue, because the Park Service's policy nationwide
``has been no take of animals from national parks,'' Hanna said.
``The role is generally to provide an unthreatened environment for
wildlife so they're behaving the way they would in the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Wupatki situation presents an agonizing choice, Hanna
said. Interior may have to look at the different language in the
legislation that formed each park and at Indian treaties, which may
open a greater range of activities.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of talk disturbs environmental groups that hold the
parks inviolate as the last haven for nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new policy coming down from the Solicitor's Office of the
Interior Department has the potential to change nearly 85 years of
precedent,'' said Frank Buono, a former Park Service employee and a
member of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, a
nonprofit group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The group cites 13 parks where American Indians seek to take or
hunt animals, and 12 parks where it found that such requests could
be reasonably anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are places that people go with their families to see
wildlife in their natural state,'' Buono said. ``They don't expect
to encounter people with guns, traps and bows and arrows killing
animals. If we say that the Organic Act that made the Park Service
didn't have to strictly protect all the animals, and we can permit
some sustainable level of taking or hunting, then the very
fundamental character that distinguishes our parks and monuments
from all other public land will be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Kaye, chief of staff for Hopi Chairman Wayne Taylor, said
the eagle, the red-tailed hawk and other birds played an essential
role in religious and cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should recognize that just as for any other peoples'
religion, this is our religion,'' Kaye said. ``We have a strong
system of religious beliefs, and the survival of our existence
depends on these beliefs. Our survival depends on these birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was the Spanish that came here, then the churches.
Then the federal government tried to stop our religious practices.
Now people are continuing trying to stop us by saying Hopi
shouldn't gather eagles. It's just another way of driving Indians
out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Simon, Southwest regional director of the nonprofit
National Parks Conservation Association in Albuquerque, said a
change in Park Service policy would be so important, so enormous
and so precedent-setting that Congress, rather than the Interior
Department, should consider it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is too big and carries too much significance to
be made solely by an administration, particularly with as little
time left that there is in this one,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard from our members on this topic. They are very
sympathetic to the Native American issues,'' he said. ``But by and
large, the response has been nearly unanimous that they are
concerned about killing of the animals in highly protected places
like national parks. They are concerned that it might mean similar
activities in parks near and dear to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
