<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES TO PROVIDE BENEFITS TO EMPLOYEES' PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Talk about an ironic sight: A room packed with
gay journalists, leaping to their feet to applaud an organization
not noted for its sexual radicalism _ Dow Jones &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones, publisher of the conservative Wall Street Journal,
will award domestic partner benefits to its employees regardless of
sexual orientation, the newspaper's managing editor, Paul Steiger,
told the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association meeting
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits allow the companions of homosexual employees to
receive or be beneficiaries of benefits that would normally be
accorded to a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing numbers of companies are offering such benefits to
all unmarried partners of employees, straight or homosexual, who
can provide some proof of a lasting relationship, such as a joint
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco audience hissed when informed that the NBC
television network and its owner, the General Electric Co., are
dragging their feet on the domestic partners issue. NBC is the last
of the four major networks not to provide such benefits to its
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Madison, NBC's vice president of diversity, sharply
questioned its domestic partners policy during her speech at the
conference, which ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Madison said that she already has appealed to NBC to extend
domestic partner benefits to all employees, and that she plans
further meetings with corporate executives. She drew a big laugh
when she added caustically that she wasn't satisfied with their
responses to date: ``I'm not sure I believe they're rational.''
</P>
<P>
   The first report about Dow Jones' decision was broken by a
Columbia University graduate student journalist, Alex Cerniglia,
31. He reported it in a newsletter, Digital Reporter Print Edition.
On Saturday, when the Wall Street Journal's Steiger, addressing the
conference, confirmed Cerniglia's story, he won a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often have you seen so many gays and lesbians stand up and
applaud the Wall Street Journal?'' said the moderator, CBS News
national correspondent Jeffrey Kofman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
