 ATTN: Travel Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Travel section for use Sunday, Sept. 17, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `t') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE-AFTERDARK (Undated) _ Report from New York Times
correspondents on some of the hottest nightspots in Europe this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER (London) _ Want a big theatrical success?
Hire yourself a celebrity, preferably a film star. This blunt
wisdom has recently brought Kevin Spacey, Cate Blanchett, Nicole
Kidman and others to London, and, with Jerry Hall replacing
Kathleen Turner as the seductive Mrs. Robinson, is currently
ensuring that an adaptation of ``The Graduate'' is packing the
Gielgud Theater. And the trend is set to continue this fall. By
Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM (Undated) _ As Dutch as tulips and considerably
more fun, bicycles _ or fietsen, as they're called in Amsterdam _
are ideally suited to the brick-paved canal streets of the old
central city and to the flat landscape surrounding the urban area.
They're everywhere: chained to bridges, parked by the hundreds
outside Central Station, rolling steadily by (often with one or two
small passengers aboard) as you sit in outdoor cafes. By Judith
Yarnall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE-AIRPORTS (Paris) _ The fatal crash of a supersonic
Concorde northeast of Paris on July 25 has renewed debate over the
construction of a third major airport to serve the French capital.
The fact that the Concorde could easily have come down on top of a
small town, with even more than the four deaths that resulted among
people on the ground, is also raising questions about the safety of
existing airports in or near cities, about their further
development and about the location of future airports elsewhere in
Europe. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Reading the fine print on package
deals. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: One of the world's largest
exhibitions of the work of the jeweler and goldsmith Peter Carl
Faberge has opened at the Riverfront Arts Center in Wilmington,
Del. ``Faberge'' features more than 1,000 works from museums and
private collections, including objects from the State Hermitage
Museum in St. Petersburg and the Moscow Kremlin Museums that have
never been seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Items: By train to the Redwoods; Sailing
in Greece and Turkey; Hiking in Switzerland. By Florence Stickney.
</P>
<P>
