<HEADLINE>
GAP LOSES SOME OF ITS LUSTER AS SALES DIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When everyone wants to be in vests, as in last
year's ubiquitous ``Everybody in Vests'' campaign, it looks great
on Gap Inc.'s bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But when everyone doesn't, it can get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Gap's sales have tumbled, and the stock has
taken a nosedive, closing at $23.88 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's sales drop at Gap's Old Navy franchise was
especially disturbing since the chain has been Gap's main growth
vehicle and was responsible for 35 percent of the San
Francisco-based retailer's sales of $11.6 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Why in this strong economy and during the back-to-school season
is Gap, once a darling of retail stocks, faltering?
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers have decided maybe everybody doesn't want to be in
leather. Or cargo pants. Or polar fleece.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sanghera, 23, and her sister, Sharon, 19, of London were
shopping at a Gap in San Francisco but did not buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make clothes for casual, everyday wear. But the sort of
prices they have aren't everyday,'' Jay Sanghera said.
</P>
<P>
   August sales at Gap stores opened at least a year dropped 14
percent, compared to an 8 percent increase for the same month a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking that down by its three divisions, Gap's namesake stores
dropped about 5 percent; its higher end Banana Republic brand
dipped 3 percent, and 6-year-old Old Navy skidded 25 percent,
according to analysts at Thomas Weisel Partners and company
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap store figures compare with a 3 percent drop in sales in
August 1999. Banana Republic and Old Navy numbers were pitted
against tough comparisons of 15 and 18 percent increases,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The more recent results followed the release of Gap's
second-quarter earnings report, which showed a 6 percent decline in
earnings to $184 million compared to $194 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gap wasn't the only retailer to hit a rough patch last month.
J.C. Penney Co., trendy Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Co. and Dillard's Inc.
all reported sales declines.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the retailers who fumbled this season were busy trying
to come up with outside explanations for why the season suffered _
the weather, decreased consumer confidence and increased debt, and
the greater number of year-round schools and schools that require
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Gap executives have blamed the problems on
weaker-than-anticipated back-to-school traffic, heavy markdowns,
inventory problems at Old Navy and an unsuccessful campaign that
concentrated on in-store promotions rather than television ads.
</P>
<P>
   While some of those excuses may be valid, David Szymanski,
director of the Center for Retailing Studies at Texas A&AMP;M
University, said they are just that _ excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too hot, too cold. It rained, it didn't rain. It's
always the Lord's working that keeps us from being successful,''
Szymanski said. ``Unfortunately, the Gap's numbers are really down,
but some of the other retailers aren't doing so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those retailers who did well happened to be Gap
competitors. Same-store sales at the Limited Inc. rose 6 percent,
buoyed by an impressive 15 percent leap at its Express division.
American Eagle Outfitters Inc. beat analysts' expectations with a
9.1 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean Millard ``Mickey'' Drexler, Gap's chief
executive, has lost the Midas touch that has made Gap one of the
most widely recognized and respected specialty retailers?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gap is in a period of adjustment. Mickey Drexler is too
smart, too good. The organization is too strong,'' said Abbey
Doneger, president of the Doneger Group, a New York-based
merchandise consultancy. ``They will fix their business in short
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Retail consultants and analysts attribute the company's
performance to problems with its fashions. Shoppers apparently
don't want Gap's hot pink Capri pants or, on the other extreme,
many of the company's monochromatic offerings.
</P>
<P>
   On the Old Navy side, the company may have skewed so far in
favor of its youthful audience with its techno/rave-like styles
that it alienated older shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a time when the economy is good and people are spending
money. But they're only going to spend it on things they're excited
about,'' Doneger said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Gap executives did not comment for this story.
</P>
<P>
   But in a presentation to investors at the Goldman Sachs Seventh
Annual Global Retailing Conference in New York on Thursday, Drexler
was pretty blunt about his company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our recent performance has been bad. We're unhappy about it .
. . and we're not making any excuses about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he reassured investors by saying that despite the sale
slump, ``We still have three incredibly strong, powerful brands we
feel have exciting long-term opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler said the brands, especially Old Navy, had grown so fast
that the company's infrastructure could not keep up. That led to
inventory and marketing problems as well as fashion mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be better disciplined in our businesses, and we
need to continue to take the appropriate risks,'' Drexler told
investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
