<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-DINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CITY GETS A GOLD MEDAL FOR FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Price chart at end; figures are in U.S. dollars)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some of the hot dining spots in Sydney:
</P>
<P>
   Sailors Thai: Fabulous Thai food in a Spartan setting (stone
walls and bare floors make for loud dining). Spicy? You betcha. Try
the duck soup with pickled limes; red peanuts curry of beef shank
and Thai basil; or stir-fried crispy pork with Chinese broccoli.
Reservations are recommended; also open for lunch Monday through
Friday. The restaurant is on the Rocks within the Sailors Home,
below the stairs of the Sydney Visitor's Center. $$$
</P>
<P>
   Bel Mondo: Another favorite for locals at the Rocks, this fine
Italian restaurant features fresh produce and Australian and
imported wines. A few Sydney samplers include spinach and ricotta
gnocchi with yabbies (shrimplike shellfish), burned butter and
Parmesan; quail and borlotti bean soup with mushroom crotini; and
fritto misto of Yamba king prawns with eggplant and zucchini with
garlic mayonnaise. The Manfredi family, chefs Stefano and his
mother, Franca, have taken Italian to new heights. $$$$
</P>
<P>
   MG Garage: They don't have a drive-in window, but four classic
MGs are for sale on the restaurant's floor. The food here is over
the top and defies categorizing. Maybe crazy Continental _ how else
could you explain galantine and leg ham of suckling pig cooked in
hay; bacon and herb-crumbed fillet of rabbit with liver faggots; or
braised grilled octopus with Spanish onions and potato gnocchi?
$$$$
</P>
<P>
   Ettamogah Bar &AMP; Restaurant at Darling Harbour: Tired of all the
high-dollar food that our Sydney hosts were serving up, we opted
for steak and chips one night at this chain eatery based on a
popular Australian cartoon strip. Located in the Harbourside
Festival Marketplace, the Ettamogah had cheap steaks _ $8 (U.S.)
for a T-bone with salad and fries and gravy. Other menu items
included Neber Neber Nachos for less than $5; seafood basket
featuring crab, calamari, fish and prawns for $8; and burgers. $$
</P>
<P>
   Nick's Seafood Restaurant: Overlooking Darling Harbor, this
waterside eatery offered up the true seafood lovers platter with
lobster, king prawns, crabs, fresh oysters, catch of the day
(baramundi is a favorite), calamari and steamed mussels. Menu price
is $85 Australian for two or about $50 U.S. _ and it is a feast of
the freshest seafood Sydney can offer. Nick's also has steak, lamb,
pasta and a children's menu. $$$$
</P>
<P>
   Harry's Cafe de Wheels, Cowper Wharf Roadway: Woolloomooloo is
home to this famous pie cart. Since 1945, Harry's has been renown
for its mushy peas and meat pies. Mushy peas are as bright green as
guacamole _ diners get a scoop on top of a flaky meat pie. This
local favorite is served on paper plates along the roadside near
the Australian fleet base. $
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$$ (U.S. $50 per person)
</P>
<P>
   $$$ (U.S. $20 per person)
</P>
<P>
   $$ (less than U.S. $15 per person)
</P>
<P>
   $ (less than U.S. $5 per person)
</P>
