<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SYDNEY-SHOPPING-HNS &LR;      09-11 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-SHOPPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING FOR BARGAINS IN KANGAROO LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The Saturday market in Paddington has a
distinctive feel, part flea market, part craft fair, with tables
and tents set up around St. John's Church offering all sorts of
crafts, jewelry, secondhand clothing and imports. Many products
bear the ``Australian Made'' tag with a kangaroo.
</P>
<P>
   On Oxford Street, the shops and cafes are doing booming
business. This is the high street of fashion for Sydney, with every
kind of clothing store you can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian fashion industry has a rising star in Collette
Dinnigan, who has a shop just a few blocks off Oxford Street. The
thirtysomething designer has dressed such stars as Sandra Bullock,
Cameron Diaz, Cate Blanchette, Nicole Kidman and Elle McPherson.
Dinnigan has shops in Sydney, Melbourne and London. A little beaded
dress at $2,599 (Australian) is gauzy and fun and just might be
what Kidman is wearing for a night out on the town with husband Tom
Cruise in the next People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best places for shoppers to explore, but especially
good on Saturday and Sunday, is the market at the Rocks,
practically in the shadow of the Harbour Bridge. Booths along
George Street stretch for what seems like miles under white-topped
canopies. At the Rocks Square, a jazz group plays catchy tunes
while families dine al fresco on take-out that includes Thai food
and McDonald's (the most obvious American fast-food franchise in
Sydney).
</P>
<P>
   For a thrifty traveler, there are some wonderful souvenirs at
the market: bargain opals (but know your stuff first), kangaroo and
koala images in every shape and kind of product from jewelry to
Christmas ornaments; boomerangs; Australian coins (pennies are
collectors' items since they don't use or make them anymore) and
stamps; posters of Sydney sites; and antiques. The little shops
around the market aren't forgotten by the shoppers. The festive
atmosphere is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   Other markets in Sydney include Balmain Market (Saturdays on
Darling Street), Glebe's market at Glebe Public School (Saturdays)
and the Bondi Beach Market on Bondi Public Beach at the northern
end of Campbell Parade (Sundays from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Sydney has a number of shopping arcades, from the 200 shops in
the Queen Victoria Building, which dates from 1897, to the modern
SkyGarden, a retail and office complex with more than 60 shops and
cafes. The area around Pitt Street is home to the Pitt Street Mall,
Mid City Centre, the Strand Arcade (opened in 1892) with 85 shops,
and Piccadilly on Pitt with salons, accessories, cafes and fashion
wear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SYDNEY-2TAKE-HNS &LR;      09-11 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-2TAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH OR WITHOUT OLYMPICS, SYDNEY IS A HOPPING PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Photos available at www.media.australia.com)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The kangaroo question is always jumping up.
So let's get that out the way. No, I didn't see any live ones but
there were lots of stuffed kangaroos, packaged kangaroo jerky and
more than a few pelts for sale.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't spot Mel Gibson, pet a koala, drink any Foster's beer
(not a popular brew on its home continent), play a didgeridoo (an
Aboriginal musical instrument), dive into a billabong (waterhole)
or experience a willy-willy (sudden gust of wind).
</P>
<P>
   What I did get in less than a week in the harbor city of Sydney
is a sample of what must be the friendliest host city for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism people are banking that TV viewers will see the joys
of Sydney and eventually give in to urges to head Down Under. The
Sydney Olympic Games are just the thing to whet the appetite of
travelers. While the city will look good when the cameras are
rolling for the Olympians, the sparkle won't stop when the athletes
and news media go home.
</P>
<P>
   This beautiful city was ``founded'' by convicts from British
prison ships in the 18th century. If it hadn't been for that nasty
revolution in the Colonies, the Brits would have had all of North
America to keep shipping convicts to. But in 1788, the British
government chose to use New South Wales and the fleet landed with a
motley group of petty burglars and debtors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were people inhabiting this vast land. The
Aboriginal presence in Australia goes back thousands of years. It
is only in recent years that the European descendants have
attempted reconciliation with the Aboriginal people and it wasn't
until the 1960s that Aborigines began to receive full rights of
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, the people of Sydney and Melbourne held separate
marches to show support for a national apology. Hundreds of
thousands of people walked across the Harbour Bridge in Sydney _ a
great big ``I'm sorry'' for many years of mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   GORGEOUS CITY
</P>
<P>
   Modern Sydney sparkles. In the words of Steve Irwin, Australia's
famous ``Crocodile Hunter,'' ``Sydney is gorgeous.'' The city of
4.5 million is perhaps the cleanest metropolis I've ever visited _
no graffiti and very little trash on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   And it's very friendly. The people in the service industry,
clerks in the stores and waiters/waitresses are very polite and
knowledgeable. Tipping is appreciated, but the system is not
entirely entrenched in Australia. Good service in upscale eateries
can be rewarded by ``rounding up'' (to the next dollar) when it
comes to paying the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Prices on my visit in early June were very reasonable, with
dining out a wonderful value for Americans. The Australian dollar
is worth about 58 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping in mind that the seasons are reversed south of the
Equator, early June in Sydney is cool _ mid 50s _ and it is winter.
September is spring in Australia, said to be one of the best times
to visit. Sydney is blessed with a temperate climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney lives along the beaches,'' said Robert West,
owner/operator of Sydney Greeters and Guides. From the airport we
take a winding tour through the streets of the city; we could have
taken the new train that serves the airport, but West is a terrific
guide and points out sights along the motor route.
</P>
<P>
   A former government worker, West has turned his knowledge of
Sydney and tourism to good use.
</P>
<P>
   A friendly waterfront park custodian offers the first advice in
Sydney _ skip the $20 guided harbor tour and stick to the ferries
for $4 ($2.55 U.S.) each way. Taxis are abundant, but you can't
beat the ferry on a blue-sky day for a great view of the famous
Harbour Bridge and Sydney Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Ferries, part of the public transportation system,
make regular runs among Circular Quay (pronounced key), Darling
Point, Double Bay, Rose Bay and Watsons Bay. Working people use the
ferries for their daily commute.
</P>
<P>
   The locals have dubbed Double Bay ``Double Pay'' because of the
upscale shops and homes. This is where you'll find the Ritz Carlton
and the newly rich. A short stay in Sydney is not enough time to
explore each section. Each suburb of Sydney has its own personality
_ from Darling Harbor to Woolloomooloo.
</P>
<P>
   Darlinghurst, which has been compared to New York's SoHo, began
as home to Sydney's gentry. Hard times came and it fell into
disrepute. Now guidebooks call Darlinghurst ``Sydney's all night
heartbeat.'' Boutique hotels such as the Kirketon and the Medusa
help mark its renaissance. The 40-room Kirketon was built in the
1920s as a hotel while the 18-room Medusa dates from the 1880s and
was a private home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocks _ houses and structures built near the water's edge _
was the first white settlement in Sydney, built in 1788 after the
First Fleet landed with 1,400 men, women and children from Britain.
The Sydney Visitor Center is here at 106 George St., a good stop
for a walking tour map ($1 U.S.). The center is housed in the 1864
Sailors Home, a refuge for visiting sailors in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DAY AND NIGHT LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The imposing Museum of Contemporary Art is housed in a 1930s Art
Deco building that faces the harbor. Near Circular Quay visitors
will find the Museum of Sydney _ on the site of the first
government house _ with a collection of items from Sydney's unusual
history.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
