<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV17-NY     09-11 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLURVIAN: YAGODDAPROLLEMWIDDAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 17)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What students of the New York accent now categorize as
``first-stage Slurvian'' was reported in the 1938 Federal Writers
Project ``Almanac for New Yorkers.'' An example given was
 &UR; onnafyah &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The definition of  &UR; onnafyah &LR; , as consumers of hurried meals in
Manhattan know, is ``a short order is being prepared.'' The
metaphor of a burger sizzling on the grill has since been extended
to a more general ``it'll be ready in a minute,'' whether or not
applied to food. This brings to mind another first-stage Slurvian
expression,  &UR; jeet &LR; ?, a quick way of asking someone if he has eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Slurvian is not limited to New York City. The most famous
example of slurred speech embodied in dialect is the Southern
 &UR; y'all &LR; , which has its equivalent in New York Slurvian  &UR; alluhyuz &LR; .
(That's if the emphasis is on the  &UR; all &LR; ; if the speaker wishes to
stress the plural  &UR; you &LR; , the phrase becomes  &UR; alluhyooz &LR; .) And in
California,  &UR; g'yonit &LR;  signifies ``get on it,'' meaning ``get
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   These amalgams and other familiar interrogatory compressions _
 &UR; tsamatta &LR; ?,  &UR; hootoadjadat &LR; ?,  &UR; whaddyanutz &LR; ? _ have no meaning
other than the phrases when separated: ``What's the matter? Who
told you that? What are you, nuts?'' Of greater semantic interest
are the phrases that gain a separate sense when deliberately
slurred. We will now consider ``second-stage Slurvian.''
</P>
<P>
   Linguists will not soon forget  &UR; fuggedaboudit &LR; . Although the
transliteration of the New Yorkese phrase has appeared on T-shirts
around the country, the expression is not being dropped by Noo
Yawkiz, which so often happens when a dialect phrase becomes
adopted by outsiders. That is because the slurred words do not mean
only the literal ``forget about it''; rather, the phrase is
second-stage Slurvian for ``don't bother me with that'' or a more
figurative ``it'll be a cold day in hell before I buy that
cockamamie notion.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Slurvian synonym to  &UR; fuggedaboudit &LR;  is
 &UR; gedaddaheeuh &LR; , which long ago lost its initial meaning of ``leave
the premises'' and now conveys disbelief shot through with an
abiding disdain. Standing alone,  &UR; gedaddaheeuh &LR;  means ``I don't
believe you'' or the more vivid ``don't give me that baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   But when used in the start of a sentence like `` &UR; Gedaddaheeuh &LR; 
wid yer fancy talk,'' the disbelief turns to vehement rejection, in
the sense of ``I vigorously reject your highfalutin language.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of the compressed phrase is no longer the sum of its
individual words; the compressed phrase conveys a meaning all its
own. Another example of the semantic change called ``figurative
extension'' that grew out of New York speedspeech is  &UR; noprollem &LR; ,
which originally meant ``I can do it easily'' but now can be a
modest response to gratitude with the primary sense of ``you're
welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Derision at such elision is misplaced. The University of
Pennsylvania's William Labov, whose classic 1966 study, ``The
Social Stratification of English in New York City,'' demonstrated
that the city is a melting pot of various dialects, should be
delighted. (I have been unable to pinpoint the locale of
 &UR; gerareheeuh &LR; , a variant of  &UR; gedaddaheeuh &LR; ; fresh street research
is needed.)
</P>
<P>
   The lexicographer Sol Steinmetz notes that the Brooklyn accent
differs from Noo Yawkese: `` &UR; Oily boid &LR;  is Brooklynese,'' he says,
``as any Manhattanite or Bronxite will inform you in no unsoyten
toyms. There is no standard New York pronunciation of words like
 &UR; car &LR; ,  &UR; bad &LR;  and  &UR; off &LR; . What we think of as `New Yorkese' is the
least prestigious of the various social dialects, or the one that
differs or deviates most from standard American English. That is
why New York speech has a low prestige even among its own
speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off &LR; . I just pronounced that as I wrote it, and it sounded like
``awf,'' as in  &UR; awful &LR; , not like ``off'' as in  &UR; offal &LR; . For help on
this, I turned to the pronunciation maven Charles Harrington
Elster, author of ``Is There a Cow in Moscow?'' (Yes, but there is
no  &UR; zoo &LR;  in zo-ology.)
</P>
<P>
   ``New York tawk features a diphthongal  &UR; aw &LR;  sound,'' Elster
observes, ``that in heavy New Yorkese sounds almost disyllabic.''
(Before a Parisian reader of this column in The International
Herald Tribune expostulates,  &UR; Gedaddaheeuh &LR;   &UR; avec ton baratin &LR; ,''
let me translate. A  &UR; diphthong &LR;  is the gliding sound of combining
vowels, as in the  &UR; oy &LR;  in the head-smacking Yiddish  &UR; oy veh &LR; .
 &UR; Disyllabic &LR;  means ``having two syllables.'') ``It's impossible for
me to transliterate this elongated  &UR; aw &LR;  here, but ask a
dyed-in-the-wool New Yorker to pronounce  &UR; dog &LR;  and  &UR; coffee &LR;  and
you'll come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers are also renowned  &UR; r &LR; -droppers,'' Elster says.
``Day eat wid a  &UR; fawk &LR; , day walk onna  &UR; flaw &LR; , an day drink adda
 &UR; bah &LR; . The superintendent of their apartment building is  &UR; da
soopuh &LR; , and The New York Times is  &UR; da paypuh &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   He agrees that ``their propensity for slurvy pronunciation can
sometimes be nothing short of miraculous. When I lived in New York,
I remember how conductors on the Long Island Rail Road managed to
slur the name of a certain station, Woodside, into the
unintelligible  &UR; wuss-eye &LR;  (the eye of a wuss?).''
</P>
<P>
   BIG APPLESOURCE
</P>
<P>
   Controversy rages over who coined ``the Big Apple'' as a moniker
for New York.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest citation is in Edward Martin's 1909 book, ``The
Wayfarer in New York.'' Martin, a founder of the Harvard Lampoon
and first editor of the humor magazine Life, was writing about the
attitude of the Midwest toward the metropolis: ``Kansas is apt to
see in New York a greedy city .... It inclines to think that the
big apple gets a disproportionate share of the national sap.''
</P>
<P>
   The Random House Historical Dictionary of American Slang notes
an absence of capitalization or quotation marks in this citation
and thinks it ``probable that the 1909 quotation represents a
metaphorical or perhaps proverbial usage, rather than a concrete
example of the later slang term.'' I dunno about that;
capitalization is not necessary in coinage, and quotation marks
only would suggest an earlier use.
</P>
<P>
   The etymologist Barry Popik, with fresh support from the phrase
detectives Fred Shapiro and Gerald Cohen, has long been campaigning
to give coinage honors to John J. Fitzgerald, a turf writer. He
wrote in The New York Morning Telegraph on Feb. 18, 1924: ``There's
only one  &UR; Big Apple &LR; . That's New York.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fitzgerald popularized the term, crediting it to
African-American stable hands in New Orleans in 1920, the columnist
Walter Winchell picked it up in 1927. A decade later it became the
name of a Harlem nightclub and a dance.
</P>
<P>
   Popik makes a strong case, but I'd credit Martin with coinage
and Fitzgerald with independent recoinage and early popularization.
But you pays yer money and you takes yer cherce (from an 1846
cartoon in the British magazine Punch).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
