<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SYDNEY-2NDTAKE-HNS &LR;      09-11 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 SYDNEY: Australia: x x x unusual history.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1840 Customs House is now home to the (free) Object
Galleries, a showcase for Australian craft and design; (free) City
Exhibition Space; and a 1:500 scale model of the city (growing
daily), plus cafes, bars and a restaurant. Outside Customs House,
in a plaza smack dab in the middle of central Sydney, you might be
entertained by street performers plying their craft _ from fire
eaters to acrobats.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Darling Harbor, the free evening laser show (Wednesday
through Sunday), ``A Fish Opera,'' vies for visitor attention with
street performers such as a young woman who throws a flaming baton.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish Opera audience is rewarded with a wonderful show mixing
whimsy of laser-light fish singing opera classics with the voices
of famous opera legends such as Luciano Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas came to Sydney in 1997 with the opening of the Star
City casino, a 24-hour gambling operation at Darling Harbor. Run by
the government, Star City seems more Disney (the art looks like a
spillover from ``The Little Mermaid'') than Vegas (and no tipping
allowed in the casino) _ funky neon and fake palm trees, Aboriginal
art, huge fish tanks and wandering costumed dancers performing on
stilts. You won't hear the bells, clanging and loud slot machines
heard at Vegas or Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   If the lure of the sea is strong, or maybe if sailing is in your
blood, there are a number of ways to enjoy the waters around
Sydney. EastSail offers ``drive-yourself'' and skippered boats.
Daylong excursions around the harbor include a sumptuous seafood
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Our group of American and Canadian journalists set sail on one
of the coldest days in June with winds up to 38 knots _ not the
best introduction to sailing Australian waters, but skipper Steve
``Smiley'' Pyne kept his good humor. Pyne, a 40ish dead ringer for
ex-Monty Pythonite Michael Palin, pointed out sites such as Pinch
Cut Island and Fort Dennison, built during the Crimean War.
</P>
<P>
   We sailed the 40-foot Madeline, protected from the rain and wind
with full rubber sailing suits. Despite the choppy waters and the
chill, we enjoyed the platters of seafood (shrimp, prawns, squid),
meat, bread, cheese and fruit. The cost of the three-hour cruise
for eight with lunch was about $500 (U.S.). EastSail is located at
Rushcutters Bay at D'Albora Marina, five minutes from the city
center.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Bounty'' sailed by as we cruised the harbor. Built for the
1978 movie starring Gibson, Australia's favorite son, the replica
sets sail twice daily for lunch and dinner Monday through Friday
and three times a day on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $31 (no meal) to $58 for a dinner cruise, per
person, with children 12 and younger charged 40 percent off adult
prices (all U.S.). Passengers are allowed to help the crew hoist
the sail and steer the ship, just as Capt. William Bligh's crew did
more than 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other cruises around Sydney, operating from Circular Quay,
include Capt. Cook Cruises, Vagabond Cruises and Matilda Cruises.
Each operates 1 1/2-to-2 1/2-hour cruises with tea, lunch or
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to enjoy Sydney Harbour is from the top of the
Harbour Bridge. Begun in 1923 and completed in 1931, the bridge
connects Kirribilli with the city.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years it has been all the rage to walk to the top of
the bridge, some 442 feet above sea level, and look out over the
harbor (and eight lanes of traffic on the bridge below). The walk
takes three hours from the start at Bridge Climb headquarters, 5
Cumberland in the Rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Climbers wear a special ``BridgeSuit'' (let's not call them jump
suits) and are attached to a static line. They walk to the top of
the arch and get a photo taken by a member of the company's staff
(climbers may not carry anything, even a camera) before returning
to base the same way. Cost of the day climb is about $68 (U.S.) for
adults and $56 for children 12-16.
</P>
<P>
   Night climbs are available Thursday through Saturday and
reservations are necessary. Check the Web at www.bridgeclimb.com.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   THE OPERA HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Opera House, home to opera, ballet and dance, is one
of the most recognizable landmarks in Australia. Jutting on
Bennelong Point like white shells on the water, the opera house was
completed in 1973 after 14 years at a cost of $59 million (U.S.).
</P>
<P>
   Guided tours are conducted daily Monday through Friday for $7.50
for adults and $5 for students. On Sunday a market selling
Australian-made arts and crafts is held near the front entrance.
</P>
<P>
   I may not have spotted the real Mel Gibson, but the reel Gibson
may be just the ticket at the newly opened (fall '99) Fox Studios
Australia. His name is on the marquee and a larger-than-life poster
of Mel stands near the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Studios Australia combines theme park fun with a working
movie studio on the edge of Sydney's Central Business District. In
scale, though, this is no Disney/MGM.
</P>
<P>
   Bent Street, the area around the studio, is a free pedestrian
mall with shopping, movie theaters, cafes, bars and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The Backlot comprises eight experiences and attractions _ the
best of which is James Cameron's ``Titanic: the Experience.''
Visitors line up to be ``extras'' on the movie, but that's where
fact and fiction meld. The special effects are outstanding and the
movie memorabilia is a treat for fans of the blockbuster film.
</P>
<P>
   An insider's secret: There are two lines at the entrance, one
group will ``sink'' and one will ``survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at Fox, visitors are entertained by roaming bands of
costumed actors, can walk through the ``Babe'' set, enjoy a goofy
show called ``Lights! Camera! Chaos!,'' experience a cartoon
adventure with ``The Simpsons Down Under'' and see a showcase of
film costumes and props. Backlot admission ranges from $13 (U.S.)
for kids 6 to 15 to $22 for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is hopping, that's for sure. You don't have to see a
kangaroo to know that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Cooper's e-mail address is jcooper(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
