<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VA-SENATE12-COX     09-11 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-SENATE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PERSONABLE EX-GOVERNOR RAISES GOP SENATE HOPES IN VIRGINIA
 &HT;    830&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Va. _ ``My daughter likes 'N Sync, too,'' declared
George Allen, recognizing the faces on the T-shirt of 11-year-old
Caitlin Mooney.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a political heartbeat, the Republican senatorial
candidate steered a conversation with Caitlin's parents through
teen music to soccer to horseback riding to public education to why
they should vote for him in the race against the Commonwealth's
incumbent Democrat, Chuck Robb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically Republicans anyway,'' Caitlin's dad, Rob
Mooney, said afterwards. ``And he did a lot for the schools (as
governor).''
</P>
<P>
   The personable Allen, 48, is the father of three pre-teen
children and connected easily with the young families awaiting
turns on the Tilt-a-Whirl and Ferris wheel at the town carnival in
this suburb of the nation's capital. But populous and affluent
Northern Virginia is the only region of the state where Robb, 61,
leads in his quest for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The race features two popular former governors _ Virginia's
dominant political figures in recent years _ and has national
implications in the struggle over control of the Senate. Losing
Robb's seat would hurt the Democrats' chances of winning back a
majority. However, Republicans need an Allen victory to offset
their likely loss of the Georgia seat that was held by the late
Sen. Paul Coverdell, and now is filled by Sen. Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Washington Post poll showed Allen leading Robb by 53
percent to 45 percent among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, Virginia has become perhaps the most
Republican of Southern states. The last presidential candidate to
carry the Commonwealth was Robb's father-in-law, Lyndon Baines
Johnson, in 1964. The Post poll showed George W. Bush with a
nine-point lead over Al Gore in this year's presidential race.
Republicans hold all statewide offices and a majority in both
houses of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robb is the last Democrat left standing in Virginia,'' said
Robert Holsworth, a political science professor and director of
Center for Public Policy at Virginia Commonwealth University in
Richmond. ``In all of the '90s, there was only one race where the
Democrat got more than 50 percent of the statewide vote'' _ Don
Beyer for lieutenant governor in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Robb won re-election in 1994 with only 46 percent of the
vote. Republicans were bitterly divided over the party's nomination
of Oliver North, the Iran-contra figure who became a conservative
radio and TV commentator. Republican Sen. John Warner refused to
back North and instead campaigned for Marshall Coleman, a longtime
Republican who ran as an independent. Nancy Reagan also spoke out
against North, who ended up with 43 percent of the vote. Coleman
got 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver North was the ultimate polarizer,'' recalled Larry
Sabato, a University of Virginia professor and expert on Virginia
politics. ``But nearly 55 percent of the vote was anti-Robb.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Robb has stubbornly survived in a GOP state for 20
years since he was elected lieutenant governor in 1981 and governor
four years later. By law, Virginia's governors cannot serve
successive terms, but Robb easily won the 1988 Senate race. A
former Marine captain who served in Vietnam and married a
presidential daughter, Lynda Bird Johnson, he has served notice
that Allen is in for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me assure you, no warrior I ever met at Quantico was
frightened by big talk, big-heeled boots or a big chew of tobacco _
and neither am I,'' promised Robb at his campaign kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``With your help, and a little luck, maybe right after the
campaign is over, we can get George a TV talk show in the time slot
right next to Ollie North,'' Robb told supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen _ who is fond of cowboy boots and an occasional pinch
of snuff, and loves country music as well _ also has an engaging
personal history. He is the son of the late George Allen, who
coached the Washington Redskins, among other NFL teams, and he
played quarterback for the University of Virginia Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen is a better campaigner,'' said Holsworth. ``He's more
engaging and connects better with people than Robb does.''
</P>
<P>
   Political handicappers say Allen has the easier road to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is going to carry Virginia, and ``given the Republican
strength in the legislature, you have to make him the favorite,''
said Merle Black, an Emory University professor and expert on
Southern politics. ``But Robb's not out of it by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Running in a Republican state against ``a popular, well-known
recent governor, Robb is already behind the eight ball,'' said
Sabato. ``But is it possible that he can win? Sure, if there's a
record turnout of African Americans and Gore wins nationally by a
margin so large as to make even Virginia close. Otherwise, I can't
see Robb winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Holsworth sees three possible outcomes: An Allen landslide. A
narrow Allen win. Or Robb eking out a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little margin for error in the Robb campaign,''
said Holsworth.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, as nationally, education is a key issue.
</P>
<P>
   Robb is running a TV spot featuring Kathryn Scruggs, a teacher
in Arlington, sitting in what appears to be a classroom and
questioning Allen's commitment to education. ``As governor, he
vetoed class size reduction,'' she warns.
</P>
<P>
   However, Allen quickly responded with a spot showing him sitting
casually with his wife and kids. ``Isn't it absurd what some people
say just to stay in Washington?'' he says. ``Heck, our own children
attend public schools. Just like you, Susan and I want them to get
a quality education.''
</P>
<P>
   Robb wants to portray Allen as being too conservative for
Virginia, but it won't be as easy as it was with North.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has proposed a $1,000-per-child federal tax credit for
school expenses such as computers and tutoring, but not private
school tuition. Robb called it a ``back-door voucher'' that would
divert federal funds from classrooms, but the Washington Post poll
showed the proposal is popular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   More TV spots attacking Allen are likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once voters focus on the issues on the campaign, they will
clearly see Allen's effort to re-invent himself as a fuzzy, cuddly
moderate is a complete sham,'' said Craig Bieber, a spokesman for
the Virginia Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But wearing his trademark cowboy boots and casual clothes, Allen
mingled comfortably with the families at the carnival. Vienna is
the birthplace of America Online, and many residents work in the
Internet industries located nearby. Successive Republican
administrations, Allen said, have helped the state become ``the
Silicon Dominion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired of Senator Robb,'' said Anders Warga, a
computer programmer, holding the leash of her pug Freya, who wore a
doggy jacket saying ``Repuglicans for Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's associated with a lot of the stances of the Clinton-Gore
administration and that's not something we view favorably,'' he
said. ``And Allen had a solid record as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.robb2000.org, www.Allen2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
