<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-THESTREETCOM-CRAMER-N     09-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THESTREETCOM-CRAMER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOWPOKE MARKET MAY BE WITH US FOR A WHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Financial Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from TheStreet.com, the
premier business/finance Web site, is available from the New York
Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By JAMES J. CRAMER  
 c.2000 TheStreet.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It still seems like summer. Everything is in that same
slow-motion cadence that the market adopted in June. Usually, at
this time, the phone would be ringing and people would be
highlighting merchandise and research calls. Instead, it's dead.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's beginning to dawn on people that the slowdown in
our business isn't going away as fast as it came. The lack of
enthusiasm for the markets lingers like a bad baseball team
suffering through the conclusion of an awful campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? What went wrong? I think people are beginning to
figure out that this is a hard game. The free money from the IPOs
is gone. The mindless buying of Nasdaq stocks no longer makes you
any money. Many of our favorites _ Dell, Microsoft, Cisco and
Applied Materials _ have stopped making you money. For now. While
the stench of the dot-com world refuses to go away.
</P>
<P>
   I hear it when I spend time with folks I don't know well. The
conversation rarely gets steered to the market anymore. Because
people aren't making any money in the market. So what happens? How
does the ennui end?
</P>
<P>
   I have bad news on that score. It was the euphoria that was
misplaced, not the ennui. Before the dot-com revolution, the stock
market often lacked excitement or enthusiasm. It was often a place
where people understood that there was limited opportunity and lots
of danger.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of putting stock scores up at the ballpark would have
seemed silly in those times. The notion of watching the tape would
turn on only the biggest geeks and those with much too much time on
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, we would have bursts of excitement and enthusiasm
and profits would be made. But for the most part, the game was,
well, boring. It's boring right now. We can't hope it gets
interesting. We need some leadership, some strength in a couple of
groups to make the stock market intriguing again.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it will keep feeling like summer. Which is how it
used to be all year round.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   (James J. Cramer is manager of a hedge fund and co-founder of
TheStreet.com. At time of publication, his fund was long Microsoft,
Dell and Cisco. His fund often buys and sells securities that are
the subject of his columns, both before and after the columns are
published, and the positions that his fund takes may change at any
time. Under no circumstances does the information in this column
represent a recommendation to buy or sell stocks. Cramer's writings
provide insights into the dynamics of money management and are not
a solicitation for transactions. While he cannot provide investment
advice or recommendations, he invites you to comment on his column
at jjcletters(at)thestreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
