<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKEBUILDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CRAFTSMAN CREATES BICYCLES FOR RIDERS OF ALL SIZES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JOHN AUSTIN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Boyd Atherton knew he was building a better
bicycle when he went to work on Tina McMillan's $900 custom job,
but the little rig turned out to be more than just a set of wheels
for her.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, McMillan, a Fort Worth stockbroker with dwarfism and an
inseam of only 13 inches, had never ridden a bicycle that she could
operate safely or comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, who cannot make a fist because of joint problems
related to her dwarfism, could not work conventional hand brakes,
straddle a child's bike properly, or find one that rolled on
anything but hard rubber tires. Then Atherton made her a mountain
bike with a frame she could mount, a curb-high crankshaft,
adjustable hand brakes and a seven-speed hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every challenge that we ran into, he figured out a way to get
around it,'' McMillan said, describing her custom bike, which
Atherton powder-coated and painted purple for the Texas Christian
University alumna. ``It was great. I can't even describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Atherton has become a big wheel in the small world of custom
bike building by catering to little people, many of whom have
physical and medical conditions that make access to cycling hard to
come by.
</P>
<P>
   His niche hasn't made him rich, but the 31-year-old Arlington
craftsman is on a roll that shows no sign of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy this,'' said Atherton, a muscular 5-foot-7-inch former
Fort Worth Country Day School wrestler who began racing and
tinkering with bikes when he was a child. ``You wouldn't believe
the satisfaction I get from doing the small bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan isn't the only dwarf _ a term accepted by many members
of the Little People of America to refer to people who inherit one
or more of more than 200 bone disorders _ who is a happy Atherton
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Grade-school friend Verne Troyer, who played ``Mini-Me'' in the
second ``Austin Powers'' movie, was his first client. Atherton
crafted a bantam 13-pounder for his buddy, who stands about 32
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``His other bike, he could only go 8 or 9 miles per hour,''
Atherton said. ``He's done 18 or 19 on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Troyer explained that many dwarfs avoid jogging because of joint
problems, and, consequently, have difficulty getting a good
cardiovascular workout.
</P>
<P>
   Troyer is having his bicycle shipped to California after a new
paint job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall quality is just enormous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was during a visit with Troyer at a Little People of America
convention in Dallas in 1991 that Atherton gained not only many new
customers but also a new career.
</P>
<P>
   Atherton, a Texas Wesleyan University marketing student, was
wondering how best to combine his skills and interests in a
satisfying post-college job when the light bulb went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little people were asking me where I could get a bike for
them,'' said Atherton, who spends his off-time racing bikes at
meets across the country. ``I told them to go to the guy who makes
bikes for little people.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that there was no such guy. But the market was
there. Little People spokeswoman Cara Egan said that while her
organization lists about 7,000 members, including some average-size
people, there may well be 10 times that many Americans with some
form of dwarfism.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with dwarfism come in all shapes and sizes,'' Egan
said. ``There are a lot of mobility issues with dwarfism.''
</P>
<P>
   A conventional bicycle crank is too long for Atherton's typical
4-foot-tall customer, and little people often have problems even
finding a frame that they can straddle. Many also need custom
features, such as the crutch hangers that Atherton built into a
bike for a Florida customer who cannot walk far without support. He
can also install a beer opener like the one on his own bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Working out of his garage beginning in 1996, Atherton has moved
the business to a south Arlington industrial warehouse, where he
runs a one-man operation.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are lined with tools, light-weight aluminum frames and
photos of smiling customers, including McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely difficult to buy a bike off the rack,'' said
McMillan, who is now 30 years old. ``They're not proportioned
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs are so short that I had to lean from side to side'' on
her old bike, which was a child's model Huffy, McMillan said. ``I'd
never had a bicycle that didn't have hard rubber tires before.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a custom bicycle is more expensive than a standard
model.
</P>
<P>
   Atherton's hand-built creations start at $735 for a steel-frame
cruiser. For a cruiser/mountain bike in steel with a seven-speed
internal hub and easy-to-use thumb shifter, the price is $885.
Aluminum frames add $300, and metallic paint can add $100.
</P>
<P>
   Atherton welds the steel frames himself. He farms out the
scandium-aluminum welding to Grand Prairie experts who build jet
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   To customize the cranks, Atherton trims a conventional model,
cuts new threads and re-mills the metal to fit the pedals. It seems
that there is always a convention to travel to, a customer to fit
or a race to make. Atherton figures he will crank out about 80
bikes this year, and he wearily acknowledges that he needs a
helper.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, who lives near Washington, D.C., has an order in for an
Atherton bicycle but knows it will be next year before she gets it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just line up because he'll take measurements and
videos,'' Egan said. ``He's been very good to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Atherton, who also makes bikes for average-size
folks, isn't backpedaling in his commitment to his clients, large
or small, or on finding challenges. He aspires to craft a
hand-powered cycle and also wants to make a tandem model for a pair
of little people. Then there's the 6-foot-7-inch, 425-pound
prospective customer who called recently.
</P>
<P>
   Large or small, Atherton tries to fit them all. Atherton
particularly likes to work on cycles for children whose dwarfism
leaves them unable to enjoy the kind of childhood that he had, full
of biking with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about helping somebody,'' Atherton said. ``Every kid
wants to get on a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
