<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      09-11 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Md.)  By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bouncing Buckyball
</P>
<P>
   To the list of remarkable properties of those single-molecule
spheres of carbon atoms known as buckyballs can be added another:
They bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley and the
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory have controlled the movement
of a buckyball by making it the centerpiece of a tiny transistor.
(Buckyballs consist of 60 carbon atoms and are more formally called
buckminsterfullerenes, in honor of the inventor of the geodesic
dome, which has the same kind of structure.)
</P>
<P>
   In a typical transistor, like those found by the millions on a
computer chip, a voltage from a gate electrode controls the current
that flows between two other electrodes, known as the source and
drain, across a semiconducting material. In the Berkeley
transistor, a buckyball sits between the source and drain
electrodes, and the current flows one electron at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the energy of the electron, it will either be
reflected from the buckyball (thus, the transistor is ``off'') or
it will hop across to the other electrode (the transistor is
``on,'' allowing current to flow). And at certain energies, the
researchers report in Nature, when the electron hops across, it
starts the buckyball bouncing between the electrodes.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that this coupling between the
electron's energy and the movement of the buckyball may have
eventual applications in very precise control of electron flow in
molecular-scale devices. In the meantime, bouncing buckyballs may
be a curiosity, but perhaps not a surprising one. After all, a
buckyball's structure of 12 pentagons and 20 hexagons is just like
that of a classic soccer ball.
</P>
<P>
   Tiniest Fullerene
</P>
<P>
   A sphere of 60 carbon atoms is not the smallest fullerene
possible. That distinction belongs to one made up of 20 atoms
arranged in 12 pentagons, with no hexagons. (Those who paid
attention in school know that this structure is called a
dodecahedron.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this fullerene was that no one had ever seen
it. There were even doubts that it could exist, given the strain
caused by the high degree of curvature of such a sphere.
</P>
<P>
   Those doubts have now disappeared, thanks to work by chemists in
Germany and the United States, who report in Nature that they have
produced the smallest fullerene, although only in its gas phase and
only fleetingly.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers made the molecule using dodecahedrane, which has
the right 20-carbon structure as its core but comes with hydrogen
atoms attached. By gently stripping off the hydrogen atoms in a
two-step process, they were able to produce the fullerene.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino's Child: Cholera
</P>
<P>
   El Nino has been blamed for a many things, from destruction of
million-dollar hillside homes in California to shrinking marine
iguanas on the Galapagos Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers from Cornell and the universities of Maryland,
Barcelona and London have come up with a new reason to curse El
Nino: They have linked it to cholera outbreaks in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Using mathematical models and data on cholera cases collected
over 18 years at a hospital in Dhaka, Bangladesh, the researchers
analyzed the role of climate and previous levels of the disease on
outbreak patterns. They found that cholera reached a peak every 3.7
years over the 18-year period, the same frequency as El Nino
events, in which warming waters in the eastern Pacific disrupt
weather patterns worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Cholera is caused by a bacterium that thrives in plankton in
brackish water and in estuaries. The researchers, in a report in
Science, suggest that warming of these waters caused by El
Nino-related atmospheric changes increases bacteria levels and the
risks of human contamination. They note there is an 11-month lag
between an El Nino and a rise in cholera cases, which makes sense
given that it takes time for the ocean warming in the eastern
Pacific to bring about climate changes in South Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
