<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      09-11 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.C., Md., Texas, Israel)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safety: Quick Returns to the Game and Hospital
</P>
<P>
   A three-year survey indicates that many high school and college
football players who suffer concussions are allowed to return to
competition too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, published last Wednesday in The American Journal of
Sports Medicine, also found that players who suffered concussions
raised their risk of repeating the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill, wrote that they thought those two findings were related. ``We
believe recurrences are more likely because injured players are
returning to practice and to games too quickly after blows to the
head,'' said Dr. Kevin Guskiewicz, the study's leader.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers regularly surveyed a randomly chosen sample of
242 athletic trainers, representing 17,500 football players, and
conducted phone interviews with a smaller group of trainers. From
this data they concluded that about 5 percent of players suffer a
concussion every year, with those numbers higher among high school
and small college athletes. The rates of concussions were roughly
equal on natural and artificial turf, but the injuries sustained on
artificial turf were more serious.
</P>
<P>
   They also reported that 31 percent of those who suffered
concussions began playing again the same day they were injured,
averaging only 13 minutes of rest. The researchers speculated that
this could reflect outdated practices of treating only those
concussions with the most severe symptoms seriously: Only 9 percent
of those injured lost consciousness, although 86 percent reported
headaches. ``This didn't surprise us, but it does worry us,'' said
Guskiewicz. ``You should never return to play with a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Neurologists believe that until the brain has fully recovered
from the trauma of a concussion it is more vulnerable to new,
possibly more severe injury, and Guskiewicz said the survey showed
that 15 percent of the players who suffered one concussion suffered
another one in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: A Village Visited Often by Alzheimer's
</P>
<P>
   An Arab village in Israel with unusually high rates of
Alzheimer's disease suggests that a recessive gene plays a role in
the condition, one that must be carried by both parents to take
effect, according to a new study in the journal Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers screened all elderly residents of the village, Wadi
Ara, a rural community in northern Israel. They found that 20
percent of villagers over 65 had Alzheimer's, twice the usual rate,
and 60 percent over 85 had the disease, compared to 40 percent
generally.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage between people related in some way is common among
Israeli Arabs; previous research had found that 44 percent of such
couples are fairly closely related.
</P>
<P>
   All the other genes that have been found to be related to
Alzheimer's are dominant, meaning that only one parent must carry
the gene for it to be activated. But in Wadi Ara, one of the genes
considered to be a prime risk factor for the condition was found in
the lowest levels on record, suggesting a new route for research,
according to the article, which was published Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Men, Women and Battles of the Bulges
</P>
<P>
   When men and women think about their extra poundage, they see it
in different terms, a new survey suggests: To women, the fat
embodies character flaws; to men, it's not their fault, it's those
darn business lunches.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by the Calorie Control Council, an
association of manufacturers of low-fat or low-calorie foods, found
that 41 percent of women blamed the failure of a diet on their own
lack of self-discipline, compared with 28 percent of men, and were
twice as likely to link their eating to emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation for going on diets differed as well: Almost half
of women cited their appearance as a reason to use low-calorie or
reduced-fat products, compared with about a third of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using appearance as a long-term motivation for weight loss is
not a good idea,'' said Dr. John Foreyt, director of the Nutrition
Research Clinic at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston and an
author of the survey. Putting the focus on a subjective factor that
may be beyond a woman's control can cause ``feelings of guilt and
frustration'' that may lead a woman to give up, he said. On the
other hand, he said, men need to stop denying personal
responsibility for being overweight, and to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION: Less Pacifier Use, Fewer Ear Infections
</P>
<P>
   Saving the pacifier for when a baby is trying to fall asleep may
cut down on ear infections, a new study from Finland has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies had found an association between more continuous
pacifier use and ear infections in children older than 6 months.
(Pacifiers are encouraged for babies younger than 6 months when
falling asleep, to decrease risk of sudden infant death syndrome.)
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, published last Tuesday in the journal
Pediatrics, the researchers followed 484 children after counseling
some parents about the possible harmful side effects of
overreliance on pacifiers.
</P>
<P>
   What they found, first of all, was that the counseling was
effective enough to lead to a 21 percent decrease in estimated
pacifier use.
</P>
<P>
   More important, they found that the incidence of ear infections
was 29 percent lower among children between the ages of 7 and 18
months whose pacifier use had been restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Why do pacifiers appear to lead to more ear infections? The
researchers admitted that they did not know, but speculated that
``the effect may lie in an alteration in the pressure equilibrium''
within the ear.
</P>
<P>
   CONSEQUENCES: Knee Injury in Youth and Arthritis in Age
</P>
<P>
   People who injure their knees as young adults may suffer for it
twice: Once at the time, and later on through substantially higher
rates of arthritis, according to a study that tracked more than
1,000 doctors for almost 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published Sept. 5 in The Annals of Internal Medicine,
drew on data collected from the Johns Hopkins Precursor Study
between 1948 and 1995. The lead author of the article, Dr. Allan
Gelber, said that while ``most people intuitively believe you're
more prone to arthritis if you've had a joint injury,'' proof of
this ``has been fairly slow in coming''; most earlier studies
relied on surveys asking older people with adults to recall
injuries from decades past.
</P>
<P>
   Of the subjects tracked in the Precursor study, 47 had early
knee injuries. Half of them were taking drugs for arthritis by the
end of the tracking period, a rate five times higher than among
those who had not been hurt. ``This suggests that we should
probably intervene before people develop arthritis, before symptoms
appear,'' said Gelber, ``perhaps by making greater use of braces or
giving up a certain activity altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found a link between early hip injuries and more
moderate increases in arthritis of the hip in later life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
