<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONFESSIONS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TV SERIES THAT AIRS KILLERS' CONFESSIONS DISTURBS IN
UNEXPECTED WAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Videotape of a criminal's confession is part of the public
domain after his or her trial, no matter how gruesome or
disturbing, and that makes possible a new Court TV series called
``Confessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as it should be called, America's Creepiest Videos.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which premiered Sunday as an ongoing series, takes
videotapes shot by police or prosecutors and presents them, edited
for intelligibility and succinctness but without narration,
analysis or commentary. Just real criminals explaining, in
sometimes brutal, frightening and even humorous terms, how they
raped, shot or stabbed their victims to death. Three confessions,
with each segment running eight to 10 minutes, each episode a
half-hour in length, all crimes based in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   First up in the premiere episode was Steven Smith, who described
how he and another man robbed, strangled and raped a female doctor
in her office at Bellevue Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I goes for the finger,'' Steven says, ``took one ring off.
Then took the watch, which I did not keep. John, all a sudden, he
wants to get sexual. So he immediately starts to take the woman's
clothes off. My motives was just to get the money and leave. John
had made love to the lady. I eventually grabbed the coat and
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously irritated, even personally offended by the line of
questioning from police officials we can hear but not see, Steven,
who fidgets uncontrollably and repeatedly bangs his fists on the
table, finally asks, ``Is that enough for you?''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than enough for me, but after Smith's confession is
over, we're given a bonus for sticking with it to the end: terse
text on the screen telling us that he was convicted and is serving
a sentence _ and that there's never been any proof of an accomplice
named John. This update, one supposes, is to make us feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate interviews are needed for the next criminal, Daniel
Rakowitz. In the first interview, he says he knows nothing about
the disappearance of his female roommate, but in the second, he
admits to killing her, dismembering the body, then boiling the
parts in a stewpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I punched her one time to send her back,'' says Daniel, whose
shoulder-length hair, messy beard and stories of pot-smoking put
you in mind of a burned-out hippie. He sounds exactly like Sean
Penn's character in ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High.'' ``And I hit
her in the throat. And then she fell down and started to gurgle.
And wasn't moving after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, returning from ``a pot run,'' Daniel says he
found her in the same place, still not moving. ``I touched her and
she was cold,'' Daniel tells police. ``That's when I realized she
was dead. I dissected her body totally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd you do that?'' a female voice asks, off camera.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel: ``I just started choppin' her up, cookin' her meat.''
</P>
<P>
   The third is a homeless male prostitute who stabs to death his
wheelchair-bound client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confessions'' is the creation of Richard Kroehling and Eric
Nadler, who came up with the idea after a brainstorming meeting
about possible Court TV programs with Robert M. Morgenthau, a
Manhattan district attorney. Simply making conversation, Morgenthau
had mentioned that he'd compiled dozens of videotaped confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Kroehling and Nadler knew right away what their venture would
be. Since videotapes are publicly available when the trial is
complete and the confession has been entered into court records,
they're up for grabs. Fourteen such confessions were obtained for
the program, the criteria being coherent story lines and compelling
testimony _ this is, after all, ``entertainment.'' Ten were edited
for airing.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing they have a hit on their hands, the producers have
already made arrangements for other taped confessions to be
collected from district attorney's offices in other parts of the
country. Might as well share the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more disturbing aspects of ``Confessions'' is, of
course, its exploitive nature and disrespect for the families of
all victims of crime. Another is its dishonesty. The producers use
a split screen to show images as the criminal talks, at times
setting the confession beside pictures that evoke the scene of the
crime. As the male prostitute, David Garcia, sets up for police
(and viewers) the first sexual encounter with his victim, the
screen shows two men taking a late-night stroll through the park.
Of course, this isn't the victim and perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9071 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SCOOTER-SAFETY-AR     09-11 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCOOTER-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TREND ON THE SIDEWALKS, AND IN THE EMERGENCY ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Utah, Pa., Ga.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lots of youngsters are darting through the streets and sidewalks
on shiny, foot-propelled scooters, the must-have sports item for
the under 15 set.
</P>
<P>
   They are everywhere, said Reyne Rice, director of the toy
services division of the NPD Group, a marketing information company
in Port Washington, N.Y., that tracks buying trends. Last year,
scooter volume was negligible. For the first half of this year, it
is already a $20 million business. Scooter sales are off the
charts.
</P>
<P>
   But so are injuries, according to a report issued last week by
the Consumer Product Safety Commission. The federal regulatory
agency notes that emergency-room visits for injuries related to
scooters have increased 700 percent since May. Data from the
commission show 9,400 scooter-related injuries treated in emergency
rooms so far this year, and 4,000 last month alone. These are not
your grandmother's clunky scooters from the 1950s, said Ann Brown,
the chairwoman of the commission. These models are slick,
lightweight and fast. But they are not easy to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold W. Kohl, director of the physical activity and
nutrition program at the International Life Sciences Institute,
Center for Health Promotion in Atlanta, is not surprised by the
high injury rate. This is the same thing that happened when in-line
skates were new. ``When Rollerblades first caught on,'' he said,
``you saw a spike in injuries. But once people became more skilled
and also started wearing protective gear, the injury rate was
lower. I expect the same thing to happen with the scooters.''
</P>
<P>
   Children, the primary consumers of scooters, are sustaining the
most injuries, although some intrepid adults have also climbed
aboard. The new report notes that 90 percent of injuries are to
children under 15 and nearly one-third occur in children under 8.
</P>
<P>
   The commission warns that children under 8 should not use
scooters without close adult supervision. Younger children do not
have the balance, stability or motor coordination of older
teen-agers, said Dr. Craig C. McKirgan, an orthopedic surgeon at
the Center of Orthopedics and Sports Medicine in Indiana, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 5-year-old that wants one,'' McKirgan said. ``I hate
to be the mean old dad, but I'm going to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Most injuries occur when children fall off the scooters. They
have a very narrow base, and with only two wheels, they can be
unstable, said Brown of the product safety commission. Her agency
suggests riding scooters only on smooth, paved surfaces without any
traffic and avoiding streets or surfaces with water, sand, gravel
or dirt. It is also best not to ride at night, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   The most important safety precaution, however, is to wear plenty
of protective gear, which, according to the agency, would reduce
the injury rate by 60 percent. Begin with a helmet, Brown said.
``You're already going to spend around $100 for a scooter, why not
throw in another $35 for a helmet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also recommend knee and elbow pads and wrist guards.
``In my practice, I've seen several fractured wrists from
youngsters' falling off scooters,'' McKirgan said. ``When kids
fall, they fall forward on outstretched hands. That can definitely
produce fractures and dislocations.''
</P>
<P>
   But will scooter riders really suit up, stiff as cyborgs, in
head-to-toe protective wear?
</P>
<P>
   Riley Hedin, 13, of Providence, Utah, said that he and his
friends did. ``I always wear pads and a helmet,'' said Riley, who
received his scooter a few months ago as a birthday present.``Where
I live, there's a big hill,'' he said. ``If you get going too fast
and lose control, you can get in a crash. I've fallen off a couple
of times, so now I'm extra careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cautious children like Riley should not have any problems with
scooters, McKirgan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any kind of activity, there's risk, so you always have to
take precautions,'' McKirgan he said. ``But while you don't want a
high-risk product out there, I would hate to see a child not get to
have fun. Ultimately, we have to let kids be kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9072 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-CONFESSIONS-2ndTak     09-11 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CONFESSIONS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: and perpetrator. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the beginning of the series and between confessions, there
are images suggesting a victim, a knife, a corridor and detectives
interrogating a suspect in a windowless room with a light bulb
dangling from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confessions'' is a very high-tech setting for some low-tech
video. The images viewers will see comes from a stationary camera
and includes a criminal sitting at a table, answering questions, as
if in a home video. It ``looks'' unsettling, and that's the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV insists that the program neatly accomplishes the show's
primary goal, which is to shed light not only on part of the
criminal justice system _ Court TV's mandate _ but also on the
criminal mind.
</P>
<P>
   As for capitalizing on the tragedies of others, Kroehling says,
``the irony is that some of the victims' advocates who have lost
children in violent situations like this have come to totally
support the program and see it as a kind of, again, understanding,
even closure.'' I'd like to meet those people.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV hopes that this is its ``Survivor,'' or more
appropriately, its ``South Park.'' Comedy Central was a small
struggling cable network looking for attention, any attention,
before the animated series earned respectable ratings but, more
importantly, became a fixture in the debate over vulgarity in
television. ``South Park'' ignited discussion and controversy, but
the important thing is that it created instant publicity, which
Comedy Central used to sell its other programming, like ``Talk
Soup'' and ``The Daily Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Since rising in prominence during the trial of O.J. Simpson in
1995, Court TV, which began in 1991 and was known for airing
trials, saw the bottom fall out as soon as the Simpson case
disappeared from daily view. Ratings dropped quickly, its
high-profile anchors and reporters who'd gain stature working the
Simpson story jumped ship, hired by the big networks.
</P>
<P>
   Though ratings have climbed somewhat since then, thanks to some
shrewd, uncharacteristic programming, like the addition of
``Homicide: Life on the Street'' reruns, the network struggled to
find a runaway hit that would thrust it back into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   This could very well be Court TV's identity piece. While some
viewers will be repulsed, others will find it fascinating. We
cannot deny that we are a people who search for the extraordinary,
anything that's outside what we see in our daily lives. We watch
violent movies _ people getting their heads blown off, people being
slashed and dismembered _ because we'd like to have an idea what it
looks like. How it's done.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Confessions'' it is, in some ways, explained. And these
aren't actors.
</P>
<P>
   What's most intriguing about ``Confessions,'' though, is how I
had to keep reminding myself that these were real criminals and
real police officials discussing real people who died real,
horrible deaths. Thinking about it now, Daniel was actually
hilarious, what with his obsession with pot, the ``dudes'' and
``aw, man,'' that peppered his speech, and this cavalier, live now,
die later attitude he seemed to have.
</P>
<P>
   But I wasn't thinking that Daniel was giving me valued insight
into a criminal's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   What stayed with me after watching the first episode was that
after all of the hours of watching actors pretending to kill other
actors, only to pop up on another show and die again, it takes
awhile to actually ``feel'' an emotion, something that's actually
real rather than imitated, pre-packaged reality.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sad, scary part, and ``Confessions'' has nothing to
do with that.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
