<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ALLIANCES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT`S THAT NOISE ON THE INTERNET? THE SOUND OF ALLIANCES BEING
FORGED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By BOB TEDESCHI  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Everyone's a cousin in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Scan a week's worth of dot-com headlines, and you'll probably
find at least a dozen partnership agreements or corporate alliances
between Internet companies or traditional companies doing business
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the partnerships involve industry behemoths such as
Sun Microsystems and Netscape. Usually they are more modest, as in
the recent alliance between Phone.com, a provider of wireless
Internet technology, and MyWay.com, which builds custom business
portals.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a whole, however, e-commerce partnership announcements
have come so often recently that they have become the white noise
of Internet business, the hum of the industry's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these are really good,'' says Steven Johnson, a
partner with Andersen Consulting, ``but some are just companies
breathing their own exhaust _ more hype than reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer sites have been among the most aggressive in their
partnership efforts, analysts say, because of pressure to broaden
the products they offer. Amazon.com, for instance, has joined
Drugstore.com, Ashford.com and, more recently, Wineshopper.com to
sell as wide a variety of goods as possible.
</P>
<P>
   With these partnerships, sites achieve two critical e-commerce
objectives: They increase the chances of shoppers' spending more on
each order, while preventing customers from straying to other
retailers. And portal sites join with companies that provide
bill-payment or group-buying technologies to give users more
reasons to stay _ ``stickiness,'' in industry terms.
</P>
<P>
   But stickiness is only part of the story. Industry analysts say
that, 20 years ago, companies were more inclined to build their own
divisions or buy other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '70s and '80s, people bought into diversification,''
says William Battino, who heads the e-business division of
PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``Now they don't want to be the jack of all
trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, Battino and others say, Web start-ups spring from a shred
of technology or involve a marketplace niche that simply cannot
serve customers without plugging in pieces of other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``With partnerships,'' Battino says, ``it makes your speed to
evolve and radically reinvent much higher.''
</P>
<P>
   In an industry in which an idea can turn into an initial public
offering in months, and in which first-mover advantage is the holy
grail, Internet executives say that stopping to develop expertise
in any given area is tantamount to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a crowd of start-ups, no one can do everything,'' says
Cornelius Willis, vice president for marketing at QPass, which
allows shoppers to buy lower-priced goods on several Web sites and
have the purchases put onto one bill. ``So companies like mine are
trying to string together a value proposition by creating a
coalition of value.''
</P>
<P>
   QPass recently made an alliance with American Express, whereby
American Express customers would be able to redeem their awards
points or shop at Web sites that use the QPass payment system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have that Amex customer list of 27 million people,''
Willis says, ``and they don't have the partnerships with digital
publishers and others that we have. It makes sense for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives predict that similar deals will become a mainstay of
the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't slow down,'' says Warren V. Musser, the chief
executive of Safeguard Scientifics Inc., an incubator of Internet
companies. ``Collaboration makes things work. There's no one group
that can have all the perspective, so the trick is to collaborate,
to make sure you don't miss anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The new information technologies allow for better coordination
between firms,'' says Charles Conn, the chairman of Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch Inc., which sells tickets and has more than 40
city sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Conn says, conglomerates such as ITT ``just
acquired everything, because it was difficult to coordinate
partnerships through the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we can communicate fluidly,'' he says, ``even with
companies that have a completely different structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Small Internet companies, he adds, are also much happier to
pursue partnerships because that allows them to maintain a small
workforce ``where people can feel the impact of their labor, and
frankly feel their impact on the company's stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies also choose partnerships over deeper equity
relationships, he says, because of the uncertain nature of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at a firm you might want to own, but they have a
cash-burn rate that's very high,'' he says, ``you might make less
than a controlling investment to get a seat on the board and get
some insight from the company without having to consolidate their
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he says, Ticketmaster Online recently formed a
partnership with Active.com, which helps users find sporting events
in which they can participate, rather than buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still losing a significant amount of money, so it
wouldn't make sense to own them now,'' Conn says. ``But this way we
still develop a strong relationship with them.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to track the Internet's infatuation with alliances is to
watch the fad du jour within e-commerce. When business-to-consumer
e-commerce held the public's _ and Wall Street's _ attention, the
pace of alliances matched the investor frenzy. When the focus
shifted to the business-to-business category, partnerships
involving online industry marketplaces and software providers
proliferated.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, wireless e-commerce, sometimes referred to as
``m-commerce'' _ the ``m'' stands for ``mobile'' _ is emerging as
another battlefront. For wireless providers, that means it is time
to find partners. Kathy Simpson, director of developer marketing
for Phone.com, says the company has created alliances with about
200 companies who want to put their Web content into a format that
could be viewed by people with cellular phones and other hand-held
devices.
</P>
<P>
   These companies have little time to devote to wireless
technology, she says, particularly because many are scrambling to
remain in business, so they rely on Phone.com to help.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Phone.com can help such a vast list of partners
develop wireless programs, Simpson laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have other partners to help with that,'' she says. ``None
of us can exist alone. It's like people are supplying various
pieces of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce executives says that, in cobbling together that
puzzle, not every piece fit nicely _ especially, Conn says, when
the partnerships are thrown together primarily for the publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate with our own alliances,'' he says. ``But
it's absolutely true that many of the ones you read about are
ill-thought-through, and are done for the P.R. value. If there's
one great thing about alliances, though, it's that they can be
undone quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bob Tedeschi covers e-commerce for The New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
