<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-AIRFARES-ONLINE-     09-11 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-AIRFARES-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SPECIAL E-FARES, ONLINE BOOKINGS SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 By EDWIN MCDOWELL  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Most United States airlines began selling tickets over the
Internet in 1996, but it was a halfhearted effort because many
airline officials viewed it as little more than the latest
electronic plaything. Now the airlines are making up for lost time,
going after potential passengers by adding more Web sites as well
as forming partnerships with online retailers better known for
selling electronic products or sporting goods than airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The targets of the carriers' most recent aggressiveness are the
big online travel companies such as Travelocity, Expedia and
Priceline. These were quick off the mark and sell about the same
percentage of online travel as the airlines do.
</P>
<P>
   An example of their power became obvious when Delta Airlines
made its unsold seats available to Priceline.com last summer. Until
then, the major airlines had balked at doing so, but after Delta's
move, they followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably seeking to reduce the power of the online travel
companies, an alliance of 27 domestic and international airlines,
tentatively called T2, had planned to open a ``one-stop shopping''
site this summer, allowing customers to book what the carriers said
would be the biggest selection of low fares available on the
Internet. But in mid-May, the Justice Department said it would
investigate whether T2 would violate antitrust regulations _
causing plans for the site to be put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the American Society of Travel Agents, which asked
the Justice Department to investigate T2, amended its original
complaint to include the newly announced Web site of 11 European
carriers. That as-yet-unnamed alliance, whose Web site was expected
to be up later this year, includes British Airways, Alitalia, Aer
Lingus, KLM and Lufthansa.
</P>
<P>
   These new alliances, if they ever get going, will provide
Internet users access to a far greater range of fares and flight
information.
</P>
<P>
   Buying tickets online has certainly taken off. Last year,
according to Jupiter Communications, the e-commerce research
company, online travel spending reached $6.5 billion, or 4.5
percent of all travel spending, and is projected by Jupiter to soar
to $28.2 billion in 2005, or 14.2 percent. More to the point,
Jupiter said that airline tickets accounted for a whopping 77
percent of online travel purchases last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the online ticket buyers are passengers who could not
resist the rock-bottom fares offered on the Internet by airlines
that would rather give deep discounts than fly with empty seats;
who fly rather than drive or take the bus; and who know a good
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Anne A. Cheng, a professor of English at the University of
California at Berkeley, belongs to the last group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been buying all my tickets online for about a year,''
Cheng said, adding that first she had to allay her fears about
paying by credit card over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She is partial to United's web site, where she and her husband
have found bargains on United flights as well as listings of low
fares on rival carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such enthusiasts, online bookings are soaring this
year. Southwest Airlines booked more than $300 million on its Web
site (www.southwest.com) in the first three months of this year,
double its Web site sales during the same period in 1999. With
online sales accounting for more than 25 percent of total passenger
revenue in the quarter, Southwest says it is on its way to earning
more than $1 billion in e-commerce revenue by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, United sold more than $500 million of tickets over the
Internet, more than double its 1998 Internet sales. In the first
three months of this year, it sold $153 million in tickets through
the Internet, 150 percent above the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold 5 percent of our tickets over the Internet last
year,'' said Kurt Ebenhoch, a United spokesman. ``But we expect
that to rise to 20 percent by 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry average is 4.3 percent, according to Jupiter
Communications, which estimates that the percentage will rise to
11.1 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
   A big Internet surprise to airlines, and a big source of
incremental revenue (revenue beyond expectations), is the sales of
tickets booked by e-mail that offer steep discounts for weekend
travel on routes that the planes would otherwise fly with many
empty seats. Examples of such fares include Miami to San Francisco
for $289 and Newark to Rio de Janeiro, $339
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started the e-fares in March 1996, we offered
them in our hub airports,'' said John Hotard, an American Airlines
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion proved so popular that it was expanded to other
cities. It now has 2.2 million weekly subscribers (people who sign
up to receive weekly information by e-mail for weekend traveling)
and enough passengers willing to fly at the last minute to add at
least $12 million a year in incremental revenue to American's
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines make no secret of their wish to drive passengers to
their web sites, to eliminate commissions paid to travel agents, to
lower the cost of maintaining their reservations systems and, if
possible, lower or to eliminate the cost of bookings made through
global reservations systems like Sabre and Worldspan.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they succeed, airlines say they have every
intention of expanding their presence online. With customers like
Cheng, there does not seem to be much standing in their way.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
