<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GHOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     09-11 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GHOSTWRITTEN': WHEN LIVES, AND WORLDS, CONVERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to describe David Mitchell's first novel, ``Ghostwritten''?
</P>
<P>
   You could say the book resembles a musical composition for
multiple instruments whose parts converge around a single theme.
You could say it blends the nonlinear techniques of movies like
Quentin Tarantino's ``Pulp Fiction'' and Krzysztof Kieslowski's
``Red'' with the narrative strategies of Alex Garland's 1999 novel,
``The Tesseract.''
</P>
<P>
   More simply, you could say that ``Ghostwritten'' relates the
intersecting stories of a dozen people all connected to one another
by six (or fewer) degrees of separation. Those individuals _ who
tell us their stories directly in looping, stream-of-consciousness
monologues _ include a member of the Japanese cult responsible for
a deadly nerve-gas attack in a Tokyo subway, an Irish physicist on
the run from the CIA, a late-night radio talk show host in New York
City, a courtesan turned art thief in St. Petersburg, a lovesick
slacker who works in a used-record store in Tokyo and an old woman
who runs a tea and noodle stand in a remote area of China.
</P>
<P>
   Though this concept of crisscrossing parallel lives seems like
an intriguing postmodern formula for examining the randomness of
life in today's global village, Mitchell is only partly successful
in pulling it off. Some of his narrators showcase his remarkable
talents as a ventriloquist, but others sound like phony
talent-contest impersonations. His aging nymphomaniac in St.
Petersburg seems more British or American than Russian; and his
Chinese tea-stand owner comes across as a paper-doll composite: we
are actually asked to believe that this woman has witnessed all the
vicissitudes of Maoist and post-Mao history from her isolated
mountainside vista.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the addition of another voice, meant to represent that of
a disembodied spirit who can move from host to host, century to
century, continent to continent, glosses the entire story with a
pompous, New Agey tone. Instead of lending credibility to the
novel's apocalyptic ending, this voice undermines it, suggesting
that all that has transpired in the story thus far is part of an
elaborate Shirley MacLaine-esque fantasy, or perhaps a coy
authorial joke.
</P>
<P>
   When Mitchell stays away from the philosophical mumbo jumbo and
sticks more closely to the here and now, he is decidedly more
successful. His portrait of a Tokyo teen-ager named Satoru who
works part time in a record shop and falls in love with a pretty
customer is finely observed: tender without being sentimental,
funny without being snide. Equally convincing is his depiction of a
London musician named Marco, who is heavily in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell proves just as adept at limning less ordinary lives as
well. In one chapter he takes a Hong Kong trader involved in
dubious financial manipulations _ reminiscent, in some respects, of
Nicholas W. Leeson, who made headlines in 1995 for his role in the
collapse of Britain's oldest investment bank _ and makes his state
of mind entirely palpable.
</P>
<P>
   In another chapter he does the same for a world-renowned
physicist named Mo, who has returned home to visit her husband and
son on a remote island off the coast of Ireland. Though her plight
_ hiding out from her former employers and mysterious American
agents intent on persuading her to help develop some sort of Star
Wars missile defense _ is ludicrous in outline, it is made
frighteningly real, thanks to Mitchell's attention to emotional
detail and his ease in conjuring up the disparate worlds (in
Ireland, Hong Kong and Switzerland) that Mo has traversed in the
course of her career.
</P>
<P>
   These characters' lives are tied together through shared motifs
that recur, like musical refrains, throughout the book. Jazz tunes
weave in and out of many of the chapters, and an assortment of
ghosts inhabit the subplots. In one case it's a real ghost who
haunts a Hong Kong apartment; in another it's a ghostly, Jamesian
doppelganger who haunts an aging man's reminiscences. One character
works as a ghostwriter; another has a strange encounter with a
ghostly voice from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these leitmotifs, Mitchell orchestrates chance
encounters between his characters that tangentially link his
multiple story lines together. Satoru, the Japanese teen-ager,
receives a mysterious phone call _ probably a wrong number _ from
the cult member responsible for the gas attack in the Tokyo subway,
and Satoru later crosses paths in Hong Kong with the renegade
trader whose financial schemes are coming unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Russian tart's accomplices in an art theft scheme
turns out to be friends with the former British Intelligence
officer whose story is being ghostwritten by Marco, the sometime
musician and womanizer who just happens to have an affair with the
Hong Kong trader's estranged wife and who happens, as well, to save
the Irish physicist from being run over by a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   These glancing meetings are not as contrived as they sound;
rather, as rendered by Mitchell, they serve to illustrate the
strange interconnectivity of the modern world and the improvisatory
nature of fate. It is when Mitchell tries to explain these random
events with portentous allusions to ghosts and never-dying spirits
that his otherwise gripping and innovative novel stumbles into the
realm of the hokey.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GHOSTWRITTEN'
</P>
<P>
   By David Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   426 pages. Random House. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
