<HEADLINE>
`SOUND OF MUSIC,' THE EVERGREEN THAT NEVER DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``The Sound of Music'': It has always suited our
entertainment needs. In the post-war '50s, when it debuted on
Broadway, it helped us find a cheery silver lining to the carnage
that was the Nazi invasion of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, in the film version that won five Oscars, it provided
the wholesome, glossy escapism that a country in the throes of
social change seemed to crave.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thirty-five years after it was made, the film still fills a
need _ this time, in our 24/7, work-mad society _ for cathartic,
unapologetic, nostalgic/kitschy FUN. You see, over in London, it
has a whole new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight for your man, girl!'' shouts an audience member at the
Prince Charles Cinema, as _ up on the screen _ Maria the governess
meets Captain Von Trapp's sultry girlfriend for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Another shouts, as Maria strolls through an empty ballroom,
``Time to go to Ikea!''
</P>
<P>
   This is the ``Singalong Sound of Music,'' a wacky incarnation of
the world's most popular screen musical (it's the third most
popular film in history, behind ``Gone with the Wind'' and ``Star
Wars''). The mass-karaoke festival of exuberant, interactive
weirdness has become a cult phenomenon in its 13 months at the
Prince Charles. And it's now in New York, running through September
at the Zeigfeld Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   On the occasion of the film's 35th anniversary, 20th Century Fox
is re-releasing a special VHS version of the movie, as well as a
new DVD version. And RCA Records, which has sold 7 million
soundtrack albums, thus far, has put together a digitally
remastered version, including a two-CD ``collectors' edition,''
with unreleased musical material, including preludes and
interludes. It's the musical that just won't die.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some might be stunned at ``Singalong Sound of Music's''
explosive popularity _ but not San Francisco's own high-camp movie
Svengali, Marc Huestis.
</P>
<P>
   The producer of local tribute screenings of cult fare like
``Valley of the Dolls,'' ``The Bad Seed'' and
dress-as-your-favorite-character ``Poseidon Adventure'' nights,
Huestis says the world is hungering for nostalgia in these
increasingly impersonal times.
</P>
<P>
   ``People revel in that `What were we thinking?' kind of thing,''
he says. He adds that playful homages ``answer a primal need to
revisit more innocent times. And to have fun, which we don't have
nearly enough of these days.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Prince Charles Cinema, it's nothing but fun aided and
abetted by the fact that attendees can bring in liquor or buy it at
the popcorn stand, where they can also purchase ``Sound of Music''
kits including foam-rubber nuns, triangle babushkas (which the Von
Trapp daughters wore), plastic edelweiss, party poppers for the big
``So Long, Farewell'' scene.
</P>
<P>
   The audience members come as their favorite characters (there
are many nuns, of course, plus lonely goatherds and baronesses), or
as reference points in songs. One man, all in egg-yolk yellow, said
he was ``Ray, a drop of golden sun.''
</P>
<P>
   A drag queen called Candy Floss, wearing a dress of drapery
material (with the curtain rod attached) similar to that which
Maria used to make clothes for the children, is host of a fierce
costume competition at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the screening, the audience gets into the interactive
spirit, hurling remarks and taunts at the screen (baroness: hiss;
Maria: cheer), and waiting for songs to erupt so they can sing
along with the subtitles provided.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking about humming. This is full-out belting,
howling and gesticulating. (The acting-out of songs gets
particularly manic during ``Do-Re-Mi,'' with the audience
frantically sticking fingers in their ears to portray antlers for
``doe a deer.'') It's participatory art at its finest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
