<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOS-FLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLY' VIDEOS MAKE FITTING HALLOWEEN FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB STEPHENS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fox Home Entertainment has released three
extraordinary, double-feature DVDs that are especially fitting for
Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Two if them contain Kurt Neumann's ``The Fly'' (1958/widescreen)
and Edward Bernd's ``Return of the Fly'' (1959/widescreen/b&AMP;w) and
David Cronenberg's ``The Fly'' (1986/widescreen) and Chris Walas'
``The Fly 2'' (1989/widescreen). The third offers Irwin Allen's
``Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea'' (1961/widescreen) and Richard
Fleischer's ``Fantastic Voyage'' (1966/widescreen).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fly'' is about a scientist who, while working on
experiments, accidentally merges with one of the tiny insects on a
molecular level. The mishap leaves the man with a head of a fly,
and the fly with the head of a man.
</P>
<P>
   At the film's climax, we experience one of the most disturbing
images of mortality in cinema history when the fly, trapped in a
web, screams with a human voice as a spider approaches. The utter
helplessness of a bug made anthropomorphic is horrifying. (Such
hideous blendings of life forms may reinforce our suspicions that
the universe is ultimately senseless.)
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Price, David Hedison, Herbert Marshall and the excellent
Patricia Owens, whose reactions to the monstrosity are more
believable and affecting than those of her co-stars, are featured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return'' deals with the son who foolishly repeats his father's
disastrous experiments. There are a couple of grotesque hybrids in
this picture, and it's in glorious black-and-white. Price repeats
his earlier role of the original scientist's brother and is joined
by Brett Halsey as his troubled nephew. This time, the researcher
is not destroyed by hubris and chance, but by industrial espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the mid-century ``Flies'' are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Cronenberg saw the 1958 ``Fly'' when he was a child and, having
been extremely literal-minded at the time, complained to the
manager about the fallacious science in the picture and demanded a
refund. The future director didn't like the alteration of the size
of the switched heads in relation to their new bodies _ the fly's
gets bigger and the human one shrinks. Cronenberg was too
inexperienced to understand that Neumann's film served an
allegorical purpose, not a scientific one.
</P>
<P>
   So Cronenberg's ``Fly'' is, in some ways, a response to the
theoretical sloppiness of the first version. But it also continues
the exploration of his own strange visions, troubling stories in
which the human race is a victim of inevitable disease and/or is
displaced by the evolution of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Goldblum plays the scientist who is seduced by the
possibilities of his work and Geena Davis is the woman who tries to
prevent his self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Walas, the creator of Cronenberg's monster models, directed
``Fly 2,'' in which the mutation is latent, inherited _ borne
silently within a young man's body. Eric Stoltz and Daphne Zuniga
are featured in this sequel.
</P>
<P>
   The two ``Voyages'' are enjoyable. In Allen's picture, a
nuclear-powered submarine descends to the darkness of the ocean
floor, a place with eerie creatures and unforeseeable hazards, in
an effort to rescue the Earth from lethal radiation. In Fleischer's
mysterious journey, human beings are miniaturized and they travel
through a scientist's body to save him from a blood clot in the
brain. The art direction of ``Fantastic'' is marvelous and portrays
the human interior, from the diminished perspective, as a vast
cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Pidgeon, Joan Fontaine and Peter Lorre star in ``Sea,''
and Raquel Welch, Stephen Boyd and Donald Pleasence are featured in
``Fantastic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
