<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-AMERICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME JAPANESE-AMERICANS WORRY ABOUT DECLINE OF ETHNIC GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Once called an ``unassimilable race,''
Japanese-Americans are the very symbol of assimilation. They are
upwardly mobile, marrying outside their ethnic group at high rates
and dispersing throughout suburban America.
</P>
<P>
   There are more children born to couples in which only one parent
is of Japanese descent than to couples in which both are, according
to the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Hawaii, where Japanese-Americans make up nearly a
fifth of the population, most of the nation's 925,000
Japanese-Americans are now so geographically scattered and
assimilated that they are culturally indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Those transformations since World War II have altered the
cultural fabric of Japanese America and, some say, raised questions
about its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the social glue of the Japanese-American community?
Probably rice,'' mused Bill Watanabe, executive director of the
Little Tokyo Service Center in Los Angeles. ``Beyond that, there's
not a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense that the ethnic group is at a crossroads has been made
more urgent by the steady stream of obituaries of nisei, or
second-generation Japanese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of the nisei _ the children of issei, or the pioneer
generation that emigrated from Japan _ is epochal for an ethnic
largely defined by its immigrant roots and unique wartime
experience.
</P>
<P>
   After Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941, 120,000 Japanese _
two-thirds of them American-born _ were forcibly removed from the
West Coast and incarcerated in remote inland camps during the war
by their own government, which suspected their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   The camps had a profound influence on Japanese-American
experience, and the passing of the nisei is a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   What that means for their highly assimilated children, the
sansei or third generation, and their children, the yonsei and
gosei _ fourth and fifth generations _ remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder for my son, who's growing up as a yonsei, what does
it mean for him to be Japanese-American?'' said Michael Omi, 49, an
ethnic studies professor at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Award-winning playwright Philip Kan Gotanda suggested that
Japanese-Americans might be ``moving into an obsolescence. We have
a museum. We have a monument going up in (Washington, D.C.). So
much of Japanese America has been institutionalized. As a
consequence, we're sort of losing our steam internally. Sometimes,
I wonder if it's simply the natural course of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Sheridan Tatsuno, 51, of Aptos, whose company gets
upstart Silicon Valley off the ground, have a decidedly different
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community's alive and well and thriving,'' he said.
``What's declining are these historical and geographic icons like
Japantowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatsuno maintains that much like dreamscapeventures.com, the
``virtual'' incubator business that he runs from his home, the
notion of Japantown's being a collection of buildings is in for
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Japantown's the old incubator, what's happening is the
Internet is the new Japantown,'' Tatsuno said. ``It's a virtual
community. We're just scattered all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese-Americans are on the decline as other Asian-American
groups grow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, there were 588,300 Japanese-Americans in the country,
making them the largest Asian-American group, ahead of 431,600
Chinese-Americans and 330,000 Filipino-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Japanese-Americans lag behind Chinese, Filipinos, Asian
Indians, Vietnamese and Koreans _ all fast-growing immigrant groups
since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese emigration to the United States peaked between 1901 and
1910. So while most of today's Asian-Americans are foreign-born,
the overwhelming majority of Japanese are native-born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese-Americans don't fit the general profile of other
Asian groups,'' Omi said. ``For many Asians, English is a second
language. That's not true for Japanese-Americans. They're older.
They're highly educated. They marry out.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost has been an erosion of a ``shared and distinctive
Japanese-American culture,'' Paul R. Spickard wrote in his 1996
book, ``Japanese-Americans, The Formations and Transformations of
an Ethnic Group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese-American institutions do not organize people's lives
very much anymore,'' wrote Spickard, adding that ``many
Japanese-Americans are connected to Japanese community institutions
by little more than sporadic ritual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, then, it was no surprise when the Japanese Community
and Cultural Center in Los Angeles last year published ``Nikkei
Donburi, A Japanese-American Cultural Survival Guide,'' a pictorial
compendium of cultural traditions, values and arts of
Japanese-American life.
</P>
<P>
   The book covers topics such as the Osechi Ryori, or New Year's
feast, and the importance of being chanto, which literally means to
be proper and in good order.
</P>
<P>
   In the forward, center director Gerald Yoshitomi said the guide
was aimed at helping families integrate Japanese-American culture
into daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about my own yonsei children, I realize that,
notwithstanding Panasonic rice cookers and Sony Walkmans, there may
be few elements of Japanese or Japanese-American culture which they
will carry forward,'' Yoshitomi wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
