<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DID LOWER TAXES BECOME SOMETHING BAD?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's talk about tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't a pitch for George W. Bush's presidential
candidacy _ although I will avail myself of the opportunity to
state my belief that the tax reduction plan proposed by the Texas
governor is far superior to the tax-and-spend shell game favored by
his opponent, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore scam known as ``targeted'' tax cuts _ the only
kind that Gore will consider _ is one of the most disgraceful
frauds ever perpetrated against American taxpayers. Under this
system, only a few politically favored categories of taxpayers get
a tax break _ and the few who get the break must allow the
government to tell them how to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted tax cut is a subject deserving of an entire column
in its own right, but this isn't the column.
</P>
<P>
   My concern in raising the tax issue is not the unfairness
inherent in Gore's tax plan. My concern isn't even the 2000
election _ not directly, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I am pondering the subject of taxes is my dismay
regarding the anti-tax-cut mind-set that allegedly prevails among
so many voters.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``allegedly'' because it is next to impossible for me to
wrap my feeble mind around the notion that people in this country
have no interest in tax cuts _ or worse, that they actually believe
that tax cuts are ``bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, there was a time in the good ol' U.S. of A. that no
politician worth his salt would attempt to run for elective office
without promising a significant tax cut. It didn't matter if you
were running for the lowliest local office or for president of the
United States; the basic plank in every office-seeker's platform
had to be a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians didn't always deliver the tax cuts they
promised, of course. But deliver or not, they would jump right back
on the tax-cut bandwagon when re-election time rolled around.
</P>
<P>
   But now? Now any politician who makes tax reduction the
cornerstone of his campaign is considered hopelessly out of touch
with voters, not to mention stupid, reckless and irretrievably
retrograde.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for example, has been criticized by his opponents and even
some supporters for vowing to return a sizable portion of the
federal government's projected budget surpluses to the hard-pressed
taxpayers who forked over the money in the first place. Gore
insists that Bush's tax cut is irresponsible; others say that the
proposal is counterproductive because it simply doesn't resonate
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the late-night TV comic/pundit types _ Bill Maher, if
memory serves _ suggested that the main problem with most tax-cut
proposals is that they don't involve enough money to tantalize the
average taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving a hundred or a thousand dollars to every
taxpayer, the comedian said, the government ought to hold a lottery
and give a trillion dollars to one taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a tax cut, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Public-opinion polls in recent years have suggested that many
Americans believe that reducing the national debt is a greater
priority than reducing the federal tax burden. Good for them;
that's a commendably selfless view.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem with it. Just because politicians say
they'll use a budget surplus to pay down the debt doesn't mean that
they will actually do it.
</P>
<P>
   Government _ especially the federal government _ has an
insatiable appetite for money. And once the government reaches into
the taxpayers' wallets and grabs those hard-earned bucks, the
politicians and bureaucrats are odds-on to find a way to spend the
money.
</P>
<P>
   So. The choice isn't between tax cuts and debt reduction; the
choice is between tax cuts and more government spending.
</P>
<P>
   A tax cut means you get to spend your own money. No tax cut
means the government gets to spend your money.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like a no-brainer. Tax cut: good. No tax cut: bad.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, some way, someone managed to turn this seemingly
indisputable premise on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cut: bad?
</P>
<P>
   Incredible.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
