<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9107 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-MUNICH-EYEWITNESS     09-11 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MUNICH-EYEWITNESS0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories of Munich in 1972 still emblazoned on mind of American
athlete
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Harry Winkler didn't plan to become an
Olympic athlete.
</P>
<P>
   He was talented enough to win a basketball scholarship to the
University of Florida. But Winkler was a realist ``on the back side
of my athletic career'' when he landed in the Army after his draft
deferment finally ran out in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, at Fort Campbell, Ky., some of the other camp jocks
coaxed him into playing team handball, a sport he'd never seen.
It's like basketball, hockey and soccer played all at once. Goals
are scored by throwing the ball past a goalie into a net.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler caught on fast, and at the right time. The Army, hoping
to burnish its image, volunteered to form America's team-handball
team for the sport's indoor Olympics debut at the 1972 Summer Games
in Munich, West Germany. The Fort Campbell team became the starting
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys came for tryouts from Japan, Korea, all over the world,''
says Winkler, now living in Palm Beach Gardens. ``I was lucky
enough to get picked.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, Winkler was on his way to the Munich Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had achieved Nirvana,'' he later wrote. ``I was going to
heaven. Everything in the world was good and in its proper place.''
From the time his place on the team was announced, ``the daily
routine from that day on could best be described as pure happiness,
incredible enthusiasm and the highest level of contentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the Olympic Village, Winkler was ``amazed at the
magnitude not only of the athletic and housing facilities but also
the magnitude of the hospitality of the German people. They wanted
to make amends to the world for World War II ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Germany's first Olympics since the war presented an opportunity
to erase memories of the 1936 Games in Berlin, where jackboots
outnumbered running shoes and Adolf Hitler's glare loomed over all.
It was an equally important opportunity for Olympics organizers to
make people forget 1968: Days before those Games were to open in
Mexico City, police gunned down a crowd of student demonstrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-END-LAMB0912-COX     09-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-LAMB0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Good-death' values shouldn't be force-fed to terminally ill
 &HT;    By KEVIN LAMB
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - As much as we need to open our minds and mouths
on the subject of dying, there are dangers when the hospice
movement glamorizes death the same way ``Friends'' makes New York
City look like a charming and affordable place for young adults.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, we must be careful about asking doctors and
nurses to warmly embrace death when preventing death is, after all,
their primary purpose. Many Americans do not consider it a weakness
that our health-care system lets too many people live for too many
years.
</P>
<P>
   A more subtle risk is the unrealistic expectations we create by
describing dying as a chapter of Kodak moments. No matter how hard
we try to make dying a personal-growth experience, dying is a
disagreeable chore both to do and to watch. Living is stressful
enough without adding pressure at the end to die properly.
</P>
<P>
   It can be wonderful when people can turn a terminal diagnosis
into an opportunity for fulfilling last wishes, reconciling
differences, reclaiming old friendships, reconnecting spiritually.
But what if the dying person doesn't want to make amends with every
antagonist in his life? What if, instead, he really wants to seek
out some heartless scoundrel from his past and tell him all the
things he was afraid to say before?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to say that, if I still hate my enemies at the
end of life, somehow that's a moral failing on my part,'' says
Marshall Kapp, a lawyer and ethicist at Wright State University's
School of Medicine. ``Some people want to die mad, and they should
have that right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a lot to improve the quality of medicine at the end
of life. But death is still not going to be a welcome event for a
lot of people, and we have to face that reality.''
</P>
<P>
   People do not usually die completely fulfilled. Their loved ones
do not shrug off the pain of grief even when death is relatively
welcome. Death is a painful time of unpleasant sounds and smells
that is almost never accompanied by harp music.
</P>
<P>
   Even Paul Ramsay, one of the first ethicists to say it's
sometimes appropriate to stop fighting death, later argued that
``we don't want to get so positive in our notion of death that we
think death is a good thing,'' said Robert Reece, another Wright
State ethicist. ``He said death is an evil thing. It's to be
avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for hospice and comfort care sometimes forget what it
is that they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death doesn't have to be bad,'' says a spokeswoman for the
National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization. ``There are such
negative connotations in this society about death, and it can be a
very good time, a very beautiful and rewarding and high-quality
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as it's offering alternatives instead of obligations,
though, the ``good death'' movement is valuable. Dying people and
their families should have as much comfort and company as they want
and can be given. The health-care system should do all it can to
relieve physical and emotional distress for the patient and loved
ones.
</P>
<P>
   The movement also has brought patients and families into
decision-making as death nears. It has encouraged dignity for dying
people that comes with such simple tokens of respect as drawing
curtains and looking folks in the eye. It has brought benefits into
dying lives consistent with the advice that we should more often
live each day as though it's our last. Hardly anyone, Kapp
included, disagrees that all of that is good.
</P>
<P>
   So are the social changes of slowly removing the taboo on
discussing a subject that makes many of us so uncomfortable and
afraid.
</P>
<P>
   Increased attention on comforting the dying has led to calls for
referring patients to hospice care earlier and for improving
Medicare reimbursement rates. It has helped pain specialists and
ethicists rally in opposition to the misleadingly named ``pain
relief promotion act`` before Congress that would actually make
pain medications more difficult to administer in the name of
preventing rare doctor-assisted suicides (see www.stopprpa.org for
information).
</P>
<P>
   But bringing good-death values to every deathbed is just as
objectionable as forcing feeding tubes and respirators on every
patient, Kapp wrote earlier this year in his article, ``The Right
to Die Mad,'' in The Pharos, the Alpha Omega Alpha medical
society's publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally defined successful dying may take many forms,''
Kapp wrote, and ``growth, forgiveness and personal fulfillment''
are less universal needs than, say, oxygen. Nobody should have to
feel guilt and shame for resisting `sensitive experts' injunctions
to `Have a nice death.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
