<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories of Munich in 1972 still emblazoned on mind of American
athlete
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Harry Winkler didn't plan to become an
Olympic athlete.
</P>
<P>
   He was talented enough to win a basketball scholarship to the
University of Florida. But Winkler was a realist ``on the back side
of my athletic career'' when he landed in the Army after his draft
deferment finally ran out in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, at Fort Campbell, Ky., some of the other camp jocks
coaxed him into playing team handball, a sport he'd never seen.
It's like basketball, hockey and soccer played all at once. Goals
are scored by throwing the ball past a goalie into a net.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler caught on fast, and at the right time. The Army, hoping
to burnish its image, volunteered to form America's team-handball
team for the sport's indoor Olympics debut at the 1972 Summer Games
in Munich, West Germany. The Fort Campbell team became the starting
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys came for tryouts from Japan, Korea, all over the world,''
says Winkler, now living in Palm Beach Gardens. ``I was lucky
enough to get picked.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 26, Winkler was on his way to the Munich Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had achieved Nirvana,'' he later wrote. ``I was going to
heaven. Everything in the world was good and in its proper place.''
From the time his place on the team was announced, ``the daily
routine from that day on could best be described as pure happiness,
incredible enthusiasm and the highest level of contentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the Olympic Village, Winkler was ``amazed at the
magnitude not only of the athletic and housing facilities but also
the magnitude of the hospitality of the German people. They wanted
to make amends to the world for World War II ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Germany's first Olympics since the war presented an opportunity
to erase memories of the 1936 Games in Berlin, where jackboots
outnumbered running shoes and Adolf Hitler's glare loomed over all.
It was an equally important opportunity for Olympics organizers to
make people forget 1968: Days before those Games were to open in
Mexico City, police gunned down a crowd of student demonstrators.
There is still no agreement on how many died; at least dozens,
possibly hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Televised shots of athletes carrying flags were juxtaposed with
shots of Mexican security forces carrying machine guns. But the
most dramatic image of the 1968 Games focused the world's attention
on an angry America, when black runners Tommie Smith and John
Carlos bowed their heads and raised their fists on the awards
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, this time, the ill feelings were supposed to be
subsumed by good will and glory. It nearly happened.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were certainly eager for distraction. The presidential
campaigns of Nixon and McGovern were scraping at old wounds over
Vietnam, as the war dragged on despite repeated predictions of
imminent peace. Few showed interest in the Washington mess the
papers were calling ``the Watergate caper.'' Even nonsports fans
were drawn to ABC's Olympics coverage, hosted by the genial and
familiar Jim McKay.
</P>
<P>
   American competitors finished the first week of the Games tied
with the Russians in medals. There was general agreement among
bartenders and taxi drivers that Bob Seagren got jobbed out of the
pole-vault gold when he was forced to switch poles at the last
minute, but everyone cheered and chuckled as Dave Wottle ran for a
gold medal in the 800-meter race with his hat on.
</P>
<P>
   The whole world marveled at the triumphs of a 22-year-old
Indiana University swimmer named Mark Spitz, who quickly claimed
his record seventh gold medal. The good cheer evaporated before
dawn the next day, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   With news anchors nowhere to be seen and ABC sports hooked to
the only live satellite feed, McKay solemnly delivered the news
that Arab terrorists had broken into the Olympic compound and were
holding Israeli athletes hostage. Nearly everyone in the States
soon knew more than the Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler was on his way to breakfast in the commissary at the
center of the dormitory complex when he heard the first rumor.
``For two days, I heard rumors, but no details,'' he says. ``We had
TV, but it was in German. I couldn't understand the commentary. You
guys back home got a lot more. I never saw the guy on the
balcony.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy on the balcony became the most frightening image in
Olympic history: A hooded terrorist moving silently outside the
Israeli quarters. Inside, two Israelis were already dead. Winkler
stood on his own balcony, less than 100 yards away but around the
corner. He watched police and soldiers below. He saw the crowd
press against the chain-link fence surrounding the compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe any of this was happening to the most
wonderful dream in the world,'' he says. ``It's like your little
puppy comes running up to you and suddenly a branch falls on it.
How could something that out of place happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Games went on. The hostage drama continued for
nearly 12 hours before the first event cancellations. Even then,
events already in progress were allowed to continue. Negotiations
with the terrorists continued late into the night. They demanded
the release of 200 Arab prisoners in Israel, plus an airplane for
their own escape.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities finally announced an agreement, and the terrorists
and hostages were escorted to a nearby airport. A rescue plan went
terribly wrong. Nine Israeli athletes were killed at the airport,
raising the toll to 11. In addition, five of the eight terrorists
and a German police officer were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorists called themselves Black September. Israeli
authorities linked the group to the Palestinian Liberation
Organization. A former PLO guerrilla wrote a book last year
acknowledging his role in planning the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy immediately drew competitors closer, Winkler says.
It was evident at a memorial service in the Olympic Village. ``When
the Games opened, we walked in as countries,'' he says. ``At the
memorial, we walked in as athletes. I was sitting with a team from
Africa. We were all there to show our grief.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay in the Games lasted just 24 hours. Many commentators
were incensed at what they saw as callousness in allowing the Games
to proceed. Many athletes felt just as strongly that the Olympic
committee did right by going ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always critics,'' Winkler says. ``But the athletes
wanted to go on, to honor those who were killed. We needed to
continue. If we stop it, the terrorists win.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, 55 and a health teacher at Forest Hill High School,
didn't get to play that year. ``I didn't have enough experience,''
he says. But he made the Olympic team again in 1976 and played
regularly. Neither of his Olympic teams won a medal. ``I didn't
expect one,'' he says. ``It was an honor just to be on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: douglaskalajian(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
