<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-INPATIENT0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palliative care becoming a specialty
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Miami Valley Hospital makes its palliative care
services available throughout all its specialties. The Dayton VA
Medical Center has a separate hospice floor on site. Grandview
Hospital and Medical Center has an arrangement with Hospice of
Dayton for dying patients' final days, and also plans to create two
hospice beds.
</P>
<P>
   As the medical consensus develops that dying patients need
specific treatments for relieving pain and distress, hospitals are
looking for better ways to tend to the patients who don't leave
their care. ``Palliative care is becoming a specialty almost,''
said Dr. Basel Yanes, the Miami Valley oncologist who chairs its
palliative services committee.
</P>
<P>
   Not all patients want to go home to die. At the VA center's
hospice, the patient is never far from his or her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many veterans do not have very good family support systems,''
Dr. Geetika Kumar said. ``If they have families in town, the wife
or caregiver is elderly, too, and it's very difficult for them to
manage symptoms at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospice of Dayton's Facility Assisted Care Program began at
Franciscan Medical Center before it closed and has expanded to
Kettering, Sycamore, Grandview and Southview hospitals. It enables
patients and families to get the Hospice's bereavement and other
services even if the patients aren't well enough to be moved from
the hospital. It served about 50 patients last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One family member told me 'I don't want my mother dying in an
ambulance in a parking lot somewhere,''' Hospice spokesman Larry
Kinneer said. ``It's for people who are imminently dying, typically
within 48 or 72 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami Valley's 2-year-old program is more ambitious, usually
with a goal of transferring patients to Hospice while they're still
mobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent the first year doing a lot of research, asking
families what we could have done better,'' said Beth Delaney, the
nurse practitioner who directs the program. One thing they found
out was they were too slow to kick the habit of repeatedly drawing
blood after the goals for a patient had shifted from curing to
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Although health plans typically cover hospice services provided
by hospices, hospitals have a harder time being paid for them. The
Miami Valley Health Foundation pays Delaney's salary, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to look at our processes and say, 'How can we
best serve the care of the dying?''' Delaney said. ``We like to get
them over to Hospice. But there are still situations where the
patient or the family doesn't want to choose Hospice because of the
connotations that hospice means dying. We have to still be able to
provide for those patients.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
