A9112 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SENIORS-SELF-ESTEEM-N     09-11 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-SELF-ESTEEM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS SENIOR SELF-ESTEEM GETS A BOOST FROM EXERCISE  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY ROBERT PREIDT  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   If you're an older adult, exercise will help you pump up not
only your physical health, but your self-esteem as well. And it
doesn't seem to make much difference how you go about it.
</P>
<P>
   A new American study shows that whether you choose
stretching/toning or walking, both regimens offer similar value in
increasing the self-esteem of older adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, as we age, our sense of physical self-worth
degenerates. We lose our strength, we lose our ability to do things
over longer periods of time. Certainly, there's evidence to suggest
that as our bodies change, so does our self-perception of what
we're like,'' says lead author Edward McAuley, a professor at the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
</P>
<P>
   His study shows that a backslide of self-esteem can get a boost
from exercise.
</P>
<P>
   McAuley and his colleagues measured self-esteem changes in
adults between the ages of 60 and 75 who participated in a
supervised exercise program for six months. The activities, done
three times a week, included stretching and toning in a gym or
brisk walking in an indoor shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, the subjects were given a physiological assessment
and completed a questionnaire about their self-esteem and physical
self-perception. Six months after completing the exercise program,
116 of the original 174 participants returned for a physiological
assessment and 152 completed a second questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that during the exercise programs, overall
self-esteem levels increased in both the stretching/toning and
walking groups, with a greater increase in the stretching/toning
group.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups had an increased overall sense of physical
self-worth and self-esteem related to body image, physical
condition and strength. In addition, the physical condition and
strength aspects of their self-esteem increased as the exercise
frequency increased.
</P>
<P>
   McAuley says he and his fellow researchers examined how
different aspects of physical self-esteem are influenced by the two
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, we find no difference. And I think that's a
positive message to be sending _ that different types of physical
activity have similar positive effects. They increase perceptions
of worth relative to physical capabilities,'' McAuley says.
</P>
<P>
   He adds that the stretching/toning and walking are considered
light- to moderate-intensity exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That in itself sends a message that you don't have to get
older people involved in high-intensity running or other similar
types of activity to garner these positive psychological effects,''
McAuley says.
</P>
<P>
   But, his study also shows, it's essential to maintain your
exercise program or your self-esteem could wither away again.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the exercise programs ended, the self-esteem
levels in both groups dropped as some participants stopped
exercising. While 75 percent of the stretching/toning group
continued exercising at the same levels as during the study
program, only 51 percent of the walkers maintained the same level
of activity.
</P>
<P>
   McAuley and his colleagues suggest that monthly newsletters or
reminders, telephone calls, follow-up exercise prescriptions or
``buddy groups'' may be ways of helping older adults continue
exercising and maintain higher self-esteem levels.
</P>
<P>
   The study was published in the July issue of Annals of
Behavioral Medicine journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issue of self-esteem being associated with being
able to do things for yourself consistently over time is something
that has been recognized for a long time,'' says Jessie Gruman, the
executive director of the Center for the Advancement of Health in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   This study bolsters the understanding of how that works, she
adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning about the nuances of how far-reaching that
finding is,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She agrees it's often difficult for older adults to begin or
continue an exercise program but adds that exercise doesn't have to
be drudgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeking the thing that you like to do, that you can do, and
that you will do, is really the most important thing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like to dance, you should dance,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And if you can start a buddy system, making exercise an integral
part of your daily routine in a secure setting, that could help you
maintain your commitment to keeping fit, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
