<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS (United Nations) _ Iraq, which has complained for
years about the effect of U.N. sanctions on ordinary Iraqis, is
refusing to cooperate with a U.N. plan for a nationwide survey of
the sanctions' effect on people. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-EGYPT (Cairo) _ President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, met Monday for 90 minutes in
Alexandria to plan strategy for the resumption of
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. But after the Palestinian decision
on Sunday to defer a declaration of Palestinian statehood for at
least two months to allow time for a renewed effort to negotiate a
final peace accord with Israel, opinion in the Arab world appeared
to have hardened against the sort of concessions, principally on
Jerusalem, that Israeli and American negotiators have said will be
necessary if a peace pact is to be reached within the four- to
five-week period set by the Israelis and Palestinians. By John F.
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FUEL (London) _ The British and German governments said
they would not give in to demonstrators who snarled traffic and
blockaded refineries Monday to protest high fuel prices, and an
OPEC decision to boost production did little to curb the
demonstrators' anger. The protests have spread to Ireland, while
some continue in France. (Summary from wires.) By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
