<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ The price of crude oil and home heating
oil surged to near 10-year highs on Monday as traders dismissed the
importance of the decision by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to increase production by 800,000 barrels a
day. In trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the price of
crude oil for October delivery rose $1.42, or 4.2 percent, to
$35.05. Heating oil jumped 5.36 cents, or 5.4 percent, to $1.0485 a
gallon. During the day, the price of home heating oil was up to
1.0690 a gallon. By Jonathan Fuerbringer and Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-ONLINE (Washington) _ U.S. regulators, putting aside
antitrust concerns, Monday approved formation of Covisint, a
mammoth online marketplace for the world's largest automakers. The
Federal Trade Commission, which voted to allow the venture to
proceed, said the government cannot say that implementation of the
Covisint venture will not cause competitive concerns and it
reserved the right to take further action. (Summary from wires.) By
Christopher Marquis.
