<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FIRES-NUKES-ART-2     09-11 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FIRES-NUKES-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDFIRES ON NUCLEAR SITES RAISE SPECTERS OF RADIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.M., Colo., Wash., Idaho, S.C., Tenn.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT6 photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By JON CHRISTENSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fires in and around nuclear facilities understandably make
people nervous.
</P>
<P>
   So this has been an unnerving summer in parts of the American
West, where some of the wildfires that ravaged millions of acres
also scorched several major nuclear complexes in New Mexico,
Washington, Colorado and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   When an out-of-control fire swept across the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico, many people fled their homes, and it was
not just the smoke and flames that sent them packing.
</P>
<P>
   Some worried that radioactivity would spread downwind. And some
firefighters even refused to work around the lab, also fearing
contamination, state and federal officials said. Similar concerns
prompted 188 firefighters who battled blazes at the Hanford Nuclear
Reservation in Washington to request tests to see if they had been
exposed to radiation. So far, 35 tests have proven negative.
</P>
<P>
   During all these fires, government scientists monitored
radiation and officials promptly issued statements declaring that
while there were elevated levels of radioactivity _ including
minute amounts of plutonium at Hanford _ most of it was a natural
result of burning vegetation, and there was no cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air and water sampling are the best methods for detecting any
problems, and we have not found levels that would present a health
risk,'' said Ellen Livingston, a senior policy adviser on
environmental management for the federal Energy Department,
speaking after the fires were under control.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists outside the Energy Department who reviewed the air
monitoring data from the fires at Los Alamos and Hanford agreed
that there did not seem to be any cause for alarm regarding
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   But the risks of radiation releases during and after wildfires
at contaminated nuclear sites are still not thoroughly understood
by scientists, let alone the public. And distrust of government
reassurances and a lack of perspective about radiation cause many
people to fear the worst when contaminated sites catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Such fears are not limited to the United States. When a fire
broke out near Chernobyl in May, the Israeli embassy in Minsk, 200
miles away, was evacuated because of fear that the fire was burning
in an area contaminated during the nuclear reactor meltdown there
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are valid concerns,'' said Ward Whicker, a professor of
radiological health sciences at Colorado State University and a
pioneer in the field or radioecology, the study of how radiation
moves through the environment. ``There is not a lot of research
available to help us quantitatively predict how much material might
be released in a given fire.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Los Alamos have been developing a program that
uses supercomputers to predict the complex behavior of wildfires in
different kinds of terrain, vegetation and wind conditions, a
notoriously difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   The program was far enough along that, had it been used, the
program might have alerted the National Park Service that
conditions were not safe for the ``controlled burn'' the service
started in May in nearby Bandelier National Monument, said Rodman
Linn, one of the scientists working on the program.
</P>
<P>
   Such fires are intended to prevent uncontrolled wildfires, but
this one spread out of control, devouring more than 47,000 acres
and destroying more than 200 homes and some structures on the
grounds of the laboratory, where decades of nuclear weapons
research was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The computer modeling program could also have been used to
predict radioactive emissions caused by fires on the laboratory
grounds. But it was not used, and Linn was evacuated along with
other lab workers during the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The project has languished, Linn said, because scientific
research on wildfires has not been a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the western half of the United States is burning
up,'' he said, ``it's hard to get money for any kind of wildfire
research.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   When fire threatens a nuclear facility, the worst case scenario
is if radioactive materials actually catch fire. That did not
happen in any of the recent fires.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department, which oversees the nuclear complexes, has
emergency management plans that include analyses of the risks a
fire would pose at each one, Livingston said. Firebreaks are
routinely cleared and area firefighters are trained on the sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos lab completed an environmental impact statement
last year that included a wildfire risk assessment. As a result,
the lab expanded a firebreak around its most vulnerable radioactive
waste site, which protected it from the recent fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were prepared,'' Livingston said. ``And our ability to
extinguish the fires at those sites under difficult weather
conditions demonstrates that we took the right steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the troubled histories of some of the nation's nuclear
facilities, however, it is not simply a matter of safeguarding the
radioactive materials stored on site. The Energy Department has
also evaluated the risk that fire could release radioactive
elements that have contaminated the soil, grass, bushes and trees
at its nuclear sites.
</P>
<P>
   At Hanford, the Energy Department routinely collects what
workers call ``hot tumbleweeds,'' which grow in contaminated soil.
To prevent the tumbleweeds from rolling off site or burning in a
fire and releasing radioactivity, the department buries them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even at contaminated sites, naturally occurring radon and
other decay products of uranium contribute much more radiation to
the atmosphere in wildfires than do manufactured radioactive
elements absorbed by plants from contaminated soil.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Energy Department, none of the fires this year
exposed anyone to more than 1 millirems to 2 millirems of
radiation, and firefighters were the only people likely to be
exposed to that much radiation.
</P>
<P>
   To put that into perspective, the average American is exposed to
about 360 millirems of radiation per year, mostly from natural
sources.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While smoke from a wildfire at a nuclear site seems to cause the
most immediate concern to nearby residents, the most significant
problems may come after the fire is out.
</P>
<P>
   The risks associated with the spread of contaminated soil after
a fire are much greater than the risks associated with radiation
from burning contaminated vegetation, according to government
studies. Radioactive contaminants in the soil can be picked up by
wind or washed into streams and rivers by rain after the fire has
scorched the earth, leaving bare ground vulnerable to erosion.
</P>
<P>
   In studies conducted at Rocky Flats and the Waste Isolation
Pilot Project in Carlsbad, N.M., Whicker found that runoff from
burned plots carried more radioactivity than runoff from unburned
ones. In Los Alamos, crews have built dams to try to keep runoff
from spreading contamination down denuded gullies to the Rio
Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The risk that contamination will spread after a fire affects how
much cleanup nuclear sites need to be made safe, said John Till, a
radioecologist with the Risk Assessment Corp. in Neeses, S.C., a
radiation research and training company.
</P>
<P>
   Till completed a study last year to determine how much uranium
and plutonium can be safely left in the ground at Rocky Flats,
where it leaked from barrels of waste left over from making bombs.
He found that a fire would greatly increase the amount of plutonium
blowing downwind afterward with the dust. The exposure did not
appear to extend beyond the boundaries of the site, or present a
health risk to people living around it. But it did mean a much more
expensive cleanup would have to be done at Rocky Flats if people
began moving onto the grassy plain, about 10 miles west of Denver.
The plutonium will remain radioactive for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Till said it was important to have independent studies and
monitoring, because of public skepticism about the Energy
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Energy makes its statements about there
being no risk, but there's always a question in people's minds,''
he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is not surprising to Brian Kelly, a health physicist
working for Integrated Environmental Management, a consulting firm
in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is sort of a knee-jerk response when radiation is
mentioned,'' he said. ``People almost get a visceral fear about
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's company has a Web site (www.iem-inc.com) on which people
can ask a certified health physicist questions about radiation.
During the fires, Kelly corresponded with numerous concerned
people, including Marie Coburn, who grows organic echinacea, a
medicinal herb, on a 3-acre farm 30 miles northeast and downwind of
the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn was concerned when the fire began sweeping through Los
Alamos, scorching canyons contaminated with radioactive waste, and
the smoke drifted in her direction: The sky turned orange and
fuschia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hard time breathing,'' Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reassurance by the Energy Department and the New Mexico
Department of Health, she fled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed my truck thinking that I might never come back, that
I might find out this area was like Chernobyl,'' she said. Nine
neighbors evacuated with her.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said turned to the Internet for information because she
distrusted the Energy Department and did not understand the
radiation reports in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly convinced Coburn that not only could she return home
safely, she could also harvest her echinacea without worrying that
she might be putting others at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn washed the dust and ashes off her crop. She borrowed a
radiation detector and walked around her property, detecting
nothing out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said she still does not trust the Los Alamos National
Laboratory. But she has come to understand radiation better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radioactivity in itself is not something that is
frightening,'' she said. ``We're in it all the time, and that's
fine, as long as it doesn't soar to really high levels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
