<HEADER>
A9124 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-T     09-11 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT'S HOT, HOT, HOT, PUT ON SOME COOL-WEATHER MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I write this, we have not had any rain for more than 60 days
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   This has gotten biblical here, and, perhaps like you, I had
enough of it about, oh, 58 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's hot at 8 a.m. You walk outside into a steamroom. Go out and
just stand there, and you start to sweat. You don't feel like
moving, much less working. Malaise lies heavy on the land. What to
do?
</P>
<P>
   There's no real relief until the rain shows up and the
temperature falls, but maybe we can think ourselves a little cooler
by listening to the music of fall.
</P>
<P>
   The what? Hear me out. Summer has always been associated with
pop songs, romance, long days at the beach, vacations, a certain
sparkle of ease and sensuous possibilities in the air. And there's
certainly no lack of songs concerned with the joys of summer:
beaches, kicking back, getting a tan and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Fall gets the short shrift. As a season, it's a reality check;
collars are turned up, school is back in session, temperatures
drop, sweaters are pulled out of the bottom drawers.
</P>
<P>
   And there are just some songs, CDs and bands _ lots of 'em _
that have a more wistful, smoky, contemplative (and sometimes
melancholy) air that feels more like October than June.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, ``Puff the Magic Dragon.'' The boy and the
dragon have played, but by the end the boy has grown up and moved
on. That's a fall song.
</P>
<P>
   Or Neil Young's ``Cinnamon Girl.'' The narrator hasn't found his
cinnamon girl; he's dreaming, and he's already looking down the
road at growing old and needing someone to be there with him. Fall
all the way _ as is all of Young's ruminative, mainly acoustic and
wildly popular ``Harvest'' CD.
</P>
<P>
   Same with ``The Band,'' with its intimations of farms going
under, people looking back in regret, a search for security. On
``King Harvest,'' the season comes in the form of a shadowy figure,
a ghost-man, who brings with him cold winds out across the rice
fields. Maybe this is why it's my favorite Band record.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, John Mellencamp released ``Scarecrow,'' a
brilliant fall record with some of the same themes as The Band. One
can almost feel the rain turning colder, the days growing shorter,
a world of hope and promise being shut off. The title track, one of
Mellencamp's most affecting moments, is all past-tense (''this land
fed a nation/this land made me so proud''), the glory of a
fruitful, profitable harvest _ and an entire way of life _ gone
forever. The narrator of ``Scarecrow'' and the narrator of ``King
Harvest'' would have had a lot to say to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, R.E.M. and U2 are fall bands; they don't offer easy
answers, and there are conflicted feelings and regret and
melancholy lurking everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, my favorite is U2's ``The Unforgettable Fire,'' the
1984 album known best for ``Pride.'' From the cover artwork to the
tone of almost every song, this is one of the greatest collections
of autumnal music; taut but troubled, full of lengthening shadows
and loneliness, and capped by ``Indian Summer Sky,'' maybe the best
song ever about not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   There are more, of course: The Cure's ``Disintegration,'' Van
Morrison's ``Moondance'' and ``Astral Weeks'' (Van's a fall kinda
guy anyway, always has been), Bob Dylan's ``Blood on the Tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   But you get the idea. There are just some songs that evoke
leaves crunching underfoot, a sharp, tingly bite in the air and
layers of clothing instead of sand between your toes, wiping the
sweat away, and worrying about how you'll look in your bathing
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm gonna go back to my apartment _ which I keep cold enough
to hang meat in _ and listen to some of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
