<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9126 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-RARE-INSECTS-830&AMP;     09-11 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RARE-INSECTS-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTHA'S VINEYARD APPEALS NOT ONLY TO VACATIONERS, BUT RARE INSECTS
TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: New England, Ill.)  By CORNELIA DEAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Ask people on Martha's Vineyard about insects
and they are likely to talk about mosquitoes, no-see-ums and
green-headed flies, all of which can make life miserable here. But
the island's insect population comprises far more than pests.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, entomologists hope to use it to re-establish rare and
endangered insect populations wiped out elsewhere in New England
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This year, beach tiger beetles, tiny ivory insects with brown
markings, were gathered on a stretch of private beach here and
transported to Monomoy Island National Wildlife Refuge at the elbow
of Cape Cod, where entomologists hope they have taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the entomologists' list is the imperial moth, a yellow
and brown insect once abundant throughout New England that was all
but wiped out by the insecticide DDT. Entomologists are studying
the moth now, hoping to determine the best places to reintroduce
it. After that, the scientists hope the Vineyard will provide still
more moth species to repopulate New England habitats.
</P>
<P>
   In all cases, said Tim Simmons, restoration ecologist for the
Massachusetts Natural Heritage and Endangered Species Program, the
idea is to identify past insect habitats that remain protected
enough to enable transplants to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The beetle, only half an inch long, but prized by collectors for
its delicate spots and stripes and bright green abdomen, was
eradicated from almost all of its New England range when
four-wheel-drive vehicles began taking to the region's beaches. The
beetle lays its eggs on the beach, and its larvae live in tubes the
beetles dig in the sand _ no match for all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, entomologists planned to reintroduce the beetle to
Monomoy last year, by digging larvae and transplanting them to
beaches there. But when they went collecting, they discovered that
the beetle's volatile population had declined, for reasons still
uncertain. This year, the numbers were better, so the project
proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Goldstein, a biologist at the Field Museum in Chicago who
is studying the state of Vineyard lepidoptera this summer along
with ecologists at the Sheriff's Meadow Foundation, a major
Vineyard conservation organization, said the work on the beetle was
conducted by Phil Nothnagle, an entomologist who is an authority on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He excavated about two dozen larvae, which is small for an
insect population, but that's all we were comfortable taking,''
Goldstein said. He added: ``Past experience shows introducing
adults doesn't work. Either they don't find each other or they
don't lay eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is too soon to say the effort is a success, Simmons
said in a telephone interview that five adult beetles had already
been spotted on Monomoy.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread spraying of DDT ravaged populations of the imperial
moth, Simmons said. The moth, whose tan-spotted yellow wings
stretch more than 3 inches, once ranged from Canada to Argentina,
but now the only place in New England where it survives is Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   That the moth survives there is partly a legacy of the late
Henry Beetle Hough, the longtime editor of The Vineyard Gazette and
an ardent opponent of the use of insecticides, which he habitually
referred to in editorials as ``poison.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The continued widespread use of poisons, particularly through
aerial spraying, will lead to results that cannot be foreseen _
except that life, the indivisible wellspring of all life on earth,
will never be the same again,'' Hough editorialized in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   At his urging, residents of the island banded together to block
widespread spraying, particularly of DDT. A few thousand Vineyard
acres were sprayed, but only once, while elsewhere in New England
hundreds of thousands of acres were routinely subjected to a fog of
DDT and kerosene. As a result, species survive here that have
vanished elsewhere in the Northeast, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Among them are the imperial moth and other moths that live in
highly specialized habitats, like depressions called frost bottoms,
that are also rare everywhere but the Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Frost bottoms are a geological reminder of how Martha's Vineyard
was formed more than 12,000 years ago as glaciers moved across New
England, pushing rocks and soil before them. When they began to
retreat, they left this material piled up in moraines, which
gradually eroded and washed out to form sand plains. Much of
Martha's Vineyard is formed of such sand plains. Glacial meltwater
carved out the frost bottoms as it streamed south from moraines
toward the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Though frost bottoms may be only 20 feet or 30 feet lower than
the surrounding landscape, Goldstein said, they can be much warmer
during the day and colder at night; some can experience frost
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Because few glacial outwash plains survive elsewhere, Martha's
Vineyard's frost bottoms are extremely unusual.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The Vineyard is not the only source of endangered insects for
repopulation efforts. For example, entomologists are using a small
population of burying beetles on Block Island, R.I., in efforts to
re-establish the species, whose range was once from Maine to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein concedes that the insects he and others are eager to
re-establish probably have little economic importance. But as
conservation becomes more sophisticated, he said, more attention is
being paid to restoring as many of a conservation area's original
inhabitants as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons put it almost the same way, speaking of the beach tiger
beetle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect there are very few people who have ever experienced
a wild beach that has all of its denizens,'' he said. ``It's sort
of a symbol of what's supposed to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
