<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9131 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-AIRPORT     09-11 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-AIRPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS DEBATE   INNER-CITY AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 17)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The fatal crash of a supersonic Concorde northeast of
Paris on July 25 has renewed debate over the construction of a
third major airport to serve the French capital. The fact that the
Concorde could easily have come down on top of a small town, with
even more than the four deaths that resulted among people on the
ground, is also raising questions about the safety of existing
airports in or near cities, about their further development and
about the location of future airports elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce disputes over inner city airports have erupted on the
Continent in recent years, notably in Italy, where a group of
European airlines has taken Alitalia to court over its plans for
Linate airport, a 15-minute drive from downtown Milan. The argument
erupted after Alitalia, backed by the Italian authorities, sought
to capitalize on local resistance to Linate by forcing its European
competitors to use a new airport, Malpensa, a $65 cab ride from
central Milan, while Alitalia reserved Linate for itself.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, controversy is simmering about the future of downtown
Tempelhof Airport, site of the 1949 airlift into Berlin by the
Western Allies. Berlin now relies mainly on tiny Tegel Airport, in
former West Berlin, and proposals to enlarge Schonefeld, the old
East Berlin airport, into a major international hub are hamstrung
by debates among politicians, air traffic planners and
environmentalists opposed to any airport enlargement. Meanwhile,
the former East German city of Leipzig, whose airport was upgraded
after the fall of the Berlin Wall, is booming, attracting travelers
from as far away as Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the numbers speak for themselves. Last year, Charles
de Gaulle Airport, departure point for the fatal Concorde flight,
registered 490,000 takeoffs and landings, a leap of 100,000 in
three years. The airport, in Roissy on the northeastern outskirts
of the city, handled 44 million passengers, almost 13 percent more
than in 1998. At that rate of growth, a ceiling of 55 million
passengers set by the French government will be reached by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Yves Cousquer, president of Aeroports de Paris, the
government-owned company that operates Charles De Gaulle and Orly,
the smaller Paris airport, said that construction of a third
airport for the Paris region had become unavoidable. After the
Concorde crash near the town of Gonesse, which killed 113 people,
the French minister of transportation, Jean-Claude Gayssot, said a
formal decision to build the third airport would probably come this
month and a site would be chosen by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Such a decision will not be easy. Originally, Aeroports de Paris
favored expanding Charles de Gaulle and Orly, but after the crash,
Cousquer acknowledged that construction of a third airport had
become ``ineluctable.'' In towns like Gonesse that profit from jobs
the airports create, mayors and other politicians are torn between
the benefits and the risks. If the Concorde had crashed in the
center of Gonesse, instead of its thinly populated outskirts, the
number of victims would certainly have been far higher.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of a possible third airport for Paris began in the
mid-1990s, as the saturation of Charles de Gaulle and Orly clashed
increasingly with French ambitions to build Paris into a major
European hub to compete with Frankfurt and London. Initially, the
government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, which took office in
1997 with the backing of Green parties and environmentally
sensitive leftists, shelved the idea, preferring instead to expand
the two existing airports. Generally, the Greens and their leftist
allies oppose hub development, favoring smaller regional airports
and preferring high-speed trains, rather than planes, for trips
shorter than 500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the government of Prime Minister Alain Juppe had
proposed a site at Beauvilliers, near Chartres about 50 miles
southwest of Paris. Mayors in the region objected, suggesting
Vatry, a town east of Paris near a proposed high-speed train line
between Paris and Strasbourg. Whatever the choice, Cousquer of
Aeroports de Paris says the third airport will not be in operation
before 2025. The Juppe government had envisaged an opening in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   These projections have encouraged a bid by Lyon, in the
southeast of France, to turn its airport, Lyon-St.-Exupery, into a
second major port of entry to France at less cost and time than it
would take to build a third Paris airport. Bernard Chaffange,
director of Lyon-St.-Exupery, says that the airport, which has a
high-speed train link to Paris and will connect next year with
Marseille on the Mediterranean coast, could absorb the 40 percent
of international travelers now flying into Paris but ultimately
destined for business or vacations in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Gayssot approved further investment at
Lyon-St.-Exupery, including two additional runways. Local
environmentalists and others opposed to the expansion are already
organizing resistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
