<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKAGES COME WITH ASTERISKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who found few bargains on travel to Europe last summer,
when flights were full and coach fares to Lisbon, for example, were
running over $900, are likely to welcome fall, when low-cost
packages arrive. For less than the price of a round-trip air ticket
in summer, tour companies in off season sell combinations of
flights, hotels and elements like sightseeing tours or transfers
between the airport and the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is hugely seasonal. As one operator said, the
income from full planes in summer helps to pay for flights in the
winter, when the per-passenger cost is increased by smaller loads
and the occasional need to de-ice planes. So if a plane is flying
30 percent empty, it benefits an airline to sign a contract with an
operator to sell the empty seats for very little.
</P>
<P>
   However the package is composed, the price is printed in big
numbers, and ``double occupancy,'' ``weekday departures'' and
airport ``fees and government taxes'' of $50 to $125 are in smaller
type; hotel taxes and service charges are normally included. These
factors affect the final cost of packages, and potential buyers
should ask about all of them. In addition, when prices are
stunningly low, the packages may be of cometlike duration and
fraught with asterisks and howevers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, because of restrictions on dates, a three-night
London package that British Airways Holidays advertises for Nov. 1
to 30 can be bought at its lowest price, $409, for only three
departure dates: Nov. 5, 12 and 26, all Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Watch the Calendar
</P>
<P>
   This package, which covers air fare from New York, three nights'
hotel in double occupancy, Continental breakfast, service and hotel
tax is being sold only until Sept. 30. Departing on Thursday,
Friday or Saturday raises the cost $25, as does returning on
Friday, Saturday or Sunday. So there goes $50, if you're not
careful. There is a $30 surcharge for Nov. 21 to 24, over
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   At this price _ and there are higher ones _ the hotels are the
Tavistock, with 345 rooms, and the Royal National, with 1,432,
which the company rates at two diamonds: ``Fairly basic''
accommodations that are well-maintained but with limited amenities.
They have private baths and showers. Both are near the Russell
Square Underground station.
</P>
<P>
   John Muller, manager of operations for British Airways Holidays,
describes the $409 package as tactical pricing: ``We are interested
in seeing more people travel at certain times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For November, the least expensive British Airways round trip
from New York would be $352. This must be bought 45 days in
advance, for weekday flights and with a Saturday night stay, a
restriction waived for the package.
</P>
<P>
   For November, the Tavistock said, it would charge each of two
guests in a room $57 a night, with the pound at $1.46, including
Continental breakfast, service charges and tax, for a total of $171
a person for three nights. The Royal National gave its November
rate as the equivalent of $60 a person a night, for $180 for three
nights, including Continental breakfast, tax and service.
</P>
<P>
   So an individual trying to replicate the $409 package would pay
at least $523 at the Tavistock, $532 at the Royal National, and the
days of the week would be constricted.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways Holidays: (800) 359-8722.
</P>
<P>
   A London package with a voucher for a choice of plays in the
West End is offered by Insight Vacations for people who want a
higher-quality hotel. With the theater ticket; air fare on British
Airways from New York; transfers from and to the airport; six
nights, double occupancy, at the Kensington Hilton with Continental
breakfasts; and a half-day sightseeing tour, this comes to $995 for
four Saturday departures in November and Dec. 2 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Kensington Hilton said its best rate for a six-night stay in
November, including a full breakfast and hotel tax, would be $106 a
person a night, making six nights worth $636. A West End theater
ticket in the stalls _ the equivalent of the orchestra _ is about
$50; if bought separately from the Applause agency in New York, it
would cost $95.
</P>
<P>
   The British Tourist Authority said that round-trip bus transfers
between Heathrow Airport and a downtown hotel would cost about
$17.50; this would involve stops at many hotels. The half-day
sightseeing tour was put at an average of $40 each.
</P>
<P>
   With a theater ticket bought there, the package components would
cost $1,095 at the hotel rate quoted above. The hotel said rates
for certain days might be as low as $83 a person a night, but with
no breakfast. Continental breakfast costs $14.50, English
breakfast, $22.
</P>
<P>
   Insight Vacations: 745 Atlantic Ave., Suite 720, Boston, Mass.
02111; (617) 482-2000; Web site www.insightvacations.com.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Holiday
</P>
<P>
   TourCrafters is resuming a $599 five-night package to Rome, from
Nov. 16 to Dec. 14. The elements are round-trip air fare on
Alitalia from New York, Boston, Chicago or Miami, not including
taxes and airport fees; five nights, double occupancy, at the
three-star Hotel Brasile, 13 Via Palestro, near the railroad
station; and Continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   A New York-Rome round-trip ticket on a weekday from Nov. 1 to
March 18, with a Sunday night stay, was quoted by Alitalia at $398,
plus taxes. On the weekend, it would be $438. The hotel, called
direct, quoted a rate of $57 a person (based on two people in a
room), including buffet breakfast, service charges and taxes. This
would mean that elements in the five-night package, purchased
individually for weekday travel, would cost $683, or for weekend
travel, $723.
</P>
<P>
   TourCrafters: 28085 North Ashley Circle, 202B, Libertyville,
Ill. 60048; (800) 621-2259; www.tourcrafters.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Visit
</P>
<P>
   ETM Travel Group is offering three nights in double occupancy in
Paris with Continental breakfast and a two-hour Cityrama
sightseeing tour for $499, with departures on Continental Airlines
from Newark on Thursday, Friday or Saturday. The offer starts Nov.
1 and runs to March 31, with a blackout Dec. 12 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest Continental fare to Paris for November is $415. For
its least expensive package, ETM uses a small hotel on the right
bank, Des Victoires at 19, rue Herold, which quotes a rate of $53 a
person a night for a double room, with the franc at 7.3 to the
dollar. Creating the equivalent of the ETM package would thus mean
$415 for air fare and $159 for the hotel, plus $25 for the Cityrama
tour, a total of $599.
</P>
<P>
   Des Victoires, with 58 rooms, has recently been renovated. It
has no restaurant, but provides breakfast in a brick-walled area
with arches; breakfast in the room is also available. On the ETM
package, extra nights there are $57 a person.
</P>
<P>
   ETM: 237 Post Road, Westport, Conn. 06880; (800) 992-7700;
www.etmtravelgroup.com.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of these packages has prices for extra nights, nicer
hotels, choicer days, even travel in blackout periods. Like the
special on laundry detergent that gets you into the market, these
packages put you in the right frame of mind for spending a little
more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
