<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV17-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAT AMSTERDAM IS A BIKER'S NIRVANA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By JUDITH YARNALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM _ As Dutch as tulips and considerably more fun,
bicycles _ or fietsen, as they're called in Amsterdam _ are ideally
suited to the brick-paved canal streets of the old central city and
to the flat landscape surrounding the urban area. They're
everywhere: Chained to bridges, parked by the hundreds outside
Centraal Station, rolling steadily by (often with one or two small
passengers aboard) as you sit in outdoor cafes. Because municipal
policy actively promotes bicycle commuting, lanes and paths
reserved for their use abound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a trip this past July, my companion, Victor, and I decided to
join the locals. We wanted to bike south out of the city along the
Amstel, to the town of Ouderkerk, where the old Portuguese Jewish
cemetery is situated, and also to explore the placid Waterland
region across the IJ harbor (pronounced eye) to the north. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But our first task was to reacquaint ourselves with the Jordaan,
the old working class district that we planned to use as our base.
Situated immediately to the west of the Prinsengracht, the
outermost of the concentric horseshoe canals that are the main
feature of the city's enduring 17th-century plan, the intimately
scaled Jordaan charms you into believing that beauty is compatible
with comfort. Its two diagonal canals, the Bloemgracht and the
Egelantiersgracht, are perhaps the loveliest in the city and also
superb places for listening to the bells of the Westerkerk, the
light-filled church where Rembrandt is buried. Anne Frank, while in
hiding around the corner, regarded its clock tolling each quarter
hour as a ``faithful friend.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our hotel, the Acacia, was almost out of the carillon's range,
though still within the Jordaan. When we saw our room there we
couldn't believe our good fortune: Half of a houseboat, complete
with kitchen facilities, a slant window near the bed for watching
ducks glide by, and a small deck above the prow, perfect for
relaxing after expeditions. We felt like part of the neighborhood,
an illusion that the Acacia's owner, Hans van Vliet, is pleased to
foster among his guests by providing a few houseboat rooms in
addition to those within the hotel's main building. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After settling in we headed for Bike City, a rental and repair
shop on the Bloemgracht with an atmosphere of funk and competence,
quintessentially Amsterdam. About 15 minutes later we emerged with
pleasantly anonymous, one-speed machines, adequately equipped for
terrain where the closest thing to a hill is the arch of a bridge
or the grassy approach to the top of a dike. Rob Olykan, the
manager of Bike City, instructed us in snakes and rear wheel locks,
antitheft devices that our rental included. He also recommended we
drop by Pied a Terre, a shop carrying detailed maps for hiking and
cycling. There we purchased a set of four maps of the districts
outlying Amsterdam, which nicely complemented a huge bicycle map of
the city and its immediate fringe we had bought earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On our ride back to the Acacia we stopped by the Westerkerk to
check posters announcing coming musical events, many of which are
free. (We had heard Bach's Christmas Oratorio and Mozart's Requiem
in this lovely, reverberant church on previous trips.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a two-minute ride to Cafe 't Smalle. Inside
this small and genial establishment you can find peace for journal
writing; outside, a deck overhangs the waters of the
Egelantiersgracht. We spread our maps on an outdoor table and
talked over the evening's and next day's possibilities. Dinner
would be at Avare, a Turkish restaurant with an abundance of tasty
choices on the Lindengracht, one of the Jordaan's two restaurant
streets. After that we'd go back to the Westerkerk, for a concert
by a visiting organist from Stuttgart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next morning we prepared ourselves for our trip to Ouderkerk
aan de Amstel by first visiting the Portuguese synagogue, about a
15-minute ride from our hotel. Dedicated in 1675, it is still used
for Sabbath services in warm weather. The community that built this
synagogue suffered great hardship: They took refuge in Portugal
after having been expelled from Spain in 1492, only to be expelled
from Portugal four years later or else forcibly baptized beginning
in 1497. A hundred years later, around the turn of the 17th
century, their descendants reached tolerant Amsterdam. Holland was
rebelling against the Spanish Hapsburgs at the time, so the Iberian
newcomers wisely chose to identify themselves as Portuguese. With
its culture and wealth, this community contributed immeasurably to
its host city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of its members, a merchant named Isaac de Pinto, lived on
St. Antoniebree-straat in an elegant house with painted ceilings
that is now a branch of the Amsterdam public library. Another,
Baruch Spinoza, the 17th-century philosopher (and lensmaker), was
excommunicated for ideas deemed heretical by its rabbis.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To reach the synagogue in the old Jewish quarter, which lies
across the Amstel, we took the long way around, avoiding the
traffic on the direct route through Dam Square and instead
following the stately Herengracht all the way to the river. (If
you're a tourist-biker, it makes sense to stick to the old
waterways: Aesthetics will reward your prudence.) We were impressed
by the building's barrel-vaulted ceiling and tall windows, the rich
woods housing its scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Built roughly four decades after the Westerkerk, the Portuguese
Synagogue has nearly identical brass chandeliers, all orb and curve
and swoop. They contain more than a thousand candles, because the
building has never been electrified. Imagine High Holy evenings by
candlelight, a sight now rarely seen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th century members of the synagogue bought land for a
cemetery they named Beth Haim (the House of Life) five and a half
miles south of the city, at Ouderkerk, where the smaller Bullewijk
converges with the Amstel. We headed there, cycling toward the road
that runs along the Amstel dike. At first our view of the river was
blocked by wall-to-wall houseboats, while far-off cranes leaned
like giraffes over half-finished apartment blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But after we passed under the thick ring road that girds the
city, vistas opened out. Here were cattails and parkland, a lazy
river traffic of yachts with their masts down in preparation for
the bridges ahead. The Amstel brims, as if one added cup would make
it tremble over its dikes. And yet that impression ignores the
intricacies of Dutch hydraulics, for the system of pumping and
drainage is so carefully calibrated that as you ride along you can
see simultaneously three different levels of water-fenced fields,
where sheep and cows never encounter barbed wire.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
