<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-11 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHATEVER HAPPENED TO CONGRESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's something missing in this fall's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It exists but neither Vice President Al Gore nor Texas Gov.
George W. Bush wishes to claim it. We talk here of the U.S.
Congress, run by an unpopular conservative Republican majority that
Bush ignores and a leftish Democratic minority that pretty much
ignores Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, our worthy legislators have been lying in the weeds,
waiting for this month's confrontation with President Clinton over
key tax and social issues with the potential to dramatize major
party differences. It seems likely, however, that barring some
disaster, this last-minute tussle will be merely a transitory
sideshow of little real election impact.
</P>
<P>
   The battle was joined with the president's vetoes _ both of
which will be sustained _ of GOP-promoted measures to kill estate
and marriage taxes. Budget spending issues are the real test of
political clout, and here too, in the pork-dispensing department,
the president seems to have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   A victory will look good on his legislative record but will not
do much to help Gore or hurt Bush. It will give the Republicans
another opportunity to complain about big Democratic spenders, an
argument that isn't worth a lot in an era awash in surplus funds.
It may also give Democrats an opportunity to claim they are going
in the direction voters want.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the presidential contest marches on to its own beat.
Bush has repeatedly cast himself as a Washington outsider, a silly
pretense for a president's son but a means of distancing himself
from Capitol Hill. High-ranking Republican members of Congress were
conspicuously missing from the Bush-controlled GOP convention or
were allowed only brief speeches at odd hours well outside of prime
television time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigns as ``a different kind of Republican'' _ different
from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and the rest of the hard-core GOP congressional
leadership. Bush bragged at the convention, ``I have no stake in
the bitter arguments of the last few years,'' although his current
policy positions resemble those already taken by other Republicans
in these continuing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promises, if elected, to set a new tone of bipartisan
cooperation in the nation's capital. ``I believe the next president
must put Republicans and Democrats in a room and say, `Let's reform
Medicare,''' Bush said in a recent interview. Wow. Merely talking
to opponents will solve everything! What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Can he really believe that Clinton, the biggest gabber of all
time, hasn't been talking to movers and shakers on Capitol Hill? If
charm alone could resolve ideological differences, Clinton would be
king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also denounces the Clinton administration for failing to
complete its agenda of overhauling Social Security and Medicare and
improving public education, as though the White House functions in
a political vacuum. Of course it is not in Bush's interest to
mention that the GOP-led Congress has been busy blocking the
administration at every possible turn. That would put some of the
responsibility for the past eight years on Republican shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore has not rushed to pose beside House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt and wrap himself in the congressional battles
either. The two have a better relationship than they did a few
years ago when Gephardt flirted with a presidential candidacy and
the question of international trade rights ripped the party apart.
But they still circle each other warily.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle is closer to Gore and to
Gore's thinking. But the Senate minority itself is philosophically
divided, and until Gore's poll numbers improved recently, most
Democrats were nervous about embracing him too closely.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush fading fast, congressional Republicans are caving in
to Clinton on several major issues, hoping to avoid a government
shutdown and a nasty public fight with a president they impeached
in 1998 but whose job approval ratings still hovers at about 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore keeps his distance from that fuss because the Clinton
shadow could yet cloud over his new authority as his own man. Bush
keeps his distance because he doesn't have an alternative strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Originally congressional Republicans didn't mind being ignored
by Bush because they had signed on with him early in the game and
expected to ride to re-election on his coattails. Now they are
confused. If there are to be no coattails, they must separate
themselves from Bush immediately. But if they run from him, will he
go down to defeat and take them with him anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The congressional Democrats have a similar problem with Gore,
whose polls can go down as easily as they went up. Initial plans
for Gore to run against a do-nothing Republican Congress got
sidelined in his desperate attempt to sell himself as Al Gore,
independent leader not bogged down in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But both Bush and Gore are coordinating their policy messages
with their party's congressional candidates, who do or don't follow
the party plan. A Republican candidate in Connecticut recently
broadcast a commercial praising Democratic vice presidential
nominee Joe Lieberman. It aired during a visit by GOP vice
presidential nominee Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Elections always come down to every person for himself or
herself. But this year the national and local races seem more
disconnected than usual.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV     09-11 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV13-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 AMSTERDAM: barbed wire. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our plan for this day's ride was to follow the route that
funerary barges took in previous centuries as they made their way
toward the water landing at Beth Haim. When we arrived, we locked
up our bikes by the cemetery fence and immediately noticed evidence
of a drainage and construction project, as well as a placard
directing us to Kerkstraat 7 across the street for more
information. There we were delighted to talk with Derek Brown,
office manager for the cemetery and its restoration. Many of the
cemetery's 27,000 graves, he told us, have now disappeared into
marsh, though in the late 19th century a member of the community,
David Henriques de Castro, had personally paid for the raising,
restoring and photographing of 70 of its most elaborately carved
marble tombs. Even these have now resettled much lower. But they
can still be seen, along with numerous other handsome, ornate tombs
set among Beth Haim's acres of grassy fields and gracious old
trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes this site so exceptional _ perhaps the most
exceptional Jewish cemetery in Europe _ is the Amsterdam Sephardic
community's loose interpretation of the biblical proscription
against images of God. One stone shows divine hands gripping a
hatchet to fell the tree of life, another an angel descending just
in time to rescue a kneeling Isaac from his father's knife _ though
most, like that of Rembrandt's next door neighbor Daniel Pinto, are
more conventional, with skillfully executed floral motifs. As we
wandered around, Victor and I searched for Spinoza's parents (grave
No. 31 on Henriques de Castro's map), but could not find them _ an
unfulfilled quest that seemed appropriate to this evocative,
elm-shaded place.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next morning we awoke not to a complex, painterly Dutch sky
but to something more rare in the Netherlands: Pure sun. We headed
for the free bicycle ferry in back of Centraal Station, which
crosses the IJ every few minutes. Its berth on the north side of
the harbor almost adjoins the shady bike path along the Noord
Hollands Canal. Dug in 1819-1825 and intended to ease the passage
of oceangoing ships into Amsterdam, the canal today provides an
amenity for cyclists and houseboat owners, though its drawbridges
still get some use from barge-pushing tugs. It's a smooth conduit
into Waterland, a region of lush polders formed from lakes drained
in the 17th century, Mondrian-straight bike paths and unspoiled
villages.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Waterland now borders the IJsselmeer, the freshwater lake formed
in 1932 from the damming of the Zuider Zee. Both Jeroen, my Dutch
son-in-law, and Rob at Bike City had mentioned looping through it
as a favorite ride, one offering a wide horizon on Dutch culture.
And when we saw the church spires of our destination towns miles
away rising over the plain, we felt as if we were cycling through a
Ruisdael painting.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first of these spires belonged to the Protestant church of
Broek in Waterland, Hans Brinker's village. Although the
beautifully detailed church is steeped in history (built in the
14th century, burned by Spanish soldiers in the 16th, rebuilt in
the 17th), its contemporary members aren't cowed by it. Their
information sheet directs visitors' attention to a stained-glass
window depicting the great conflagration, but someone has also
provided a soft sculpture granny who's asleep in one of the pews.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the outskirts of Broek we spied the towers of Monnickendam,
an old port town about two miles northeast, noted for its fish
restaurants and pleasure boats. Following signs for the town's
``haven,'' or harbor, we came to the waterside terrace of 't
Markerveerhuis, where we lunched very pleasantly. But outside
Monnickendam, we gave up our spire-markers to follow the long
curves of the path atop the IJsselmeer dike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeroen had warned us about prevailing winds on the dike and on
the causeway out to the nearby island of Marken in the late
afternoon. Today, however, we had nothing to worry about: The
IJsselmeer was an unruffled sheet of haze, still as the herons
perched by the polders' ditches. We veered southeast down the
headland, glorying in the dike's exposure. Approximately 5 miles
beyond Monnickendam we turned inland, toward the tiny, boggy
village of Holysloot. Its attraction was a bicycle ferry, indicated
on our map, which made possible a shortcut back to the city. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first person we queried in Holysloot turned out to be the
ferryman himself, who sold us cold drinks while we waited for a
boatful of cyclists to accumulate. The ferry dropped us off in a
cow-pied pasture _ no bike path in sight, only five white
sawhorselike structures that upon closer inspection included narrow
rails at ground level. These were loopbruggen, as we learned from a
sign, ditch-spanning bridges intended for cyclists on foot pushing
their bikes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sophistication of Amsterdam seemed a long way off, though in
fact we were back within city limits in less than an hour. In the
trickiest part of the whole expedition, we had to chart a careful
course back across the Noord Hollands Canal in order to reach the
IJ bicycle ferry, which docks on its western side. Our ride to and
through Waterland had totaled nearly 19 miles _ about 7 more than
the previous day's _ leaving us pleasantly tired when we returned
to our temporary home in the Jordaan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any of the towns along our routes, even diminutive Holysloot,
can be reached by bus from Amsterdam. But the slower pace and
unframed vista of bicycle travel give one _ besides the chance to
be a reborn 10-year-old _ ample time to absorb the landscape. In
this city and its surroundings, where not only architecture and
history are human creations but also much of the land itself, the
lack of velocity offers a special opportunity. And it won't take
your breath away.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
