<HEADER>
A9139 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV     09-11 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AMSTERDAM-$ADV13-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
AMSTERDAM: breath away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps a houseboat on a canal?
</P>
<P>
   Lodging
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Acacia, Lindengracht 251, (31-20) 622-1460; or fax (31-20)
638-0748, has 14 rooms, 2 studio rooms with kitchenettes, and 5
houseboat rooms furnished as studios, which can accommodate two to
five people; all have private baths. Though in a quiet, peripheral
location, the Acacia offers easy access to the city center from a
nearby tram stop. Doubles range from $62.50 for a regular room to
$90 for houseboat accommodations, breakfast included. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canal House Hotel, Keizersgracht 148, (31-20) 622-5182, fax
(31-20) 624-1317), offers some of the area's most pleasant and
elegant accommodations. Breakfast (included in the price) is served
in a large room, with grand piano, overlooking the garden. Its 26
antique-furnished rooms range from $115 (single) to $150 (double).
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotel van Onna, Bloemgracht 102-108, (31-20) 626-5801, is a
small budget hotel in a beautiful location. Rooms are clean but
spartan; all have private baths but no telephones. Rates are $32 a
person per night, breakfast included.
</P>
<P>
   Food
</P>
<P>
   Two streets in the Jordaan contain numerous ethnic restaurants
and cafes: The Lindengracht and the Eerste Leliedwarsstraat (which
veers off the Bloemgracht and changes its name every block). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avare, Lindengracht 248, (31-20) 639-3167, serves an extensive
menu of fresh, well-prepared Turkish food in a cozy atmosphere;
dinner for two, with wine and tip, is about $50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cafe 't Smalle, Egelantiersgracht 12, (31-20) 623-9617, offers a
long list of reasonably priced sandwiches and drinks, as well as
delicious soups of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Bikes
</P>
<P>
   One- or multispeed bicycles can be rented at Bike City,
Bloemgracht 68-70; (31-20) 626-3721; MacBike, Visserplein 2,
(31-20) 620-0985; and Holland Rent a Bike, Damrak 247, (31-20)
622-3207. All three charge $5 for the first day of renting a
one-speed. Their weekly rental rates for one-speeds are,
respectively, $20, $24 and $26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Bike, Nieuwezijds Kolk 29, (31-20) 620-6940, runs daily
bike tours from April 1 to Nov. 1 of the Amsterdam and Waterland
areas. The tours, which are led by English-speaking guides, cost
$13 (in the city) and $17 (in the country); the fee includes bike
rental but not lunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pied a Terre, Singel 393, (31-20) 627-4455, has a large
selection of hiking and biking maps and travel books; it's a great
place to browse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ferry at Holysloot costs 40 cents; it runs from 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. every day in July and August, and on Saturdays and Sundays in
other warm weather months.
</P>
<P>
   Places to See
</P>
<P>
   The Westerkerk is at Prinsengracht 281; (31-20) 624-7766. Groups
form there for hourly tours of the tower from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Monday to Saturday, April through September; $1.20 a person; if you
join the Tuesday noon tour, you'll see the carillon player at his
strenuous art. Part of the church's concert schedule is posted on
its organist's Web site: www.josvanderkooy.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Visserplein 3, the Portuguese Synagogue, also called the
Esnoga, is across from the Jewish Historical Museum and quite close
to the Rembrandthuis. It is open all year round Sunday to Friday
from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. The admission charge is $3. For more
information, call &QL; 
(31-20) 624-5351 or visit www.esnoga.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Haim is where two rivers converge in the attractive old
town of Ouderkerk aan de Amstel. For more information check its Web
site: www .bethaim.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
