<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-RETIRE-WHEN-NNS &LR;      09-11 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-WHEN-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL ASPECTS OF RETIREMENT RANK HIGH, BUT ARE LITTLE STUDIED 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, Sept. 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Note time element in 3rd graf, Streisand
concerts are Sept. 20-21 and Sept. 27-28 
 ART ADVISORY: With a photo of Terry Alan Beehr (NNS1); and with a
graphic listing people's reasons for retiring. For information
about purchasing theis photo call 202-383-7824.
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For ad man Edgar Hatcher, retirement came at age 65, after ``I
had done work for all the clients I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   For accountant Lois Schwartz, it was age 60, when she felt
``completely burned out. ... I had worked 80 hours a week for two
years, without a day off. Including holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   For superstar Barbra Streisand, 58 is the age to retire from her
public singing career, which she will do after four highly
publicized concerts this month.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone with a job, there comes a time to retire.
Determining, from an emotional standpoint, precisely when to leave
the work force is one of the most life-altering decisions a person
can make _ and, ironically, one of the least studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know much about it,'' said Terry Alan Beehr, a
psychology professor at Central Michigan University in Mount
Pleasant. ``Economists have studied it using financial models, but
money doesn't explain everything.''
</P>
<P>
   From a psychological point of view, ``there's just not much
research on that, period,'' Beehr said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the decision process is hard to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speculation would be _ and this is just speculation _ that
it's harder to get that kind of information,'' said Andy Eschtruth
of the Center for Retirement Research at Boston College. For
financial and health-related retirement topics, ``there are data
sets available, providing hard numbers. This is a softer issue,''
demanding in-depth interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers may focus more on the emotional and
psychological aspects of the retirement decision as the working
population ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to change with the baby boomers retiring,''
said Jean Talaga, who holds a doctorate in
industrial/organizational psychology and has examined gender
differences in retirement decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomers are interested in finances, but other issues also are
important, such as making sure they feel their lives are
fulfilling,'' said Talaga, of Grand Rapids, Mich. ``So I think in
the future there will be more research from that standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   For now, when trying to explain the timing of their decision,
people from the famous to the ordinary tend to resort to that vague
``It's just time'':
</P>
<P>
   _ Rock legend Tina Turner announced her retirement in July.
``Sixty is a good time to stop,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Houston Comets star Cynthia Cooper, 37, announced her
retirement at the end of this season, after 15 years of pro
basketball. ``I just think it's time to move on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lynn Crooks retired in July after 31 years as an assistant
U.S. attorney in Fargo, N.D. ``I think it's just time,'' said
Crooks, 59.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alfreda Wilson, 73, retired in February after 30 years as
organist at Ray Winder Field in Little Rock, Ark., playing for the
Arkansas Travelers baseball team. ``It's just time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finances do figure greatly into the retirement timing decision.
But, perhaps surprisingly, money is not the most important factor.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Cornell University's Retirement and Well-Being Study tracked 664
people, older workers and recent retirees ages 50 to 72, from 1994
to 1999. Participants were surveyed every two years. One question
focused on reasons for retiring when they did.
</P>
<P>
   Their top answer: About 70 percent said they ``wanted to do
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Retirement expert Marion Haynes agreed that is a good benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave when there's something else you'd rather be doing, not
just because you want to get away from work,'' said Haynes from his
Springdale, Ark., home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after a 35-year career, Haynes retired from Shell Oil
Co. as manager of pensioner relations. He is a past president of
the International Society of Retirement Planning and author of
several books, including ``From Work to Retirement'' and ``The Best
of Retirement Planning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's life is so different,'' Haynes said. ``The bottom
line is this: What else would you be doing with your time _
traveling, or caring for an elderly parent, or serving on a
community board _ if you weren't at work?''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, the accountant, worked for 45 years before retiring
from a large manufacturing firm in 1997. Now she tends the garden
of her Columbus, Ohio, home, in addition to painting and bowling _
``but I've bowled forever,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   She also takes care of her ailing parents. Her mother broke a
hip last year, and her father has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz began seriously considering retirement in the
mid-1990s. After examining her finances and medical insurance
options, she figured she could leave at age 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also started playing bridge a couple years before I
retired,'' she said. ``I decided I needed a new interest. Bridge,
that's a fascinating game.'' Now she plays on Friday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience provides examples of what researcher Beehr calls
``retirement push and pull variables.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz was burned out by her job, which pushed her toward
retirement; she was pulled toward retirement by her healthy
financial situation and outside interests.
</P>
<P>
   Other push variables may include employee cutbacks, employer
incentives and workplace social factors (not getting along with
co-workers). Pull variables might be more time for relaxation,
concentrating on hobbies or doing volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   One important consideration for former advertising executive
Hatcher was timing _ getting out while the getting was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to leave feeling you got beat,'' said Hatcher,
now 74, who lives in Manhattan. ``You'd like to leave feeling you
kicked the last butt you could kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, who worked on ad campaigns including ``Ford has a
better idea,'' retired nine years ago from McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising in New York. A week later he got a call from
the office: Would he help finish a project? So, for several years,
he worked part time.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees choose to transition into retirement by doing
that. The 10th annual Retirement Confidence Survey shows that 25
percent of retirees in 2000 have worked for pay since they have
been retired. Of those, 75 percent report they are doing so because
they ``enjoy work and want to stay involved.''
</P>
<P>
   That survey, of 1,000 adults (779 workers and 221 retirees), was
conducted by the American Savings Education Council and the
Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the occupation itself affects the timing of
retirement. University of Illinois research just out shows that
farmers, for example, are nearly twice as likely to continue
working beyond age 65 than are workers of similar age in other
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older farmers simply don't think about retirement most of the
time,'' said Andrew Sofranko, professor of human and community
development, in announcing the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of young people around them reminding them
of their older age,'' Sofranko said. ``And unlike a lot of other
professions, no one is encouraging their retirement to reduce a
company's payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,700 Illinois farmers responding to the survey, 25
percent were 65 or older; this compares with about 13 percent of
all workers nationwide who are 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the decision when to retire remains a very
individual one, perhaps because it signals an end as well as a
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's owning up to our mortality,'' Haynes said. ``Depending on
one's viewpoint, you can say that you've gotten work out of the way
and can get on with living. But often the attitude seems to be,
life is more over than what lies ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9144 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-SELMA-REVISITED-NNS &LR;      09-11 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-REVISITED-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA CITY REVISITS ITS CIVIL RIGHTS HISTORY IN MAYORAL RUNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, Sept. 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of activist Lilly Brown (NNS6) and
activists at a get-out-the-vote rally (NNS7) For informaion about
purchasing this photo call 202-383-7824 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Election is Tuesday, Sept. 12 
 By JONATHAN TILOVE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ By car, van, bus and plane, scores of activists _
some of whom were in Selma in 1965 and some who had never heard of
it until last week _ poured into this small Alabama city in advance
of Tuesday's election. Their mission: to defeat, at long last, the
white mayor who has held power since the bloody voting rights
confrontations that ultimately empowered blacks throughout the
South.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their mecca,'' said Joe T. Smitherman, the object of
their animus.
</P>
<P>
   It would be, he acknowledged, a nice symbol for the activists,
an easy story for the national media were he to lose Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But to Smitherman, now 70, his transformation from diehard
segregationist to the mayor of an administration dominated by black
department heads, and dependent on black votes to survive, is as
telling a symbol of change as anything these modern-day freedom
riders hope to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Either way it goes, the symbol that is Selma will be burnished
or burdened anew as voters in a city with more civil rights history
per capita than any place in the nation decide whether _ as his
opponents' slogan puts it _ ``Joe Gotta Go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-some-odd years ago, Selma began the process of changing
America. Selma was part of the wall coming down in Germany. Selma
was part of ending apartheid in South Africa,'' said Emmanual ben
Avraham, a community activist from Trenton, N.J., who was back in
Selma this week.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, it is time for Selma to do for Selma what it did
for the world.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In ways charming or chilling, depending on one's mind-set and
experience, Selma, Ala., appears undisturbed by time. Remove the
cars from the truly Broad Street that is the city's spine, and one
could shoot a movie set in 1960 or 1920 or 1850.
</P>
<P>
   Antebellum buildings dominate the landscape. The Rexall sign on
the pharmacy appears at once vintage and pristine. Walk in, in
search of a map, and the reply is, there aren't any, but where you
trying to get to?
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman's visage peers down from posters on many of the
second-story exteriors.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's challenger is James Perkins Jr., at 47 making his
third run at Smitherman. Each time he comes closer, this time, in
the Aug. 22 preliminary election, falling behind Smitherman by 276
votes only after the absentee ballots were counted. But he had
forced a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Smitherman's days ought to be numbered. Selma
has 9,300 black voters and 5,700 white voters. Smitherman will get
virtually all the white vote, and Perkins the overwhelming majority
of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   When Smitherman was first elected mayor in 1964, Selma had
10,000 white voters and 300 black voters. This time, said
Smitherman, ``I've got to get about 1,000 black votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins has run a pretty low-profile campaign. A computer
consultant, he is the protege of F.D. Reese, the civil rights
leader, educator and pastor who made the first serious run by a
black candidate against Smitherman in 1984. Perkins managed that
campaign, but Reese didn't come close.
</P>
<P>
   According to attorney J.L. Chestnut, a leading figure in Selma's
black community, Reese made the tactical mistake of trying to pick
up some white support, a fruitless exercise that only undermined
black turnout.
</P>
<P>
   All the real noise against Smitherman this year comes not from
Perkins but from Rose Sanders, a law partner with Chestnut, and her
husband, Hank, a state senator. Together they wield enormous
influence throughout Alabama's Black Belt, so named for its rich
soil but as fitting a sobriquet for its concentration of
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Sanders especially is loved and hated in Selma, and
Smitherman said his main purpose in running is because ``I don't
want Rose Sanders taking over the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, it is Smitherman who uses words like ``diversity'' and
``inclusion.'' To ``Joe Gotta Go,'' the Smitherman campaign
replies, ``Why Change?'' on an ad trumpeting the fact that ``Blacks
have 9 of 13 of the Highest Paid Positions in the City,'' from
police and fire chiefs to cemetery sexton.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``What more can you change other than make it all black, and I
think that would be bad for Selma,'' Smitherman said, adding that
no matter Tuesday's outcome, ``You are looking at the last white
mayor of Selma.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, Smitherman's longtime antagonist even as they have
forged a relationship of mutual respect, said that the mayor's
attempt to present himself as some kind of symbol of racial
progress is clever, and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's misleading because nobody has traded more effectively on
racial division in this town as successfully or as long as he
has,'' Chestnut said. ``For nearly 40 years he's been running as
the last white hope.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chestnut charged, Smitherman has given blacks
just enough to stay in power, and taken credit for all the things
the federal government would have required him to do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the most gifted politicians I've ever met,''
Chestnut said. But he added, ``There is no way that Joe Smitherman
can win this election. He has to steal it.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of fraud and intimidation have been flying in both
directions, and when the call went out to civil rights activists
around the country, scores of folks from as far away as California
and New England responded. So did students from Tulane University
in New Orleans, Tougaloo College in Jackson, Miss., the University
of Mississippi in Oxford and Fisk University in Nashville, Tenn.
The NAACP dispatched 75 staff and volunteers from throughout the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   It echoed the city's history. In the 1960s, the black community
invited first the Student Non-Violent Coordinating Committee and
later the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, led by Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr., to come to Selma to press for voting
rights. Selma was chosen because it had the kind of hard-edged
white resistance that the movement needed to make its case plain to
a watching world.
</P>
<P>
   When blacks in Selma attempted to march to Montgomery in 1965,
they were met at the Edmund Pettus Bridge by state troopers and a
county sheriff's posse who beat them bloody. It became known as
``Bloody Sunday'' and led directly to enactment of the 1965 Voting
Rights Act, which opened the floodgates of black political
empowerment in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, of course, Smitherman was a leader of the white
resistance,infamously referring to Martin Luther King as ``Martin
Luther Coon.'' It was, he said, a slip of the tongue, but one that
he acknowledges he will take to his grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really wanted to come to Selma. I saw the whole mess
on television,'' said Margaret Scrivens, of Nashville, who came,
nonetheless, as part of the latest NAACP entourage. ``I felt
obligated.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Melissa Burch, a Canadian by birth who now lives in
New Orleans, said, ``I never heard of Selma until a couple of weeks
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Burch is associated with Estacion Libre, which works on behalf
of the people of Chiapas, Mexico. Earlier this year, she was an
observer at the Mexican elections that ousted the ruling party
after 71 years in power. On Sunday she was here, distributing
election literature to residents of the George Washington Carver
Homes, a housing project on Martin Luther King Street.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, inside First Baptist Church where services were soon to
start, the complexity of Selma's racial politics was fully in
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In the last pew, Gloria Shears, head of the usher board,
expressed her displeasure with the ``Joe Gotta Go'' campaign. She
considered it coarse and mean. ``Joe's helped a lot of people,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   One pew forward, Louella Wilkins, who moved down from New York
in hopes of reviving a black boarding school outside Selma, reacted
with shock.
</P>
<P>
   Shears was part of the protests back in 1965. She marched with
King. She was arrested. ``I was right in the middle of it,'' she
said. ``It was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was necessary, don't you think?'' Wilkins asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, said Shears. But that was then; she was young. She is
older now.
</P>
<P>
   She knows Selma remains a terribly divided and prejudiced place.
She has white friends who are the ``dearest, sweetest people'' one
could find. They visit each other's homes. But, she said, they have
to hide that fact from other white friends. ``Isn't that
terrible?''
</P>
<P>
   While Shears and Wilkins talked, a white women in shorts and a
``Resist'' T-shirt stepped into the church and offered them fliers
about voting. Michelle Gross of Minneapolis, Minn., had come to
Selma to help out however she could.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, Gross said, she doesn't believe in voting. It only
legitimizes the system. But there are exceptions, she said, and
this is one.
</P>
<P>
   To D'Linell Finley, a political scientist at the University of
Alabama, the presence of folks like Gross is as likely to hurt as
help the effort to oust Smitherman.
</P>
<P>
   But the symbolic weight of everything about Selma makes such
practical considerations almost beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   For many who arrived here in recent days, it is about something
unfinished. There is something unsatisfying about the Selma story,
something that they cannot let stand.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, at least for a moment, said Gloria J. Sweet-Love,
president of Tennessee's NAACP _ who came down to Selma despite a
bad leg and doctor's orders _ the whole world is watching. And, she
said, if after the votes are counted, Joe has gotta go, ``I think
people around the world will be jumping and shouting, `It's finally
happening where it began, in Selma, Alabama.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
