<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-US-AUSSIERIVALRY-NNS &LR;      09-11 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AUSSIERIVALRY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIES REPLACE SOVIETS AS AMERICANS' BIG RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, Sept. 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By PAT BORZI  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not Ali-Frazier, Yankees-Red Sox or John Rocker-Mets fans.
Not yet, anyway. But the words are already flying in what could be
the best Olympic big-country rivalry since the breakup of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Outspoken U.S. swimmer Gary Hall hadn't even boarded the plane
to Sydney when he trashed Australian swimmers, boasting the United
States ``would smash them like guitars'' once the Olympics commence
this week in Sydney. So much for diplomacy. Australia adores its
swimmers like rock stars, and from across the Pacific, two-time
1,500-meter gold medalist Kieran Perkins answered with a harsh,
personal slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take a lot of notice of drug cheats,'' said Perkins,
referring to Hall's two positive marijuana tests, the second
earning Hall a three-month suspension in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This followed Australian long jumper Jai Taurima's startling
assertion that America's ``dark athletes'' don't jump well in cold
weather, which Savante Stringfellow said inspired him to beat
Taurima at a pre-Olympic meet in Brisbane last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Red Menace is no more. But the country that gave the
world Olivia Newton-John, Rod Laver and ``Waltzing Matilda'' offers
the biggest challenge to the United States in this XXVII Olympiad,
boosted by the home-country advantage the United States enjoyed
four years ago in Atlanta. Opening ceremonies are Friday, but play
begins in soccer Wednesday (men) and Thursday (women).
</P>
<P>
   From swimming to softball, Australians are good in many
traditionally strong U.S. events. The depth isn't there, especially
in track and field, but the top-end quality is. The United States
should still win more medals, though it won't be like Atlanta, when
its 44 more than quadrupled Australia's nine.
</P>
<P>
   And though Australia embraced the world at the 1956 Games in
Melbourne, U.S. athletes and coaches aren't expecting similar
warmth this time. Take softball, where Australia has been trying to
knock off the United States for years. ``Hopefully, things won't be
thrown from the stands at us,'' said pitcher Michele Smith.
</P>
<P>
   That rivalry goes back to 1996, when Australia handed the United
States its only loss in Atlanta because Dani Tyler missed the plate
on a home run. Two years ago the United States bested Australia for
the world championship, and the United States is 5-0 against them
since Dot Richardson rejoined the team last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've played them since '96, it's been a battle,''
said Smith, who joked she might do the Bobby Bonilla thing and wear
earplugs to block out the crowd. ``They don't like us a whole lot.
We don't like them a whole lot. That's what is going to make it so
great and so exciting. And the fact it's going to be in their home
country is going to make it bigger and better.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time those teams meet Sept. 21, the Aussie-American thing
should be rolling. The first medals are awarded Saturday in women's
triathlon, and Australia could sweep with world champion Nicole
Hackett and top-ranked Michellie Jones and Loretta Harrop. Imagine
the party if that happens. ``I really want to head-start the
Australian team,'' Harrop said.
</P>
<P>
   That night, at the 17,000-seat Aquatic Center, 17-year-old
Aussie sensation Ian Thorpe is heavily favored in the 400
freestyle, where he holds one of his 10 world records. The United
States has no one in Thorpe's class.
</P>
<P>
   And the women's 4 x 100 relay with '96 200 butterfly gold
medalist Susie O'Neill should challenge a veteran U.S. group with
former gold medalists Jenny Thompson, Dara Torres and Amy Van
Dyken. The United States barely beat the Aussies for the team title
in last year's Pan Pacific Championships, and U.S. Women's Coach
Richard Quick knows the Americans had better tune out the
pro-Aussie crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a little bit of an adjustment, but a
powerful adjustment,'' said Quick, who coaches Thompson and Torres
at Stanford Swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's taking on the atmosphere of a United States vs.
Australia dual meet. Their goal is obviously to win as many gold
medals as they can. Our goal is to defend our position as the best
swimming country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the host country twice earned Australia generous
tournament seedings. In women's soccer, the world's top teams _ the
United States, Norway and China _ were bunched in the opposite side
of the draw from Australia. And Australian beach volleyball pairs
Lee Zahner/Julien Prosser and Natalie Cook/Kerri Potthurst drew top
men's and women's seeds ahead of Brazilian and American teams with
higher world rankings, easing their paths to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Australia should win women's field hockey gold; the
United States didn't qualify. In track the United States has no
answer for women's world 400 champion Cathy Freeman, an Aborigine
and one of the country's biggest sports heroes. Australia's Emma
George faces Stacy Dragila, who broke her world record, in the
first Olympic women's pole vault.
</P>
<P>
   In women's basketball, and to a lesser extent men's rowing
eights, Australia presents enough problems to the favored United
States to make home crowds a factor. ``When we go to Australia,
they're going to want to rip us (apart) and send us home,'' said
U.S. basketball player DeLisha Milton. ``Our goal is to win.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   But to Smith, everything comes down to softball. In their last
two championship meetings, in 1998, Lisa Fernandez beat the Aussies
in the South Pacific Classic (perfect game) and the world
championships (one-hit shutout plus a home run). Incentive? The
Aussies have plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their whole country is going to be behind that team,'' Smith
said. ``They have a lot of good chances for medals, but I think
even more so, this is the sport they want to come home with that
gold medal. And we're going to be there making sure it doesn't
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
