u k BC-RETIRE-WHEN-NNS &LR;      09-11 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-WHEN-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL ASPECTS OF RETIREMENT RANK HIGH, BUT ARE LITTLE STUDIED 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Monday, Sept. 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Note time element in 3rd graf, Streisand
concerts are Sept. 20-21 and Sept. 27-28 
 ART ADVISORY: With a photo of Terry Alan Beehr (NNS1); and with a
graphic listing people's reasons for retiring. For information
about purchasing theis photo call 202-383-7824.
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For ad man Edgar Hatcher, retirement came at age 65, after ``I
had done work for all the clients I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   For accountant Lois Schwartz, it was age 60, when she felt
``completely burned out. ... I had worked 80 hours a week for two
years, without a day off. Including holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   For superstar Barbra Streisand, 58 is the age to retire from her
public singing career, which she will do after four highly
publicized concerts this month.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone with a job, there comes a time to retire.
Determining, from an emotional standpoint, precisely when to leave
the work force is one of the most life-altering decisions a person
can make _ and, ironically, one of the least studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know much about it,'' said Terry Alan Beehr, a
psychology professor at Central Michigan University in Mount
Pleasant. ``Economists have studied it using financial models, but
money doesn't explain everything.''
</P>
<P>
   From a psychological point of view, ``there's just not much
research on that, period,'' Beehr said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the decision process is hard to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speculation would be _ and this is just speculation _ that
it's harder to get that kind of information,'' said Andy Eschtruth
of the Center for Retirement Research at Boston College. For
financial and health-related retirement topics, ``there are data
sets available, providing hard numbers. This is a softer issue,''
demanding in-depth interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers may focus more on the emotional and
psychological aspects of the retirement decision as the working
population ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to change with the baby boomers retiring,''
said Jean Talaga, who holds a doctorate in
industrial/organizational psychology and has examined gender
differences in retirement decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomers are interested in finances, but other issues also are
important, such as making sure they feel their lives are
fulfilling,'' said Talaga, of Grand Rapids, Mich. ``So I think in
the future there will be more research from that standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   For now, when trying to explain the timing of their decision,
people from the famous to the ordinary tend to resort to that vague
``It's just time'':
</P>
<P>
   _ Rock legend Tina Turner announced her retirement in July.
``Sixty is a good time to stop,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Houston Comets star Cynthia Cooper, 37, announced her
retirement at the end of this season, after 15 years of pro
basketball. ``I just think it's time to move on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lynn Crooks retired in July after 31 years as an assistant
U.S. attorney in Fargo, N.D. ``I think it's just time,'' said
Crooks, 59.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alfreda Wilson, 73, retired in February after 30 years as
organist at Ray Winder Field in Little Rock, Ark., playing for the
Arkansas Travelers baseball team. ``It's just time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finances do figure greatly into the retirement timing decision.
But, perhaps surprisingly, money is not the most important factor.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Cornell University's Retirement and Well-Being Study tracked 664
people, older workers and recent retirees ages 50 to 72, from 1994
to 1999. Participants were surveyed every two years. One question
focused on reasons for retiring when they did.
</P>
<P>
   Their top answer: About 70 percent said they ``wanted to do
other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Retirement expert Marion Haynes agreed that is a good benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave when there's something else you'd rather be doing, not
just because you want to get away from work,'' said Haynes from his
Springdale, Ark., home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after a 35-year career, Haynes retired from Shell Oil
Co. as manager of pensioner relations. He is a past president of
the International Society of Retirement Planning and author of
several books, including ``From Work to Retirement'' and ``The Best
of Retirement Planning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's life is so different,'' Haynes said. ``The bottom
line is this: What else would you be doing with your time _
traveling, or caring for an elderly parent, or serving on a
community board _ if you weren't at work?''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, the accountant, worked for 45 years before retiring
from a large manufacturing firm in 1997. Now she tends the garden
of her Columbus, Ohio, home, in addition to painting and bowling _
``but I've bowled forever,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   She also takes care of her ailing parents. Her mother broke a
hip last year, and her father has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz began seriously considering retirement in the
mid-1990s. After examining her finances and medical insurance
options, she figured she could leave at age 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also started playing bridge a couple years before I
retired,'' she said. ``I decided I needed a new interest. Bridge,
that's a fascinating game.'' Now she plays on Friday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience provides examples of what researcher Beehr calls
``retirement push and pull variables.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz was burned out by her job, which pushed her toward
retirement; she was pulled toward retirement by her healthy
financial situation and outside interests.
</P>
<P>
   Other push variables may include employee cutbacks, employer
incentives and workplace social factors (not getting along with
co-workers). Pull variables might be more time for relaxation,
concentrating on hobbies or doing volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   One important consideration for former advertising executive
Hatcher was timing _ getting out while the getting was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to leave feeling you got beat,'' said Hatcher,
now 74, who lives in Manhattan. ``You'd like to leave feeling you
kicked the last butt you could kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, who worked on ad campaigns including ``Ford has a
better idea,'' retired nine years ago from McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising in New York. A week later he got a call from
the office: Would he help finish a project? So, for several years,
he worked part time.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees choose to transition into retirement by doing
that. The 10th annual Retirement Confidence Survey shows that 25
percent of retirees in 2000 have worked for pay since they have
been retired. Of those, 75 percent report they are doing so because
they ``enjoy work and want to stay involved.''
</P>
<P>
   That survey, of 1,000 adults (779 workers and 221 retirees), was
conducted by the American Savings Education Council and the
Employee Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the occupation itself affects the timing of
retirement. University of Illinois research just out shows that
farmers, for example, are nearly twice as likely to continue
working beyond age 65 than are workers of similar age in other
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older farmers simply don't think about retirement most of the
time,'' said Andrew Sofranko, professor of human and community
development, in announcing the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of young people around them reminding them
of their older age,'' Sofranko said. ``And unlike a lot of other
professions, no one is encouraging their retirement to reduce a
company's payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,700 Illinois farmers responding to the survey, 25
percent were 65 or older; this compares with about 13 percent of
all workers nationwide who are 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the decision when to retire remains a very
individual one, perhaps because it signals an end as well as a
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's owning up to our mortality,'' Haynes said. ``Depending on
one's viewpoint, you can say that you've gotten work out of the way
and can get on with living. But often the attitude seems to be,
life is more over than what lies ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-END-MAINBARDAY3-COX     09-11 1980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-END-MAINBARDAY3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day3 main death story
 &HT;    Treat patient's suffering as well as the disease
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - For Sharon Morgan, the conversation didn't take
place until her mother arrived at the emergency room, in septic
shock for the fourth time in less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, she didn't expect Dr. Basel Yanes to suggest letting
her mother die. She knew sepsis, a common infection among cancer
patients, is life-threatening on its own. She's a registered nurse.
``But in our minds, this was something you could fix,'' she said.
Her mom had survived it three times.
</P>
<P>
   But come to think of it, Mary Monnin had shared some regret
about surviving that last sepsis. Even if she pulled through this
time, she didn't figure to live more than another two months while
her multiple myeloma became progressively more painful. Her living
will was clear that she didn't want to endure a lot of heroic
measures to extend her life.
</P>
<P>
   All Yanes had to do for Morgan, her father and 11 siblings, was
connect the dots. ``He knew this was a good time to let go,''
Morgan said of Yanes, who directs cancer care at Miami Valley
Hospital and chairs its palliative care committee.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation Yanes initiated doesn't happen often enough or
soon enough, dozens of health care workers and patients' family
members agree. They told the Cox News Service that is the main
reason barely two in 10 people use hospice services when a loved
one has a terminal illness, and those who have hospice services are
there for a median length of only 29 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to let go,'' Morgan said. ``You don't want to let
go. But I'm very glad he brought it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients and families generally don't want to discuss impending
death and doctors don't know how to. They aren't trained in
breaking bad news, and more fundamentally, they aren't trained in
battling anything beyond illness and injury, even though the need
for care continues after that battle is lost
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to bring the mindset of physicians more into making
sure the patient's suffering is treated in addition to the disease
being treated,'' Dr. Richard Wyderski said.
</P>
<P>
   That is the purpose of the elective course Wyderski teaches to
new doctors in Wright State University's internal medicine program
at Miami Valley. It's called palliative medicine, which is the
comforting treatment that goes on after the classic curative
treatment has failed. More and more residency programs also are
incorporating hospice care.
</P>
<P>
   Monnin, 69, did not go to a hospice but received some of its
psychological benefits in Miami Valley's palliative care program,
which shares the hospice philosophy that terminal illness brings
the opportunity to actually live today as if it might be your last.
She achieved another goal of palliative care by dying about 12
hours after her trip to the ER in July and bypassing the
disheartening steps of deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was there one day and the next day she was gone,'' Morgan
said. ``There was no in-between. She could still go to the bathroom
by herself and take a shower. The in-between is what's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fears of dying patients are pain and becoming
burdens to their families, research shows. A report in the May 16
Annals of Internal Medicine listed several other elements of what
hospice advocates now are calling a ``good death.''
</P>
<P>
   They want to be involved in medical decision-making and prepared
for what their disease will do to them. To resolve conflicts and
say goodbye. To energize their spirituality. To remain with loved
ones. To keep contributing to others' well-being. And to be
recognized until death as complete people, not overlooked or
dismissed like wallpaper or a finished novel.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to stay alive as long as it's absolutely possible
to keep living meaningfully. Good-death advocates forget to mention
that sometimes, but for people experiencing it, ``good death'' can
be ``a tough phrase to swallow,'' said James Londis, Kettering
Medical Center's ethics director.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern, even among those committed to palliative care,
that doctors should not be so enthusiastic about hospice advantages
that they prepare a patient for death before all reasonable options
are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People beat the odds every day,'' said Mary Murphy, who leads
a Hospice of Dayton team that draws on specialties in grief
counseling, financial management, psychology, spirituality,
nursing, home care and pain relief. ``If you're a doc and you've
seen that, you're thinking any person could be one of them. Some
people, you don't know why they make it out the doors, but they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   So even when doctors decide no more can be done to cure a
disease, Yanes said they keep accounting for the possibility that
they're wrong. ``You tend to err on the side of doing more than
doing less. You can reverse that decision. You can't reverse the
decision to let the patient die.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes experience to learn when trying to extend a life ``is
really just extending the dying process,'' said Dr. Cathie Zofkie
of Kettering Medical Center, who specializes in caring for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most physicians are not trained to do these things,'' Yanes
said. ``We learn how to treat diseases, but we lack knowledge in
the areas of emotional support and how to break bad news to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to learn that caring for patients is not just helping
control their disease, but also helping them learn to live with
their disease. Our job is also to relieve suffering, control their
symptoms, help them emotionally to deal with the disease. I think
we need to learn that when we fail to control a disease, that does
not mean our job ends.''
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental model of medicine changes at that point, said
Miami Valley pain specialist Dr. Townsend Smith. All the basic
medical goals of diagnosing and curing are abandoned in favor of
alleviating symptoms. Whether the symptom is nausea or pain,
loneliness or depression, palliative care requires the same focus
that an oncologist takes when downplaying the side effects of
chemotherapy for the primary goal of curing the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   That shift toward comfort can't completely take place without a
conversation among doctor, patient and family. The subject is less
taboo than it was, said Beth Delaney, Miami Valley's
palliative-care coordinator. ``But it's not something we routinely
discuss with every patient, and I think that's where we need to
go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients and families don't always want to have that talk,
though. ``One researcher refers to us as the temporarily
immortal,'' Wright State medical ethicist Robert Reece said. ``We
all like to think of ourselves as immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, that delusion is more comforting than pain medication.
``They equate getting treatment with hope,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Others don't believe there's an advantage to hospice care, often
out of misunderstanding. Research by the National Hospice and
Palliative Care Organization indicates fewer than one in 14
Americans associate hospices with pain control or family support.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it widely known that hospice care is covered by Medicare
and more than 80 percent of health plans for large or medium-sized
businesses. Medicare saved $1.52 in 1995 for every dollar it spent
on hospice services, largely by replacing more expensive
hospitalization, according to the national hospice organization.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's mother had her own reasons for avoiding hospice. She
was comfortable with the people at Miami Valley and didn't want to
be constantly interrupted by strangers. She didn't even like it
when Morgan took her blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some families are afraid, 'You're not going to take as good
care of my loved one,' if they choose hospice or palliative care,''
Delaney said. ``We give the same attention to the patient in a
palliative-care mode as we give to the patient in the next bed with
open-heart surgery. The care just has a different purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients don't choose hospice or palliative care to hasten their
deaths but to improve what remains of their lives, said nurse Kathy
Hayes, who coordinates the hospice unit at the Dayton VA Medical
Center. Hospice of Dayton surveys indicate about six of every 10
families wish their loved one had been sent there sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are astounded by our environment,'' Hayes said. ``It's
not a depressing, oh-my-gosh-people-are-dying-here. Our emphasis is
on enjoying the time you have left.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a time for ``finishing unfinished business,'' Murphy said.
``Who do you want to talk to? What do you want to do?''
</P>
<P>
   VA psychologist Nicole Best calls it ``righting wrongs,
forgiving each other, remembering good times and bad times.'' And
everyone connected to hospices talks about relieving pain.
</P>
<P>
   Physical pain can almost always be controlled after doctors have
given up on fighting the disease, pain specialist Smith said.
Higher doses of pain medicines can be given. Patients aren't taking
therapeutic drugs that cause pain. The question is how sedated the
patient wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   Even patients who die after feeding tubes are withdrawn do not
appear to suffer greatly, Zofkie said. Their blood pressures and
heart rates aren't those of people in pain. ``It's more painful
psychologically for the people watching,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Physical pain is easier for most dying patients than their
functional impairments, Smith and Zofkie said. Some can no longer
swallow. Others develop shortness of breath. Anxiety attacks are
fairly common.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person with ALS is not really having any pain,'' Smith said.
``He just can't use his arms or his legs. There can't be anything
more miserable than that. That situation is much more difficult for
improving the quality of life.'' But as he said, palliative care
can concentrate on quality of life as its only goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they never have to give up hope,'' said Dr. Geetika Kumar
of the VA hospice. People beat the odds all the time. The hospice
guideline of six months' remaining life is not an unbreakable rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put many people in hospice who prove me wrong,'' Zofkie
said. ``That's not a failure. I think if every patient you put in
hospice winds up dying, then you're probably not putting enough
people in hospice. You're waiting too long until it's obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens during hospice and palliative care, it's not
likely to begin unless the doctor, patient or family initiates that
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The talk really should be just another step in the doctor's
ongoing communication with them, Yanes said. ``By understanding the
patient's and family's wishes, we can identify situations that can
help them say goodbye or stop aggressive treatment and move on to
the palliative.''
</P>
<P>
   Kumar doesn't go into the discussion by saying it looks like the
patient's not going to make it. ``I will tell them that yes, the
disease is terminal, but you can make the best use of this time for
any last wishes you have, any remorse you have,'' she said. ``The
patient usually understands. Patients usually know when their time
has come.''
</P>
<P>
   They might even be relieved to learn they don't have to keep
trying to save their lives, said Hospice of Dayton's Murphy. Or
they might also slam the figurative door in the doctor's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to emphasize is, when the time is right, do
patients know their choices,'' she said. ``Just as they know they
can get treatment, they also need to know there's a point when
repairing their bodies is no longer possible and what their options
are then. That's part of being an informed consumer, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Web site for the National Hospice and Palliative Care
Organization has consumer brochures at www.hospiceinfo.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
