<P>
   KELLY PRESTON IN PARADISE
</P>
<P>
   KELLY-PRESTON-LIFEBEAT _ Kelly Preston has invited me to spend a
day with her at home in Hawaii, one of three she owns with husband
John Travolta, 46. I expected to find a pampered, self-involved
starlet vacationing with an army of servants. The little I knew of
her _ her marriage to a megastar, a few notable roles opposite some
marquee names, such as Kevin Costner and Tom Cruise, did nothing to
dispel that image. Yet here she is, answering her own front door in
flip-flops, denim shorts, a bikini top and no makeup. I have to
admire a 37-year-old woman who, 10 weeks after giving birth to Ella
Bleu, greets me in the middle of her daughter's mealtime. By Debra
Birnbaum. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Kelly Preston is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOREVER PARENTING
</P>
<P>
   PARENTING-MONEY-LIFEBEAT _ Living and working in Beverly Hills,
I've become all too accustomed to fashionably clad twentysomethings
styling down Rodeo Drive, cell phones pressed firmly to their ears.
Arranging a business meeting? Perhaps. Arranging another ``loan''
from Mom and Dad? More likely. Not to disparage today's young
people, but too many have come to expect their parents' unequivocal
support, financial and otherwise. Blanket approval and a blank
check. By Esther M. Berger. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS TARGET AN ELUSIVE SILENT KILLER
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-OVARIAN-CANCER-LIFEBEAT _ Ovarian cancer has been
nicknamed the silent killer because it is difficult to detect. When
found, it has often spread beyond the ovaries and is too advanced
to cure. Even the symptoms are vague and easily ignored: Who hasn't
felt bloated and tired from time to time? But experts in the field
say that a new National Cancer Institute initiative, the Ovarian
Cancer Early Detection Program, promises to yield more sensitive,
highly specific _ and thus accurate _ screening tests for ovarian
cancer within the next five years. By Vicky Lowry. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Dr. Beth Karlan is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KIDS WHO DO TOO MUCH
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-ACTIVITY-OVERLOAD-LIFEBEAT _ For most kids, September
doesn't just mean back to school, it also means back to music
lessons, karate, dance class, religious education, soccer practice
and tutoring. Whew! While the hours spent at school or day care get
the spotlight, a child's off time can be just as important. If that
off time becomes a source of stress instead of fun, say experts,
the added pressure can negatively affect the time a child spends at
school or day care. By Helen Cordes. 1,250 words.
</P>
