<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WARNING SHOT TO ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore says he would propose new laws to protect children from
violent entertainment, as the Federal Trade Commission released a
report criticizing the movie, music and video-game industries.
``It's hard enough to raise children today without the
entertainment industry making it more difficult,'' Gore said in a
statement Monday. He and running mate Joe Lieberman said that if
elected, they would give entertainment-industry leaders a six-month
deadline to adopt voluntary controls over their products. If the
industry did not begin self-policing, he said, he'd recommend the
FTC take action.
</P>
<P>
   `OPRAH': WHERE THE WOMEN VOTERS ARE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore appeared on the ``Oprah'' season premiere in Chicago
Monday, kicking off a week in which he hopes to solidify gains
among women voters. But he left the talk show diva wanting. ``No
kiss? I was hoping for something,'' Oprah Winfrey shrieked after
Gore greeted her with a handshake and one-armed, half hug. Gore's
lighthearted appearance was the first time Winfrey had invited a
politician to her TV stage. George W. Bush is scheduled to appear
on Winfrey's show Sept. 19. Asked by an audience member if he would
ever make an issue of Bush's drinking history before quitting at
age 40, Gore said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH IN FLORIDA, NOW NO SURE THING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush promoted his health care and prescription drug
proposals Monday in Florida, a state where his brother Jeb is
governor and strategists once believed was firmly in his column for
November. Hoping to ignite momentum, Bush armed himself with a new
slogan and a fresh style, chatting informally with elderly voters
in Clearwater on everything from Cuba to classrooms. In
shirt-sleeves and microphone in hand, Bush stood in the midst of a
packed recreation room answering questions and stressing his ``real
plans for real people'' theme. He briefly talked about his $198
billion plan to overhaul the health-care system for the elderly and
provide them with a prescription drug benefit, sharpening his
differences with Al Gore on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   GORE ON FENCE ON ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been a leading advocate of a $7.8 billion, long-term
Everglades rescue effort, but an airport controversy at the
southern rim of the Florida Everglades is causing him problems. The
dispute over Homestead Air Force Base, less than 10 miles from the
Everglades, has dampened environmentalists' enthusiasm toward him.
Gore has refused to either support or oppose conversion of the base
to a commercial, reliever airport, as some powerful South Florida
Democrats and business interests have urged. The Air Force is
expected to make a decision after completing an environmental
impact review, possibly this month. ``We'd like to see Gore come
out and say he's adamantly opposed to a commercial airport at this
location,'' said Michael Chenoweth, president of Friends of the
Everglades and a national director of the Izaak Walton League.
</P>
<P>
   FACE-LIFT WITH THE SAME FACES
</P>
<P>
   As George W. Bush gives his campaign a face-lift to try to halt
his slide in the polls, there's one thing he hasn't changed: any
faces. No staff shake-up. No calls to the bullpen. No relocation of
headquarters. The same close-knit Texas band that was with Bush two
years ago _ long before the first GOP primary _ is still steering
his campaign today. Among the stalwarts: Don Evans, campaign
chairman; Joe Allbaugh, campaign manager; Karl Rove, chief
political strategist; Karen Hughes, communications director and
close adviser; Mark McKinnon, in-house ad maker.
</P>
<P>
   GORE CONFIDENT OF THREE COMMISSION DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said he expects his campaign to work out a plan for
three prime-time debates with George W. Bush, despite friction
between the two camps over the issue. ``I think that it's clearly
in the public interest to have three 90-minute prime time debates
sponsored by the bipartisan commission,'' Gore told the Chicago
Tribune. ``If (Bush) is ready to accept the commission's basic
recommendation, I'm certain that all the disagreements over the
minor details can be worked out.'' Gore declined to be specific
about details. ``I'm going to let Bill Daley handle it,'' he said,
referring to his campaign chairman, the former secretary of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   GORE CLOSER IN COLORADO POLL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has closed gap with George W. Bush in Colorado, says a
new poll, continuing a pattern that has seen the Democrat catch up
with Republican in many states since the Democratic convention. In
a Talmey-Drake poll taken for the Rocky Mountain News and KCNC-TV
(4 percentage point margin of error) Bush led 43-40 percent, with
the Greens' Ralph Nader at 5 percent, the Reform Party's Pat
Buchanan at 1 percent and Libertarian Harry Browne at 3 percent.
That same poll had Bush up 14 points in July. And an NBC News-Wall
Street Journal national poll (2 percentage point error margin)
showed Gore ahead 45-42 percent, with Nader at 4 percent and
Buchanan at 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIES OF DUKAKIS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is beginning to look to political observers like
another presidential candidate who blew a big post-convention lead:
Michael Dukakis, the pride of Massachusetts, in 1988. Each used his
record as governor of an important state to capture his party's
nomination. Each faced a sitting vice president armed with a go-go
economy. Each came out of his national convention with a sizable
poll lead, as much as 17 percent in both instances. And each
managed to lose that lead by Labor Day. Dukakis never did recover.
</P>
<P>
   BLEAK FUTURE FOR THIRD PARTIES
</P>
<P>
   The splintered Reform Party is the only minor political party
eligible to receive federal funding this year for its presidential
candidate. The Federal Election Commission meets today to decide
whether Pat Buchanan should get the $12.6 million. But there may
well be no money to fight for in 2004. A candidate needs at least 5
percent of the general election vote to qualify his party for
funding in the following presidential election, and Buchanan has
mustered only 1 or 2 percent in recent polls. Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader initially appeared to be the best hope for people
yearning for third-party options this year. Polls had placed his
support as high as 8 percent, but the numbers have since dwindled
to 3 or 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   VEEP CANDIDATES: MAKE IT OR BREAK IT?
</P>
<P>
   So far, it appears, Joe Lieberman has done more for Democratic
candidate Al Gore than Dick Cheney has for Republican George W.
Bush. Whether it matters that much is debatable. Many political
scientists say it doesn't, that people vote for presidents and not
vice presidents. Lieberman, however, isn't so sure. ``Obviously,
the most important element in a vote is the presidential
candidates, but I think vice-presidential candidates could be part
of a decision on who to vote for,'' said Lieberman, attending a
pair of fund-raisers Monday in Dallas. For his part, Cheney says he
wants neither credit nor blame as the campaign's poll numbers rise
and fall.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY'S LOW-KEY STYLE WORRIES SOME
</P>
<P>
   The question is not whether Dick Cheney has the makings of an
excellent vice president. Many Republicans and Democrats say he
might be the most valuable asset for George W. Bush _ as president.
But so far, there is scant evidence that Cheney is helping Bush to
get the top job. GOP grumblings continue that he may be hurting the
ticket. Some longtime Republicans voice particular concern, given
the evident campaign chemistry between Al Gore and his running
mate, Joe Lieberman. One thing appears certain: Lieberman is having
more fun on the campaign trail than his GOP counterpart. While the
taciturn Cheney sometimes seems to be fighting acid reflux, the
smiling and ruddy-faced Lieberman jokes as if he's auditioning for
a comedy club slot.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN'S SENATE FOE CHARGES NEGLECT
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman's Senate challenger, Waterbury Mayor Philip
Giordano, is accusing him of being an absentee politician,
forsaking his Connecticut constituents for a shot at the vice
presidency _ even as he seeks re-election. No one expects the
attacks to do much damage. Lieberman has missed all six of the roll
call votes the Senate has taken since he was tapped as Al Gore's
running mate. And Lieberman plans to be in Washington Wednesday for
a hearing on a Federal Trade Commission report accusing
entertainment industries of marketing violence to minors. In a 1988
campaign ad, Lieberman likened his Senate opponent then _
Republican incumbent Lowell Weicker _ to a slumbering, snoring bear
who missed votes in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO PRESSED ON ARAFAT PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   Staying on the offensive in the latest New York Senate campaign
controversy, Hillary Clinton criticized opponent Rick Lazio again
Monday after a photo surfaced of Lazio shaking hands with Yasser
Arafat. The photo, taken in December 1998, shows Lazio shaking
hands with Arafat and grinning broadly. The White House released
the picture a day after Lazio sharply criticized President Clinton
and the first lady for their own greetings of controversial foreign
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IF THEY HELD AN ELECTION AND _
</P>
<P>
   In her drive toward the final weeks of her Senate campaign,
Hillary Clinton has neglected one thing: she's not the Democratic
candidate just yet. There's a primary Tuesday, and she faces an
opponent. Turnout is certain to be extremely low _ very few people
know a primary is happening _ but that is precisely the danger. The
nightmare scenario going through some party leaders' minds is this:
What if scads of anti-Hillary Democrats show up to cast protest
votes, while nearly everyone else stays home? Could she get tossed
out in a fluke? Her challenger is a 39-year-old Manhattan
orthopedist and Harvard Medica; School graduate named Mark McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   POLLS DIFFER ON CLINTON AND JEWISH VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Two weekend polls put Hillary Clinton's support among Jewish
voters at 70 percent and 52 percent in her Senate race against Rick
Lazio. Some analysts believe that to win statewide in New York, a
Democrat needs at least 60 percent of the Jewish vote. Most recent
statewide polls have had Clinton's support between 50 percent and
60 percent. The New York Post poll showed Clinton's support at 70
percent versus 23 percent for Lazio, while a poll conducted for
Albany's Times Union and the Buffalo News found Clinton leading
52-34 percent. ``I think the truth is probably somewhere in the
middle,'' said independent pollster John Zogby, whose organization
conducted both surveys.
</P>
<P>
   MR. FIX-IT FOR DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   While Al Gore has sought to put distance between himself and the
scandal-plagued President Clinton _ it's been almost a month since
they shared a public podium _ Democratic House and Senate
candidates clamor for the president's presence. Clinton went to
Connecticut Monday to lend a political hand to Rep. James Maloney a
public event in Danbury, then headline a fund-raiser on the
lawmaker's behalf, expected to net $175,000. Monday night the
president was to be in New York for more fund-raisers, including
one benefiting his wife, Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
