</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ACTIVITY-OVERLOAD-LIFEBEAT-1250-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS WHO DO TOO MUCH
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 By HELEN CORDES  
 c. 2000 Child magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most kids, September doesn't just mean back to school, it
also means back to music lessons, karate, dance class, religious
education, soccer practice and tutoring. Whew! While the hours
spent at school or day care get the spotlight, a child's ``off
time'' can be just as important. If that off time becomes a source
of stress instead of fun, say experts, the added pressure can
negatively affect the time a child spends at school or day care.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, several trends are converging to make kids'
leisure time decidedly less leisurely. The amount of free time 3-
to 12-year-olds have each week has shrunk by about an hour and a
half since 1981, reports a recent study at the University of
Michigan in Ann Arbor that compared daily diaries of preschool and
elementary-age kids in 1981 and 1997. The study also showed that
sports participation has doubled to nearly four and a half hours a
week, and time spent going to movies and other events increased
fivefold to more than three hours a week. Enrollment in academic
enrichment classes, like Kumon Math and Reading Centers (which
enroll more than 2.6 million students worldwide and accept kids as
young as 3), is also booming.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind of activities means that time for traditional
children's pastimes _ doodling, playing outside _ is shrinking.
``Creative, spontaneous play is taking a beating,'' says University
of Pennsylvania professor of education Dr. Joan F. Goodman. ``Free
time for playing and imagining is important,'' she says. ``This is
where kids learn to create and think imaginatively. Aren't these
the skills we most want them to develop?''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, family therapists and school counselors are seeing
more stressed-out kids. ``Children as young as preschool age come
in with symptoms including depression, stomachaches, headaches,
fatigue and plain old crankiness,'' says Dr. Ann Vernon, professor
of counseling at the University of Northern Iowa in Cedar Falls.
``We're seeing increased instances of biting, shoving, choking and
other aggressive behavior by preschoolers and early elementary
school children,'' adds Dr. Carlota Schechter an education
professor at St. Joseph's College in West Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   While stress can be caused by many factors, enrichment classes
draw particular ire from some child-development experts.
``Particularly for younger children, these classes force a child to
do something he's not ready to do, which is to sit in a classroom
and learn facts instead of exploring the world through creative
play,'' says Dr. Suzanne Johnson, an associate professor of
psychology at Dowling College in Oakdale, N.Y. When older kids are
put in enrichment classes after a full day of school, it can add
stress, impinge on creative playtime and even dampen a child's
enthusiasm for learning, Dr. Johnson adds. The key is choosing
activities wisely, and keeping in mind that there's no time limit
on learning.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure out if your child's schedule is too stressful?
Compare her behavior on less scheduled days and more scheduled
days, or current behavior with behavior in less busy times. Is she
crankier, more anxious or more sluggish? (Talking with your child's
teacher about her behavior can give you valuable clues.) Evaluate
each activity to determine whether it is worthy of your child's
time. ``The one question I always ask parents about their child's
activities is: 'Is this really meaningful for your child?''' says
Dr. Vernon. If you feel it is, then it's a keeper. If not, then
seriously consider dropping it from your child's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Parents concerned about providing their kids with learning
experiences outside of structured activities should be reassured by
a recent University of Connecticut study. Ordinary activities
(going to the park, helping to prepare meals) provided the richest
learning environment for children. ``Children learn best by doing
ordinary things, especially those the family values,'' reports lead
researcher Dr. Mary Beth Bruder, director of child and family
studies at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Just stepping out the door can be a learning experience.
``Little kids love to watch things outdoors and play around in the
dirt,'' notes Dr. Mary Rivkin, the Baltimore-based author of ``The
Great Outdoors: Restoring Children's Right to Play Outside.'' Older
kids often enjoy identifying animals and plants. They might find
that they like drawing flowers or starting a collection of rocks or
shells. ``When they do that, they are using their sensory skills to
investigate. They're loading up on direct information about nature
and science they will draw on for a lifetime,'' Dr. Rivkin says.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents create free time for their children by choosing
activities that don't require a lot of time, or that allow
flexibility. Emmi Volosov, 41, a mother of two boys, 5 and 8, in
Morehead City, N.C., cut back on the karate program her older son
attended several times a week. ``He wanted to go more often, and I
let him, but then he got burned out,'' says Volosov. ``Now that he
goes just once a week, he really enjoys it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to scale back your child's commitments, be
prepared for some resistance in the beginning, says Dr. Vernon.
``When children become used to stimulation from a lot of activity,
they may find it hard to keep themselves amused at first,'' notes
Dr. Goodman. You may want to schedule more play dates initially to
show kids that they can still keep up with friends outside of
activities. You can also suggest home-based activities kids may
have forgotten, such as doing crafts and reading.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will eventually find something to do, assures Dr. Vernon.
``The job of children, from preschoolers even up to the middle
school years, is to play,'' she says. ``They don't need lots of
structured activities or TV and videos. When you give kids free
time, they find ways to amuse themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Another smart strategy: Schedule family activity ``dates'' that
carry the same importance as the soccer practice, dance class or
enrichment course that they replace. ``When our kids were younger,
we set a time once a week for an hour or two to do something as a
family,'' says Dr. John Covey, co-creator with brother Stephen
Covey of ``The 7 Habits of Highly Effective Families.'' ``No one
would schedule anything else for that night. We did all sorts of
fun things: played games, took walks. It was one of the most
memorable things we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Set realistic goals to increase family time, Dr. Covey adds.
Many families can't eat together every night, but they can pick a
few nights a week and stick to them. Cutting back on TV, video
games and computer time should also be gradual, and Dr. Covey
encourages families to watch some TV programs together. ``Talking
about the show is fun, and sometimes brings up related topics,'' he
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that children aren't the only ones spreading
themselves too thin. Parents are trying to do too much, too, and
children can suffer when parents get cranky and tired. That was the
biggest concern reported by more than 1,000 kids in ``Ask the
Children: What America's Children Really Think About Working
Parents,'' by Ellen Galinsky, co-founder of the Families and Work
Institute in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it may be time to rethink your own schedule.
Dr. Vernon advises, ``Apply the 'Is this meaningful?', question to
your own commitments.'' Adds Walton: ``Children are with us such a
short time. We should enjoy as much time with them as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
