<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-KELLY-PRESTON-LIFEBEA     09-11 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLY-PRESTON-LIFEBEAT-ART-1400-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLY PRESTON IN PARADISE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Kelly Preston is available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By DEBRA BIRNBAUM  
 c. 2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first thing I notice is her breasts. The otherwise petite
blonde answers the door at her unassuming ranch-style house near
Honolulu nursing a newborn. It isn't until she shifts her balance
and shakes her long curly hair from her face that I recognize those
clear blue eyes and realize who's standing before me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to answer the door breast-feeding,'' says
Kelly Preston, laughing as she ushers me inside.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't expect her to either.
</P>
<P>
   Preston has invited me to spend a day with her at home in
Hawaii, one of three she owns with husband John Travolta, 46. I
expected to find a pampered, self-involved starlet vacationing with
an army of servants. The little I knew of her _ her marriage to a
megastar, a few notable roles opposite some marquee names, such as
Kevin Costner and Tom Cruise, did nothing to dispel that image.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here she is, answering her own front door in flip-flops,
denim shorts, a bikini top and no makeup. I have to admire a
37-year-old woman who, 10 weeks after giving birth to Ella Bleu,
not only agrees to pose naked with her baby for a photo shoot but
is confident enough to greet me in the middle of her daughter's
mealtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Preston-Travolta house is remarkably unostentatious. True,
the patio leads right to the Pacific Ocean's deep blue waters, and
there is that skylight-lit indoor pool. But the comfy, casual decor
is more beach house than celebrity manse.
</P>
<P>
   I sneak a peek at the countless framed photographs that fill the
place. Our day's adventures will take us away from her baby for
several hours, but she talks constantly about Ella and 8-year-old
Jett.
</P>
<P>
   Ella has Preston's blue eyes, but her shock of black hair is
clearly her father's, as are her ``big delicious lips.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a Mini-Me of Johnny,'' Preston says, referring to the
character from the Austin Powers sequel. ``He was holding her the
other day, and he did the Mini-Me dance with her. She was even
doing the same sneer that he was. It was hilarious!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, abruptly, she says, ``We did it at home, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It?'' Then ``it'' hits me: ``You had a home birth?'' I
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievably beautiful,'' she says. ``We did it for the
closeness of it _ and for the simplicity.'' A Scientologist,
Preston believes in ``quiet birth,'' an approach that requires
silence _ no music, no talking during labor and delivery. After
giving birth to Jett in a hospital, she and Travolta decided a
quiet birth would be even better at home.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been wondering how to bring up her involvement in the
controversial church, but she's wholly unguarded as she launches
into her defense of the practice. ``We're always recording,'' she
explains passionately. ``You know everything that's going on right
now, although you're not aware of it. So it's just a peaceful,
beautiful entry into this earth.'' So, surrounded by her ob/gyn,
her midwife, an osteopath, a couple of her closest friends and
Travolta, Preston gave birth to Ella in what would become the
baby's own bedroom in their Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Preston was just 16 and living in Australia when she saw a
poster for ``Grease'' and had a flash of foresight: She just knew
she would one day be with the movie's star, the young John
Travolta. At that point, however, she was thousands of miles from
California, and she'd set her sights on a career in advertising.
But when the family moved back to Hawaii after two years, the
would-be advertising executive, whose only acting experience was a
few Japanese commercials, flew to Hollywood for her first screen
test. Years later, she auditioned for a role in ``The Experts,''
opposite Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw John,'' she says, ``I was sitting in the
reception area waiting for my screen test. He was so devastatingly
handsome. I thought, 'Thank God I'm meeting him out here, because I
would be speechless in there.''' Preston got the job.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a glitch: Preston was married to actor Kevin Gage,
though they were on the road to divorce. ``I would come to work
sobbing,'' she recalls, ``and Johnny would give me these 'body
assists''' _ Scientology-speak for a kind of touch therapy _ ``and
I would go from sobbing to completely giggling. I just thought, 'I
would like life to be like this. I want to giggle and laugh and
play and love every aspect of life, because I used to be that
way.''' Preston, who'd found Scientology years earlier through an
acting class, was delighted to discover that Travolta was also a
devotee.
</P>
<P>
   Once the film wrapped, though, they drifted apart. Three years
passed before they were reunited in Vancouver _ both now
unattached. Kirstie Alley invited them to dinner and, playing
matchmaker, seated them next to each other. By the end of the
night, Preston and Travolta had decided to date. Seven months
later, on New Year's Eve in Gstaad, Switzerland, at the stroke of
midnight, Travolta proposed before a group of friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   This month they celebrate their ninth anniversary _ a
near-record for Hollywood. ``There are hard times,'' she admits,
``but they are few and far between. We almost never fight because
we know what pushes each other's buttons, and we have made an
agreement not to push them.''
</P>
<P>
   She's the rule maker in the marriage, that's for certain.
``Without a doubt, my husband is the biggest pushover that God put
on this earth,'' she laughs. ``He will let Jett stay up all night.
I once caught them on the trampoline at 1:30 in the morning. He
told me he was putting him to sleep, then I hear these shrieks of
giggles from the backyard. When Jett was little, I caught them on
the floor in the pantry throwing rice up in the air because it felt
like snow. I said, 'This is all very cool, but Mom is not cleaning
this up.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different when you have kids,'' she says. ``The
greatest moment in my life was right after Ella was born. I was
sleeping in her room with her _ eventually, we'll sleep with Dad,
but first we have to work it out so he doesn't roll over on her.
Anyway, I was lying there; I had nursed her, and she had just
fallen asleep. Jett crawled into bed with me, and I was stroking
him until he fell asleep, too. Right then I realized I had my two
babies. It was the most magical moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Preston and Travolta divide their time among homes in
Hawaii, Los Angeles and Maine, Preston clearly cherishes any time
she can spend in her hometown. ``It feeds me,'' she says simply of
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   And she's not just talking spiritual hunger: Before the hike we
stop at Leonard's, ``the greatest bakery on the island,'' for
malasadas _ the Portuguese doughnuts she calls ``the most insane
thing you've ever had in your whole life.'' I watch in amazement as
she licks the sugar off her fingers, then rummages in the box for
loose crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Our hour-long trek takes us along the side of a mountain,
through lush vegetation, past bamboo trees, to a breathtaking
waterfall. With the exception of a couple of passersby who elbow
each other and wonder aloud, ``Is that Kelly Preston?'' she goes
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   On our way down the trail, a teenager is brazen enough to
approach us: ``Are you a movie star?'' she asks, then collapses
into giggles and runs downhill with her boyfriend in tow.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair question. Preston's scene-stealing turn as Tom
Cruise's fiancee in ``Jerry Maguire'' earned her critical praise,
and her role as a lesbian pro-choice activist in ``Citizen Ruth''
won her fame among the indie crowd. But that's a far cry from the
A-list stardom her husband enjoys (``Battlefield Earth''
notwithstanding).
</P>
<P>
   Is she just along for the ride? She insists not. After all, she
married Travolta three years before his ``Pulp Fiction'' comeback,
when he was still mired in ``Look Who's Talking'' sequels. ``I fell
in love with the man, not the career,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As for her own career, she's determinedly laid-back. ``I decided
a long time ago that life is too short, that I only want to work
with people I really want to work with,'' she says. ``I don't want
to leave my kids for even a minute to work on something that I am
not excited about, or to work with somebody who is a screamer, a
yeller, who makes everybody unhappy. Right now, I'm just trying to
open a script. It's hard,'' and now she's joking again. ``There are
malasadas to eat, waterfalls to climb.''
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
