<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-OPRAH12-COX     09-11 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OPRAH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE PROMOTES FAMILY POLICIES IN 'OPRAH' APPEARANCE
 &HT;    430&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore used an appearance on the
Oprah Winfrey television show Monday to promote his family-friendly
politics, scold the entertainment industry, and try to sustain his
surging popularity among women voters.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president left the talk show diva with at least one
complaint, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``No kiss? I was hoping for something,'' she said after Gore
greeted her Monday with a handshake and one-armed hug. She was
alluding to the lingering kiss Gore gave his wife, Tipper, on the
night he accepted the Democratic presidential nomination last
month.
</P>
<P>
   But after an hour of talk, which wandered from tax policy to
Winfrey's ruby-red stiletto boots, Winfrey marveled that Gore, long
known for his stiff public demeanor, was a ``fun, funny guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to believe, isn't it?'' Gore quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Gore often tried to steer the conversation into policy areas.
But just as often, Winfrey steered the talk into more entertaining
areas, asking the vice president provocative questions that
occasionally led to titters from the mostly female studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during a portion in which Winfrey quizzed Gore
about his favorite things, she asked him about his favorite thing
to sleep in, a question stemming from his wife's disclosure that he
sleeps in the nude.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bed,'' Gore replied. ``You get the picture?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared a bit flirtatious when he complimented Winfrey on
her spike-heeled boots. ``Aren't they great?'' he prompted the
audience before high-fiving Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to charm the audience with his earnest discussion of
his marriage and family. He called Tipper his ``soul mate'' and
declared ``family is first,'' even amid the demands of a
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The two former Nashville journalists briefly reminisced about
their early careers and having crossed paths on assignments
occasionally, although Winfrey expressed some skepticism: ``Do you
really remember that, or did you just research that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance on the season premiere of the hourlong Winfrey
show _ which has an audience of 22 million, mostly women _ reflects
a campaign strategy to solidify their support for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he barely led his Republican rival, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, among women voters. But polls since the
Democratic convention in mid-August have suggested that Gore's lead
among women has grown to double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey, who has given $12,000 to Democrats since 1992, has Bush
scheduled for an appearance on her program next week.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance coincided with the release of a Federal Trade
Commission report that concludes that more needs to be done to
shield youngsters from violent and adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose wife led the campaign for parental guidance labels
in the recording industry more than a decade ago, embraced the
report's findings and called on the entertainment industry to stop
marketing such material to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are calling for in this case is industry
self-restraint and self-regulation, not censorship,'' the vice
president said in a statement. ``It's about parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Florida, said the vice president has no
credibility on the issue because President Clinton and Gore had
raised millions in campaign funds from the entertainment industry.
Bush said Gore is ``changing his tune'' about the industry now that
the election is approaching.
</P>
<P>
   On the Winfrey program, Gore recalled how Tipper had persuaded
the recording industry to place warning labels on their products.
And when he tried to work the FTC report into remarks about
``inappropriate albums'' being marketed to children, Winfrey
stopped him cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're called CDs now,'' she said. ``They've been CDs for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
