<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPICS-MAGAZINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPICS COMMITTEE SUES OVER MAGAZINE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. Olympic Committee, which carefully
guards its rights to the words and symbols associated with the
Olympic Games, has a new complaint: an ``Olympics USA'' magazine
sold by the publisher of the National Enquirer, and filled with
references to Olympic events, athletes and medals.
</P>
<P>
   The publication violates a federal law granting the USOC ``the
exclusive right to use Olympic terminology and symbols,'' the
committee said in a lawsuit filed in federal court in San
Francisco, a week before the opening of the Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks a court order halting distribution of the
magazine and damages for trademark infringement. No hearing has
been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC used the same law to stop a San Francisco organization
from calling its athletic competition the Gay Olympics, a case that
reached the Supreme Court in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But American Media Inc. of Lantana, Fla., which also publishes
the Globe and Star tabloids, said the committee was going too far
by trying to limit what news media could say about the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The law may give the USOC the right to control commercial and
promotional uses of Olympic names and symbols, but ``does not and
could not give (the USOC) the right to prevent editorial coverage
of the Olympics,'' Roger Myers, a lawyer for American Media Inc.,
said in court papers filed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee ``does not own the Olympic athletes, the locations
of sporting events in which they participate or the various sports
that comprise the Olympic competition, and it cannot control
reporting about them,'' Myers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, a monthly publication called ``AMI Specials,''
contains 76 pages of articles and pictures of U.S. Olympic athletes
and their sports. It has ads, but none for products bearing Olympic
names or symbols. It also has a disclaimer saying the publisher and
magazine have no connection with the Olympics, the USOC or any
other official body.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic committee's lawsuit said the disclaimer was too
small to be effective and, in any event, could not excuse the
publisher's failure to seek its consent for use of Olympic words
and symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher ``misappropriated'' the USOC's rights and created
the false impression that the magazine was approved by the
committee, wrote USOC lawyer Jeffrey Benz.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said any law allowing the USOC to control written
descriptions of the Olympics would be unconstitutional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
