<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAIN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONTROVERSIAL BILL REGULATING PAIN MEDICATION HEADED FOR SENATE
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill designed to discourage physician-assisted
suicide may meet strong opposition when it goes to the Senate next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, called the Pain Relief Promotion Act, would impose
criminal penalties if the Drug Enforcement Administration
determines that controlled substances such as morphine were used to
intentionally hasten death.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bill worry that the DEA would have the power to
prosecute physicians who prescribe potentially lethal medications
in the usual course of their medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argue that the bill clearly defines the difference
between using medication to ease pain and using medication to
deliberately kill, and imposes a federal prohibition on
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sponsored in the Senate by Republican Whip Don
Nickles of Oklahoma and Democratic vice presidential nominee Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut and has the support of the American
Medical Association. The bill passed the House by a vote of 271-156
last October. President Clinton has expressed concerns about it,
but has not threatened a veto.
</P>
<P>
   John Guest, executive director of the American Pain Foundation,
an independent organization which lobbies for effective pain
management, said the bill would reduce a patient's right to
effective treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system already chills effective use of pain medications.
This would expand the DEA's role from fighting illegal drug
trafficking to regulating the practice of medicine,'' Guest said at
a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge that Congress instead develop and pass legislation
that addresses the real problems in our health care system that
block access to high quality pain and symptom management and
palliative care.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walter Hunter, a member of the Americans for Integrity in
Palliative Care, an umbrella group for organizations that support
the bill, said opponents do not understand its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a hospice physician, this bill will not alter one iota what
I do,'' he said, arguing that the DEA would not be given any
additional authority in reference to assisted suicide
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very good legislation. It says very clearly that
the U.S. government recognizes the importance of pain relief.''
</P>
<P>
   If adopted, the bill would largely overturn a 1997 Oregon law
that allows doctors to prescribe lethal dose of pain medications,
but not administer them.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Hamilton, president of the Physicians for Compassionate
Care, said many assisted suicide cases in Oregon have involved
federally controlled substances. The bill would end that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association: www.ama.org/
</P>
<P>
   Stop PRPA Campaign: www.stopprpa.org
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
