r e BC-TV-POPSTARS-TEX     09-11 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POPSTARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `POPSTAR' IS BORN ... OR NOT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ The lobby of the Rodeo Center's Hampton Inn
and Suites is a dizzying blur of activity _ hand- and crane-held
cameras and microphones swirl about, people in matching purple
T-shirts hustle from one room to another, women of all ages and
races chatter, compare outfits and pose for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene Dallas has seen before: A TV network _ in this
case, the WB _ is holding auditions for a new series, and about a
hundred young women have gathered to try out for it.
</P>
<P>
   What seems a little odd, though, is the number of police
officers swarming around. When a member of the WB army _
distinguishable by a purple T-shirt with the name of the series,
``Popstars,'' emblazoned on it _ is asked why so many cops are
here, she says, refusing to give her name, ``in case something
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Like what?
</P>
<P>
   Before she can answer, she is responding to someone else on her
walkie-talkie and quickly scurries away.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the audition room, members of the press are asked
to sign confidentiality agreements, promising not to reveal certain
details of the show. The photographers and writers make the show's
publicist visibly antsy _ staring eyes, sweating brow _ when they
start shooting photos or scribbling notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think this was NASA,'' a fellow reporter whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the hush-hush world of reality-TV auditions, a place
where hopeful actors and actresses are known by numbers, not names;
confidentiality agreements must be signed by all those involved;
and every episode is safe-guarded with Cold War-like intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Following the reality-TV formula, such secrecy is only for the
show, not the hundred or so young women who've gathered for their
shot at TV fame. Just like on the wildy popular ``Survivor'' and
its successor ``Big Brother,'' abandoning your privacy is a
prerequisite for auditioning for ``Popstars.''
</P>
<P>
   The show traces the cutthroat formation of a singing/dancing
girl group, a la Spice Girls, pieced together by three
music-industry people who will handpick the five members through
auditions such as this one. Similar auditions have already happened
in Atlanta, Miami and Chicago. After Dallas, the entourage travels
to New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The first few episodes of ``Popstars'' will feature scenes from
these auditions, which explains why the hotel lobby of the Hampton
Inn in Mesquite is bustling with so many cameras. Every audition is
taped. Some girls will have camera crews follow them around after
the audition. Even the girls who do not make the final cut, they
are told, may appear on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Which means Raegan Payne might just get some screen time after
all.
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly likely candidate to make the final cut, Payne is a
model-gorgeous 22-year-old from Dallas whose audition was one of
the day's most impressive. She's got the look _ slim and trim, with
blond, curly hair showering across her shoulders _ and a strong
voice. But after her audition, which consisted of her singing a few
lines of Christina Aguilera's ``What a Girl Wants,'' she's given a
thumbs-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want me back,'' says Payne, plopped in a chair in
the hotel's lobby. ``I don't have the right look. It could be that
I'm too old. Who knows? They know what they're looking for and if
you're not that, you can't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopes were higher for 18-year-old Dawntoya Pettie, an
18-year-old student at Richland Community College in Dallas. After
her performance, the trio of judges asked her to come back the next
day for another audition.
</P>
<P>
   Pettie says the WB people were talking her up so much, it looked
pretty promising that she would at least be one of the 25 selected
from around the country for the final-five showdown.
</P>
<P>
   That thought seemed even more likely when she was selected by
the WB to be the one and only contestant in Dallas to have a camera
crew follow her every move on Day 2 of the auditioning process.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m. the second day, the crew was at her door, filming her
in her pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watched me pick out the clothes I was gonna wear and
everything,'' Pettie says. ``They interviewed me, my mom, and they
drove to the hotel with us. It was a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to her dismay, though, Pettie didn't survive Round 2. ``I
don't know what the deal was,'' she says. ``This was the closest
I'd gotten to make my dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry folks in charge of the show, of course, are keeping
the who's-in results under lock and key. Even those who've made it
to the last round won't be told until after the final audition in
Los Angeles on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing's for sure, it will take a strong person to do
this,'' says Kelli, a 20-year-old redhead from Dallas who asked
that her last name not be used, perhaps because she's embarrassed
that she, too, was not invited back. ``Cameras following you around
every day, taping everything you do, every conversation you have,
I'm not sure if I could have handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   She sure tried, though.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli says she practiced singing for days; she says she even put
her smoking habit on hold in hopes it would help her voice sound
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Now smoking outside the hotel, Kelli blames her failure on
nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally nervous, and that fouled me up,'' she says,
blowing smoke into the morning air. ``But I'm not really sure I'd
wanna be a part of a girl group. They seem too temporary. But it
would have been cool anyway. Like I'd say, `No, thanks.'''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiments of Kelli and Pettie are echoed throughout the
day. The few who are chosen for callbacks are elated; the ones who
are not chalk it up as experience, dismiss it with a ``they don't
know what they're missing'' or _ and this is certainly no secret _
see it for what it's worth: two fleeting fads rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, getting picked would be a setback,'' says Pettie.
``Because no matter what, people would always look at you as
someone who was on a reality show and in a girl group. I don't know
how far that would have taken me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
