<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAV-JEROME-LADN &LR;      09-11 2593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-JEROME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE TO ITS ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box and captions below) 
ART AVAILABLE 
 
 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
JEROME, Ariz. _ It was the dot-com of its day, a speculative
enterprise that soared, stalled, soared again, then plunged
precipitously and ultimately flickered out.
</P>
<P>
   The byproduct was Jerome, an Arizona frontier town that perches
on a steep hillside in the Mazatzal Mountains, a 110-mile drive
north of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Copper mining was the industry. It was begun in the late 1800s,
but its nosebleed vagaries caused Jerome to go from tent encampment
to boom city to certifiable ghost town by 1955. Then, in the 1970s,
the hippies and bikers and artists found their way here (some
squatting in abandoned buildings), and a tentative percolation back
to life began.
</P>
<P>
   Sightseers can't resist such swings of fortune _ which exemplify
a wilder era of the West _ so ultimately they began trickling in,
too, often on detours from Sedona or Flagstaff to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome stands ready to satisfy them, and all curiosity-seekers
who seek to pick through its gloriously checkered past.
</P>
<P>
   It has been declared a National Historic Landmark, which means
that if anyone acquires one of its crumbling brick ruins and seeks
to rebuild, a degree of integrity must be maintained _ you have to
be faithful to the design of the whorehouse or card parlor that
once stood there. A portion of the town is also a state historic
park, with an exceptional museum (housed in the former mansion of a
mining boss) that chronicles its past.
</P>
<P>
   The mining entrepreneurs picked the site for one reason: Beneath
the surface sat a rich lode of ore, one that would produce 1.45
million tons of copper over the life of the operation (plus 1,700
tons of silver and 47 tons of gold). This proved fortuitous in an
era when the nation was being newly wired for both electricity and
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   The mine bosses were otherwise unconcerned with location, but
they picked a great one. Jerome teeters astride Cleopatra Hill at
nearly one mile in elevation, affording its visitors a spectacular
view to the east of the Verde Valley, Arizona's Mongollon Rim and,
on a clear day, the San Francisco Peaks above Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   You can enjoy that sweep from about any point in town because of
Jerome's unique geography. Again, the mine dictated settlement, and
this one is on a slope that in many places is 50 degrees. There is
a 1,500-foot fall in elevation from the town's highest point to its
lowest, and it's said that in Jerome's heyday, a person could walk
out on his front porch ... and look down the chimney of his
neighbor's kitchen stove.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Jerome don't stroll its streets. They climb them.
And shortcuts across the switchbacks are routinely achieved with
staircases. One such span features 92 steps, another 56. Early one
morning, a local resident was encountered jogging through town. ``I
do all the stairs in town,'' he puffed as he passed. ``It's the
Stairmaster Supreme, especially at this elevation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce lists the number of permanent residents
as 475, but tourism keeps Jerome's pulse strong and steady.
Especially on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you want to incorporate Jerome into an Arizona
excursion, you might want to plan your visit for midweek _ unless,
that is, you own a Harley-Davidson or embrace the biker lifestyle.
The little town reverberates with the noisy motorcycles on weekends
_ in open defiance of a sign on the edge of town feebly warning,
``Vehicle Noise Ordinance Strictly Enforced'' _ and the generally
sullen riders, when not sweltering in their leathers at the town
center, crowd into the Spirit Room to drink beer and rock to a live
band.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors might recoil at this, but actually it's in keeping
with Jerome's heritage. Those weren't choirboys working in the
depths of the mine.
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly evident in a historical walking tour conducted
by Nancy Smith, former curator and archivist for the Jerome
Historical Society. As she led two visitors through a downslope
section of town, Smith pointed to buildings in various stages of
disrepair or restoration and said, ``That was a brothel. That was a
brothel. That was a brothel. They'd usually have a bar, gambling, a
dance hall, rooms for the girls, pool (tables).''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the town's rough edges have since been smoothed over by
craftsmen. The shops here, many of them started by counter-culture
nomads who settled here in the '70s, offer a selection of goods of
exceptional quality: pottery, jewelry, wood carvings, Southwest
baskets, antique glass, wind chimes, textiles, and, fittingly,
copper items ranging from jewelry to gigantic pots.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, some artisans sell their wares from open-air stalls
along the streets. We encountered one persistent fellow selling his
handmade clay flutes. ``The Arabic scale is my favorite,'' he said,
breaking into a plaintive dirge and making the musicianship look
easy.
</P>
<P>
   The general eccentricity of this community is reflected in the
names of its shops: Pure Foolishness &AMP; Artful Stuff. Color Outside
the Lines. One establishment with a more conventional name, the
Jerome Gallery, carries particularly fine merchandise, notably an
elaborate selection of stained-glass kaleidoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome has been a day-trip or pass-through destination for
several years, but it is straining to be considered as an overnight
option. It has a clutch of bed-and-breakfasts, but it celebrated a
pivotal event four years ago when the Jerome Grand Hotel was opened
after a two-year renovation.
</P>
<P>
   That much time was required to whip this lodging property into
shape because the building, a former hospital for mine workers, had
been abandoned for 44 years. ``It's basically an above-ground bomb
shelter done in Spanish Mission,'' proprietor Larry Altherr quipped
of the hotel, which currently offers 22 rooms (with 14 more in the
renovation plans).
</P>
<P>
   The state required a fire-sprinkler system to be put in, which
was kind of laughable because there is virtually no wood in the
five-story vault. Mine officials, who had had trouble with other
buildings cracking, ripping apart and even sliding downhill as the
result of underground tunneling and blasting, built this one for
keeps _ entirely of concrete, with wood used only in windows and
doors.
</P>
<P>
   The Altherr family tore up the ``battleship linoleum'' that was
found throughout and replaced it with carpet, but otherwise sought
to maintain as much of the building's original integrity as
possible. The self-service Otis elevator still works _ you have to
close the cage behind you when you get in _ and the place is heated
through its original steam-radiator system.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's vaguely institutional feel probably can never be
shaken (nor, perhaps, should it be). The hallways and doors are
much wider than you'll find in any other hotel. There is no grand
lobby. And although there are ceiling fans and colorful curtains
and pots of silk flowers in the spotless rooms and hallways, there
are also gray walls, gray carpet and gray-and-white tile in the
bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Advisory: some of the rooms are outfitted only with bathtubs,
and do not have showers. If this is important to you, especially
for an extended stay in a dusty mining town, be certain to specify
this when you make your reservation. Also, be warned: while the
concrete walls often result in pin-drop sleeping conditions, there
are transom windows above the doors to the rooms, and if you leave
yours open, any late-night conversation in the hall will sound as
if it's being conducted at the foot of your bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motto is, `Experience the past,''' said Altherr. ``So
there you go. ... If you want climate control, you need to go to
the Hilton. Here, if you want to make a call, you have to pick up
the receiver and wait. We use the old-fashioned switchboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lodging option in town has a similarly medical theme. It
is the Surgeon's House, the former home of the mine doctor which is
now a four-room bed-and-breakfast inn. ``This is like staying with
Aunt Minnie,'' said owner Andrea Prince, ``except you don't have to
put up with Aunt Minnie.''
</P>
<P>
   Or do you? The inn seemed a pleasant enough place for those who
are comfortable lodging in someone else's house, but Prince seemed
to be a bit fussy. When we asked if we could see a vacant room, she
said, ``No, because if I took you in there I'd have to clean it
again.'' (Gee, thanks.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, there seemed to be a lot of prickly signs posted. One
warned passersby of dogs (she didn't seem to have any). Another
declared that touching the thermostat was ``a no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of Jerome life that required an upgrade to
attract overnight travelers was its dining. Most of its offerings
for dinner are glorified lunch spots _ notably the Jerome Palace
(an after-dinner glass of Grand Marnier was served on !ital!ice)
and the Jerome Brewery, a pizza joint housed in a former automotive
garage.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Jerome Grand Hotel sought to fill this void by
recently opening Jerome's Bistro, a fine-dining restaurant with an
ambitious menu. (It and the hotel's new lounge were not yet open
when we visited in May.)
</P>
<P>
   For breakfast or lunch, meanwhile, it's tough to beat the
Flatiron Cafe, a triangular building that sits where Main Street
and Hull Avenue come to a quirky point. In the morning, it serves
up hearty scrambles, breakfast quesadillas and gourmet coffee
drinks, while its stereo features such intriguing musical artists
as The Innocence Mission and Michelle Shocked.
</P>
<P>
   It's obviously a popular spot with locals, and the restraining
spring on its wooden screen door has long since played out, such
that it bangs reassuringly in the frame every time someone happens
in or out.
</P>
<P>
   These businesses represent quite a comeback from Jerome's
ghost-town days. When the mine was shut down in 1953, its workers
and support folk bolted immediately. Two years later, the
population was estimated to be between 50 and 100 _ down from a
high of about 15,000 in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   My family passed through here on a trip home from nearby Oak
Creek Canyon in 1964, and the place was eerily deserted, an effect
deepened by a dark, threatening cloud cover. Occasionally a face
could be seen peering from behind a curtain, but otherwise there
were absolutely no signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome doesn't seem keen on shedding that image entirely,
though. It has no gas station. It has no market, not even a small
convenience store. It has no liquor store. Not a single fast-food
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   A gas station isn't feasible because current building codes
require that it have a substantial setback from the road, and this
road, remember, clings to a veritable cliff. Meanwhile, markets,
even small ones, have had difficulty squeezing enough commerce out
of those 400-plus residents. Any proprietor must also take on the
expense of maintaining or restoring the historic features of
whatever building he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several come in and try it,'' said Mary Lou
Thompson, who came here in 1949 when her dad took over the garage
(now the brewery). ``We don't want any McDonald's or so forth like
that. We want to keep the flavor of the town as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when your heritage, when the source of your appeal,
lies in ghostly, dilapidated buildings, you certainly don't want to
proceed too quickly on urban renewal. &QL; 
_______ &QL; 
all photos shot by Noland
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME 1)
</P>
<P>
   The Jerome Grand Hotel is a former mine hospital that stood
abandoned for 44 years. The patients' rooms have been turned into
guest rooms, and a restaurant and lounge recently opened on the
property.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME2)
</P>
<P>
   When you visit Jerome, Ariz., you have to be prepared for some
serious climbing. The town was built on a steep mountainside, and
it's not unusual for two parallel roads to be connected by
seemingly endless staircases.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME3)
</P>
<P>
   While many of Jerome's buildings have been carefully restored,
some remnants from its days as a 1950s ghost town are very much in
evidence. Some sorry structures, in fact, appear ready to tumble
down the hillside at any instant.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME5)
</P>
<P>
   !When massive copper deposits were found beneath Arizona's
Cleopatra Hill, a town sprang up to support the mining operation.
Today, Jerome is still hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME6)
</P>
<P>
   !Jerome's merchants aren't about to downplay a history that
included numerous houses of prostitution, as reflected by the names
of some of the boutiques that today occupy former brothels.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME7)
</P>
<P>
   !Restoration is a hit-and-miss proposition in the former ghost
town of Jerome. It's not uncommon to find a renovated residence
standing right next to a crumbling ruin that is home only to
weed-like trees.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME8)
</P>
<P>
   !Because of its designation as a National Historic Landmark,
Jerome maintains a frontier look and feel. High on the hill, the
Jerome Grand Hotel, a former mine hospital, is an unmistakable
landmark.
</P>
<P>
   (TRVL JEROME9)
</P>
<P>
   !Several of the lodgings in Jerome have a medical history,
including the Surgeon's House, a former physician's residence that
is now a bed-and-breakfast inn.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO &QL; 
GETTING THERE: Jerome, Ariz., is about a two-hour drive north of
Phoenix via U.S. 17 and state routes 260 and 89A. It is 27 miles
southwest of Sedona via a scenic stretch of 89A.
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVITIES: The museum at Jerome State Historic Park is an
excellent place to get an overview of the history of the town.
Housed in the Douglas Mansion (eastern edge of town), it is open
daily from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is $2.50 adults, $1 children
ages 7-13. Historical walking tours of Jerome are conducted by
former Jerome Historical Society curator Nancy Smith. Cost is $10.
Phone: (520) 634-8654. Smith, a 28-year resident, is a bit crusty
in manner and doesn't seem to appreciate questions that break up
her prepared commentary, but this is not someone winging the tour
and glossing over unfamiliar parts _ she knows her Jerome history
chapter and verse.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Rooms at the Jerome Grand Hotel (200 Hill St.) start at
$70. You might want to specify a room overlooking the Verde Valley;
the hotel is at the very top of the hillside town and has quite a
view. Phone: (888) 817-6788 or (520) 634-8200. Web:
www.jeromegrandhotel.net. Rooms at the Surgeon's House (101 Hill
St.) start at $100. The Chauffeur's Quarters, detached from the
main house, cost $150. Phone: (800) 639-1452 or (520) 639-1452.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: Jerome's Bistro, which recently opened at the Jerome
Grand Hotel, offers an a la carte menu featuring pasta, seafood,
steaks and chops. Entrees average in the mid-$20s. It's the only
restaurant in town that takes reservations: (520) 639-3197. The
only thing memorable about the Jerome Palace (410 E. Clark St.) was
the view from its wrap-around veranda. Phone: (520) 634-0554. The
Jerome Brewery (111 Main St.), a glorified pizza parlor with
microbrews, is a downscale option. Phone: (520) 639-8477. For
breakfast, it's tough to beat the tiny but comfy Flatiron Cafe (416
Main St.). Phone: (520) 634-2733.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Jerome Chamber of Commerce can be reached at
(520) 634-2900. Web: www.jeromechamber.com. The Jerome State
Historical Park can be reached at (520) 634-5381. It does not have
its own Web site, but information on Jerome is available through
the Arizona State Parks site: www.pr.state.az.us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
