u w BC-ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENC     09-11 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEDS SAY ENTERTAINMENT INDSUSTRY PITCHES SEX, VIOLENCE TO
MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A government report released Monday accused
entertainment companies of aggressively targeting children in their
advertising for sexually-explicit movies, violent video games and
music with explicit content and threatened possible action against
the industry for ignoring its own rating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission Chairman Robert Pitofsky, whose agency
produced the report, said he was developing potential sanctions if
the industry ``is unable to clean up its act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If self-regulation doesn't work, sanctions should be
considered,'' Pitofsky told a news conference here. He emphasized,
however, that he did not believe the FTC should become the
``thought police'' and that ``bureaucrats should in no way try to
influence the work of artists and studios.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic and Republican presidential candidates both
seized the opportunity to comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said that if he is elected president, he
will ask the entertainment industry for a voluntary ``cease-fire''
in marketing inappropriate videos, games and music to children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose wife Tipper began calling for warning labels on
recordings with explicit lyrics in the 1980s, added that his
administration would give entertainment companies six months to
stop targeting children. If they failed, he would encourage the FTC
use its power to prohibit false and deceptive advertising. Or he
said he would propose legislation to broaden the government's
ability to sanction the industry.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, said
entertainment companies needed to do a better job policing their
sales pitches. But he questioned whether Gore was the person to
deal with the industry, asserting that the vice president had
failed until recently to take a strong stand on violence in
entertainment media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the man's short on credibility on the issue,'' Bush
said, adding that Gore has raised millions of dollars in campaign
money from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who commissioned the FTC investigation,
challenged the industry to be responsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will give, I think, the entertainment
industry a period now to fix this but something has to be done,''
Clinton said during an appearance in Scarsdale, N.Y., with his
wife, Hillary, who is running for the Senate. ``They say these
rating systems mean something. They can't turn around and advertise
to people that shouldn't see this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the key findings contained in the FTC study:
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the 44 movies rated R for violence that the commission
selected for its study, 35 had advertising campaigns targeted at
children under 17. In addition, marketing plans for 28 of those
films expressly stated that the movies' target audience included
children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   _ Every one of the advertising campaigns of the 55 music CDs
with explicit content labels chosen for the FTC study targeted
children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventy percent, or 83, of the 118 video games labeled as
violent went used advertising promotions aimed at children under
17.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed that MTV, with a core demographic of 12- to
24-year-olds, was the largest cable advertising outlet for each of
the 44 rated R-rated movies in the study. In addition, magazines
with majority under-17 audiences, such as Teen, Jump, YM, DC Comics
and Marvel Comics, contained advertisements for a number of R-rated
films.
</P>
<P>
   The commission study relied on internal marketing documents
provided by the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry leaders dismissed the report, saying the
FTC incorrectly evaluated many companies' marketing campaigns. They
also said that movies and video games have no effect on children's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are causing moral decay in this country, we ought to
have an explosion of crime,'' said Jack Valenti, head of the Motion
Picture Association of America. ``The exact opposite is
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Hollywood voluntary imposed a rating system on
movies to help parents choose which films were appropriate for
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``For almost 32 years, this industry has been the only segment
of our national marketplace that voluntarily turns away revenues at
the box office to redeem the pledge that we have made to parents,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tushnet, who specializes in the First Amendment at
Georgetown University, said the government could write a law
allowing the FTC to regulate entertainment marketing but that its
enforcement would be ``complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was convinced the law could be enforced in cases
where companies seem to be undermining their own rating and
labeling standards in their advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the industry violates its own rules and actively misleads
parents with advertising, then the industry should be held
accountable,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address HYPERLINK mailto:reportername &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
