<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Sept. 12 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-KIDS-SELL (Undated) _ The Federal Trade Commission
releases a report on marketing of violent games and videos to
children. ``Companies in those industries routinely target children
under 17 as the audience for movies, music and games that their own
rating or labeling systems say are inappropriate for children or
warrant parental caution due to their violent content,'' the report
says. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE (Albuquerque) _ Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos
scientist accused of stealing a library of nuclear weapons secrets,
is expected to be released on Monday after pleading guilty to a
single felony count of improperly downloading classified material
onto an unsecure computer. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-SPY-CHARGES (Washington) _ On what has happened to the
espionage case against Wen Ho Lee. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-AD (Washington) _ A careful look at a Republican television
commercial. Byline TK.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-IGNITION (Washington) _ A look at a long-running dispute
over complaints that Fords in the 1980s and '90s were unexpectedly
stalling including on highways and while making left turns across
oncoming traffic. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-HEALTH (Washington) _ A look at the Medicare debate in
the presidential campaign: George W. Bush jumped into the Medicare
wars this week, promising that, if elected, he would form a White
House task force that would send legislation to Congress within
nine months to transform the 35-year-old government insurance
program into an efficient, largely private health care marketplace.
But many health care experts __ and sadder-but-wiser veterans of
past Medicare wars __ say that the last decade has shown the
immense difficulties in accomplishing such reforms. The
philosophical differences between the two parties over how to
reshape Medicare are large and enduring. The experience with
private HMOs in the Medicare program has been rocky, with hundreds
of thousands of Medicare beneficiaries dropped in recent years by
health plans who say they cannot make a profit. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS (United Nations) _ Iraq, which has complained for
years about the effect of U.N. sanctions on ordinary Iraqis, is
refusing to cooperate with a U.N. plan for a nationwide survey of
the sanctions' effect on people. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
</TEXT>
