<SLUG> BC-REPLICATED-RECIPES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST LIKE THEY SERVE AT...
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes you find a dish worth copying when you least expect
it. Such has been the case during several of my recent travels.
</P>
<P>
   First in today's quartet of replica offerings is a terrific
hummus, copied from The Prado restaurant at Balboa Park in San
Diego _ a good dining choice in a lovely setting if you're in that
area.
</P>
<P>
   A small container of this hummus accompanied by crispy pieces of
flatbread arrives at the table once you're seated _ and makes great
noshing while you're perusing the menu selections and waiting for
your meal. Although we don't usually ask restaurants for ingredient
lists, chef Jeff Thurston was happy to share his creation. In fact,
he even sent along the quantity recipe, based on 4 1/2 gallons
cooked garbanzo beans and 9 cups tahini!
</P>
<P>
   We relied on taste memories from a recent visit there to create
our copycat version. Although the restaurant starts by cooking
dried garbanzo beans, we took the liberty of streamlining the
recipe by using rinsed and drained canned beans.
</P>
<P>
   The mixture goes together in short order in the food processor
with fresh garlic or garlic pepper, lemon and lime juices (be sure
to use freshly squeezed), tahini (sesame seed paste), cilantro and
chipotle peppers in adobo sauce (available in some supermarkets and
Latino markets). Be sure to include the chipotle chiles, which lend
the signature smoky flavor along with some heat. Serve with crispy
thin baked lavosh pieces. This appetizer is a winner _ and one
that's difficult to stop eating.
</P>
<P>
   A recent trip to check out what's new at the takeout deli
counter at Gelson's in North Hollywood yielded a couple of
excellent salads that are a breeze to turn out at home. The first _
made with strips of cactus that can be purchased in a jar _ is
unusual and delicious. The strips are teamed with chopped avocado,
onions, green peppers, tomatoes, cilantro, lime juice, olive oil
and small pieces of queso fresco cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Our tasters raved about the Barbecue Potato Salad from Gelson's,
which is a novel combination but one that works well _ and is great
tasting. Cook red potatoes in the microwave oven until tender, then
cool and chill. The dressing is a mixture of sour cream,
hickory-flavored barbecue sauce (Chris &AMP; Pitts preferred), chopped
green onions, celery and red peppers, corn and crumbled bacon (buy
cooked bacon in a jar if time is at a premium). Zip up the mixture
with a few dashes of cayenne pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with grilled or broiled chicken or meats. Clip and save
this idea to use all year long when you want to add barbecue flavor
to the table without heating up the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Last in today's roundup is a copycat version of a Mascarpone
Cheesecake sampled at Buca di Beppo at Universal CityWalk. Pick up
the mascarpone cheese _ which makes a divine dessert _ at an
Italian deli, Costco or the supermarket. Top the baked slices with
a ruby red raspberry sauce whipped up in a food processor with
frozen unsweetened raspberries and a little powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Give these restaurant replicas a whirl to jazz up end-of-summer
and fall menus. &QL; 
CHIPOTLE HUMMUS &QL; 
2 (15 1/2-ounce) cans garbanzo beans, well rinsed and drained &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic pepper OR 1 to 2 cloves garlic, pressed &QL; 
1/4 cup fresh lemon juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon lime juice &QL; 
3 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
1 1/4 teaspoons chipotle peppers in adobo sauce (pick out a few
pieces of peppers along with sauce and measure) &QL; 
4 teaspoons tahini (sesame seed paste) &QL; 
1 tablespoon cilantro leaves &QL; 
Seasoned salt to taste &QL; 
Baked Lavosh
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with a metal blade, combine all
ingredients except Baked Lavosh. Process until almost smooth. Using
an ice cream scoop, turn into a small ramekin or crock. Serve with
cracker bread pieces. Makes about 2 cups dip.
</P>
<P>
   BAKED LAVOSH: Place 1 large rectangle lavosh (cracker-like
bread) on EACH of 2 large baking sheets. Brush tops with olive oil
and sprinkle with a little ground chile powder OR ground cumin.
Bake in preheated 450-degree oven 3 to 4 minutes or until browned
and crisp, watching carefully to avoid burning. Cool 5 minutes,
then break into pieces. &QL; 
CACTUS SALAD &QL; 
1 avocado, peeled, pitted and cut into 1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
1/3 cup chopped white onion &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped green pepper &QL; 
2 cups diced fresh tomatoes &QL; 
3/4 cup jarred cactus strips, rinsed and well drained &QL; 
2 to 3 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
3 to 4 tablespoons fresh lime juice (from 2 limes) &QL; 
1 cup of 1/2-inch cubes queso fresco cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, gently toss together all ingredients except
cheese. Chill well. Just before serving, gently stir in cheese.
Makes 5 to 6 servings (about 5 cups). &QL; 
BARBECUE POTATO SALAD &QL; 
1 1/2 cups dairy sour cream (light OK) &QL; 
2/3 cup hickory-flavored barbecue sauce &QL; 
3 to 4 green onions, chopped OR 1/2 cup chopped red onion &QL; 
1 cup cooked OR canned corn kernels &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped celery &QL; 
1/2 medium red bell pepper, chopped &QL; 
1/3 cup crumbled cooked bacon &QL; 
Few dashes cayenne pepper &QL; 
Seasoned salt &QL; 
2 pounds red OR small white potatoes, cooked, cooled and cut into
1-inch cubes (peel, if desired) &QL; 
In a medium bowl, mix together sour cream and barbecue sauce until
blended. Stir in all remaining ingredients except potatoes, mixing
until coated. Gently stir in cold potatoes. Chill well. Makes 4 to
6 servings. &QL; 
MASCARPONE CHEESECAKE &QL; 
1 cup graham cracker crumbs &QL; 
3 tablespoons butter, melted &QL; 
1 (16-ounce) container mascarpone cheese &QL; 
2 (8-ounce) packages cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
2 tablespoons flour &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) package frozen raspberries &QL; 
1/3 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Mix together graham cracker crumbs and butter until well
blended. Press into bottom and 1/2-inch up sides of an 8-inch
springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, beat together all remaining ingredients,
except raspberries and and powdered sugar, until smooth and creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Turn filling into crust. Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 15
minutes. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees F and continue
baking about 45 minutes or until set. Cool. Then refrigerate until
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in a food processor, combine raspberries and powdered
sugar. Process until pureed. Chill until serving time. Serve
cheesecake pieces topped with raspberry sauce. Makes 8 to 10
servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
