<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT'S A MAN'S JOB, SEND FOGARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asked about the worldwide explosion of vapid teen-pop the other
day, U2's Bono said it was time for the boys to move over and let
the men show how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   John Fogerty did just that at Sunday's New Orleans festival at
the L.A. Tennis Center in Westwood, an imaginative bill that
suffered from a woeful lack of promotion that caused the place to
be only two-thirds full.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shame more people didn't get to see this revered
roots-rocker, whose songs for Creedence Clearwater Revival are some
of rock's most popular and best-crafted tunes.
</P>
<P>
   At 55, Fogerty is still in top form, his guitar chords ringing
with conviction, his build slim and energetic and his vocal
delivery a burnished thing of gritty beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Charged readings of classic Creedence material, such as ``Green
River,'' ``Bad Moon Rising,'' ``Born on the Bayou'' and ``Down on
the Corner,'' were marvelous.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the excitement of Fogerty's well-paced set was a
dynamic backing unit that included veteran drummer Kenny Aronoff
and guitarist Rick Vito.
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty is still one of the best performers of the rock era,
right up there with Bruce Springsteen and Don Henley, and he seemed
to be in an expansive mood. Maybe there was extra spark to the set
Sunday because the gig was the final night of the band's world
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Irma Thomas performed her slinky New Orleans r&AMP;b to a
sparse house, while Big Easy jazz-funk pianist Dr. John brought an
unusually ragged band on stage to perform such classic Mardi Gras
material as ``Big Chief'' and ``Right Place, Wrong Time.''
</P>
<P>
   That last tune seemed to sum up an evening that should have
attracted many more customers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
