<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICALMAN0912-COX     09-11 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICALMAN0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practical Grandma has seen it all, and discloses almost all of
it
 &HT;    By The Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The practical man went to his grandma
for advice last week.
</P>
<P>
   He figured he'd Q&AMP;A the 90-year-old Indiana native. She's seen
two world wars, the Great Depression, raised three children, a load
of grandkids, scrimped, saved and survived it all. Surely, he'd get
plenty of practical tips.
</P>
<P>
   He got a beating instead.
</P>
<P>
   No, the rickety oldster didn't whip out the wooden yardstick she
busted over his head when he lied to her about the broken lamp back
in '69.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't dig up the tattered tennis shoe and thump his rump
like she did when he sassed her in '71.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't even try to cram another cake of Palmolive in his
mouth _ despite the cussing. Even she could understand the
practical man's dip into the dark side this time, given the topic:
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, she did a little swearing
</P>
<P>
   herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lands o' Goshen!'' she howled. ``You better watch out. That
girl's boy-crazy!''
</P>
<P>
   Painful words, for the girl in question was the practical man's
16-year-old daughter, who recently proclaimed that she's ``in
love'' _ and not with the practical man.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Forget her father _ that soft and soothing spirit
who babied her diapered behind and wiped her nasty nose. Dump that
dear old doofus! So what if Pop bandaged her boo-boos, blew bubbles
on her belly and wasted weeks wading through algebra with her?
Scratch that slate clean! Barbies and makeup and princess outfits
and glitter pens _ bah! Get the gummy geezer out of her sight!
</P>
<P>
   Oops! The practical man was digressing. He didn't come to
Grandmother's house to whine. He came to explain his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I figure I'll be in the front yard nonchalantly firing up
the chain saw the next time this pimply puke ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Oops! At that point, the practical man lost his train of thought
again, for the image of his daughter's boyfriend distracted him.
This young fella, one Jacob _ so young, so handsome, so innocent _
wait _ so uninnocent! Sweet mother of heaven! The practical man was
16 once, and he'd be danged if he'd have let himself date his
daughter!
</P>
<P>
   Grandma, what to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, for Pete's sake! Don't you have any sense? A saw won't do
any good when a girl is boy-crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   No? Then how about a sledgehammer? Ax? Please Grandma, wise the
practical man up!
</P>
<P>
   ``Merciful heavens! Think about it, son. There's only one thing
that'll keep a young woman and a young man apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Cough it up, Grandma! The practical man needs help!
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, for crying out loud. I shouldn't have to tell you
everything! You have to go with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Go with her?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes! Sit right between them, keep them apart. Take all
the fun out of it! That's how my mom fixed me when I was boy-crazy,
and that's what I did with your mom. Nip the hanky-panky in the
bud, that's what I say. Otherwise, we'll all be sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandma, that might not work ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Hush! You wanted the facts. And no going out after dark!''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. And you guys thought the practical man was extreme. On
other topics, though, the Practical Grandma took a less radical
line.
</P>
<P>
   PM: Grandma, give me some money advice.
</P>
<P>
   PG: Ooh, that's easy! Pay cash, son. Even for cars. I like my
credit card, but I always pay it off at the end of the month.
You're silly to pay interest to those crooks.
</P>
<P>
   PM: How about cooking. What's the most practical meal?
</P>
<P>
   PG: The most practical meal is whatever the cook wants to eat!
Hee hee! If the rest of the family doesn't like it, tough! Beggars
can't be choosers.
</P>
<P>
   PM: What's the best thing about being married?
</P>
<P>
   PG: You're trying to get me to talk about sex, aren't you? Well,
I'm not going to do it, Mr. Smarty Pants! I don't know what the
best thing is, but I know what I remember. When I got married, I
was 18, and I used to love to wash my husband's clothes! I scrubbed
them on a washboard, and it made me feel so free! I was grown up, I
was a woman. I'll always remember that.
</P>
<P>
   PM: What's the biggest mistake parents make nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   PG: I don't want to stick my nose in anyone's business, but I
think it's wrong to give a child an allowance. Parents should buy
kids what they need when they need it, and get them what they want
when they deserve it. And then when kids get old enough to start
making money on their own, they should give you a little something
out of every paycheck. My land! It's the least they can do!
</P>
<P>
   PM: Last question, Grandma. What's the secret to long life?
</P>
<P>
   PG: Oh, gracious! I don't know. I thank the good Lord, of
course, and then I think maybe it's two things, but you're not
going to like the first one: No drinking! I've never tasted a drop,
and I'm not about to start now. The other thing is hot peppers. I
love 'em _ eat 'em raw, with just a little salt. They keep you
clean on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in the interest of fairness, the practical man opens
the floor to nuts ... Oh, wait, the practical man didn't mean to
say nuts. He meant to say readers who are intelligent, yet somehow
misguided and muddle-minded ... Dang! Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's just call them readers who disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I enjoy your column but was bewildered by
Sunday's response to the troubled parent with the boys in sports.
</P>
<P>
   I was waiting for the ``Only Kiddin'' one liner, but it never
happened. Man, what have they done to you? Life is not all this or
all that. It's all about balance.
</P>
<P>
   My eldest of three daughters, age 12, is a soccer star and
parents routinely approach me asking how I got her to be so
competitive, to outwardly show desire, commitment, drive to
succeed, intensity and discipline. Whaddaya know, an early example
of the ultimate employee!
</P>
<P>
   Growing up as a jock, I thrived on competition. I learned to
work hard if I wanted results, what I started I finished, it takes
a team to win, goal setting, learning how to win and lose with
pride, knowing I did my very best, a strong work ethic and
discipline. I believe it's not competition that is evil but
complacency, a laissez faire, Jimmy Buffett, kickin' back approach
to life which is, by its nature, self-destructive. Failing to
attain your potential through conscious inaction is the `evil'
which you should rail against.
</P>
<P>
   I will end by saying this _ this same daughter baby-sat an
infant next door full-time during the summer. She spent her first
week's pay on her 5-year-old sister to purchase her a baseball
glove, bat and ball. Success in life is built on a firm foundation
of balance. The intense sportsman is also the most generous loving
daughter in the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, via e-mail
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: As an appliance dealership that tries to
operate with a high standard of ethics and professionalism, I feel
compelled to respond to your article of Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Our objective is to assist customers in making the correct
choice in their purchase. We try to find their needs and
requirements, show them their options and match them with the best
value. Many times, cheapest is not always in the best interest of
the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Would it have been better if you were ignored and not
greeted?... Is it not sad that when you were greeted and offered
help, you assumed that this person was the ``enemy'' instead of
someone to help you, a friend?... You mention ``bullets flying''
when it appears that the only shots being fired are by you.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest thing about this article is your preconceived idea
of what shopping might be.... Most people want to be assisted and
appreciate the knowledge of a professional salesman who can assist
them in a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Your article was shortsighted, narrow-minded, and was totally
off-base. It is a shame that The Palm Beach Post would give such an
irresponsible person the weapon of words to display such an
off-base article.
</P>
<P>
   I hope you will have the courage to publish this response and
not hide behind your veil of words.
</P>
<P>
   _ Very Truly Yours, Leonard Rosner, President, Rosner's Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, FL 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
