<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9234 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      09-11 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)
</HEADLINE>
  
 BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S `NEW &AMP; NOTABLE' BOOK REVIEWS(a)  &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LAST RIVER''
</P>
<P>
   By Todd Balf
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, 1998, world-class kayaker Doug Gordon went over an
8-foot waterfall on the Yarlung Tsangpo River in Tibet. As three
fellow boaters watched horrified from shore, an obviously sluggish
Gordon tried to right himself in the roiling water but could not.
He was swept into the main current and never seen again. The
kayakers were exploring ``the Everest of rivers,'' writes Balf,
``every bit as mysterious, myth-laden, and malicious as the
unconquered summit was when Sir John Hunt's expedition arrived at
its icy doorstep in 1953.'' It's tempting to compare his book to
Jon Krakauer's (beginitalic)Into Thin Air(enditalic), and it's true
that if you liked it you'll probably like this one. But there are
no heroic rescues here, no amateurs among the men on the river that
day. Balf conveys the skill and motivation of the kayakers and the
ensuing controversy among members of the paddling community who
wondered if Gordon and his colleagues should have been on the
Tsangpo at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``MILLENNIALS RISING''
</P>
<P>
   By Neil Howe and William Strauss
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They got lucky with the name. Other choices, according to an ABC
news poll, were ``Generation Next,'' ``Echo Boom'' and ``Boomer
Babies.'' Instead, the generation of kids born in or after 1982
will be associated with the turn of the century, and according to
Howe and Strauss, they deserve the honor. As a group, the authors
say, these kids are positive, trustworthy, cooperative and smart.
Most of them don't have green hair, although we can't be sure about
tattoos or body piercings. According to a survey of the class of
2000, the 10 events that made the biggest impression on them
included the shootings at Columbine, the war in Kosovo and the fall
of the Berlin Wall. Princess Di's death came in fourth, but no
one's perfect. All in all, this profile of the emerging generation
is both heartening and overdone. After plowing through more than
400 pages of millennial madness, we decided we'd rather meet them
one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE UNEXPECTED LEGACY OF DIVORCE''
</P>
<P>
   By Judith Wallerstein
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are two faulty beliefs that form our attitudes about
divorce: If the parents are happier, the children will be happier
too. And divorce is a temporary crisis that exerts its most harmful
effects on kids at the time of the breakup. The truth, writes
Wallerstein, is more complex and disturbing. Her previous books
reported on a core group of 131 children of divorced parents,
recruited and interviewed in 1971 and revisited at the five-, 10-
and 15-year marks. This book represents a 25-year follow-up of
those children, who now are 28 to 43. The findings? Divorce has
long-term ramifications, and its biggest effects occur only as
children grow up and embark on relationships of their own. It
alters the way they view the prospect of raising children and
leaves many with a lifelong fear of abandonment and betrayal. In
short, divorce changes everything. This excellent book will inspire
heated discussion on a subject that affects all modern families.
</P>
<P>
   ``NEVER DIE EASY''
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Payton with Don Yaeger
</P>
<P>
   (Villard, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's something to be said for books that make you cry, but
we're too soggy to know what it is right now. Consider that a
warning. Payton was writing his autobiography before he died last
fall, and Yaeger has salvaged the book by interspersing
biographical passages about Payton's life - his Mississippi
childhood, his evolution as a football player in the newly
integrated South, his pro career in Chicago, his family, retirement
and battle with liver disease and cancer - with first-person
reminiscences from Payton and his family and friends. It's a moving
way to portray a good man who was loved fiercely by many people.
Among the contributors are Jim Brown, Matt Suhey, Jim McMahon,
Roland Harper and John Madden, but it's Mike Ditka who steals the
show with an eloquent and emotional eulogy. As one reporter said,
Payton's liver went bad but his heart went on forever. If you can
read this with dry eyes, you're a sturdy soul indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
