<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Works by Faberge In Wilmington Show
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's largest exhibitions of the work of the
jeweler and goldsmith Peter Carl Faberge has opened at the
Riverfront Arts Center at 800 South Madison Street in Wilmington,
Del. ``Faberge'' features more than 1,000 works from museums and
private collections, including objects from the State Hermitage
Museum in St. Petersburg and the Moscow Kremlin Museums that have
never been seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Faberge was the official jeweler of czarist Russia, and the show
highlights the luxurious tastes of Russian and European
aristocracies in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Exhibits
include at least 10 imperial Easter eggs, a family of silver
rabbits from the former collection of the king of Bulgaria, and
decorative boxes and cigarette cases in gold and enamel. Several
items are on loan from royal families, such as a gold- and
silver-mounted diamond-set tiara shaped as a myrtle wreath from the
Duke and Duchess of Westminster.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission, by timed entry, includes a brief orientation and a
45-minute recorded tour; advance ticket purchase is recommended.
The price is $14.50, with discounts for seniors, children and
students. ``Faberge,'' through Feb. 18, is open Tuesday to Sunday 9
a.m. to 7 p.m., with the last entry at 5. Tickets: (888) 395-0005
or on the Web at www.faberge-exhibition.com.
</P>
<P>
   Completed on Malta
</P>
<P>
   The Hal-Saflieni Hypogeum, a Neolithic site in the town of
Paola, Malta, reopened to the public last month after a nine-year
restoration. The 6,000-year-old Hypogeum, discovered in 1902, is
thought to be one of the largest and most complex examples of
prehistoric rock-cut chamber tombs in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance has been covered by a chamber to keep the humidity
and temperature at proper levels to protect the caves. Visitors
enter in groups of 10 at set times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The site, built without metal tools, has three levels. There are
more than 30 chambers, some with elaborate carvings, as well as
paintings in ocher. The numerous statues, amulets, figures and
vases found in the Hypogeum are now at the Valletta Archaeological
Museum in the Maltese capital, with a small selection displayed at
the site.
</P>
<P>
   Four visits a day are scheduled, at 9, 10 and 11 a.m. and noon.
Tickets cost $6.90, at 2.3 liri to the dollar, and can be purchased
only on site; it is advisable to get them a day in advance. From
the Valletta bus station, there are numerous buses to Paola.
Information: (356) 825579; or
www.magnet.mt/home/museums/hypogeum.html.
</P>
<P>
   A Mark of Authenticity For Aboriginal Art
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to steer tourists away from fake Aboriginal art _
much of it mass-produced in Asia _ a nonprofit group representing
indigenous Australian artists has introduced a label to help
visitors recognize the real thing. The National Indigenous Arts
Advocacy Association's labels have begun appearing on individual
souvenir items such as boomerangs and T-shirts with Aboriginal
designs, and also on the windows of approved shops. The association
hopes the program will also boost indigenous artists' shares of an
industry that generates more than $120 million a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the label, artists must submit an application for
approval by two Aboriginal leaders willing to vouch for the
artists' identity and acceptance within their community. More than
300 artists have already registered for the label. The association
expects the list to grow into the thousands as its workers reach
more remote Aboriginal communities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because the program is still in its infancy _ the labels made
their debut in June _ arts and crafts bearing Aboriginal designs
but not the association's label aren't necessarily fakes.
</P>
<P>
   The association can be reached in Sydney at (61-2) 9241-3533.
</P>
<P>
   Freshwater Aquarium Opens on Lake Superior
</P>
<P>
   The Great Lakes Aquarium, which says it is the first aquarium in
the United States with all freshwater tanks, recently opened on the
shore of Lake Superior in Duluth, Minn. It examines the geology and
plant and animal life of the lake, as well as the effects climate
and humans have had on it. The aquarium contains 70 species of fish
along with otters, frogs and turtles.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-foot-long model of the Great Lakes allows visitors to float
toy boats from Lake Superior to the St. Lawrence Seaway via the
lakes' system of locks. Visitors can also use a camera to look at
tiny living organisms native to the lake's sandy, rocky bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium is at 353 Harbor Drive in Duluth. It is open 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. daily except Thursday, when it will close at 9, and
Sunday, when it will close at 4 (Sept. 17 is the last Sunday with a
summer 6 p.m. closing time). Beginning Sept. 18, admission will be
lowered by a dollar to $9.95, $4.95 ages 4 to 17 and $7.95 ages 62
and over. Information: (218) 740-3474 or www.glaquarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   A Haven in the Heart of the Left Bank
</P>
<P>
   Suite 801 of the Pont Royal, according to a manager of the Left
Bank hotel, is the only hotel room in Paris with a view over the
entire city _ or at least its heart and its major monuments, from
the Invalides to Sacre-Coeur to Notre-Dame. Among the viewing
points in the suite, done in mauve toile de Jouy, are two terraces
and even the bathroom, which has two windows.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not that view is unique, standard and deluxe rooms on
the sixth and seventh floors, cozily tucked under the mansard roof,
offer delightful vistas over Paris rooftops. There is a total of 10
suites and 65 rooms, with two-line phones and in-room faxes and
dataports. The decor in the gracious 1920's building is classic and
understated, with rooms attractively done in tones of coffee, coral
or plum.
</P>
<P>
   Reopened a year ago after a major renovation, the hotel added a
small fitness center and massage room in the basement, and a
conference room on the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, there were sightings of Sartre and de Beauvoir in
the hotel bar and spacious restaurant, Les Antiquaires, long a
hangout for literary types. Today the lunch crowd is more likely to
be politicians, journalists and fashion folk, as well as people
from Gallimard, the publishing house just down the Rue de
Montalembert; Antoine Gallimard himself lunches there often.
Favorite dishes on the luncheon menu include beignets of crayfish
and mushrooms ($14.50, at 7.53 francs to the dollar) and red fruits
in sabayon sauce ($6.50). In the morning, the restaurant is a
comfortable setting for an ample buffet breakfast ($20).
</P>
<P>
   Just off the Rue du Bac near its juncture with the Boulevard
St.-Germain, the Pont Royal offers air-conditioning, pleasantly
efficient service and an island of calm in this busy part of the
Seventh Arrondissement. A few steps away is the Rue du Bac Metro
stop, not unimportant given Paris' increasingly fierce traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Pont Royal Hotel, 7, rue de Montalembert; telephone (33-1)
42.84.70.00, fax (33-1) 42.84.71.00. Doubles $259 to $305; suites
$425 to $597.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
