<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy
rain, will precede a cold front slowly pushing east from the Great
Lakes. Meanwhile, winds from the south-southeast along the
Northeast Seaboard will continue to direct muggy air inland.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, some locations near Dallas will have the first
measurable rain in over two months as showers develop ahead of a
cold front. The clouds and showers will also bring cooler weather
to parts of the southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front moving south from the Canadian Rockies will mark
the leading edge of noticeably cooler air. Some of this chilly air
will arrive in the East this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Florence, which formed Monday, will remain nearly
stationary about 400 miles east of Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FLYING BLIND &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Each night from mid-August through October meteorologists are
blinded when, for two hours, the satellite that monitors North
America and the Atlantic loses power. During that time, from the
point of view of the satellite, there is a solar eclipse. The
solar-powered satellite is in a geostationary orbit 22,500 miles
over northern South America. Each year around the equinoxes, the
Earth passes between the satellite and the sun. In the fall, the
data loss can interfere briefly with hurricane tracking, but other
weather observations from ground-based instruments and
reconnaissance aircraft help fill the void. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
