<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CHRONIC-DISEASES-     09-11 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHRONIC-DISEASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES MONITORING OF CHRONIC DISEASES
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Mont.) By PHILIP J. HILTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pew Environmental Health Commission and 13 top public health
groups have proposed that the United States establish a system to
count and monitor chronic diseases like birth defects, asthma and
Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   A report from the health commission, based at the Johns Hopkins
School of Public Health, said that while scientists had managed to
map the human genome and could track infectious diseases with some
speed and accuracy, they still lacked basic information about
chronic diseases, like how often they occur, whom they afflict,
where they frequently occur and the environmental factors
associated with them.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Weicker, the commission chairman and the former governor
of Connecticut, said, ``We responded quickly to the threat of West
Nile virus, tracking and monitoring every report of infected birds
and people, but 20 years into the asthma epidemic, this country is
still unable to track where and when attacks occur and what
environmental links may trigger them.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, endorsed by several public health groups, including
the American Cancer Society, the American Lung Association and the
American Public Health Association, noted that a survey conducted
for the commission showed that Americans believe, erroneously, that
chronic diseases are being monitored.
</P>
<P>
   The misperception comes from the small surveys done on different
diseases that often suggest, for example, that a disease's
occurrence is rising. But, said Dr. Thomas Burke, leader of the
study that produced the report, surveys cannot give the vital
information needed to help solve the mystery of how diseases move
and what may be causing them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the diseases and disorders that are not counted and
tracked, but should be, the report said, are asthma, emphysema,
birth defects, Alzheimer's, multiple sclerosis, cerebral palsy,
autism, mental retardation, and a variety of cancers, especially
childhood cancers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report said, toxic agents that are not
monitored, but which are suspected of causing disease, include
pollutants like PCB's and dioxin, dangerous metals like mercury and
lead, and pesticides. The Environmental Protection Agency sets
limits on how much of some of these substances can be put into the
environment, but it does not track them and try to link their
effects to human diseases.
</P>
<P>
   An example of the failure to monitor chronic diseases and
possible environmental causes was the case of Libby, Mont., the
report said. In that town of 2,700, an epidemic of respiratory
diseases, including asbestosis, unusual cancers and emphysema, has
been unofficially noted for decades. Only this year did a federal
investigation find that a vermiculite mine not far away had been
releasing tons of tremolite for 50 years. Tremolite is a natural
but rare and highly toxic form of asbestos. Investigators estimate
that 200 residents have died from diseases associated with the
substance, and many more are ill.
</P>
<P>
   Active tracking of respiratory disease ``might have picked this
up much sooner, and started preventive activities 10 to 20 years
ago,'' said Dr. Henry Falk, administrator of the federal Agency for
Toxic Substances and Disease Registry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-WENHO-BOS &LR;      09-11 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WENHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ALAMOS INJUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plea agreement between federal prosecutors and lawyers for
nuclear weapons scientist Wen Ho Lee _ in which the government
dropped 58 of the 59 counts in its indictment _ amounts to an
admission that the prosecution had no case against a man who spent
nine months in prison, too often in shackles and solitary
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   If it is viewed in the most general and positive light, the
government's belated confession of error can be taken as evidence
that the American justice system includes a self-correcting
mechanism. In that view, there should be something reassuring in
the prosecution's tacit acknowledgment that Lee did not pass
nuclear secrets to a foreign power, did not alter the strategic
balance of power, and did not lie to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   After all, from the very beginning Lee has conceded that he
downloaded classified nuclear codes from a secure computer within
Los Alamos to an unsecure computer within that federal laboratory.
Among scientists working at Los Alamos, he told ``60 Minutes,''
this kind of negligence was ``a very common practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The one count to which Lee pled guilty was his negligent
downloading. For this offense he deserved to be fired. Even if
there was no question of espionage and even if others were equally
careless about security rules, these are rules that must be
enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it now seems plain that Wen Ho Lee was made to
suffer inordinately for the government's incompetence and for a
bureaucratic effort to cover up its own bungling.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI agent recently admitted that he testified falsely that
Lee was deceptive with a colleague whose computer he used to
download classified codes and that Lee intended to use computer
tapes in a job search abroad. These were symptoms of excessive
prosecutorial zeal and perhaps also of a willingness to mislead the
court, but they were not the government's worst misdeeds. The fibs
told by the FBI came at the end of a long skein of unfounded
assumptions and obtuse attempts to tamp down the furor of
politicians who had been stampeded into believing that China was
stealing the ``crown jewels'' of America's nuclear weapons
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The government had no reason to assume originally that the X
Sector, or nuclear weapons division, at Los Alamos had to be the
source of a damaging security leak. There were more than 500
computers in federal government offices and private sector defense
contractors that received the design of the miniaturized W-88
warhead that Beijing had obtained by 1988. And there was no good
reason to assume that Lee was the likeliest espionage suspect.
</P>
<P>
   If there were damaging leaks or spies within the nation's
nuclear weapons establishment, then the foolish pursuit of Wen Ho
Lee made it easier for the thieves to get away with their theft
while making it harder for Los Alamos to recruit and retain able
scientists. The government's blunder harmed national security as
much as it harmed one scientist who was unjustly imprisoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
