<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9253 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER     09-11 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEST END IS STARSTRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Want a big theatrical success? Hire yourself a
celebrity, preferably a film star. This blunt wisdom has recently
brought Kevin Spacey, Cate Blanchett, Nicole Kidman and others to
London, and, with Jerry Hall replacing Kathleen Turner as the
seductive Mrs. Robinson, is currently ensuring that a
none-too-brilliant adaptation of ``The Graduate'' is packing the
Gielgud Theater. And the trend is set to continue this fall.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Hannah, a lovelorn mermaid in the 1984 movie ``Splash,''
plays the human siren in George Axelrod's ``Seven Year Itch''
(Queen's, Oct. 9), a role made famous on screen by Marilyn Monroe
and her billowing white dress. Then it's the turn of Macaulay
Culkin, who opens at the Vaudeville in mid-October in ``Madame
Melville,'' a play about a teen-ager sexually involved with a
French teacher played by Irene Jacob, who won Best Actress at
Cannes in 1991 for the film ``The Double Life of Veronique.'' Some
will suspect this is merely an excuse for the baby-faced actor to
kick-start a stalled career; but the author is Richard Nelson, the
American dramatist who has had no fewer than eight plays performed
by the Royal Shakespeare Company, last year winning an Olivier
Award for his ``Goodnight Children Everywhere.'' The omens are
better than cynics might think. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the Hollywood influx finished. Nobody would be likely to
revive O'Neill's intense and grueling ``Long Day's Journey Into
Night'' in the West End these days with a mere theatrical dame as
the morphine-addicted Mary Tyrone; but with Jessica Lange in the
role the play is deemed worth the risk and will open at the Lyric
on Nov. 21. The presence of Charles Dance as Mary's husband, James,
a lightly disguised version of the famous actor who was O'Neill's
father, won't harm the production's chances, either.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry. Not all major stage performers are in
hibernation this fall. Simon Callow is now at the Comedy, offering
a lively portrait of the great Victorian in Peter Ackroyd's
``Mystery of Charles Dickens.'' Opening at the same theater on Nov.
15, Michael Gambon is to play the foul old tramp Davies alongside
Rupert Graves in a revival of ``The Caretaker'' by Harold Pinter.
That superb actress Janet Suzman is the wife whose fidelity is
interminably tested by her actor-husband in Molnar's ``Guardsman,''
which is at the Albery from Oct. 11. Felicity Kendal and Frances de
la Tour open at the Apollo on Oct. 25 in Noel Coward's gorgeously
flippant tale of frivolous women, ``Fallen Angels.'' Derek Jacobi
is scheduled for a yet unnamed theater in November in ``God Only
Knows'' by Hugh Whitemore, in whose ``Breaking the Code'' he had a
huge success in the West End and on Broadway 14 years ago. And
before then, on Sept. 21, the Redgrave siblings, Vanessa and Corin,
will have opened at the National in Trevor Nunn's revival of
Chekhov's ``Cherry Orchard.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National is pretty busy this fall, and certainly busier than
the RSC, whose openings at the Barbican are a small-scale
``Tempest'' and ``Duchess of Malfi,'' with the exciting young
Aisling O'Sullivan as Webster's doomed heroine. But the National
has already launched its new season by presenting Simon Russell
Beale's brilliantly fresh Hamlet, and is following up this critical
triumph with revivals of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' Ibsen's ``Peer
Gynt'' and Michael Frayn's preposterously funny ``Noises Off,'' as
well as Pinter's stage version of the film script he constructed
from Proust's ``Remembrance of Things Past'' and a play by the
unknown Zinnie Harris, which I much admired at this year's
Edinburgh Festival. ``Further than the Furthest Thing,'' as it's
called, involves islanders based on those who were forced by a
volcano to abandon their primitive life on Tristan da Cunha in the
1960s and find sanctuary in England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fall also brings London two major musicals. One is Andrew
Lloyd Webber and Ben Elton's ``Beautiful Game'' (Cambridge, Sept.
26), about a soccer team in religion-riven Ulster, and the other
the latest of a series of shows that, for no clear reason, involve
French subjects. ``Lautrec,'' a musical about the painter, was an
early summer flop at the Shaftesbury. Quasimodo is still flaunting
his hump in ``Notre Dame de Paris'' at the Dominion, a show that
has impressed the public more than it has the critics. And on Oct.
17 the Shaftesbury plays host to ``Napoleon,'' a musical by Timothy
Williams and Andrew Sabiston that rumor says is more likely than
either to match the success of ``Les Miserables'' and ``The Phantom
of the Opera,'' both of which still illumine the West End. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are also intriguing prospects for those venturing beyond
mainstream Shaftesbury Avenue and the big national companies. I
myself can vouch for the quality of Gary Mitchell's ``Force of
Change,'' a highly topical tale of police corruption in Ulster that
follows David Hare's new ``My Zinc Bed'' into the Royal Court on
Nov. 8. I liked ``Howie the Rookie,'' Mark O'Rowe's play about
near-Homeric violence in Dublin that returns to London's
outstanding pub theater, the Bush, on Oct. 27. I enjoyed a young
actor called Jason Watkins, who reprises a hilarious performance as
a harlequin in Goldoni's ``Servant to Two Masters'' at the New
Ambassadors on Dec. 14. But I'm also hoping for a bit of stimulus
from the work opening, sight unseen, at the three most fashionable
of London's small theaters, the Donmar in Covent Garden, the
Almeida in Islington and the Royal Court's studio playhouse, the
Theater Upstairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes may have established himself as a successful
moviemaker with his Oscar-winning ``American Beauty,'' but he's
still the artistic director of the Donmar, and marks his return to
the theater staging a play by a completely unknown dramatist. Nick
Whitby's ``To the Green Fields Beyond,'' about a tank crew in World
War I, opens on Sept. 25, and will be followed on Dec. 11 by a
pocket revival of Sondheim's ``Merrily We Go Along.'' Meanwhile
Mendes' contemporary Stephen Daldry, whose extraordinary production
of ``An Inspector Calls'' by J.B. Priestley is in its fifth year in
the West End, directs a new play by Britain's leading female
dramatist, Caryl Churchill. Her ``Far Away,'' about strange doings
in a weird old mansion, opens in its attic theater on Nov. 30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what follows the darkly comic ``Conversations After a
Burial,'' the latest play by Yasmina Reza, author of ``Art,'' into
the ever enterprising Almeida on Oct. 31? The answer is ``Light,''
an adaptation of a novel about a man who leaves his village in
search of love, and returns bearing death in the form of a
plague-ridden rabbit, by the Swedish writer Torgny Lindgren. What
gives this play special interest is that the company responsible is
Theatre de Complicite, despite its name the most highly regarded of
English troupes specializing in physical theater. Would most
British critics rather see this odd-sounding piece than yet another
Hollywood star in yet another revival? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
