<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH, GORE COURT WOMEN VOTERS IN HARD-FOUGHT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush appealed to elderly women worried by
prescription drug costs and Democrat Al Gore touted his nationally
televised kiss with ``soul mate'' Tipper Gore as the rivals on
Monday courted the female voters who could decide the outcome of
their hard-fought contest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest polls showing Gore enjoying a slight lead over
Bush thanks to his edge among women, the two candidates are
devoting much of the coming week to issues with appeal to women _
health care, education, conservation and protecting children from
violence and sexual content in television, movies and music.
</P>
<P>
   Bush carried his campaign into the once GOP-reliable state of
Florida to persuade senior citizens that his plan for voluntary
prescription drug insurance would help bring coverage under the
1960s-era Medicare program in line with modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the $158 billion package of Medicare changes and
creation of a prescription drug benefit ``will make the system
modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Doffing his suit jacket to campaign in a shirt and tie, Bush
told senior citizens in Clearwater that his plan would provide
greater choice for coverage in contrast to a Gore plan would force
them into a ``government-run'' health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan offers elderly Americans the choice of staying
within Medicare, the federally-subsidized health insurance program
forged in the 1960s, or joining a private plan that would provide
similar benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to highlight his proposals to strengthen health
care for senior citizens again on Tuesday during a campaign
appearance in Orlando as he wages a five-state, cross-country
campaign swing that also takes him to Missouri, Washington,
California and New Mexico by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Gore shed his policy-laden campaign persona to
devote an hour-long appearance on Oprah Winfrey's Chicago-based
television talk program, showing a charming, playful side that
voters rarely see.
</P>
<P>
   Gore explained that his three-second embrace of his wife of 30
years at the Democratic convention reflected ``an overwhelming
surge of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``This was a great moment in our lives. I mean it's
not as if I got there by myself. This has been a partnership and
she is my soul mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose wife once disclosed that the vice president likes to
sleep in the nude, flashed a wry smile when Winfrey asked him about
what he liked to sleep in.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bed,'' Gore said, triggering titters from the audience.
``You get the picture?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to appear on Winfrey's show on Sept. 19. Her
program reaches 22 million viewers weekly, most of them women.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left it to campaign staffer Ron Klain to challenge Bush's
prescription drug plan, saying that Bush's income-based formula for
eligibility for government-backed coverage could leave out 6
million senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's effort to sell his proposals as real plans for real
people falls real flat,'' said Klain, a former chief of staff for
Gore at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' entreaties to women underscored that these
voters may hold the key to the Nov. 7 contest between Gore, a
24-year veteran of Washington including almost eight years as vice
president, and Bush, a second-term governor of Texas and former
Texas businessman who is son of President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore leads Bush 49 percent to 41 percent, according to a
Newsweek magazine survey of likely voters that appeared in Monday's
editions of the newsweekly. Much of Gore's 8-point edge over Bush
stems from the Democrat's 14-point lead among women.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has overcome Bush's earlier strength among men to force a
1-point edge over the Republican candidate, according to the survey
that has a margin of error of 4 percentage points. Support from
women voters helped the Clinton-Gore ticket win the White House in
1992 _ setting the stage for the first two successive terms by a
Democratic president since 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Gore moved quickly to embrace a Federal Trade Commission report
that accused the nation's multibillion dollar entertainment issue
of aggressively marketing violent movies, music and video games to
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, calling for a ``cease-fire'' in marketing such material,
devoted a campaign appearance at an elementary school in
Belleville, Ill., to urging ``tougher penalties'' such as liability
for false advertising if the entertainment industry fails to curb
the marketing of violent material to children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett countered that Bush's
election would change the climate and ``restore integrity to the
White House and usher in a new era of responsibility'' that would
include the entertainment industry. Bartlett added that Gore
deserved ``an Oscar award in hypocrisy'' after Gore and Democratic
campaign committees had raised $13.6 million in campaign
contributions from Hollywood and the entertainment industry this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, working to build support in Florida, waved off evidence
that he now has his work cut out for him to hold onto a state where
he once led handily. Bush campaigned with his brother Jeb, the
governor of the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   The latest public opinion poll in Florida, taken in August
following the parties' conventions, showed Bush trailing Gore by 8
percentage points, according to North Carolina-based Rasmussen
Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in good shape here,'' Bush said, referring to a state
that had voted Republican in four straight presidential elections
until the Clinton-Gore ticket wrested it away in 1996. ``This is
going to be a good state for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Slade, the former Republican Party chairman in Florida, said
that the Bush campaign had allowed Gore to seize the initiative on
issues important to the elderly, including prescription drug
coverage and bolstering Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were whistling down the street thinking it would be a
cruise and all of a sudden we're in a no-joke race,'' Slade told
the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal's Hotline newsletter calculated Monday that
Gore has narrowed Bush's state-by-state lead in electoral votes.
According to latest state-by-state public opinion surveys reviewed
by the Hotline staff, Bush leads Gore in 21 states with 232
electoral votes; Gore leads Bush in 14 states with 228 electoral
votes, including Florida, with 25 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address HYPERLINK ``C:\\Program Files\\Microsoft
Office\\Templates\\stewart &LR; hearstdc.com`` )
</P>
</TEXT>
