<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BLUM-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      09-11 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUM-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATOR'S HUSBAND SUES CARPENTER FOR $20M 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Richard Blum, the wealthy financier and husband of
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, wants $20 million in damages from a retired
carpenter who accused him on an Internet Web site of looting a
union pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual claim filed in U.S. District Court, Blum contended
he had been defamed by Horacio Grana, a disabled retiree who draws
a pension of $570 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Grana has enraged Blum by using the Internet to pillory him and
officials of the $2 billion Carpenters Pension Trust for Southern
California for alleged mismanagement and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   Blum, who is the fund's investment adviser, has repeatedly
denied Grana's allegations of impropriety, which are also contained
in a lawsuit filed in Los Angeles by Grana and two other dissident
carpenters.
</P>
<P>
   But the financier has become so irritated by Grana's
``UnionPlainfacts'' Web site that in July he asked a federal judge
to make the retiree pay him a stunning $20 million in punitive
damages _ hundreds of times more than Grana's entire worth.
</P>
<P>
   No trial dates have been set in either lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Mozer, the lawyer representing Grana, said her client was
``merely seeking to find the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is a poor, innocent carpenter who believes that his
pension fund and the pension fund of his fellow carpenters has
absolutely been misused,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the legal contest has changed Grana's view of a
politician who once was one of his favorites _ Feinstein, D-Calif.,
who is favored over Republican challenger Tom Campbell in her bid
for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Grana was a big booster of Feinstein, and at a Labor Day picnic
in 1992 he was photographed as she autographed his sweatshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I supported her once. No more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Blum collects damages from Grana, he would use the money to
fund scholarships for children of carpenters, according to a
spokesman for Blum.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the damages, Blum wants the judge to order Grana
to post a retraction on the Internet, and never to repeat his
allegations again.
</P>
<P>
   Grana, 63, lives in the Los Angeles suburb of Thousand Oaks. In
January, he and fellow retirees Phillip R. Helsius and Walter J.
Sprenger sued the pension fund, Blum and fund trustee Ronald Tutor,
who is head of the giant Tutor-Saliba construction firm, alleging
multiple violations of the U.S. Employee Retirement Income Security
Act (ERISA).
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the suit accused the fund managers of paying
Blum excessive fees: $8 million in 1997, and $33 million in 1998,
according to federal records.
</P>
<P>
   And it claimed that in 1997 Blum and Tutor had improperly pumped
$27 million in union pension funds into the Perini Corp., a
financially troubled Massachusetts construction company that Tutor
later took over.
</P>
<P>
   The investment allegedly was made by a Blum investment
partnership called RB Capital Partners. The pension fund's
investment was lost as Perini's stock plunged, the lawsuit says,
but the investment allowed Blum, as a major shareholder, to name
Tutor to Perini's board of directors. Tutor took over the company
last year by buying $40 million in stock, according to a Perini
press release.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said that the alleged transactions violated ERISA rules
against self-dealing and conflict of interest. It asked the court
to replace Tutor and national carpenters union President Douglas
McCarron as fund trustees, and to fire Blum as investment adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in the suit, Grana said, are based in part on
records he obtained via the U.S. Freedom of Information Act, and on
tips and documents slipped to him by dissident carpenters who know
him because of the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   When the suit was filed, Tutor dismissed it as ``idiotic,'' and
Blum said he was innocent of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   His fees are based on performance of the investments he makes
for the pension fund, Blum has said in court, and overall the
returns have been excellent. He also contends that it is utterly
untrue that any carpenter's pension funds were invested in Perini.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the pension fund's lawyers asked U.S.
District Judge George King to throw the Perini allegations out of
court and sanction Grana's lawyers for raising what they called
``frivolous'' and untrue allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge declined, saying that although Blum and the
trustees have insisted that no pension fund money went into Perini,
they had refused to open the books to Grana to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the parties to meet informally to settle that part of
the suit. Blum filed his defamation claim after that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
