<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, EMMY AWARDS GET A LITTLE RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 52nd annual Primetime Emmys broke out of the ratings slump
of recent years with a telecast seen at least in part by an
estimated 46 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nielsen's preliminary numbers released Monday, the
three- hour-plus broadcast on ABC Sunday averaged 21.6 million
viewers, the Emmys' largest average audience since at least 1986
when Nielsen began tracking total viewer figures.
</P>
<P>
   It was up 23 percent from Fox's audience last year, in part, no
doubt, due to promotional spots aired during ABC's top-rated shows
such as ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards telecast, hosted by Garry Shandling, also gained 16
percent from last year in the adults 18-49 demographic that is most
popular with advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of households, the show delivered a 14.2 rating and a
23 percent share of households using television. A rating point
equals 1,022,000 television homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
