<HEADLINE>
NIGHT MOVES OF ALL KINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hotspots in the European club scene, with reports from New
York Times correspondents in 5 cities:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN A CITY OF CONSTANT CHANGE, THE LATEST TREND IS A BIT OF
DISCRETION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ An aquarium seems almost de rigueur in Berlin bars
these days, an indication perhaps that the high-energy,
low-sophistication scene of the 1990s is giving way to the quieter
comforts of a leather chair, a fine martini and a touch of fish
gazing. Not that the adrenaline is gone from Berlin; it is merely
being channeled in more refined directions. The all-night techno
parties still burn, but an after-work scene of neophyte government
and e-business types has also come to life in the new capital.
</P>
<P>
   Take Reingold, an elegant watering hole that hides its charms
behind a very discreet entrance in the midst of Mitte, the buzzing
central area that once abutted the eastern side of the Berlin Wall.
The bar stretches almost the entire length of a narrow room whose
far wall is adorned with an androgynous mural. The place is chic
but understated: No gleaming mirror reflects the bottles behind the
bar and the overall effect may be described as Manet meeting
Hopper. Even the fish tank is discreet.
</P>
<P>
   The cocktails are mediocre, but Berlin's beautiful people are
here in abundance after midnight. And in Berlin, sensuality often
has a brash and electric tinge, the charge of a city whose very
essence is flux.
</P>
<P>
   For movement, it is hard to beat WMF, a club that has already
shifted premises several times since it began life soon after the
fall of the Berlin Wall in what had been the WMF kitchenware
factory. In vast new premises since June, its entrance now commands
a magnificent view of the illuminated dome of the restored
Oranienburgerstrasse synagogue. The exhilarating open-endedness and
strangeness of Berlin is evident as you edge down a dimly lighted
street, along a crumbling graffiti-smattered wall, to emerge into
WMF, a converted warehouse where large crowds dressed mainly in
gray and black dance on concrete floors to sounds dominated by
house and techno music. This club is spare, intense, raw, a great
place to let loose.
</P>
<P>
   For a cooler, and very flirtatious, note, try the Greenwich on
Gipsstrasse, a new joint that has taken the aquarium craze to
impressive lengths (the length of the bar, to be precise). Cowhide
adorns the padded walls and a certain animal intensity is
definitely in the air as couples, heterosexual and homosexual,
admire each other over some of the best martinis and whiskey sours
in the city. This establishment, full of Asian-Germans and
African-Germans, gives a real sense of the new Berlin, a city whose
population is an exotic mix. Closing time is 6 a.m. on weekdays and
8 a.m. weekends, so there is little problem squeezing in that last
drink.
</P>
<P>
   As you roll home, you may wish to look in on Newton's, a
swinging bar on the handsome Gendarmenmarkt decorated with Helmut
Newton's photographs, and on 90 Grad, an upmarket disco that is as
louche as the city it serves.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich Bar, 5 Gipsstrasse; (49-177) 280-8806. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   90 Grad, 37 Dennewitzstrasse; (49-30) 2300-5954. Open Tuesday,
Friday and Saturday. Admission, $6.80 to $9, at 2.2 marks to the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   WMF, 23 Ziegelstrasse; (49-30) 2838-8850. Closed Wednesday and
Sunday. Admission, $6.80 to $9.
</P>
<P>
   Reingold, 11 Novalisstrasse; (49-30) 2838 7676. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, 57 Charlottenstrasse; (49-30) 2029 5421. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   -ROGER COHEN is chief of the Berlin bureau of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALK OR FUNK, WHATEVER YOUR TASTE THERE'S ALWAYS GUINNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Against a tide of gaudy international discotheques, the
traditional Irish pub has no problem holding its own in Dublin.
Historic watering holes and polished nightclubs are learning to
live side by side.
</P>
<P>
   For a hip, young European capital, though, the standard of
high-fashion night life still falls far shy of London or Paris. But
even on the slowest of nights, there's never a problem finding the
unremitting buzz of laughter and conversation _ and a well-poured
pint of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   You'll rarely have to walk more than 20 minutes to get anywhere
in Dublin's compact center. And it's just as well: Public
transportation and taxis are hard to come by. Dress at clubs is
almost uniformly casual. A growing number of bars and clubs now
have a no-sneakers rule, the only strict requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A fixture in the traditional pub establishment, Kehoe's Bar and
Lounge maintains an intimate air in one of Dublin's busiest areas,
just off Grafton Street. It's just as much home to Irish Times
journalists as it is to cell phone addicts in four-button suits.
Recently, I couldn't help but get dragged into conversation by
locals complaining about rip-off real estate prices. .
</P>
<P>
   The decor hasn't changed much in a generation or so, as
evidenced by scarred hardwood floors, high mirrors behind the bar
and running boards to hold pint glasses and tired elbows. Several
small rooms, or snugs, create a conspiratorial atmosphere. The
coziest snug in Kehoe's _ with effort, six people can squeeze in _
was previously the women's bathroom, now outfitted with
red-cushioned benches.
</P>
<P>
   On warm summer nights, the crowd at Kehoe's spills out onto the
sidewalk, and seats on the curb are as contested as stools at the
bar.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller crowd turned out recently at Vicar Street, a music
hall and bar in the Liberties area, to hear the Latin jazz master
Pucho. A Harlem native who revived a salsa-funk sound in '90s
England, he appeared with a nine-piece horn-and-percussion ensemble
that kept the audience dancing throughout the show (the cover
charge was slightly more than usual, about $15, at the rate of
$1.15 to the punt).
</P>
<P>
   For more-highbrow jazz acts, like the Mingus Big Band and Brad
Mehldau, both of whom played at Vicar Street recently, tables and
stools fill the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   The attentive staff of Vicar Street wouldn't feel at home in
Switch, a basement nightclub that stands out in sharp relief
against the increasingly tourist-dominated Temple Bar area.
Floor-level speakers in four corners barrage the packed dance
floor, while glowing cigarettes glimmer from couches in the
shadows. Camouflage netting hangs from the ceiling and the walls,
adding to the grungy feel. Most Fridays feature drum and bass by
the local D.J. crew Bassbin; the rest of the week ranges from hard
techno to deep house.
</P>
<P>
   A word on the pace of the evening: Drinking starts much earlier
than in other European countries. Many Dubliners down their first
pint after work about 6:30 and continue straight through until
midnight, when bars stop serving alcohol. Nightclubs and specially
licensed late bars serve until around 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   For music and entertainment listings, see the free, widely
distributed Event Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Kehoe's Bar and Lounge, 9 South Anne Street, (off Grafton
Street); (353-1) 677-8312. No cover.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar Street, 58-59 Thomas Street; (353-1) 454-5533. No cover
for bar, $11.50 to $21 for the music hall.
</P>
<P>
   Switch, Eustace Street, Temple Bar, (below Riverhouse Hotel;
(353-1) 670-7655. Cover, $8 to $9.25.
</P>
<P>
   -BRIAN LAVERY reports for The New York Times from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STARTING AT A STYLISH BAR, ENDING ON A HOT DANCE FLOOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ ``You have to go to Queen,'' my friend said. ``It's the
baddest club in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a surprising diversity to the after-dark diversions of
Paris, enough to please anyone from the bused-in Dutch tourists
lined up for topless shows in Pigalle to the blue bloods of the
16th Arrondissement checking each other out at BCBG (bon chic, bon
genre) bars.
</P>
<P>
   But ``bad'' is not the first thing that comes to mind.
Parisians, in public at least, are generally fairly well behaved.
So, for something different, we decided to make Queen the goal of a
night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   Not without a few preliminaries, of course. Though Paris may
lack the after-hours exuberance of, say, Madrid, things don't
really get started at Queen and other clubs until at least 1 a.m.
or so, which left us about three hours to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was Le Fumoir, a clubby place across the street
from the Louvre. Its cigar bar ambience, bare wood floor and Art
Deco fittings draw a self-consciously stylish crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Next to us, shaven-headed Internet entrepreneurs reclined in
leather armchairs and discussed ``le start-up,'' which they said
would be engaged in ``le B-to-B.'' A fashion-industry type in
python-skin pants moved toward the bar and ordered a mojito. We
decided it was time to move on.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
