<SLUG> BC-LATIN-GRAMMYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LATIN GRAMMYS HIT EARLY SOUR NOTE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By SANDRA BARRERA 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the same old story for the Grammys, which has had its share
of controversy over the years: You can't please all of the people
all of the time.
</P>
<P>
   That realization comes none too soon for the premiere of the
Latin Grammy Awards, being televised Wednesday on CBS from the
Staples Center. A couple of weeks ago, an independent record label
criticized the Latin Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences for not
enlisting any Mexican regional artists to perform at the awards
show. Then Mexican regional balladeer Alejandro Fernandez was added
to the bill, silencing critics.
</P>
<P>
   But bad feelings still lingered, leaving some in the music
industry speculating just how well-represented Latinos really are
in this first awards ceremony of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the Latin Grammys is to ``celebrate the
excellence'' of music made in Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking
communities throughout the world. To be nominated, the songs must
be sung partially in Spanish or Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   But the question is, does it?
</P>
<P>
   With the Latin Grammy Awards inaugural ceremony being held in
Los Angeles and televised nationally, it's no surprise that the
show skews more to the American-bred crossover acts.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Aguilera, Ricky Martin and Jennifer Lopez are the
performers topping the list of entertainers that night. Because of
that, Beto Cuevas of the Chilean electronic band La Ley likens the
Latin Grammys to a showcasing of the latest trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never too excited about fashion shows,'' he says, speaking
to America's version of Latin music. ``I mean, I know they exist
and I respect them, but I thought this Grammy was going to be the
Latin Grammys for all those big artists from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Mauricio Abaroa, senior vice president of LARAS, it
is.
</P>
<P>
   This Grammy was conceived from an idea started by the heads of
the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences 11 years ago
when they began venturing into Latin countries to network with the
recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   That grew into LARAS, founded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the academy has more than 2,400 members from
Latin communities, including those inside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Abaroa says it's these members who are responsible for having
narrowed the more than 5,000 entries down to 200. And it's they who
decided who the 40 winners will be.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the academy's selection of nominees that has drawn
criticism _ not entirely, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was Van Nuys-based Fonovisa that criticized LARAS for not
asking any Mexican regional artists to perform on the broadcast.
Instead, the Latin Grammy organization was accused of catering to
artists associated with Sony Music and its executive Emilio Estefan
Jr., the Miami-based producer who has worked on a number of
crossover albums, including English debuts by Ricky Martin and Marc
Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Estefan was honored Monday as LARAS Person of the Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Fonovisa was also ruffled because only five of its top-selling
performers were nominated for Latin Grammys. And they were all in
the regional category.
</P>
<P>
   With Mexican regional music making up an estimated 60 percent of
all Latin music sales in the country, this sent Fonovisa and its
supporters crying foul to a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Cookman, who manages a number of Latin music acts
including Grammy nominees, was among those outraged in the article
that was picked up by news outlets across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But he has since changed his tune, saying that the reporter who
contacted him may have ``extended my opinion a little bit more than
my initial idea.''
</P>
<P>
   He was told the Latin Grammys would feature no Mexican or
Mexican regional artists on the bill. And that the list had been
finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, if it really was that way, then that's horrible,''
he says. ``But it wasn't finalized. So she sort of just jumped the
gun by saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   LARAS shot off a press release early last week that listed the
names of performers including Alejandro Fernandez. He is touted as
the Grammys answer to regional music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents the new generation of rancheros,'' says Abaroa.
He then gushes, ``What Ricky Martin is to pop, Alejandro Fernandez
is to regional music.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if Fernandez fits that bill for Fonovisa.
Representatives from the label refused to say anything more about
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty is that neither Fonovisa's employees nor its
artists, including the five who were nominated for awards in the
regional music category, will be attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   Rejelio Macin, general manager of BMG US Latin, says he's sorry
Fonovisa, one of the first American labels he worked for, has
decided to steer clear of the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Macin says he understands their frustration, but he also knows
the Grammys have a show to put on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very difficult the very first time _ as is
everything,'' he says. ``And to be honest, I don't know what the
result is going to be. I think we're just coming up with
conclusions and the show is not even over. The show hasn't even
started.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that most people in the recording industry are
looking forward to the Latin Grammys and all that it represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of it,'' says Maribel Schumacher, vice president of
marketing for Warner Music Latin America. ``I'm glad that we've
been able to garner the recognition that it merits a show in and of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumacher, too, admits Fonovisa will be sorely missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always sympathy for your competition, and I'm being
very serious,'' she says. ``Because if they took that kind of
position, then that leads me to believe that they were seriously
hurt. I am sorry for them, and I hope that next year they will be
vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   That could very well be.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Grammy Awards show is being held in L.A. this year,
but next year it could be broadcast from Mexico City, Buenos Aires,
Madrid or Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Abaroa says this will give each year's show a different flavor,
explaining, ``That's why we have more crossover artists in this
first edition because it's going to be held in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is launching a satellite into orbit with this
first edition and, you know, we're not in the mood for sadness,''
he says. ``We are not the Regional Mexican Recording Academy of
Arts and Sciences.'' &QL; 
---The show: ``Latin Grammy Awards.'' &QL; 
What: Inaugural awards show. &QL; 
The stars: Hosted by Jennifer Lopez, Jimmy Smits, Gloria Estefan
and Andy Garcia. &QL; 
Where: CBS (Channel 2). &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-AFTERDA     09-11 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-AFTERDARK-$ADV17-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: move on.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our next stop, the Buddha Bar, was not far away, around the
corner from the Hotel de Crillon off the Place de la Concorde.
Since it opened in 1996, this 1940s Saigon speak-easy on steroids
has spawned several other colonial-nostalgia imitators in Paris.
One of these, Man Ray _ which includes Johnny Depp among its owners
_ now gets more publicity, but I prefer the Buddha Bar.
</P>
<P>
   After descending a grand staircase, you enter a dimly lighted
open space with red-lacquered walls. Dominating it all is a
20-foot-tall statue of Buddha, a brooding presence _ perhaps
warning the thin women seated at low tables around him of the
dangers of doing anything more than picking at their Asian fusion
food.
</P>
<P>
   But eating is not the reason to go there. It is a comfortable
spot for conversation, or just mingling, with enough attitude
thrown in to make it feel like Paris. Bigger than the New York
establishment of the same name that enjoyed its 15 minutes of fame
in the mid-1990s, Paris' Buddha Bar packs in a less exclusive
crowd, a mix of visiting young businessmen who want to spend some
money and Parisians who might or might not want to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, it was the French who seemed to be enjoying
themselves the most, particularly when the music shifted from
Asian-themed house to North African rai and they got up to dance in
the darker corners.
</P>
<P>
   But by now we were ready for more serious dancing, so we caught
a cab up the Champs-Elysees and stopped outside Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the setting, it is hard to imagine that this is a
``bad'' club, let alone the baddest in the city. The heavily
globalized avenue is about as conventionally bland a place as there
is in Paris. The cheesy purple sign over the door hardly
distinguishes the club from the theme restaurants that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   But kitsch is part of the appeal, attracting a part-gay,
part-straight crowd that moves quickly past the doorman (except for
groups of women, on some nights, I am told.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it quickly became clear that we were not at the Disney
store. The coat-check boy wagged his tongue at guests. The house
music made my eardrums throb. Several women swung from netting
covering the dance floor, as a crowd writhed underneath. In the
cavernous unisex bathroom, there was evidence of seriously bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether Queen is the baddest club in Paris. But
after a night of dancing, the worst was yet to come: Trying to hail
a taxi at 4 a.m., when the Metro stopped running three hours
earlier and there are no gypsy cabs. Talk about bad.
</P>
<P>
   Le Fumoir, 6, rue de l'Amiral-de-Coligny; (33-1) 42.92.00.24. No
cover.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buddha Bar, 8, rue Boissy d'Anglas; (33-1) 53.05.90.00. No
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Man Ray, 34, rue Marbeuf; (33-1) 56.88.36.36. Cover $13.70,
Fridays only, at 7.3 francs to the dollar.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Queen, 102, avenue des Champs-Elysees; (33-1) 53.89.08.90. Cover
charge (one drink included), $6.85 Sunday to Thursday, $13.70
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   _ERIC PFANNER is deputy business editor of The International
Herald Tribune in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOT SPOTS THAT MAKE YOU FEEL AS IF YOU BELONG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ There is nothing easy about going out for an evening in
London. Sure you can always belly up to the bar at the local pub,
but painting the town red here takes much more effort than that.
Almost in a throwback to the old British penchant for classifying
people by aristocratic pedigree, when you line up behind the velvet
rope, it doesn't matter how primped you look; the bouncer doesn't
care. The real question: Are you a member?
</P>
<P>
   London's hottest bars and clubs are for members only and that
means being a celebrity, knowing one, or anteing up as much as
$3,000 a year after being nominated by another member _ and
seconded _ just to get your foot in the door.
</P>
<P>
   For the tourist passing through town, hitting the hottest spots
can be a risky, though thrilling endeavor. And for those less
adventurous, there are still a number of good places to try without
the hassle of having to be or look like Claudia Schiffer.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner or the theater in the West End, a good place for a
drink is Mezzo, a relatively low-key bar and restaurant in Soho.
One of Sir Terrance Conran's ever-expanding number of overly
designed bars and restaurants around town, Mezzo is a bit luxurious
without a sense of arrogance. The expansive bar on the first floor
has an eclectic mix, from 20-somethings in jeans to 60-year-olds in
suits. It's easy to feel comfortable, unless you like dimmer
lighting.
</P>
<P>
   For something a bit more exclusive, try the Purple Bar inside
Ian Schrager's newest London hotel, Sanderson. It will take a
little work to talk your way in _ if you're not a hotel guest, get
there really early _ because the bar is normally for members only.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside this small purple temple of chic arrogance, order a
classic martini _ no fruit martinis _ or vodka, though everything
is expensive ($10 or more a drink). With Frank Sinatra playing in
the background, the Purple Bar is a great people-watching place,
especially if you care which people you're watching. If you'd
rather leave celebrity watching to the cable channel E!, go to
Mezzo.
</P>
<P>
   For a bit of dancing while you drink, make your way to the
Notting Hill Arts Club in the heart of Notting Hill. Catering to a
distinctly younger set _ 20s and 30s _ the club has a steady stream
of cool D.J.'s spinning house and garage music into the early
morning, with a different theme each night. In a huge basement, the
club seems a bit grungy, but attracts a very attractive clientele.
And it's not impossible to get past the bouncer.
</P>
<P>
   If your goal is to dance into the night, go to a club like China
White, near Soho, or Heaven, north of Piccadilly Circus. It will be
helpful to get on the guest list for either place, so creativity
counts. You can try calling ahead and citing some business
affiliation or a local connection you might have. A concierge at a
trendy hotel can help, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both are multifloor extravaganzas, filled with thumping music
that doesn't stop until the sun comes up. These clubs are great for
getting sweaty with beautiful people, but don't expect meaningful
conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A note about getting home: The subway stops running at midnight.
Your only choices after that, until about 5:30 a.m,, when it
resumes service, are a bus or taxi. Both are extremely hard to come
by in the early morning hours, and gypsy cabs are not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to ensure a ride home is to take the telephone
number of an authorized radio taxi company with you. And yes, even
the taxi company will ask when you call: Are you a member?
</P>
<P>
   Mezzo, 100 Wardour St.; (44-207) 314-4000. Reservations
required. Cover, $7.25 for music downstairs, at $1.45 to the pound.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson, 50 Berners Street; (44-207) 300-1444. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   The Notting Hill Arts Club, 19 Notting Hill Gate, (44-207)
460-4459. Admission, $4.35 before 8 p.m., $7.25 after.
</P>
<P>
   China White, 6 Air Street, (44-207) 343-0040. Closed Sunday.
Admission, $21.75.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven, Under the Arches off Villiard Street, near Charing Cross
Station; (44-207) 930-2020. Closed Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
Admission, $1.50 to $17.50.
</P>
<P>
   -ANDREW ROSS SORKIN reports from London for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF THE CAFFEINE DOESN'T KEEP YOU AWAKE THE MUSIC WILL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRAGUE _ A town swarming with tourists does its best to cater to
their nighttime whims and to make some money besides, but it's
still possible to find a few places to drink, sup, listen or dance
where not everyone is foreign or wearing a baseball cap backward or
tripping out on Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Prague has some nice jazz, and like everything here, the price
is reasonable. Downstairs at U Maleho Glena (At Little Glenn's) is
a small cellar with tables and an unusually good selection of local
groups, including the excellent Robert Balzar Trio; Jan Knop, a
pianist who calls himself Najponk; and Yvonne Sanchez, a popular
half-Cuban, half-Polish chanteuse. There is a cafe and bar
upstairs; the jazz club in the basement has a cover charge of 90
crowns, all of $2.30, at 39 crowns to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Little Glenn is an American, Glenn Spicker, who also introduced
bagels to Prague at his two Bohemia Bagel restaurants. But his jazz
club has a friendly, local feel and it's close to the crowded
Charles Bridge, which you'll end up strolling at night even if you
vow not to.
</P>
<P>
   Prague's cafes are open late into the evening. The most famous
is Cafe Slavia, where President Vaclav Havel and other dissidents
often lingered and argued when they weren't in jail. In 1992, it
was closed over an ownership dispute (though broken into in an act
of liberation for a couple of nights by Havel and friends, who
brought their own coffee).
</P>
<P>
   Slavia reopened in late 1997, refurbished with a green theme. It
is rooted in a painting the new owners resurrected, Viktor Oliva's
``Absinthe Drinker,'' featuring a comely bright green female
fantasy sitting on a customer's table. Perhaps you'll share the
vision in this country where absinthe remains legal and on sale.
It's likely to be better than the coffee, which is Dutch and weak,
or the service, which is glacial. Granny's cake with walnuts,
however, is great.
</P>
<P>
   Another lovely cafe, closed for 10 years in a different
post-Communist ownership dispute, the Cafe Imperial, reopened just
three months ago. Informal yet spectacular, its original 1914 tiled
walls and ceiling are intact. The coffee is Italian and comes with
a free kobliha, or jam doughnut. And it isn't too crowded, yet.
</P>
<P>
   Radost FX remains Prague's most famous nightclub cum cafe and
lounge, with everything from vegetarian food upstairs to a hazy,
smoky dance floor and D.J. in the basement. There is a small
gallery above it from which one can watch others dance, kiss or
negotiate other forms of intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   It is very loud and very popular. On a recent night, however,
the sofas covered with animal prints were occupied by rather glum
groups in their early 20s. It got better, presumably, much later.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, try Palac Akropolis, a somewhat quieter and more
adult spot in an old movie theater, with a performance hall and two
downstairs bars where one might actually hold a conversation.
You'll find more Czechs there than tourists, at least most of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   U Maleho Glena, Karmelitska 23; (420-2) 535-8115. Jazz club
cover, $2.30.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Slavia, Smetanovo nabrezi 2; (420-2) 2421-8493.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Imperial , Na Porici 15; (420-2) 231-6012.
</P>
<P>
   Radost FX, Caf Belehradska 120; (420-2) 2425-4776. Cover, $1.30.
</P>
<P>
   Palac Akropolis, Kubelikova 27; (420-2) 2271-2287. No cover at
bar; admission to concerts, $2.50 to $10.
</P>
<P>
   _STEVEN ERLANGER is chief of the Prague bureau of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
