<SLUG> BC-TIRE-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGESTONE PLANS TO END DUAL STANDARD ON FIRESTONE QUALITY
CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In his first public appearance since the recall of 6.5
million Firestone tires in the United States, the president of
Firestone's Japanese parent acknowledged Monday that the company
had not paid proper attention to quality control.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Bridgestone, Yoichiro Kaizaki, said the company
would exert stronger control over the management of its American
subsidiary, Bridgestone/Firestone, and that it would apply the same
quality-control criteria for both its Bridgestone and Firestone
tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we have managed it was wrong,'' Kaizaki said. There
had been dual standards within the company regarding problems with
the two brands, he said. ``The responsibility for the problem lies
with Tokyo.''
</P>
<P>
   The acknowledgment was unusual for a company that has been
criticized for not having its top executives actively address the
tire problems. In another sign of a new public tack,
Bridgestone/Firestone said Monday that it had named Ketchum, a unit
of the Omnicom Group, as its new public relations firm, after
Fleishman-Hillard International Communications resigned earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we have been slow in responding to public
concerns, that we underestimated the intensity of the situation,
and that we have been too focused on internal details,'' Masatoshi
Ono, the chief executive of the American subsidiary, said in a
statement announcing the hire. ``We are determined to change all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   His boss, Kaizaki, said earlier at a news conference in Tokyo
that Bridgestone/Firestone was managed independent &UR;  &LR; of the parent.
``We managed subsidiaries located in Japan quite carefully but have
not applied the same attention to managing overseas subsidiaries,''
Kaizaki said. ```We let the U.S. unit use its own culture. There
was an element of mistake in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dual standards also existed when it came to technology support.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a problem with a Bridgestone tire, our technology
staff in Tokyo would rush to the site'' overseas to help out,
Kaizaki said. ``But if a problem arose with a Firestone tire, they
wouldn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the company has not identified specific defects
in the tires. He said there were variables that could have
contributed to the accidents, including air pressure and length of
use. He added that the number of accidents in other vehicles using
Firestone tires was considerably lower than those involving Ford
Explorers. The accidents ``for some reason'' keep happening, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaizaki, who was president of the United States subsidiary in
the early 1990s, said Bridgestone would do its ``utmost to keep the
Firestone brand.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had no plans to resign. Shares of Bridgestone
have plunged 46.6 percent since the Aug. 9 recall announcement. In
Tokyo trading Monday, Bridgestone slipped 2 yen, to 1108 yen
($10.45).
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fully aware that we suffered a critical damage,'' Kaizaki
said. ``But we firmly believe we can rebuild Firestone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
