<SLUG> BC-JOAN-OSBORNE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING THE HIGH NOTES
</HEADLINE>
  Record label dropped her, but Osborne took righteous road 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By SANDRA BARRERA 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years is a long time for an artist to go without making a
new record.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Osborne knows this firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't put out a record since her 1995 debut ``Relish.''
That was the album that went multiplatinum and scored a major hit
with ``One of Us,'' a song that starred God as an Everyday Joe. It
even got her a handful of Grammy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mercury Records began breathing down her neck for
another hit, Osborne failed to deliver. So she was dropped like a
flash-in-the-pan only to resurface sans the corkscrew curls and
nose ring with the album ``Righteous Love.'' It hits stores today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put any expectations on it because I feel like
it would be too easy to be disappointed,'' she says. ``I just hope
people are interested and that the music has some positive
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Righteous Love'' opens with the funky ballad ``Running Out of
Time'' and is followed by 10 more tracks that grind a la Britney
(``Love Is Alive''), play on Eastern rhythms (``If I Was Your
Man'') before ending in a stunning version of Bob Dylan's folky
``Make You Feel My Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so in love with that song,'' Osborne says. ``You know,
people think of him as this sort of cerebral, political,
intellectual writer _ and he certainly is that. But he's able to
have come through all of that and write this simple, beautiful love
song that just tears your heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   From the bluesy swagger of ``Righteous Love'' to the soulful
stride of her single ``Safety in Numbers,'' Osborne's voice has a
blues finesse that made her so desirable as a singer in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   While he was still hosting a radio show back in Woodstock, Nic
Harcourt, who now hosts ``Morning Becomes Eclectic'' on KCRW, began
playing Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   This was before she had put out ``Relish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so long ago I don't really remember the details,''
Harcourt says. ``But I must have connected with someone who was
involved in managing her and they sent me some cassettes, which I
really liked but didn't put on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she released an EP that we played on the air, and two
years later, I guess, she came out with this album that exploded,''
he says. ``She's just an amazing artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly if somebody's not interested in supporting you as an
artist then you don't want to be on their label,'' she says. ``So
I'm not unhappy that I'm not there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne is now signed to Interscope Records, and she's gearing
up for a tour in support of ``Righteous Love.'' Tonight she
performs at the House of Blues and launches a new online
publications, Heroine Magazine (www.heroinemag.com).
</P>
<P>
   She says the focus of the magazine is to profile ``women who
have done amazing things,'' adding that the first issues features a
conversation between Susan Sarandon and the Indigo Girls on their
political activism and how they mix that with their art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of done everything from coming up with story ideas
to interviewing people,'' Osborne says. ``I can't do that anymore
because I have a lot of other work to do. But it was fun for me to
get started.'' &QL; 
---Who: Joan Osborne. &QL; 
Where: House of Blues, 8430 Sunset Blvd., West Hollywood. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL; 
Tickets General admission is $21; tickets can be purchased at the
House of Blues box office or by calling (323) 848-5100. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
