<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES-N     09-11 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELLIOUS HOUSE CONSERVATIVES TRYING TO BE MORE PRAGMATIC, AND
POLITICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House conservatives, who five years ago forced a
government shutdown to combat spending and helped oust Newt
Gingrich as speaker, have retreated this year and stayed mostly
silent about President Clinton's desire for significant increases
in spending levels.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to shut down the government or hamstring the
Republican leadership at every turn, as they previously did to get
what they wanted during year-end negotiations, these conservatives,
members of the so-called rebel class elected in 1994, have embraced
the art of Washington politics, in many cases swapping
philosophical principle for political pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   With their numbers dwindling to 60 or so stalwarts, these
conservatives say they have learned to make peace with Clinton's
powerful veto pen, to compromise and practice patience, and to
funnel money back home to protect themselves and the tenuous
Republican majority in the House. They recognize that a slim,
seven-vote margin of power does not allow them to behave like
revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, in an era of budget surpluses, their
crusade to slash spending has become mostly irrelevant and
difficult to justify to their leaders and constituents. They are
soldiers in flux, their mission blunted by prosperity. In 1994,
they coalesced around balancing the budget, ending wasteful
spending and ridding the country of a ballooning deficit. Now that
has been accomplished, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past month, I was running around the district trying to
find one person that still seemed interested in spending in
Washington,'' said Rep &UR; .  &LR; Joe Scarborough &UR;  &LR; of &UR;  &LR; Florida and a
one-time firebrand. ``Republicans have been the victim of their own
success, just like after the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, said Rep. Mark Sanford of South Carolina, an
uncompromising fiscal conservative, ``the class of '94 has really
been co-opted. Our game now is trade-offs. What marbles can we
trade as opposed to the old line of when we first got here that
this is a matter of principle.''
</P>
<P>
   They are also biding their time, understanding that Gov. George
W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, could win the White
House and smooth the way for many of their causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not make waves so we don't cause a train wreck because
it will all be fixed when Bush gets in,'' Sanford said, a message
most conservatives have heeded.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some Republicans in the Senate are doing their best to
run from the label of conservative in the upcoming election.
``We've seen dozens of Republican general election ads and not one
has contained the words Republican or conservative,'' said Jim
Jordan, a spokesman for the Senate Democratic campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic leaders will meet with Clinton at the
White House on Tuesday in their first discussions to determine
exactly what spending levels the president wants. The talks come at
a time when many Republicans voice distrust that Clinton will
negotiate in good faith, feeling that he is more interested in
provoking disputes or delays with conservatives that would help
Democrats at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Although their numbers have dwindled and their mission grown
more fractured, these conservatives have not given up the fight
entirely. Their list of demands may be much shorter now _ gone for
the most part are battles over the National Endowment for the Arts,
education spending and, in many cases, abortion _ but they are
still making them.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they want to underscore their displeasure with all
this spending; they are already squabbling with the leadership over
several appropriations bills, arguing that the bills exceed
spending limits outlined in the budget blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to blunt the increase in spending, they hope to offer a
plan to protect some of the surplus by setting aside $2 billion to
$5 billion on each &UR;  &LR; appropriations bill to pay down the debt. It is
a politically popular idea that pleases Republican leaders and
would be difficult for Clinton to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives may also force an impasse on several of
Clinton's top policy priorities, including passage of a bill to
make hate attacks on gays a federal crime, expand school
construction and tighten gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our base doesn't expect us to win, but they want to make sure
we're fighting for them,'' said Rep. John Shadegg &UR;  &LR; of &UR;  &LR; Arizona, who
is chairman of the 60-member Conservative Action Team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES-2     09-11 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Action Team.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That is a long cry from their all-or-nothing position back in
1994 when 73 freshmen became the foot soldiers in Gingrich's
Republican revolution to carry out the Contract With America, the
conservatives' manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over since 1995, a band of the rebellious freshmen held
up major spending bills with their demands to strip funds from the
National Endowment for the Arts, prevent federal dollars to be used
for abortions or to promulgate abortions or to permit striking
workers to be replaced, among many others. In 1995, they fueled the
push to seek a balanced budget by 2002, and shut down the
government to do it, a move that backfired politically.
</P>
<P>
   But now, many of those hard-line rebels, known as CATs, for
Conservative Action Team, have mellowed in tone and tactics, and
have acknowledged their willingness to compromise or accept failure
so long as they can say the House tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a practical conservative now,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham
of South Carolina, without a touch of remorse. ``I'll vote for
bills that I wouldn't have voted for two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert has helped along their transition.
In part, it was Newt Gingrich, Hastert's predecessor, who stoked
the conservatives' rage. A rebel himself, Gingrich often issued
dictates and seldom sat down to listen to them, the conservatives
said. They also said he was quick to promise much and deliver
little.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, a conciliator whom the conservatives say they trust,
has done the opposite, setting a less combative tone and explaining
the difficulty of governing with such a slim majority. Had Gingrich
still been in charge, said Rep. Mark Souder of Indiana, once of the
most defiant rebels, ``The CATs group, as well as moderates, would
have blown up by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny identifies, really listens, changes, and then says how
would you do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, who is still critical of the
Republican leadership, also concedes that there are differences
between Gingrich and Hastert. ``You can absolutely trust what Denny
Hastert tells you.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn is part of a shrinking number of rebels who say they
cannot stomach all of this capitulation on spending, despite the
budget surplus. Sanford is another. Not coincidentally, both men
are leaving at the end of this term as they make good on pledges
not to serve more than six years in the House. Their farewells,
they say, are colored with disillusion.
</P>
<P>
   The two men say that Republicans, for all their talk of
accomplishments, have nevertheless abandoned their principles for
political survival and lost sight of grander goals _ less
government and bedrock conservative social policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leadership has not had courage to face Clinton down
because they're more interested in maintaining control of Congress
than doing what's best for the country,'' Coburn said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most rebels, like Scarborough, &UR;  &LR; look back and see victory,
ticking off their successes since 1994. Sanford does the opposite.
The budget surplus, he said, has nothing to do with tightening
spending but everything to do with economic expansion and a bull
market, which could decline at any time. Clinton's tax increase,
which he secured before the rebels got elected, helped it all
along, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frequent words you probably heard in those CAT
meetings four years ago is this is a matter of principle and we
can't vote for this,'' he said. ``But I guess as time goes by, and
one becomes a more seasoned legislator, the best word now is, `What
can we trade off in this bill?' That is a pretty, pretty, pretty
violent contrast.''
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, the two words that do not cross any of the
rebels' lips is government shutdown. Now it is Clinton, they note,
who is making that veiled reference, something they note with a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice little switch,'' Scarborough said. ``We wish him
all the best. It's not as fun as it sounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
