<P>
   SELMA-ELECTION _ SELMA, Ala._Everything's changed and nothing's
changed here in the cradle of the Civil Rights movement. The town
where the famous voting rights march led by Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr. took place in 1965 now has its first black police chief and
blacks now make up a majority of the registered voters. That's a
far cry from the days when blacks had to demand their right to
vote. One thing hasn't changed. Joe T. Smitherman, the mayor in
1965 when state troopers beat and trampled protestors on the Edmund
Pettus Bridge, still holds office. But there's hope among the black
community that's tried to unseat him for 36 years. Smitherman, a
former washing machine salesman, is in a runoff for the first time.
He's challenged by a black businessman who's tried twice before to
beat Smitherman. The election is Tuesday night. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
