<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT-PROBLEMS09     09-11 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-PROBLEMS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ritter Collett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Bob Knight's problems with the administration at
Indiana University _ particularly with Athletics Director Clarence
Doninger _ that bubbled to the surface in the past year, go further
back.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the 1988-89 basketball season, a lot of people on and
off the campus weren't overjoyed when Knight added his son, Pat, to
his staff. Although he had no public comment on the subject,
Doninger was among those who questioned the move.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the withdrawal of a blue chip recruit, Springfield's
Jason Collier in his sophomore season before the Big Ten Conference
schedule, that drew heavy criticism of Knight's program among IU
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Collier had been rated among the nation's most sought after and
highly publicized recruits of the previous year. There had been
other players who had left the program before, but no one of the
national stature of Collier.
</P>
<P>
   Knight felt that Doninger was not publicly supporting his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were promising players that same year transferring from
the likes of Kentucky and North Carolina, but I was the guy getting
the most heat,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   Collier is an athlete of considerable skills, but Knight didn't
believe the competitive fire was burning in his belly. Collier
transferred to Georgia Tech where he didn't come close to
All-American status as expected and was actually blamed by some for
contributing to veteran coach Bobby Cremins losing his job last
season. (Collier was named second-team All-Atlantic Coast
Conference and he was an NBA first-round draft choice, 15th pick
overall).
</P>
<P>
   But if Knight was criticized for Collier's departure, the real
firestorm blew up a year later when Luke Recker announced his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Recker was Indiana's ``Mr. Basketball'' in his senior year in
high school. That he committed to IU without ever considering
another school was something special. Recker later went on record
that he wasn't developing his talent _ a slap at Knight's coaching.
</P>
<P>
   But the coach's view was that Recker was unwilling to adapt to
Knight's long-standing concept of starting the offense off
defensive play _ which such players as high scoring Steve Alford,
Brian Evans, Isiah Thomas and A.J. Guyton had learned to accept and
do.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, Knight's philosophy could be criticized
around the state in places it had never been before.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, there were two critical mistakes in
recruiting that came back to haunt Knight. Longtime assistant coach
Ron Felling was a participant in both.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved Brian Cardenal, whose father was athletic
trainer at Illinois. Felling apparently took the word of Illini
assistant coaches at the time that Cardenal wasn't Big Ten
material. The player later said he actually wanted to go to IU, but
wasn't recruited. He wound up at Purdue where he tormented the
Hoosiers every time he faced them.
</P>
<P>
   The balding Cardenal played basketball the same way Pete Rose
played baseball. He won a reputation of leading the league in floor
burns. He is evidence that recruiters never know what is inside a
man that drives him to perform beyond his potential.
</P>
<P>
   The other recruiting snafu involved is Andre Hutson, the power
forward out of Trotwood-Madison High School who helped Michigan
State to back-to-back Big Ten titles and has a year of eligibility
left.
</P>
<P>
   Vandalia Butler coach Ray Zawadzki recalls being surprised last
year to get a call from Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if any member of his staff had contacted me for an
opinion on Hutson,'' Zawadzki said.
</P>
<P>
   Felling had turned in a negative report on Hutson. Knight fired
him last December in a move that drew attention to some in-house
unrest _ a prelude to the final sad story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
