<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TORONTO-FILM-FESTIVAL     09-11 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FILM-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TORONTO,   FILM FESTIVAL   IS A PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ On the opening day of the 25th Toronto International
Film Festival, a sunny and muggy Thursday afternoon, a minor
miracle took place. At the corner of Bay and Bloor Streets, by the
Varsity Theater, a festival site, a sprinkle of water fell to offer
relief from the irritating heat.
</P>
<P>
   The moisture from a cloudless sky had everyone looking and
muttering the same question, ``Where's this coming from?'' It was
just the kind of thing you would expect from this festival and this
city, a place that's both sophisticated and pleasant, and for those
dashing from one theater to the next, the light drizzle was like a
a needed splash for a boxer between rounds. (I found out that the
water was coming from a construction site, but its origin seemed
almost beside the point.)
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's festival is among the most cosmopolitan and inclusive
because the city turns out to support film. It's a metropolis for
movie lovers who take the opportunity to immerse themselves in
their enthusiasm. (Toronto has one of the three largest moviegoing
populations in North America, along with New York and Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   The joke has always been that Canadians in general _ and Toronto
residents specifically _ have to make up for a lack of cool with a
reflexive cordiality that borders on the pathological; this
couldn't be less true.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 300 films at this year's festival
dramatize family life in distinctive and idiosyncratic ways. The
wry and subtly atmospheric ``Angels of the Universe,'' a film by
the Icelandic director Fridrik Thor Fridriksson, looks with
sumptuous intensity at obsession, loss and spirituality through the
eyes of its suffering and game protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all equal before God, angels of the universe,'' he says,
though it's hard to believe when you see him and several other men
with Messiah complexes puffing nervously on cigarettes. This
anxiety keeps the movie vibrating. Equally sumptuous is
Fridriksson's use of music; it's a big part of his hero's life, as
the star pounds the walls of his house to ``I Put a Spell on You,''
and the luscious colors shine while the lovely, weightless songs of
the Icelandic pop group Sigur Ros play. Some may find the
miraculous essence of ``Angels'' too literal, but Fridriksson has
manufactured a gorgeous fugue state.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cox's ``Innocence'' is about a body blow to family. Its two
elderly lovers pick up after a gap of 50 years, and reveries of
their earlier involvement intrude into their current lives. The
picture's a little square, but the performances by its leads, who
come to life slowly _ as they spend more time together, and old
feelings and insecurities re-emerge _ move the picture beyond a
safe timorousness. The two actresses playing the older and younger
Claire have the same pained lines around their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Even director Benoit Jacquot's ``Sade,'' a melodrama about the
Marquis de Sade (Daniel Auteuil), has the roving sensualist acting
as a father figure. It's the most unusual performance that the
generally laid-back Auteuil has ever given. Savoring every syllable
as each rolls off his lips, he incorporates a theatrical and
outsize audacity, like a French Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   His daring and gentleness is responsible for one of the best
scenes of any movie in the festival: a group, including the
luminous young actress Islid Le Besco, has gone through a mild
debauchery tutorial by Sade, and while they can't hold their heads
up to look anyone in the eyes, Sade ravenously devours a peach;
another day, another virgin.
</P>
<P>
   The director Stephen Frears was honored by the festival for his
body of work. His remarkable and intimate new film, ``Liam,'' is
playing here in addition to other films by him. Though his work
seems to be about ad hoc families, he rolls his eyes when that
point is raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about these things that much,'' Frears said.
``The whole business of giving so much attention to directors is
rubbish. I know the contributions that others make. When I was a
boy I just went to the pictures. I didn't question things. Though I
have been the beneficiary of a questioning generation, that's very
true. I'm just sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Liam'' is about family and tragedy in Liverpool in 1930; its
7-year-old title character is played by Anthony Burrows. A family
struggles to make ends meet as Fascism begins to ripen in England,
though it's also a comedy about repression, a subject that
resonates through most of Frears' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, all right,'' he said with a laugh. ``This one is about
family. It's about a child's view of the world, and the cruel way
the father is treated, a man who's trying to maintain his dignity.
If you're treated like that by the world, then Fascism makes sense.
I feel sorry for him. I admire the mother, who keeps things going
in the house. I've always admired actresses in my films because
they're stoic and dignified, like the mother in `Liam' or Michelle
Pfeiffer in `Dangerous Liaisons.' Actors are always the ones who
complain, about their lines or their makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Fascism leads to racism in the horrifying climax of ``Liam,''
and it's like the best of Frears' work: an apparent calm is
disrupted by characters coming to grips with the misery they're
capable of causing.
</P>
<P>
   Encountering that evil in Hanif Kureishi's script for ``My
Beautiful Laundrette'' saddened him, Frears said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism first appeared publicly in England in 1957, during the
race riots,'' he said. ``Otherwise it's very quiet and insidious.
When I read Hanif's script, my heart sank. There's so much denial,
there. But, yes, `Liam' is about denial, too. I first learned I was
Jewish when I was 20, when my mother told me. It was startling, but
it was much more startling to have something concealed from me for
so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say it made a sort of dollar-book-Freud sense of my
life. But it's funny about `Liam.' In the scene when the kids come
running out of the cinema after seeing the movie, they're playing
cowboys and Indians. And they didn't know how, so we had to teach
them to be racist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
