<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-11 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LOAVES AND WISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife was buying groceries at the supermarket shortly after Al
Gore chose Joe Lieberman as his running mate. It was a Friday, and
as the checkout lady bagged my wife's groceries, she was left at
the end with two breads _ one a Sabbath challah and the other a
Roman Meal sandwich loaf. The checkout lady picked up the two
breads, put them in a bag together, looked at my wife with a little
smile and said: ``I think the Roman Meal and challah can go
together, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   My wife told me she was sure it was the grocery lady's little
commentary on the Gore-Lieberman ticket. I tell that story when
people ask if I think Americans will actually vote for a ticket
with a Jewish vice-presidential candidate. Sure, for some
Lieberman's religion will be a negative, but I have no doubt most
Americans will judge him on his merits, which, thus far, have only
elevated his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   It's become something of a truism in American politics that, to
paraphrase H.L. Mencken, you'll never go broke underestimating the
American people. I think just the opposite is true. It certainly
has been in this campaign. There is still a basic fairness and
intelligence to the American electorate, and both candidates have
gotten into their worst trouble when they have underestimated that.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Gov. George W. Bush's lengthy dodging of the official
presidential debates. Bush had a complicated explanation about how
it was really Gore who was dodging the debates, because he wouldn't
go on ``Larry King'' or ``Meet the Press'' first. But that didn't
fly. Eskimos in their igloos in Alaska could see that Bush was
running away. Australian aborigines tuning in by satellite could
tell that Bush was dodging Gore. That's why, when you listened to
Bush accusing Gore of avoiding the debates, you just wanted to say:
``Am I wearing a sign that says `Stupid' on it?'' A politician
should never put such a question on voters' lips. Bush seems to
have gotten the message.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's low point _ the moment that deflated his whole primary
campaign _ was when he declared that he believed that the Cuban
refugee Elian Gonzalez should not automatically be reunited with
his father, but that the case should be resolved in family court _
and that none of this had to do with Florida politics. People are
always ready to accept a certain amount of pandering, but they
resent it when it goes to a point of insulting their intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's recent rebound surely has to do with the fact that,
having underestimated American voters for so many months by
appealing to them with various disguises and Alpha Male routines,
he finally settled on running as, well, Al Gore. His convention
speech basically said: I'm a wonk, I'm a bore, but I love my wife,
I believe in government, and I know from experience in Washington
how to make things work at home and abroad. That was a person a lot
more people thought they might like as president. And on the
question of his association with Clinton's scandals, Gore declared:
Don't worry, I'm my own man.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, has run as himself from the start. And while
there are aspects of his personality that are clearly appealing to
voters, his inability to consistently put sentences together _ and
the holes in his knowledge that lead him to calling Greeks
``Grecians'' and to other eyebrow-raising bloopers _ have forced
him to essentially say to voters: Don't worry, I won't be my own
man.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last week Bush introduced Colin Powell at a
campaign event by saying: ``The next man I introduce used to be in
government. And if all goes well ... (he will be in my cabinet
too).'' Message to voters: Don't worry, I won't be driving alone.
Powell will be there in the front seat, along with dad's other old
advisers. But this may not be a bad strategy, because it addresses
what voters worry about with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For many voters this election is clearly about differing
policies, but for many I believe it's about something more basic _
a feeling that the country's engine is running OK, and we're more
or less headed on the right road, and therefore the key question
is, to whom do you want to entrust the car keys? That's a question
the American people come to with a lot of good instincts _ whether
in evaluating character or tax cuts. And my own bet is that in
these closing weeks of the campaign the candidate who loses will be
the one who underestimates that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
