A9306 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIZMAGS0912-COX     09-11 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM tries to shine up Cadillac image
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elvis bought them six at a time. President Eisenhower rode one
to his 1953 inauguration. John F. Kennedy tooled around Palm Beach
in a convertible. And they graced the driveways of King Saud and J.
Paul Getty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after decades ``stuck in the mud,'' the Caddy _ Cadillac to
the uninitiated _ is about to make a new entrance in a ``bold new
campaign to rev up its image and its sales,'' Fortune (Sept. 18)
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The new marketing effort ``represents a high-stakes move by
General Motors' Cadillac division to reposition itself in the
luxury-car market after a quarter century of declining sales and
diminishing prestige,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cadillac trails Mercedes-Benz, BMW, Audi and Lexus
models by a wide margin, it was once the premier luxury automobile
with its long fins and twin taillights _ and is still the
longest-running luxury-car brand name, Fortune notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadillacs were icons of American might,'' writes Lucian
Truscott IV in a personal reminiscence about his first Caddy.
``Driving one of those monsters, a man of achievement must have
felt as if he could bluff his way through anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Warren Buffett might blink at the bill he would get from
the ``ultimate investment club'' assembled by Money (October), a
personal finance magazine. Among the 10 members are Wall Street
strategist Abby Joseph Cohen, mutual fund legend Peter Lynch and
Vanguard funds founder John C. Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a portfolio of stocks gleaned by Money from its
interviews with these high-priced gurus: American International
Group, Amazon.com, Aventis, Bank of America, BJ Services, Cisco,
Extreme Networks, Exxon Mobil, Fleetwood Enterprises, Merck, PE
Corp.PE Biosystems and WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor has rushed to assure consumers that it is doing
everything possible to quickly fix the problem of defective
Firestone tires. But Business Week (Sept. 18) says the automaker
should have acted at least three years sooner, when tire problems
first appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crisis that is testing (CEO Jacques) Nasser's
relatively new leadership and the strength of the Ford brand,''
says the magazine. Ford's strong sales and financial record and
fine reputation under Nasser are ``suddenly up in the air'' until
ultimate responsibility for the tire debacle is answered. For
Firestone, it may be too late, says Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   Cash in the hand can calm frazzled nerves in a down stock
market, which is why investors should buy shares of companies that
pay dividends, says Barron's (Sept. 11). The financial weekly's
best bets include General Electric, Merck and Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
whose stock performances have outstripped the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
in at least five of the past 10 years _ and they consistently up
their dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Synovus Financial, a Columbus-based financial services company,
is the lone Georgia company on the latest list of ``100 best
companies for working mothers,'' published annually by Working
Mother (October) magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's list is based on five criteria: child care, leave
for new parents, flexible work arrangements, work/life benefits
such as elder care and opportunities for advancement for women.
</P>
<P>
   Stock splits can be money-making opportunities for investors,
says Technology Investor (October), which walks readers through a
series of steps designed to make it easier to spot potential splits
before they happen.
</P>
<P>
   The latest spin by law firms that specialize in initial stock
offerings is to demand a share of the stock in the companies they
take public, Smart Business (September) says. And that's ``on top
of hefty fees,'' it adds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
