u i BC-SAFIN-RUSSIA-NYT     09-11 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIN-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS ARE QUICK TO CLAIM U.S. OPEN CHAMP AS THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW &UR;  &LR; _ In a nation where there are but two sports _ soccer,
and everything else _ Russians were positively glowing with pride
today over the athletic prowess of 20-year-old Marat Safin.
</P>
<P>
   This, even though he practices a third-tier sport, tennis, in
which the only physical contact is between a racquet and a ball &UR; ;  &LR; 
even though he is an ethnic Tatar, a people too often derided here
_ a millennium after the fact, to boot _ as Atilla the Hun's
henchmen &UR; ;  &LR; and even though he and his family left Russia some four
years ago to live and play tennis in the sunnier climes of
Valencia, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Safin's accomplishment far outweighed any imagined negatives. On
Sunday, he became the first Russian ever to win the U.S. Open, one
of what Russian tennis buffs call the ``great helmets'' _ to
Westerners, the Grand Slam _ of tennis prizes. Better still, he did
it by demolishing the reigning American champion of world tennis,
Pete Sampras, in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to say that Russians bear the average American
any great ill will. On the other hand, it would be just as wrong to
say that Russians have not been itching for the opportunity to show
that they are as good as the so-called sole remaining superpower,
particularly after a devastating August of submarine sinkings,
flaming television towers and stage whispers that the Russian bear
no longer can manage his own affairs, much less the world's.
</P>
<P>
   And so President Vladimir Putin hailed ``a bright new star'' in
the tennis firmament, and added: ``We are proud that today's victor
is a Russian.'' Reporters trailed Safin to a New York nightclub to
chronicle his early-morning victory celebration. And Monday
evening, the young tennis star's New York triumph _ and his
$800,000 first prize _ led all three network newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of all Russians, we will be your fans,'' cooed an
anchorwoman on ORT, Russian Public Television, at the end of a
telephone interview on the 8 p.m. news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to have such young men being so optimistic,''
chimed her male co-anchor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first Russian who is the U.S. champion,'' cheered a
reporter for a competing network, NTV _ and then deadpanned,
``nobody heard anything from Marat that he wanted to change
citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his parents moved him to Spain in 1996, where he
established a base for his tennis career, there seems little doubt
in Safin's mind today of where his roots lie. He is no stranger to
Moscow, his hometown, where he has occasionally been spotted at
some of the city's tonier nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter for Moscow's Izvestiya newspaper tracked him
down before sunrise on Monday in a New York disco shortly _
drinking celebratory beer, not vodka _ the new Open champion
credited much of his victory to the counsel of Aleksandr Volkov,
the Russian tennis star who had earlier made it to the Open
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   And he made it clear that his next stop, before flying to Sydney
and a spot on the Russian tennis team in the the summer Olympics,
would be Tashkent, Uzbekistan, a former Soviet state where he had
committed to friends to play in a decidedly lower-rung tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The nation seemed to return the embrace. From the top down,
Russia _ and its Soviet predecessor _ have long pigeonholed people
by religion and ethnicity beyond what most westerners would
consider acceptable. Tatars and Caucasians, usually Muslim, usually
darker-skinned people, have borne the brunt of discrimination, and
Safin's name marks him as being of Tatar descent.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's news accounts did not identify the nation's new
tennis sensation as a ``Rusian,'' the term applied to most ethnic
Russians, but instead as a ``Russki'' _ that is, the moniker
usually reserved for Russia's majority Slavic population.
</P>
<P>
   The government labor minister Aleksandr Pochinok observed that
all Russia indeed has a powerful reason to celebrate Safin's
victory. Not only has a major new force in tennis surfaced in
Russia, he told the news radio station Echo Moskvy _ ``a major new
taxpayer'' has arrived, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
