<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SCI-AIDS-POLIO-NYT &LR;      09-11 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-POLIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCONCLUSIVE TESTS OF VACCINE LEAVE ORIGINS OF AIDS A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tests have failed to support a theory that the worldwide AIDS
epidemic was touched off because an experimental oral polio vaccine
used in Africa more than 40 years ago was made from chimpanzee
tissue, scientists reported in London Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tests do not conclusively disprove the possibility, however,
because other vaccines for which samples were not kept could still
have been made from chimpanzee cells. The tests leave unsolved the
mystery of the origins of AIDS, one of the worst epidemics in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in his book, ``The River,'' a British journalist,
Edward Hooper, advanced the provocative theory that such a vaccine
might have been made with chimpanzee tissue contaminated with an
ancestor of the virus that was to cause AIDS. The theory is based
in part on the general scientific belief that HIV-1 derives from a
simian virus in chimpanzees. HIV-1 is the virus that has caused the
overwhelming majority of the more than 50 million cases of AIDS and
HIV infection in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper suggested that the contamination might have come from an
experimental oral polio vaccine prepared at the Wistar institute, a
research center in Philadelphia. Scientific papers published at the
time did not say what primate tissues were used to make the
vaccine, Hooper said. The institute has denied that its scientists
used chimpanzee cells to prepare the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   After the vaccine theory was first raised in 1992 in an article
in ``Rolling Stone,'' the Wistar Institute appointed an independent
committee led by Dr. Claudio Basilico, chairman of the microbiology
department at New York University, to look into the matter. The
committee recommended testing the remaining stores of the vaccine.
But Wistar did not carry out the tests at the time, it has said,
because of a lack of scientific interest. Though Hooper's thesis
was not widely accepted, it led to calls for performing the tests.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Wistar provided the tiny amounts of remaining polio
vaccine to Dr. Vincent Racaniello at the Columbia University
College of Physicians and Surgeons in New York. He divided and
coded the samples before delivering them to the researchers at
three independent laboratories who had agreed to perform the tests:
Dr. Shirley Kwok at Roche Molecular Systems in Pleasanton, Calif.;
Dr. Svante Paabo at the Max Planck Institute in Leipzig, Germany;
and Dr. Simon Wain-Hobson at the Pasteur Institute in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Kwok tested the samples for the presence of HIV and SIV, its
simian cousin. Paabo tested for the presence and species origin of
two types of DNA in the samples. One comes from the nucleus. The
other comes from from mitochondria, which generate energy in the
cell and are quite species specific. Wain-Hobson performed both
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The three laboratories also tested samples sent from the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention. The federal agency in Atlanta
prepared samples that included old polio vaccine that it had kept
stored and other material that were used as controls for scientific
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The tests identified DNA from only one species of primate _ the
Asian macaque monkey, not the chimpanzee _ in the Wistar vaccine
samples, Basilico told the meeting in London at the Royal Society
on the origins of HIV and the AIDS Epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the results from these tests to support
the theory that HIV entered the human population during the late
1950s polio virus clinical trials in Africa,'' Basilico said.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper could not be reached for comment Monday. In interview
last week, Hooper said he expected that the tests would not find
evidence of chimpanzee tissue because he believes the critical
samples are no longer available for testing.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling case for the contaminated vaccine theory
would have been finding evidence of chimpanzee cells in the stored
vaccine. But even if the scientists had found evidence of a
chimpanzee virus in the samples tested, it would not have proved
that the virus started the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   An unanswered question is how HIV-1 jumped from primates to
humans. The earliest documented HIV-1 infection is from 1959 in a
man in Kinshasa in what was then the Belgian Congo.
</P>
<P>
   A widely held theory is that simian viruses passed from primates
to humans in blood-to-blood contact, like a bite or cut during the
slaughter of chimpanzees. But humans have killed chimpanzees for
centuries. Thus, an unanswered question is why widespread
transmission apparently did not begin until the late 1950s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
