<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COINS-HNS &LR;      09-11 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COINS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW FACES ON COINS? HOW ABOUT KING, REAGAN AND TRUMAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER A. DLOUHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress considers whether to order new designs
for U.S. coins, a poll of 1,940 collectors, released Monday, showed
that they favor adding Martin Luther King Jr., Ronald Reagan and
Harry Truman to the face of America's pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   A few of those polled would dispense altogether with the
presidents _ Abraham Lincoln, Thomas Jefferson, Franklin Roosevelt,
George Washington and John F. Kennedy _ who are now depicted on
most U.S. coinage.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the civil rights leader and the two presidents who led
the list, the top 10 figures named by collectors in the survey
included, in order, astronaut and former Sen. John Glenn, Theodore
Roosevelt, the Rev. Billy Graham, astronaut Neil Armstrong, Albert
Einstein, John Wayne and Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Marsh, marketing director of the Littleton (N.H.) Coin
Company, which commissioned the poll, said one collector wrote that
the U.S. Mint ``should just lighten up and put a hot dog or a
turkey on a coin.'' Among other offbeat suggestions: former
Cincinnati mayor turned talk-show host Jerry Springer and the
animated cartoon character Elmer Fudd.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was No. 14 on the list, and former President
George Bush ranked No. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results were released two days before the Senate
Banking Committee is scheduled to hold a symposium to discuss new
coin designs.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said the goal of
Wednesday meeting is to encourage designs ``worthy of a great
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the nation's last major effort to redesign coins,
Gramm said, ``We may not be able to match the golden era of coin
design under Theordore Roosevelt, but we should try.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bobbitt, spokesman for the American Numismatic
Association, said current coins' static portraits _ which
collectors sometimes call ``dead heads'' _ don't do justice to the
figures depicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbitt cited Lincoln, whose likeness has graced U.S. pennies
since 1909. ``Nothing against Abraham Lincoln, but I'm sure there
are some (other) portraits we could use. And the same with
Jefferson and Kennedy and Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   New images on coins could pique the interest of collectors,
already eagerly gathering quarters released through the U.S. Mint's
50 State Quarters Program, Bobbitt added. Under the program,
quarters honoring the states are being released about every 10
weeks. The program started last year and will continue through
2008.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Mint Director Jay Johnson said that ``more than 110 million
people nationwide have started to collect the new quarters, and we
see that number rise each time a new (one) is released.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the enthusiasm is coming from people new to collecting.
``It certainly has helped the hobby overall,'' Marsh said. The
images on the new quarters are ``something people can relate to,''
he explained. ``They're unique designs specific to each state and
the fact that they're on quarters makes them inexpensive to
collect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobbitt said the recent rise in collecting has also been
stimulated by the new golden dollar coin featuring Sacagaewa, the
Indian woman who led explorers Meriwether Lewis and William Clark
on their 1804-1806 expedition to the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Littleton coin dealership is one of the world's
largest, claiming to handle more than 200,000 orders a month. It
sponsored a similar poll five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Dlouhy can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address jdlouhy(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
