<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: SANCTIONS DECISION DUE
 &UR;  &LR; A decision on whether European Union partners will lift diplomatic
sanctions against Austria is expected soon, according to France's
European affairs minister, Pierre Moscovici. A European Commission
panel said last week that continuing the sanctions would be
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL COMEBACK
 &UR;  &LR; After a 10-month absence, former Chancellor Helmut Kohl returned
to a regular strategy session of his Christian Democratic Party's
parliamentary group. Kohl, who retained his seat in Parliament
after being ousted as chancellor in 1998, skipped all meetings
after admitting last year that he had accepted illegal campaign
donations. At the session in the Reichstag building, two colleagues
began clapping when he appeared, but quickly stopped when no one
joined in.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: LAND MINE CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   The global campaign to ban land mines is urging governments to
take steps to pressure or isolate countries that have yet to sign
the 1997 treaty banning the devices. Campaigners have been urging
NATO members to refuse to take part in military actions involving
use of land mines, and so far France and the Netherlands have
indicated a willingness to do so. Delegates from 138 countries that
have signed the pact are meeting in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: IMF PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of students protesting the policies of the
International Monetary Fund were detained by the police in Istanbul
and the southern city of Adana. At the urging of the IMF, Turkey
has been taking tough measures to cut inflation, and the
possibility of harsher steps arose over the weekend. About 50
protesters were stopped as they approached the American Consulate
in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: BID TO BAR LESBIANS
</P>
<P>
   A mayor on Lesbos has asked a district court to bar entry to 100
British lesbians, saying their tour operator falsely advertised his
town as ``a paradise of gay love.'' Mayor Polydoras Abatzis said
the operator had damaged the reputation of Eressos, the legendary
birthplace of Sappho. A ruling is expected Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: HEALTH SPENDING
</P>
<P>
   With elections expected by next spring, Prime Minister Jean
Chretien offered to increase federal health spending transfers to
provinces by 25 percent, or $15 billion, over the next five years.
After heavy cuts in the late 1990s, Canadians now tell pollsters
health care is their No. 1 concern. With a large surplus this year,
Chretien would have a hard time winning an election without
restoring funding to the national health system.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: RIGHTIST GAINS SEEN
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Canada's two right-wing parties faced voters in
special elections expected to strengthen the voice of conservatives
when Parliament reconvenes on Sept. 18. Stockwell Day, leader of
the Canadian Alliance, is expected to win easily in British
Columbia. Joe Clark, the Tories' leader, is also expected to win in
Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   BARBADOS: STEMMING AIDS
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the highest incidence of AIDS and HIV infection
outside sub-Saharan Africa, members of the Caribbean Community are
meeting in Barbados for two days to try to develop a regional
response to the disease. While Haiti and the Dominican Republic
account for 85 percent of the HIV and AIDS cases in the Caribbean,
the virus is spreading in other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
