<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS HE'LL COME DOWN HARD ON HOLLYWOOD VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore, distancing himself from the entertainment
executives who have donated very generously to his campaign, Monday
threatened that as president, he would find ways to punish
Hollywood for marketing violent material to children if it ``does
not clean up its act'' in six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to raise children today without the
entertainment industry making it more difficult,'' the vice
president said as he campaigned in Belleville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was reacting to a blistering Federal Trade Commission
report on the entertainment industry's deliberate advertising of
R-rated material to young teens, was mocked by the Bush campaign as
``reaching new levels of hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, Al Gore is telling Hollywood to clean up its act
after aggressively cleaning out their wallets for the past year,''
said Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for Texas Governor George W. Bush.
``Al Gore waving around a report that he denounced at a Hollywood
fund-raiser just a year ago makes him a deserving candidate for an
Oscar award in hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not make an issue of the new FTC report as he
campaigned in Florida Monday. A spokeswoman said he supported the
agency's inquiry, which was ordered more than a year ago by
President Clinton in the wake of a White House summit on media
violence and the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and Conyers,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers said it was smart for Gore, who is working
hard to woo women voters and determined to remove any taint of the
Clinton administration scandals, to seize the opportunity to
champion a family-values issue. Gore's running mate, Joseph
Lieberman, has been a stern Senate critic of the entertainment
industry, and Gore's wife, Tipper, led a fight in the mid-1980s to
get record companies to agree to put parental warnings on albums
and later CDs with dirty lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore and Joe Lieberman are playing the moral card, and it
makes sense strategically because the Gore ticket is most
vulnerable on moral issues,'' said Robert Knight, senior director
cultural studies at the conservative Family Research Council.
``Given the Democrats' ties to Hollywood, one would think this
would be perilous ground for them to occupy. But Gore has made an
end run, largely because the Republican ticket has not been
aggressive in addressing issues like entertainment violence.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some disagreement about how aggressive Vice President
Gore was on the media violence issue before it started popping up
in opinion polls as a concern, particularly of women.
Representative Edward Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat who pushed
Congress to enact legislation requiring program-blocking V-chips in
televisions, says President Clinton ``subcontracted''
telecommunications issues to Gore, and he remained prominent
political player.
</P>
<P>
   ``On every issue that dealt with children's television, with
media violence, with the ratings systems, it all came out of the
vice president's office,'' Markey said. ``Joe Lieberman helps Al
Gore get the credit on these media issues that he should have
gotten all along.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Los Angeles Times reported last year that shortly after
the president called for the FTC probe, Gore attended a Hollywood
fund raiser and privately disclosed that it had not been his idea,
nor had Clinton sought his input before initiating it. During the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles in August, neither
Gore nor Lieberman attacked gratuitous sex and violence in the
media, though Lieberman has for a number of years bestowed the
``Silver Sewer'' award on Hollywood's worst ``cultural polluters.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wyatt, president of the Parents Music Resource Center,
which Mrs. Gore founded in 1984, said she was asked by the Gores to
close the organization in 1988, when then-Senator Gore first ran
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gores absolutely backed away and said, `Our mission is
completed,' '' Wyatt said. ``I want to give him his due, but
Clinton and Gore could have done much more over the last eight
years to use the bully pulpit on this issue, and they have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believed it was because the Clintons, in particular, had
become too comfortable with Hollywood entertainment executives and
entertainers. Since 1990 the television, film, and music
industries, including their corporate leaders, have contributed
$83.9 million to political races. Democrats received 65 percent of
the money, while Republicans got 35 percent, according to the
Center for Responsive Politics, a campaign-finance watchdog group.
So far in this election cycle, Gore has received $929,000 and Bush
has received $728,000, the center reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he is biting the hand that feeds him, but to
some extent Gore is distancing himself from Hollywood the way Bush
and Cheney need to distance themselves from the oil industry,''
said Larry Makinson, who directs the center. ``I think Gore
perceives that in the mind of the general public, there is too
close a connection between Democrats and Hollywood, and he needs to
break that connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of an entertainment-industry trade group, who did not
want to be identified, went further, suggesting that Gore and
Lieberman have adopted the political strategy that ``there is hay
to be made in villifying our industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``By speaking out against this big constituency, by standing up
to the people who fund their campaign, Gore and Lieberman are
blunting the effort to be painted as captives of Hollywood and
special interests and affirming, `We have integrity.' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Lieberman will get another opportunity to do that
when he testifies at a hearing on media violence before the Senate
Commerce Committee, which is chaired by Senator John McCain. Lynne
Cheney, wife of Bush running mate Dick Cheney, will also testify, a
committee spokeswoman confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   David Walsh, president of the National Institute on Media and
the Family, a nonprofit group in Minneapolis, said he is happy to
see the bipartisan concern over the issue, even if the flurry of
activity has strong political-season overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women and mothers really relate to this issue, they `get it'
better than men,'' Walsh said. ``Partly it's because they are more
attuned to the things that are influencing their kids. Partly it's
because men tend to have a greater appetite themselves for
action-oriented media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most everyone, though, wants a more civil, decent, and
respectful society,'' Walsh said. ``And both men and women perceive
that the media contributes to the culture of disrespect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
