<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MOB-WIRETAP-BOS &LR;      09-11 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-WIRETAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS JUDGE BACKS WIRETAP USE IN MOBSERS' PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a stunning reversal that restores key evidence in
the government's racketeering case against gangsters James
``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen Flemmi, a federal appeals court ruled
Monday that information the pair provided while working as FBI
informants may be used against them at trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a 31-page decision, the US Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit ruled that US District Judge Mark L. Wolf ``erred'' last
year when he tossed out evidence gathered from the FBI bugging of
four Mafia hangouts during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf had concluded that FBI agents promised Bulger and Flemmi
that information gleaned from the bugs wouldn't be used against
them because the gangsters had helped them get the court order they
needed to install the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court overturned Wolf, ruling that even if
agents had promised Bulger and Flemmi immunity for some of their
crimes, the agents didn't have the authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, the alleged promise of use immunity, even if made, was
unauthorized (and therefore, unenforceable), and the district court
erred in suppressing the evidence in question,'' wrote Appeals
Court Judge Bruce Selya.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is a major blow to Flemmi, 66, who revealed that he
was an FBI informant two years after the January 1995 federal
racketeering indictment charging him, Bulger and members of the
Mafia with racketeering. He argued that the charges should be
dismissed because he was promised immunity from prosecution in
exchange for information he provided the FBI on his Mafia rivals.
Bulger, 71, another longtime FBI informant, remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi claimed that he and Bulger had been promised immunity for
any crime short of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Kenneth Fishman, who represents Flemmi, said he's
reviewing the decision and has yet to decide whether to appeal the
decision to the US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of evidence came out that supports his ultimate
defense, that he was given a green light to commit a number of the
offenses he's been charged with in order to gather information for
the FBI,'' Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern said the appeals court ``firmly
rejected Flemmi's bogus claim of immunity'' and made it clear FBI
agents don't have the power to confer immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other result would turn the criminal justice system on its
head, leaving to individual agents the power to protect informants
even where the informants commit serious crimes and have a corrupt
relationship with their handlers,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will allow prosecutors to introduce important
evidence and push the case toward resolution, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   During 10 months of hearings throughout 1998 which exposed the
cozy relationship among Bulger, Flemmi and their FBI handlers, it
was revealed that one former FBI supervisor had pocketed $7,000 in
payoffs from the pair.
</P>
<P>
   A number of agents were accused of tipping off Bulger and Flemmi
to investigations and the identity of other informants.
</P>
<P>
   In a 661-page ruling last September, Wolf rejected Flemmi's
claim that he had been promised immunity from prosecution, but he
found that agents had assured Flemmi and Bulger that information
gleaned from four bugging operations wouldn't be used against them
because Bulger and Flemmi had helped gather evidence that was used
to win court authorization for the buggings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wolf barred prosecutors from presenting evidence at
Flemmi's trial from the 1981 bugging of the North End headquarters
of Patriarca family underboss Gennaro ``Jerry'' Angiulo; the
1986-1987 bugging of Vanessa's Italian Food Shop in the Prudential
Center by the FBI and State Police; and the infamous Oct. 29, 1989
Mafia induction ceremony at a Medford home, where four aspiring
mobsters pricked their trigger fingers and burned Holy cards in a
pledge of loyalty to the New England mob.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf concluded that Flemmi and Bulger were promised immunity by
former FBI Agent John Connolly Jr. and former FBI supervisor John
Morris. Connolly was indicted last December on racketeering charges
for allegedly protecting Bulger and Flemmi. Morris, who has been
granted immunity from prosecutors, has admitted taking $7,000 in
payoffs from the pair.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court concluded that under federal law, only
prosecutors have the authority to grant immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rule were otherwise, a minor government functionary
hidden in the recesses of an obscure department would have the
power to prevent the prosecution of a most heinous criminal simply
by promised immunity in return for the performance of some act
which might benefit his department,'' Selya wrote. ``Such a result
could not be countenanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Monday's ruling, there is still no trial date in sight
for Flemmi. Federal prosecutors are currently appealing another
ruling by Wolf that bars them from using key testimony linking
Flemmi to the 1967 slayings of Richard Grasso and three Boston
brothers, William, Walter and Edward Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf ruled in July that prosecutors abused the grand jury
process when they added the four murder charges to an existing
indictment against Flemmi. Arguments on that issue have yet to be
heard by the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Flemmi is awaiting trial in two other cases: a 1997
federal indictment on money laundering charges, and a racketeering
indictment returned last year charging him along with Bulger and
Connolly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
