<SLUG> BC-GENZYME-GELTEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENZYME TO PAY $1 BILLION FOR GELTEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the largest biotechnology deals this year, Genzyme
Corp. said Monday it has agreed to buy GelTex Pharmaceuticals Inc.
for $1.016 billion in stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to catapult Renagel, a GelTex product used
by kidney dialysis patients to bind and remove high phosphate
levels, into Genzyme's biggest moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme and GelTex officials projected Renagel revenues would be
rising from $19.5 million last year to $45 million this year to
$500 million in five years and $1 billion by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme's biggest drug is Cerezyme. That drug and its
predecessor, Ceredase, has been available for nearly nine years to
treat 2,700 patients with the rare disorder known as Gaucher's
disease. Cerezyme had sales of $479 million last year, 84 percent
of the company's total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genzyme has been successful in developing a pipeline of drugs
to treat extremely rare diseases and this product (Renagel) brings
us a to a different level, where the patient population undergoing
kidney dialysis is 1 million people worldwide today, growing to 1.7
million in the next decade,'' said Henri Termeer, chairman and
chief executive of Genzyme, which has its headquarters in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, shareholders of GelTex will receive 0.7272
shares of Genzyme General unit stock, or $47.50 in cash, for each
GelTex share with the cash portion of the deal fixed at $500
million. The offer is a 27 percent premium to GelTex's Friday
closing price of $37.38.
</P>
<P>
   GelTex is based in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street analysts reacted positively to the deal, citing
the long-term prospets for GelTex shareholders under Genzyme.
</P>
<P>
   ``GelTex shareholders are getting a good deal,'' said Felicia L.
Reed, vice president of equity research at Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill
in Boston. ``GelTex does not have the commercial capacity that
Genzyme has and Genzyme will be able to take advantage of new
information about kidney dialysis plus expand its drug pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   In heavy trading on the Nasdaq exchange, GelTex shares Monday
rose $5.88 to $43.25 while Genzyme General stock slipped $7.63 to
$57.69.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of industry consolidation where most biotech companies
are scrambling to find new drugs that can provide immediate
revenues and profits, Genzyme did not have to look very far.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years ago, GelTex and Genzyme signed an
agreement to jointly market Renagel and share equally in the
profits. GelTex developed the drug, which costs about $1,200 a year
per patient, while Genzyme brought its marketing clout to the
agreement. Renagel gained US Food and Drug Administration approval
in November 1998 and has been approved for Medicare reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   But after a New England Journal of Medicine study in May,
Genzyme and GelTex saw an opportunity to transform Renagel into a
blockbuster drug. The study revealed how young patients on kidney
dialysis who were taking calcium-based drugs to lower their
phosphate levels suffered unusually high levels of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   The article said these patients had major signs of coronary
artery calcification that could lead to death and urged
nephrologists _ kidney specialists _ to rethink their use of
calcium-based drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike existing drugs, known as phosphate binders, Renagel does
not contain calcium. That enables kidney dialysis patients to
achieve better control of their levels of phosphorus and calcium in
the blood.
</P>
<P>
   The GelTex drug, which costs three to six times more than
calcium-based medications, works by absorbing water in the
digestive tract forming hydrogels that bind and remove phosphorus.
By contrast, healthy patients have kidneys that remove excess
phosphate into the urine.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both companies said the New England Journal study
along with some other reports indicated to them that Renagel had a
bigger future than originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Journal article made us think we really have something
important here, and it started to give us a lot of momentum,'' said
Mark Skaletsky, the GelTex chief executive, who noted prescriptions
had started to rise significantly earlier this year. ``And for us
to continue with a small sales force or work with Genzyme led us to
rethink what was best for our shareholders and employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, there will be no layoffs among the 110
GelTex employees who will continue to work in Waltham, although the
GelTex name will disappear, said Termeer. Skaletsky will stay with
Genzyme during a transition phase, but indicated he would leave at
some point to create or join a biotech startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company begins is the period I find most exciting,''
Skaletsky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
