<HEADER>
A9323 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH0912-COX     09-11 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush campaigns Florida where polls say Gore has taken lead
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ In a day as politically symbolic as they get,
GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush on Monday campaigned in a
battleground state that wasn't supposed to be much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't blame it on my brother,'' Bush joked, Florida Gov. Jeb
Bush at his side, as he arrived here. ``We're in good shape here in
Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, back when Bush looked like he was on the easy street
to Pennsylvania Avenue, Florida's 25 electoral votes were included
as a solid part of the 270 he needed for victory. But, like the
rest of the nation, Florida is now a toss-up as Vice President Al
Gore enjoys the biggest surge of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, whose chances of winning electoral vote-rich
California and New York are slipping, Florida has become a must-win
battle. No Republican since Calvin Coolidge in 1924 has taken the
White House without winning Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a battleground state, but we feel we can win it and will
win it,'' Bush aide Karen Hughes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign is not taking Florida as a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb lost one time and then won next time,'' Hughes said.
``Recent elections have been very much swing elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's uptick here has been issue-driven as the Democratic
nominee has been scoring points by hammering on Social Security,
prescription drugs and health insurance. Meanwhile, Bush's $1.3
trillion tax cut is not playing well among the state's elderly
voters who are often misperceived as all wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple answer is the issues are all going Democratic right
now,'' said Jim Kane, editor of the nonpartisan Florida Voter poll.
``You've got Medicare, prescription drugs, Social Security. A third
of our electorate, among likely voters, is over 60 years of age.
Those issues, I think, are benefitting Al Gore in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush countered Monday by talking about those issues in a speech
and question-and-answer session with a friendly crowd at the On Top
of the World retirement community on Florida's west coast. He
sought to inoculate himself against Democratic attacks on his
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb got a pretty good lesson of old-style politics in 1994,''
he said, referring to his brother's narrow loss to Democrat Lawton
Chiles. ``I don't know if you remember the scare tactics that go on
in states like this. The easiest thing to do is not have a platform
and try to scare somebody. They'll be saying, `If George W. becomes
president he is going to take away your Social Security benefits.'
Don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush engaged in a little scare talk of his own, branding Gore's
health-care plan as a ``government HMO.'' That's the message he'll
have to keep sounding to win over key elderly voters, said state
GOP Chairman Al Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore promised health care and prescription drug coverage in
'92,'' Cardenas said. ``He promised them in '96 and now he's
promising them in the year 2000. It's a credibility issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the town-hall meeting marked the start of a busy week
in which he also will take his new ``Real Plans for Real People''
theme to Missouri, Washington, California and New Mexico. It's a
key week in key states as the candidates move toward the Summer
Olympics that begin Friday and will compete for attention through
the Oct. 2 closing ceremonies. Both sides say the Olympics will
impact the race, but they are unsure how or how much.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's day-and-a-half in Florida included a Monday night event
in Palm Beach that raised more than $500,000 for Florida
Republicans, and a campaign stop today in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   By all measures, Florida's importance has been torqued up by
recent polls showing Gore leading, for the first time, in states
with more electoral votes than the states in which Bush leads.
</P>
<P>
   As a suddenly swing state, Florida reflects the way the race has
shifted in recent weeks. For months, Bush campaign officials were
buoyed by a belief that the battle was being fought on Gore's turf.
</P>
<P>
   At campaign headquarters in Austin, the Bush team has believed
he could win California, a recent Democratic stronghold; a healthy
chunk of the Midwest, which (save for Indiana) went Democratic in
1992 and 1996; and even Tennessee, Gore's home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing is we are fighting on his territory rather than
him fighting for ours,'' Karl Rove, Bush's top strategist, said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Bush battled for part of his family's political
empire. His father carried Florida by a wide margin in 1988 and a
two-point edge in 1992. In 1998, after the narrow 1994 loss to
Chiles, Jeb Bush won the gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, President Bill Clinton easily defeated GOP challenger
Bob Dole here.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Democratic National Committee officials were
conceding Florida to Bush, citing the family ties and noting that
the state trailed only Texas in the number of Democratic
officeholders jumping to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore never conceded Florida. He chose Tallahassee for his
victory party in March on the night he knocked Democratic foe Bill
Bradley from the chase for the nomination. Last month, Gore picked
Florida as the delegation to put him over the top for the
nomination at the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pollster Whit Ayers, a Republican not working in the
presidential race, said Florida will remain Bush country because
``Jeb Bush is wildly popular and a very effective politician who is
more than a little committed to a George W. victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayers believes Bush is helped by the fact that GOP governors
back him in swing states like Florida, Michigan, Illinois,
Wisconsin, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, the only real political organization worthy
of the name in most states is owned by incumbent governors,'' said
Ayers. ``They can't make a candidate who's not competitive
competitive. But they can make a difference of a point, maybe a
point in a half. So that if a presidential candidate is competitive
in those states, governors might make just enough difference to
pull out a close one.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb Bush, though still highly popular in Florida, has hit
some bumps. His school voucher plan, passed last year, is in a
legal limbo after a challenge from the state's National Education
Association affiliate. ``One Florida,'' his plan to end racial
preferences in state college admissions, raised eyebrows even among
some supporters, said Richard Scher, professor of political science
at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``While in general that was popular, the way he handled it was
very heavy handed and a lot of people resented that,'' Scher said.
``He has a reputation of ready, shoot, aim.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
