<HEADER>
A9324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENC     09-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY REPORT ON TARGETING CHILDREN WITH VIOLENT
GAMES, MOVIES, MUSIC DRAWS POLITICAL SNIPING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A government report that found the entertainment
industry targeted children with violent games, movies and music
created political sniping Monday while fueling a debate over
whether sounds and images provoke violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission released a 104-page report that
detailed the extent to which makers of popular entertainment evaded
restrictions on violent content to pitch their products to children
as young as 12.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found the entertainment companies ``routinely target
children under 17 in their marketing of products their own ratings
systems deem inappropriate ... due to violent content,'' said FTC
Chairman Robert Pitofsky.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, game and music industries' marketing and advertising
campaigns, ``showed strategies to promote and advertise their
products in the media outlets most likely to reach children under
17,'' the report found.
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of R-rated movies and virtually all of the
popular music with violent content pushed their products with
``pervasive and aggressive'' advertisements, Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC study uncovered promotional material from the publicity
departments of entertainment firms that showed the companies sought
the ``elusive teen target audience'' with R-rated movies.
Similarly, video game companies devised ad campaigns for `mature'
rated products that said the key audience would be ``males,
12-17.''
</P>
<P>
   Games, movies and music that were restricted because of violent
content were hawked on children's web sites and promoted in ``teen
hangouts such as game rooms, pizza parlors and sports apparel
stores,'' the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC called for stricter compliance by the industry with
voluntary restrictions on violent material. Movie theaters should
check identification or require parental approval before selling
tickets to R rated movies. Retail stores should also check before
selling compact discs labeled ``explicit'' or games rated R or M to
those younger than 17, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   And the industry should impose ``meaningful sanctions'' on
companies attempting to market violent products to children, said
the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were endorsed by President Clinton, who ordered the
study in June 1999 in response to the Columbine high school
killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say these rating systems mean something. They can't turn
around and advertise to people that shouldn't see this stuff,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore pounced on the issue
Monday, saying he would set a six month deadline on the industry to
change its marketing approach. If that didn't happen, he would
propose tougher regulatory powers for the FTC to control the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough to raise children today without the
entertainment industry making it more difficult,'' Gore said in a
statement released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican rival George W. Bush blasted Gore for hypocrisy on
the issue, pointing out that Gore had lobbied Hollywood hard for
cash over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Clearwater, Fla., on Monday, Bush said Gore was
``short on credibility on the issue'' because he and the Democratic
Party continued to accept millions of dollars in contributions from
entertainment figures.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will ``work with the CEOs of Hollywood, those who
produce the products that pollute our children's minds.'' But he
stopped short of vowing a governmental crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Bush campaign quoted news accounts which
that charged that Gore had met with entertainment executives last
year to assure them of his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to help families counter Hollywood's influence on
our children is to elect Gov. Bush, who will restore integrity to
the White House and usher in a new era of responsibility,'' said
Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics in Washington said Monday
that Gore, the Democratic National Committee and other Democratic
organizations had taken $13.6 million from the music, movie and
video game industries during this election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore was slated to appear at a series of fund-raisers this
week headlined by entertainers and hosted by Hollywood movie, music
and publishing executives at which he is expected to raise another
$8 million for his campaign and the DNC, according to the CRP.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the Republican National Committee had taken nearly $2.5
million from entertainment industry companies, the CRP said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., will hold hearings on ``marketing
violence to children'' on Wednesday. Among the witnesses will be
the heads of movie, video games and recording companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, who is scheduled to testify at that hearing, declined to
comment on the FTC report Monday. In the past, Valenti has defended
the industry against charges that violent entertainment bred
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative groups are hoping that the FTC report will
spur major changes in the way movies, video games and recordings
come to the attention of pre-teens and teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry was forced to discontinue its use of `Joe
Camel' because it obviously targeted kids,'' said Robert Knight of
the Family Research Council. ``Well, Hollywood has a `Joe Camel'
problem of its own _ aggressive marketing of adult material to
underage children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts said there is no valid evidence that watching
or listening to violent material leads to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be seen as a diversion from the U.S. facing the
real causes of violence in this country,'' said Mike Males, a
researcher from the University of California at Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Males said in other cultures like Japan, Western Europe and
Canada, young people are exposed to even more violent imagery than
American youth are, without resulting in high rates of violence. He
said economic circumstances, not violent entertainment, was the
root cause of most violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are large population pockets in this country where the
kids are exposed to more movies, violent music and games than
anywhere else which haven't had a youthful murder in decades,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Santa Cruz area, an upscale part of California with about
250,000 people, there had been only three violent crimes among
teen-agers in the past 10 years, Males said. He compared that to
much higher rates of violence elsewhere in California with lower
household incomes. He added that the trend crosses racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report did not name specific movie, record or video game
companies whose products it said were improperly advertised to
young people.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said the problem was found almost universally.
</P>
<P>
   Of 44 movies rated R for violence studied by the FTC, 35 were
targeted for children younger than 17, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The commission looked at 55 music recordings with labels warning
of explicit content, and found that all of them were marketed at
youths younger than 17. And 70 percent of the 118 video games with
a `mature' rating for violence were aimed at an underaged audience,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also staked out movie theaters, finding that just under
half admitted children as young as 13 to R-rated movies without an
accompanying adult. ``The surveys also revealed that unaccompanied
children ages 13 to 16 were able to buy both explicit recordings
and mature-rated electronic games 85 percent of the time,'' the FTC
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
