<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-KIDS-SELL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC SAYS ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY MARKETS VIOLENCE TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Restructures lead, adds comments from industry and commission
officials; no pickup. Now coded for Page One.) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deploring what it called the ``pervasive and
aggressive marketing'' of violent entertainment to children, the
Federal Trade Commission said Monday that the vast majority of the
best-selling restricted movies, music and video games were
deliberately marketed for children as young as 12.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, reporting on a year-long study released an
internal memorandum apparently from a movie studio about an R-rated
film saying that its promotional ``goal was to find the elusive
teen target audience and make sure everyone between the ages of
12-18 was exposed to the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Another memorandum described how, in Kansas City, fliers and
posters about an R-rated movie would be distributed to
organizations like the Campfire Boys and Girls.
</P>
<P>
   A memorandum about an M-rated video game characterized the
``primary'' audience as ``males 12-17.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings established by trade associations are voluntary and
do not carry the force of law. R-rated films are supposed to
require an adult to accompany children under 17. M-rated video
games are not to be sold to children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   In another case described by the commission, an advertising
summary for a recording with a label identifying violent content
identified the ``target audience'' as listeners 12 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the commission was not allowed to identify the companies
that were the source of the memorandums describing marketing aimed
at children. Mary Engle, a lawyer at the agency, said the documents
had been submitted to the commission under procedures that prohibit
disclosure of trade secrets or other confidential financial or
commercial information.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission examined a sampling of movies, recordings and
electronic games selected because they were best-selling products
or those most likely to appeal to young people and found that, in
the vast majority of the cases, advertising had been aimed at
underage children.
</P>
<P>
   All 55 music recordings with explicit content labels were
marketed to children under 17. So were 35 of the 44 movies rated R,
or 80 percent, and 83 of the 118 video games, or 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission found that violent movies, recordings and
electronic games were heavily advertised in outlets likely to reach
children under 17 _ television programs like ``South Park'' and
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and magazines like Teen, Jump and YM.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment industry officials have repeatedly denied that
their companies make a policy of directing advertisements toward
children. They say it is impossible in today's world of
communications to keep promotions of products for young adults away
from the eyes and ears of children.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several days, Democratic politicians have used the
commission's report to burnish their credentials as crusaders
against violence in popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the commission's findings was reported in an article
on Sunday based on interviews with officials familiar with the
report. In an interview with The New York Times on Sunday, Vice
President Al Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, took note of the study and said that, if elected, they
would offer legislation or new regulations cracking down on the
entertainment industry if the industry did not take steps to comply
with the FTC recommendations within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, President Clinton, making a rare appearance with Hillary
Rodham Clinton to support her candidacy for the Senate in New York
at the Jewish Community Center in New Rochelle, N.Y., condemned the
abuses cited in the report. The Clintons suggested they would
support some kind of government restraints if the industry did not
itself curb advertising aimed at an underage audience.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential candidate,
agreed Monday that the entertainment industry needed to rein in its
marketing practices. But he questioned Gore's credibility, saying
the vice president had not previously taken a strong stand against
violence in entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual political twist, the Senate commerce committee,
under the chairmanship of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., will hold a
hearing on Wednesday about the commission's findings and provide a
forum for Lieberman, who is scheduled as a witness. Also testifying
will be several other politicians, entertainment industry
executives and representatives of advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the Federal Trade Commission study last year
shortly after the massacre by two teen-agers at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, the commission chairman, said at a news
conference Monday that no particular companies were worse offenders
than others.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky also was careful not to blame violent entertainment for
the violence in society. ``We reviewed the literature and found
that scholars and observers generally agree that exposure to
violent materials alone does not cause a child to commit a violent
act,'' he said. ``Exposure to violent materials probably is not
even the most important factor. It is nevertheless a valid cause
for concern. Exposure does seem to correlate with aggressive
attitudes, insensitivity to violence and an exaggerated view of how
much violence occurs in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Pitofsky said, the entertainment industry would
strengthen its self-regulation. If that does not work, he said, he
would consider new legislation or enforcement under existing law.
But he quickly added, ``That's down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said he was concerned about breaching the First
Amendment guarantee of free speech. ``I don't want the Federal
Trade Commission to be the thought police,'' he said. ``I don't
want a bureaucrat like me influencing the content of these
materials, but rather, we need to influence the way these materials
are marketed.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that trade associations publish the names of their
members who direct marketing of restricted products to underage
audiences. ``a little sunlight might be a very effective sanction
in this area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
