<SLUG> BC-GA-CENSUS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Census hype no habla Espanol, panel told
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spanish speakers in Georgia _ the most undercounted
group in Georgia 10 years ago _ may have been ignored this year by
census advertising, advocates said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very upset and disappointed,'' Jacqueline
Thomas-Rosier of the Mexican-American Legal Defense and Education
Fund said. She appeared before the U.S. Census Monitoring Board,
which met in Atlanta Monday. ``There are more than eight (Hispanic)
radio stations in Georgia,'' she said after the meeting. ``When
census did media buys, they skipped us and went to Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, Georgia has seen an enormous increase in its
Spanish-speaking population. In 1990, 7.4 percent of Hispanics in
Georgia were not counted.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Georgia lost out on $180 million in federal money
because 2.3 percent of its population was not counted. If that
percentage does not improve this year, Georgia will lose about $272
million in federal funds for transportation, education and social
service programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we will have less of an undercount than we did
last time,'' said Atlanta lawyer Joe Whitley, one of four
Republicans on the eight-member monitoring board.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring board was created two years ago, with the
Republican-controlled U.S. House and U.S. Senate appointing four
members and the president naming four. The board produced several
reports detailing problems with the 2000 census and another is
expected early next month.
</P>
<P>
   One approach taken this year to get a more accurate count was to
fund a $167 million advertising campaign that included multilingual
ads, directed mainly at minorities who were less likely to fill out
the form.
</P>
<P>
   But in Georgia, Thomas-Rosier said, almost every ad in a
language other than English was an unpaid public service
announcement, airing during the wee hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jost with the census communications office in Suitland,
Md., said the agency spent money where market research showed it
would get ``the biggest punch.'' The response rate was the highest
it has been in four decades. A larger percentage of households in
the Atlanta area _ 59 percent _ returned their census forms via
mail, answered questions on the Internet or competed questionnaires
at a census ``be counted'' center than the number 10 years ago _ 55
percent. But it was short of the goal of a 60 percent return rate
for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
