<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Total Movie makes slick premiere
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought there was no room left on newsstands,
another magazine makes its debut. This month's newcomer is Total
Movie ($7.99), a slick 112-page bimonthly publication aimed at film
buffs. The cover with a scantily clad, serpent-wrapped Elizabeth
Hurley is certainly eye-catching, and the content is a cut above
the usual stuff. Articles include previews of new films; Hollywood
gossip; a look at ``Unbreakable,'' Bruce Willis' follow-up to ``The
Sixth Sense''; and a mini-magazine of DVD reviews and a DVD with
previews and extra features. ``We're a little more discerning than
your average movie mag,'' says Editor-in-Chief Gary Whitta. ``You
won't find coverage of every single new release in every genre but
you will find better, hipper and more in-depth coverage of the
movies you love.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Literary South: The new Oxford American ($5.95) doesn't
include a bonus CD like the previous Southern music issue, but it
does offer a treasury of fine writing. The action picks up in the
fifth installment of John Grisham's six-part serial novel, ``The
Painted House,'' when young Luke witnesses another murder. In
nonfiction, author William Gay ventures to an eerie cave in Adams,
Tenn., in search of the truth behind the Bell Witch legend. And
Matthew Teague reports on the three-day UFO conference in Eureka
Springs, Ark., where he found fuzzy photos of what were purported
to be flying sauces and plenty of ``Star Trek'' memorabilia, but no
little green men. Also of note: John T. Edge profiles Duncan Hines,
the man who revolutionized dining on the road, and Jan DeBlieu
takes a look at efforts to save endangered red wolves in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More than parties: The Season ($3.95) continues to expand its
coverage beyond that of charity balls and other society events in
the area. The fall issue also includes a profile of Oprah Winfrey;
an article on the single life in Atlanta; interviews with Southern
authors Stuart Woods, Paul Hemphill, Terry Kay and Kathy Hogan
Trocheck; a dining section; and a fashion layout. For the piece on
the single life, the magazine's editors interviewed a focus group
of 22 unmarried Atlantans, ages 20s to the 40s. Yes, they agreed
that a good man and a good woman are hard to find, but singles
``experts'' offered tips and a list of clubs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The big three: In a rare coincidence, none of the newsweeklies
has a copycat cover or mirror image of George W. Bush and Al Gore.
Newsweek ($3.50) offers a fascinating report on the redefining of
race in America and concludes that the old labels of black and
white no longer capture the nation's diversity. There used to be
three Census categories, the editors note; now there are 30, with
11 Hispanic subsets.... Time's ($3.50) cover story on dying is
equally compelling. In interviews with doctors and terminally ill
patients, the magazine's staff writers explore ways we can manage
pain and ``die a good death at home.'' Also interviewed is Bill
Moyers, whose documentary ``On Our Own Terms'' airs on public
broadcasting stations this week (part three is tonight; the
concluding chapter on Wednesday at 9 p.m. on GPTV). Moyers is
promoting a dialogue about death on the Web site
www.pbs.org/onourownterms.... The cover story in U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($3.50) looks at the U.S. military and whether our fighting
force is going soft.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: The New Yorker's ($3) Jeffrey Toobin chats with
Maria Hsia about the controversy surrounding the Hsi Lai Buddhist
temple and Al Gore's fund-raising activities. In the interview with
Toobin, Hsia insists Gore did nothing wrong. ``He should say...
this is no different from people visiting the black churches or any
churches or a Jewish temple''.... In a cover reminiscent of the
James Bond flick ``Goldfinger,'' Sports Illustrated ($3.50)
features a clever cover shot of gilded gymnast Ivan Ivankov and an
inside spread of a gold-covered gallery of other Olympic athletes
who will be favored in Sydney. Also included is a guide to the
Games..... Speaking of the Olympics, Maxim ($3.99) provides tips on
how to find the gems in the 441 hours of television coverage. And,
as a special bonus for its predominantly young male audience,
there's a revealing layout of eight female Olympic stars. Less
entertaining but more informative is Maxim's article on other
people's paychecks. A rodeo cowboy, for example, makes
$50,000-$60,000 in prize money; an air traffic controller earns
$64,880; and surgeons make $217,000 _ far below the average salary
of $1,408,000 for an NFL lineman.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
