 &HT;    News about the net: 09.12.00
 &HT;    By John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Napster downloads a Net record of its own
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lowdown on Warner Music's planned downloads
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chapter and verse: Chapter 11 links with Contentville
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heidi Fleiss' 15 minutes of fame goes into overtime
</P>
<P>
   NET RECORD: Being in trouble in the courts apparently hasn't
hurt Napster a bit; in fact, the song-swap site is the
fastest-growing such creature ever tracked by Media Metrix. Home
users climbed from 1.1 million unique visitors in February to 4.9
million in July, a 346 percent increase. And at work? Napster more
than doubled, from 417,000 unique users in May to nearly 887,000 in
July. Overall, Napster ranks as the 43rd most popular home
application, representing more than 6 percent of all U.S. home PC
users with a modem.
</P>
<P>
   www.napster.com
</P>
<P>
   DOWNLOAD DEALS: Now, Time Warner's getting into the act. The
Warner Music Group plans to let customers download music starting
in November through Web sites of retailers such as Wal-Mart. The
service initially will sell about 100 singles at a price yet to be
disclosed. Warner hopes to offer 1,000 digitized albums and singles
from performers such as Madonna and Bjork.
</P>
<P>
   QUITE CONTENT: Metro Atlanta-based Chapter 11 Discount Bookstore
has joined other independent booksellers as a partner with
contentville.com, an e-commerce site that brings different kinds of
content ( books, magazines, e-books, etc.) together. Booksellers at
contentville are part of a special site option, ``Visit the
Experts,'' where they share their knowledge (Chapter 11's is
nonfiction in paperbacks). Each seller's page features their photo,
their area of expertise, a description of their store and a link to
the Web site. ``At a time when independent booksellers are meeting
new challenges presented by traditional brick-and-mortar chain
stores and online superstores, contentville.com is providing us
with a unique opportunity to showcase what makes us special,'' said
Chapter 11 owner Barbara Kaufman. _ Don O'Briant.
</P>
<P>
   www.chapter11books.com
</P>
<P>
   www.contentville.com
</P>
<P>
   HEIDI CHRONICLES: That sly Heidi Fleiss. The infamous madam of
Beverly Hills thinks she has a story to sell, er, tell, despite
what the courts say. Her parole and bankruptcy court agreements
forbid it, but Fleiss thinks authorities will look the other way if
she scripts a tell-all available online. Her plan, says the New
York Post, is to self-publish and sell the title off one of her Web
sites, www.heidifleissbook.com. Audiotapes and videos also are
promised. No costs are listed but you can preregister.
</P>
