<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRAYER-DOCTORS12-COX     09-11 0226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-DOCTORS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Approaching your doctor
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you would like to pray with your doctors as a way to help the
healing process, how do you let your physicians know?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't be afraid to approach them. Ask them if they practice a
certain faith and how comfortable they are bringing those beliefs
into the examining room. Doctors say there is usually a time _
after they have discussed treatment options and explanations _ for
the patient to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Explain your faith and what aspects are important to you. Tell
them if you would like to pray and when. If you are having surgery
a week from the appointment, tell the doctor you would like to have
a short time of prayer or meditation. That way, you can find a
place in the surgery schedule before you are medicated or too sick
to follow through.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you meet resistance or a high level of discomfort, consider
taking your requests for prayers to someone else _ the nurses, a
hospital chaplain or your family. However, if you believe this is
very important and you are shaken by your doctor's lack of
enthusiasm, perhaps you should think about finding a different
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
