<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-WHITES-NYT &LR;      09-11 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-WHITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S NEW POOR: WHITE AND BEWILDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Martin van Niekerk wakes with a
start and his sleepy blue eyes wander from the fraying curtains
fluttering over the window to the sagging ceiling and the shabby
walls lined with brown cardboard. And then he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   He is not at home. He has tumbled through a hole in the floor of
his once predictable life.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughterhouse where he weighed and priced animal skins for
17 years shut down in 1998. The clothing store where he worked as a
security guard closed abruptly three weeks ago. For days, he and
his wife and three children slept in the street until they landed
in this shelter, the Kempton Christian Action Settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He and the scores of men and women living here are members of a
tiny but growing slice of South Africa's evolving society: They are
unemployed, homeless and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cell phone, I sell that,'' said van Niekerk, 38, as he
guided a visitor through Shack No. G7, his temporary one-room home.
``And the iron. Even my wife, she sells our wedding rings. But it
is not enough to pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new South Africa is a very difficult place,'' van Niekerk
admitted quietly as he sat on his borrowed bed. ``I used to feel
different. I used to feel like it was my country. You can't say
it's your country anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a white man in South Africa used to mean a steady job, a
house, a car, respectability. For the overwhelming majority of
white men, it still does.
</P>
<P>
   But for an increasing number of whites, there are startling new
realities. Between 1995 and 1999, the ratio of unemployed whites
increased from 3.4 percent to 6.8 percent, government statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
   That is minuscule, of course, compared with the unemployment
rate among the black majority _ about 35 percent _ after decades in
which an all-white government denied educational and professional
opportunities to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The poor are still overwhelmingly black and the rich and working
class are still overwhelmingly white. Still, stories like van
Niekerk's send shivers through many whites, who account for about
10 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that once refused to hire blacks now seek them out.
Whites are facing increasing competition, particularly at the lower
rungs of the work force, as the economy sheds thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And Greyling Bezuidenhout, an organizer for the Mine Workers
Union, fears the future will only bring tougher times to a country
that once reserved decent jobs for those with white skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new problem in this country, and that's white
poverty, but nobody want to talk about it,'' said Bezuidenhout,
whose union represents 65,000 Afrikaners in mining,
telecommunications and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that whites benefited from the racist employment
practices of the past. Some, he says, got by without being
productive simply because they were white. But now, he adds, people
are suffering for old government policies they did not actively
support, and no one seems to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority rights are seen as politically incorrect,'' he said,
as he shepherded a visitor through several homeless settlements for
whites last week. ``At the end of the day, we have to look after
ourselves. There's no one else to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bezuidenhout _ lanky and bearded, with bespectacled eyes that
burn with his passion for helping the poorest of his people _ is on
a mission that seems decidedly unpopular. He keeps a list of
settlements and visits them regularly, keeping track of their
problems and needs. But when he approaches big companies for
donations, executives typically listen politely and decline, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Few businesses want to invest publicly in a whites-only venture,
he said. As a result, places like the Kempton Christian Action
Settlement, which opened several years ago, quickly fall into
disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't condone the racism that has been done,'' Bezuidenhout
said. ``But a lot of these guys were never supportive of the
apartheid system. Now they pay for the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The forlorn wooden shacks here, all inhabited by parents with
children, house 120 people. When the rains come, the water stands
two inches above the floor. At night, the cold winds squeeze
through cracks in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Some whites here are prisoners of their insatiable thirst for
drink and drugs. Others simply lost their grip on their
working-class existence, falling out of modest but comfortable
lives when factories closed or breadwinners fell sick.
</P>
<P>
   Van Niekerk keeps a gold-framed certificate of his son's
scholastic achievement hanging on the flimsy walls, a reminder that
his children must continue to strive.
</P>
<P>
   And J.J. Wait holds on to his silver-plated watch, which ticks
away the time in a world he no longer recognizes or understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a house worth 250,000 rand'' _ $35,000 _ ``and the bank
took it back,'' said Wait, 42, who spent 10 years in the military
police and eight as a security guard before he injured his back and
lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then followed my furniture, then my car,'' he said. ``I
thought I'd work myself up, become a manager or something like
that. But since the new government comes in, everything has fallen
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait says he lacks the proper certification to find a new
security job, but he still blames his troubles on the end of
apartheid, as many people do here. When he applies for jobs, he
says, he is often told the slot is reserved for a black candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm not a racist,'' Wait cautioned hastily. ``My best
friends in the army were black. But this government is doing
nothing to help whites to improve their lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, many wealthy white business executives would say just
the opposite. Earlier this year, a group of prominent Afrikaner
executives issued a public declaration in support of President
Thabo Mbeki, praising his fiscally conservative policies, which
have reduced interest rates, inflation and the budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But that left the people here feeling more betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Even the predominantly white opposition party now courts black
voters, the homeless here grumble, while poor whites rummage
through bags of second-hand clothing and dine from dented cans of
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to stand outside and scream, but it won't help,''
said Meie Erasmus, 51, a resident of Shack No. D7. She said her
husband lost his job as a truck driver to a black who was willing
to work for less.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must accept how we are,'' she said, shaking her head. ``We
can't do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Niekerk spends his time filling out job applications. It is
a measure of his desperation that he is seeking manual labor, which
for most whites is still unthinkable. ``I will even do a black
man's work, just to get money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would rather start over in a new country where he could
feel like the man he once was. And when he gets depressed, he
imagines a green land with vast, open spaces and room for a
wandering people in search of a new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of Canada,'' van Niekerk said wistfully. ``Everything
on TV, I like about Canada. But getting the money to get there,
that's the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
