<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRAYER-HEALING12-COX     09-11 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-HEALING12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spiritual side of healing edges into doctor's office
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dr. Robert Cowgill was a disbeliever.
</P>
<P>
   A man of science and surgical precision, the Atlanta physician
believed in the power of a scalpel and a practiced hand _ not in
spirituality and a healing touch.
</P>
<P>
   But after attending a weekend seminar on holistic approaches to
treatment, the oncology surgeon changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of his cancer patients come to his office not to learn
merely about their medical options, but to share a moment of
meditation. ``I'm trying to be open to all possibilities; I'm
trying not to disbelieve too much,'' said Pat Waldo, a Brookhaven
resident who had a mastectomy last year to treat breast cancer.
``Dr. Cowgill helps me with this. This is his gift to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowgill, however, may be the exception to the rule. Many doctors
regard the mixture of church and science as taboo as integrating
church and state. Only 10 percent of physicians say they have
prayed with their patients or discussed spiritual issues with them,
according to a 1996 survey _ one of the scant pieces of research on
the subject. Yet almost 65 percent of people believe doctors should
join them in prayer if requested, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing body of research has suggested that prayer,
meditation and other mind-body approaches appear to be beneficial
in the healing process, although scientists are still baffled on
why. Some research, including a controversial study recently in the
Archives of Internal Medicine, has suggested that even patients who
are prayed for by a third party tend to fare better than those who
aren't the subject of prayer. Others indicate that the faithful
recover better from such procedures as open heart surgery and that,
among the elderly, blood pressure rates are lower.
</P>
<P>
   Still, approaching your physician _ if you believe the spiritual
aspect should be part of your treatment _ can be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors are trained not to focus on the metaphysical side
of healing, says Dr. David Hilton, a former family physician who
works with Emory University's dean of religious life and often
``hangs out'' at the anatomy labs to discuss any spiritual issues
medical students have as they work on cadavers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical education is focused almost exclusively on the
physical side; they are taught to stick to that,'' said Hilton, a
lifelong Methodist. ``And yet, there's definitely a need to address
more fully the other aspects of being human and being healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who do pray with their patients believe the best
approach is for patients to be honest about the importance of the
spiritual side of their own healing. They advise telling your
physicians about your own faith and gauging their comfort level
with prayer and other spiritual practices. And if you sense
resistance _ and the issue is important enough _ it might be better
to seek someone who is more in line with your own spiritual
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also don't want to offend or disappoint some patients.
And people who don't believe in God aren't going to want to hear
their physician bringing up spiritual issues. And some patients are
a lot more interested in fixing the problem _ whether it be a
blocked artery or a tumor _ than praying about it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some patients and even a few doctors feel a need to do
something beyond IVs, stitches and pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure more patients probably wished that we did (pray) with
them more than we do,'' said Dr. Kenneth McGrath, a cardiologist
and director of non-invasive cardiology at Saint Joseph's Hospital.
``But I think it's something we're just not accustomed to.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the doctor is motivated, a deeper relationship can be
forged between healers and those in their care. For example,
Cowgill and Waldo still meet occasionally for special spiritual
sessions. They'll relax in Cowgill's examination room, dimmed for
the purpose. He will loosen his tie, they will both remove their
shoes and Cowgill will beseech what he calls ``the source'' to help
Waldo heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To limit yourself to being a body mechanic, well, it's like
applying handcuffs to yourself,'' Cowgill said. ``But if you can
work with the right patients and provide care on a mental,
emotional and spiritual plane, it's much more satisfying _ for both
me and the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dale A. Matthews, author of ``The Faith Factor: Proof of the
Healing Power of Prayer'' (Penguin, $13.95 paperback), says such
experiences are common among physicians who delve into a spiritual
realm with their patients. Matthews, a Washington internist and
speaker at a recent Harvard seminar on the subject, said he became
a convert after he was cajoled into praying with an elderly patient
experiencing symptoms of congestive heart failure. He wanted her to
go to the hospital immediately, but she refused.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they held hands and prayed together for healing, with
his patient clutching her rosary. She then said she would take the
fistful of prescriptions he gave her and would go home and pray
some more. A week later, she returned. She had lost 25 pounds _
much of it fluid that had built up in her body tissues _ and her
heart, once twice its size, was back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the question is, was it the medicine or the
prayer?'' Matthews said. ``Was it a miracle? I don't know, but it
sure was a dramatic turnaround in one week.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. G. Lee Cross, an Atlanta orthopedic surgeon, also prays with
his patients. And every morning, he prays for patients undergoing
surgery that day.
</P>
<P>
   Cross, a Baptist, believes the power of prayer not only helps
the patient, but is a good way to remind physicians that
ultimately, they are not alone in the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of us are perfectionists _ and we don't deal
well when things don't go our way,'' said Cross, who practices at
Atlanta Medical Center. ``I have found prayer is calming for me; a
reminder that there are things beyond my control.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
