r l BC-PROSTATE-QA12-COX     09-11 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-QA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctor a detective in fight against prostate cancer
 &HT;    By Gracie Bonds Staples
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is well past noon, 1:30 p.m., when Dr. James Bennett breaks
for lunch: a takeout container of dressing, carrots, green beans
and squash that his research nurse just picked up for him.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, a clinical associate professor of urology at Emory
University School of Medicine and a prostate cancer researcher,
settles at a table in the office library at Midtown Urology and
digs in, carefully avoiding the mound of Thanksgiving fare.
</P>
<P>
   A diet low in saturated fats and high in vegetables, he
acknowledges later, may play a key role in decreasing the rates of
prostate cancer, the most common cause of cancer in American men.
This year, an estimated 180,000 American men will be diagnosed with
the disease and 37,000 will die.
</P>
<P>
   But as with many deadly diseases, prostate cancer is showing up
in African-Americans at disproportionate rates _ 234 cases per
100,000 black men compared with 135 per 100,000 white men. What's
worse, black men are twice as likely to die from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   To raise awareness about the disease, Bennett, along with other
doctors and researchers, will be on hand to discuss research, risk
factors and treatment at a free two-hour public forum Thursday.
Also on the program will be notable Atlantans who have been treated
for prostate cancer, including former U.N. ambassador and former
Mayor Andrew Young.
</P>
<P>
   The forum, sponsored by the Georgia Prostate Cancer Coalition,
is scheduled for 7:30 p.m. in the Fox Theatre's Egyptian Ballroom,
660 Peachtree St. N.E. To register, call 404-816-4994. Parking is
free for the first 300 people who register.
</P>
<P>
   The event, co-sponsored by Saint Joseph's Hospital and the
Southeast Division of the American Cancer Society, is one of three
this week. The second, Walk for HIM (Health Initiatives for Men
Against Prostate Cancer), will begin at 8 a.m. Saturday at
Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the walk, free screenings for prostate
cancer, diabetes and high blood pressure will be offered at Big
Bethel AME Church, 220 Auburn Ave. Screenings will be 10 a.m.-2
p.m.; Saint Joseph's will also offer free prostate cancer screening
7:30 a.m.-2 p.m. at its cancer center, 5665 Peachtree Dunwoody Road
(registration: 404-851-5175).
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't attend the free forum, Bennett answered
these questions:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the prostate and how often should it be checked?
</P>
<P>
   A: The prostate is an organ that sits right beneath the bladder.
Its central function is providing nutrients for reproduction, and
it should be checked every year beyond the age of 50. For men at
high risk of developing prostate cancer _ men of African descent
and men with a family history _ the time is every year after the
age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   Q: African-American men are 66 percent more likely to get
prostate cancer than their white counterparts. Why are the rates so
high?
</P>
<P>
   A: We really don't know why. We are suspicious of dietary issues
such as animal fat, but I don't think it's the match that starts
the fire. There may be a hereditary predisposition, and gene
mutations might even be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any telltale signs of trouble that men should be
looking for?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's the problem with prostate cancer. Early cancer, in
particular, has no symptoms at all. That's why it's important to
get regular checkups. In most cases, if symptoms are present _
decreased force of stream, hesitancy, blood in the urine, stinging
or burning during urination _ the cancer is already advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you make a diagnosis?
</P>
<P>
   A: We do a digital rectal exam and a prostate-specific antigen
exam, which measures the PSA in the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're the principal investigator of the African-American
Hereditary Prostate Cancer Study. What exactly are you looking for?
</P>
<P>
   A: The goal of the study is to confirm the correlation of
hereditary prostate cancer to a genetic region on chromosome in
African-American men and for other genes associated with the
disease among this same group. We're hoping this information will
help us understand how genes cause or influence the course of
prostate cancer and better ways to diagnose and treat the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the status of the study?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's ongoing, and we're funded for the third year now. We
currently have about 50 African-American families nationwide
enrolled in the study, including nine families in Atlanta. We're
hoping that we can get an additional six more here in metro
Atlanta. (Information: 1-888-218-6157 or Bennett's office at
404-881-0966.)
</P>
<P>
   Gracie Bonds Staples writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
