r l BC-PROSTATE-TRIAL12-COX     09-11 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-TRIAL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    32,000 men in selenium, vitamin E trial
 &HT;    By Gracie Bond Staples
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors have believed for some time that selenium and vitamin E
might play a role in the prevention of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in perhaps one of the largest national trials ever
conducted, they hope to get a definitive answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some interest in selenium as a cancer
preventioe the mid-'90s, when a large trial was performed to
determine whether it would prevent skin cancer,'' said Dr. Holt
Sanders, a urologist at Saint Joseph's Hospital in Atlanta. ``It
did not, but (prostate cancer rates were) much lower, so it's going
to be very exciting to see how this one turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the Selenium and Vitamin E Cancer Prevention Trial
will likely get under way in January. Funded by the National Cancer
Institute, the $180 million trial will be conducted in Atlanta and
virtually every state in the country. It will involve some 32,000
men, who will take part in the study for five years with a
seven-year follow-up period.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the men will get selenium, others a placebo. Another
group will get vitamin E or a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two hypotheses,'' said Sanders. ``The first is that
one selenium tablet per day may decrease the risk of prostate
cancer, or taking vitamin E may do the same. This trial is designed
to figure this out.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, researchers need healthy men over 55 and
African-American men who are over 50 and have minimal medical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Saint Joseph's, the Atlanta portion of the
clinical trial will enroll men at DeKalb Medical Center, WellStar
Cobb Hospital, Wellstar Kennestone Hospital, Northside Hospital,
Piedmont Hospital, Gwinnett Hospital System and the Southern
Regional Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Men interested in participating should call Saint Joseph's
Cancer Center at 404-851-7116.
</P>
<P>
   _Gracie Bonds Staples writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constituion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
