<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-REPLAYTV12-COX     09-11 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-REPLAYTV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New television service gets Coke ad deal
 &HT;    By Scott Leith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. has inked a deal to become one of the
first advertisers on ReplayTV, a fledgling service that lets
watchers record shows without videotape.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is how many consumers will ever view the
beverage giant's ads. ReplayTV is still struggling to build an
audience and is trailing its main rival, TiVo. Coke's decision to
become a ReplayTV advertiser, however, could be a good sign for the
Mountain View, Calif., company.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV sells digital video recorders that look much like VCRs
but don't use tape. Viewers can create custom lineups of favorite
shows, along with manipulating live programs through the use of
slow motion and pausing while the actual show continues. Recording
is also simpler than with a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Digital video recorders could be problematic for advertisers,
however, because they can make it easier to skip commercials.
Coke's deal could help the company splash its name in front of
viewers more effectively, such as through sponsorship of ReplayTV's
``ReplayZone,'' which offers a menu of channels.
</P>
<P>
   Coke ads won't appear as ever-present banners during shows,
however. ``None of our advertising with ReplayTV will show up in
the normal television programming,'' said Chuck Fruit, Coke's vice
president and director for media and marketing assets.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Pictures was ReplayTV's first sponsor. Coke's ads will
start in October.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Coke isn't sure what to expect. ``One of our goals in
forming this partnership with ReplayTV is to learn, while they
learn, about what the public thinks,'' Fruit said.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV won't reveal the number of users it has. Its recorders
cost $499 to $599.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Bernoff, principal analyst with Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., said the entire industry encompasses only 60,000
digital video recorders so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of that, probably 80 percent are TiVos,'' Bernoff said. TiVo
also has the highest profile in the business because of a
summerlong ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Coke and ReplayTV declined to discuss financial details, but
Coke does not have a financial stake in the smaller company.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff said ReplayTV probably gave the beverage maker a good
deal to gain a big-name advertiser. ``Once you have Coke, it's
going to be easier to get Pampers or McDonald's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because ReplayTV is an interactive system, it offers several
potential selling points for advertisers. ``We're building a media
system that will allow us to send the right ads to the right
people,'' said Michael Teicher, senior vice president of
advertising sales for ReplayTV. The system uses normal phone lines
to connect to a user's home so a program menu can be updated.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, ReplayTV remains in its infancy. ``Within this
category, the first pitch of spring training hasn't been thrown
yet,'' Teicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke doesn't have an ad deal with ReplayTV rival TiVo, which
charges users a monthly fee of $9.95 and is not dependent on
advertising. ReplayTV charges no fee once a recorder is purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had conversations with a number of other personal
video recorder systems, and at some point in the future, we may do
something similar,'' Fruit said. While Coke is apparently bullish
on the prospects for digital video recorders, investors have been
skeptical so far.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo, which is based in San Jose, Calif., went public in October
1999. Its stock closed Monday at $20.13, far off its high of
$78.75.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Enterprises is among TiVo's investors.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV had planned to go public but backed down in August
following the tech-sector shakeout on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
