<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BOURSE-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE ON LONDON-FRANKFURT EXCHANGE MERGER POSTPONED AGAIN  

</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ What had been presented as a fait accompli just five
months ago faced a new setback Monday when the Frankfurt stock
exchange decided to postpone a shareholder vote meant to ratify a
planned merger with the London Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurt exchange's decision to cancel the Sept. 14
shareholder vote on the proposed merger with London to form the iX
exchange underscores the increasing complexities in the
consolidation of Europe's equity markets.
</P>
<P>
   The London exchange already had canceled its vote on the merger
in the aftermath of a hostile bid from Sweden's OM Gruppen, which
runs Stockholm's stock exchange. Details of OM's offer were made
public to shareholders Monday and did not significantly differ from
its original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a grand scheme of cooperation among Europe's
major stock exchanges has in practice been much harder to
implement. While most of the participants agree that they want a
pan-European market that makes it easier and less costly to trade,
how to get there has been a source of increasing contention. Even
as the stock exchanges disagree on the best model for
consolidation, the shareholders find themselves at odds over
differing agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulties of these mergers in Europe should never be
underestimated,'' said Ruben Lee, director of the Oxford Finance
Group, a consulting firm, and author of ``What Is An Exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurt exchange's decision to postpone the vote was
motivated more by strategy than pragmatism, said people close to
the exchange. They said it would be imprudent to hold a vote that
could be binding when the situation is changing so rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt would be unlikely to sweeten its 50-50 merger terms
until it receives a clear signal from London shareholders on their
view of OMs proposal, these people said. The Frankfurt exchange
will continue exploring the option of joining forces with the
Madrid and Milan stock exchanges in its attempts to secure a deal
with London, they added.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Nasdaq, which has said it would take a stake in iX,
now appears to be keeping its options open. Nasdaq executives met
with officials from OM last week in New York for a ``friendly
discussion,''people close to those talks said. It is understood
that Nasdaq has hired Dresdner Kleinwort Benson as its adviser,
although the bank declined to confirm or deny it had been retained.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the London-Frankfurt merger plans will go a long
way toward deciding how stock exchanges will consolidate throughout
Europe. OMs model is based on a single trading system, one
regulatory system and consolidated processes for clearing and
settlement _ the financial details of paying for and receiving
shares that are purchased on the exchange. The iX plan, by
contrast, would use one trading system, but would split the markets
between London and Frankfurt, rely on two sets of regulations and
separate clearing and settlement houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the transaction costs come from clearing and
settlement,'' Lee said. ``If the key point is to reduce transaction
costs, then iX is flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bidding for the London Stock Exchange is pitting
big banks against smaller retailer brokers _ both of which want to
promote competing visions of how stocks will trade in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the larger banks have expressed support for iX as a step
toward a Pan-European exchange, because it combines two of Europe's
largest markets.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Brian Winterflood, founder of retail brokerage firm
Winterflood Securities, is critical of iX, because it calls for
growth stocks, his main source of trading business, to list in
Frankfurt.Instead, he said he prefers a combination of the London
Stock Exchange, OM Gruppen, Nasdaq and the London futures market
called Liffe.
</P>
<P>
   Winterflood is also one of a growing number of retail brokers
who are calling for the dismissal of London exchange's chairman,
Don Cruickshank, and its chief executive, Gavin Casey. Both are up
for re-election at what is expected to be a contentious board
meeting Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
