<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.12.00
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Ericsson unveil phone deal
</P>
<P>
   Young buyers spend $164 billion online
</P>
<P>
   Online advertising revenue drops
</P>
<P>
   Students get $1 billion in online loans
</P>
<P>
   Intuit announces business shopping site
</P>
<P>
   SMARTER PHONES: Swedish cell phone giant Ericsson expects 1
billion people to use cell phones to link to the Web by 2005.
That's part of the reason it hooked up with Microsoft in a new
joint venture. Ericsson and Microsoft will tie cell phones to
corporate e-mail accounts and computer networks by the end of the
year. Their newly formed company, called Ericsson Microsoft Mobile
Venture AB, is part of a broader alliance that's expected to crank
out a new breed of so-called ``smart'' phones. Ericsson Microsoft's
software will also include calendars, to-do lists and other
personal organization functions.
</P>
<P>
   COMPETITION FOR MALLS: U.S. consumers aged 8 to 24 are spending
$164 billion a year online, according to a survey by Harris
Interactive. The survey, based on 3,900 responses, noted the online
purchases of 18- to 24-year-olds represented about 13 percent of
their total spending. Online purchases mimicked mall spending: the
most popular items were music, movie tickets and books.
</P>
<P>
   AD SALES DOWN: U.S. Internet advertising revenue fell 7.6
percent to $1.41 billion in August from the previous month as some
smaller companies cut back their spending, according to AdZone
Interactive. America Online's AOL.com shop, which spent $28.5
million, bought the most online ads last month, while NextCard Inc.
spent $25.8 million and Amazon.com Inc. spent $22.2 million. It's
the first month-to-month drop in online ad spending this year.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT LOANS ONLINE: Sallie Mae says it rang up more than a
billion dollars in student loans in the first year of an online
venture. The loan processor, dubbed Laureate, launched last summer
and was one of the first Web sites to handle the entire student
loan process. More than 190 college and university campuses are
using Laureate, Sallie Mae said.
</P>
<P>
   www.salliemae.com/schools/laureate.html
</P>
<P>
   INTUIT BEEFS UP B2B: Intuit, the maker of personal-finance
programs Quicken and Turbo Tax, will launch an Internet-based
shopping site for its small-business customers. The site sells
supplies at discounts of up to 40 percent from retailers such as
Office Depot and Gateway. Intuit has partnered with privately-held
Metiom. The companies will make money by charging commissions on
customer purchases.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   The Gap back at the top
</P>
<P>
   July is a slow time for clothing sales, and that showed up at
the mall and online. More than half of the top 15 apparel sites got
fewer visitors in July, according to Media Metrix. Gap.com regained
its spot as the most-visited apparel site. VictoriasSecret.com, the
No. 1 site in June, cooled for a second straight month. Other
clothing-related sites that got a boost in July catered to older
customers, such as Spiegel.com (up 65 percent), Nordstrom.com (up
27 percent) and ColdwaterCreek.com (up 30 percent).
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   NetIQ Corp. (NTIQ), up 8 percent to $54. Announced licensing
agreement with Unisys.
</P>
<P>
   Tut Systems (TUTS), down 13% at $88.31. Reiterated ``strong
buy'' by Dain Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.12.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   Resource for women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the most user-friendly site on the Web, but it's got a
ton of information for female entrepreneurs who want to do business
with the government.
</P>
<P>
   www.womenbiz.gov
</P>
