<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GEORGIA-SENATE0912-CO     09-11 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-SENATE0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tone nonpartisan as Miller begins ad campaign for Senate
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - As Zell Miller began his TV ad campaign for the U.S.
Senate last week, not even a distant echo remained from his fiery,
partisan keynote speech that invigorated the Democratic National
Convention eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in his second TV ad in less than a week, the newly
appointed senator goes out of his way to strike a nonpartisan tone
as he competes with six other candidates for the unexpired term of
the late U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, a United States senator should take Georgia
values to Washington, not bring Washington values to Georgia,''
Miller said in the 30-second commercial that debuted on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he should be the senator for all our people _ and not just
Democrats and not just Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   If it continues to go unanswered, Miller's apolitical theme,
coupled with his support for Republican-oriented plans to end the
so-called marriage tax penalty and estate tax, could deflate the
already lagging campaign of his chief challenger, Mack Mattingly,
political experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The special, nonpartisan election to fill the remaining four
years of Coverdell's term is Nov. 7. Miller was appointed by Gov.
Roy Barnes to serve until then.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly, a former one-term U.S. senator, has yet to begin TV
advertising, which political observers believe to the most
effective way he can reintroduce himself to Georgia voters who
haven't seem his name on the ballot in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the nonpartisan ballot are Summerville lawyer Ben
Ballenger, Atlanta lawyer and author Jeff Gates, Alpharetta
businessman Paul MacGregor, Savannah free-lance writer Winnie Walsh
and Duluth Realtor/owner Bob Wood. None of them has started TV
campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Mattingly's work has been concentrated on campaign stops
across the state with Republican Georgia congressmen, reminding the
party faithful that Miller is long-time Democrat and friend of
President Clinton and Al Gore. Miller's 1992 convention address in
New York preceded Clinton's party nomination for president. Earlier
that year, Miller changed the date of Georgia's presidential
primary, which helped the then-Arkansas governor carry the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattingly's constant mantra _ that only a Republican should
have been tapped to fill Coverdell's shoes _ does little to
resonate with the broader base of Georgians he must reach to win in
November, Emory University political scientist Merle Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't sell among all Republicans and it has no
resonance at all outside the Republican Party,'' Black said. ``This
is Zell's race to win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mattingly, who used an upset victory in 1980 to become the
state's first Republican elected to the U.S. Senate this century,
says he's gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Mattingly's aides cite the Miller campaign's
apparent change-of-heart on debate policy.
</P>
<P>
   First, the former governor's campaign said he would consider
only debate proposals that included all seven candidates, that were
broadcast statewide and that didn't fall within the final three
weeks of the campaign.(Miller will spend September and possibly
early October in Washington while the Senate is in session.)
</P>
<P>
   But late last week, Miller spokesman Rick Dent said the debate
posture remains ``flexible'' and that Miller's only condition is
that all debates be broadcast statewide to reach as many potential
voters as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because we said we'd accept everything,''
Mattingly spokesman Bill Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly also is calling for one-on-one debates, a format
Miller's campaign now says he's willing to accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Press Club has scheduled live U.S. Senate debates
Oct. 15 and Nov. 5 for statewide broadcast on Georgia Public
Television. Organizers are still awaiting confirmation from the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the sprinkling of TV ads, proposed debates and
Mattingly's establishment of advisory ``kitchen cabinets'' from the
coast to the mountains, the Senate contest has been slow to ignite.
Black and other political observers expect little activity until
the final month of what was initially projected to be a brief but
intense three-month campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag for Miller's initial round of TV advertising was
about $86,000 on four metro Atlanta stations, giving him less
face-time than 7th District congressional candidate Roger Kahn
bought on one Atlanta station over a nine-day period in a much
tougher contest against U.S. Rep. Bob Barr. Similar Miller ads also
hit the airwaves in Macon, Columbus and Savannah last week.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's had to do little more than that to remain a solid
frontrunner. Miller left office with a remarkable 85 percent
approval rating, and not even his huge uptick in personal income
last year from a variety of corporate board memberships and
consulting work for the Philip Morris tobacco company has drawn
more than glancing attacks from opponents.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller's chief challenger, Mattingly is well-known among
Republicans for party fund raising. But to defeat Miller, his own
challenge is to re-establish himself among rank-and-file voters _
and offer them a compelling message _ after such a long absence
from public life.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that national Republicans have indicated a
reluctance to invest money in the contest unless Mattingly
demonstrates he's competitive. Despite that public posture,
national Republican senatorial groups have begun forwarding
campaign contributions, Mattingly said.
</P>
<P>
   He projects a $3 million campaign, and though he won't discuss
specifics, he says his fund raising is going well. The Miller
campaign claims pledges of more than $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Black and others, however, speculate that Mattingly wants to
reserve his limited pool of funds until the final weeks of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller's setting the pace,'' Black said. ``The question is
whether Mattingly has the money to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
