<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TOUTS EDUCATION PLAN, JOKES WITH OPRAH, URGES ENTERTAINMENT
INDUSTRY CONTROL OF VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVILLE, Ill. _ With polls showing increasing support from
women voters, Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore kicked off
the campaign week Monday touting his $170 billion education plan
and promising to help parents shield their children from sex and
violence in entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   A clearly relaxed Gore began the day by appearing on the
nationally syndicated ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' before traveling to
Belleville to hold a town hall meeting at an elementary school, and
then on to Ohio, where he will spend Tuesday taking a Dayton to
Cincinnati tour in a yellow school bus.
</P>
<P>
   On the lighthearted ``Oprah,'' the vice president recounted for
a mostly-female audience his feelings before planting the big kiss
on wife Tipper at the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles. He answered questions on his favorite movie (``Local
Hero''), his favorite breakfast cereal (Wheaties) and his favorite
childhood memory (playing baseball with his dad).
</P>
<P>
   The vice president admired Winfrey's red boots and joked about
his reputation for being stiff.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore turned serious when he called for a ``cease-fire'' on
advertising adult-themed movies, music and video games in
publications and television broadcasts targeting young audiences.
If the entertainment industry doesn't police itself within the next
six months, he said, he and running mate Joe Lieberman would back
tougher laws to crack down on such advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about censorship. It's about citizenship, and that
includes corporate citizenship,'' he told Winfrey. He added that he
would build on long-standing efforts by his wife, Tipper, and
Lieberman to hold the entertainment industry accountable for
warning parents when their products contain adult-themed lyrics and
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Lieberman and I are following up on that,'' he said, ``so
that young kids can't get these albums that are inappropriate for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're called CD's now,'' Winfrey interjected to laughter and
applause. But Gore was ready with a high-tech comeback: ``Well,
ever since I shifted over to the MP3 ...,'' he began, referring to
an audio format used for playing and distributing music on
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement came in response to a Federal Trade
Commission report released Monday criticizing the entertainment
industry for its marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
   During a town hall meeting at Westhaven Elementary School in
Belleville, in southwestern Illinois, the vice president repeated
his call for the industry to ``clean up its act.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to several students about their fears of school
violence, Gore pointed out that two students who killed their
classmates and teachers at Columbine High School in Colorado had
been obsessed with the violent video game ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   The television, movie and music industries are together the
fourth-largest source of cash for the Democratic Party, raising
$5.9 million so far this campaign cycle for the party and $928,000
for Gore _ figures not lost on Gore's opponent, Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the man's short on credibility on the issue,'' said
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's schedule this week includes several fund-raisers in which
the Democratic National Committee hopes to raise $7 million from
donors attending concerts by such stars as Bette Midler, Cher,
Michael Bolton, Jimmy Buffett, Paul Simon and James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said that Gore can accept money from
the entertainment industry while still holding it responsible for
its actions. The is not true of Bush, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has taken huge amounts of money from the HMO
industry, from the big oil industry, from the pharmaceutical
industry. And then you look at the agenda that he has put forth,
and it parrots the interests of those special interests,'' Lehane
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, Al Gore has put forth an agenda that
benefits the people and he's on the people 's side, regardless of
who supports him and who doesn't support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that, he said, could be found in Gore's record on
supporting the V-chip to allow parents to control what shows their
children can watch and in supporting a TV rating system and more
educational TV programming.
</P>
<P>
   Taking questions from an audience of parents, teachers and
students in Belleville, Gore outlined his education plan, calling
for higher pay and better training for teachers, smaller classrooms
connected to the Internet and universal preschool for 3- and
4-year-olds. He also said he would offer tax credits to families in
which one parent stays home to care for the children, and to
families seeking to send their children to college.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would expand the federal Family and Medical Leave
Act to include those working at small companies so they can take
unpaid time off work to care for sick relatives or to participate
in their children's school activities.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed requiring school districts to adopt strict
disciplinary codes and expand character and citizenship education.
And he promised to triple federal funding for charter schools,
allowing parents more choice in which public schools their children
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on ``Oprah,'' Gore said parents need more support from
their communities and from government, and he said they need more
time to spend with their children and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to appear on the show next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
