A9360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-KENNEDY-ARRESTED-BOS &LR;      09-11 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-ARRESTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAN KENNEDY CHARGED WITH DRIVING WHILE INTOXICATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN AND FARAH STOCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joan B. Kennedy, the former wife of US Senator Edward M. Kennedy
who has struggled for years with alcoholism, was arrested for drunk
driving Sunday evening on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest is her fourth since 1974 and comes just after the
64-year-old marked nine years of sobriety and publicly said she
felt ``free'' from the addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Barnstable, Mass. police said they received a call from another
motorist between 8:30 and 9 Sunday night reporting a blue Buick
driving erratically and crossing the center line in the rural
Marstons Mills section of Barnstable, about five miles from the
Kennedy compound in Hyannis. The motorist followed the car while
talking to police on a cell phone, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy pulled off the main road and parked on a dead-end
street, where she got out of the car and spoke to the motorist, who
stopped to ``ask if she was okay,'' Barnstable police Sgt. Sean
Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, Kennedy would only give her first name and
politely refused to produce a driver's license or car registration,
Sweeney said. She admitted having wine earlier in the evening and
``exhibited signs of intoxication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer didn't conduct any field sobriety tests, Sweeney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy pleaded innocent to the charges at her arraignment
Monday in Barnstable District Court. A pretrial conference is set
for Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, US Rep. Patrick Kennedy, who has also received
treatment for alcoholism, issued a statement requesting that his
mother's privacy be respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``What my mother did was wrong, and she will pay a price for it
through the legal system,'' said the Rhode Island Democrat.
``However, my mother has always been very supportive of me, and I
intend to stand by her side in this very difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask that all individuals, and especially the media, respect
the personal nature of this insidious disease she has been fighting
for many years and give her the room and privacy to be able to deal
with this latest incident as she has handled other setbacks in her
life. I love my mother very much and will continue to provide her
with the support and help she needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Kennedy began speaking publicly about her struggle with
alcoholism after her tumultuous marriage to Senator Edward M.
Kennedy ended in divorce in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In an article this year, she told The Boston Globe Magazine that
she ``had not had a drink in nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a relief to be free,'' she also said. ``So much of
my married life was about keeping secrets and pretending that I was
doing great and happy. Once you sober up, the whole idea is to be
honest with yourself and other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has devoted time and her family name to charitable
causes, and also counseled other women at Alcoholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has made many successful attempts at staying sober,'' Hope
Podell, who develops programs to help alcoholics conquer their
addictions, said Monday. ``If in fact she relapsed, it's too bad it
happened, but it's not the end of the world. She probably will
sincerely make the next attempt to put down her drink and not pick
up the next one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-HEALTH-POLITICS-ANALY     09-11 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POLITICS-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DIFFERENCES ON MEDICARE PLANS, CANDIDATES APPEAL TO ELDERLY
VOTERS _ AND THEIR CONCERNED MIDDLE-AGED CHILDREN &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   A handful of pills and a fistful of dollars are the pictures
that might come to mind first for voters considering the competing
plans of George W. Bush and Al Gore to provide prescription drug
payments for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But in the political sense, the proposals also suggest the image
of IV poles _ structures that each candidate can carry around in
the race for president to dangle a variety of campaign themes,
strategies and debate points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who announced his $158 billion plan last week in response
to Gore's and campaigned on the issue Monday in Florida, would use
federal Medicare funds to subsidize the premiums that elderly
people would pay to private insurance companies. The firms would
provide coverage for prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that dovetails into the traditional Republican
side of the Texas governor's overall agenda, because it relies on
competition within the private sector rather than the Medicare
program itself, which any faithful GOP member would be tempted to
call a government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   But it also gives Gore another line of attack, because the vice
president is fond these days of criticizing health maintenance
organizations, pharmaceutical companies and other corporations that
he says are powerful interests lined up against ``the people.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the vice president indeed demonstrated in the last few
days, it gives the Democrats a chance to cast doubt on whether Bush
can deliver on spending programs and an ambitious income tax cut at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Bush seeks the upper hand on a health care issue,
Democrats also attack his record in Texas. Gore's running mate,
Joseph Lieberman, waged the fight last week with a campaign
appearance in Houston, where he criticized Bush's record on
Medicaid programs for children. The program is different from
Medicare, which covers the elderly, but it was a health-coverage
topic nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Now switch sides.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's $253 billion Medicare plan would provide prescription
drug payments for the elderly directly through the government
program, not through private insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   This approach dovetails into the traditional Democratic theme of
preserving the government's so-called entitlement programs, such as
Medicare and Social Security, against attempts by the GOP to change
this ``sacred'' territory by mixing it with the private business
world.
</P>
<P>
   But it also allows Bush to push his vision of a less
confrontational and more bipartisan approach in Washington, because
the National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare has
recommended that private insurers rather than the government
provide drug benefits to seniors. And it allows Bush to portray
himself as the more reform-minded contender, because Gore's plan
does not change the function of Medicare as much as Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences on Medicare, though, the plans give
both candidates the chance to appeal to elderly voters _ and to
their concerned middle-aged children who are elderly-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   As drug prices soar, a glance at the electoral map shows why the
elderly, most of whom rely on fixed incomes to pay their medical
costs, are an important group in this election.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, where Gore erased Bush's early lead in the polls, is
studded with retirement communities. In the Midwest, where the
contest is neck-and-neck, analysts say the most crucial cluster of
undecided voters is older members of the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush both propose to pay for prescription drug coverage
with part of the projected federal budget surplus. On a timeline,
Bush's plan is more aggressive. It would start next year. Gore's
plan would phase in over several years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the issue must be fought on what is usually Democratic turf,
because polls indicate that voters trust the Democrats more than
the Republicans to address problems with health care.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably one explanation for the findings of a July poll
by the Wall Street Journal and NBC. Forty-four percent of voters
said Gore would do a better job on prescription drug coverage, 22
percent said Bush would and 10 percent said the two were equal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may have altered Bush's pace on the issue, too. The
Democrat came out with his plan first, then spent weeks flogging
his opponent for having no plan. Of course when Bush did put forth
his proposal last week, Gore picked at the details.
</P>
<P>
   It was a political ritual reminiscent of Gore's steamrolling of
challenger Bill Bradley in the Democratic primaries. Gore
criticized the former New Jersey senator for offering no plan on
education issues then pecked at the details of Bradley's subsequent
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as the prescription drug debate is fought out over
competing specifics, it feeds into Gore's strengths. He is running
partly on his grasp of government details, while Bush's appeal runs
closer to factors of character and freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Bush's favor, his plan shows on its face that he can
match Gore detail-for-detail when it comes to offering enticing
ways to spend surplus money.
</P>
<P>
   For voters thirsting for concrete proposals that would change
their personal finances if not their lives _ rather than shallow
posturing and what Bradley called ``the politics of a thousand
promises and a thousand attacks'' _ the prescription drug debate
offers all the ingredients, good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans would provide free prescription drugs for seniors
earning less than $11,300 a year. Gore's plan would pay part of the
premiums for drug coverage for seniors earning less than $12,450 a
year; Bush's plan would provide the same benefits for seniors
earning less than $14,600.
</P>
<P>
   For those who earn more, Gore's plan would subsidize half the
cost of prescription drugs. Bush's plan, by providing subsidies for
payments to insurance companies, would allow seniors to pay more
for more generous coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan, no elderly person would have to pay more than
$4,000 a year for drugs. Under the first four years of Bush's plan
the annual limit on drug costs would be $6,000, but after that no
senior would have to pay more than $6,000 a year for all health
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Both approaches apparently would involve dictating terms to
private industry. Gore's plan, at least according to Bush, would
put the government in the position of negotiating drug discounts
from pharmaceutical manufacturers. Crimping the Republican
philosophy of free markets, though, Bush would require all insurers
that provide Medicare coverage to include a prescription drug
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
