<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALBANIAN-PAGEANT-ART-     09-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIAN-PAGEANT-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE SHE IS, MISS ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and 18 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Krenare Abazaga fled Kosovo with her family two years
ago. Things were bad. Her best friend was killed by the Serbs. But
backstage last night in her adopted homeland of the Bronx,
surrounded by a fog of hair spray and glitter and cigarette smoke,
her hair piled in swirls, Abazaga, 16, was not just a refugee.
</P>
<P>
   She was contestant No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody like to kill us, to take our culture and our
language,'' she said as she adjusted her green-and-yellow dress
with the scoop neck. ``But we are still alive and we are proud of
ourselves. It's something that I like to tell the whole world, that
even though we had to separate and go all over the world, we have
come back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauty pageants have always been patriotic affairs, but at the
first Miss Albania U.S.A. Pageant in New York, at Lehman High
School, the fervor got a little intense at times.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, when 2 of the 13 contestants, Violeta Nikci
and Elona Prela, marched out carrying the Albanian and American
flags and placed them next to each other, the noise from the 400 or
so spectators jamming the auditorium nearly drowned out the
thundering drumbeats from the recorded martial music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I miss my country so much, the Albanian flag replaces it
somehow,'' Prela, 18, said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The pageant's organizer, Shureta Povataj, said: ``Because of the
war that's happening, we're trying to restore people's dreams. To
try to bring some attention to the brighter side.''
</P>
<P>
   Povataj, 27, who runs the Midtown showroom of the decorator F.
Schumacher and Co., said she got the idea for the pageant when she
went to Kosovo last October to fulfill her father's dying wish:
that he be buried in the village where he was born, near Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``I experienced a lot of what the refugees are seeing, homes
burned to the ground, the massive graves,'' she said. ``My
relatives, when they were trying to comfort me, were saying, `At
least your father was able to die naturally, no one massacred him,
you were able to bury him in one piece.' It was very sad. But I
felt proud that people were moving on in life, that with all the
destruction that has occurred, they had the will to move on and
rebuild their homes and their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The contestants, who ranged in age from 16 to 24 and live mostly
in the Bronx, home to about 30,000 Albanian-Americans, were vying
for a $3,000 prize and a slot in the Miss Albania contest in
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Povataj said she was trying to strike a blow for the liberation
of young Albanian-American women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albanian culture is very conservative,'' she said, ticking off
the restrictions that Albanian girls in this country chafe against.
Makeup and dating are discouraged, tight clothes considered
scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to break that barrier, and have parents accept that
it's OK to be fashionable, OK to look pretty,'' Povataj explained,
``that there's nothing wrong with your daughter being in a pageant
and showing off her beauty. She's not committing a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Povataj, who recruited contestants through ads in local
Albanian newspapers and over the Internet, said, ``We had
contestants back out because their families were against it.''
</P>
<P>
   The father of one contestant, Erjona Boshnjaku, 17, did not want
her to take part. ``At first my father said, `No way, why do you
want to do that?''' Boshnjaku said. ``But everyone else in my
family disagreed. I wanted to do this to show who I am, and my
personality, and to show I'm proud to be Albanian.''
</P>
<P>
   If it seems odd to think of beauty pageants as a force of
women's emancipation, consider that when the Miss America Pageant
began in 1921, the year after women won the right to vote, it was
considered dangerous and subversive and drew protests from
religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   For all its revolutionary ideology, last night's pageant was
pretty old-fashioned. The girls paraded across the stage carrying
torches. They answered questions about what Albania meant to them,
and spoke of their hopes and dreams. Abazaga, a student at Lehman,
said she wanted to go to college ``and help my country and my
friends and everyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In between events, the dressing room was a flurry of grooming
and teasing and cursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hair looks terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You messed up the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   All that was missing was the bathing-suit competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the community doesn't like to show the girls in
bikinis,'' said the producer, Dajan Sukai. ``Next year they will
trust me for this thing, but this year we have to be serious.''
</P>
<P>
   As the girls came out in Albanian red and black _ red T-shirts
tied at the side and emblazoned with the national symbol, a
two-headed lion, and black short-shorts _ the audience hooted and
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our flag, our culture,'' said Mark Krasniqi, 24, a real
estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the evening, when Prela, whose career aspiration
is to become Miss America, was crowned queen, the place exploded in
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy!'' the winner gushed, then she marched the
Albanian flag around the stage one more time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
