u a BC-CALIF-FREE-TUITION-NY     09-11 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FREE-TUITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA ENACTS NATION'S MOST GENEROUS STUDENT AID PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California on Monday enacted the most generous
college financial aid plan in the nation, guaranteeing needy high
school students with good grades that it will pay their full
tuition at the state's public colleges and universities, or offer
close to $10,000 a year toward tuition at one of the state's
private institutions. The plan will cost the state more than $1
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with a $12 billion budget surplus and fighting years of
declines in its once-proud public education system, California will
have by far the largest and most financially comprehensive student
aid program for graduating high school seniors, with what amounts
to a new entitlement program nearly twice the size of a similar
program in New York State, for example, and about one-third of the
total spending by all states on student grants and aid combined.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal passed both houses of the State Legislature
unanimously last month, and in signing it Monday on the Los Angeles
campus of the California State University, Gov. Gray Davis
pronounced it ``a historic day for higher education.'' Indeed, the
measure sails against the recent trend in scholarship programs,
including another signed Monday by Davis, that are focused on tax
credits or academic performance without regard to financial need,
which have tended to help middle-class families most.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the so-called Cal-Grants, a vast expansion of a program
that has been in place since 1956, blend merit and financial need.
Starting next year, any high school senior in the state with a
``B'' average who lives in a family of four earning $64,000 a year
or less would qualify for free tuition at any public university in
the state, or $9,700 toward tuition at a private one. Even ``C''
students from families earning less than $34,000 a year would
receive $1,500 a year for living costs and books, intended to help
them catch up at local community colleges and qualify to go on for
four-year degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What California said today was need still matters,'' said
Travis Reindl, a policy analyst at the American Association of
State Colleges and Universities in Washington. ``For the last seven
years, with the emphasis on accountability in education, the
emphasis has been on merit. This says let's look at the need and
merit combined.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials did not hesitate to call the program, which is
expected to cover almost one-third of all graduating high school
seniors, about 100,000 students a year, an entitlement, akin to
Medicare or Social Security, though Davis, a moderate Democrat and
staunch fiscal conservative, did not use that word. He had proposed
a separate measure, also signed into law today, that will award
$118 million a year in merit scholarships of $1,000 to the top 10
percent of scorers in each high school on the Stanford 9
standardized achievement test and $2,500 to the highest performers
on Advanced Placement exams in math and science.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative critics had said that would tend to favor
middle-class students, and the governor eventually bowed to
bipartisan pressure from both houses, which agreed to pass the
bills as a package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize,'' Davis said Monday, ``these bills are
not a free ride. They are a fair reward for extraordinary
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' interim secretary of education, John Mockler, said in an
interview: ``The beauty of it is you can say to every kid in high
school: You do your part and get the grades and income is not going
to be a deterrent to your going to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1970s, the state offered free tuition to its higher
education system. But it has not had enough money in recent years
to offer Cal-Grants to all students whose grades and family incomes
would make them eligible. When Davis took office two years ago, the
program was spending about $400 million a year, one-third the
amount it will now spend, and last year only about 55,000 of the
137,000 students eligible for aid received it. California ranks
39th in the nation in college-going, with just over half its
high-school graduates going on to college, compared with the
national average of close to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have similar programs, including New York's Tuition
Assistance Program, which provides about $700 million in annual aid
to needy students and was previously the most generous state
program, according to Reindl of the Association of State Colleges
and Universities. But its maximum annual grant is $5,000, and it
fully covers tuition for only the poorest families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This catapults California into the lead,'' Reindl said. Reindl
warned that the risk of creating such a new entitlement is that it
would face intense pressure in lean budgetary years. ``This is a
huge financial commitment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nani Escudero, 19, and Nicolette Birdsong-Gibson, 24, both
juniors at California State at Los Angeles who say they could not
have afforded tuition without the Cal-Grants, said Monday that the
expanded program will greatly help them to persuade other high
school students to apply to college. Both work as interns in local
high schools, answering students' questions about college
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come on a lot of situations where kids say, `I don't want to
go to college,''' said Escudero, whose father, a mechanic, died in
her senior year of high school, ``and I ask why not, and they say,
`I can't afford it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Birdsong-Gibson added: ``Cost is always the major thing. I know
a lot of students with good grades who just don't believe they can
afford it. This should really help.''
</P>
<P>
   John Burton of San Francisco, the Democratic president pro tem
of the State Senate, who pressed hard for the measure, called it
``the biggest thing since popcorn,'' adding: ``What this says to
poor kids in high school is no longer can they say to themselves,
`Why should I study? I ain't going to go anywhere anyway because my
family can't afford it.' It's like the G.I. Bill was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
