<SLUG> BC-OPED-NUKE-SECRETS-LILLEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING THE TRUTH ABOUT CHINESE ESPIONAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Sept. 12, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JAMES LILLEY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The case of Wen Ho Lee may be resolved, now that
the government has dropped all but one indictment against him. But
the problems underlying the case are unlikely to disappear, and the
government must rethink how it resolves the central conflict
between democratic principles and national security.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese-Americans were quite right to raise alarms about ethnic
profiling in weapons laboratories. The accusations of racism and
ethnic targeting of foreign-born scientists have poisoned the
atmosphere at the National Security Agency and the national
laboratories, including Los Alamos and Lawrence Livermore.
Asian-Americans have been leaving the labs, partly because of
higher salaries offered elsewhere, but also because they are
worried about discrimination and heavy-handed new security
measures.
</P>
<P>
   In our laudable determination to avoid racial profiling,
however, we must not damage our national security by painting a
benign picture of China's espionage techniques. It is an
established fact that China tries to recruit ethnic Chinese in the
United States, particularly those who may be vulnerable to
seduction, payoffs, appeals to Chinese nationalism and, in some
cases, coercion. A 361-page book put out by China's intelligence
office in 1991, and obtained by the Far Eastern Economic Review,
described how China maintains a thorough system of gathering
intelligence abroad for military purposes, aimed primarily at the
United States. Rep. Christopher Cox of California updated this
information in his 1999 report on China's espionage efforts. In the
spy business, targeting ethnic groups is widespread; the Soviets
went after Russian emigres for years.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Eftimiades in his 1994 book ``Chinese Intelligence
Operations'' describes China's efforts to collect technology _
information on night vision equipment, blueprints for F-14 fighter
aircraft, for example _ from ethnic Chinese agents in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   China has been accused of recruiting agents in a number of
cases. In 1985, Larry Wu-Tai Chin, a CIA analyst, was charged with
passing secrets to the Chinese Government for 40 years (he
committed suicide in jail). Peter Lee, an American scientist at
TRW, was accused of passing submarine detection technology to
China. Federal prosecutors in Los Angeles said they wanted to
charge Lee with espionage but were unable to, partly because Navy
officials in Washington would not allow testimony about the
technology in an open courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Cox report states that Johnny Chung, a
Chinese-American at the center of the campaign finance controversy
involving the Democratic Party, was given $300,000 by two Chinese
military officials in a purported attempt to acquire American
technology and to help the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that China tries to recruit spies doesn't
mean that Chinese-Americans as a group should be suspect. When Cox
released his report, he said the Energy Department had demonized
Wen Ho Lee, and his study did not mention the Los Alamos scientist.
</P>
<P>
   To catch any spy requires good investigative work. Chinese
intelligence methods are complex and arcane, and special skills and
experience are needed to detect them. What seems to be missing on
our side is the painstaking, timely investigative use of wiretaps,
computer access, independent surveillance and informers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the government prematurely leveled a 59-point indictment
at Wen Ho Lee, Chinese-Americans have been harassed and evidence
has disappeared. What is needed to regain trust among
Asian-Americans are fair, scrupulous and professional
investigations; we cannot allow poorly handled cases to alienate a
segment of our population.
</P>
<P>
   (James Lilley is a former ambassador to China and a former
senior officer for the Central Intelligence Agency.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
