<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-U.N.-MISSION-WRI     09-11 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-U.N.-MISSION-WRIGHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEACE THAT'S WITHIN OUR GRASP 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Tuesday, Sept. 12, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ROBERT WRIGHT    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ United Nations meetings are famous for
accomplishing nothing concrete, and some observers have cited last
week's millennium forum as a prime example. Still,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan could rightly claim that he gained a
measure of support for one of his most ambitious and controversial
proposals: that the United Nations regularly intervene in civil
wars when the human stakes are high. President Clinton came as
close as he has come to endorsing the idea, and other leaders
embraced, in vaguer terms, a toughened U.N. role in imploding
states.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Annan's idea sometimes argue that intervening in
intrastate conflict is no great departure from the United Nation's
founding doctrines _ that the Charter of 1945 leaves plenty of room
for reaching inside a nation to stop slaughter or the widespread
abuse of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   As Annan himself put it when he unveiled the idea last year,
``Nothing in the Charter precludes a recognition that there are
rights beyond borders.'' Maybe not, but for practical purposes this
sentence comes pretty close: ``Nothing contained in the present
Charter shall authorize the United Nations to intervene in matters
which are essentially within the domestic jurisdiction of any
state.''
</P>
<P>
   As an unabashed one-worlder, I don't mean to say that the United
Nations should never intervene in a civil war, or that there is no
conceivable legal basis for doing so. The Charter is a sometimes
ambiguous document, and, rather as the U.S. Supreme Court
ultimately decides what the Constitution means, the Security
Council decides what qualifies as a threat to ``international peace
and security'' _ the threshold that justifies the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that the United Nations was designed to
stop war between nations, not within them. Those who want a
systematic broadening of this mandate would do well first to ponder
the logic behind the more modest aims of the organization's
founders. Otherwise, they could wind up further damaging its
perilously low credibility.
</P>
<P>
   One virtue of the founders' focus on interstate conflict is the
relative ease of assigning blame: any nation that violates another
nation's border is subject to collective retaliation. Sometimes, to
be sure, identifying the bad guys in internal conflicts is
similarly simple. (When men are hacking off the arms of children,
raping women and looting homes, that's a clue.) But often things
are murkier. So the consistent punishment of transgressors is even
harder in intrastate wars than in interstate wars.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, actually administering the punishment is no picnic in
either case. But, with interstate wars, it has gotten easier. The
evolution of ``smart'' weapons, by letting an advanced military
force wreak massive damage while sustaining little, has lowered a
longstanding barrier to fulfilling the U.N.'s mission: the
reluctance of even right-minded nations to risk lives when their
territory isn't immediately threatened.
</P>
<P>
   These smart bombs and missiles are much less valuable in the
usual internal conflict. Witness their mixed record in the Kosovo
intervention. Yes, they brought Slobodan Milosevic to his knees by
decimating Serbia's infrastructure. But they had little effect in
Kosovo itself, where the enemy possessed no distinct, sizable
territory and no fixed industrial base _ where, in short, the enemy
resembled the enemy in many intrastate wars.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Charter's focus on interstate war was due partly to
political reality: the need to get the Charter signed in the first
place. It is one thing for a nation to agree not to fight another
nation except in self-defense. It is another thing to agree that,
should internal rebellion arise, the government's response will be
subject to Security Council approval. This tension persists.
Nations that face internal turmoil _ Russia, for example _ may not
back the United Nations in halting transborder aggression if they
consider a strong United Nations a threat within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the main reason the founders of the United Nations
focused on interstate conflict was their memory of the immediate
past: four years of horrendous world war. But they were also moved
by images of the future: a nuclear world in which war among nations
could make World War II look like a dustup. It is easy to forget,
especially in good economic times, that we still live in such a
world.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that reaching the essential goal of the United
Nations _ collective action to stop cross-border wars _ is more
practical now than during the Cold War. The rollback of Iraqi
aggression in the Persian Gulf war, explicitly authorized by
Security Council vote, showed as much. Still, even this challenge
is hardly mastered. Milosevic's orchestration of savagery in Bosnia
was technically a case of transborder aggression, since Bosnia had
gained its sovereignty and joined the United Nations, but his
campaign met no forceful international resistance for years.
</P>
<P>
   If world leaders want the United Nations to address intrastate
conflict seriously, that's fine with me. But they should brace
themselves. This will involve, for starters, a standing U.N. army
(perhaps an all-volunteer army, to make casualties politically
tolerable at the national level). It will involve not just
``peacekeeping,'' but peacemaking _ deciding who the bad guys are
and then killing them until a white flag appears.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it will involve picking fights carefully. To define a
goal of suppressing all intrastate war is, for both political and
military reasons, hopelessly unrealistic, a recipe for the further
loss of U.N. credibility. And credibility could be crucial when it
comes time to perform the original mission _ to prevent or halt
transborder aggression in, say, the now-nuclear South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humanitarian intervention'' is the name for U.N. involvement
in intrastate wars. But preventing interstate war is also
humanitarian. The founding, thoroughly humanitarian insight of the
United Nations is that, in a nuclear world, ending war between
nations is job one. Today _ when, for the first time in history,
that goal may be reachable _ it would be a shame to lose sight of
it.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Wright, a visiting scholar at the University of
Pennsylvania, is the author of ``The Moral Animal'' and ``Nonzero:
The Logic of Human Destiny.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
