<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9379 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-OLYMPICS-OZ12-COX     09-11 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-OZ12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic drama will be played out against a dazzling, exotic
backdrop.
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Welcome to the Olympics of Oz.
</P>
<P>
   These Games Down Under, the first of the new millennium, promise
to be strange, magical and wondrous even by Olympic standards.
Marion Jones, Michael Johnson, Maurice Greene, a pack of great
swimmers and thousands of the best athletes from around the globe
are poised to put on a riveting, heart-swelling and heart-tugging
show, the likes of which are staged only once every four years. The
Summer Olympics command world-wide attention like nothing else in
or outside of sports, and this time around the drama will be played
out against a dazzling and exotic backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Oz is an Aussie nickname for their homeland. We're not talking
an HBO show, but a real penal colony experiment begun in 1788 when
11 ships of Britain's First Fleet sailed into the harbor here. This
same port can now glisten as brightly as any Emerald City,
especially when fireworks are cascading over the sail-shaped Sydney
Opera House, as they will when these Olympics begin.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, once a cultural backwater, is now a teeming, bustling,
beach-going, partying polyglot of Pacific cultures. With four
million souls Sydney has more than one-fifth of Australia's
population of 19 million. Oz has about as many people as does
Texas, housed on an arid land mass the size of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic citizens here are hoping that Jacques Rogge was
right when he proudly announced, ``Sydney is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogge is head of the International Olympic Committee's Sydney
Co-Ordination Committee. Deep down he's got to be about as nervous
as a 100-meter sprinter eyeing Greene while waiting for the
starter's gun to shatter the hush. Just a mere century ago the
modern Olympics were the small, quixotic dream of Frenchman Baron
Pierre de Coubertin, who wanted to bring the youth of the world
together in friendly amateur athletic competition to be faster,
higher and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes are certainly that these days, although they are
also older and sometimes quite rich. Under the reign of current IOC
head Juan Antonio Samaranch the Olympics have embraced
professionals and the TV-ratings-swelling concept of the best vs.
the best.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch was spotted Saturday impatiently waiting for a bus
that never arrived. His Olympics have become so popular, so grand
and so large that they can now make the most advanced of cities and
countries look inept as they did in the summer of 1996, when only
residents of Atlanta clung to the notion that the city hadn't been
brought to its knees by the enormity of the event.
</P>
<P>
   This time around there's even a couple of quirks to add to the
typical Olympic madness. These Summer Games are almost the winter
games. Australia, in the southern hemisphere, is just coming into
spring. Mornings are so brisk you might need to rub your hands
together for warmth. Days warm quickly as the sun rises in an azure
sky to beat down on palm trees and squawking birds right out of an
old-fashioned jungle movie. But still the temperature never gets
much above 70 degrees and blustery winds seem to kick up in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That's afternoon here, which would be perhaps the witching hour
in the U.S.'s Central Time zone. Australia lies across the
International Dateline from the U.S., and there's an eight-hour
difference from our time zone. Preliminaries that are run early in
the morning here fall in the evening of the previous day in the
U.S. Nightly finals here wind up finishing on the same day in the
U.S., but in the early morning hours when only people working the
graveyard shift are awake. That kind of time warp is why, even with
all the TV coverage in the U.S., not a single minute of the drama
will be televised live. The warp here will be in the strained
transportation system, as residents have been warned that typical
one-hour trips may stretch to three hours or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Some Australians fear the worst and have already headed out of
town for the duration. Others remain lukewarm to some events, such
as volleyball, where at last count there were 96,000 unsold
tickets. The Aussies are even downplaying their own medal hopes,
lest they be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   That attempt at distance should last less than a day, once the
Olympic competition begins. The first medal event, the women's
triathlon, is one strategically placed to get the residents of Oz
into a flag-waving frenzy. The U.S. has its own hopes in
triathlon's Olympic debut, led by San Antonio native Jennifer
Gutierrez, who has vowed to swim with the sharks that sometimes
infest the harbor. But the Aussies plan to have something even more
unsettling, a staggering one million fans lining the swimming,
running and cycling course. They're thinking of a gold, silver and
bronze sweep right out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   From there the main action will quickly shift to the dazzling
18,200-seat Sydney International Aquatic Center, one of the
facilities that makes the Olympic Park here arguably the greatest
collection of athletic facilities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The battle to rule the pool will have a pronounced Aussies vs.
U.S. theme, one that will replace the old Cold War conflict between
the Eastern Bloc and the U.S. that used to emotionally drive the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Aussies chanted, ``Carter's a wanker!'' at a
spirited U.S.-Australia basketball exhibition game at Melbourne,
they were just trying to get NBA star Vince Carter to miss a few
free throws. They don't dislike the U.S., or its athletes, they
just would relish dishing out a little comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   In no sport has the U.S. more dominant than in swimming. The
last time the Olympics were held in Australia in 1956 at Melbourne,
the Aussies won more medals than the U.S. in swimming. No one here
has forgotten that fact. At the recent U.S. Swimming Trials in
Indianapolis there were Australian coaches actually comparing times
with those of their own swimmers and scoring it like a mock dual
meet.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgent Australians have teenage sensation Ian Thorpe.
Propelled by size 16 flippers, Thorpe is thought by bookies here to
be almost as unbeatable as Carter and the rest of the USA Dream
Team of hoopsters. One of the swimmers who'll try to sink the
Thorpedo is the most decorated male athlete of the last Olympics,
three-time gold medal-winner Josh Davis. The Austin resident and
Texas ex will face Thorpe in the 200 meters and figures to anchor a
4X200 meter team that could include current UT swimmers Scott
Goldblatt, Jamie Rauch and Nate Dusing, one that's a decided
underdog to the Aussies.
</P>
<P>
   A much stronger event for the U.S. will be the 100-meter
backstroke where Lenny Krazelberg and Austin's Neil Walker are
expected to medal. Walker is also given a strong shot in the 100
meters, along with the talented Gary Hall. As for the Aussies,
they're looking forward to the 1,500 meter freestyle. Really. A
distance that doesn't produce much more than yawns in the U.S. is
being touted as the biggest thing of these Olympics, a showdown
between Australia's Kieren Perkins and Grant Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   As for the U.S., eyes there will focus on Jones once the track
competition begins midway through the Olympics. Johnson will be
defending his 400-meter crown and Greene will be racing for the
title of World's Fastest Human, but neither is on a quest like
Jones. Ms. Jones, as she's known in Nike ads, is going for an
unprecedented five gold medals. If this is Oz, she's Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones looked like something out of the 22nd century when she was
decked out in a Swift Suit for the September 11 issue of Newsweek.
One of the cover lines there, ``The Drug Game,'' unfortunately
applies to these Olympics. In spite of hopes and promises
beforehand, tests are still not in place to detect human growth
hormone, rumored to be the drug of choice in the Atlanta Games, and
a host of other performance enhancing drugs that will allow
cheaters to fly beneath the radar of official drug police here.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the Olympics will leave some wondering what was real
and what was a drug-aided illusion. But that never seems to foil
the drama, which is now about to unfold in Oz.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
