<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT-NYT &LR;      09-11 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF KNIGHT FIRING, PLAYERS THREATEN TO LEAVE INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indiana University's campus was rainy and calm Monday after a
night of angry demonstrations over Bobby Knight's ouster and
threats against the student whose accusations were a factor in the
dismissal of the legendary basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs of more potential fallout from the end of
Knight's three-decade reign at Indiana. Several players demanded
that one of Knight's assistants, either Mike Davis or John Treloar,
be hired as the interim coach; if one of the assistants is not
hired, they said, they will leave the university. Other players,
including Dane Fife, a junior guard, said they were considering
leaving anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things work out the way we want it, we'll stay,'' forward
George Leach, a sophomore, told The Associated Press. ``We are
ready to go if they don't meet our demands. Indiana will not have a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' reactions underscored the intense loyalty Knight
inspired. All were somber and some were teary at the news
conference Sunday when Myles Brand, the university's president,
announced Knight's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis, one of the assistant coaches, was asked Sunday if he
would stay, he said: ``Coach brought me here; he gave me this job.
Whatever Coach tells me to do, whatever the players say, I'm going
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some rabid fans among the students had a similar reaction that
night, calling for the resignation of Brand instead of the
dismissal of Knight, who has a history of abusive behavior.
Thousands of students marched to Brand's home on campus Sunday
night, chanting ``Hey, hey, ho, ho, Myles Brand has got to go,''
while police officers in riot gear watched.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators also handed out flyers with a picture of Kent
Harvey, the freshman who had lodged the most recent complaint
against Knight, with a caption reading: ``Wanted. Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Horns blared across campus. Signs and banners appeared on
dormitories and fraternities. One read ``Bob Knight is God,'' and
another said, ``Knight 4 President.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the protests, Knight met with his team. He then
appeared outside Assembly Hall and addressed a throng of student
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next couple of days, I'm going to get together
somewhere with as many students who want to come out, and then I'm
going to tell you my side of this thing,'' the 59-year-old coach
said. ``And I think you'll be interested in hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing Knight, Brand cited a pattern of ``uncivil,
defiant and unacceptable'' behavior since May that culminated last
week with Harvey's accusation that Knight had manhandled him and
verbally abused him. Knight accosted Harvey because he had failed
to use an honorific when he spoke to the coach, saying only: ``Hey,
Knight, what's up?''
</P>
<P>
   But Brand stressed that the incident with Harvey was just one of
many transgressions by Knight since the university gave him an
ultimatum last May to control his behavior or face dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   On campus Monday, some students expressed anger over Knight's
departure, while others were indifferent or supported Brand's
decision. The ugliness of Sunday night's protests seemed to have
blown over. The campus was full of glum faces and an almost
funereal quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for a campus bus, Micheala Karr, a senior, rolled her
eyes when asked about Knight. ``I didn't come here because of I.U.
basketball,'' she said. ``Anyone who is thinking of leaving I.U.
because of this has whacked-up priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Burton, a graduate student in music, said it was ``time
for Bob Knight to move on, anyway.'' Burton said the protests had
disgusted him. ``That was only a small percentage of the students
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt McGregor, a senior, said a less authoritarian coach might
do a better job. ``President Brand did what he had to do,'' he
said. ``I like Bobby Knight, but I'm not sure we could win a
championship under him in this era.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students said they expected many fans to boycott the
season. ``I think a lot of people are going to protest and not buy
tickets,'' Courtney Clark, a junior, said.
</P>
<P>
   Even students who had protested said they were resigned to
losing the coach. Joe Ryan, a junior, said Knight and the
basketball program were one of the main reasons he had chosen the
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most students realize it is a lost cause,'' Ryan said.
``He is already fired.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Hoosier fans said they felt something irretrievably
precious had been lost. ``Bobby Knight is like a god here,'' said
Ian Kara Novich, who described himself as a lifelong Hoosier
fanatic. ``It's not going to be the same.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
