<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-ROCKER0912-COX     09-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quietly, Rocker putting together a solid season
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - In the pro-wrestling dream scenario, John Rocker
spends the 2000 season lifting hitters high over his head and
dumping them at home plate. The umpire declares them down for the
count with a thrust of the right fist, and Rocker gets to growl at
his detractors, his fans and anyone else who can't seem to turn
away.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocker could not stage his baseball season. The reality made
him far from a superhero responding to his infamous Sports
Illustrated story. Instead, it hurt his accuracy with the baseball,
sent him to the minors briefly and split a callous on his thumb.
Now, though, it's September, and Rocker is back to saving the day.
He is throwing strikes, dominating hitters and giving the Braves
the security of facing the Mets six times in their last 19 games
with their closer back. Since Aug. 15, Rocker is six for six in
save opportunities. He now has 20 saves, 10th in the National
League, despite just two each in June and July. And his control
problems finally have subsided. He walked 10 batters in seven
innings over his first eight appearances of August, but in nine
outings since Aug. 16 he hasn't walked anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's throwing strikes again,'' Bobby Cox said. ``His
fastball's clicking, and his curve is good at times. When both are
going, he's almost unhittable, like Randy Johnson. He's working
himself into that form.'' Pitching coach Leo Mazzone points to an
adjustment Rocker made after a film session the two had several
weeks ago. They looked at video of his delivery from this time last
year and compared it with his delivery in early August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, he was much more relaxed on the back side of his
delivery,'' Mazzone said. ``This year, he'd been much more tense.
That's a result of trying to make a pitch do more than you can,
throw harder than you can, throw a breaking ball sharper than you
can and have better control than you have. It takes away from
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker thinks a lot of it has to do with the healing of his
callous and the resulting regular work on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I would make an adjustment within a couple days.
This year, it's been a gradual thing,'' said Rocker, whose ERA is
down to 3.30. ``I'm fixing it piece by piece. ... I'm still on the
verge of having an extremely solid year. (If I end up with) 25
saves and a 2.90 ERA and the team wins, it can still be a very good
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker estimates that 80 percent of his challenge has been
mechanical and 20 percent mental.
</P>
<P>
   What has gotten him through that 20 percent? ``Just time,''
Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who has helped him the most, Rocker said it has been
his girlfriend, Staci Sutton, daughter of Don Sutton, the TBS
broadcaster and Hall of Fame pitcher. She has been his ``sounding
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Braves' trip to New York in late June, the media crush
that was Rockermania has died down. He has managed to keep himself
out of the spotlight, with the exception of St. Louis, where he was
filmed bumping into a local TV cameraman, a move he said later was
unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been more careful,'' Brian Jordan said. ``As far as
changing much, not really. We know (the media attention) will flare
up again when we're in New York. We think and hope he's learned
from all he's been through, the struggles he's had. He's finally
started to calm down and pitch the way he's capable of pitching.
We're all just hoping that little reality check will keep him
grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker takes credit for the quiet, given his pattern of telling
most members of the media to ``beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened because I've made it happen,'' he said. ``I'll
blow everybody off.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has focused on blowing the baseball past hitters,
such as the Diamondbacks' Greg Colbrunn, who faced him in Arizona
when Rocker was struggling last month and again ast week when
Rocker saved his 19th game to keep Tom Glavine a winner over Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a lot of strikes (this time),'' Colbrunn said. ``When
a guy throws that hard and has that quality of stuff with good
control, he's one of the toughest pitchers to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   With two runners on, Rocker threw nine pitches to Colbrunn, only
one of which was out of the strike zone. Colbrunn fouled off
several before finally putting a ball in play to the left side of
the mound. Rocker came down off the mound, smothered the ball,
wheeled and fired to first to end the inning on the defensive play
of the night. He let out a roar Braves fans had not heard in a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how I got there, or what I had to go through, I
just expect to get there,'' Rocker said. ``I'm not going to fall
back on excuses. The way this team works, it's so focused on
winning, it's tough to excuse a guy's personal life for why he's
not performing on the field. You get paid to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to enjoy playing more again. Before, I was just
trying to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
