<HEADER>
A9384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS12-COX     09-11 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defensive faces makeover
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired after arriving home about 2 a.m. Monday, Falcons coach Dan
Reeves had no more answers than a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But the goals are clear: Rectify and simplify after Sunday's
42-14 thrashing in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (1-1) play at Carolina (1-1) Sunday, the first of
four consecutive games against opponents either vastly improved or
world champions.
</P>
<P>
   After the Panthers, the Falcons are home against the Super Bowl
champion Rams (2-0). Then, they play at Philadelphia (1-1), home
against the Giants (2-0), and then at St. Louis (2-0).
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two weeks are really crucial, with Carolina and St.
Louis being two (NFC West) division games,'' Reeves said. ``We
didn't expect to go undefeated.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody expected the Falcons to lose so decisively in Reeves'
return to Denver, where he coached from 1981-92.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta trailed 10-0 with 7 minutes, 14 seconds left in the
first quarter, 13-0 with 1:42 left in the period and 20-0 with
12:14 left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Only a 100-yard kickoff return by rookie cornerback Darrick
Vaughn shortly before halftime brought Atlanta to within 34-7.
Atlanta was outgained 291-42 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   A defense ranked No. 26 in the NFL, not including the Monday
night game, is giving up 73 yards and 35 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a huge hole that we couldn't get out of,''
Reeves said. ``Why? I wish I had the answers. My experience on
defense is if you aren't getting the execution, you better pull
back and start doing less things.''
</P>
<P>
   So defensive coordinator Rich Brooks will pull in the reins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're making too many mistakes,'' Brooks said.
``There are some busted assignments, but the major concern is when
you make as many mistakes as we do, you've got to figure you've got
to simplify it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons weren't much better on offense. The Broncos sacked
quarterback Chris Chandler six times. Chandler completed 9 of 22
passes for 128 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Falcons pointed to 1998, when the Falcons took a 2-0
record to San Francisco, fell behind 28-7 in the first half, and
lost 31-20. That team won 12 of its final 13 games, and went to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Other successful turnarounds have come after blowout losses. In
1989, the Steelers lost 51-0 to Cleveland and 41-10 to Cincinnati.
Then, Pittsburgh won 10 of 14, won a playoff game and then lost
24-23 at Denver to Reeves' Broncos who went to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has happened a lot of times, but that doesn't mean it is
going to happen,'' Reeves said. ``We got beat, and hopefully we
will learn from it and re-dedicate and come back out this week and
play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
