<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SELMA-ELECTION12-COX     09-11 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-ELECTION12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bitter history shadows Selma mayoral vote today
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, ALA. _ Nearly every day since August, retired department
store clerk Lillie Brown has stood on street corners waving her
campaign sign _ ``Joe Gotta Go!'' _ while yelling at motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honk if Joe's gotta go!'' the 69-year-old hollers from the
brick and concrete sidewalks of downtown. A cacophony of car horns
beep back.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is 70-year-old Joe T. Smitherman, Selma's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the former segregationist faces a runoff for the first
time in his 36 years in office. If he loses, Smitherman will be
replaced by the city's first-ever black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The former washing machine salesman has held office since 1964 _
one year before Bloody Sunday, a galvanizing day in the civil
rights movement when state troopers on horseback beat marchers on
the Edmund Pettus Bridge who were demanding voting rights for
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the wrong side,'' Smitherman said, while
chain-smoking a pack of Winstons in his City Hall office, his back
to a cabinet holding an antique cash register, a 1996 Olympic torch
and a houndstooth hat like that worn by legendary Alabama football
coach Bear Bryant. His transformation is authentic, Smitherman
said. Just witness his friendship with Rep. John Lewis, a civil
rights leader branded an outside agitator in the 1960s who now is a
congressman from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Without the calamitous past, Smitherman said his is just another
mayor's race in a middle-of-nowhere city of 22,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selma's a catchy name, and everybody lays the sins of the
nation at Selma's footsteps as far as segregation and voting and
brutality and all of that, when most of that happened in
Birmingham, Montgomery or Mississippi,'' Smitherman said. ``We had
one instance that was outside the city and that was with state
troopers and sheriff's deputies, no city police. And guess who gets
blamed? Me.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Walking With the Wind,'' Lewis' memoir of the civil rights
movement, the congressman writes that the Smitherman of the 1960s
``had to please everyone. And so he wasn't above calling Dr. King
`Martin Luther Coon,' then chuckling at his slip of the tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman has stayed in office because he is adept at floating
with the political current, said Auburn University-Montgomery
political science professor Carl Grafton
</P>
<P>
   ``He's first and foremost a politician. Like George Wallace,''
Grafton said. ``Like George Wallace, they were what they were at
the time. To know whether they've changed deep down in their
hearts, there's no way to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own reckoning, Smitherman will be the last white mayor
the city will ever see.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bloody Sunday, blacks have forged a voting majority in the
city, on the City Council and on the County Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the national office of the NAACP set up a ``Voter
Empowerment Command Center'' near the foot of the Edmund Pettus
Bridge. Other activists from across the country are expected to
arrive today.
</P>
<P>
   Selma had 10,000 white voters and 300 black voters when
Smitherman was first elected in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a hill to climb. I've got to get black voters,'' said
Smitherman, who counts 9,300 active black voters and 5,700 active
white voters in Selma. ``And I've got black workers out trying to
get black voters, mainly through the absentee (ballots), because a
lot of them are intimidated when they go to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, one of those beaten on the bridge 35 years ago, is among
those hoping today's election ousts Smitherman and replaces him
with black computer consultant James Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lord. If that were to happen I know I would be singing
Alleluia, Alleluia, Alleluia,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, 47, has lost two previous elections to Smitherman. In
this year's four-man August primary, Perkins actually led
Smitherman before absentee ballots delivered the incumbent a
276-vote plurality.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of change works against him, Perkins said, even
though 60 percent of Selma's population is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can find comfort in oppression as long as they're
comfortable,'' Perkins said. ``The concept of change is a scary
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to rally behind a single candidate, blacks have been
unable to knock Smitherman from power despite becoming a majority
of the population in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Selma City Council President Pro Tem Yusuf Salaam, who is black,
received 11 percent of the primary vote. Since then, the Muslim has
accused Perkins of being disrespectful toward his faith. In ads,
Perkins has underscored his Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman says he needs to win only 400 of Salaam's 1,021
primary votes to secure another victory.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Smitherman has hosted a fish fry complete with beer.
Perkins supporters claim the barbecues and booze target poor,
uneducated black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who will sell their vote for a fish sandwich is
outrageous,'' said Brown, the campaigner with the ``Gotta Go''
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have fired charges and countercharges of vote fraud
and intimidation. Perkins supporters say their voters have been
offered up to $50 for absentee votes in favor of Smitherman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens in every election,'' Smitherman said. ``Tell
(Perkins) he's got a legitimate choice _ challenge the election,
challenge the vote, whatever. I've got the same charges against
him. They ride around with bullhorns, screaming at my workers and
intimidating them. Same difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman's campaign literature boldly asks ``Why Change?'' His
newspaper-size ad shows nine of 13 city department heads _
including the chief of police _ are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made some black friends through the years, obviously
through some of these appointments,'' Smitherman said
matter-of-fatly.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is frustrated that his issues of economic development
and improved education have been sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   A car with ``Joe Gotta Go'' bumper stickers was found burning at
the law office parking lot of Rose Sanders, a black attorney in
Selma and an activist noted for her strident rebukes of Smitherman.
</P>
<P>
   Smitherman said he ran for re-election because he didn't want
the city run behind the scenes by Sanders, partner in the largest
black law firm in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Grafton said Sanders is an easy target for Smitherman. Sanders
became an active campaigner for the New South Coalition, an
election machine created by Richard Arrington, the first black
mayor of Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, whose office is decorated with a picture of Nation of
Islam leader Louis Afrikaans, once charged the Southern Poverty Law
Center in Montgomery _ a civil rights organization known for
fighting white supremacist groups _ with racist hiring policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose Sanders is a polarizing figure,'' Grafton said.
``(Smitherman's) almost running against her. She's an abrasive,
radical kind of person.''
</P>
<P>
   A block from the Edmund Pettus Bridge, Brown, the retired store
clerk, recalls the day she was trampled by a state trooper's horse.
She is cheered by the prospect of removing from office a lingering
reminder of that day, but she knows there are no guarantees. ``If
we don't get him now, he might stay there for another 30 years,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
