<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SPACEWALK-HNS &LR;      09-11 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEWALK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX-HOUR SPACEWALK PREPARES POWER, COMMUNICATIONS FOR SPACE
STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Spacewalkers Ed Lu and Yuri Malenchenko floated
outside the international space station on Monday, stringing power
and communications cables and zipping through other tasks intended
to ready the orbital outpost for its first resident crew in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour outing marked only the fifth time that an American
astronaut and a Russian cosmonaut have strolled in space together.
</P>
<P>
   Lu, 37, an astrophysicist, and Malenchenko, 38, a Russian Air
Force officer, made it seem like it had never been any other way.
Wearing puffy spacesuits and loaded down with an assortment of
tools, they made their way more than 110 feet from the airlock of
the shuttle Atlantis along the uneven hull of the space station.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis and its crew of five Americans and two Russian arrived
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spacewalk went very well,'' said NASA's Mike Hess, who
planned Monday's excursion and monitored its progress from the
Johnson Space Center in Houston. ``I think we've made a lot of
headway in working together on the international space station.
This is the harbinger of things to come, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the Atlantis crew members planned to board the
station for the first time since their arrival, and make their way
through a dozen air tight hatches to reach its most distant point.
</P>
<P>
   Still early in its development, the outpost spans more than 140
feet and includes three major modules. Its latest addition, the
Russian-built Zvezda crew module, arrived in July. More than two
years overdue because of Russian economic difficulties, Zvezda
furnished the living and working space for a crew of three that
made future assembly possible.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing 42,000 pounds, Zvezda was too massive to be launched
with all of its life support systems in place. They followed in an
unmanned Progress cargo capsule that is parked temporarily at one
end of the new module.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis skipper Terry Wilcutt and his crew will spend this week
transferring systems that generate and recycle air, a toilet and
other equipment from the Progress to Zvezda. They will haul large
power storage batteries, an exercise bicycle and treadmill from the
shuttle's cargo hold into the new module as well.
</P>
<P>
   The work will prepare the station for the arrival of American
commander Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko and Sergei
Krikalev within two months. Their four-month stay is intended to
kick off at least a decade of permanent staffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of work to do,'' said Milt Heflin, NASA's
mission operations director. ``Basically, it's a cabin we have that
we are trying to get furnished and move into. There is a tremendous
amount of coordination required between now and the end of the
flight to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew is conserving electrical power so that mission
managers can extend its visit from Saturday to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Lu and Malenchenko established a fast pace for their colleagues,
finishing Monday's spacewalk 14 minutes early.
</P>
<P>
   Their most important task was the linking of nine utility cables
between Zvezda and Zarya, the propulsion module launched in
November 1998 to initiate the station's construction.
</P>
<P>
   The cabling will permit future exchanges of solar generated
electrical power between the station's U.S. and Russian segments.
It will permit station crews to observe activities in remote
modules over a closed circuit television system. The work will
enable astronauts and cosmonauts flexibility in their choice of
wearing U.S. or Russian spacesuits and using Russian or American
airlocks for future spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   At the most distant point of their spacewalk, Lu and Malenchenko
erected a six-foot mast and equipped it with a magnetometer, a
guidance device. By sensing the Earth's magnetic field, the
instrument enables the station's flight computers to point the
station correctly as it orbits the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Lu also released a no longer needed docking target that had
become an obstruction to future spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Monday, NASA towed the shuttle Discovery to a coastal
launching pad at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively scheduled for an Oct. 5 liftoff, Discovery will
carry a crew of seven to the station to deliver the first segment
of external truss and four large gyroscopes that are part of the
station's future steering system. The truss will serve as the base
for a large solar power generation module that the shuttle
Endeavour will deliver in late November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
