<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite Cunningham's strong performance, Aikman still Dallas
starter
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas - One day after reserve quarterback Randall
Cunningham's terrific performance in a 32-31 loss to Arizona, Coach
Dave Campo stressed that Troy Aikman is still the starter for the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it very clear that Troy is our starting
quarterback if he's ready to go,'' Campo said at his Monday press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham made a legitimate bid to become the starter by
hitting on 24 of 34 passes for 243 yards and three touchdowns
against a patched-up Arizona defense. The entire offense, however,
played poorly in the final five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona overcame an eight-point deficit in the fourth quarter.
The final blow was Arizona quarterback Jake Plummer's 17-yard
scoring strike to David Boston with 1 minute, 54 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The scars of this loss were much deeper than the scars inflicted
in the opening-day loss to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Campo heard a familiar tune in closing minutes Sunday. Last year
the Cowboys lost five games when they led in the fourth quarter.
The emergence of a second-string quarterback did not offset the
pain of going 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with what Randall did, but we didn't win the
football game,'' he said. ``My happiness (over Cunningham's game)
is tempered by the result. I think we have two winners here. I've
been here 12 years, and Troy won 90 games in the '90s, the most any
quarterback has had in any decade. Let's not forget that. Troy is
our guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham accepted Campo's decision, saying, ``I pray there's
not a controversy or anything like that. We need unity on this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cunningham's success came against an Arizona defense
missing two key players. All-Pro cornerback Aeneas Williams
(bruised left thumb) missed the second half, and starting
cornerback Tom Knight (sprained knee) also missed much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman reluctantly missed Sunday's game after suffering his
ninth career concussion in the loss to Philadelphia. It is unclear
whether Aikman will be ready for Monday night's game in Washington,
though Campo said he hopes to make a decision on Aikman's status by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On the injury front, middle linebacker Dat Nguyen has a sprained
medial collateral ligament in his right knee and will miss two to
four weeks. His spot will be taken by Barron Wortham, who played in
the Super Bowl this year with Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Campo's biggest concern is improving a defense that gave up 243
yards passing Sunday. Two of the biggest plays of the game were a
37-yard pass-interference call on rookie cornerback Kareem
Larrimore and Boston's 63-yard catch and run against cornerback
Phillippi Sparks on Arizona's game-winning march.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer used a play-action fake, rolled to his right and
connected with Boston on the right sideline. Sparks tussled with
Boston before finally knocking the receiver down at the Cowboys'
22.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks admitted he made a mistake. ``I fell for (Plummer's)
fake, went for the fake, and made a terrible play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Campo described Larrimore as a ``neophyte,'' someone who ``will
have to improve under fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
