<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-MONTENGRO-ART-2T     09-11 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-MONTENGRO-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-ELECTION OF YUGOSLAVIA'S MILOSEVIC MAY HELP DRIVE MONTENEGRO'S
INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ The Clinton administration says it
worries that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia might move
against Montenegro before or after Yugoslav federation elections
scheduled for Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   But in the small republic itself, where Montenegro's president,
Milo Djukanovic, has decided to boycott the elections, there is
less concern. The current situation seems to serve both Milosevic
and Djukanovic, with the boycott protecting the Montenegrin's
political base while effectively handing Milosevic control over the
new federal Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, a Milosevic understudy who broke with the master and
turned toward the West in 1997, spurned efforts by Washington to
get him to take part.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that his coalition, optimistically named For a Better
Life, might break apart, and that to have the vote would legitimize
constitutional changes that Milosevic rammed through without
consulting Montenegro, Serbia's sister republic in what remains of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic also rejected an American proposal that he run
candidates for the federal Parliament _ even if they vowed not to
serve _ to deny Milosevic an easy victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Djukanovic is afraid of a vote,'' one American
diplomat said. ``He's putting his own interests in Montenegro ahead
of the larger interest, which is to defeat Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, says Drasko Djuranovic, the editor of the independent
weekly Monitor, Djukanovic is betting on Milosevic's remaining in
power, which is likely to produce an independent Montenegro in the
next few years _ the same bet being made by Kosovo's Albanian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic is beaten by the candidate of Serbia's democratic
opposition, Vojislav Kostunica, it will be harder to get Western
support for the further breakup of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kostunica wins, he will offer a decent deal to
Montenegro,'' said Zoran Predic, an editor with the private
television station Elmag. ``If Milosevic disappears, the world's
interest in Milo Djukanovic will also disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Milosevic ``doesn't need a war after the
elections, but a better position for negotiations with the West,''
suggested Ranko Krivokapic, a leader of an independence-minded
party in Djukanovic's coalition. ``He may use Montenegro as a
bargaining chip.''
</P>
<P>
   If the point of the early election is to give Milosevic new
legitimacy, Krivokapic noted, Milosevic would be foolish to throw
it away again by moving openly against Montenegro. The ``American
panic is a bit overblown,'' Krivokapic said. ``The Americans are
more worried about their own elections than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``this is the Balkans and everything is possible,'' he
said. ``Milosevic could need a crisis, even before the election,
and he could decide to do something in just a few days. Everything
is prepared for various options.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is much talk here of the Seventh Battalion of the Yugoslav
Army, about 700 men who seem more like paramilitaries and who, it
is thought, could help provoke civil strife, providing a pretext
for the overthrow of Djukanovic without triggering an overt Western
military response.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milic, an adviser to Djukanovic, said Milosevic ``could
seem completely clean'' and say: ``It's those crazy Montenegrins.
We haven't sent a tank or a plane, so let me see what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Predic, from the independent television station, said the
problem was that ``a significant minority here is fanatically
pro-Milosevic, and another part that hates him wants to stay with
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A referendum for independence remains too risky, said
Djuranovic, the newspaper editor. ``Here in the Balkans the
question isn't the opinion of the majority,'' he said. ``It's what
the minority with guns will do, when they have the support of
another country.''
</P>
<P>
   While Djukanovic's government has officially discouraged the
state media from reporting on the campaign, the president is
allowing Montenegrins to vote in the election, trying to avoid an
open conflict with the 35 percent to 40 percent of the population
that favors unity with Serbia. Nor is Djukanovic pressing for an
early referendum on Montenegrin independence, a vote that would by
itself create security risks and more vividly display the
republic's divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Filip Vujanovic is accustomed to dancing around
the question. ``We need to be very patient and careful, and a
referendum should be taken as a last resort,'' he said in an
interview. But if Milosevic wins, as Vujanovic is convinced he
will, by manipulation if necessary, ``he will continue his
destructive approach to Montenegro,'' he said. ``That's why if he's
elected, in the next four years Montenegro will be at one point
forced to ask the citizens for their answer in a referendum. But
it's not our political decision to do it immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't willingly leave office,'' Vujanovic said of
Milosevic, ``and then the Serbian people and the international
community must work to push him out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody in Montenegro is against Milosevic. In Herceg
Novi, a coastal town that voted out Djukanovic's coalition in local
elections this summer, opting instead for the pro-Belgrade
Socialist People's Party, there is skepticism about Djukanovic's
real aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to get the names of the people who vote in the
election, because every vote is like a vote to keep Yugoslavia
together,'' said 50 year-old Jovan, providing only one name, who
said he intends to vote, but for the Serbian opposition candidate,
Kostunica. ``I worry about my pension.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is divided, and Djukanovic's party and coalition are
divided, said Zeljko Ivanovic, editor of the independent daily
Vijesti. ``It's why Milosevic can sit and laugh. Whatever he's done
to Montenegro, they just issue a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Djukanovic wants independence, Ivanovic said: ``It's clear.
He needs to be able to say, `With Milosevic still in Serbia, we
have no other option.'''
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic is simply being prudent, trying not to give Belgrade
a pretext to provoke a civil war. In the meantime, Montenegro is
building the institutions of statehood, including a banking system
and an army.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the presence of the Yugoslav Army, pressure from
Belgrade includes a blockade of trade, which cuts off Montenegro
from Serbia's price-controlled food and other products, and forces
it to try to export abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's turn to the German mark as its currency has
protected it from the deflation of the Yugoslav dinar, but it has
also made prices more expensive and led to louder grumbling from
the many unemployed in this republic of just 650,000 people. And
not all of the jobless can work in Montenegro's thriving black and
gray economy, where smuggling goods to and from Italy is a way of
life.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are so many stolen cars in Montenegro _ or cars bought
cheaply in Europe and driven here, then declared stolen by their
owners _ that the joke goes: ``Come and visit Montenegro. We have
your car here waiting for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's limbo as a quasi-nation-state _ an independently
minded part of Yugoslavia _ has meant that it cannot get direct aid
from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund. But because
it is perceived as a bulwark against Belgrade, Montenegro does get
millions of dollars in government aid from Europe and the United
States to cover its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   As many as half of Montenegro's salaried workers are paid by the
state, including the large regular and special police forces, with
their new white Land Rovers, who number up to 30,000 men and have
been built up, in part by trainers from Western armies, to counter
the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   There is little international oversight of how the foreign money
is spent, said Arne Jan Flolo of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe. Everyone agrees that the privatization of
government-run enterprises is anything but transparent or clean.
</P>
<P>
   There is currently a fight within the governing party over a
fuzzy contract with the French hotel chain Accor to manage
Montenegro's nicest seaside hotels.
</P>
<P>
   One huge aluminum plant, with all of its associated industries,
represents half of Montenegro's gross domestic product, and much of
the profit goes to a Swiss holding company that provided loans in
1998 _ a contract that Washington and the aluminum company itself
seemed to be quietly trying to cancel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption is a time bomb ticking under the Djukanovic
government,'' Flolo said. ``But the West doesn't want to hear about
it. The international community is making a big mistake by not
attaching conditions to its aid and letting this go on so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebojsa Medojevic, an economist, is a Djukanovic critic: ``The
line here is that if you criticize Djukanovic you help Milosevic.
It creates space for manipulation and is an excellent pretext to
postpone any real economic reform. The problem is that the
international community supports Djukanovic without reservation,
despite dirty privatization and corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Flolo said: ``There are free and fair elections here, but there
is little transparency of decision-making. There is democracy from
a distance, but you dig and there's a long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
