<SLUG> BC-MA-MEDICAID-BOOSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE COSTS COULD QUADRUPLE FOR SOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dramatically demonstrating that health-care costs are
climbing despite managed care, HMOs will hit senior citizens with
the largest premium increases ever next year and, in some areas,
will quadruple their monthly out-of-pocket payments.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Medicare program, which is expected to approve 2001
premiums this week, was not expected to release the numbers until
Saturday. But in Massachusetts word of extra-strength increases
began to seep out over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The four Massachusetts health-maintenance organizations that
insure most seniors _ Tufts Health Plan, Harvard Pilgrim Health
Care, Fallon Community Health Plan, and Blue Cross's HMO Blue _
will all begin charging monthly premiums or will raise existing
fees, the insurers confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While most HMOs will charge between $25 and $45, Blue Cross will
raise its $25-per-month premium to $85, $95, or $105 depending on
the county. Seniors at all HMOs will be charged co-payments for
prescription drugs and visits to the doctor _ if they can still see
their doctor at all. Some senior citizens will be forced to change
doctors because their HMO will pull out of some counties Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross Executive Vice President Peter Meade said the company
will lose more than $15 million this year on its Medicare HMO,
called Blue Care 65, because of low payments from the federal
government and climbing drug costs. Executives decided the best way
to break even in 2001 was to raise premiums. Medicare, the federal
health insurance program for the elderly, pays HMOs fixed amounts
to insure senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The only other options, he said, were to cancel the program
entirely in some counties, or to cut payments to the hospitals and
doctors who treat its members _ and risk them turning away Blue
Care 65 members. ``We decided we want a stable provider network,''
Meade said.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential candidates debating the best way to help
senior citizens pay for expensive prescription drugs, some saw the
premium increases as evidence for immediate action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to hurt some people, there's no question about
it,'' said Geoff Wilkinson, executive director of Massachusetts
Senior Action Council. ``It's pretty clear that restructuring
Medicare to provide lots of little options in the private sector is
not going to work. That's not a viable model.''
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed out that the price increases hitting the elderly
are a warning for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Premiums for employer-provided health insurance rose 8.3 percent
nationally during the last year, the largest increase since 1993,
according to a survey by the Kaiser Family Foundation. But because
employers are so desperate for workers, most were reluctant to pass
the cost onto their employees and ended up shouldering the burden
instead.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the economy slows down, employers are expected to
start shifting health insurance costs back to their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, higher health-insurance premiums are chipping away
company profits and are a reminder that no matter what they
originally promised, HMOs can no longer be counted on to hold down
the nation's soaring medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The late 1990s were the go-go years for Medicare HMOs,'' said
Tricia Neuman, a vice president with Kaiser. ``They were free to
seniors. The benefits were generous. We did focus groups and the
seniors said, `This is too good to be true.' Well Congress decided
it was too good.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Congress passed the Balanced Budget Act, which reduced
Medicare payments to HMOs by $22 million over the last three years,
according to the American Association of Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, HMOs nationwide have pulled out of the Medicare
program, dropping 727,000 seniors citizens in the last two years
and announcing plans to drop another 125,000 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Health Care Financing Administration, which runs
Medicare and pays health insurers to provide HMO plans to senior
citizens, has said that a federal prescription-drug benefit would
help ease the crunch. Presidential candidates Al Gore and George W.
Bush both have plans to expand drug coverage but disagree on just
how to do that, with Gore including a subsidy for medications
through Medicare, and Bush favoring private-sector competition.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Fallon, Harvard Pilgrim, and United Health
Plans all plan to pull out of certain counties on Jan. 1 where they
say they are losing money. Harvard Pilgrim is leaving Barnstable,
Bristol, Plymouth and Worcester counties, while Fallon is leaving
Essex and Suffolk. Senior citizens in those counties can enroll in
another Medicare HMO, or opt for a traditional fee-for-service
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross, which enrolls 32,000 Medicare clients in its HMO,
will remain in all 11 counties where it's developed provider
networks _ a decision that advocates such as Wilkinson applaud.
</P>
<P>
   The insurer will increase its annual prescription-drug benefit
from $500 to $600, and pay $150 a year toward health-club
membership. But Blue Cross will introduce office visit, emergency
room and prescription drug co-payments of between $5 and $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not cavalier about the difficulties that seniors are
facing across the country,'' Meade said. ``But we want fees that
reflect the cost of providing service. These kind of prices are
happening everywhere in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim is reducing its annual drug benefit from $800 to
$600, and eliminating its Medicare dental benefit in the counties
where it will continue to do business _ Essex, Middlesex, Norfolk,
and Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts, which as the state's largest Medicare HMO provides
coverage to 101,000 seniors with Secure Horizons, is also adopting
or raising premiums. Tufts will also reduce its prescription drug
benefit, which will remain at $600 a year, but current co-payments
will buy a 30-day, rather than a 90-day, supply of medication.
</P>
<P>
   Secure Horizons, however, is facing difficult contract
negotiations with hospitals, eight of which have told the HMO they
will leave the Medicare network if they don't receive better rates
next year.
</P>
<P>
   That means seniors could be faced with a difficult choice:
paying a higher premium for Blue Care 65 or finding a new hospital
or doctor with Secure Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   As tough as it was, Joan Mahoney, 72, of Chatham, chose the
latter. When Harvard Pilgrim told her its Medicare HMO, First
Seniority, would no longer be offered in Barnstable County as of
Jan. 1, she switched to Secure Horizons _ even though it meant
leaving the oncology team at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center
that first diagnosed and treated her uterine cancer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Secure Horizons requires members to be treated within 30 miles
of their homes. ``It was a blow,'' she said. ``I had to say goodbye
to all my doctors. But maybe it's a blessing in disguise. I won't
have to drive as far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
