<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT &LR;      09-11 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY MANHATTAN, TOMORROW TASHKENT, NEXT WEEK THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marat Safin rubbed his glassy hazel eyes Monday
afternoon, attacked by a barrage of flashbulbs for what seemed like
the four billionth time since he won the U.S. Open only 17 hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Moscow native leaned in front of a model Kremlin
on the fourth floor of the Russian Tea Room, grinning with his
trophy for a dozen jostling photographers. Moments before, he stood
outside with three giddy middle-aged women holding Metropolitan
Museum of Art bags, obliging their tourist cameras. He had put his
arms up, striking a ``Marat Takes Manhattan'' pose in front of a
taxi, at the driver's request.
</P>
<P>
   Safin's day began only an hour after he went to sleep, the
euphoria from winning his first Grand Slam title almost immediately
mixed in with the heaping obligations. He was afraid to drink
coffee before appearing on CNN Live at 9 a.m, for fear the vodka
still churning in his system would not appreciate such a wake-up
call.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after taping the Charlie Rose show and an MSNBC program,
Safin was gulping caffeinated soda at the Russian Tea Room, picking
at the smoked fish and avoiding the borscht. After posing with four
waiters in costume, Safin finally sighed. ``Please! Make it fast,''
he exclaimed. ``I cannot smile so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Flexing his mouth muscles Monday seemed more difficult, and
lasted longer, than his improbable straight-sets victory over the
esteemed Pete Sampras. Safin could not explain why he dominated the
winner of 13 Grand Slam titles, and he was still unable to
comprehend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't let me,'' he said. ``I need time, at least one
day, to be alone with my friends. I need time to understand what I
did. Right now, this is my job, but I hope I will have time to talk
with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not the only 20-year-old wishing to do so Monday. Venus
Williams, the U.S. Open women's champion who won her second
straight Grand Slam event, was caught in a similar whirlwind,
appearing on three morning shows, and running to appearances before
flying back home to Florida. Tuesday she leaves for the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Williams was chatty with President Clinton on Saturday,
Safin spoke with his new friend by phone Sunday, only a day after
he was honored to meet him in person at Arthur Ashe Stadium. The
Russian president. Vladimir Putin, chipped in with his wired
congratulations Monday. ``A new tennis star has risen,'' he said in
his message.
</P>
<P>
   When Safin finally left the National Tennis Center Sunday, he
went to a dinner at Serafina in Manhattan, followed by the SoHo
club 357, where he met the singer Lenny Kravitz. Monday at 5 p.m.,
Safin taped the ``Late Show With David Letterman'' before taking a
9 p.m. plane to Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievably, Safin has to be back on the court Wednesday in
Tashkent, Uzbekistan, for a tournament to which he committed three
months ago. ``He made an agreement. You have to be professional,''
said his agent, Gerard Tsbobanian. ``It has to be this way now.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin vaulted to No. 2 in the world and has expectations and
responsibilities. He began to realize them this spring, when he
became more disciplined in his practices (leaving the cell phone
behind) and more concentrated, for the most part, on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Already, said Sampras, Safin is more powerful than he was when
he won his first U.S. Open at 19. But Sampras also cautioned that
Safin had to choose to become a legendary champion or just a
one-hit wonder. Safin's advisers, most recently Aleksandr Volkov,
have issued such warnings and Safin knows his duty.
</P>
<P>
   After Tashkent, Safin goes to Sydney to compete in the Olympics
for Russia. Then, he will return home to Monte Carlo, where Safin
hopes his friends will take him out to celebrate, at least when he
is not reflecting on his achievement.
</P>
<P>
   His apartment has no stunning view of the Mediterranean Sea,
though. ``It's a wall. I will change that,'' Safin said, this time
with a real grin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
