<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT12-COX     09-11 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feelings at IU mixed over Knight's departure
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. _ Clad in a red T-shirt bearing the name and
likeness of Bob Knight, Deanna Fry literally was wearing her heart
on her sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a member of the family died,'' the
20-year-old Indiana University senior said Monday. ``One of the
reasons I came to IU was Indiana basketball and coach Knight. I
almost feel betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeri Ryerson, also 20, took the polar-opposite view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some students may think it's a tragedy, but everyone I know
thinks they should have (fired Knight) years ago, because he's a
big joke,'' Ryerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Knight's 29-year coaching reign ended, he proved
to be controversial as ever, with the campus community deeply
divided in its reaction to his firing by IU President Myles Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Classes on this campus of more than 37,000 students resumed
quietly Monday following the massive protest Sunday by thousands of
students at Brand's house, during which Brand was burned in effigy.
Police in riot gear arrested several students, and there were
sporadic incidents of property damage.
</P>
<P>
   Richard McKaig, vice chancellor and dean of students, said it's
too early to tell whether eight students arrested during the
protest will face university sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think there would be action through the campus
judicial system,'' he said, adding that punishments could range
from ``a reprimand to probation to suspension to expulsion.''
</P>
<P>
   There was scattered property damage _ two decorative
streetlights were destroyed, a goal post at the football field was
pulled down, some parking signs were uprooted and some fish
figurines were removed from a fountain, McKaig said. But no
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the students I talked to made it clear their intent
was not violent,'' McKaig said. ``They wanted to have their voices
heard and show support for coach Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Candice Lowe, a 30-year-old graduate student in
anthropology, was disturbed by the protest and threats against
Brand and Kent Harvey, the 19-year-old student Knight grabbed by
the arm Thursday, the incident that set the stage for the firing.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Knight was fined $30,000 and suspended for three games
because of his temper. He was allowed to keep his job, but ordered
to follow a ``zero-tolerance'' policy, which Brand said Knight has
violated on several occasions since then, most recently when he
grabbed Harvey and gave him a lecture on manners.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who has attended IU for six years, said she first became
concerned about Knight's supporters in May after threats were
directed against members of the committee that disciplined the
coach. The events of recent days were even more disturbing, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supporters treat him like he's some kind of Christ
figure,'' Lowe said. ``It bothers me that people would threaten to
kill Myles Brand and this boy (Harvey) over a basketball coach. It
makes me feel unsafe _ and sad. I thought this was a really open
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight supporter Andy Dammeyer, 23, who participated in the
protest, admitted the threats _ including a poster of Harvey
bearing the words ``Wanted: Dead'' that was circulated on campus _
were ``a little too much.'' But ``it's Indiana basketball _ people
just go crazy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wrong, what they did to the man,'' Dammeyer said
of Knight's firing. ``He's been here 30 years. He should have left
on his own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Dick, a 21-year-old junior, said the offenses that brought
Knight down seemed petty. He said it'll be hard for the university
to fill Knight's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does overreact a lot and he does have a bad temper, but
that's part of what makes him the man he is,'' Dick said. ``They're
going to have to bring in a very respectable, high-rank coach to
get the kind of following that Bob Knight has.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie Schoenbaechler, 18, of Louisville, Ky., described herself
as a lifelong Bob Knight fan, following in the footsteps of her
mother, an IU grad and a ``huge'' fan of Knight. She arrived on
campus Aug.23, and feels cheated by Knight's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my freshman year and I was so excited about seeing Bob
Knight as an IU student,'' she said. ``He has a temper, but he's
such an exciting person to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Several university employees declined to be interviewed Monday
about the firing. ``No comment _ I have to go to work again
tomorrow,'' one employee said.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna Fry thinks there could be some serious fallout from the
firing. Players may leave the team, she said, and some pro-Knight
alumni may withhold contributions to the university. ``Bob Knight
had a lot of clout,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Garrett, 67, is one IU alumnus who won't miss Knight.
Garrett, a Bloomington resident since his college days in the mid
1950s, said a Knightless IU will be an improved IU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for it,'' Garrett said as he pulled a copy of the
Indiana Daily Student, with its ``Knight fired'' banner headline,
from a newspaper box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I despise that son of a gun,'' Garrett said. ``He's a big jerk
as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Tom Beyerlein at tombeyerlein(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
