<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT &LR;      09-11 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY ARRESTED IN TAMPA ON DRIVING VIOLATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, currently suspended from baseball for
violating terms of his drug program and still recovering from
treatment for a cancer relapse, was arrested Monday in Tampa, Fla.,
and charged with reckless driving and leaving the scene of an
accident. It was the latest setback for the 38-year-old Strawberry,
who missed most of last season, has not played this year and no
longer seems to have a viable future as a baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's incident, Strawberry was taken into custody at
gunpoint shortly after 9 a.m. by an off-duty officer who witnessed
Strawberry's sport utility vehicle hit a street sign and then
strike the rear of another SUV stopped for a red light. Strawberry
was being held without bail in Hillsborough County Jail pending a
court hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Sgt. Anthony Kolka, told The Associated Press that
when he confronted Strawberry, with his pistol drawn, he had to
bang on the window of Strawberry's vehicle to get his attention.
</P>
<P>
   Kolka said Strawberry kept asking, ``What did I do? What did I
do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't know he hit the car or the sign,'' Kolka
added. The officer said he drew the gun for ``my own safety and
everybody else's,'' and that he was not initially aware that the
driver was Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ficarrotta, a lawyer for Strawberry, told The AP that
Strawberry had ``blacked out'' while driving because of a reaction
to prescription medication and that when he visited him later in
the day he seemed ``very weak and very tired.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Hillsborough County sheriff's department
said Strawberry told officers he had taken a sleeping medication,
Ambien, and Ficarrotta said Strawberry also has prescriptions for
two painkillers _ Percocet and Vicodin. A blood-alochol test showed
no alcohol in his system; the result of a urine test was not yet
available.
</P>
<P>
   For Strawberry, the bad news has been unrelenting for much of
the past two years. He was suspended from baseball for most of the
1999 season after he pleaded no contest to charges of possession of
cocaine and solicitation of prostitution. He ultimately rejoined
the Yankees near the end of the season and then served as a
designated hitter as the team went on to win its second straight
World Series and its third in four years.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry then flunked an off-season drug test last January
and a month later was suspended from baseball for a full year, his
third suspension for drug use in the last five years. Last month,
Strawberry had surgery for the removal of a stomach tumor, nearly
two years after he had a cancerous mass removed from his colon. In
the latest surgery, one of Strawberry's kidneys was also removed.
</P>
<P>
   News of Monday's incident circulated through the Yankees'
clubhouse Monday afternoon as the team prepared for an evening game
against Boston. Most of the members of the organization did not
know the details of Strawberry's arrest and both Yankees Manager
Joe Torre and Strawberry's longtime teammate, Dwight Gooden,
declined comment. But David Cone, one of the Yankees who visited
Strawberry during his recent hospital stay, was willing to talk
about his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl's been through hell,'' Cone said. ``Obviously, we all
feel for him. It's not easy to go through what he's been through _
coming to the realization that his career is probably over. He's
always had baseball to look forward to, and for the first time in
his life, he doesn't have that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Darryl's probably finally coming to that realization.
I think he had always held out hope that he was coming back.
Baseball was always a motivating factor for him, so I'm quite sure
he's probably as low as he's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he tried to understand the path of Strawberry's life _
from the young baseball star to the troubled addict to Strawberry's
bouts with cancer _ Cone said it would be ``foolish of me to even
try.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back to his background, his upbringing, what
he's had to deal with all the way through, including cancer and a
relapse of cancer and losing his kidney, and all the depression
that comes with that. I think it would be abnormal to think that he
wouldn't have problems, with what he's been through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for the guy,'' Cone said. ``I really do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
