<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-2TAKE     09-11 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN MISTRUST, DOCTORS' PROFITS HINDER MEDICARE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story moved Sept. 10 and was held; it is now released for
publication.) 
 By ROBIN TONER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush confidently proposed last week
that as president he would put an overhaul of Medicare on the
``fast track,'' directing a new White House task force to send
legislation to Congress within nine months to transform the
35-year-old government insurance program into an efficient, largely
private health care marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But many health experts _ and sadder but wiser veterans of past
Medicare wars _ say that the last decade has shown the immense
difficulties in accomplishing such reforms. The philosophical
differences between the two parties over how to reshape Medicare
are large and enduring. Health maintenance organizations and other
managed care insurance plans, which could play a central role in
Bush's proposal, are no longer viewed as an easy cure-all that can
both control health care costs and deliver better care.
</P>
<P>
   And the record of HMOs in the Medicare program has been
particularly rocky, with hundreds of thousands of Medicare
beneficiaries dropped in recent years by health plans complaining
that the government does not pay them enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of HMOs and seniors, and HMOs and very sick
people would leave most analysts cautious about the capacity of the
private sector to care for people who are very sick or very old _
people on whom you might lose money, to put it in the plainest
language I can,'' said Drew Altman, president of the Kaiser Family
Foundation, a health research group.
</P>
<P>
   Altman and others praise Bush for addressing the Medicare issue,
including the need to provide some relief for the cost of
prescription drugs. And many experts agree that Medicare, a program
that was essentially designed in the 1960s, needs to be
reconstructed to reflect the realities of modern medicine _ not to
mention the coming wave of retiring baby boomers, who will double
the number of Medicare beneficiaries in the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore supports a ``modernization'' plan
advanced by the Clinton administration last year, aides say,
although he has focused in his campaign on shoring up the
traditional program and adding a prescription drug benefit to it.
</P>
<P>
   But as is so often the case in health policy debates, the
details of creating a Medicare ``modernized for our times,'' as
Bush puts it, are a matter of intense dispute. ``There's no
consensus view about which direction we should be heading,'' said
John Rother, legislative director for AARP, an advocacy group for
older people.
</P>
<P>
   At its root, the debate over the Bush proposal revolves around
how much Medicare should be turned into a competitive marketplace,
in which beneficiaries are given a fixed amount each year and are
expected to choose among a variety of health plans, much as federal
employees do. Bush is careful to say that the elderly can stay with
the traditional fee-for-service Medicare program if they like, but
critics assert that the traditional program would be inexorably
weakened _ in part because it is likely to retain the frailest and
sickest population.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, partisan mistrust is high. Many Democrats are convinced
that Republicans simply cannot abide a huge, government-run social
insurance program and have always wanted to privatize it. Many
Republicans contend that Democrats are less interested in policy
improvements than in scaring elderly voters every election year
with dire warnings about what the Republicans will do to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Memories are still vivid from the battles of 1995-96, when the
Republicans sought to extract $270 billion in savings from the
Medicare program, and the Democrats used that proposal in a wave of
campaign advertising to devastating effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics are lethal,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., who
led a bipartisan Medicare commission that ended in a deadlock in
early 1999. ``Been there, done that,'' he said of Bush's statement
last week that he would convene another Medicare task force to
draft new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's proposal, the new bipartisan task force would build
on the work done by the earlier commission, considering Bush's own
plan as well as possible improvements. Its recommendation to
Congress would get an expedited final vote by the end of 2001 under
``fast track'' provisions Bush would ask Congress to agree to in
advance, if all went according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's allies assert that the political hurdles can be overcome
with the right leadership in the White House. And they argue that
the real-world problems with Medicare HMOs can be resolved with a
less bureaucratic, heavy-handed approach than the one now exercised
by the Health Care Financing Administration, the federal agency
that oversees Medicare and the HMOs who participate.
</P>
<P>
   The current experience with Medicare HMOs ``is not a good
indicator of potential problems,'' argued Gail Wilensky, a top Bush
health adviser who ran the health care administration under
President George Bush. She said the rules have changed too often,
the regulations are too burdensome and the payment increases to
HMOs are often too low.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is proposing a very different system for private health
plans in Medicare than the one that exists, Wilensky said. ``While
I don't want to pretend that this is going to be easy,'' she added,
``there was a period when many analysts, and members of Congress,
thought the basic idea'' of this proposal ``was something they
could support.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current Medicare system, the government sets prices
and reimburses doctors and hospitals directly for the 33 million
Americans in the traditional Medicare program; for the 6.2 million
elderly Americans who choose HMOs, the government pays their health
plan under a formula established by law.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bush proposal, which Wilensky said is broadly
patterned after the work of the Breaux commission, the traditional
fee-for-service program would be preserved, but it would be
required to compete with other plans.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, beneficiaries would decide how to use their
government-allotted premium. Private plans would, ideally, compete
vigorously for the business; beneficiaries could add their own
money to the government premium and buy more generous benefit
packages. This ability to choose from an array of plans is a major
selling point for the program. But critics assert that under such
systems, the government-allotted premium _ particularly if it is
tied to a national average of bids from the major health plans _
will never keep up with the cost of the traditional Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that would mean is that a lot of beneficiaries would have
to go to managed care because they couldn't afford the premiums of
traditional fee-for-service Medicare,'' said Sarah Bianchi, a Gore
adviser. Wilensky rejected that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   This exchange, though, illustrates the political difficulties of
the Bush approach. while some versions of this competitive model
have support across party lines, some Democrats contend that it
marks a fundamental shift away from the guaranteed benefits, a
35-year-old entitlement, of the Medicare program. Republicans
counter that it would provide Medicare beneficiaries with a range
of new options and benefits _ like a variety of prescription drug
plans _ that the government simply cannot match, while still
guaranteeing every beneficiary a core benefit package.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of the Breaux commission, which is regularly
praised by Bush, is instructive. As a similar proposal took shape
on the commission, the 17-member panel broke down on party lines;
it needed 11 votes to make a formal recommendation. While Bush
often hails the commission's proposal as bipartisan, only two
Democrats on the panel _ Breaux and Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska _
supported it; eight Republicans did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world ought to remember that the bipartisan commission
didn't support it, and the bipartisan support was two Democrats and
eight Republicans,'' said Stuart Altman, a member of the commission
appointed by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Altman of the Kaiser Family Foundation said, ``The reason
it went nowhere is it uncovered all the nerves that divide
Democrats and Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's restructuring proposal also seeks
to encourage more competition among private health plans, but keeps
traditional Medicare out of the competition. In general, Democrats
assert that they have been good stewards of the Medicare program,
noting that its hospital trust fund is projected to be solvent
until 2025. And Gore is campaigning hard on his promise to put
Medicare in a ``lock box'' so that its $400 billion in surpluses
cannot be used for tax cuts or other new spending.
</P>
<P>
   In line with Gore's positioning as the defender of traditional
Medicare, some health advocates expect Gore to pick apart Bush's
plan for Medicare as he picked apart former Sen. Bill Bradley's
health care plan in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare debate, in fact, is infused with the memory of past
health care struggles, including the backlash in recent years to
HMOs and the insurance industry in general, which was immediately
preceded by the backlash toward government stoked by the Clinton
attempt at universal coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dr. Judith Feder, now the dean of policy studies at
Georgetown University, formerly a top Clinton health adviser, said
she found it ironic that Bush would propose another White House
task force, ``given the experience of '93-94.'' She added, ``Surely
that indicates that complex issues are not likely to be dealt with
in a swift way.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if a candidate can survive the election with his health
care proposals intact, Rother of AARP noted, ``People are making so
much money off the health care system that any effort to change it
runs into very well-financed opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
