<HEADER>
A9413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GWBUSH-FLA12-COX     09-11 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GWBUSH-FLA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush tries to gain Florida's 'attention'
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ His campaign in Florida no where near
the sure thing he hoped it would be, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said
Monday he is trying hard ``to gain people's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He did gain the attention of more than a thousand supporters at
Palm Beach International Airport who heard a few quick words from
the Republican presidential nominee before he left for the home of
Bud Paxson founder of the PAX television network. Bush was there to
raise money for the Florida Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew into Clearwater aboard his chartered 757 to begin a
day and half of Florida campaigning. He is courting the older
voters he needs if he is going to stall the rising fortunes of Vice
President Al Gore's campaign in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders here are worried that Bush has not spent
enough time in Florida and that he is losing momentum on key
issues, especially those involving older voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I expect Florida to be a battleground state? No,'' said
U.S. Rep. E. Clay Shaw R-Fort Lauderdale. ``But now it has to be a
battleground.''
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with Florida reporters, Bush said that he has
changed his campaign style so that he is giving shorter speeches
and spending more time answering questions from his audiences. In
Clearwater he answered more than a dozen questions on a wide
variety of topics.
</P>
<P>
   It is an effort to better connect with voters, said Bush.
``People need to hear me answer questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects many voters will tune in to the coming
debates and hat he has already started, ``pepper drills'' with
members of his staff who fire questions at him. He said he would
not contact Gore directly to resolve the remaining issues about the
debates ``because that's best left up to our seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   While winning Florida is going to be tougher than some state
Republican had hoped, Bush said he is convinced that his issues
will click with Florida voters.,
</P>
<P>
   Dangling the promise of lower prescription drug prices, more
flexible Medicare options and guaranteed Social Security payments,
Bush is trying to deflect inroads made by Gore among seniors who
represent a third of Florida's likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to an enthusiastic crowd of more than 300 at the On Top
of the World, retirement community in Clearwater, Bush warned them
to ``ignore the old style politics of fear.'' He said Gore is
trying to scare older voters by telling them that Bush would take
away their Social Security if he became president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't campaign by scaring people and then lead them,''
said Bush. ``I'm the kind of fella who does in office what I said I
was going to do on the campaign trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said if elected he will modernize Medicare giving seniors
more options for their coverage including prescription drug
benefits for low income seniors. During the first four years of his
administration, Bush said he would spend $48 billion to pay the
entire prescription drug cost for low income seniors. Part of the
money would go to all seniors who spend more than $6,000 a year for
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He was cheered by the crowd when he promised to abolish
inheritance taxes which the Republicans call ``death taxes.''
Congress failed last week to override President Clinton's veto of
an inheritance tax repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that Gore has accepted millions of dollars from
Hollywood, Bush said he was skeptical of Gore's recent promise to
use the FCC to force the entertainment industry to reduce the
violence seen by children. Bush said Gore refused to take a stand
on entertainment violence last year ``until now when we're in the
middle of a campaign,''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would push Hollywood producers to stop ``the
pollution of our children's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure about him but after listening to him I'm very
impressed,'' said Millie Turner of Clearwater, a 74-year old
retiree from Michigan. ``I like Jeb and I just think the Bush's are
a very decent family.''
</P>
<P>
   His younger brother said Bush will have to work hard here to win
Florida's 25 electoral votes in the November election. ``I think
he's going to have to make at least three more trips here. That
would be about the right amount,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor will be back in Florida on Sept. 22 with a
stops in Tampa and Miami. Other locations may be added that day,
according to the campaign. His brother said he hopes ``at some
point he won't have to come here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the point where Bush was so far ahead of Gore that
he would be certain of a Florida victory. So far, neither campaign
believes that is likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
