<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GUNS-NYT &LR;      09-11 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA, DESPITE SUPPORT FOR BUSH, REFRAINS FROM OFFICIAL ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defying expectations, the board of the National
Rifle Association declined to endorse Gov. George W. Bush for
president at its final meeting of the year on Saturday. The
development makes it unlikely that Bush will receive the group's
formal approval before Election Day, NRA officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that the rifle association will sit
out the election. Far from it: The association intends to spend
millions of dollars supporting Bush and trying to discredit his
Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, as a threat to gun
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the rifle association said Monday that they did
not want to provide the Democrats new fodder for attacking Bush, so
had decided to withhold a formal endorsement. Polls suggest that
the NRA, while popular in many Republican areas, is viewed
negatively by large numbers of the independent suburban voters whom
Bush is trying to court, particularly women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to do no harm'' to Bush, one NRA official said,
noting that the group was already pouring money into the race to
help the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has had a good working relationship with the rifle
association in Texas. But he has tried to maintain a polite
distance from the group during the campaign and aides said Monday
that Bush had not sought the group's endorsement or its neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has described the rifle association as ``the
Bush gun-policy team'' and has accused Bush of working ``hip
holster to hip holster'' with the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   And Handgun Control Inc. has been running an advertisement in
several swing states featuring a previously disclosed film clip of
Kayne Robinson, an NRA vice president, telling a friendly audience
that if Bush is elected, ``we'll have a president where we work out
of their office.''
</P>
<P>
   Once averse to getting involved in politics, the 129-year-old
rifle association did not begin endorsing presidential candidates
until the 1980s. But since then, it has been solidly in the
Republican camp, endorsing Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984, and
George Bush in 1988. The group did not endorse Bob Dole in 1996,
because of differences on some issues, but it spent millions of
dollars attacking President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sudbay, political director of Handgun Control, said he was
not surprised that the rifle association had not endorsed Bush,
because, ``they've become a real albatross for candidates,''
particularly among women.
</P>
<P>
   Sudbay added that the rifle association did not need to trumpet
its support for Bush because it was already making crystal clear to
its 4 million members _ through speeches by its leaders, Web site
postings and mailings _ that it wants him elected.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rifle association officials said Monday that it would
soon be launching a new round of mailings and, perhaps, television
commercials attacking Gore in several important swing states where
gun ownership is high, including Pennsylvania, Michigan, Missouri
and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Gore of trying to downplay his support for strong gun
laws, the official said, ``The guy's tried to reinvent himself on
our issue since the convention. He makes statements that even I
could agree with about supporting the Second Amendment. But come
on. Look at the record. And we will certainly be reminding our
members of that record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
