<HEADER>
A9418 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-OHIO12-COX     09-11 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OHIO12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, Lieberman to tour Ohio
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMISBURG, Ohio _ National television cameras and presidential
hopefuls will be focused today on the students of Anna K. Wantz
Middle School in Miamisburg as Vice President Al Gore kicks off a
day of campaigning by greeting students and meeting with parents,
children and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic nominee for president, will be accompanied
by his vice presidential pick Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., at
Wantz and two other southwest Ohio campaign stops where they will
speak on education.
</P>
<P>
   Education has been a key issue this campaign for both Gore and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee. Earlier this
year, Gore stayed at the home of a Columbus-area school teacher and
her family and he has toured schools throughout his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At Wantz Middle School, preparations for the visit added to an
already hectic pace of the new school year. School officials have
been juggling having their building searched and secured by Secret
Service agents and preparing for a previously scheduled open house
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The district learned Wednesday Wantz could be the site of a
campaign stop and learned at 2 p.m. Friday it would be the site,
said Wantz Principal Gary Schomburg .
</P>
<P>
   ``From then on it's been non-stop work, frantically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this school, and the district in general, is an
example that you don't have to be the most affluent in the state to
have a high degree of success,'' he added. ``We overachieve what
our economic level would tend to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Wantz was named a National Blue Ribbon School of
Excellence by the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   From Miamisburg, Gore and Lieberman will travel to Middletown
High School where they will have lunch with students and speak
briefly with them.
</P>
<P>
   They finish the southwest Ohio tour with a public rally 2:15
p.m. at Cincinnati State Technical and Community College, 3520
Central Parkway. Tickets for the rally are free and available at
the school's main lobby information desk.
</P>
<P>
   Gore on Monday evening was greeted on his arrival at Dayton
International Airport by the Northmont High School marching band.
The vice president shook hands with students in a crowd of more
than 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me his son plays middle linebacker for his school, and
I told him that's the position I play,'' said Ryan Woodie, a senior
football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the band was really good,'' said Maria Schreel, a
senior flute player who spoke with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the theme of his visit, Gore kept brief his
conversations with the adults in the crowd and instead exchanged
greetings and waves with the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more into the youth,'' said the band director, Reg
Richwind.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's entourage then moved downtown, as he began a night's stay
at the Doubletree Hotel across the street from Dayton's City Hall.
He had no public events scheduled for Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was scheduled to arrive at Dayton International
Airport around 1 a.m. today. The two are expected to greet Wantz
students as the school day begins.
</P>
<P>
   The visit marks the second local stop in a week by the two main
presidential campaigns. Bush spoke to 400 military veterans last
week during a campaign stop at Wright State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were worried we weren't going to see (the candidates) much
in Ohio, but now their practically living here,'' said U.S. Rep.
Tony Hall, D-Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio, with 21 electoral votes, is considered one of a handful of
key battleground states. A statewide mail poll by the Columbus
Dispatch , published this month, showed Bush leading Gore 49
percent to 43 percent, with 5 percent undecided. The margin for
error was plus or minus 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Jim Bebbington at (937) 225-2262 or e-mail him at
jimbebbington(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
