<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERACTIVE-ANIMATION     09-11 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-ANIMATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE TO STAR CHARACTERS THAT ACT LIKE WE DO 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to fuse entertainment, education and artificial
intelligence, a company in Newton, Mass., is starting a Web site
featuring interactive cartoon characters imbued with behaviors that
mimic human responses.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Zoesis Studios, is seeking to eventually create a
new medium of interactive entertainment parallel to television.
</P>
<P>
   Zoesis was founded in 1996 by Joseph Bates, a Carnegie Mellon
University computer scientist who develops interactive dramas, an
area of artificial intelligence research that tries to create
fantasy worlds and characters with whom humans can interact.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.thelivingletters.com, is scheduled to go online on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The free site, which can be accessed with a Windows-based
personal computer, will present Web users with two cartoon-style
characters with whom they can interact by using a mouse as a
pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The two characters, Otto and Iris, will exhibit behaviors like
fear of the dark, giggling when ``tickled'' by a user's mouse and a
variety of facial expressions. The characters can play tag with a
computer user in one scene, or sing in response to a user acting as
``conductor,'' wielding the mouse as a baton.
</P>
<P>
   Another character _ a ``villain'' _ will appear on the site
later on, the company said, to help build a story line and some
tension into the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Zoesis has initial backing from Fujitsu Ltd., the Japanese
consumer electronics giant. Fujitsu has previously financed
research on the ``virtual worlds,'' which permit users, represented
by figures known as avatars, to move about in fantasy environments.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zoesis project is unrelated to that work. Rather, it is
the outgrowth of research that Bates first did with several other
members of the start-up at Carnegie Mellon over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Oz Project, the research tried to use artificial
intelligence techniques to create a new medium by blending
characters, presentation and drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is broadly an extension that was started in the 1980s on
behavior-based robots,'' Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   The group has worked at creating software ``agents'' whose
behavior appears to be goal-based and who can even be imbued with
emotional qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at other academic centers like the MIT Media
Laboratory and Stanford University have long worked on similar
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Hayes-Roth, a Stanford artificial intelligence
researcher, has also founded a company, Extempo Systems Inc., to
develop interactive software agents. Extempo has developed its
agents for Internet customer service applications, in which, for
instance, a character might answer questions from computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Some social scientists and industry executives say that
interactive drama has the potential to replace the television
sitcom as an entertainment medium.
</P>
<P>
   Bates said he believed that such a transition was possible, but
he was not certain how quickly the interactive entertainment medium
might evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear what will make this more compelling than
sitcoms,'' he said, ``but certainly if you have character and story
you're in the right ballpark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-11 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EMPHASIZES DEVOTION TO FAMILY IN VISIT TO OPRAH WINFREY SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVILLE, Ill. _ Oprah Winfrey knew that it might be a rough
day at the office. Before introducing Vice President Al Gore to her
audience Monday, television's high priestess of self-revelation
told her fans that she had always ``stayed away from politicians''
as guests because she never felt she could have an honest
conversation with them. ``After 15 years,'' she said, ``I thought,
OK, I need to try to penetrate that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   But after an hour with Gore seated beside her in a yellow
leather armchair, Winfrey had done little more than chip away at
the mortar. In the interview, which was broadcast from Winfrey's
studio in Chicago, Gore revealed little that was new, though
viewers did learn that his favorite book is ``The Red and the
Black'' by 19th century French novelist Robert Stendahl; that his
favorite movie is the 1983 Scottish film ``Local Hero,'' and that
his favorite cereal is Wheaties.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Gore may have achieved much of what he wished in the
interview. On a show with 22 million viewers a week, three-fourths
of them women, the Democratic presidential nominee portrayed
himself as a sensitive and devoted family man.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite indulgence, he said, is water skiing with his
family on a Tennessee lake. If the demands of the presidency became
toxic for his family life, he said he would simply ``change the
nature of the job.'' When Winfrey asked him how he responded when
he first learned that his wife, Tipper, suffered from depression,
he said, ``To feel the love and search for the healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey also asked Gore about the lengthy kiss he gave his wife
at the Democratic Convention, and twice showed videotape of the
prolonged smooch. Gore then explained that ``this is a partnership
and she is my soulmate,'' a choice of words that elicited
appreciative applause from the largely female audience.
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared at ease with Winfrey, who will interview his
Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush, on Sept. 19. But for most of
the show, Gore stuck closely to his campaign script. When Winfrey
asked him why she should vote for him, he responded, ``I'm for the
people, not the powerful.'' When she relayed a question from an
online viewer about the greatest problem facing the country, he
replied that ``we need more meaning in our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his least scripted responses came after the cameras
blinked off, when Gore lingered in the studio for about 20 minutes
to take more questions from Winfrey and the audience. When a woman
asked about Bush's ``problems'' with alcohol, Gore said he did not
make any judgments about his opponent, that he took Bush at his
word that ``he's had a personal transformation and a period of
growth.'' Bush, 54, has said he drank more than he should have
until he swore off alcohol 14 years ago, but that he never
considered himself an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey also asked Gore after the taping whether there were
things he could say now about President Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky that he could not say at the time. ``Did you and
Tipper talk about it over dinner and say, `Can you believe?'' she
asked. ``I'm not giving you any exact quotes,'' Gore said. ``You're
in the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   In the broadcast, Winfrey had fun playing a game of ``favorite
things'' with Gore. Favorite subject in school, she asked. ``Hmmm,
science,'' he responded. Favorite teacher: ``Dean Stambaugh, who
was my art teacher.'' Favorite quote: ``Hmm, ah, Bob Dylan: those
who are not busy being born are busy dying.'' Favorite time of
year: ``Springtime.'' Favorite thing to sleep in: ``A bed,'' Gore
responded in an instant. All-time favorite musical group:
``Beatles.'' Favorite indulgence: ``Hmm, oh, going to the lake near
our home in Tennessee on a houseboat and just waterskiing with the
kids and floating and swimming.'' Favorite meal: ``Chinese.''
Favorite childhood memory: ``Playing baseball with my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Chicago, Gore flew to Belleville, Ill., for an
open meeting on education at Westhaven Elementary School. There, he
repeated his ultimatum, first issued on Sunday, that the
entertainment industry immediately stop marketing violent films,
recordings and video games to children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Monday told reporters that Gore was ``short of credibility
on the issue'' because the Democrats have received more than $13
million in contributions from the entertainment industry. The
Republicans have received nearly $9 million from the same source.
Bush said that as president he would ``absolutely talk with CEO's
in Hollywood, those who produce the products that oftentimes
pollute our children's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the school forum, Gore was asked by a woman about what
he could do as president to bring prayer back to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   After joking that there would always be prayer in schools as
long as there are arithmetic tests, Gore said that ``in some school
settings the impression is given that it's wrong if a student wants
to exercise or display his or her faith or engage in a truly
voluntary prayer that the school employees have nothing to do
with.'' Supreme Court prohibitions against organized school prayer,
he said, have sometimes been ``taken to an extreme that actually
discriminates against some people of faith who wish to bring faith
into their school life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
