<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-NYT &LR;      09-11 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HIS HEALTH PLAN WOULD AVOID GORE'S `GOVERNMENT-RUN HMO'
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT13,14 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
  
By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ Gov. George W. Bush told elderly people in
Florida on Monday that his plans for changing Medicare and
providing prescription drug benefits would give them control over
their health care, while Vice President Al Gore would give them
only ``a government-run HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like to me we need to trust seniors to be able to tailor
a plan to meet each person's needs,'' Bush said during a town
hall-style meeting at a large retirement complex early Monday
afternoon here. ``The federal government ought to be humble enough
to allow you to make choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit was intended to help sell the proposal he unveiled
last week to coax Medicare recipients to select from a variety of
government-subsidized private health insurance plans that include
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But it also underscored the potency of the threat that Bush is
suddenly experiencing from Gore. Although his aides once talked
about Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is governor, as an almost
certain win, recent polls classify the state as a toss-up, and Bush
was scheduled to spend part of Tuesday and the end of next week
here as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan quite a few visits here,'' Bush said on the tarmac of
the St. Petersburg-Clearwater International Airport, where he
arrived from Austin, Texas, at about noon. His brother greeted him
at the airport and later introduced him at the retirement complex,
a campaign stop that reflected the disproportionate number _ and
influence _ of elderly voters in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk at the retirement center Bush offered a broadly
drawn portrait of Gore's plans for prescription drug coverage. ``My
opponent's point of view,'' he added, was to create ``only one
government-run HMO. You'll be thrown into it _ in a government-run
HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   With his description of a big, scary, arrogant federal
government, Bush sought to distill the policy differences between
him and Gore, who has called for strengthening Medicare and adding
prescription drug coverage within the entitlement program.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was also providing a hint of how he might _ and might
not _ incorporate the copious and often unsolicited advice that his
campaign has been receiving from Republican strategists and other
political analysts ever since Gore emphatically erased Bush's lead
in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those experts maintain that Bush should float above the
details of issues, like health care, on which Democrats in general
and Gore in particular seem to enjoy more voter confidence.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Bush heeded that counsel, using health care as a
prism through which he wanted voters to see the philosophical
disagreement between him and Gore about the role of the federal
government. Bush essentially cast himself as the genuine populist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have this concept that the federal government is
all wise and all knowing,'' he said. He also said that his Medicare
plan could and would actually happen, an allusion to failed
health-care initiatives during the Clinton administration and an
assertion that he could be more effective in office than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also waded into the brambles of the issue itself,
telling his audience in Clearwater that under Gore's plan, they
would have to make binding decisions about their coverage before
they turned 65 and would, in some cases, pay more for prescription
drugs than they currently do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell your friends and neighbors to use the calculator to make
sure you look at the fine print _ the fine print _ before people
buy into a program that's going to mean more of the same,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said that
Bush's characterizations of Gore's proposal were misleading or
erroneous and that Gore, in strengthening Medicare, would be giving
elderly people a guarantee of benefits that Bush would not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush puts seniors off on the tender mercies of the insurance
companies,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's focus on health care marked the beginning of a week in
which his aides said he would confront Gore repeatedly and directly
on issues, like the environment and education, that are typically
considered Democrats' strong suits.
</P>
<P>
   They said that their goal was to remind people that Bush is ``a
different kind of Republican,'' one of the campaign's longstanding
catch phrases, and that Bush is armed with ``real plans for real
people,'' the campaign's newest slogan. The Bush campaign's target,
clearly, is the pivotal group of undecided centrist voters without
predetermined allegiances to either party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's stylistic efforts to reinvigorate his candidacy were also
on display. Instead of looking down at his audience of several
hundred from a stage or podium, he stood at eye-level with most of
them, pivoting this way and that as he answered questions about a
variety of issues.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed more relaxed and confident, and he talked for about 50
minutes, easily triple the time of a standard stump speech just a
week and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just before his remarks, Bush met privately with three elderly
women who, according to campaign officials, would fare better under
Bush's proposals for Medicare and prescription drug coverage than
they would under Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   This represented the campaign's newly aggressive attempt to put
human faces on Bush's policy proposals. But while Bush's aides
cited facts and figures to buttress their claim about the trio of
elderly supporters, reporters did not meet or have access to them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was acutely conscious of the age and political interests of
his audience in Clearwater, making a point of telling them that he
would protect their Social Security benefits and that those
benefits would not be endangered by his sweeping tax cut proposal.
He moved through the arithmetic of that equation more fluidly than
he had in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To his aides, it was proof that their campaign was flying along
just fine. En route to Florida, Karen Hughes, the director of
communications, told reporters that ``after our much-publicized
retooling efforts last week, I thought you all would be glad to
know that we're going to be on Top of the World today _
literally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was right. It was the name of the Clearwater retirement
complex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
