u a BC-DEATH-PENALTY-STUDY-N     09-11 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY REPORTS RACIAL, GEOGRAPHIC DISPARITY IN FEDERAL DEATH
SENTENCING 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND BONNER AND MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the first official review of the federal death
penalty since it was reinstated in 1988, the Justice Department has
found disturbing disparities by race and geography, according to
officials who have seen the report.
</P>
<P>
   In 75 percent of the cases in which a federal prosecutor sought
the death penalty in the last 5 years, the defendant has been a
minority, and in more than half of the cases, an African-American,
according to the report, which officials said the Justice
Department would release on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a lack of geographic uniformity in the application of
federal capital punishment, the Justice Department has found that a
handful of the 93 U.S. attorneys account for nearly half of the
cases that had been sent to the Justice Department for review,
according to officials who have seen the report.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, about 20 U.S. attorneys did not file a single
death penalty case since 1995. SInce there are more than 40 crimes
for which the federal death penalty is a potential punishment, the
lack of cases in those jurisdictions raised the question of the
equitable application of death penalty prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's troubling,'' said an administration official who has
reviewed the findings. ``The president has expressed concern about
the problem, and this backs that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the report was a compilation of about 400 pages
of data, and that it contained almost no analysis. Justice
Department officials were still writing the report's introduction
late Monday evening, officials said. They added that at a news
conference on Tuesday, Attorney General Janet Reno will announce
more studies to provide analysis of the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The report is expected to increase calls for a moratorium on the
federal death penalty. The American Bar Association, which does not
have a position for or against the death penalty, sent a letter to
President Clinton on May 2 asking him to impose an executive
moratorium pending a thorough review of the federal capital
punishment system. An association official said Monday that Clinton
had not responded.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., and Rep. Jesse Jackson
Jr., D-Ill., introduced legislation calling for a national death
penalty moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the Justice Department report has been given to
lawyers for Juan Raul Garza, who is scheduled to be executed on
Dec. 12. His lawyers are planning to file a clemency request with
the Justice Department on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He was originally scheduled to be executed on Aug. 5, but
Clinton granted him a reprieve so that his lawyers could use new
clemency rules drafted by the Justice Department for capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   While a death penalty for at least some federal crimes has been
on the books since 1988, it has yet to be carried out. The last
federal execution was 37 years ago, when Victor Feguer was hanged
in Iowa for kidnapping and killing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court declared in 1972 that the death penalty,
as it was then being applied, was unconstitutional, states quickly
adopted laws that the court upheld. In 1988, Congress adopted what
has become known as the drug kingpin statute, which allows for the
death penalty against an individual who commits murder as part of a
larger drug running enterprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, in 1994, Congress enacted the Federal Death
Penalty Act, which greatly expanded the number of crimes for which
a defendant can be executed.
</P>
<P>
   They range from murder of the president of the United States, to
large-scale drug trafficking even when no one is killed, and
include drive-by murders, sexual abuse resulting in death, murder
during a bank robbery, carjacking and destruction of a plane, train
or motor vehicle resulting in death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
