<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EXP-BUSH-NYT &LR;      09-11 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HIS HEALTH PLAN WOULD AVOID GORE'S `GOVERNMENT-RUN HMO'
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ Gov. George W. Bush told elderly people in
Florida Monday that his plans for changing Medicare and providing
prescription drug benefits would give them control over their
health care, while Vice President Al Gore would give them only ``a
government-run HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like to me we need to trust seniors to be able to tailor
a plan to meet each person's needs,'' Bush said during a town
hall-style meeting at a large retirement complex early Monday
afternoon here. ``The federal government ought to be humble enough
to allow you to make choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit was intended to help sell the proposal he unveiled
last week to coax Medicare recipients to select from a variety of
government-subsidized private health insurance plans that include
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Although his aides once talked about Florida, where Bush's
brother Jeb is governor, as an almost certain win, recent polls
classify the state as a toss-up, and Bush was scheduled to spend
part of Tuesday and the end of next week here as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan quite a few visits here,'' Bush said at the St.
Petersburg-Clearwater International Airport. His brother greeted
him at the airport and later introduced him at the retirement
complex, a campaign stop that reflected the disproportionate number
_ and influence _ of elderly voters in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk at the retirement center Bush offered a broadly
drawn portrait of Gore's plans for prescription drug coverage. ``My
opponent's point of view,'' he added, was to create ``only one
government-run HMO. You'll be thrown into it _ in a government-run
HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   With his description of a big, scary, arrogant federal
government, Bush sought to distill the policy differences between
him and Gore, who has called for strengthening Medicare and adding
prescription drug coverage within the entitlement program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have this concept that the federal government is
all wise and all knowing,'' he said. He also said that his Medicare
plan could and would actually happen, an allusion to failed
health-care initiatives during the Clinton administration and an
assertion that he could be more effective in office than Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
