<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE DIRECTOR WILL QUIT FOR HARVARD TEACHING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Health
Care Financing Administration, the federal agency that runs
Medicare and Medicaid, announced Monday that she was resigning on
Oct. 1 to take a temporary job teaching at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said she would become a fellow at the Institute of
Politics, which is affiliated with the John F. Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Her resignation comes near the end of a presidential campaign in
which Medicare is a major issue.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said she had known Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic candidate for president, for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of his biggest fans,'' said DeParle, who, like Gore,
is from Tennessee. ``I want to do everything I can to help him be
elected and to do a great job with the Medicare program. The vice
president is a friend. But I don't have any plans to join a Gore
administration. I feel ready to get back to the private sector, and
that's what I'll be pursuing over the next several months.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Care Financing Administration helps pay medical bills
for more 75 million Americans and has a budget of more than $330
billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle worked at the White House Office of Management and
Budget from 1993 to 1997. She became deputy administrator of the
Medicare-Medicaid agency in July 1997, and four months later she
was confirmed by the Senate as head of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message to agency employees Monday, DeParle said:
``Through your hard work, we have accomplished some of the Clinton
administration's most important policy goals. We extended the life
of the Medicare trust fund through 2025 and began significant
initiatives to modernize Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   DeParle supervised the first years of the Children's Health
Insurance Program, created by Congress in 1997. She supervised
hundreds of changes in the way Medicare pays doctors, hospitals,
nursing homes and other health care providers. Her top priority
last year was to fix government computers for the year 2000, so
benefit payments would not be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put beneficiaries first in everything we've done,'' DeParle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress of both parties worked closely with DeParle.
But Republicans, some Democrats and many health care providers have
criticized the agency as a heavy-handed regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the agency had been slow to recognize two major
problems in the last few years. Officials initially underestimated
the importance of decisions by health maintenance organizations to
pull out of the Medicare program, forcing hundreds of thousands of
elderly people to make other arrangements for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials were also slow to notice that hundreds of
thousands of poor people had been improperly deprived of Medicaid
coverage when they lost welfare benefits. In the 1996 welfare law,
Congress tried to restrict eligibility for cash assistance while
preserving access to Medicaid, but many states inadvertently cut
off Medicaid for people leaving the welfare rolls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-LEE-SPY-CHARGES-2TAKE     09-11 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-SPY-CHARGES-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PLEA BARGAIN OF LOS ALAMOS SCIENTIST SNAGS, U.S. RE-EVALUATES
SPY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: See also LEE-RELEASE) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   with WILLIAM J. BROAD and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An investigation that began eight years ago to
determine how China obtained classified information from American
weapons labs about one of the country's most advanced nuclear
warheads appears to be back where it started, with the mystery
still unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wen Ho Lee, a nuclear weapons scientist at the U.S.
government's Los Alamos weapons laboratory in New Mexico, became
the leading suspect in the investigation of the alleged theft of
warhead data, he was never charged with espionage or accused of any
crime connected with the loss of information for a device known as
the W-88. Nor did the government ever obtain any direct evidence
linking Lee to the suspected theft of W-88 data.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said on Monday they were prepared to accept
a plea bargain in which Lee would plead guilty to a single count of
improperly downloading secret information. The material Lee
downloaded was unrelated to the suspected warhead design theft that
triggered the government's investigation of possible Chinese
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement effectively means that prosecutors have ended
their pursuit of Lee as a possible source of any stolen warhead
data, once described by government experts as ``the crown jewels''
of America's nuclear secrets. It also leaves them with no clear
answer about how the Chinese obtained the warhead data, or from
whom.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year ago, when questions were raised about whether the
Justice Department had focused prematurely and unfairly on Lee,
Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh ordered
what law enforcement officials described as a top-to-bottom
re-investigation of the suspected W-88 theft. But intelligence
experts and scientists said they had made little progress.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the expected release of Lee was canceled as
prosecutors and defense lawyers in Albuquerque, who had signed a
plea agreement on Sunday, backed away from the settlement. But U.S.
District Judge James Parker said he would reschedule a hearing for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must regretfully say that we cannot proceed with the hearing
this afternoon,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers following the case said later that Lee's lawyers were
unsettled about a document in which Lee outlined the admissions he
was prepared to make in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear precisely what aspect of Lee's prospective
admissions had jeopardized the deal, or how serious the dispute
might be. Both sides said they hoped the issues could be resolved
by Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, Lee was charged in a 59-count felony
indictment with gathering a massive amount of research and design
data from the computers at Los Alamos ``with the intent to secure
an advantage for a foreign power.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to explain how the case collapsed, government
officials acknowledged in interviews Monday that they had no clear
idea what Lee intended to do with the information he downloaded.
This proved an almost insurmountable problem, because many of the
offenses with which Lee was charged would have required prosecutors
to prove Lee's motives.
</P>
<P>
   The officials who spoke about how the case was viewed from
inside the government as it evolved during the last several months
said that prosecutors on the trial team had concluded recently that
the case was flawed, and that they would never be able to
demonstrate convincingly at a trial why Lee had downloaded the
information, or what he had done with it.
</P>
<P>
   After interviews and polygraph examinations, FBI agents searched
Lee's office and home in early 1999. They discovered that he had
downloaded 806 megabytes of information, which law enforcement
officials said, amounted to 400,000 pages of information. Lee
transferred the data to computer tapes which he said he either
saved or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the turning point that led them to agree to
the plea bargain was the realization that they would never fully
know Lee's motives in downloading the information.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, government officials said, prosecutors and
investigators had competing theories as to which government Lee
might have been aiding. Some investigators had theorized that Lee
might have been aiding China, where he had visited and where he had
made contacts with local scientists. Others reasoned that because
he was a native of Taiwan, he might have been helping that
government.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time doubts and misgivings were mounting within the
government, prosecutors became concerned as the case started to
unravel in the courtroom. And just as importantly, according to law
enforcement officials, the prosecutors realized that public opinion
about the case had begun to shift against the government and in
favor of Lee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lee's supporters, with his daughter serving as an effective
spokeswoman, mounted an aggressive effort to portray the
government's tactics against him as a racist campaign against
Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, prosecutors began to grow more receptive to overtures
to settle the case _ especially after an embarrassing appearance by
a senior FBI agent at a bail hearing last month who said that he
had testified falsely that Lee lied to a colleague about the
purpose of his downloading.
</P>
<P>
   According to law enforcement officials, the 59 felony charges in
the indictment were a tactical step aimed at pressuring Lee into
pleading to what some officials suggested could be far more serious
charges.
</P>
<P>
   A number of government officials who were convinced that Lee
provided classified information to the Chinese government remain
unpersuaded of his innocence, although they acknowledge as one
former senior government official did Monday that, ``There was
smoke but nothing you could hang your hat on.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The effort to investigate Lee for espionage began to unravel
almost as soon as it began in 1995 when Energy Department officials
turned over to the FBI a list of people, including Lee, who they
said might be responsible for a sudden and unexplained advance in
Chinese nuclear warhead technology.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department investigators concluded that the Chinese could
have only obtained the crucial information about the W-88 warhead,
the most advanced American nuclear weapon, by stealing it from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the investigation was hobbled by internal
disagreements whether China might have obtained the information
from other sources. Some counterintelligence officials accused the
FBI of failing to take the allegations seriously enough, and FBI
agents became embroiled in time-consuming debates with the Justice
Department over whether the agents could legally justify
wiretapping to collect evidence against Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said that Lee has agreed to cooperate fully and
has promised to tell them in more detail what he did with the
tapes. But the officials said that they are not optimistic that Lee
is likely to add much to his statements that he downloaded the
information for personal use.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   What remains of the inquiry is an investigation into whether
there exists another explanation or suspect for the loss of the
W-88 technology, which began with a government effort to pinpoint
the source of the leak. The new investigation included looking for
any possible clues and textual ``finger prints'' on a Chinese
document that the CIA had obtained in 1995 and had long resided at
the heart of the spy case.
</P>
<P>
   It has previously been reported that its Chinese text cited five
key attributes of the W-88 warhead, including two measurements
accurate to within four-hundredths of an inch. That information was
the smoking gun that proved beyond a doubt that the Chinese had
obtained national secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, experts said, a federal panel made up of people
from the Central Intelligence Agency, the Defense Intelligence
Agency, the State Department and the Energy Department and its
weapons laboratories was surprised to learn that such secret
information on the W-88 had been distributed widely beyond Los
Alamos, intelligence experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of one detailed description of the warhead were
distributed to 548 addresses, including ones in the Defense
Department, the military services, the National Guard, federal
agencies and contractors like the Lockheed Missile and Space Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the lost secrets, it appeared, were available to
thousands of individuals scattered throughout the nation's arms
complex and thus available from myriad sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
