u p BC-BUCHANAN-ART-NYT     09-11 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERING BUCHANAN CONSIDERS CAMPAIGN OBSTACLES ON MANY FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT21 and NYT22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   McLEAN, Va. _ With his ``pitchfork brigades'' gone the way of
his gall bladder, Pat Buchanan, the persistent presidential
candidate, was feeling well on the mend from surgery on Monday when
his front doorbell rang and he was greeted with another subpoena
from the tireless antagonists he has stirred in the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Ross Perot people,'' Buchanan fairly sighed at the
pains of fate. After four weeks of medical recuperation and not a
single day of campaigning, the candidate is laboring to regain his
edge. Yet he must resume a fight not so much against the major
party nominees as within his fractious adopted party.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh Reform steed Buchanan envisioned saddling for himself
has behaved more like a dragon threatening to devour his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's nine-month struggle for the Reform nomination is
continuing into a chaotic campaign homestretch. He must deal with
state-by-state skirmishes over ballot legitimacy that he never
foresaw when he left the Republican Party last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Perot's funding all this,'' Buchanan said of the
flurry of court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else are they getting the money?'' Buchanan asked as he
put the subpoena aside and focused on sweeter possibilities this
week that might resurrect his candidacy, now moribund at 1 percent
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vote Lazarus!'' the combative conservative exulted grimly. His
laughter cracked forth here in his home in a sylvan enclave
neighboring the Central Intelligence Agency's suburban compound.
</P>
<P>
   A touch of the old pugilist's gleam returned to a figure
harrowed by hospitalization. He anticipates a firm victory on
Tuesday from the Federal Elections Commission. The commission,
which is to rule on a challenge from anti-Buchanan Reformers, has
already received a staff recommendation that Buchanan is the
legitimate nominee and deserves the party's $12.7 million in
federal campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also hopes for favorable word soon in his own lawsuit
challenging the decision to bar him from the presidential debates.
He concedes that this national arena is his last chance to salvage
something from the third-party defection that followed his long
career as the Republicans' hard-right gladiator. If he is barred
from the debates, he said, ``any chance to achieve something
dramatic probably fades away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he wins the funding and debate victories, Buchanan
expects court fights all the way to November from the Reform
minority that bolted his nominating convention and endorsed John
Hagelin, an Iowa physicist.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Buchanan maintains that he has no regrets about
quitting the Republican Party only to plummet in the polls. Four
years ago, he electrified his supporters _ the ``pitchfork
brigades'' _ with his upset victory in the New Hampshire primary.
He switched parties last October after his renewed quest flatlined
as Gov. George W. Bush of Texas moved for the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you watch this year's Republican Convention?'' Buchanan
asked about a party he feels has abandoned conservative bedrock to
ape President Clinton's centrist techniques. ``Bush would have put
me down in the basement with all the other conservatives. I still
feel liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve pounds lighter than his usual trim as a polemical
slasher, the candidate is promising his best shot for the remaining
eight weeks _ providing he can get noticed. ``In American politics,
that's a lot of time,'' he said. But he acknowledged that he had
been unable to afford advertising and that all the court fight fees
would cut into the federal subsidy even if he could gain it soon.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan concedes that he never imagined such a year as this has
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if we had gotten our money the day after the convention
and I'd have been healthy, we'd be about 5 percent now in the
polls,'' he said. ``And if we got into the debates, we'd get far
more than Ross Perot got in 1996,'' he added. Perot won 8 percent
of the vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan paused as he scratched behind the ears of Gipper, his
15-year-old house cat. ``Yeah, well, of all the words of tongue and
pen,'' he said, ``The saddest of these is `might have been.'''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly substituted optimism for regret. ``Hey, Gipper, we
may have the Secret Service back out in the driveway again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a history buff, cited the case of Frederick the Great
suddenly delivered by absurd political accident to triumph after
failing steadily at multiple wars. (A rival monarch died and was
succeeded by a great admirer of his, who immediately signed a peace
treaty.) ``And what did they say about Calvin Coolidge? His career
was the clearest example ever seen of `Providential
intervention!'''
</P>
<P>
   The recuperating candidate grinned; the cat purred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who don't want us to be alive,''
Buchanan said, conspiring with Gipper at Providential intervention.
``At least that's a good feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
