<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-LASORDA-LADN-(SLA     09-11 1719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LASORDA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA RELISHES JOB AS OLYMPIC COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Five in the morning and the house in Fullerton was
dark when Jo Lasorda was awakened by a noise in the den. At first
there was shouting, then a few gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a prowler or a gang fight. It was John Wayne, so
Jo went back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, she has gotten used to the booming voice
of the Duke from the 1948 film ``Sands of Iwo Jima'' that plays at
all hours on the family's big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   And she said she still smiles, remembering the footsteps on the
nearby treadmill that quickened every time the Marines took the
hill and raised the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen so much of John Wayne around here, you'd think he
was a relative,'' Jo Lasorda said with a giggle. ``These days, our
house has been that treadmill and John Wayne movies. Tommy was
getting in shape for the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question might be whether the Olympics is in shape
for Tom Lasorda, the blustery former Dodgers manager who will run
the U.S. team at the upcoming Summer Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans hit the ground in Australia after a 17-hour flight
from San Diego with three consecutive victories in a pre-Olympic
tournament. Lasorda met his team of minor-league players just last
Saturday, but with the renewed zeal of the manager who led the Los
Angeles Dodgers to two World Series titles, Lasorda has them
believing they can defeat the mighty Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are unbelievable but not unbeatable,'' Lasorda bellowed
into the phone recently. ``We did not come 6,000 miles to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ In the spotlight, again
</P>
<P>
   For Lasorda, who will turn 73 on Sept. 22, the day the U.S.
faces his beloved Italy, the victory might already be at hand
regardless of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than four years since then-Dodgers owner Peter
O'Malley coaxed him into retirement after the manager suffered a
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has had the second of two heart operations, an
ulcer and both knees replaced. He briefly became the Dodgers
general manager in the summer of 1998 and came under fire for
trading away many of the team's top prospects. He languished in a
senior vice president role that was undefined and unfulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Lasorda was forced to watch as his successors
helped tear down an organization that won four pennants and eight
division titles during his 20 years on the job. Although he
received huge ovations at Dodger Stadium when introduced from time
to time, Lasorda, for the most part, was becoming forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all bad. He was inducted into baseball's Hall of Fame
in 1997 and got a chance to watch his only granddaughter, Emily,
grow from a toddler. Lasorda remained a busy public speaker and
also rediscovered on scouting trips through the Dodgers farm system
his love of nurturing young talent.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Olympics. Lasorda, the son of an Italian-immigrant
father, always has had plenty of reasons to wave the flag. At his
induction speech to Cooperstown, he told the crowd he was proof of
the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy likes everything he does, but managing is what he does
best, it's what he is,'' said New York Mets manager Bobby
Valentine, who played for Lasorda in the minors 30 years ago and
remains a close family friend. ``He has come through a period in
his life that always hasn't been great, but he never complained.
This is his reward.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ Reinventing himself
</P>
<P>
   Although his naming to the manager's post with the Olympic team
took place last spring, the reinventing of Tom Lasorda actually
began in the summer of 1996 after he stepped down as manager of the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   He reluctantly retired due to his heart condition, which
required a second angioplasty in October of that year. He also was
being treated for an ulcer and his knees were a source of constant
discomfort. Atlanta manager Bobby Cox, whose team was headed to the
World Series, urged Lasorda to follow his lead and undergo knee
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda resisted for two more years, but under the care of
Dodgers internist Michael Mellman and cardiologist Anthony Reid, he
began some radical changes.
</P>
<P>
   His eating was legendary, as the restaurants in Australia are
beginning to discover. But the scare of another heart attack was
not enough to bring down a cholesterol level well over 300.
</P>
<P>
   Reid didn't care how Lasorda exercised, he just wanted him to
keep moving. Into the den went the treadmill that he walks on 45
minutes a day, five times a week. He also swims regularly and does
some light weight training. Most important, he maintains the
regimen in hotel weight rooms on his trips around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda had dropped 38 pounds in 1988 on a bet by players Kirk
Gibson and Orel Hershiser. With the aid of dietary supplement
Slim-Fast, he became a spokesman for better eating. But he gained
all the weight back within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Reid got him to cut out the yo-yo dieting, plus most steaks and
creamy sauces. More impressively, Reid taught him moderation. When
Lasorda underwent his pre-Olympic physical three weeks ago, his
cholesterol was 152.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a major heart attack, but it certainly was a wake-up
call,'' said Reid, who is headed to Sydney to watch the Games. ``He
always has been an incredibly motivated person and he has channeled
his energy toward his health and the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he struggled in adjusting to life beyond the dugout,
Lasorda's reduced stress levels probably helped get him to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, Lasorda took over for fired Fred Claire as general
manager. It was a job he coveted in the late 1980s and was
devastated when Claire was named to replace Al Campanis.
</P>
<P>
   But the late-'90s GM job was a pressure cooker. He and his wife
did not even have a telephone-answering machine until last year,
but Lasorda found himself glued to a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star break, he traded first base prospect Paul
Konerko and pitcher Dennis Reyes to Cincinnati for closer Jeff
Shaw. He learned two days later that Shaw could demand a trade at
the end of the season if his contract was not renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   He worked feverishly at the trade deadline to acquire Mark
Grudzielanek and Carlos Perez for prospects in an attempt to reach
the playoffs. The Dodgers faltered anyway and Lasorda was left
drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``His health worried me a lot more during his time as GM than it
does now,'' Dodgers president Bob Graziano said. ``I think he did a
good job. We needed a closer and he got us a good one, but he took
a lot of heat and it took a lot out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda stepped aside at the end of the 1998 season, but Jo
remembered the experience as perhaps the low point of his life
after managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough time,'' she said. ``That really wasn't his
cup of tea. He would rather scout and work with players. The other
thing was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ `I feel like it's 1968'
</P>
<P>
   Jo Lasorda laughed at the thought of her husband's retirement.
Never good with the lawn mower or vacuum cleaner, Lasorda tried to
find his niche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a manager, I love the field, and the players and the
game,'' he said. ``And the chance to do it for your country. With
these kids, I feel like it's 1968 again and I'm in Ogden, Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   His center fielder that year was Valentine. Steve Garvey and
Bill Buckner also played on the team.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the U.S. is using professionals for the first time,
but they are not expected to beat Cuba, which has won gold the past
two Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of 37-year-old Pat Borders, a former World
Series MVP with Toronto, few have major-league experience. Cuba
lost international tournaments to Japan in 1997 and Australia last
year but clearly is the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his background in player development, Lasorda was not
the overwhelming choice when USA Baseball, an arm of the
commissioner's office, went looking for a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Watson, co-general manager for the team with former Angels
GM Bill Bavasi, favored the younger Terry Collins, who managed the
Angels last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, at the urging of old friend and two-time Olympic coach
Rod Dedeaux, lobbied hard. He had the support of commissioner Bud
Selig and baseball's executive vice president, Sandy Alderson, who
liked the media coverage Lasorda could generate.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the third time baseball will be a medal sport at
the Olympics and it lags behind track and field, swimming and
basketball for exposure. But this year NBC, along with its cable
affiliates CNBC and MSNBC, have more than doubled the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a unique quality to the Games that haven't been
there before,'' Bavasi said of Lasorda. ``But Tommy is more than
just an ambassador or a curiosity. He always has connected well
with young players. He gives us the best chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Fullerton, the house and the treadmill will be quiet for
the next three weeks. A little lonely, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Lasorda decided last spring during an illness that she
wouldn't make the trip to Sydney. She's fine now but said she knows
her husband's place is with his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you make a team,'' Jo Lasorda said. ``It's been
that way with Tommy for as long as I can remember.''
</P>
<P>
   And as long as anyone can remember, they've been a team,
celebrating their 50th wedding anniversary last April. In 1950,
Buzzie Bavasi, Bill's father and general manager of the Brooklyn
Dodgers, lent Lasorda $500 to get married.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzie is still waiting for his money. Bill is hoping he'll get
paid back in gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me what was my greatest accomplishment,'' Lasorda
said before leaving for Sydney. ``They ask if it was the World
Series games or All-Star games or induction into the Hall of Fame.
In 1949 there were 680 players and 26 managers in the Dodgers
spring-training camp. The greatest thing is that Jo and I are still
together and I am the only Dodger left from that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that could top that is winning a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, Tom Lasorda can lay claim to comeback player of
the year. If he does, he can hang his medal on the treadmill with
an inscription.
</P>
<P>
   ``For, Jo, Tommy and the Duke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
