<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LEE-RELEASE-620&AMP;ADD-N     09-11 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-RELEASE-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENTION OVER PLEA DETAILS DELAYS RELEASE OF LOS ALAMOS
SCIENTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (With LEE-SPY-CHARGES) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ A last-minute dispute between the government
and defense lawyers over a plea agreement for Wen Ho Lee, the
former Los Alamos weapons lab scientist accused of mishandling
nuclear secrets, delayed for at least two days a guilty plea that
would allow him walk out of court a free man.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would explain the delay, which left members of
Lee's family looking despondent. The U.S. District Court judge
hearing the case, James Parker, said the hearing was scheduled to
resume on Wednesday morning, but ``we may have and may not have it
depending on what happens in the interim.''
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen supporters of Lee stood briefly in shock, and then
someone shouted out, ``Hang in there Dr. Lee!'' That prompted
applause for several minutes in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   It was a surprising twist to what was already a surprise ending
to this important national security case. A 2 p.m. hearing had been
scheduled Monday to conclude a plea agreement worked out in secret
in recent weeks and reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Lee, a former Los Alamos scientist, had been
investigated on suspicions that he had spied for China. But when he
was arrested last December, he was charged in a 59-count indictment
with illegally downloading a trove of data about weapons secrets
with the intent of harming the United States, but he was not
charged with espionage. He was denied bail because of government
assertions that he posed a threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, lawyers said that the government had agreed to
abandon almost its entire case after several courtroom reverses.
They said Lee had agreed to plead guilty to one felony charge that
he illegally gathered and retained nuclear weapons secrets, and to
cooperate with investigators trying to determine why he downloaded
the secrets and what he did with them.
</P>
<P>
   In return, they said, the government had agreed to drop the
other 58 charges, which could have resulted in a life sentence.
Under the agreement, Lee would be released immediately, pay no fine
and serve no probation, lawyers familiar with the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's family and supporters insisted from the time of his arrest
that he was innocent, and that he had been singled out because he
was Chinese-American. A party was planned on Lee's street near Los
Alamos, and several dozen supporters showed up in court to cheer
his expected walk to freedom after nine months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted Americans to see Wen Ho Lee come home,'' said
Jean Marshall, one of his neighbors and an organizer of the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the expectant mood in the courtroom slowly turned into
exasperation after a series of delays. Parker twice recessed court,
each time saying that the two sides had requested a one-hour delay
to conclude some details.
</P>
<P>
   When Parker recalled the court to session at 5 p.m., a glum
Parker said only that the terms had not been completed and that the
hearing would resume Wednesday. But then he added that resumption
would depend on whether the lawyers had reached an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few details to work out,'' said John Cline, one of
Lee's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorneys would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously very upset,'' said Lee's son, Chung. ``We
don't know what's going on. We hope and expect to see our Dad on
Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was frustrated, Lee's daughter, Alberta, who seemed
near tears as the hearing ended, remarked, ``I think it shows on
our faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung Lee said the applause had heartened his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong guy and he's very encouraged, and he was
encouraged by all the supporters,'' Chung Lee said. ``I think it
was very heartwarming for him to see all the supporters out
there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawyers insisted that Parker had told both sides not to discuss
the problems and they would provide no information on what was
holding up the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, lawyers for the government and defense lawyers had
said a deal had been completed and the terms agreed upon in detail.
</P>
<P>
   When Lee was arrested in December, the government claimed that
he had improperly downloaded the ``crown jewels'' of the nuclear
weapons program onto an unsecure computer and then onto 10 computer
tapes. The downloading was discovered after Lee was fired from his
job at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in March 1999. The
government found just three of the 10 tapes, and Lee later said
through his lawyers that he destroyed the other seven.
</P>
<P>
   But the government said that uncertainty over the fate of those
tapes, and the prospect that Lee might try to spirit them to a
foreign power, required his incarceration pending his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Parker agreed, but he reversed his decision last
month after an FBI agent recanted testimony about Lee's supposed
deceptive behavior. Also, defense experts disputed the value of the
information Lee downloaded, saying most of it was already in the
public domain and all but useless to another country.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said in Washington on Sunday that those
reverses had not motivated them to negotiate a plea deal, but it
was clear that the case was looking weaker. The trial had been
scheduled for November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
