documents is ready to replace older encasements that have begun to
break down. On Friday, the National Archives and Records
Administration will let the public see one of the new cases for the
first time. A restorer works on an area of ink flakes on the
Constitution. (National Archives/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
OLY-MUNICH-EYEWITNESS-COX-2 -- Harry Winkler, 59, a health teacher
at Forest Hill High School in West Palm Beach. Fla., was a member
of the U.S. handball team at the 1972 Munich Olympics, the year of
the massacre of Israeli athletes by Palestinian terrorists. Harry
watched the scene unfold from his balcony, but he actually knew
less than most of us back home because the television news
commentary was in German, which he doesn't speak. Winkler in an
undated photo playing handball. (Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
OLY-MUNICH-EYEWITNESS-COX-1 -- Harry Winkler, 59, a health teacher
at Forest Hill High School in West Palm Beach. Fla., was a member
of the U.S. handball team at the 1972 Munich Olympics, the year of
the massacre of Israeli athletes by Palestinian terrorists. Harry
watched the scene unfold from his balcony, but he actually knew
less than most of us back home because the television news
commentary was in German, which he doesn't speak. (Allen
Eyestone/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-PRIMATE-EXTINCTION --
For the first time in at least a century, a member of the primate
order, the taxonomic group to which human beings belong, has gone
extinct, scientists say. Debate has not yet ended on whether Miss
Waldron's red colobus, the loud-mouthed, red-cheeked dweller of the
rain forest canopy of West Africa, deserved full status as a
species in its own right or should have remained a colobus
subspecies. But now that debate is moot, a team of primatologists
reports in an article in the forthcoming issue of the peer-reviewed
journal Conservation Biology. An artist's rendering of a Miss
Waldron's red colobus done in 1936. (Conservation International/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-DRUGS-CHILDREN
-- Many parents might be surprised to learn that most of the drugs
prescribed for children, from allergy relievers to asthma inhalants
and antidepressants, have never been formally tested on children.
Starting this December, however, a new Food and Drug Administration
rule mandates that any new adult drug that could be used by
children with the same disease must undergo pediatric study, and
its manufacturers must list doses for children on the label. Dr.
Dianne Murphy of the F.D.A. is leading efforts to test medications
on children. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) McLEAN, Va. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- BUCHANAN-2 -- With his
political popularity gone the way of his gall bladder, Patrick J.
Buchanan, the chronic Presidential candidate, is feeling well on
the mend from surgery. But Buchanan's 9-month, tooth-and-claw
struggle for the Reform Presidential nomination is continuing into
a chaotic campaign homestretch of state-by-state skirmishes that he
never envisioned when he bolted the Republican party last fall.
Buchanan during an interview at his home, Monday. (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) McLEAN, Va. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- BUCHANAN-1 -- With his
political popularity gone the way of his gall bladder, Patrick J.
Buchanan, the chronic Presidential candidate, is feeling well on
the mend from surgery. But Buchanan's 9-month, tooth-and-claw
struggle for the Reform Presidential nomination is continuing into
a chaotic campaign homestretch of state-by-state skirmishes that he
never envisioned when he bolted the Republican party last fall.
Buchanan in front of his home, Monday. (Justin Lane/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- ARMY-JOURNALIST-COX -- Jim
McLaughlin, 55, an Army correspondent, considered himself more
fortunate than the combat soldiers in Vietnam. Much of McLaughlin's
work as an Army journalist consisted of covering ``grip and grin''
awards ceremonies, held in secure areas. McLaughlin wrote many
articles about generals pinning Purple Hearts on wounded GIs. He's
standing near the press vehicle he used in Vietnam. (Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BELLEVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- Vice
President Al Gore, right, the Democratic party's candidate for
president, looks at Rep. Jerry Costello, seated left, and Sen.
Richard J. Durbin, as they raise their hands in answer to Gore's
question about who had been married a long time during a town hall
meeting on education, Monday at Westhaven Elementary School. Gore
called on the entertainment industry Monday to stop marketing
violent and adult material to children and threatened tougher
government restrictions if it did not. (Ruth Fremson/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- ALBANIAN-PAGEANT-2 -- At
the first Miss Albania U.S.A. Pageant in New York, 13 contestants,
who ranged in age from 16 to 24 and live mostly in the Bronx, home
to about 30,000 Albanian-Americans, were vying for a $3,000 prize
and a slot in the Miss Albania contest in Tirana. The event was a
patriotic affair for many Albanians, especially with all the
destruction that has occurred in their homeland. Contestants on
stage during the pageant. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- ALBANIAN-PAGEANT-1 -- At
the first Miss Albania U.S.A. Pageant in New York, 13 contestants,
who ranged in age from 16 to 24 and live mostly in the Bronx, home
