<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- NY-OLYMPICS -- Organizers
are very serious about bringing the Summer Olympics to New York
City in 2012. They envision beach volleyball in Greenpoint, water
polo on Orchard Beach and an Olympic Stadium on the West Side. The
logo for New York's bid for the Olympics. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHICAGO -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- GORE -- In the `''Oprah''
easy chair, Al Gore charmed with talk of his ``soul mate'' Tipper,
promises to make life easier for working parents, and a high-five
for ruby red stilettos. Gore with Oprah Winfrey on her show,
Monday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-SCOOTER-SAFETY -- Those
shiny, foot-propelled scooters are everywhere, but so are injuries,
according to a report issued last week by the Consumer Product
Safety Commission. One of the popular scooters in downtown
Manhattan in April. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ALAMOS, N.M. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-FIRES-NUKES --
Fires in and around nuclear facilities understandably make people
nervous, and so this has been an unnerving summer in the American
West, where the wildfires that ravaged millions of acres edged into
several major complexes. Seeding crews last month work to reseed a
forest near Los Alamos burned in fires earlier this year. (Los
Alamos National Laboratory/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WESTCHESTER COUNTY, N.Y. -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
SCI-BUTTERFLIES -- Over the past 20 years, biologists have voiced
increasing concern about the monarch butterfly's most threatened
and critical habitat, a single stretch of Mexican forest to which
hundreds of millions of these butterflies migrate from the United
States each year to spend the winter. Now in the first scientific
study of the region, an international team of researchers report
that this swath of forest has been reduced to peppered remnants in
a sea of farms, homes, cattle grazing areas and logged and degraded
woods. A monarch butterfly in Westchester, north of New York, in
July, 1999, following its migration from its winter haven. (Suzanne
DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- OLY-AUSTRALIA-BOS -- When
the 2000 Summer Olympics open on Friday, Australia will command the
world's attention as never before. Australia is eager to shed its
persistent image as a pleasant but remote nation, strangely rooted
in its penal colony past, filled with bush-hat-wearing,
crocodile-wrestling, shrimp-barbecuing, Foster's-Lager-drinking
yobbos. The Sydney skyline from a ferry August, 15. At center, the
famed opera house. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- ENTERTAINMENT-VIOLENCE --
The movie, video game and music industries aggressively market to
underage youths violent products that carry adult ratings,
according to a report released Monday by the Federal Trade
Commission. Commission Chairman Robert Pitofsky talks to reporters
about the findings, Monday. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- CATS-ENDS-2 -- After a
nearly 18-year run, ``Cats,'' Broadway's longest running show,
closed with a roar Sunday night at the Winter Garden Theater before
an invited audience of friends and fans. Andrew Lloyd Webber, who
wrote the show's music, on stage following the show's last
performance Sunday night. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- CATS-ENDS -- After a nearly
18-year run, ``Cats,'' Broadway's longest running show, closed with
a roar Sunday night at the Winter Garden Theater before an invited
audience of friends and fans. Confetti falls on stage following the
last curtain call. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
