<P>
   (NYT33) PODGORICA, Montenegro -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
YUGO-MONTENEGRO-2 -- The Clinton administration is worried that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia might move against
Montenegro before or after Yugoslav federation elections scheduled
for Sept. 24. But in the small republic itself, where Montenegro's
president, Milo Djukanovic, has decided to boycott the elections,
there is less concern. Montenegro's prime minister, Filip
Vujanovic, in his office, and president, Milo Djukanovic, are not
seeking an independence vote now. Nor are they trying hard to
defeat Milovesic in coming elections. (Andrew Testa/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) PODGORICA, Montenegro -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
YUGO-MONTENEGRO-1 -- The Clinton administration is worried that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia might move against
Montenegro before or after Yugoslav federation elections scheduled
for Sept. 24. But in the small republic itself, where Montenegro's
president, Milo Djukanovic, has decided to boycott the elections,
there is less concern. The current situation seems to serve both
Milosevic and Djukanovic, with the boycott protecting the
Montenegrin's political base while effectively handing Milosevic
control over the new federal Parliament. Children playing near
pro-Milosevic grafitti in Podgorica, Montenegro. (Andrew Testa/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- BUSH-AD -- Toward the end
of a 30-second commercial against Al Gore, which was produced for
the Republican National Committee but approved by the Bush
campaign, fragments of words dance around the edges of the screen.
But the only full word that pops up -- right after Gore's face
appears -- is ``RATS,'' for about three frames. Republican and
Democratic admakers who were told of the commercial, as well as
several independent academics, agreed that the message appeared to
be part of a subliminal effort to discredit Gore and his
prescription drug program. They said it was similar to the attempts
decades ago by movie theaters to flash images of popcorn on the
screen to entice audiences to buy more popcorn. Frame grabs from
the video sequence just before and after the word appears. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- FORD-IGNITION -- When
thousands of car owners were complaining that their Fords were
unexpectedly stalling throughout the 1980's and the 1990's, top
company executives repeatedly assured regulators that there was no
way to know what might be causing the problem. Even as Federal
investigators opened and closed five investigations based on Ford's
assurances that it knew of no particular defect, the company
withheld many documents from the regulators that would, in fact,
have shed light on the problem. Alan Kam, a former official with
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, with some of
the documents he reviewed regarding the problem. (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) COLLEGE PARK, Md. -- Sept. 11, 2000 --
SCI-CONSTITUTION-PROTECT-3 -- After more than five years of
concerns and planning, the first of a new set of cases to protect
the original United States Constitution and other key national
documents is ready to replace older encasements that have begun to
break down. On Friday, the National Archives and Records
Administration will let the public see one of the new cases for the
first time. Conservation experts Mary Lynn Ritzenthaler, left, and
Kitty Nicholson monitor the insertion of argon gas into a case
housing a page of the original U.S. Constitution last week. The
equipment in the foreground monitors the environment inside the
case. (Marty Katz/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
