commentary was in German, which he doesn't speak. (Allen
Eyestone/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-PRIMATE-EXTINCTION --
For the first time in at least a century, a member of the primate
order, the taxonomic group to which human beings belong, has gone
extinct, scientists say. Debate has not yet ended on whether Miss
Waldron's red colobus, the loud-mouthed, red-cheeked dweller of the
rain forest canopy of West Africa, deserved full status as a
species in its own right or should have remained a colobus
subspecies. But now that debate is moot, a team of primatologists
reports in an article in the forthcoming issue of the peer-reviewed
journal Conservation Biology. An artist's rendering of a Miss
Waldron's red colobus done in 1936. (Conservation International/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- SCI-DRUGS-CHILDREN
-- Many parents might be surprised to learn that most of the drugs
prescribed for children, from allergy relievers to asthma inhalants
and antidepressants, have never been formally tested on children.
Starting this December, however, a new Food and Drug Administration
rule mandates that any new adult drug that could be used by
children with the same disease must undergo pediatric study, and
its manufacturers must list doses for children on the label. Dr.
Dianne Murphy of the F.D.A. is leading efforts to test medications
on children. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) McLEAN, Va. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- BUCHANAN-2 -- With his
political popularity gone the way of his gall bladder, Patrick J.
Buchanan, the chronic Presidential candidate, is feeling well on
the mend from surgery. But Buchanan's 9-month, tooth-and-claw
struggle for the Reform Presidential nomination is continuing into
a chaotic campaign homestretch of state-by-state skirmishes that he
never envisioned when he bolted the Republican party last fall.
Buchanan during an interview at his home, Monday. (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) McLEAN, Va. -- Sept. 11, 2000 -- BUCHANAN-1 -- With his
