</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCENE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glitches, jams greet Games visitors
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ By now you probably know about shrimp on the barbie,
about the magnificent harbor and opera house that frame this
gorgeous Olympic City.
</P>
<P>
   But just three days before the 2000 Games begin, as the picky
world press begins its 17-day camp-out and athletes and sponsors
start to crowd this vast Australian metropolis, Sydney itself is on
the barbie.
</P>
<P>
   The first whiff of smoke came from no less than International
Olympic Committee President Juan Antonio Samaranch, who was left
waiting 25 minutes for a bus that never came the other day. Oops.
Won't happen again, said Sydney 2000 Chief Executive Officer Sandy
Hollway in an apology.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the fire caused by an Opening Ceremony dress
rehearsal. No worries, mates. Just a few firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, there were more headlines and heartaches.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-town bus drivers said they weren't getting enough
training, sleep or food. Visiting journalists had to help lost
drivers navigate their routes. A conductor on a stalled train told
passengers he had no idea what was wrong, thus creating a
mass-transit jam that turned the 45-minute downtown commute into a
two-hour ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Early morning temperatures continued to feel like February in
Atlanta, and one foreign journalist was seen lugging a down
comforter back to the Media Village, a warren of trailers on the
grounds of a cheery-looking Victorian insane asylum.
</P>
<P>
   In a less worrisome world, it would simply be enough that Sydney
is one of the great wonders of the world, that the torch is making
its triumphant journey through a city draped with banners of red,
orange, blue and green, that 14 of the 28 sports are being played
in a pedestrian-friendly complex of venues that looks like a
science-fiction film set.
</P>
<P>
   But like Atlanta four years ago, Sydney is anxious about its
ambitious Olympic experiment and the 8 million visitors it will
bring.
</P>
<P>
   Will public transportation run on time?
</P>
<P>
   Will the weather be nice?
</P>
<P>
   Will Australia ``cringe'' when it sees itself in the mirror at
Friday night's Opening Ceremony?
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is ready,'' Lord Mayor Frank Sartor boasted Monday at
a press conference for the torch relay, which this week makes its
way around the Sydney suburbs, Bondi Beach, the opera house and
onward to Friday's caldron lighting at the Olympic Stadium. ``In
case you haven't noticed, it's ready, it's sparkling.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic organizers trotted out weather forecasters to assure
visitors that the 50-degree early mornings will turn into perfect
70-degree afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, the weather looks good for Friday,'' said Kevin
O'Loughlin, director of the region of New South Wales' Bureau of
Meteorology. ``We expect a clear day with cool temperatures in the
morning and again in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the sort of temperature that will cause
angst to athletes,'' said Milton Cockburn, spokesman for the Sydney
Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the bus that stiffed Samaranch _ and some early
reports that drivers were getting lost _ Cockburn said: ``We've had
some concerns in terms of the transportation system. .... But I
don't think anyone is slashing their wrists yet in relation to
that. It's a good wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a California manager of one of the marching bands
that will play at Friday's opener was injured in a car crash.
``He's apparently got some broken ribs and being airlifted to a
hospital,'' Cockburn said. ``It's not a life-threatening situation
at all.'' The band manager was identified as Bill Lutt, head of
World Projects Corp. of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's subway delay stalled travel to Olympic Park Station,
the only one serving the rambling park of venues, press offices,
concession stands and souvenir stores. During the Games, 50,000
people will use the platform every hour, a number that ``puts a
huge strain on our rail resources,'' Cockburn said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing Sydneysiders seem relaxed about is Opening
Ceremony, whose cast of 12,700 outnumbers the 11,000 athletes.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday night's dress rehearsal, the Sydney Morning
Herald called the event ``tasteful, sophisticated, humorous,
spectacular and inventive.'' While the news media are heeding
Olympic orders to keep details of the ceremony secret, pundits are
reassuring the country that it won't suffer the embarrassment of
four years ago, when kangaroos on bikes filled the stadium at
Atlanta's Closing Ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   G'day, mates. It's going to be an interesting 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
