<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-AIRBAGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME AIR BAGS IN 2 MODELS ARE FLAWED, GM REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The driver-side air bags on 115 Oldsmobile and Buick cars have
inflated spontaneously when the car was started or during normal
driving condition, and 268,000 cars in the 1995 and 1996 model
years are vulnerable to the problem, General Motors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the carmaker has not recalled the vehicles because it does
not have replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is taking longer than would be optimal,'' said Terry
Rhadigan, a spokesman for the company, who said GM was working with
new suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Rhadigan said the company had received 60 reports of injuries,
``primarily abrasions and bruises.'' None of the injuries had been
serious, he said, and no crashes had resulted from the air-bag
deployments, which were caused by corrosion on a wire linked to the
air-bag inflator.
</P>
<P>
   The company hoped to be ready to begin replacements by the end
of the year. In a letter to its dealers, GM said the inflator
modules were ``complex, precision devices with many parts,''
explaining why it would take months to build replacements.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affects 1995 Buick Regals and 1995 and 1996
Oldsmobile Cutlass Supremes, according to GM, which sent letters to
car owners in July explaining the situation.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing a driver can do to prevent the air bag from
deploying, the company said, although in some cases there may be a
warning: the red ``air bag'' light on the dashboard that usually
flashes when the car is started may come on and stay lighted. In
that case, GM said, the driver should stop and have the car towed.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, a driver can apply to the Transportation
Department to have an on-off switch installed on the air-bag
system, but GM thinks that driving without an air bag would be an
even greater risk, Rhadigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers should follow the instructions in the owners' manual and
sit as far back from the air bag as possible, according to GM.
</P>
<P>
   The problem does not affect passenger-side air bags, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
