<HEADLINE>
ANAN ENLISTS WEST AFRICAN COALITION TO HELP KEEP PEACE IN THE
REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As the Security Council prepared to expand the
U.N.'s peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan met on Monday with a group of nine West African countries to
coordinate efforts to resolve the crisis created by a brutal
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Annan used the meeting to seek their help in defusing tensions
between two of their members, Guinea and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   The nine countries in the Economic Community of West African
States, known by its acronym Ecowas, also include Burkina Faso,
Gambia, Ghana, Mali, Nigeria, Senegal and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The group previously fielded its own intervention force to help
the Sierra Leone government fight the rebels of the Revolutionary
United Front. Member countries have since contributed troops to the
U.N. peacekeeping mission and want a voice in the future of Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting on Monday, Annan expressed concern at the latest
border clashes reported between Guinea and Liberia, two neighbors
of Sierra Leone affected by the maelstrom of refugees fleeing the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust that Ecowas will do all it can to prevent any
deterioration in this situation, which could have an adverse effect
on Sierra Leone,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released later, Annan said he was ``distressed at
the loss of life and injuries sustained by innocent villagers'' on
Guinea's border with Liberia and Sierra Leone. The Guinean
government reported that about 80 people have been killed in
clashes and others are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Guinea has rounded up more than 1,000 refugees from Liberia and
Sierra Leone and blamed them for contributing to the rising
instability, according to news reports. In retaliation, Liberia's
president, Charles Taylor, deployed troops at Guinea's embassy in
Monrovia, purportedly to protect Guinean nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The humanitarian implications of the continued instability in
the sub-region cannot be underestimated,'' Annan told the West
African group on Monday. ``Various crises in the region seriously
affect the civilian population.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 people have been internally displaced in
Sierra Leone since renewed fighting broke out last May, he said.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees had registered
nearly 15,000 refugees from Sierra Leone in Guinea since then.
Another 37,000 Sierra Leonian refugees in Liberia cannot return
home because of precarious security, Annan said.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; At Annan's request, the Security Council this week is
discussing a new resolution that would expand the size of United
Nations' peacekeeping force in Sierra Leone to 20,500 troops, from
the current 13,000. The force already constitutes the largest
contingent among the peacekeeping missions deployed by the United
Nations. Annan said on Monday that he expected the resolution to be
adopted by Sept. 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
