<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS HAVEN'T USED SHOTGUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So far, Trojans haven't pulled the trigger on
shotgun &QL;
</P>
<P>
   USC's game-winning drive against Colorado was nearly perfect
Saturday, but nowhere to be found in that sequence was the shotgun
formation that was supposed to be integrated into the offense
following last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the Trojans' first two games, no plays have been run out of
the shotgun, including the last-minute drive against the Buffaloes,
which seemed a natural situation for it.
</P>
<P>
   But USC coach Paul Hackett is reluctant to switch to the
formation, especially this early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you're young at the quarterback position, the
more things familiar that you can do, the better off you are,''
Hackett said. ``It certainly proved itself on that drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett stressed he hasn't ruled out the shotgun, although it
probably won't be used soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a definite place for it. We might use it
later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Waiting for an answer: Hackett said after the victory he
still isn't sure what kind of team the Trojans are, two games into
the season. But with another bye this week, and then a game against
San Jose State, Hackett was asked if he might not have a firm
handle on the Trojans a full month into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely possible,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ford update: Defensive lineman Lonnie Ford (twisted back) is
expected to be OK for the San Jose State game.
</P>
<P>
   USC remains hopeful cornerback Kris Richard (sprained knee)
could be back in two weeks, although three weeks remains a good
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   __ The best of Carson: Quarterback Carson Palmer attributed his
25-for-30 performance against Colorado to the blocking of his
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got touched maybe two or three times the whole night,''
Palmer said. ``I could have stayed back there for 12 or 13 seconds
on some of those throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett believed that Palmer was sharper mentally than during
his subpar effort against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very focused and completely different on the
sideline,'' Hackett said. ``He got into a rhythm that he didn't
have against Penn State.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Top 10: USC, which is ranked 10th in the Associated Press Top
25 poll, is ranked in the top 10 for the first time since 1996,
when the Trojans were ranked seventh entering the season opener
against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruit watch: Notable recruits at Saturday's game included
linebacker Austin Jackson of Serra High in Gardena, linebacker
Michael Craven of Palm Desert and safety Jabril Raymo of Beverly
Hills. There were no new commitments over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   __ Opponent record: Colorado tailback Marcus Houston's 150 yards
rushing were the second-most gained by a freshman against USC. The
record is 180 yards by Mike Mosley of Texas A&AMP;M in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   __ Newbury honored: USC kicker David Newbury was named the
Pacific-10 Conference's special-teams player of the week after
making the game-winning field goal against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury, who made 1 of 3 field goals, wore new shoes in the
Colorado game, after having the sole on his old shoe glued on
before the season-opener against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get those two misses out of my head,'' Newbury said.
``It wasn't like me to miss like that. My brother would have killed
me if I had missed that last one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be the hero or goat as a kicker, but you have to love
those last-second opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mr. Confident: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who played at
traditionally strong Long Beach Poly High, said he wasn't nervous
when the Trojans were given a final chance with 1:14 remaining
against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nerves,'' Kelly said. ``I've played in big games. I was
more anxious than anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
