<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN0912-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman taps Texas for $1 million at fund raisers
 &HT;    By Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Vice-presidential candidate Joe Lieberman knows
he and Al Gore probably won't get any electoral votes from Texas in
the upcoming election. But on Monday, the Connecticut Democrat came
to the Lone Star State to collect something almost as valuable in
an election year _ money.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman helped raise raise more than $1 million for the
Democratic Party in Gov. George W. Bush's home state, including
$725,000 at a pair of Austin fund raisers. Most of that money will
be shipped out-of-state, where the party will run advertisements
intended to boost the Gore-Lieberman campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a close contest right to the end,'' Lieberman
told a group of about 125 supporters who paid $1,000 each to attend
the first fund raiser, a lunch at the One World Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous amount of money on the other side. So what
you've done here today in these two events in Austin, I couldn't
really thank you enough because this will allow us to remain
competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman recounted a childhood memory of watching his
working-class parents count his father's income each evening to
figure out if they ``had a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I talk to my mother tonight I can tell her we had a
good day,'' he told his cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The day was especially good for Lieberman because of the second
fund raiser, a $2,500-per-plate lunch at the Westlake Hills home of
former Dell chief financial officer Tom Meredith and his wife,
Lynne. The lunch brought in $600,000 and attracted such supporters
as former first lady Lady Bird Johnson and former Dallas Cowboys
star Hollywood Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent politicians and Austin business leaders
co-hosted the event, which demonstrated political candidates'
growing reliance on contributions from high-tech leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``To raise that kind of money in the Lone Star State capital is
really a remarkable indication of the support we have here,'' said
U.S. Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D_Austin. ``There's no doubt that Texas
will provide financial resources for both these parties. What (the
Democrats) are doing in being here is they're not letting the
Republicans have all the resources of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lieberman said he still hoped for a ``November
surprise'' in which Gore wins Texas and it 32 electoral votes, he
acknowledged several times that the state is Bush country.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to differentiate between the Democratic and Republican
tickets, saying that the Republicans would dedicate most of the
federal surplus to tax cuts while the Democrats would use it pay
down the national debt, increase education spending and fund
targeted tax cuts for the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a recurrent theme of the Gore campaign, Lieberman
criticized Bush's record in Texas and questioned why 1.4 million
children don't have health insurance in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Gore would propose legislation to allow the
government to sue entertainment companies that target adult
products to children.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush spokesman said Lieberman was ``playing it fast and
loose'' with the truth when discussing Bush's tax cut proposals and
record on health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that Sen. Lieberman spends most of his days
trashing Texas and some of his nights looking for Texas money,''
said Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan. ``The truth is that Gov. Bush and
our state have a good record on children's' health, the governor
signed a law creating (a health insurance) program to cover
children whose families earn up to 200 percent of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said Lieberman's visit would help energize
Texans to vote for the Democratic ticket for president and support
other Democratic candidates once inside the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush hasn't historically had very long coattails and I think
he'll have less this election than he had the last two elections,''
said Garry Mauro, who lost to Bush for governor in 1998 and is now
the state co-chair of Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential campaigns are now relying on their parties to
raise money since the campaigns, which receive $67.56 million in
federal matching funds, have raised the maximum amount allowed by
law.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are expected to raise $500 million in soft money
this election cycle, twice as much as 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman have said they support campaign finance
reform but will not curb their party fund-raising efforts until
both parties are required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: gsusswein(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
