u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT     09-11 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT'S TASK: NEGOTIATING SACRED GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During a critical 90-minute meeting in his
Manhattan hotel suite last week, President Clinton listened for
productive ideas from the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, to
help the badly flagging Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Arafat suggested that the Jerusalem Committee of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference be given sovereignty over
Haram al-Sharif, known to Jews as Temple Mount, the holy site in
Jerusalem that has become the make-or-break issue of the talks,
senior Clinton Administration officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his advisers thought that Arafat's idea was pretty
much a nonstarter, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They interpreted the notion, which they said was only vaguely
sketched by Arafat, as an attempt to pass to a group of Arab
countries the weighty question of sovereignty over an ancient space
that is sacred to Muslims and Jews and a cradle of both religions.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Iran and Iraq, which oppose the very existence of
the peace talks, are among the group's 56 members. The chairman of
the Jerusalem committee is Morocco, and its 16 members include
moderate Arab nations, like Egypt and Jordan, as well as Iran, Iraq
and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his role as a mediator, told Arafat what Israel's
objections would be, an aide said. Roughly stated, Clinton
explained that if the Israelis could not accept exclusive
Palestinian sovereignty, they would not accept the sovereignty of a
group of Islamic countries. The essence of the message was that
Arafat's solution met his own needs, but not those of the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The general atmosphere in the president's suite at the Waldorf
Astoria was, as always, quite civil and proper, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the moments before meeting with Clinton, Arafat had
stalked out of a session in the hotel with the Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, saying he had to consult with his delegation
waiting down the hall. Earlier in the day, Arafat became quite
heated in an interview on CNN, in which he and the journalist
Christiane Amanpour tested each other's wills on every point.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's theatrical behavior was interpreted by some officials
as a desire on his part to show to his people, and the Muslim world
at large, that he was in a struggle to the end on a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear exactly what Arafat's timetable is and
whether the critical political situation in Israel, which is likely
to end the Barak government in its current form, is part of his
calculations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After Arafat left New York last Friday, one of his senior aides
said that the Palestinians would start intensive talks with
Israelis and extend the informal deadline for the next five weeks,
but there appeared to be little optimism within the administration
or by the Israelis that those steps would produce much.
</P>
<P>
   Following the decision on Sunday by the Palestinians to defer a
declaration of statehood for at least two months, Arafat flew to
Egypt on Monday for a 90-minute meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak that appeared to confirm the generally gloomy
prognostications for the new talks. The meeting followed a
longstanding pattern of Arafat conferring with the Egyptian leader
at critical moments in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's information minister, Safwat al-Shareef, told reporters
after Arafat's plane left on the return journey to the Palestinian
headquarters in Gaza that Arafat had given Mubarak an extremely
pessimistic report on the talks in New York.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that there appeared to be one enticing
element of Arafat's presentation to Clinton, though. It showed,
some said, that Arafat knew he could not get an agreement with the
Israelis if he continued to insist on sole Palestinian sovereignty
of Haram al-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's proposal also came as the Americans were trying
desperately to move the discussion away from any form of exclusive
sovereignty and toward the concept of shared sovereignty between
Israel and the Palestinians, or better still, the concept of
``divine sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   According to this idea, the two Muslim shrines at the site, the
Dome of the Rock and Al Aksa, and the area under the earth where
the First and Second Jewish temples stood, would be under the
sovereignty of God, an idea that was once broached by King Hussein
during his reign in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, accepting the sovereignty under God as a solution
would keep the status quo at the site, which is run on a day-to-day
basis by Muslim clergy and guarded by Arab security. Jews rarely
visit the site.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Arafat's visit to New York, administration
officials were somewhat dismayed, seeing momentum of their summit
meeting six weeks ago all but frittered away.
</P>
<P>
   In his frequent diplomatic encounters since the Camp David
summit meeting, where the history of Haram al-Sharif and the Temple
Mount were first discussed by senior Israelis and Palestinians,
Arafat has denied that the Jewish history of the site exists,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By trying to move toward a solution that suggested sovereignty
under God, the administration hoped that the deep and bitter
arguments of religious identity and the history of thousands of
years _ an exercise that could go on indefinitely _ would not have
to be opened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
