<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD DOCUMENT CITE'S DIFFERENCES IN EXPLORER TIRES FOR U.S. AND
EXPORT MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ While the Ford Motor Co. has resisted recommending a
higher pressure for Firestone tires on Ford Explorer sport utility
vehicles in the United States, the automaker was moving by 1999 to
start using a slightly different tire with higher pressure for
Explorers in Venezuela, according to a document obtained by
congressional investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The document, a one-page table listing various tire
specifications for a variety of Ford models in export markets, also
shows a difference in quality between the tires that Ford chooses
for cars and the tires that it chooses for sport utility vehicles
and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The tires on Ford and Lincoln cars and even Ford Windstar
minivans can be safely driven for up to half an hour at a time at
top speeds of 130 mph to 149 mph. That allows an ample safety
margin because few of these cars can actually go that fast,
according to the Ford document.
</P>
<P>
   But the tires on most Ford light trucks _ sport utilities and
pickups _ are only designed for a temporary top speed of 106 mph to
112 mph. That provides a small safety margin because some of these
models can go close to 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Light trucks have been built differently and regulated
differently from cars for decades, a reflection of their origins as
commercial vehicles driven slowly in cities by small business
owners. But with growing evidence that many Americans view sport
utilities as cars and drive them like cars, regulators have begun
looking at whether sport utilities should be regulated more like
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the document does not provide tire speed ratings for
vehicles in the United States, these tend to be similar to the
speed ratings for exported models, which are often produced in the
same factories.
</P>
<P>
   The steps taken in Venezuela are significant because as
Firestone proceeds with the recall of 6.5 million tires in the
United States, Firestone and Ford have disagreed publicly over the
recommended pressure for the recalled tires. Ford declined to
comment on the document.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Karbowiak, a Firestone spokeswoman, said Firestone
stopped supplying new Explorers with tires in Venezuela in
September 1999, when Goodyear began supplying them.
</P>
<P>
   Higher pressure makes these tires less likely to fail and allows
them to carry more weight. But higher pressures also make the ride
bumpier and can make a vehicle more likely to roll over, even
without a tire failure.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the introduction of the Explorer in late 1990, Ford
has recommended that owners inflate the tires to 26 pounds per
square inch. That is a lower pressure than most automakers
recommend for rival midsized sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone did not publicly question the pressure recommendation
in the United States for 10 years, but did so when the recall was
announced on Aug. 9, surprising Ford executives by suddenly
suggesting that Explorer owners inflate their tires to a pressure
of 30 pounds per square inch until they could find replacement
tires. Ford officials subsequently recommended a range of pressures
from 26 to 30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, Ford chose new tires with a recommended pressure
of 30 pounds in 1999, according to the document obtained by
investigators that is dated June 6, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new tire was the same size as the tire being recalled in the
United States _ Firestone's P235/75R15 _ and the new tire was
certified as usable for the same top speed as in the United States,
112 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new tires were introduced, Ford had been using
Firestone tires of the same size, but rated for a top speed of 106
mph and a recommended pressure of 28 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Explorers sold in the United States have computerized
engine controls that limit their speed to 99 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who is the chairman of the House
Commerce Subcommittee on Consumer Protection, has emphasized tire
pressure in his investigation, while Ford has called it a ``red
herring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0409 </DOCNO>
