<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIATHLON TRIES TO SHED ITS EXTREME IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Whether you make the pilgrimage by way of
Circular Quay or by way of the Royal Botanic Gardens, the Sydney
Opera House with its jutting shells is the first-day objective of
most tourists here.
</P>
<P>
   The Opera House will also be a major destination on Saturday,
the first day of competition at the Summer Olympics, but the crowds
will not be gawking at the unconventional architecture. They will
gather on the shores of one of the world's more picturesque harbors
to watch 48 women swim in the ocean, bike on the street and run
through the park. The woman who does them fastest will be awarded
the first gold medal of the Sydney Games, and it is no coincidence
that she will probably be an Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia's strength in triathlon was a pretty good factor in
the scheduling,'' said the race director, David Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter who wins the competition, this will be the
triathlon's Olympic debut. ``You couldn't ask for a better
showcase,'' said Nick Radkewich, one of three Americans who will
compete in the men's race on Sunday. ``I really hope this brings us
out into the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC plans to feature both the women's and men's races
prominently in its first two nights of Olympic coverage from
Sydney, but the mainstream may be too much to hope for in the
United States, where the triathlon began. It is already a
mainstream sport in Australia, where the best triathletes, like
Michelie Jones and Miles Stewart, routinely earn six-figure annual
incomes and routinely appear on cereal boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I get recognized in airports here,'' said Radkewich, a
29-year-old Notre Dame graduate who is ranked 55th in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The general perception of the triathlon may be that it is an
oxygen-busting, masochist's delight. The Olympic event, though, is
not nearly as full a day's work as the Hawaii Ironman, the extreme
version of the triathlon that was first contested in 1984 and has
grabbed most of the early attention devoted to the new sport. The
Ironman includes a 2.4-mile swim, followed by a 112-mile bike race,
followed by a marathon (26 miles and a few hundred yards more). In
comparison, the Olympic triathlon is a sprint. In conventional
Olympic style, it is based on the metric system: a 1,500-meter
swim, followed by a 40-kilometer bike race and a 10-kilometer run.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic distances were chosen to correspond to existing
events in swimming, cycling, and track and field. ``It was a
challenge for us in the early years of trying to get into the
Olympics, because we were fighting the perception of triathlon as a
freak sport,'' Tim Wilson, the executive director of Triathlon
Australia, said.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the demands and the distances, the goal remains the
same: cross the finish line first. The decision to have Olympians
cross it in front of one of the world's most famous buildings was
made shortly after the triathlon received provisional Olympic
status in 1994. That was too late to get on the Olympic program for
the 1996 Games in Atlanta but just right for Sydney, which had
already been awarded the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The initial plan had been to contest the triathlon in Homebush
Bay and finish the event in the Olympic Stadium. Les McDonald, the
president of the International Triathlon Union, thought the Opera
House and the harbor would be an ideal backdrop, however, and he
convinced the Sydney organizers and NBC, which was already planning
to devote airtime to the Danish architect Joern Utzon's masterwork.
</P>
<P>
   Six World Cup triathlon events have already been held on site,
and 11 of the 12 winners were Australians, most recently Peter
Robertson last April. The favorite in the men's race at the
Olympics, though, is Simon Lessing, a South African who left home
at age 18 because he was disenchanted with apartheid and who now
represents Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The women's favorite is Jones, an Australian who is now based in
Carlsbad, Calif., The other two Australian women in the field,
Loretta Harrop and Nicole Hackett, are also medal contenders. Like
Jones, both women are former world champions. Unlike Jones, who
clinched her spot on the team by winning here in April, Harrop and
Hackett were not certain they would be on the team until last
Tuesday, when the Court of Arbitration for Sport finally dismissed
the appeal of Emma Carney, another former Australian world
champion. Carney believed she had not been treated fairly in the
selection process and that either Harrop or Hackett should cede
their place.
</P>
<P>
   There is clearly a glut of Australian triathlon talent, one that
has inspired at least a dozen of the country's elite triathletes to
compete for other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes competing on Saturday and Sunday will begin by
diving off a pontoon next to the Opera House into Farm Cove. After
swimming, they will then bike and run through and around the lush
gardens nearby. Because it is spring, not summer, in Sydney, water
temperatures are cool enough (64 degrees on Sunday) to require
wetsuits. Since triathletes rarely compete in them, the wetsuits
make the transition from water to bike all the more awkward.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much discussion about sharks in the harbor,
although Australian researchers say that cool water reduces the
number of sharks. An increase in shark sightings and aggressive
behavior by sharks earlier this year forced the Sydney organizers
to adopt measures for the April triathlon to soothe the concerns of
foreign competitors. During the Olympics, a team of divers equipped
with anti-shark sonar devices and pods will patrol the water
throughout the swim leg. But in reality, the chance of an attack is
virtually nil. According to Hansen, there has not been a shark
attack in Sydney between the months of May and November in 208
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess NBC will provide the sharks,'' Radkewich joked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000911.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BKO-AUSSIES-NYT &LR;      09-11 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-AUSSIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AMERICANS CAST INTO ROLE AS VILLAINS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ It was a good scrum, a spirited encounter
between an Australian basketball legend and perhaps the most
breathtaking player in the world. Andrew Gaze versus Vince Carter,
for everything in the national-pride kitty.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring image from their altercation during an exhibition
game in Melbourne last Saturday night featured Carter standing over
Gaze, a 35-year-old man with gray flecks near his temples, about to
compete in his fifth Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   No punches were thrown and no one was ejected in the 89-64
United States victory, but the incident immediately thrust the
Americans into the role of international hoops villains _ as
opposed to the hardwood heroes originally scheduled for glory in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights played out badly on Australian television the
next day. It was not just Carter pictured standing over Gaze, like
Ali over Liston, or Alonzo Mourning berating an Australian female
referee called in as a replacement for an injured official; during
one inadvertent and later-corrected call made beside the American
bench, every reserve and assistant leaped up incredulously, as if
the Russians had again been given extra seconds in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men are 40-0 since National Basketball Association
players were first allowed to compete in 1992. But the 15,000
people who turned out for the pre-Olympic doubleheader _ American
men and women versus Australia _ saw David Stern's newest marketing
tool malfunction on occasion, showing its age. They watched
inferior players get under the skin of the Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   Gaze admitted to instigating the mess, which began with him
hooking Carter's arm while trying to draw a foul in the opening
minutes. The two went to the floor and rolled to midcourt, locked
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince was running at me and I tried to draw a foul, and I
probably grabbed him to try to exaggerate a foul,'' Gaze said.
``There was no malice in it. Certainly not. Unfortunately, he
interpreted it as I was having a go at him or something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot-headed Australian point guard Shane Heal got in Carter's
face and made him more enraged. It took a low-key Ray Allen to calm
Carter down and avoid deportment.
</P>
<P>
   In that one emotionally charged moment, the Preen Team had
arrived Down Under, for an ugly night of American Rules Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather worry about that fine line and possibly get
beat?'' Carter said afterward. ``Or would you rather be aggressive
and deal with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Either Australia and other parts of the world are co-opting the
game enough to make America sweat, or some of the greatest
entertainers on earth need to deal with some fear-of-failure issues
soon, before they come across as insecure kids unable to realize
their place in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies are indeed growing up with the game. The men
finished sixth in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992 and fourth in Atlanta
in '96, just missing a medal. The women, who won a bronze in
Atlanta and may push the United States for gold, gave Lisa Leslie
and Sheryl Swoopes a competitive run before the men played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the basketball is so fantastic in the U.S., it's quite
often hard for them to realize what goes on in the rest of the
world,'' Gaze said. ``There is an enormous amount of talent around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if the American men could be beaten. ``It would
have to be an extraordinary set of circumstances for that to
happen,'' he said. ``It's highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' composure causes more concern than the
competition. Gary Payton and Tim Hardaway feed off the bully role,
always talking and instigating.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett is more playful, but he can't just win; he needs
to dominate to feel good about himself. Zo is Zo, always ready to
blow _ whether it's New York or New Zealand. Level-headed souls
like Allen, Allan Houston, Jason Kidd and Steve Smith are almost
obscured.
</P>
<P>
   At the world championships in Toronto in 1994, a team featuring
Shawn Kemp and Larry Johnson made Stern wince in disgust. On an
international stage, they yakked and then cracked, grabbing their
crotches, taunting inferior nations.
</P>
<P>
   With Charles Barkley elbowing an Angolan and his teammates
refusing to wear Reebok's team apparel because of endorsement
conflicts in 1992, even the authentic Dream Team was good for an
international incident or two.
</P>
<P>
   In their own cocoon before the exhibition on Saturday night, the
Americans somehow felt disrespected by the host nation. Several
players said they were emotionally wounded by a pregame article in
a Sydney newspaper that said, essentially, that they were a team of
nobodies, instead of lauding them as the world's greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they felt that the Southern Hemisphere had to be
eternally punished. ``My motto is, you don't wake a sleeping dog,''
Mourning said after the game. ``I felt a little disrespected.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich, the U.S. coach, actually went along with this
theme proving, sadly, that even overseas you must feel slighted and
have your guys back to maintain respect in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, too, often created artificial motivation, using
the most innocuous comments to juice himself up for a game. He
could be ornery and mean for no justifiable reason. But he also
comported himself well internationally, understanding that he was
the show rather than a bull imported for the local matador to slay.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 team, with an average age of 27.6 years, is made up of
youngsters in many ways, players who do not yet fully grasp their
role as celebrity ballplayers who deigned to come to Sydney and
compete against mortals. Like the league today, they simply do not
yet have the pedigree, experience or the tools of some of their
mature and classy Olympic predecessors.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least they have three weeks to grow up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
