<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SLAYER-PENALTY-KAN &LR;      09-11 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYER-PENALTY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES OF SLAYER, VICTIM CAUGHT UP IN MISSOURI'S DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ One man is dead. Another is waiting to die.
</P>
<P>
   One mother mourns a son murdered 11 years ago. Another couple
prepares to lose their son to Missouri's death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Lifelong residents of Kansas City, the Harris and Willoughby
families had never seen one another until after George Harris
killed 20-year-old Stan Willoughby in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the trial, at which Harris was sentenced to death by
lethal injection, the families never met.
</P>
<P>
   Late tonight, they will be together in the Potosi Correctional
Center in southeastern Missouri. Unless a last-minute stay of
execution spares Harris, his family and the Willoughbys will watch
prison authorities strap him to a gurney and inject an intravenous
poison that will kill him a few minutes after midnight. He will be
the fourth Jackson County resident executed by the state since
Missouri reinstated the death penalty in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' death will provide closure for Minnie Willoughby,
Stanley's mother, and an additional measure of pain for Edward and
Carrie Mae Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard on his mother, just like it was for
me,'' Willoughby, 62, said last week. ``She's going to hurt just
like I did. I got nothing against that family. No, his execution's
not going to change anything, but it's going to help me. I want him
executed. If you can't give a life, don't take a life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harrises say they feel for Willoughby but want their son's
life spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can prepare yourself for that,'' said
Edward Harris, 66, on his son's approaching execution. ``I'm just
trying to cope with it. I feel for Mrs. Willoughby. I imagine she
feels like we do about our son. She misses him. We sure do miss
ours. When young men and young girls make mistakes, it hurts two
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 300 miles away from Kansas City, alone in his cell on
death row, George Harris tries to push aside thoughts of his
family, his two children and Stanley Willoughby. Instead he focuses
on his law books, looking for an angle that might save his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to lie on the gurney, it will hurt me to see my
parents over there,'' said Harris, 41.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke into a telephone receiver, his words echoed faintly
from behind the bulletproof glass in the prison's visiting room.
``I apologized in the course of the trial. Mrs. Willoughby don't
have no remorse for me. I understand how she feels. I can't change
her feelings. I got to be strong. I wish I could change the pain.''
Family ties
</P>
<P>
   In the face of death, a parent's love is stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Willoughby remembers her son as a generous young man who
helped those in need. The fact that he died in a house considered a
crack den by authorities has no bearing on who he was, she
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' Willoughby said.
``People're going to lie and say what they are going to say. But it
doesn't matter. Stanley had a very good attitude. If he had
something you needed, he'd give it to you. That's how I raised my
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Harrises describe their son as ``just as normal
as can be. He's nice,'' his mother said. ``He wouldn't harm a hair
on your head. You'd like him. Nice person. Very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Donn-e, 17, called her father a ``good man. He
tells me to carry myself as a young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was another side to Harris. He had five felony
convictions between 1976 and 1989. He also was accused of four
armed robberies, but the charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Then on March 11, 1989, Harris killed Stanley Willoughby.
</P>
<P>
   According to evidence presented in the trial, Harris shot
Willoughby with a .41 caliber-Magnum revolver at Willoughby's house
on Chelsea Avenue. Prosecutors said Harris killed Willoughby
because he was too slow in fetching machine guns that Harris had
asked him to hide.
</P>
<P>
   The defense countered that Willoughby and others in the house
had tried to steal the Thompson and Uzi machine guns that belonged
to Harris and, in the resulting argument, Harris killed Willoughby
in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else saw the victim with a gun,'' said Patrick W.
Peters, who prosecuted Harris. ``Harris was well known for robbing
and shooting people. This is a cold mother. You don't have guns?
Bam! Go find them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner Davis, an attorney representing Harris, claims to have
found an ``impartial third-party witness who saw (Willoughby)
advancing with a weapon at Harris. That would have been of critical
importance. The jury would have benefited from hearing that
testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis filed petitions for a stay with the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the 8th Circuit and the Missouri Supreme Court, which were
denied Friday. He filed another petition with the U.S. Supreme
Court on Monday.
Death row
</P>
<P>
   George Harris has spent his 10 years at Potosi studying the law
and regretting the day he laid eyes on those machine guns. To him,
what happened that day stemmed from a simple business transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the streets, you're hustling,'' Harris said.
``You deal with hot stuff.'' As he spoke, he slapped the palm of
his left hand or tapped the bulletproof glass to emphasize a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a salesman out to make a profit. The guns were pawned to
me for $500. I could sell them for $2,000. That's what I'm looking
at. It's like real estate. You buy a house for a certain amount,
fix it up and sell it for more. See what I'm saying?''
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses any characterizations of him as a violent man. In
his mind, they are exaggerations of people who have set him up so
they wouldn't have to go to jail. He continues to assert that he
shot Willoughby in self-defense. He regrets his fondness for
gambling that first drew him to the streets. He says he is now a
practicing Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in somebody more powerful than me and you,'' Harris
said. ``If the execution takes place, I believe I will meet my
higher power. I know I got a good heart. He knows. Nobody's
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   He first learned that his execution had been scheduled when he
was removed from the general prison population last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come and get you and handcuff you and then they tell
you,'' he said. ``It hit me. I wasn't going to do something silly.
I wasn't going to cry. My attitude _ where you going to take me?
Let's go. That's how I look at it. Let's go.''
Home front
</P>
<P>
   Edward and Carrie Mae Harris blame the judicial system for their
son's plight. In their view, George Harris should not have been
charged with first-degree murder for a shooting they say resulted
from an argument and was not premeditated.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they catch themselves talking about him in the past
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never talked back or cursed me,'' Edward Harris said last
week from his home on East 58th Terrace, off Swope Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of our children,'' Carrie Mae Harris said sitting near
her husband in the living room. ``We've been lucky on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Harris estimated that he has spent almost $40,000 in
legal fees on behalf of his son, mortgaging his house to raise the
money. With interest, he said he owes $66,000 on the loan, a huge
amount for a man who earns only $1,900 a month from a retirement
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to be a parent when you're poor and have to
work,'' he said. ``We had to work nights. Your kids are supposed to
be home, but might not be. They might just beat you home five
minutes before you arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Mae Harris looked at a faded wedding photograph of her
daughter. It is a group portrait. George Harris stands near his
sister wearing a white shirt, blue vest and matching slacks. He
looks directly at the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my son,'' Carrie Mae Harris said.  &LR; brk:Wrongs
</P>
<P>
   Harris' execution is the talk of the 4600 block of East 46th
Terrace, where Willoughby was raised. It's a dead-end street dotted
with boarded-up homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he get a choice how he dies?'' a man asked about Harris.
``He get to choose how he's going to die?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't kill him,'' a woman said. ``It would be torture
to stay there for life. Only Jesus can take a life. You think he
found Jesus?''
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Willoughby doesn't participate in the street gossip. She
spends her days at her fiance's house on Prospect Avenue and her
nights working at a group home.
</P>
<P>
   Most afternoons, she sits on the porch in slippers, shorts and a
tank top, away from the hot kitchen where she bakes bread. She
thinks about Stanley Willoughby and another son who was killed when
a man tried to rob him. Like Stanley Willoughby, the other son was
just 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, still another of her surviving three sons
suffered a leg wound in a shooting. So commonplace is the violence
around her that she can't recall the month he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two sons dead and gone,'' Willoughby said, returning
from the kitchen where she had checked her bread. ``It's not easy _
especially holidays. You have good days, bad days. I'm used to
being around my boys. We had good times together.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her son was planning to go to college in Arkansas but
became a father when he was 16 and scrapped his education plans.
When he died, he had four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Stanley got shot, I was in bed asleep,'' Willoughby said,
staring across the street at a garbage truck. The truck drove off,
but her gaze didn't waver. ``Somebody called me on the phone. I was
stuck, in shock, couldn't move. I sat there and finally a doctor
called from Truman. `Is my child dead?' `Mrs. Willoughby we need
you to sign some papers.' I had a feeling he was dead. They didn't
have to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, prison officials informed Willoughby that an
execution date had been set for Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought they had forgotten about me,'' she said. ``I
don't feel they should have kept him on death row so long. I work
every day. My taxes feed him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects to feel relief when she sees Harris strapped to the
gurney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked in the nursing field for 25 years,'' Willoughby
said. ``I've seen things every day _ gunshots, stab wounds, you
name it. It won't disturb me to watch him die. When you are in this
world, you got to be part of the world and not do things that is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have feelings for everybody, but wrong is wrong and he was
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
