<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN &LR;      09-11 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AMID BUMPS AND SPIKES, A LABOR OF FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ On a gorgeous morning at Bondi Beach, two
solitary figures stepped inside the 10,000-seat arena built for
Olympic beach volleyball competition. They stood and looked.
</P>
<P>
   All was quiet. High sun, deep blue sky and the Tasman Sea
serving as a backdrop for the surfers riding the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Annett Davis and Jennifer Johnson-Jordan looked around the
stadium, soaked up sights and sounds of a place that soon would be
crazy with cheering and tension over a competition.
</P>
<P>
   For now there was peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really beautiful here early,'' Davis said Monday. ``I
want to enjoy it, and remember this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Johnson-Jordan, along with Misty May and Holly McPeak,
are vying to become the first American women to win a gold medal in
beach volleyball, a sport that made its Olympic debut at Atlanta in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   They are like thousands of other Olympians who have persevered,
shouldered burdens and broken barriers to get here.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many in the sport, Davis and Johnson-Jordan have made the
trip as an unbroken unit. They also represent a bridge that links
families, generations and memories. Davis' father is Cleveland
Buckner, who played one season with the Knicks. But Buckner is part
of enduring history. His claim to fame is that he once scored 33
points against Wilt Chamberlain in 1962 in Hershey, Pa.
Unfortunately that was the afternoon Chamberlain scored 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson-Jordan's father is Rafer Johnson, who won the gold medal
in the decathlon in 1960 Rome Games. The fathers have made it clear
that these Games are about their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased and excited,'' Buckner said from California.
``But this is really about Annett and how hard she's worked. Who
knew that it would ever get to this level? From getting her
involved in something to keep her busy to reaching the Olympics,
that's pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from UCLA, where they were teammates, roommates
and best friends, Johnson-Jordan and Davis decided to play beach
volleyball rather than seek a spot on the United States women's
indoor team. The two started out in the beach team format and
played a handful of two-women tournaments in 1997 before switching
full time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport defined by frequent breakups and mercenary alliances,
the greatest achievement of this tandem is having stayed together
for nearly four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial decision to get together was not based on results
or competition because we never played together,'' Jordan-Johnson
said. ``We made the commitment before we had even played a
tournament together. We didn't want to have to worry about being
dumped or having to dump some one else. We just wanted to be able
to relax in our environment. Making that commitment allowed us to
do that. The commitment makes you more comfortable and trusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The international experience tested faith, friendship and
commitment. In their first season on the world outdoor tour in
1997, they finished 93rd over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to hang in,'' Davis said. ``Financially we
weren't making any money. I was in the hole, but every month
something would come along right on time that allowed us to pay our
bills. I knew this was where I was supposed to be. I wasn't
supposed to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkably short span of three years, they have risen to
the upper echelon of their sport. By 1999 they were ranked No. 2.
Now they have a chance to be the first American women to win an
Olympic medal in beach volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when Johnson-Jordan still can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each step that we've taken, ever since we knew we had
qualified, this becomes a little more real,'' Johnson-Jordan said.
``It started with making the team and then getting our gear, going
through processing, getting on the plane now arriving here at the
venue. It's going to take more and more steps to feel like its here
as we go to opening ceremonies, as we put our uniforms on for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
   The circle will be complete when her father and mother arrive in
Sydney Monday. Johnson won his first Olympic medal in Melbourne in
1956; in 1984 he ignited the Olympic flame in Los Angeles. This
week he will effectively pass the torch to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that motivates me,'' Johnson-Jordan said
``It makes the whole experience that much more special. To be on
the 2000 Olympic team 44 years after my dad won a medal in the same
country is sentimental. It is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
