<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT &LR;      09-11 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAK BREWERS OUTMUSCLE THE STRUGGLING METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bad teams are supposed to be dangerous in September.
They are relaxed, the thinking goes, with nothing to play for but a
chance to spoil a good team's season. The Mets are finding that to
be true.
</P>
<P>
   They lost two of three over the weekend to the Philadelphia
Phillies, who had baseball's worst record. Monday night, they
played host to the Milwaukee Brewers, another also-ran, and again
the Mets crumbled. They managed only seven hits in an 8-2 defeat,
with bases-empty home runs accounting for all their offense at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost for the eighth time in 10 games in September,
dropping to three games behind the Atlanta Braves in the National
League East. Their wild-card lead over Arizona was cut to four
games before the Diamondbacks played at Los Angeles later Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   A weak team is weak for a reason, and the Brewers have
baseball's worst batting average and have issued the most walks.
But Monday night they banged 12 hits, the final one a 425-foot
homer over the left-field bleachers by Charlie Hayes, whom the Mets
released this spring. And when walks got the Brewers in a
bases-loaded jam in the third inning, the Mets could not take
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets played without one of baseball's best bases-loaded
hitters, third baseman Robin Ventura, who was benched by Manager
Bobby Valentine in favor of Matt Franco. They also played without
an effective starter in Rick Reed.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had won 8 of Reed's last 10 starts, but he was not
sharp Monday night. Richie Sexson muscled a homer to right-center
on the first pitch of the second inning, and Mark Loretta doubled
in two by outlasting Reed on a nine-pitch at-bat in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Reed (9-5) worked a perfect fourth and fifth, but Geoff Jenkins
doubled off the top of the right-field wall to lead off the sixth,
and Hayes singled him in. With one out and the bases loaded, the
pitching coach Dave Wallace visited Reed on the mound. One pitch
later, Raul Casanova lifted a sacrifice fly to the warning track in
left, and the Brewers led by 5-2. After a strikeout to end the
sixth, Reed's evening was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' runs had come on bases-empty homers, by Franco in the
second and Benny Agbayani in the third. Franco's homer was his
second this month _ no Met has three _ and of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Franco struggled for four months with the Mets, partly because
he thought he could be a power hitter. In a two-week stint at Class
AAA Norfolk in August, he shortened his swing and has gotten back
to hitting line drives. Two of those have gone over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   But none of Franco's 13 career home runs have come with the
bases loaded, and he batted in that situation in the third. After
Agbayani's two-out homer, Milwaukee starter Paul Rigdon wavered,
allowing a single to Derek Bell and two walks. Franco came up and
lined sharply to short, but Loretta caught it on one hop and threw
out Franco to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rigdon lasted until the seventh, when David Weathers relieved
him with two outs and a runner on, and got Agbayani to fly out.
Rigdon improved to 4-4 over all with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura almost always starts against right-handers, and he
seemed dumbfounded to be out of the lineup for the third time in
five games. Like most players, Ventura seems to believe he can best
fight a slump by playing through it. Valentine had given him that
chance until this month, when the slump has worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine rested Ventura last Wednesday because a ball had
deflected off the top of the batting cage and struck his elbow in
batting practice the day before; Ventura said he was healthy enough
to play. Ventura got a routine off-day Sunday but was benched again
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said that Ventura needed the extra day to give him
time to work on his swing. ``You don't hit with theory _ you hit
with feeling,'' Valentine said. ``And he needs to have a good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, whose .222 batting average is about 50 points below his
career mark, accepted Valentine's decision, though he sounded a bit
bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what's going to happen, so that's what I'm going to
do,'' Ventura said. ``I understand it. I don't blame him at all.
All I'm doing is trying to work to get better, and when he wants to
play me, he's going to play me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has 3 hits in his last 43 at-bats and no hits in his
last 23. He has essentially been in a season-long slump and has
tried subtle adjustments in his stance all year. On Sunday, he
said, he learned of a new flaw to correct, and he took an extra
round of batting practice Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to see the ball a little bit longer, really,''
Ventura said. ``Instead of hitting ground balls to the right side
all the time, just staying up the middle a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said the hitting coach Tom Robson and another coach
noticed this flaw on videotape on Sunday. Robson said it was ``not
a new revelation.'' In any case, he said, Ventura has been too
often standing with his front shoulder turned toward third base in
an effort to reach the outside pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Robson said Ventura needed to stand upright at the plate and get
back to driving the ball to all fields, especially to center and
right. ``It's just controlling your center of gravity,'' Robson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine would not commit to starting Ventura Tuesday night,
but he did say this was not an audition for Franco to take over at
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a productive third baseman, that's for sure,''
Valentine said. ``But this isn't any plan for that. Robin's going
to be the guy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
