<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-ON-LINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKERS CONFIDENT INTERNET WINE SALES CRACKDOWN WILL PASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Utah)   By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Backers of a federal crackdown on
direct-to-consumer sales of wine and spirits remain optimistic
Congress will this year enact legislation that would give states
new authority to block such interstate shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bill aimed primarily at the growing market in
Internet sales has been stalled in the Senate since March, its
supporters say it is likely the ``21st Amendment Enforcement Act''
will be attached to one of the sweeping catch-all measures that
will move through Congress in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very hopeful it is going to be passed this year,'' said
a spokeswoman for Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the Judiciary Committee
chairman who has championed the initiative for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Wine and Spirits Wholesalers of America, a
powerful lobbying force behind the effort, expressed a similar
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very confident,'' said David Dickerson, a spokesman for
the group. ``Senator Hatch has not backed down one iota and he is
not a member to be taken lightly. He has assured us it is very high
on his agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Even wine industry lobbyists leery of the legislation conceded
there is a good chance the measure will be part of the flood of
legislation likely to clear Congress in the final pre-election
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see some pretty massive bills in the next
couple of weeks and I think it will go through on one of those,''
said Simon Siegl, head of the American Vintners Association.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate passed separate shipment restrictions
last year, but the latest Senate version has been mired in
unrelated political fights.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, state legal officials would be granted
the power to go into federal court to block shipments made
illegally into states that bar such transactions. The 21st
Amendment lifting Prohibition gave states broad authority to
regulate sale and transport of liquor within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Some state attorneys general joined liquor distributors in
complaining to Congress that the Internet was enabling shippers to
bypass legal channels and making it easy for minors to buy alcohol
via the Web. States said they needed access to federal courts to
pursue out-of-state sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The wine lobby disputed the underage access claim and said
wholesalers were simply trying to protect their financial interest
as middlemen. Vintners say the Internet presents a substantial new
marketing opportunity for smaller wineries that don't produce
enough wine to make them attractive to the wholesalers that control
the national distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   But the vintners association and the California-based Wine
Institute dropped their opposition to the legislation after the
Senate Judiciary Committee last March added a provision that
narrowed the reach of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Internet sales say such limiting language could be
important in court, where they believe the issue will ultimately be
decided.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in New York last week ruled that a challenge
could proceed to that state's prohibition on direct shipments of
out-of-state wines to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Judge Richard Berman, saying times and technology had
changed, refused to grant a request by wholesalers to dismiss the
suit on the grounds that the ban had been previously found
Constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technological advancements facilitate _ as never before _ the
commerce between and among states,'' wrote Berman in clearing the
way for possible trial in the suit brought by the Washington-based
Institute for Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson warned against reading too much into the initial
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point he has heard almost no facts in the case,'' said
the spokesman for the wholesalers. ``This decision isn't based on
the merits of the case as much as it is simply he was in a position
where he felt like it had to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau Chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by The New York Times News Service &QL;
</P>
