<SLUG> BC-BID-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADBEAT DOT-COMS UP FOR BID 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Going ... going ... dot-gone.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest trend in online auctions, money-losing Internet
firms are now putting themselves on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Philip Kaplan, founder of an irreverent Web site with
a profane name that skewers failing Internet enterprises, put
F_company.com up for sale on EBay.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to more than 27,000 subscribers, Kaplan said he
decided to put the 3-month-old site up for auction because he was
``bored.''
</P>
<P>
   The site, a play off the trendy business magazine Fast Company,
trumpets itself as a ``dead pool'' for dot-coms, awarding game
points to surfers who most-accurately predict the demise of
e-commerce firms.
</P>
<P>
   By yesterday afternoon, the auction attracted more than 70 bids,
with the top bid just under $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the auction has all the appearance of a prank since
Kaplan's site, after all, pokes fun at the Internet economy. Sure
enough, the person who placed a $10 million bid, Edward Reed,
turned out to be a college sophomore at Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke,'' Reed said of his bid. The bid was later
removed, and some other bids appeared to be made in jest. Although
EBay requires people who place bids of more than $15,000 to give
their credit card numbers, there is usually no financial penalty
for placing phony bids, though users can be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kaplan told Cnet that he was serious about the auction.
He said he didn't have time to convert the site into a profitable
business. And he said auctioning the site on EBay was easier than
negotiating with individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan isn't alone. Other dot-coms are also trying to sell
themselves online.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Freewebstuff.com, which paid people to surf the
Web, put itself up for auction on EBay. Spokesman Bill Johnson said
the San Jose firm initially asked for a minimum bid of $2.5 million
and expected the business to fetch as much as $10 million. But the
company didn't get any takers, even after lowering the minimum
threshold bid to $650,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the site has since shut down, Johnson said the
investors will likely try to sell the Internet address on EBay
again. ``A lot of people watch EBay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, a Maryland online auction house, Bid4assets,
successfully sold the assets of a failed dot-com, Civiczone.com.
The auctioneers sold that plus more than 100 other Internet
addresses and some computers for about $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bid4assets Chief Executive Officer Tom Kohn said his company has
10 other dot-com-related sales in the pipeline. The company
concentrates on selling assets for distressed firms. Kohn also said
the average auction on his site is worth $31,000. By contrast,
analysts in the past have pegged EBay's average final bid at
between $25 and $30. An EBay spokesman said that is probably low
now and that it has handled auctions where the final bid was more
than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to sell a Beanie Baby or an autographed
basketball, EBay is the way to go,'' Kohn said. ``We are a site for
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, though, dot-coms aren't fetching as much money as
they once did.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for instance, MotherNature.com, an online vitamin and
health retailer based near Boston, had a market value of more than
$200 million. Now it is considering a tender offer for $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jonathan Gaw, an analyst with International Data Corp.,
said Kaplan's Web site could be valuable because it is widely read
by venture capitalists, technology journalists, Internet executives
and recruiters. Such audiences are normally coveted by advertisers,
though the vulgar name could scare some away.
</P>
<P>
   Gaw also said an online auction ``makes sense'' for a company
that owes its existence to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Internet is also a haven for pranksters, he
noted, most people still ``go to a reputable auction house when you
auction things off of high value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at twallack(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
