<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REELING AWAY: CRITICS SAY OUTDATED TAX BLOWS AWAY INHERITANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although the federal inheritance tax has
survived the Republican Party's latest attempt to kill it, its days
may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Republican-controlled Congress failed to override
President Clinton's veto of a bill that would have phased out the
tax out  &LR; within 10 years. The issue, though, is certain to come up
again throughout the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 82-year-old tax, originally designed to help pay for U.S.
participation in World War I and to ``break up the swollen fortunes
of the rich'' _ as its fervid authors put it _ is becoming an
anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   We're not just talking Bill Gates and Larry Ellison here.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the booming real-estate and stock markets, the
inheritance tax has begun to impinge on the assets of middle-class
citizens who have never attended a $10,000-a-plate fund-raiser and
can't tell you the difference between a Rolls-Royce and a Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, because of soaring housing prices and
extraordinary investment success, people who thought of themselves
as working Joes are being surprised by this tax,'' says Norm Boone,
a San Francisco financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, even a Democratic president could find it
politically perilous to support a high-percentage tax that puts the
squeeze on growing legions of his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 65 of the 212 Democrats in the House of Representatives
sided with the Republicans when the bill was passed. The House
failed to override the veto only because several Democrats reneged
on their original votes for the sake of party unity in an election
year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax, which brings the government about $23 billion in
revenues annually, takes a bite out of estates whose value exceeds
$675,000. (There are special exemptions or postponements when
assets are passed along to a spouse.)
</P>
<P>
   The bite starts at 37 percent on assets that exceed $675,000 and
is graduated upward to 55 percent on multimillion-dollar estates.
</P>
<P>
   While the $675,000 cutoff is scheduled to be raised in stages to
$1 million by 2006, the notion that $675,000 today constitutes a
``swollen fortune of the rich'' ought to provoke a few horse laughs
from just about anyone living in the San Francisco Bay Area _
particularly those who have bought or sold a house recently.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, $675,000 will buy you a reasonably spacious,
decently maintained suburban house on a street where it's safe to
walk your dog at night.
</P>
<P>
   In vetoing the bill to terminate the inheritance tax, Clinton
noted that only 2 percent of estates are required to pay it.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while he might be inclined to parcel out tax
breaks from the $4.6 trillion budget surplus projected for the next
decade, he doesn't particularly want to give them to ``the
wealthiest few.''
</P>
<P>
   That viewpoint is echoed by Michael Ettlinger, tax-policy
director of Citizens for Tax Justice, which ardently supports the
inheritance tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to give tax cuts, let's give tax cuts to
people who are most in need,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the inheritance tax reply that it indirectly has
adverse effects on far more than 2 percent of all estates.
</P>
<P>
   Many people whose estates would otherwise be vulnerable to the
tax manage to avoid it by giving money away or by establishing
foundations and trusts that limit their control of their assets.
</P>
<P>
   Says Dan Blankenburg, manager of legislative affairs with the
National Federation of Independent Business in Washington, D.C.:
``More people deal with this on a daily basis than you can
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Galina Knackwurst _ not her real name because she
requests anonymity _ an 84-year-old widow living in Corte Madera,
Calif. Her house, which she and her husband built for $30,000 in
1959, now is worth around $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   She worked for many years, but is long retired and living
``comfortably _ as long as I stay well'' off her pension and other
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I wouldn't have given the inheritance tax any
thought,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she feels compelled to play the legal angles, which
includes making gifts of up to $10,000 per person per year _ the
tax-exempt limit _ to her son, daughter and their children.
</P>
<P>
   If she doesn't stay well, perhaps her heirs will give some of
the money back to meet any extra expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are all those venturesome high-tech entrepreneurs who
have been fortunate enough to carve out a niche for their new
products and services in this receptive economy.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their reward, they must seek the services of
high-powered tax attorneys _ collectively, perhaps, the biggest
winners as long as the inheritance tax stays on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Golec, 35, an engineer by training, co-founded a software
firm called Supplybase in San Francisco four years ago with two
buddies. Early this ,year they sold the company for about $300
million in stock to I2 Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Golec won't say how much he cleared on the deal, although he
indicates that venture capitalists who financed the firm before the
acquisition got the lion's share.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he has now been introduced by his lawyer to a
brave, new world of revocable trusts and probate avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   He says it is quite a culture shock for someone who, not so long
ago, was ``living off my credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
