<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMA BETTY LEFT VALUABLE LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHLEEN PENDER  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Politicians who think estate taxes only impact
oil tycoons, tech millionaires and San Francisco Bay Area
homeowners never knew my grandmother Betty, or thousands of people
like her.
</P>
<P>
   Betty died two weeks ago, just shy of her 95th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her long and frugal life, she accumulated a nest egg
that will probably _ depending on her final medical expenses _ be
subject to estate taxes, which start at 37 percent on anything over
$675,000.
</P>
<P>
   Her small fortune was not built on inherited wealth or real
estate; the condo she lived in until this summer is worth perhaps
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   She earned her money the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Austrian immigrants, she grew up on the South
Side of St. Louis, where her job as a girl was cleaning the family
outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of high school, she went to work as a
stenographer. Although her real and preferred name was Elizabeth,
her boss shortened it to Betty, saying that, ``Elizabeth was too
long a name for such a small lady.'' This being the days before
women's lib, my 4-foot-11-inch grandmother kept her mouth shut and
Betty she became.
</P>
<P>
   At age 21, she married my grandfather, a presser in a tailor
shop. She quit work and had two daughters. But her husband died
suddenly, without life insurance, on my mother's 13th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, she went into the American Red Cross office to
have word sent to relatives in Austria that her husband had died.
Turned out the Red Cross needed a secretary, and my grandmother
needed work. She took the job and held it for 26 years, until she
retired at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   So how did she amass such an ample estate, and put her two
daughters through college, on a secretary's salary?
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and 1970s, she bought 100 or 200 shares in a dozen
or so blue-chip companies. Her brother, a knowledgeable investor
who took big risks with his own money, advised her to stick with
solid companies she knew something about.
</P>
<P>
   Her investments were mostly in St. Louis companies _ like
Anheuser-Busch, Union Electric and Laclede Gas _ and in Fortune 500
outfits such as Exxon and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   She rarely sold a share. She was happy to collect her dividends
and watch her stocks split again and again, and spin off other
companies. The 220 shares of Anheuser Busch she bought in 1979 have
split into 2,640 shares today.
</P>
<P>
   Later in life, Betty invested mainly in certificates of deposit
and Treasury bills. Whenever a CD came due, she would make my mom
drive her to whatever bank in town was offering the best rate.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, she also managed to tuck away money for her eight
grandchildren. After the funeral, my mother handed me an envelope
full of U.S. savings bonds my grandmother began buying for me in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   Until her death, she handled all of her own finances. She would
occasionally call me when a company sent her an incomprehensible
document about a messy merger or a poison-pill plan. I usually
couldn't understand it any better than she could.
</P>
<P>
   Although Betty never took a stock market course or had a
financial adviser, her portfolio looked like a textbook example of
how to invest for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   But our current tax policy does not reward that kind of
behavior. In fact, it discourages it.
</P>
<P>
   Subject to certain exclusions, the government taxes money we
earn, it taxes income from money we save and it taxes money we
leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular opinion, there are not a lot of ways
ordinary people can reduce estate taxes. My grandma could have
spent or given away more money while she was still alive. But then
she would run the risk of outliving her assets. Most people don't
live to be 95, but some do.
</P>
<P>
   Betty's goal in life was to never be dependent on anyone,
including the government, and she never was.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Wallack, one of my younger colleagues at The Chronicle, is
not opposed to estate taxes. He thinks $675,000 is a huge amount of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Many people would agree. Invested entirely in conservative,
income-producing assets (not a house), it might yield 6 percent, or
$40,000 a year. Add Social Security and a pension, and most people
could live quite comfortably _ as long as they didn't suffer a
serious or lingering illness or go into a nursing home. One
ambulance trip cost my grandmother $550.
</P>
<P>
   Todd also figures that if you have to tax somebody, you might as
well tax the dead. After all, most of them don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the dead that shoulder the estate tax, it's their
heirs.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother's heirs are not rich, and they're not
enthusiastic about estate taxes. My mom, at age 69, still works
full time. Her sister is a retired schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   They're middle-class, Middle Americans. And they vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
