<HEADER>
A9602 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHR     09-11 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PE RATIOS ARE HARD TO FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have heard stock commentators say that if a company's
earnings are growing at 10 percent per year, its stock should sell
at a price-earnings ratio of 10. If it is growing at 15 percent per
year, the price should be 15 times earnings per share. And so on.
How do they make this calculation?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: That calculation is bogus. It is a superficial rule of
thumb, cobbled together by people who can't or won't think deeply
about such things. Its only merit is to affirm that fast-growing
companies deserve higher price-earnings multiples than slow-growing
companies.
</P>
<P>
   For stocks in general over the course of many decades, 10
percent to 12 percent annual growth is about average. Because stock
prices tend to track earnings in the long run, you could conclude
that a company growing at 10 percent to 12 percent annually
deserves an average price-earnings ratio.
</P>
<P>
   But the average price-earnings ratio varies greatly from year to
year, hinging on such circumstances as the Federal Reserve's
interest-rate policies and expectations about the overall economy's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the average stock among the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is
selling at a price-earnings ratio of close to 30 times earnings for
the latest 12 months. In years gone by, however, the average
price-earnings ratio has occasionally fallen well below 10.
</P>
<P>
   In calculating an appropriate price-earnings ratio for a stock,
you also have to consider how far ahead a company's present growth
rate is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   If Company A and Company B start out with the same earnings, but
A's growth rate is a middling 10 percent and B's is 15 percent,
Company B's earnings will increase by 25 percent more than Company
A's during the five-year period. On that basis, you might conclude
that Company A deserves a middling PE _ say, 25 _ and Company B
deserves a PE in the low 30s. (This assumes that you aren't scared
off by today's historically high PE levels.)
</P>
<P>
   If the same growth rates were to continue for 25 years _ a
scenario that is possible, but extremely dangerous to predict _
then at the end of the quarter-century, Company B's earnings would
increase to three times Company A's. You might therefore conclude
that Company B today deserves a PE of 75 if Company A deserves a PE
of 25.
</P>
<P>
   So, even using this plausible method of appraisal, you get
widely differing results, depending on the prevailing level of PEs
and how far ahead you can confidently predict.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating? That's investing for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Long-Term Inheritance
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mother died in April, and I am about to inherit her stock
portfolio. I know that the cost basis of the stock for tax purposes
is the price on the day that she died. But I don't know what the
acquisition date is for tax purposes. Is it the day she died, or
the day she bought the stock?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: You don't have to worry about that, says Internal Revenue
Service spokesman Jesse Weller. If you inherit stock, your capital
gain or loss when you sell is treated as long-term. It doesn't
matter how long you hold the stock, nor does it matter when the
stock was bought by the person who willed it to you _ even if the
purchase was made the day before the death occurred.
</P>
<P>
   When you fill out IRS Schedule D, where capital transactions are
reported, simply write the word ``inherited'' in the column where
you are asked to indicate the purchase date, Weller says. That
automatically signifies that the gain (or loss) was long-term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
No Deduction on IRA Loss
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, I invested the $6,000 in my individual
retirement account in a real-estate investment trust. The
investment turned out to be a bad one and is now worth only about
$3,000. Can I convert my traditional IRA to a Roth IRA and then
claim the $3,000 loss as a tax deduction?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have a deductible IRA, then the answer is an
unequivocal no.
</P>
<P>
   You already deducted your contribution from your income when you
put the money into the account, so you don't have what tax people
call a ``cost basis.'' Or, to put it another way, your cost basis
is zero.
</P>
<P>
   So, anything you remove from the IRA _ whether by taking it out
directly or rolling it over to a Roth _ is treated as ordinary
income, taxable at your usual rate.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you have a nondeductible IRA, then you do
indeed have a cost basis _ the amount of your nondeductible
contributions. Your question doesn't make clear what that amount
is, so I'll assume that it is the $6,000 you sank into your
regrettable REIT investment.
</P>
<P>
   I also have to assume that this is your only IRA. If it is not,
then the situation becomes vastly more complicated, and I would
refer you to IRS Publication 590, ``Individual Retirement
Arrangements.'' You can download a copy from the Internet at
www.irs.gov or call (800) 829-3676 for a hard copy.
</P>
<P>
   IRS spokesman Weller says that if you are converting a
one-and-only IRA to a Roth, and if you later liquidate the Roth,
you may be able to claim a tax deduction. That could be the case if
the value of your Roth account stays below the $6,000 you
originally invested.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that you close out the Roth and receive proceeds
of $5,000. Then you report a $1,000 deduction on IRS Schedule A, in
the section set aside for ``miscellaneous deductions.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a hitch. If the total of all your
miscellaneous deductions does not exceed 2 percent of your adjusted
gross income, then none of your miscellaneous deductions can be
subtracted from your income. Only the amount above the 2 percent
threshold is deductible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(at)sfchronicle.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag
column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
