<SLUG> BC-BAYVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY VIEW CAPITAL SALE POSSIBLE AFTER LENDING UNIT CLOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM ZUCKERMAN  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bay View Capital said yesterday it will shut its
troubled franchise lending unit and take a restructuring charge of
$14 million, paving the way for the sale of one the largest San
Francisco area banks.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo bank, which has about $6 billion in assets, said
it will close its money-losing Franchise Mortgage Acceptance Corp.
by the end of the month. About 140 employees of the unit will lose
their jobs, most of which are in Southern California and New York.
Few are in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   With the unit's fate resolved, ''what we're going to be doing is
evaluating strategic options,'' said Bay View chief executive
Edward Sondker. The phrase is corporate jargon for putting a
company up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The bank should attract plenty of bidders drawn by Bay View's
strong position between San Francisco and San Jose, one of the
richest banking markets in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a very attractive branch network,'' said Joseph
Morford, an analyst with the brokerage Dain Rauscher Wessels. ``I
could come up with a whole laundry list'' of potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the banks that might want to buy Bay View are Wells Fargo,
Honolulu's Bank of the West and Minnesota's US Bancorp, Morford
said.
</P>
<P>
   FMAC, as the Bay View's franchise unit is known, is one of the
nation's largest lenders to buyers of gas stations, restaurant and
other franchises. To make money in the business, Bay View has to
sell FMAC's loans to institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bay View bought the company 10 months ago, that market has
dried up. As a result, the bank has had to slow the unit's lending
to a crawl while still paying its overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Bay View hired the investment bank Merrill Lynch earlier this
year to find a buyer for FMAC, but the offers that came in were
disappointingly small, people familiar with the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown at FMAC happened with stunning speed. Bay View paid
about $230 million in cash and stock for it in November 1999. The
bank said it may now have to write down virtually that entire
amount, not counting the recent sale of some of unit's assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible deal,'' said Sondker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(at)sfchronicle.com
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BAYVIEW1 (59996 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
