<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Tuesday, Sept. 12, on the New York Times wire.
For questions, please call Harry Mok at (415) 777-6206 or the
business desk at (415) 536-5172. 
 
 ESTATE:  Although the federal inheritance tax has survived the
Republican Party's latest attempt to kill it, its days may be
numbered. The 82-year-old tax, originally designed to help pay for
U.S. participation in World War I and to ``break up the swollen
fortunes of the rich'' _ as its fervid authors put it _ is becoming
an anachronism.  By Arthur M. Louis.  
 
 NETWORTH:  Politicians who think estate taxes only impact oil
tycoons, tech millionaires and Bay Area homeowners never knew my
grandmother Betty, or thousands of people like her. Betty died two
weeks ago, just shy of her 95th birthday. Throughout her long and
frugal life, she accumulated a nest egg that will probably _
depending on her final medical expenses _ be subject to estate
taxes, which start at 37 percent on anything over $675,000. Her
small fortune was not built on inherited wealth or real estate; the
condo she lived in until this summer is worth perhaps $40,000.
 Column by Kathleen Pender  
 
 BID:  Going ... going ... dot-gone. In the latest trend in online
auctions, money-losing Internet firms are now putting themselves on
the block. On Monday, Philip Kaplan, founder of an irreverent Web
site with a profane name that skewers failing Internet enterprises,
put F_company.com up for sale on EBay.  By Todd 
 Wallack  
 
 BAYVIEW:  Bay View Capital said Monday it will shut its troubled
franchise lending unit and take a restructuring charge of $14
million, paving the way for the sale of one the largest local
banks. The San Mateo, Calif., bank, which has about $6 billion in
assets, said it will close its money-losing Franchise Mortgage
Acceptance Corp. by the end of the month.  By Sam Zuckerman  
 
 MONEYBAG:  Weekly investment advice column by Arthur M. Louis.
