 PERSONALS: The Eye of the Beholder Isn't Dazzled 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
With musicians wielding paintbrushes, actors picking up palettes
and royals setting up easels, the Mirror of London asked art critic
 &UR; Brian Sewell &LR;  to rate some of their fine arts. The paintings of
the rich and famous were shown to Sewell without identification
until after he'd given his verdict, says the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   On  &UR; Paul McCartney &LR; : ``Though the artist cannot draw and there
is no sense of structure, at least the painting has some sense of
vigor. There is some punch and purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   On  &UR; Prince Charles &LR; : ``Old-fashioned in style, but painted by
somebody who knows some techniques and draws quite precisely.''
</P>
<P>
   On  &UR; Ron Wood &LR; : ``One of the few pictures here which suggest the
artist has an eye capable of observation.''
</P>
<P>
   On  &UR; Jane Seymour &LR; : ``My God, this is just appalling! This is
Women's Institute stuff and would not be good enough to grace a
church bazaar.'' Seymour's paintings appear on a series of American
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TRACK RECORDS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Runner  &UR; Michael Johnson &LR;  listens to different kinds of music
before and after running in various events. ``For the 200
(meter),'' he told Playboy, ``I want to put myself in a much more
aggressive mind-set, because it's a more aggressive race. I usually
listen to some rap, usually something like  &UR; Tupac &LR; , something hard
and aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the 400 . . . I want something that's a little more
rhythmic, that kind of just flows. . . . It's usually something new
and current, some kind of R&AMP;B.''
</P>
<P>
   After a race, he said, he's likely to listen to Motown from the
'60s or '70s, ``something like  &UR; Aretha Franklin &LR;  or  &UR; Marvin &LR; 
 &UR; Gaye &LR;  or maybe  &UR; Joe Cocker &LR;  or War, sometimes Earth, Wind and Fire,
 &UR; Curtis Mayfield &LR;  or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MORE IS LESS? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Renee Zellweger &LR; , who gained some weight to star in ``Bridget
Jones' Diary,'' is saying that the extra pounds cost her the cover
of Harper's Bazaar. The magazine's editor,  &UR; Kate Betts &LR; , ``felt
that the weight gain, which was for a movie role, was not the image
Harper's wanted to present to the public _ an actress 10 pounds
overweight,'' Zellweger's spokeswoman told the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   A magazine representative said the decision didn't have to do
with weight but with the fact that Zellweger ``looked very
uncomfortable'' in the pictures, ``and as a result, it didn't make
for an inviting cover.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DON'T SPEAK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A source at Talk magazine told New York magazine that the
magazine's staff has been instructed not to make direct contact _
e-mail, memo or outright talk _ with editor  &UR; Tina Brown &LR; , because
staff input is ``driving her crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Perry van der Meer &LR; , who New York says was hired to
``streamline the editorial process,'' denied the dictum, saying
that staff members were still free to contact the top brass ``at
any time about any issue. And believe me, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Post's  &UR; Cindy Adams &LR;  writes that  &UR; Barbra &LR; 
 &UR; Streisand &LR; 's secretary prepares hostesses by telling them that
Streisand drinks Perrier or Evian at exactly 72 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABC newswoman  &UR; Diane Sawyer &LR;  is talking with Coach about a
line of Diane Sawyer purses, says WWD.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Craig Black &LR; , who raises llamas and lambs, insists that in
the wide world of manure, ``sheep poop rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``1. Got arrested . . . for riding my bike with a group called &LR; 
 &UR; Critical Mass to raise cycling rights and environmental &LR; 
 &UR; awareness issues. 2. Spent 48 hours in jail for said arrest and &LR; 
 &UR; countless hours in meetings and legal counsel . . . Now looks &LR; 
 &UR; like all charges will be dropped. 3. Got fired from my . . . job &LR; 
 &UR; so my boss, male, could hire a woman that he's far more likely &LR; 
 &UR; to (make whoopee to). 4. Girlfriend moved into an ashram, says &LR; 
 &UR; she's not coming home.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Written excuse received by a college professor _ and forwarded
to Personals _ from a student late with a paper. Certain changes
have been made (and ellipses inserted) to protect the identity of
the student and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
