<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
GENENTECH'S BREATH OF FRESH AIR &HT;    By KELLY YAMANOUCHI
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Myrtle Potter's recent arrival at Genentech Inc. filled a
glaring need for the South San Francisco, Calif., biotech company:
marketing know-how.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing traditionally has not been a major focus of biotech
firms, which tend to be driven by research and development.
</P>
<P>
   But that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good indicator that they're recognizing the
commercialization side of the business as equally as important as
research and development,'' said Cynthia Robbins-Roth, a founding
partner of BioVenture Consulting in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Potter, Genentech's new executive vice president of commercial
operations and chief operating officer, arrived earlier this year
after moving from pharmaceutical firm Bristol-Myers Squibb.
</P>
<P>
   At Genentech, she is planning the marketing strategy for the
company's next pharmaceutical product, an asthma treatment known as
Xolair.
</P>
<P>
   ``What got me to come to Genentech was coming here and meeting
the people,'' Potter said. ``The people are some of the brightest
and most committed people I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter's background is quite different from the extensive
science and research backgrounds of its top executives. Genentech's
last chief operating officer, William D. Young, had a background in
engineering and manufacturing. He departed from the company a year
ago to become chairman of the board and chief executive officer of
ViroLogic Inc., another South San Francisco biotech firm.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hellmann, then senior vice president of development, was
named executive vice president of development and product
operations. She had joined the company as a clinical scientist.
Chief executive Art Levinson began his career at Genentech as a
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Potter took a different route into the pharmaceutical business.
To pay her way through college at the University of Chicago, she
got a job at a hospital. At that time, she was interested in health
care but didn't want to be a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   She found her true passion during an internship at IBM through
the business school. ``I loved the business milieu. I thought it
was stimulating, it was cutting edge, it was fast-paced, it was
innovative,'' Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to start her career on the business side of health
care. Her first job after graduation was in the patient care
products division of Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has always been on the business side, first with
pharmaceutical company Merck &AMP; Co. for 14 years and then with
Bristol-Myers Squibb for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Potter said managing the high-growth cardiovascular and
metabolics business at Bristol-Myers Squibb prepared her to take on
Genentech's pipeline of products. Potter said she was one of the
lead architects at Merck of the business plan that established
Astra Merck, a joint venture with a Swedish firm that has since
been sold and is now called Astra Zeneca.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Coles, an area vice president at Bristol-Myers Squibb,
has praised Potter for having ``a passion for the business and the
people without compromising on either.''
</P>
<P>
   To Sue Markland Day, president of the Bay Area Bioscience
Center, Potter's move from Bristol-Myers Squibb to Genentech just
means that ``she's seen the light and started to see where all the
action is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the biotech industry, Potter is among only a few African
American women in senior executive positions.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech executives say to be successful, they need diversity in
their leadership and boards of directors, said Robbins-Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Some biotech firms have social circles that perpetuated hiring
of the same types of people to lead the firm _ predominantly white
males _ which could indirectly lead to a stagnation of ideas, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Potter declined to discuss her strategies for bringing Genentech
products to the market. She would say only that it requires ``very
stealth marketing'' to tell physicians how the product is used
before patients come to their offices asking about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
