<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
DISPARITY BETWEEN HAVES AND HAVE-NOTS EXTENDS TO HEALTH, TOO
(COLUMN) &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week psychologist Nancy Adler will take the wraps off a
guerrilla scientific group that is questioning biotechnology's
governing premise, namely that the best way to fight disease is by
finding and fixing the mechanical breakdowns that plague us.
</P>
<P>
   Adler would agree that when illness does gum up the body's
works, researchers should design drugs or devices to treat the
ailment.
</P>
<P>
   But as the director of the Center for Health and Community at
the University of California at San Francisco, Adler says we put
too much emphasis on mechanical medicine, and too little effort
into addressing issues like income, race and social status that can
also spell the difference between sickness and health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to health than your genes and organs,'' said
Adler. ``Who you are, where you live and how you live makes a huge
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Health and Community is a group of 250
researchers, many of them anthropologists, sociologists and other
social scientists, who are amassing evidence to support the view
that disease has a social dimension. Working out of UCSF, one of
the bastions of biotechnology, has left Adler and her allies
feeling somewhat beleaguered.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, people (like us) have felt like a band of
outcasts,'' she said, as the glory _ and research funds _ flowed to
scientists who tinker with the body's molecular machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of money to figure out what makes us sick,'' she
said. ``But there's not a lot to study what makes us well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Adler's social scientists have been toiling away for a
couple of years at UCSF, she plans to christen the center's offices
at the Laurel Heights campus Thursday to raise the visibility of
their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center is one of those places that will be very important
if we hope to eliminate the disparities in health between different
racial, ethnic and economic groups,'' said Surgeon General David
Satcher, who will officiate Thursday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   These disparities are enormous. Consider infant mortality.
African American babies are 2.5 times more likely than Caucasian
children to die during their first year, Satcher said. Native
Americans and African Americans both suffer diabetes more
frequently than the general populace. Vietnamese women have five
times the rate of cervical cancer as women of other ethnic groups,
and the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these differences can be tied to income. Poor people
have less access to insurance and medical care, nutrition and
exercise. But social status has been shown to affect disease in
ways that seem to confound the view of man as a machine whose
breakdowns are primarily caused by malfunctioning parts.
</P>
<P>
   One influential study of thousands of British civil servants _
all of whom had access to the same socialized health care _ found
that their status in the hierarchy was the single best predictor of
health.
</P>
<P>
   Even after controlling for age, weight, family history and other
medical variables, people in the top rank were healthier than those
in the second rank, and so on down to the ninth and lowest tier of
officials who were the sickest of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   It would be as if BMWs driven in Richmond evidenced more engine
and transmission breakdowns than the same cars driven in Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One rheumatologist described two patients, one a truck driver
and the other an insurance executive, who had such similar
arthritis indications that their charts could have been
interchangeable,'' Adler said. ``A year later the truck driver was
flat on his back, while the executive was still working and playing
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for such different outcomes in two similar
patients, treated by the same physician? Adler postulates that
people who feel in charge of their lives are healthier. They have
greater disease resistance, and when they do get chronic conditions
like arthritis, they are more apt to have milder symptoms than
people who feel they are being ground underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   Social analysis can also be applied to the health status of
ethnic and minority groups, although such efforts are likely to
raise eyebrows or touch nerves. For instance, one group of center
researchers is puzzling over why Latino women have fewer postnatal
problems than African American women of comparable economic status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latino women, despite their poverty, have fairly good birth
outcomes,'' Adler said, leading researchers to ask, ``What is it
about Latino culture that is protective'' of pregnant women?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the flip side of the question carries an implicit
criticism of African American culture, imparting a preachy and
judgmental tone to the social school of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say I'm guilty of that, but I don't think it's
preaching,'' said Satcher, who added that he believes individual
choice is constrained by the circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people should exercise five days a week, but if we
don't have parks that are safe to walk and jog in,'' Satcher said,
then it is society that is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers like Adler say the best way to improve health is
through community organization. Consider lung cancer, a top killer
and one that disproportionately affects the poor. Finding a new
treatment for lung cancer would be great. But eliminating cigarette
billboards and undertaking aggressive anti-smoking campaigns could
prevent the cancers before they start. Likewise, Adler would target
the surplus of liquor stores in poor neighborhoods to lessen the
problems of alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But such organizing impulses must come from the grass roots.
They can't be imposed by visiting do-gooders. ``Two things have
failed in the past,'' Adler said. ``Academics have failed when they
parachuted into a community, and communities have failed when they
didn't have the expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   What the center hopes to do is help community groups tackle
their own public health problems by linking the groups to
foundation grants and government programs to pay for public health
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Social health advocates hope to do more than bemoan the problem.
``We have set a 10-year goal of eliminating disparities in health
care between different racial, ethnic and economic groups,''
Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem wildly optimistic. After all, haves and have-nots
are the oldest rivals in history.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems to me that a nation smart enough to crack the
genetic code, and bold enough to redesign plants, animals and even
people, should have the moral courage to make sure that all its
people get the same basic health care.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the center or to organize a community
health effort, contact Susan Garritson at (415) 476-7408 or visit
 &LR; chc.ucsf.edu &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
