<HEADLINE>
EMERSON COUNTED ON BY KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ As the Los Angeles Kings' first-round
playoff series vs. Detroit was slipping away last spring, no one
felt more helpless than Nelson Emerson.
</P>
<P>
   He had been brought in at the March 15 trade deadline along with
Kelly Buchberger to provide scoring and character. Against the Red
Wings, the Kings showed neither.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, a five-time 20-goal scorer, was sidelined with a broken
finger, suffered just five games after he joined the team from
Atlanta. He got back for the fourth and final game against Detroit,
but his Kings career really began last Friday with the opening of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about the improvements we made over the summer, I
count Nelson in there,'' said coach Andy Murray, an assistant in
Winnipeg during the 1993-94 season when Emerson scored a
career-high 33 goals for the Jets. ``He has looked terrific in our
first few practices, great timing and instincts. We didn't get to
see much of him last year, but you're going to hear a lot about
this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson will be teamed on the second line with center Bryan
Smolinski and winger Glen Murray. With the contract holdout of
first-line center Jozef Stumpel expected to drag on, the
performance of the second unit could become even more critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I played only five games last year before the
injury, I got back for the last game of the playoffs and that made
me feel like part of the team,'' Emerson said. ``I didn't come in
this week feeling like a stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be a stretch to say Emerson, 33, has felt that way
the past few years. He has played for five organizations since the
end of the 1998 season. The next year began with 33 games for
Carolina, 27 games with Chicago, three more with Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson signed a four-year deal with expansion Atlanta last
summer that will pay him $1.8 million this year and also has an
option year in 2002-03 at $2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   By joining the Kings in a deal that sent Donald Audette and
Franticek Kaberle to the Thrashers, Emerson was reunited with Rob
Blake, a friend from childhood outside Toronto and a college
teammate at Bowling Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent a lot of time together since I`ve gotten here,''
said Emerson, who moved his family to Southern California last
month.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: No movement on the Stumpel front. The Kings have
offered a three-year contract for more per season than the $1.75
million he made in 1999-2000. . . . Newcomer Mathieu Schneider
missed practice with a hip pointer. Fourth-line center Bob Corkum
will skip today's workout with the same injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
