<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE KILLING TIME UNTIL PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even with the Yankees in control of the American
League East, Manager Joe Torre qualifies comments he makes about
postseason plans with the disclaimer that his team has not actually
clinched a spot.
</P>
<P>
   But it is probably only a matter of time now, and the Yankees'
priorities for the final weeks of the season are changing. With
their starting pitching strong and their offense generating ample
runs, the Yankees need to stabilize their middle relief before the
playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   They took a major step in that direction Monday night, even
though they lost to the Boston Red Sox, 4-0, at Yankee Stadium.
After Orlando Hernandez surrendered four runs in six innings, the
struggling left-hander Mike Stanton struck out the side in the
seventh, and Jeff Nelson allowed one hit and no runs in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Rolando Arrojo allowed five hits and no runs in seven
and one-third innings in helping to snap the Yankees' four-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   In their final meetings with Boston during the regular season,
the Yankees took three of four games from the Red Sox over the past
four days, pushing their lead over Boston and Toronto to eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   Torre would never suggest that the Yankees are in a position to
coast a little bit, but Torre does have the luxury of discretion
when he determines his lineup every day; the Red Sox are fielding
Nomar Garciaparra, Trot Nixon and Pete Schourek and others with
nagging injuries out of necessity. Torre rested David Justice and
his sore right leg Monday night, and the Yankees are easing Bernie
Williams (strained rib cage) back into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Yankees clinch, Torre can manage the way he might
in spring training. He can limit the starts of his position
players, the pitch counts of his starters, and regulate the way he
uses his relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The sort of situation presented itself Monday night. The Yankees
trailed, 4-0, after six innings, and even though the game was not
close and Arrojo did not appear to be in jeopardy, Torre summoned
Stanton to pitch the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, who had allowed home runs in four consecutive outings
in one stretch in the last month, struck out Nixon, Jose Offerman,
and Carl Everett, throwing high fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than leave Stanton in for the eighth, Torre called for
his other setup man, Nelson, to pitch the eighth, and Nelson threw
well, whiffing Brian Daubach to end his stint.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and Stanton are the linchpins in the late innings, after
the starter tires and before Mariano Rivera takes over. If the
Yankees were to play Cleveland in the first round of the playoffs,
which is what would happen if the playoffs began today, then Nelson
would pitch to the likes of Manny Ramirez and Travis Fryman, and
Stanton would be needed against the switch-hitters Kenny Lofton,
Omar Vizquel and Roberto Alomar, as well as the slugger Jim Thome.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest games Hernandez pitched in Cuba, he said last week,
were the games he pitched against Rolando Arrojo. El Duque pitched
for Industriales and Arrojo was the ace of Villa Clara, and the
stadiums filled and the atmosphere was tense.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo was better Monday night, his stuff sharper, more
explosive. Hernandez's fastball was exceptional in his previous
start, in Kansas City; some of his teammates said they had never
seen him use his fastball as aggressively as he did against the
Royals, a good offensive team.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez's fastball had far less zip Monday night, and the
Red Sox hitters swung lustily, bashing about a half-dozen foul home
runs, along with a couple that stayed fair. Hernandez walked Nixon
leading off the game, after getting ahead in the count no balls and
two strikes, and Offerman ripped a fastball for a two-run homer _
the first home run allowed by the Yankees since Sept. 3, a span of
66 consecutive innings, including the entire seven-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez looked frustrated in the Yankee dugout after the
half-inning, shaking his head, sweeping the air with his hand in
remorse. Jorge Posada, the catcher who would be the first to
recognize that El Duque's stuff was lacking, walked over and began
chattering at Hernandez, seemingly challenging him, for each time
El Duque turned his head, Posada repositioned his own body to stay
close to El Duque's face.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's first fastball in the second inning was clocked at
91 miles an hour, about 3 or 4 MPH faster than the previous inning,
before he regressed. Brian Daubach singled leading off the second,
and with one out, Manny Alexander drove a breaking ball over the
left-field wall, increasing Boston's advantage to 4-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
