<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-TECH21-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
MUSINGS ON MODO, CLIE, CLEARTYPE (COLUMN) &HT;    By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, odds and ends from here and there.
</P>
<P>
   I reported in Friday's Chronicle that Scout Electromedia's Modo
_ a new $99 device that uses paging technology to deliver local
``lifestyle'' and entertainment information ``targeted to a
socially active 18- to 34-year-old demographic'' _ made a splash at
the DemoMobile 2000 conference in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't have enough space in the story for some details
that give more of the flavor of the Modo, which Scout founder and
CEO Geoff Pitfield said is ``designed for the 260 million people in
the U.S. who don't use PDAs.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Pitfield and his team seem to have done a remarkable job
in designing both the hardware and the software for the Modo.
Although the paging network transmits only text, the Modo combines
it with icons stored permanently in the device to create an
easy-to-use graphical interface, controlled by a scroll-wheel and
buttons on the side of the device. The hardware comes in three
colors: Neptune, Moon and Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the service, which is free forever to those who spend $99
to buy the hardware, will be supported mainly by advertising, Scout
naturally hopes to have lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the demo I saw, the ads on the device's main screen
consisted of only a few unobtrusive words at the very bottom of the
screen, and company officials told me they'd stay that way. (Only
if the user presses a dedicated ``Ad button'' on the front of the
device do ads expand to fill the full 105-by-140-pixel screen.)
</P>
<P>
   The Scout team also insists that they will maintain a strict
separation between advertising and editorial content. Unlike many
directory publishers, Scout won't charge a fee for including a
club, restaurant or theater in its listings. Raw data for the
listings in the San Francisco version will be provided by the Bay
Guardian, but a staff of four full-time editors, plus freelancers,
will select their own favorites and write the reviews, according to
Marc Vogl, the company's content director.
</P>
<P>
   A feature called Gambles will offer randomly chosen dining and
entertainment suggestions. And in keeping with the current mania
for ``reality-based'' entertainment, Modo includes a feature called
``Characters,'' where nonprofessional writers from its target
audience will provide personal commentaries on the local scene.
</P>
<P>
   Through auditions Scout has already selected four local
``twentysomethings'' to take on this role in San Francisco. Olivia
Ongpin owns Fabric8.com, an online clothing store that also
features a digital haiku generator. Alexa Merrill is an instructor
at a South-of-Market yoga school. Justin Segal runs a technology
``incubator.'' And Jude Herrera, according to Vogl, is ``a waiter
by day and an aspiring drag-show actor by night.''
</P>
<P>
   What exactly are they going to write about? Here's how Scout
answers that question on its Web site,  &LR; www.modo.net &LR; : ``Tap into
the days and nights of the city's coolest hipsters, freaks and
other major and minor cultural icons. Find out what club they'll be
at tonight, whether that crush ever amounted to anything, how much
that nipple-piercing hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Forbes, a one-time colleague of mine who's now producer of
DemoMobile, declared that ``Modo defines a new category.'' He
wasn't just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING ON THE RITZ: The hotel where the conference was held,
the Ritz-Carlton Huntington Hotel in Pasadena, was built in 1907,
but that didn't keep it from offering the best connectivity for
guests I've ever experienced in a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the phone in every room, apparently, is a modem-sized
device provided by a company called STSN. It has three ports _ one
that's just a standard phoneline jack, but one for a USB (Universal
Serial Bus) connection and another for an Ethernet networking
cable. Color-coded cables for each hang in a plastic bag in the
closet.
</P>
<P>
   If you lift the lid of the device, you find clear, simple
directions explaining the options: Use the Ethernet cable and port
if your notebook has a networking adapter; USB if you have that but
not Ethernet; and the phone plug only if all else fails.
</P>
<P>
   When I found a CD-ROM in the bag with the cables, I thought I
was in trouble, because my 3-pound ultraportable doesn't have a
built-in optical drive; its external expansion unit has a DVD
drive, but I hadn't bothered to bring that along.
</P>
<P>
   But I tried connecting to the Ethernet jack anyway, and to my
delight I was online instantly _ no reconfiguration required. My
browser opened to the hotel's home page, where a large button was
labeled ``High-speed Internet access.'' Then all I had to do was
click another button authorizing a charge on my hotel bill of $9.95
for 24 hours' worth of unlimited access _ and I was off to the
races.
</P>
<P>
   The connection wasn't nearly as zippy as what I get with DSL at
home. According to the 2Wire Bandwidth Meter 2.0
( &LR; bm.2wire.com/bandwidthv2/bmv2.asp &LR; ), downstream throughput
fluctuated between 155.7 kilobits per second and 546.1 Kbps,
depending partly on the time of day.
</P>
<P>
   But that was plenty fast for my purposes _ checking mail and Web
news sites _ and the connection never failed me. Compared with the
modem madness I usually have to deal with on the road _ I hardly
ever get a reliable dial-up connection on the first try _ it was
bliss.
</P>
<P>
   And even though $10 a day may seem a little steep, it's easily
worth it if you're under time pressure _ especially when you
consider that many hotels have decided to supplement their already
hefty rates by charging $1 or even $1.50 for each and every local
call, whether or not you successfully establish a connection.
</P>
<P>
   To top that off, Wayport, another company that specializes in
high-speed Internet access for hotels, airports and conferences,
set up 802.11b wireless Ethernet access points, connected to the
Internet, in and around most of the meeting rooms where the
conference was held.
</P>
<P>
   I'd brought along my Dell wireless card, but for some reason I
couldn't get it to work, even though the access hardware was made
by the same company that made the Dell card (Aironet, now part of
Cisco Systems).
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, IBM had brought along a stack of Lucent-made,
IBM-branded 802.11b cards to lend to attendees. After a few quick
tweaks to my configuration by a Wayport technician _ basically just
replacing the name of my home wireless LAN in a couple of places _
I got that connection working, too.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was a terrific taste of what travel should be
like in the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   SONY STUMBLES OVER PALM: I haven't yet gotten my hands on the
Clie, Sony's new Palm OS-based handheld, but judging by the product
Web site ( &LR; www.sony.com/clie &LR; ), I'm sorely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The company headlined its press release about the product ``Sony
brings entertainment and electronics leadership to handheld
market,'' and that's just what I expected of it. Given the
company's history of fine design, I figured this product would put
Palm and Handspring to shame in this respect. I was sure it would
have a gorgeous color screen, too, particularly after company
officials said as much back in June.
</P>
<P>
   And because Sony has been associated _ at least since the first
Walkman appeared decades ago _ with portable audio, and its
executives blather at every opportunity about what they call the
convergence of AV and IT, I assumed the product would be the first
Palm OS device with built-in ability to play digital music.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, I was looking forward to a killer product.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what Sony announced is a $400 product that promises all
the excitement of watching video clips on a 160-by-160-pixel
 &LR; monochrome &LR;  _ not even grayscale _ screen. And in silence at that
_ apparently the product has no more audio capability than any
other Palm device.
</P>
<P>
   Even the industrial design looks pretty pedestrian to me, at
least in the pictures posted online.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the latest Pocket PC devices _ Compaq's iPaq
handheld, Casio's Cassiopeia E-100 and-115 and Hewlett-Packard's
Jornada 540 series _ all offer excellent hardware and software
support for digital music.
</P>
<P>
   Given the market-share numbers, I suppose the Palm camp doesn't
take the competition very seriously. But given the excitement
generated particularly by the iPaq, that could be a shortsighted
miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   SUB-PIXEL RENDERING EXPLAINED: In last week's column I mentioned
ClearType, a Microsoft technology that improves the legibility of
text on LCD screens.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of readers asked for more details about what it does
and how. You can find some information on Microsoft's ClearType
page ( &LR; www.microsoft.com/typography/cleartype/default.htm &LR; ) and the
other documents linked there.
</P>
<P>
   But the clearest explanation of the core technology I've seen is
at a site created almost two years ago, shortly after Bill Gates
first announced ClearType, by Steve Gibson, the hot-shot programmer
whose work on PC security I've commended in several previous
columns. Gibson's discussion of what he calls ``sub-pixel font
rendering'' begins at  &LR; grc.com/cleartype.htm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In addition to illustrating his explanation with screen captures
and photographs, Gibson wrote a 35-kilobyte application that
displays the same text with and without this advanced rendering
technique. You can enter your own sample text and vary the font,
size and style to see how it works with various kinds of onscreen
type.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing ClearType at a Comdex keynote, Gates touted it as
a major breakthrough and said that Microsoft would seek patent
protection on it. But Gibson, among others, notes that Steve
Wozniak used the same basic approach in designing the Apple II's
display subsystem almost a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, some differences, and I don't doubt that
Microsoft's researchers have added some refinements of their own.
But it was interesting to search the best patent database I know of
( &LR; www.patents.ibm.com &LR; ) and find no sign of any patent issued to
Microsoft in this area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
