<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-CABLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLES CROSSED
</HEADLINE>
  By TODD WALLACK
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; c &LR; .2000 SANFRANCISCO CHRONICLE
</P>
<P>
   Jason Frankovitz figured it would be a breeze to sign up for
AT&AMP;T's superfast cable modem service.
</P>
<P>
   Frankovitz, a 29-year-old technical consultant, already has
AT&AMP;T's digital cable service. He lives in Berkeley, where AT&AMP;T has
upgraded its equipment to deliver both speedy Internet service and
local phone service. And AT&AMP;T mailed him a full-color brochure
promising to install the service within a week.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankovitz, who has called AT&AMP;T six times during the past
two months to order the service, said customer service
representatives keep telling him he's out of luck. The company
can't serve his home yet, on the second-floor of a duplex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's massively ridiculous,'' Frankovitz said, pointing out
that the service is available to his landlord downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   Frankovitz is hardly alone. AT&AMP;T spokesman Andrew Johnson
estimates that ``tens of thousands'' of potential customers in
duplexes and apartment buildings in the Bay Area cannot order
Internet or phone service from AT&AMP;T _ even in towns where AT&AMP;T has
upgraded its lines to offer the products. AT&AMP;T is the dominant
cable company in the region, controlling the wires in 2.6 million
Bay Area homes.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the problem could become especially critical in coming
months as AT&AMP;T rolls out the high-tech services in more-densely
populated neighborhoods in San Francisco and Oakland. Nearly 69
percent of San Francisco households and 53 percent of those in
Oakland are in multidwelling units, compared with 35 percent in
AT&AMP;T's Bay Area territory overall. (So far, AT&AMP;T has upgraded only
one neighborhood in San Francisco _ Bernal Heights _ and none in
Oakland.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson blamed two main culprits for the lack of service:
</P>
<P>
   DATABASE ERRORS: Johnson said it's difficult hard enough to keep
keeping track of individual addresses, but logging every individual
apartment unit, including houses that have been recently divided,
can be nearly impossible. Some households also aren't in the
database because they have tapped into neighbors' cable wires
without permission.
</P>
<P>
   UNCOOPERATIVE LANDLORDS: AT&AMP;T needs written permission from
every landlord to offer the new services. But Johnson said many
don't return phone calls or respond to mailings. Some have
exclusive agreements with satellite companies. Others don't want to
make space for AT&AMP;T's equipment. to offer the service. Many are
simply busy and don't consider AT&AMP;T's calls a priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the California Apartment Association, which
represents building owners, blamed AT&AMP;T for trying to lock
landlords into 10-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bannon, executive vice president of for the group, said most
apartment building owners would be willing to let AT&AMP;T offer new
services if they would settle for verbal permission or a short-term
deal. But Bannon said landlords are were leery about getting stuck
in a long-term contract, because the technology and market are is
changing so rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they need to do is talk to the property owner,'' Bannon
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bannon insists that AT&AMP;T is focusing on
single-family housing and larger luxury units, while ignoring many
smaller apartment buildings in poorer neighborhoods. ``They're
going for the low-lying fruit,'' Bannon said. ``We would be
delighted if they would respond to all our members.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T denied the statements. accusations. ``We want to serve
everyone,'' Johnson said. Also, Johnson said the 10-year contract
is just a standard opening offer, and it is willing to negotiate a
shorter contract.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that AT&AMP;T has successfully delivered the cable
modem and phone service to many apartment residents.
</P>
<P>
   And AT&AMP;T is not the only cable company having trouble serving
every apartment unit. Seren Innovations, for instance, said it has
been shut out of more than a quarter of apartment buildings in
Concord and Walnut Creek because the building owners believe they
have an exclusive agreement with AT&AMP;T or a satellite provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will become a real problem in the next 90 to 120 days,''
said Bob Stice, a sales director for Seren, pointing out the
company in coming months plans to launch the service in
neighborhoods in coming months with dense concentrations of
apartment buildings. So far, it has only lit up only areas
dominated by single-family houses.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, AT&AMP;T said it is willing to renegotiate its
exclusive agreements to give other cable companies access, and
probably would not go to court to force landlords to abide by the
pacts. AT&AMP;T said the exclusive deals were signed by TCI, the cable
company it bought last year, and said it no longer signs exclusive
deals. In addition, the Public Utilities Commission passed a rule
guaranteeing cable companies access to buildings to provide phone
service, which some cable executives say feel makes the exclusive
pacts void.
</P>
<P>
   But Stice said AT&AMP;T isn't advertising the fact that it won't
enforce its exclusive pacts. And Stice said many landlords will
abide by the agreements anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `I have a handshake agreement with AT&AMP;T and I am not
going to let you in,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies typically give landlords about 6 to 8 percent of the
revenue in exchange for access to the building, Stice said. And
even when landlords give Seren access to wire their buildings,
Stice complains that they often aren't allowed to sell their
service door-to-door. Stice said Seren's service _ selling a
package of phone, television and Internet service in one package _
is so novel for most customers that they typically need to spend 90
minutes an hour and a half with each customer in person to sell the
service.
</P>
<P>
   Stice said the company has signed up about 30 percent of the
residents it has contacted, two-thirds of whom are buying all three
services.
</P>
<P>
   Other cable companies insisted the problem is minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Cox Communications said it can serve ``99
percent'' of apartment buildings in Orange County. Marty Zajic said
the company signed agreements with apartment owners several years
ago to offer cable modem and telephone service, so it was already
prepared when it started launched the new services.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, RCN Communications, which has rolled out service in
northern San Mateo County and has its sights set on San Francisco,
promised that it can serve nearly all apartment dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Spiegleman, director of regulatory government affairs for
RCN, said the company is willing to spend the time necessary to
sign up every building in the city. He also pointed out that RCN
has experience serving densely populated areas laden with
apartments, such as New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, from AT&AMP;T, said he believes the cable company will have
fewer problems in the future because it plans to roll out the
service more gradually, one neighborhood at a time, giving its
sales department a chance to blanket the area. In Berkeley, by
contrast, AT&AMP;T lit up the entire city ``in one fell swoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Johnson has two pieces of advice for tenants having
trouble ordering service. First, he advises them to check with
their landlords to find out if they have an agreement with AT&AMP;T in
place. Second, he suggests residents write to AT&AMP;T at P.O. Box
5147, San Ramon, CA 94583. Frankovitz, the Berkeley resident who
couldn't get cable modem service, offered another solution: If AT&AMP;T
doesn't respond to his request soon, he plans to order DSL, an
equally fast Internet connection that works over phone wires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
