TECH21: This week, odds and ends from here and there. COLUMN BY
HENRY NORR. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DNA: Souvenirs of the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney are being
tagged with invisible ink containing DNA strands from an
unidentified Australian athlete. The goal is to thwart increasingly
sophisticated forgers trying to get a piece of the $389 million
market for Olympics keepsakes. BY CAROLYN SAID. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BIOSCOPE: This week psychologist Nancy Adler will take the wraps
off a guerrilla scientific group that is questioning
biotechnology's governing premise, namely that the best way to
fight disease is by finding and fixing the mechanical breakdowns
that plague us. Adler says we put too much emphasis on mechanical
medicine, and too little effort into addressing issues like income,
race and social status that can also spell the difference between
sickness and health. COLUMN BY TOM ABATE. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GENENTECH: Myrtle Potter's recent arrival at Genentech Inc. filled
a glaring need for the South San Francisco, Calif., biotech
company: marketing know-how. Marketing traditionally has not been a
major focus of biotech firms, which tend to be driven by research
and development. But that's changing. BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI. &QL;
