By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DRIVING LESSONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Guy Verhofstadt &LR; , prime minister of Belgium, has been in San
Francisco for the past few days, and he spoke at a joint meeting of
the Commonwealth Club and the World Affairs Council. But the visit
wasn't all work; Verhofstadt, 47 and an avid cyclist, brought his
bicycle with him, met with  &UR; Dan Osipow &LR;  of the U.S. Postal Service
Cycling Team _ which sponsored  &UR; Lance Armstrong &LR;  _ and took a ride
in Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   - ``A caller reports that a car on College Avenue with its door
open appears to be vandalized inside,'' says the St. Helena Star
Police Log, in an entry forwarded by  &UR; Vera Trinchero Torres &LR; . ``The
car's owner reports that he left the door open by mistake and the
interior always looks like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; - Queen Elizabeth &LR;  will be given a new Bentley limousine on
the occasion of her 50th anniversary as monarch, in 2002.  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Wieder &LR;  notes that Bentley's announcement about of &LR;  the new car
said it ``will fly the flag for the British automotive industry.''
Bentley is owned by Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Lourdes Livingston &LR; , who was in New York last week, e-mailed
her pal  &UR; Doug Morgan &LR;  that between the U.N. summit meetings and the
MTV video music awards at Radio City Music Hall, the streets were
packed with limousines. The only way she could tell a rock star's
motorcade from a presidential motorcade, she said, was by ``the
faint scent as they rush by.'' Morgan said the rockers' scent is of
Mendocino-grown matter, while the diplomats waft vapors of
Colombian gold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANG BANG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association is offering new members who send
in $25 a silver bullet engraved with  &UR; Charlton Heston &LR; 's signature.
This was Heston's idea, reports George magazine, in an effort to
double the group's membership by election day.
</P>
