   &UR; SHOPPING LIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Shiseido has sent word of its new fragrance (perfume is such
an outmoded word): Zen. Amen and pass the atomizer. This innovation
should open the market to new lines of smelly stuff named after
other forms of religious observance: Seventh Day Adventist, Jew,
Christian Scientist and, for the incurably romantic, Anabaptist.
</P>
<P>
   - Driving past a Pleasant Hill shopping center,  &UR; Walt Shugert &LR; 
saw a sign he says warned of the future if the  &UR; Gore &LR; - &UR; Lieberman &LR; 
ticket wins: The T in Toys R Us was out.
</P>
<P>
   - The Llama Poop _ $7 for two pounds _ sold at the Working
Gardener in Healdsburg is superior to your everyday poop because
``it's not as acidic as some manures can be,'' says owner  &UR; Merede &LR; 
 &UR; Graham &LR; , ``it's been composted, so it doesn't contain any weed
seeds'' and ``it doesn't contain any burning agents.'' Not everyone
agrees. ``You've got to be careful who you ask because gardeners
are very particular'' about their manure, says Graham.
</P>
<P>
   - Perusing the Pottery Barn catalog,  &UR; Bunny Henderson &LR;  was
amazed at the ``Wheat Sheaf ... gathered from the field'' and
reflecting ``the bounty of the harvest.'' The price is $49, but
it's ``a generous bunch,'' says the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   - Bring me the fruit: A Manhattan political consultant who once
worked for  &UR; Joe Lieberman &LR;  told the New York newspaper Our Town
that the senator's secretary asked him to get Lieberman two apples.
He should wash the apples, he was told, and hold them by their
stems when carrying them back to the office, in order to keep them
kosher.
</P>
<P>
   When he brought the apples back to the secretary, she said she'd
bring them to Lieberman. ``I just embarrassed myself walking
through the Senate's halls of power holding two apples by their
stems,'' he said. ``I'd like to deliver the apples myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
