<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-11 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      09-11 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING FLAG RETURNS TO GLORY, COURTESY OF A PRANKSTER; SHOT-PUTTER
PULLS OUT: A REASON TO SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Harry Prieste took the dare. Challenged by
his friend, the swimmer Duke Kahanamoku, Prieste shinnied up a
15-foot flagpole at the end of the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp,
Belgium, and stole the official flag. The Irish linen flag came
home with Prieste to Los Angeles, the fruit of his athletic prank
and further evidence of his presence at the seventh Summer
Olympiad, where he won the bronze medal in platform diving.
</P>
<P>
   For 77 years the flag was stored in a suitcase during Prieste's
years in swimming and diving shows, as a vaudeville comedian, a
tumbler, a banjo player, a circus juggler and an Ice Follies
performer.
</P>
<P>
   He did not regard the flag as valuable or worth returning until
a reporter told him at a U.S. Olympic Committee banquet three years
ago that the International Olympic Committee had been unable to
find the missing Antwerp flag, the first one with the five rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can help you with that,'' he said. ``It's in my suitcase.''
</P>
<P>
   Prieste, 103 years old, legally blind and severely deaf,
returned the slightly faded and tattered flag to the IOC Monday as
the organization began a session leading up to the start of the
Summer Games on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving it to them,'' Prieste said. ``I ain't going to be
around long. I had it a long time. A lot of my friends have seen
it. You can't be selfish about these things. It's no good to me. I
can't hang it in my room. People will think more of me by giving it
away than by keeping it.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that he would be giving the flag to Juan Antonio
Samaranch, the IOC president, Prieste said, ``What's he going to do
with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Prieste was born in 1896, the year of the first modern Olympics
in Athens, with the name Haig Prieste. Before the Olympics, he was
a stunt man and a Keystone Kop in Mack Sennett's silent comedies,
then entered the 1920 Olympics under the name Harry Prieste. In his
subsequent show business career, he was Hal Haig Prieste.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he wanted to make sure that the plaque beside the
Antwerp flag in the Olympic museum in Lausanne, Switzerland, will
identify the man who returned it as ``Hal Haig Prieste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm informed by my friends in Belgium that the statute of
limitations has run out on Prieste,'' said William Hybl, the
president of the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste is the oldest living U.S. Olympian and possibly the
oldest one in the world, said Cindy Stinger, who directs the USOC's
alumni relations department. ``The IOC wanted him to come to Nagano
but it didn't happen,'' she said. ``I was worried, and the
committee was worried, about someone this old traveling to
Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   But Prieste got medical approval and arrived at the IOC session
dressed in a blue blazer, white shirt, colorful tie, white cap and
white pants, sitting in a wheelchair he did not need until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste, who learned to ice skate in his 40s and continued until
he was 96, met Carolyn LaMaina at the Coliseum rink in Voorhees,
N.J., where the Philadelphia Flyers used to train, and he was still
performing on-ice tricks with a hockey stick. -- RICHARD SANDOMIR  &QL; 
SHOT-PUTTER PULLS OUT
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter, the reigning world champion in the shot-put and the
husband of the sprinter Marion Jones, became the latest in a
growing number of athletes to withdraw from the Sydney Olympics
Monday, a week after undergoing orthoscopic surgery on torn
cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed the injury has forced me to withdraw from the
Olympic Games,'' Hunter said in a statement. ``Marion and I had
looked forward to competing together in Sydney. But I'm a
professional athlete. Unfortunately, injuries are part of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who grew up in Hyde Park, N.Y., will be replaced on the
American team by John Godina, who won a silver medal in the
shot-put at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. Godina has already been
training in Australia for the discus, at which he will also compete
in the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's withdrawal comes only two days after Regina Jacobs of
Oakland, a gold-medal favorite in the women's 1,500 meters, dropped
out with a respiratory viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter injured his knee last month and attempted to throw at a
Grand Prix meet in Brussels, only to withdraw after several throws
because of persistent pain. He underwent surgery last Sunday and
said that he still hoped to compete in Sydney. He has withdrawn,
however, apparently feeling he would not be a contender.
Twenty-seven athletes were withdrawn from China's Olympic team
after a number of them had suspicious results on blood tests that
detect the presence of the performance-enhancing drug EPO. -- JERE
LONGMAN  &QL; 
A REASON TO SMILE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch chuckled twice in public Monday,
evidence, perhaps, that he is comfortable that the IOC he leads is
past being in a perpetual state of siege.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's cheerful gesture came early in the opening day of a
three-day IOC session leading up to the opening ceremony of the
Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Games have not begun but the IOC is faced with doubts about
the credibility of a new test for the performance enhancer EPO,
chastened by the Australian government's refusal to admit members
of its ``family'' from Uzbekistan and Hong Kong and constantly
under scrutiny about the efficacy of reforms enacted last year
following the Salt Lake City bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beleagured? Beleaguered by whom?'' said Francois Carrard, the
IOC's director general. ``We are experienced in seeing stories
raised in anticipation of more important things to happen. It is
quite normal. We do our job. The media does their job.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days are not entirely normal for the IOC _ and not
just because Samaranch was stranded the other day by an Olympic van
outside the Regent Hotel, where he is staying. In the IOC's attempt
to be more egalitarian and transparent, the president and his
delegates have given up limousine transport for something more
plebeian.
</P>
<P>
   A local transport official apologized to Samaranch and the error
has not been repeated since. -- RICHARD SANDOMIR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
