<HEADER>
A9624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TV-SPORTS-(1600)2     09-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-SPORTS-(1600)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBERSOL LIVES AND DREAMS THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Olympics come to American television Friday, the
maestro overseeing the five-hour nightly extravaganza will be Dick
Ebersol.
</P>
<P>
   No sports television executive has held as much power in the
Olympics as Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports. No one has spent
as much for the TV rights or is as close to Juan Antonio Samaranch,
the embattled president of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And no one has had the opportunity since Ebersol's mentor, Roone
Arledge, to shape so completely how Americans will view the Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea of being in the middle of a 28-ring circus,''
said Ebersol, who persuaded General Electric, NBC's parent, to
underwrite his passion with $3.5 billion for the rights to televise
the Olympics from 2000 to 2008. ``I love being the guy in the
center of all that, sorting out what we're doing and what the
viewer is going to see. There isn't anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol has been closely identified with the National Basketball
Association and with deals that coincided with the ascent of
Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls. But his legacy rests with the
Olympics, as a deal maker and an executive producer, roles played
by Arledge at ABC from the early 1960s to the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he came to us as an Olympic freak,'' said
Arledge, who hired Ebersol in 1967 as the first Olympic researcher
at ABC Sports when Ebersol was 19 and a sophomore at Yale. ``But he
became one.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol's Manhattan office features a giant photograph of
Muhammad Ali lighting the Olympic caldron at the 1996 Summer
Olympics in Atlanta and a coffee table painted with images from the
1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything I love more than the Olympics,
other than family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is not likely to see much of his wife, the actress Susan
Saint James, and their 10-year-old son, Teddy, the only one of
their children who will be in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   By 6:15 each morning, Ebersol will begin his 20-hour day at the
NBC compound after lifting 15-pound weights and running three and a
half miles on a treadmill, a regimen he started four years ago
after he suffered a mild heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   From his ``Captain Kirk'' chair inside NBC's control room or
from a seat in an adjacent office, Ebersol will control what
Americans see from Sydney. He will view what is happening on more
than 100 monitors, make suggestions to his chief producers, Tommy
Roy and David Neal, speak to commentators arrayed across Sydney or
ask a deputy, Peter Diamond, how one change in each evening's
preset formats would affect the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be shocked if we didn't change the formats by as much as a
third, as we go along,'' Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Olympic events beamed to American viewers will be
taped, Bob Costas, the prime-time host, will be live in the studio
in Sydney, introducing events, providing reports and delivering
commentary. Ebersol will occasionally speak into his earpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually guidance,'' Costas said. ``I may say something,
and he'll say something amusing. He's a very calm presence no
matter the circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   In their third Olympics as a unit, Costas, the production crew
and most of the commentators know Ebersol's Olympic formula.
``Storytelling is king,'' said Bucky Gunts, who directs the
prime-time show.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol takes the work so seriously that he bans all
nonessential personnel from his Olympic workplace, including his
wife and Jack Welch, the G.E. chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so annoying,'' Saint James said. ``I'm from the business.
I know how to be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol explained: ``This job requires 100 percent
concentration. When air traffic controllers let families in to
watch them work, I'll let Susan in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol, 53, is the most vocal and image-conscious of the four
networks' sports division leaders. Like Arledge, he is a
producer-executive who revels in being his division's public
relations specialist. But primarily he is a pragmatic executive
protecting his self-interest, never more so than in his vigorous
defense of Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't care what was said against him,'' said Ebersol,
referring to criticism that Samaranch personified the hidebound IOC
bureaucracy that led to the Salt Lake City corruption scandal last
year. ``There is no question in my mind that there was no way back
from the abyss without Juan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol, whose strong ties with the Olympic committee were
enhanced by his appointment to its reform commission, recalled
flying to Lausanne, Switzerland, in March 1999 after reading an
article in which Samaranch scorned American politicians who were
threatening to sanction the IOC if it did not overhaul the way it
did business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right or wrong, I told him, `You get nowhere taking on the
American political system,''' Ebersol recalled. ``But I said, `If
you want me to, I'll spread the word about what you'll do to key
Washington politicians.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said he had met with Sen. John S. McCain, R- Ariz, a
harsh IOC critic, and George Mitchell, the former senator whose
commission recommended an overhaul of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said he had stewed for months as David D'Alessandro,
president of John Hancock Financial Services, an Olympic sponsor,
lambasted Samaranch. Then in June 1999, Ebersol exploded during a
conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of watching this two-bit bully get on his soapbox,''
he said of D'Alessandro. ``His actions demanded a response and that
response is, `Shut up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol's tongue-lashing heartened the international committee,
which needed to assuage sponsors' worries that the scandal was
diminishing the value of their Olympic investments. Having
Ebersol's passionate faith meant the IOC was blessed by its largest
benefactor, who was protecting both his friend and his investment.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, an IOC vice president, said, ``It was important for
someone to speak out in favor of what the Olympics were all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Ebersol quietly met with D'Alessandro for
the first time in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us felt this was a rocket that was getting away from
both of us and it was getting personal,'' D'Alessandro said. ``But
part of the issue is that we'd never met. I've learned over time
that it's easier to throw shots at somebody you didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said, ``We got through the frostiness and talked for two
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro said they found more common ground than he had
expected. Several months later, Hancock renewed its IOC sponsorship
for the Sydney Games and then committed to spend as much as $15
million to advertise on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   That strain of pragmatism and getting what he wants are themes
throughout Ebersol's tenure at NBC Sports. This is his second
go-round at NBC; in 1975, he helped create ``Saturday Night Live,''
and he produced it from 1981 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He left to become an independent producer, creating shows like
``Friday Night Videos,'' ``Later with Bob Costas'' and ``Saturday
Night's Main Event,'' in partnership with the World Wrestling
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Arledge recalled Ebersol's return to NBC as president of NBC
Sports in 1989. ``Everybody thought he was a politician, including
their top people,'' Arledge said. ``I said, `Wait till you see him
in action.' He is a bit of a politician, which is part of the job
of getting rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1995 Ebersol publicly savaged Major League Baseball for
the collapse of the Baseball Network, a joint venture of NBC, ABC
and baseball, and vowed not to make another deal with the leaders
of the sport until the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet four months later, he sat in a box seat at the World Series
beside Bud Selig, then baseball's interim commissioner, discussing
a new deal. Ebersol admitted afterward that Welch, the G.E.
chairman, told him to ``get over your extreme displeasure'' and
pursue a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Selig recalled that time. ``The more we talked,'' he said, ``the
more we talked about history, and in the end, Dick is a very
reasonable, very decent person.'' They agreed to a five-year deal
worth $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, when he decided that the National Football League
was demanding too much from NBC for its rights, Ebersol pursued
``Monday Night Football.'' When that failed, he tried to create a
new football league with Turner Sports. When that died, he teamed
up in March with the WWF to form a new spring football league, the
XFL, which he said would be legitimate despite its pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his tenure at NBC Sports, Ebersol's closeness to
Welch and Bob Wright, the president of NBC, has enabled him to make
quicker financial decisions than his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to take risks,'' said Neal Pilson, an industry
consultant who once competed against Ebersol as the president of
CBS Sports. ``Welch and Wright believe in him. He's earned their
respect. It took courage to chase the Olympics, and frankly I think
he made a terrific deal for NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his most pragmatic maneuver will be on view from Sydney:
the Olympics on basic cable. MSNBC and CNBC will carry 171 original
hours of Olympic coverage, featuring sports that NBC has ignored in
the past, like soccer, softball, boxing, weight lifting and
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had CNBC, and MSNBC was still America's Talking, and I
thought, we could do this,'' Ebersol said. ``I didn't check with
anyone, I just told Samaranch we'd commit to X hours.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
c
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-11-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
