<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S EDUCATION PROPOSAL: $97.7 BILLION OVER 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMIRA, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick A. Lazio Monday night proposed new
spending of $97.75 billion on education over 10 years if elected
senator, with a substantial amount devoted to disabled students and
programs to make teachers more accountable.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-minute speech at Elmira College, Lazio, the Republican
nominee for Senate from New York, laid out a far more ambitious
plan than that of Gov. George W. Bush, who wants to spend $13.5
billion over five years. Lazio's plan would come close in cost to
the one proposed by his Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, whose education proposals call for $123 billion in new
spending in the next decade, her aides said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from cost, Lazio drew sharp distinctions between his plan
and Clinton's, firmly declaring his support for federally financed
vouchers _ although he avoided using that word, instead calling for
``opportunity scholarships,'' which would provide money to parents
in struggling school districts for their children's enrollment in
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The largest chunk of his plan _ $60 billion _ would go toward
financing federally mandated programs for the disabled, the only
part of his plan that drew applause from the 100 or so parents,
politicians and mostly college students attending the speech. And
Lazio said he would encourage the federal government to make some
financing to states contingent on the testing of teachers for
competency every five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If accountability means asking more of students, it also means
asking more of teachers as well, by challenging our teachers to
keep learning and improving and putting their own skills to the
test,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's speech came as he sought some momentum before his first
debate with Clinton on Wednesday. Some Republican Party officials
reportedly have complained that he has not maintained a rigorous
enough campaign schedule lately and has not been clear enough about
what he would do if elected. And it follows within a few days
Clinton's tour of public schools late last week, and new Clinton
television advertisements stressing her commitment to education and
criticizing Lazio's legislative record of voting for cuts in
education funds. This is Lazio's second major policy address; the
other, to unveil a tax-cutting proposal, came Aug. 24 in Buffalo
and prompted a flurry of criticism over the validity of his
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and his aides left promptly after Monday night's speech.
He answered only two questions as he hustled out, declaring
education the top concern in the election and saying his
tax-cutting plan would help finance the education plan. An
assistant explained later that Lazio would propose using some of
the budget surplus to finance both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
