<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S GIULIANI CRITICIZES GOP SENATE CANDIDATE FOR ARAFAT
HANDSHAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday that it was a
mistake for Rep. Rick Lazio to have enthusiastically shaken the
hand of Yasser Arafat during an official visit to the Middle East
nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little confounded by it,'' Giuliani said at a news
conference in Harlem, adding, ``I don't particularly like to shake
hands with murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor also said that Lazio's handshake was ``not a big
deal'' and that maybe he ``doesn't have the background and
understanding of Arafat that I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks about his fellow Republican, who replaced him
in the Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton, were not well
received by Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is perfectly welcome to have his opinions,'' said
Dan McLagan, Lazio's chief spokesman. He added that Lazio's
handshake ``was appropriate at the time'' and that ``the mayor
apparently wants no contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's comments came in response to questions about a
picture released by the White House during the weekend showing
Lazio grabbing the hand of Arafat in a reception line while on a
trip to the Mideast nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they released the official
White House photograph because Lazio criticized President Clinton
last week for shaking hands with President Fidel Castro of Cuba
during the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the White House officials said, also criticized Hillary
Clinton for kissing Arafat's wife, Suha, during a visit to the West
Bank last year. On Monday, Giuliani repeated his own criticism of
the kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Clinton are in a tight race, and Jewish voters are
viewed by both sides as crucial to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's comments were consistent with the mayor's longtime
view of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Giuliani expelled Arafat from a concert for world
leaders at Lincoln Center, even though the Palestinian leader had
been invited to the White House and had been embraced as a
peacemaker by the Israeli and U.S. governments.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said his distrust of Arafat went back to his days as a
federal prosecutor, when he investigated several terrorist
incidents linked to the PLO, including the 1985 hijacking of the
Achille Lauro cruise ship, in which an American was killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Giuliani likened the Palestinian leader to Hitler and
Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot forget that this man is a dictator and that he's a
murderer and that he's murdered Americans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani acknowledged that the Clinton administration needed to
negotiate with Arafat, but he also said that, ``I'm not going to
romanticize him the way we romanticized, for a period of time,
Stalin, the way we romanticized Hitler, the way we romanticized
other dictators small and large during the last century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
