<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PREVIEW-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS YEAR ON THE RUNWAYS, STARVATION CHIC IS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 By GUY TREBAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there is one look that won't be hitting the
runways during the spring 2001 collections in New York, which begin
on Thursday and run through Sept. 22, it's that of the
exaggeratedly thin models who reached a kind of apogee (or nadir,
depending on your viewpoint) during the eras of heroin chic, grunge
and the waif. Fashionable standards of beauty fluctuate _ within a
narrow range _ but among the largely unremarked, and salutary,
changes in the modeling business, insiders say, is a renewed
appetite for women who do not look fundamentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing everyone is looking for is a more natural,
sexier look,'' said Annie Veltri, president of T Management, the
year-old model agency owned by Donald Trump. ``There are curves
again and there are bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Gisele Bundchen and her fellow Brazilians _ that amazing
influx of beautiful cynosures who captivated the United States with
their ripe, often biracial features and with their authentic (well,
most of the time) bosoms and hips. And don't discount the effects
of the first Body Image Summit, a meeting convened this June in
London by European editors and the British Medical Association to
consider the relationship between the largely unrealistic images of
women's bodies represented by most fashion models and an escalation
of eating disorders in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, styles in models have caromed from prom
queens (Christie Brinkley) to blank-eyed androgynes (Kate Moss),
from surgically enhanced supermodels (let's not say) to anonymous
nobodies, from athletic all-Americans (Nikki Taylor) to gorgeous
slackers who wear septum rings when they're not in front of the
camera (Sybil Buck).
</P>
<P>
   From the supply side, the consensus on the coming season's
models is that the Brazilians are not a phase, and that ``health''
is so ubiquitous a buzzword you couldn't give a waif away. ``I want
girls who, when they walk into a go-see, you can tell they're
models,'' said Bob Dean, who books runway models for the Click
agency. ``They have to look very clean, very fresh, very natural,
and with a presence, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Following what Ashton Hundley, a Ford agent, called the
``supermodel sexy moment'' of the mid-90s, there came an
interesting and less traditionally sexy time, essentially the era
of Kate Moss. Now, Hundley said, the look is ``a little more
diverse and much more natural.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
