SURPRISE: McCANN TO START AT QB THIS WEEK 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Ryan McCann showed up at school Monday
morning to lift weights, he was summoned to see UCLA coach Bob
Toledo in his office. If McCann was searching for a some good news,
he might have noticed that he wasn't told to bring his playbook.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore quarterback from Agoura High had played poorly
enough in his first start of the season that he was benched at
halftime in favor of Scott McEwan in UCLA's eventual 24-21 win over
Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   McCann had missed open receivers, made poor reads and called
audibles into plays he shouldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   So, with UCLA poised to play No. 3-Michigan on Saturday at 12:30
p.m. at the Rose Bowl, McCann trudged into Toledo's office like a
brave soldier. He stood at attention as Toledo cleared his throat
and informed McCann that he would be . . . starting?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was ready for me to tell him he wasn't going to be the
starter,'' Toledo said. ``When I told him he was going to be the
starter, he wanted to get out of my office real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann said later Monday he wasn't surprised _ either that he
was starting or that Toledo made a decision between himself and
McEwan so early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can play,'' said McCann, who described his
performance against Fresno State as subpar. ``I've demonstrated
that. Against Alabama I did OK. The more experience I get the
better I'll be.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what Toledo is counting on.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over Michigan propels a team coming off a 4-7 season
into the thick of the national-championship hunt. A loss and poor
quarterback play send the Bruins to Oregon for their conference
opener with shaken confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's important that Ryan starts performing better
because we need him to perform better,'' Toledo said. ``We've got a
good football team. I also said this when season started _ as the
quarterback goes, so goes the Bruins. I told (McCann) that this
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of McCann's faults, he has a stronger arm, is a running
threat and poses more concerns for a defense than McEwan, who
completed 5 of 10 passes in the second half for 29 yards with no
touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' said McEwan, a junior from Thousand Oaks whom
Toledo praised for his poise Saturday in the most extensive action
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan just didn't perform like he was capable,'' he added.
``But I knew that he was better than that and he knows that he's
better than that and I think the coaches know he's better than
that. There's a reason why Ryan was starting on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo came to a decision Sunday after reviewing game film and
meeting with his coaches. He moved just as quickly Monday to help
restore McCann's confidence, which, he added, could be shaken from
his play but not from being pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern,'' Toledo said. ``It's probably a concern with
his teammates, too. Potential is great, but performance is what
counts. I like the kid, he's great kid, he's got a lot of ability.
I don't want to be ripping him in the paper, he's a great kid. He
knows he didn't perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann has made just two career starts, but he's played
virtually all of the Bruins last four games dating back to last
season and Toledo is clearly searching for a way to get through to
him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was frustrated with McCann, Toledo replied,
``Probably. He's not a freshman or a redshirt freshman. He's a
sophomore who's been in the program three years. Yeah, I get a
little frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann's teammates, such as linebacker Ryan Nece, are rallying
around him. He had breakfast Sunday with Nece, who encouraged him
not to lose faith in his ability.
</P>
<P>
   __ Michigan update: Michigan will definitely be without starting
quarterback Drew Henson, the Detroit Free Press reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Wojtys, the team's physician, said there was no
chance he would clear Henson to play Saturday. Wojtys performed
surgery on the broken fifth metatarsal in Henson's right foot on
Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   So far, backup John Navarre has performed extremely well _ he
leads the nation in pass efficiency with a 238.81 rating. But he
has done it against Bowling Green and Rice, neither of which is on
the same talent level as the Bruins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
