<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, A TOSS UP; TRYING TO EXPLAIN THE LANGUAGE; LIEBERMAN
RETURNS TO TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE POLLS: FOR NOW, A TOSS-UP
</P>
<P>
   Four new national polls _ those for Time, Fox News, CNN/USA
Today and NBC/The Wall Street Journal _ showed little change in the
presidential race since Vice President Al Gore closed the gap with
Gov. George W. Bush after the Democratic National Convention. None
of the polls, released over the weekend, has Gore ahead by more
than three points, about the same spread that many polls released a
week earlier showed. So with about eight weeks until Election Day,
the race appears to be a toss-up _ at least for the moment. One
caution: A fifth poll, conducted for Newsweek, has Gore ahead by a
more-comfortable eight percentage points. In individual state polls
released, a Marist Institute survey had Gore ahead of Bush in New
York by 25 percentage points, a gain of 14 points from the last
Marist poll, and a Rocky Mountain News/KCNC-TV poll in Colorado
indicated that Gore had pulled to within three points of Bush, a
gain of 11 points since the last poll. In Missouri, a state in
which Gore and Bush ran neck and neck for months, a new Zogby Poll
has Gore now ahead by 5 points. Likewise, in Illinois, where the
race has been a toss-up, a Zogby Poll has Gore 15 points ahead.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: TRYING TO EXPLAIN THE LANGUAGE Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas has demonstrated a sometimes tortured relationship
with the English language, saying ``hostile'' when he meant
``hostage,'' ``terrier'' when he meant ``tariff'' and ``vile'' when
he meant ``vital.'' An article in Vanity Fair magazine that is
about to hit the newsstands offers an possible explanation,
suggesting that Bush has dyslexia and is being skewered by
reporters for a tendency beyond his control. Karen P. Hughes, the
director of communications for the Bush campaign, said that the
magazine's sympathy for the ribbing that Bush has taken is
misplaced. Hughes said that while one of Bush's brothers, Neil, has
dyslexia, the Republican presidential nominee does not. ``In the
case of this story,'' Hughes said, ``fiction is stranger than
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   FUND-RAISING: LIEBERMAN RETURNS TO TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in four days, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut traveled to Texas, this time not to embarrass Gov.
George W. Bush in one of the state's poor neighborhoods, but to
reap campaign cash in some of its wealthiest. Lieberman, the
Democratic vice-presidential nominee, spoke at four events on
Monday in Dallas and in the Austin area, raising $1.7 million for
the Democratic National Committee. ``Some people may have different
ideas about Texas, but I feel I'm in Gore-Lieberman country,'' he
told contributors in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lieberman held a forum in a low-income part of
Houston to attack Bush's record on children's health care. On
Monday, he traveled to the Westlake Hills neighborhood outside
Austin. At the home of Thomas J. Meredith, who directs Dell
Computer's venture capital fund, Lieberman spoke to 150 people at a
$5,000-a-couple luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush: Orlando, Fla., and St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney: Wilkes-Barre and Pittsburgh, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman: Miamisburg, Middletown and
Cincinnati in Ohio; Erlanger, Ky.; Philadelphia; Camden, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Buchanan: No appearances scheduled
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader: Los Angeles
</P>
</TEXT>
